<HEADLINE>
KARROS SAYS IT TAKES BRAVE MAN TO BE ALL-STAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Eric Karros never has been named to the All-Star team
and likely won't be again this season. But as more and more
starters are sidelined by injuries, his frustration mounts.
</P>
<P>
   Karros, traditionally a second-half player, has 25 home runs and
70 RBI. His career bests are 34 homers and 112 RBI, set last year.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, when Mark McGwire said this week he won't play, Atlanta
manager Bobby Cox, who will coach the National League on Tuesday,
named Edgar Renteria as McGwire's replacement.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Bonds and Ken Griffey Jr. alxu]Y7't p+V/nk R(
