<HEADLINE>
A STILL-GROGGY PIAZZA RIPS BACK AT CLEMENS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs 3rd graf for updating about Piazza missing All-Star Game)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mike Piazza got up off the mat and came up swinging _
verbally _ at Roger Clemens Sunday night. To the Mets' catcher,
Clemens committed an unconscionable act on Saturday when the
Yankees right-hander gave Piazza a concussion with a fastball to
the head.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I could remember him as a great pitcher, as a Cy Young
award winner,'' Piazza said. ``But I know I can't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Piazza missed Sunday night's 2-0 triumph over the Yankees, and
he will stay home and rest instead of going to Tuesday's All-Star
Game, where he was scheduled to be the starting catcher for the
National League.
</P>
<P>
   He said he felt fine, but also that he was groggy and had a
headache. Very soon, Piazza said he will have a magnetic resonance
imaging test to see if the beaning inflicted any damage to his
brain. ``I consider myself very fortunate that I have at least a
little bit of my faculties today,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza prepared some comments before answering questions from
the news media Sunday night, and he said that would be the only
time he would ever address the incident. He had plenty to say, and
in doing so gave voice to a rivalry that now may be more intense
between the teams than it is between fans of those teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about the team,'' said Mets General Manager Steve
Phillips. ``It's not exclusively about an individual.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips forbid the Yankees from using the weight room in the
Mets' locker room, a facility normally shared between teams. He
also scrapped plans to have Mets all-stars Al Leiter and Edgardo
Alfonzo and their families fly on the Yankees' post-game charter to
Atlanta for the All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if things are ever over,'' Phillips said. ``Guys
have long memories in baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Piazza was upset not only at Clemens but at other Yankees who
said Clemens was only trying to pitch inside when Piazza was hit in
the second inning.
</P>
<P>
   ''I thought it was definitely intentional,'' Piazza said. ``I
could respect the fact that he's throwing inside, I could respect
the fact of getting hit, getting hit in the ribs or the body. I
know that's part of the game, I accept that and I don't have any
problem with that. But I feel there's a difference between that and
almost ending my career.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens responded by saying he had no reaction to Piazza's
comments. He repeated what he said after Saturday's game, a 4-2
Yankees victory in the second game of their day-night doubleheader.
``I wasn't trying to hit him,'' Clemens said. ``I was trying to
pitch him inside.''
</P>
<P>
   Piazza, who has seven hits _ including three homers _ in 12
at-bats off Clemens, was not buying that.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got no remorse,'' said Piazza, who added he had no
interest in accepting Clemens' phone call on Saturday. ``I'm kind
of flattered, in a weird way, because he's trying to tell me the
only way to get me out is to try to hurt me.''
</P>
<P>
   Piazza and the Mets manager, Bobby Valentine, both said they
felt Clemens would not have thrown such a pitch at Shea Stadium,
where Clemens would have had to hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really can't say I have respect for him right now,'' Piazza
said. ``Roger has very good control. I think he only walked one guy
during the game. If the shoe fits, that's the way it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``Also, I want to say this: I thought sometime down the line in
my career maybe I could have been a designated hitter. But I think
that's probably not a good thing for baseball. I think that if he
knew he had to come up the next inning, he probably would have been
a little more careful.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentine said he did not remember if Clemens threw at any Texas
Rangers when Valentine managed there _ ``We beat him a lot, I
remember that,'' Valentine said _ but he also noted that Clemens
was protected by the presence of a designated hitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are responsible for your actions and the consequences,''
Valentine said. ``In that American League situation, there's very
little responsibility and very little consequences. So your
teammate gets hit in the butt by an 86 mph fastball.''
</P>
<P>
   That is what the Mets left-hander Glendon Rusch did to Tino
Martinez, the first Yankee he faced Saturday after Piazza was hit.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza, of course, was hit in a far more dangerous area, and he
wondered if it would have long-term implications on his career.
Piazza is one of baseball's best hitters, but he said he could not
be sure how he would be affected by the beaning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's going to take me a little while to get comfortable
in the box,'' he said. ``You have to deal with it. I've been hit
before and you just put it behind you. You can not do the job if
you're not completely comfortable in the box. If you have one ounce
of anxiety or fear, you're not going to play well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
