<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For MONDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Monday, July 10.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-EXAM (Beijing) _ This is ``Black July'' in China, time for
the long-anticipated exam that determines who goes to college in a
country where a degree is seen as a ticket to prosperity, and
failure can mean consignment to drudgery. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   EGYPT-RIGHTS (Cairo) _ The arrest last week of a prominent
sociologist on suspicion of defaming Egypt has alarmed human rights
advocates around the region who say it reflects a policy among Arab
leaders toward political criticism that can best be described as
``killing the messenger.'' By Susan Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   YUGO-KOSOVO (Gracanica, Yugoslavia) _ A U.N. agreement to
provide better security to Kosovo's Serbs, designed to get some
Serbs back into international institutions here, has deepened
divisions among them and caused a key Albanian politician to
suspend his own participation. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-TAINTED-WATER (Gaiwalkerton, Ontario) _ Almost two months
after North America's deadliest outbreak of E. coli contamination
hit this town, its sentiments are captured on a road sign: ``E.
coli, please go away.'' By James Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   CAMEROON-PYGMIES (Mabolo, Cameroon) _ Behind the hills next to
this Pygmy village in the Central African rain forest, a pipeline
is to be built in a few years to carry oil to the Atlantic coast,
where it will be shipped to the West. The pipeline, which the World
Bank endorsed in June after heated debates, will be a huge project,
costing $3.7 billion. It represents a big, risky test for the bank
and for African development policies. Historically, the oil
exploitation in Africa has generated ruinous corruption or
long-running wars, not wealth for nations and their citizens. In
this village, there are both doubts and hopes. By Norimitsu Onishi.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Locator map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-EGELAND (Bogota, Colombia) _ He organized the
``Norwegian channel,'' which led to a peace plan between Israelis
and Palestinians, and has had a hand in peace talks from Central
America to Central Africa. Now, as a U.N. emissary in Colombia, Jan
Egeland is leading efforts here to solve a a 35-year conflict
unlike any he has ever seen. By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Locator map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PAY-YOUR-WAY-PRISONS (Owensboro, Ky.) _ The county jailers of
Kentucky are eagerly preparing to levy room, board and medical
charges on inmates under a pay-your-way practice that dates to
medieval England but is finding fresh life in America, the global
leader in incarceration. Chief jailer Harold Taylor fondly recalls
his salad days in the 1960s when county inmates were respectful
winos who barely taxed the public budget, versus modern inmates who
sue for full dentistry, he says, running up bills under federal
regulations that under a new state law they will have to begin
footing. It's an increasingly fashionable practice nationwide in a
booming jail market now handling 10 million admissions a year. By
Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TAX-CUT-POLITICS _ With projections of the federal budget
surplus rising and both parties in full election-year mode, the
debate over tax cuts is shifting from whether to what kinds.
Republicans continue to press for bigger reductions than most
Democrats will support, and the super-charged politics of the
campaign season will make it difficult for any tax cuts to be
enacted before a new president and Congress take office next year.
But in Washington and on the campaign trail, Democrats from
President Clinton on down are joining Republicans in backing tax
cuts _ enthusiastically in some cases, grudgingly and with
conditions in others _ to a far greater degree than they were a
year or even six months ago. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   ANTIMISSILE-POSTOL-PROFILE _ Theodore A. Postol knows how to
play the role of the rocket scientist that he is. He also knows how
to infuriate Washington officialdom. Postol, a big, bearded
54-year-old physicist at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology,
has combined evidence, emotion and expletives in his crusade to
prove that a proposed $60 billion missile shield for the United
States is based on faulty science, fantasy and outright fraud. By
Elaine Sciolino.
</P>
<P>
   FISHING-QUOTAS _ The way the government limits the catch of
fishermen may heighten the risks for those who go down to the sea.
In most waters, you can catch all the fish you are able until the
overall quota is reached. That spurs a mad race, regardless of high
seas and foul winds. Instead, reformers want individual quotas: a
boat can catch so much, and it can take its time. By Carl Hulse.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   WORKPLACE-NOOSE (Undated) _ The hangman's noose has long been
one of the most frightening representations of racism in America, a
reminder that thousands of blacks met a horrific death at the hands
of lynch mobs from the end of the Civil War well into the 20th
century. But while the symbolic use of a noose has traditionally
been associated with hate groups like the Ku Klux Klan, employment
experts say that nooses, while still rare, are increasingly turning
up in workplaces. In most cases, they say, the noose was placed
anonymously on an employee's chair, in his locker, or on a door. By
Sana Siwolop.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   JEWISH-PRESS-MEDIA (Undated) _ Usually, The New York Jewish Week
newspaper, affiliated with the UJA-Federation, sees its job as
putting the Jewish community in a positive light. And so it was a
remarkable departure for the paper to run an extensive
investigative article recently about a local rabbi, the regional
director of the Orthodox Union's summer youth program, who had been
accused for years of sexual improprieties toward teen-age girls.
After the article appeared, the rabbi was fired, despite his
insistence that the accusations were false. The reaction, within
the metropolitan Jewish community, as well as the regional and
national Jewish press, highlights the tension between advocacy and
objectivity in specialized journalism that is aimed at specific
religious, ethnic or cultural groups. By Felicity Barringer.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT4) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-WIRELESS (Undated) _ The wireless Internet, which
provides Web access on devices that include pagers, cell phones and
Palm handheld devices, is being touted as the most promising
technological development since the Internet itself started taking
off in the early 1990s. In two or three years, there are expected
to be almost as many wireless Internet users as people accessing
the Web on wired PCs. But given the current state of play in the
industry _ and some distinct technical shortcomings _ can the
wireless Web live up to the hype? By Simon Romero.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT2) has been sent to NYT photo clients.
Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-WIRELESS-USES (Undated) _ A look at the wide variety of
uses for wireless Internet access that are being offered to
companies and consumers. Are any of them viable businesses? By Saul
Hansell.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   BOLSTER-PROFILE-MEDIA (Undated) _ Profile of Bill Bolster, the
executive leading CNBC's charge in the TV financial news ratings
battle. By Jim Rutenberg.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT1) has been sent to NYT photo clients.
