<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOLDEN BOY ESPINOZA IS NEW MAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ A veteran racetrack official was strolling
past the Hollywood Park jockeys' room last weekend when he spotted
a young Latino man wearing riding pants, an undershirt and, ahem,
bright yellow hair.
</P>
<P>
   ``That,'' the official said lightly, ``used to be Victor
Espinoza.''
</P>
<P>
   Espinoza had dyed his hair - in honor, he said, of the upcoming
Hollywood Gold Cup. Gold, get it?
</P>
<P>
   Honestly, it's not a good look. A more pleasing makeover is the
one Espinoza has given to his career in the past year, an
application of glamour for which his victory aboard 24-1 Early
Pioneer in Sunday's Gold Cup provided the prettiest curl.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Espinoza, a 28-year-old native of Mexico City, was
just another jockey on the tough Hollywood Park-Santa Anita-Del Mar
circuit. Certainly he was no threat to win a riding title, to say
nothing of a $1 million race.
</P>
<P>
   Today, much improved and polished, he leads the standings at
Hollywood Park with two weeks to go in the spring-summer season and
has colored himself a formidable big-race rider to boot with his
performance aboard Early Pioneer.
</P>
<P>
   The 61st Gold Cup had shaped up as a wide-open race in which a
new star might be born. And one was. A two-legged one. A
yellow-haired one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I've seen him (ride) for several years,'' winning
trainer Vladimir Cerin said after the race. ``But I never paid much
attention to him. I just thought he was an OK rider, a transplant
from Northern California who maybe should have stayed there.''
</P>
<P>
   That used to be Victor Espinoza.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then, the last couple of months, I watched him very
closely,'' Cerin said. ``This kid is just phenomenal, the way he
sees holes developing and judges pace.''
</P>
<P>
   Espinoza hadn't competed in a Gold Cup. He'd been aboard Early
Pioneer only once before and that was in a workout, not a race. The
ex-claiming horse had been ridden in recent starts by Matt Garcia,
a jockey on the fringes of the track's top 10. But when Cerin saw
an opportunity to put the leading man on his Gold Cup horse, he
didn't hesitate.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it's the horse who does most of the work and deserves
mWgl,B\uhe credit for beating favorite General Challenge and jockey
Corey Nakatani. Since his days as a $62,500 sprinter, Early Pioneer
has gone on to longer races and has gotten good.
</P>
<P>
   It's Espinoza, though, who gave him every chance to win, which
is the jockey's job description in a nutshell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good horse. Good ride,'' Espinoza said, putting it in the
right order.
</P>
<P>
   Espinoza says all the right things. And Sunday he made all the
right moves.
</P>
<P>
   Cerin's instructions called for Espinoza to let Early Pioneer
settle behind the front-runners in the opening stages of the 1-mile
race. The rest would be up to the rider.
</P>
<P>
   Espinoza and Early Pioneer rounded the clubhouse turn in the
middle of the nine-horse field. Ahead of them were David, Big Ten
and Cat Thief, who were supposed to be among the pacesetters, and
General Challenge, who was not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't expect General Challenge to be ahead of me. I
expected him to be behind me,'' Espinoza said later. ``I said,
`Well, that's the horse to beat, so I'll stay right here (following
him).' I wanted all the top horses in front of me. I didn't want
'em behind me.''
</P>
<P>
   Espinoza kept Early Pioneer well off the heels of the leaders, a
few running lanes away from the inner rail - by himself, the best
place a horse can be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather be 10-wide than stuck inside,'' Espinoza said.
</P>
<P>
   By the far turn, he sensed that his 5-year-old gelding needed
rousing, and he went to the whip earlier than he might have
preferred. The result was a three-eighths-mile drive that was too
much for a rusty General Challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a magnificent ride,'' Cerin said.
</P>
<P>
   For Espinoza - as for Cerin, owners David and Holly Wilson and
Early Pioneer himself - it was the first victory in a Grade I
stakes.
</P>
<P>
   It was especially emotional for Espinoza. He had spoken on the
phone Sunday morning with agent Tony Matos' mother, recovering from
emergency heart surgery in Puerto Rico. He told her, ``I want to
win just for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Matos had to leave for a couple of days to be with his mother,
and flew back to California only for the day to attend the Gold
Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Don't worry about it. Business will always be here.
Your family won't,''' Espinoza said.
</P>
<P>
   Espinoza is committed to seeing that he'll be here for a long
time. He speaks of wanting to work hard and ``do it right.'' The
results speak for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   He finished third in the standings at Santa Anita last winter,
so his Hollywood Park numbers are no fluke. His victory aboard 10-1
Elaborate in the $300,000 Triple Bend Handicap later on Gold Cup
day was his sixth stakes win of the meet, and only Hall of Famer
Chris McCarron has more.
</P>
<P>
   Is this the young jockey who didn't rate much attention? That
used to be Victor Espinoza. No longer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
