<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-STATUS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLD 'EM OR FOLD 'EM? RANGERS GM NOT TIPPING HIS HAND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON _ The time has come to break up the Texas Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Their outfield has not produced enough offense, their starting
rotation was overrated, their defense is among the worst in the
American League and their bullpen has been a major disappointment.
It doesn't take long to figure out what went wrong for the Rangers
in the first half of the season or why they will spend the All-Star
break in last place in the AL West.
</P>
<P>
   Wait a minute...
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Rogers and Rick Helling have pitched well, John Wetteland
can still get people out in the ninth inning, their offense can
still score runs and the young players are becoming
battle-hardened. Just when it seemed to be time to write their
obituary, the Rangers finished the first half strong to pull within
striking distance of first place (they trail Seattle by 81/2 games)
or a wild-card spot (they trail Oakland by 51/2 games). They are
far from being finished.
</P>
<P>
   So...
</P>
<P>
   Break up the Rangers? Keep trying to win?
</P>
<P>
   The exhaustive debate is waged almost daily, both in public and
in the Rangers' clubhouse, where players openly wonder what changes
are coming. But the man who will ultimately answer the questions
won't say _ because he hasn't decided.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers general manager Doug Melvin just believes his team is
still in contention and needs to keep winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll keep watching it and try to enjoy it while we're
winning,'' Melvin said.''I've got a feeling for what might happen
or not happen. I'd really like the team to win and to keep the team
together. We're still trying to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Win what?
</P>
<P>
   The wild card, possibly. The division title, maybe. The American
League pennant, doubtful. The World Series? Don't bet on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know people say the ultimate goal is to win the World
Series,'' Melvin said. ``But to win the World Series, you've got to
get to postseason. You take it one step at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   And other things must be considered.
</P>
<P>
   The Baltimore Orioles were in a similar situation in 1996 when
they were 52-52 on July 30. General manager Pat Gillick was ready
to start trading veterans for young players, but owner Peter
Angelos wouldn't let him. Angelos looked like a hero when the
Orioles won the wild-card spot in 1996 and the division in 1997.
But they failed to reach the World Series, and now they have aging
veterans and few decent young players.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin wants to avoid that. Owner Tom Hicks wants to win the
World Series, not just another division title. Trading some
marketable veterans now _ closer John Wetteland, pitcher Esteban
Loaiza, designated hitter David Segui _ could get the Rangers a
head start on putting together a World Series team next year.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston Astros traded reliever Larry Andersen to the Boston
Red Sox for minor-league third baseman Jeff Bagwell in 1990. The
Atlanta Braves traded pitcher Doyle Alexander to the Detroit Tigers
for John Smoltz in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   But the Oakland Athletics traded first baseman Mark McGwire to
the St. Louis Cardinals for pitchers Blake Stein, T.J. Mathews and
Eric Ludwick in 1997. Some midseason trades work out better than
others.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, the Rangers might win something this year.
</P>
<P>
   Go for it? Wait 'til next year? Each area of the team offers
reasons why the Rangers should keep going for a playoff spot and
why they should look toward next year. STARTING PITCHING
</P>
<P>
   GO FOR IT: The Rangers have two capable starters, Rick Helling
and Kenny Rogers, at the head of their rotation. Darren Oliver and
Esteban Loaiza pitched well in the second half last year. With
similar second-half performances from Oliver and Loaiza this year,
the Rangers could have the rotation they envisioned in spring
training.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, they would have an opening for a fifth starter, which
would allow them to look at Matt Perisho, Ryan Glynn or Doug Davis.
Even if the Rangers trade Loaiza, which seems a foregone
conclusion, they could make a strong run with two young pitchers in
the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   WAIT 'TIL NEXT YEAR: The Rangers have three promising young
pitchers: Perisho, Glynn and Davis. The Rangers need to find out
about them now because tough and expensive decisions will need to
be made in the off-season, particularly when pursuing free agents.
The potential free agents include Mike Mussina and Mike Hampton.
BULLPEN
</P>
<P>
   GO FOR IT: This area revolves around closer John Wetteland. He
has had some costly blown saves, but, for the most part, he has
pitched well since getting his 300th save. They won't win anything
this year if they trade him.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' biggest disappointment in the bullpen is that
right-handers Tim Crabtree and Jeff Zimmerman haven't been as
dominant as they were last year. But both are young, healthy and
able to throw the ball 93 to 95 mph. If they recapture last year's
glory, they can pair with left-handers Mike Venafro and Doug Davis
and middleman Francisco Cordero to give the Rangers a formidable
bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   WAIT 'TIL NEXT YEAR: Wetteland has been worth every nickel the
Rangers have paid him, even if he has never had a save opportunity
in the playoffs. But he will be a free agent after the season. The
Rangers would get two draft picks as compensation if he leaves as a
free agent, but they should be able to get more through a trade.
</P>
<P>
   The right trade would give the Rangers a big head start on next
year. And, if they trade Wetteland, the Rangers could take a hard
look at Crabtree, Zimmerman, Cordero, or even Loaiza, as closer.
and decide if next year's closer is already on the team or if they
need to pursue Robb Nen. INFIELD
</P>
<P>
   GO FOR IT: Include catcher Ivan Rodriguez and designated hitter
David Segui with the four regular infielders, and the Rangers have
a championship unit. Certainly, Luis Alicea would have to maintain
his pace and third baseman Mike Lamb would have to improve his
defense. But if first baseman Rafael Palmeiro and shortstop Royce
Clayton pick up their offense a little bit, then the Rangers would
have what it takes here to win the division.
</P>
<P>
   WAIT 'TIL NEXT YEAR: Then there is Frank Catalanotto. If the
Rangers decide to start getting ready for next season, he has to
figure prominently in their plans.
</P>
<P>
   Alicea and Segui can become free agents, and Catalanotto is a
candidate to replace either. First, the Rangers must find out if he
can play defense well enough to play every day at second base. If
not, he could end up as the Rangers' designated hitter. He appears
to be a front-line offensive player. OUTFIELD
</P>
<P>
   GO FOR IT: The Rangers have not had much good news in the past
three weeks. But if there is one bright spot, it is that left
fielder Rusty Greer is healthy and at the top of his game again.
That does wonders for the Rangers' offense and could help Palmeiro
break out in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   But, by staying the course, the Rangers commit themselves to
Gabe Kapler in center field and the platoon of Dave Martinez and
Chad Curtis in right. Even with Greer playing well, this is not an
outfield that produces enough power for a championship team. Kapler
would really need a big second half for the Rangers to win.
</P>
<P>
   WAIT 'TIL NEXT YEAR: The Rangers' outfield is missing something,
and Ruben Mateo's broken leg was a major blow, both for now and
next season. It's not that he won't be back next season, but he's
missing four good months of development that might have allowed him
to move to the next level next year.
</P>
<P>
   Kapler plays hard and plays good defense, but his slugging
percentage is under .400, totally unacceptable in the American
League.
</P>
<P>
   If the Rangers scrap the season, finding an outfielder with some
pop would be among their priorities. But they could move Kapler
back to right, put Scarborough Green in center and see if Green can
develop into a front-line leadoff hitter. GO FOR IT 1. The New York
Yankees and Cleveland Indians are down. The league is wide-open.
The team that improves the most between now and the end of the
season will win the pennant.
</P>
<P>
   2. Darren Oliver, Esteban Loaiza, Jeff Zimmerman and Tim
Crabtree could recover the form that made them successful pitchers
last year. Those are four big ifs but a four-pitcher parley
improves the Rangers' chances tremendously.
</P>
<P>
   3. Even if Oliver and Loaiza continue to struggle, the Rangers
could make a run with a rotation that includes Doug Davis, Ryan
Glynn and Matt Perisho.
</P>
<P>
   4. They have a powerful offense that could get better if Rafael
Palmeiro, Royce Clayton and/or Gabe Kapler step it up in the second
half.
</P>
<P>
   5. The Rangers had a bad first half, and they are right around
.500. WAIT 'TIL NEXT YEAR 1. This team is not good enough to win
the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   2. A good general manager should be able to get something good
in return for John Wetteland.
</P>
<P>
   3. Taking a hard look at young players will give the Rangers a
better idea of how to proceed in the free-agent market.
</P>
<P>
   4. The offense could stumble if Ivan Rodriguez, David Segui and
Luis Alicea can't maintain torrid first-half paces.
</P>
<P>
   5. George Steinbrenner will buy the Yankees another pennant.
ANALYZING THE TRADING BLOCK
</P>
<P>
   1. Esteban Loaiza. He's all but gone. Most contending teams need
pitching. Even if the Rangers don't give up, they're all but
convinced one Ryan Glynn or Doug Davis could do as well as Loaiza
now and be better in the future. 2. John Wetteland. He might not be
gone, even if the Rangers fall out of the race. Wetteland is a team
leader, and the Rangers think it would be easier to develop some
young pitching with a dependable closer saving their victories. 3.
David Segui. He has been great, on and off the field. Trading him
could put more pressure on the younger players _ Mike Lamb, Gabe
Kapler and Frank Catalanotto _ at the bottom of the lineup. Plus,
while some teams can use a .340 hitter, it's unlikely they'll give
up a big-time prospect for Segui. 4. Darren Oliver. The Rangers
might be sorely tempted to trade him if they could find somebody to
take his contract, allowing Texas to move another young pitcher
into the rotation. First, Oliver has to show he's healthy. 5. Luis
Alicea. What a shame if it comes to this. The guy has been terrific
and is a great player to have on the team. But the Rangers might
want to take a look at Catalanotto. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
