<HEADLINE>
THINGS BREAK RIGHT FOR RED SOX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ All it will take, of course, is the next loss,
especially if (God forbid) Pedro Martinez is less than perfect
Thursday night against the New York Mets.
</P>
<P>
   But for the next three days, at least, the grumbling about the
Red Sox will pale compared to other local aggravations of the
moment, like finding a decent perch from which to watch the Tall
Ships. Even newcomer Ed Sprague, who was booed Sunday as if he were
a cousin of Izzy Alcantara, should catch some slack after a 7-2 win
over the Atlanta Braves Sunday sent the Sox into the All-Star break
on a winning note.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody's walking out of here in a bad mood,'' said catcher
Jason Varitek, who had three hits, all of which figured in the
scoring on a day when shortstop Nomar Garciaparra hit two home runs
for the second time in five games, Jose Offerman rediscovered the
triple, and Brian Daubach did a three-point turn himself. ``It's
nice to end with a win.''
</P>
<P>
   Imagine if the opposite had occurred. Instead of celebrating
what looks as if it might be the start of something big _
cast-aside knuckleballer Tim Wakefield has won three in a row since
being restored to the starting rotation _ someone might be
demanding an investigation of why outfielder Carl Everett is
allowed to show up 45 minutes after the rest of the team was
required to be in uniform, as he did Sunday. (``Not an issue,''
said Jimy Williams.)
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Everett received best wishes from all corners of the
clubhouse as he headed to Atlanta for his richly deserved first
All-Star appearance, where both he and Garciaparra could be in the
American League's starting lineup because of injuries to elected
starters Manny Ramirez and Alex Rodriguez. Yankees manager Joe
Torre has told New York writers that Everett will, indeed, start
for Ramirez. Derek Lowe, who pitched a 1-2-3 ninth, will be in the
AL bullpen as another first-timer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was listening to WEEI the other day,'' said Jeff Frye, who
spent another day as Trot Nixon's stand-in in right field, ``and I
heard people saying we're ruining their summer. Unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   Far too early, of course, to nail a ``Condemned'' sign on this
season. The Sox, who dodged a date with Greg Maddux Sunday when the
Braves' ace was winged during batting practice Saturday by a line
drive and scratched with a bruised right shoulder (also knocking
him out of the All-Star Game), collected 14 hits against Maddux's
replacement, Kevin Millwood, and two relievers to avoid a
three-game sweep by the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   They go into the break just two games over .500 (43-41), 2 1/2
games behind the Yankees in the AL East. They were 10 games over
.500 (49-39) and four games behind the Bombers at the break last
season. The big difference was in the wild-card standings. The Sox
were three games in front of the pack at this point last season;
they were five games back Sunday &UR;  &LR; night, and six teams were ahead
of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's nothing,'' said outfielder Troy O'Leary, referring to
the ground that has to be made up.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the end of the month, everybody should be back,'' said
O'Leary, whose second-inning single helped set up the Sox' first
run, ``and everybody here knows what we can do if we've got
everybody back.''
</P>
<P>
   Wakefield, of course, has been here all along, even if it has
been back among the rakes in Joe Mooney's toolshed. Wakefield, who
was mutinous after being used as mopup man in the Sox' 22-1 loss to
the Yankees, two days after he'd thrown 58 pitches, gave up a
second-inning home run to Reggie Sanders but otherwise limited the
Braves to just five singles and a walk in his seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   How important have Wakefield's three wins in a row been to the
cause? Since May 30, Sox starters have won just seven games _ Ramon
Martinez has two, brother Pedro and rookie Paxton Crawford one
each, and Wakefield three.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not trying to prove a point,'' Wakefield said. ``I just
want to be as consistent as I can.''
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra, who walked and scored on Varitek's single in the
second, homered to make it 2-1 in the third. Offerman, who has led
the AL in triples the last two seasons, hit his first triple since
the calendar rolled over to score two more runs in the fourth. In
the fifth, Daubach's triple, Garciaparra's second home run, and
Varitek's RBI double made it a 7-2 breeze.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra now has four home runs in his last five games after
hitting seven in his first 62 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think home runs are as important as driving in runs,''
Williams said. ``It doesn't matter. I don't look at home runs. I
look at RBIs and runs scored.''
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra has knocked in 59 runs, second to Everett's 69, and
his 47 runs scored are also second to Everett (53).
</P>
<P>
   ``Nomar knows how to play the game,'' O'Leary said. ``If we need
a home run, he'll hit it. If we need a base hit or an RBI, he'll
get it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sprague, the infielder acquired last weekend from San Diego,
went hitless on the weekend (0 for 9) and is batting just .118 (4
for 34) since switching coasts. The sellout crowd of 33,018 let him
know it noticed by booing each successive at-bat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-00 0031EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
