<HEADLINE>
SCIOSCIA: DODGER STADIUM RETURN NO PROBLEM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GORDON VERRELL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Even though he spent 13 years as a player, two
as a coach and two more as an instructor with the Los Angeles
Dodgers, Angels manager Mike Scioscia said he expects no problem
figuring out which dugout to go to Thursday when Anaheim begins a
three-game interleague series at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``After some of those collisions I had at home plate, I wasn't
always sure which dugout was ours,'' Scioscia said Sunday. ``But
this shouldn't be a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia said he got over any nervousness about glimpsing Dodger
Blue for the first time since leaving the organization last year
when the Dodgers played in Anaheim in June.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are still a lot of close ties ... with guys I played
with, like Eric Karros and Dave Hansen,'' Scioscia said, ``and guys
I coached, like Paul LaDuca. (Coach) Rick Dempsey and I go back a
long way. And Claude Osteen was my pitching coach last year at
Albuquerque.
</P>
<P>
   ``That part of it is strange, seeing those people on the other
side. But as far as preparing our club to play them, they're just
another club.''
</P>
<P>
   Merk perks up: Scioscia, on left-hander Kent Mercker, still
recovering from a cerebral hemorrhage suffered nearly two months
ago:
</P>
<P>
   ``We are all excited about what he has accomplished. That first
day we visited him in the hospital, ... if somebody had told me
then that he'd be pitching again in the major leagues in two or
three months, I'd have said they were crazy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so encouraging seeing him. But, it's like the first week
of spring training for him. He's got to keep going, and maintain.''
</P>
<P>
   Another left-hander, Scott Schoeneweis, disabled since June 17
because of a strained right rib cage, moved closer to getting back
into the starting rotation with a strong showing in a three-inning
simulated game Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Schoeneweis didn't seem overly impressed with his 45-pitch
workout - ``All a part of getting back,'' he said - but Scioscia
termed the session ``great.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shame he wasted so many pitches,'' Scioscia kidded.
``We could have used him (Sunday night). It was very encouraging.
He had great stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Schoeneweis, who was 5-5 with a 5.08 ERA in 14 starts before he
was hurt, will make at least two rehab starts, the first one Friday
for Lake Elsinore. If all goes well, he'll be back with the Angels
in two more weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Around the horn: Ken Hill and Kent Bottenfield will start the
Angels' first two games after the All-Star break, Thursday and
Friday nights at Dodger Stadium. Rookie left-hander Seth Etherton,
recalled last week from Edmonton, will start Saturday. ... Colorado
entered Sunday evening's game as the No. 1 NL team hitting with
runners in scoring position: .326. Yet, in the first two games
against the Angels, the Rockies were just 2 for 18 hitting with
runners at second or third base.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
