<SLUG> BC-CAR-RYAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEWART DEDICATES WIN TO IRWIN 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUDON, N.H. _ You know what? This is the way it should have
ended, in leaden skies with the rain falling to bring a premature
halt to a race that was frustratingly inconclusive, and,
ultimately, flawed.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Stewart won the race and money at the New England 300 at
Sunday's New Hampshire International Speedway, but a good time was
not necessarily had by all. From the minute Kenny Irwin's car
slammed into the wall at Turn 3 Friday, everything changed. In a
better world, everyone would have gone home, right then and there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked at that spot more than once today,'' said third-place
finisher Mark Martin, alluding to the infamous Turn 3 where Irwin
lost his life in a practice run. ``I'm not going to elaborate for
you, but more than once I did look at those skid marks.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be untruthful to suggest that Irwin's death meant
nothing. Each competitor had a decal in memory of Irwin slapped on
the driver's side door. Bishop Michael Cote of the Diocese of Maine
made immediate references to the deaths of both Irwin and Adam
Petty, who was killed on that same turn two months ago, during his
invocation. There was an Air Force flyover that supposedly paid
symbolic respect, assuming you were versed in Air Force customs.
But it took grand marshal Ken Squier two tries to make any allusion
to the tragic deaths. The wall where Irwin's car made contact has
been freshly painted (frequent re-paintings, we were told, is track
policy). And how is it remotely possible that the American flag on
display was not flying at half-mast?
</P>
<P>
   I'm sorry, but the overriding feeling conveyed by both NASCAR
and track officials was: ``Business as usual.'' They certainly
could have dispensed with the balloons at the start of the race.
Oh, and did anyone ever hear of black armbands?
</P>
<P>
   Death at a NASCAR event is a messy topic, and death at New
Hampshire International Speedway is a particularly unsavory item
now that two drivers have gone to their final rewards at the same
treacherous turn within two months. The drivers suddenly have
safety issues with NHIS.
</P>
<P>
   Should that turn be better-banked coming off a long
straightaway? Some people say yes. Others say it's a bogus issue,
that there are many tracks similarly configured and that what
happened to Petty and Irwin adds up to a totally improbable
coincidence.
</P>
<P>
   The denial policy is easy for those people to adopt. They know
that lots of people will show up _ 101,000 in this instance _ and
that few of them have spent much time dwelling on either the Petty
or Irwin tragedies. The great risk these brave men take racing
these cars at tremendous speeds is the lure. If one of them cracks
up every now and then, well, it's supposed to be a dangerous
enterprise. If everybody could do it, racing wouldn't be such a big
deal.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't so easy for the drivers. A fatality is a graphic
reminder of their own mortality. There was hardly a man among the
43 starters for whom this race was not just a little less important
than he would have thought a week ago, and that most specifically
includes the man who won.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long weekend,'' said Stewart, ``and I would like
to dedicate this race to Kenny Irwin.''
</P>
<P>
   To Stewart, Irwin was not just another driver on the Winston Cup
circuit. Irwin was his personal measuring stick. ``I spent the last
nine years competing with him,'' said Stewart. ``I spent more time
with him than I did with my parents. We had our ups and downs, but
it wasn't much different than it was with my fiancee. In the end,
we always had respect. It wasn't a bitter rivalry, but it was a
rivalry.''
</P>
<P>
   At every event, Stewart would have one question during
qualifying: ``How did Kenny do?''
</P>
<P>
   So, victory or no victory, Stewart will not recall this trip to
Loudon with great fondness. ``Friday was difficult, and Saturday
was even worse because we all were able to get into race mode and I
was actually a little frustrated about that,'' said Stewart. ``And
it was just a weird feeling to get into a racing car today.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart altered his typical prerace routine. ``I watched all the
tributes on TNN and ESPN,'' he said. ``I didn't want to miss any of
them, because Kenny deserved them.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone had his own Irwin-related grief. For runner-up Joe
Nemechek, it opened wounds from having lost a brother in a crash in
Homestead, Fla., three years ago. ``You find yourself asking why so
many young drivers have this happen,'' he said. ``You just realize
that the Lord works in mysterious ways.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a wake-up call, a reality check,'' said Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   That said, the Irwin mishap is not likely to make ex-drivers out
of any of these men. They all know the risk; it is a given. These
are totally confident men who are immensely proud of their skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would rather drive 190 miles an hour at NHIS all day long
than run a half hour with some of the morons on the street,''
Stewart said. ``Our crews do everything they can to make us as safe
as possible in our cars. In fact, I feel for Kenny's crew. Someone
had to go home on Friday saying, `Did I make a mistake?' And we all
make mistakes. The day we don't make mistakes, this sport will
become boring.''
</P>
<P>
   What these men deserve is a fair shake from the tracks
themselves. If New Hampshire International Speedway is
fundamentally unsound, then someone had damn well better do
something to make it sound before another big race takes place. The
big boys are returning here Sept. 17 for the New Hampshire 300. It
would be nice if all the stories have to do with the competition,
and the competition only.
</P>
<P>
   Irwin's funeral will take place in Indianapolis Wednesday. May
it be the last one ever held for a fallen NASCAR driver.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-00 0036EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000710.0012 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 00:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7504 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-CAR-NEWENGLAND300-BOS     07-10 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NEW </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEWART DEDICATES WIN TO IRWIN 
</HEADLINE>
 ENGLAND 300-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUDON, N.H. _ The first time he steered his car through Turn 3
in Sunday's New England 300 at New Hampshire International
Speedway, Tony Stewart made sure he was focused on the task at
hand.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart tried not to become distracted by thoughts of Kenny
Irwin, a former sprint car teammate and NASCAR Winston Cup rival
who was killed Friday in a violent wall crash that was hauntingly
similar to the death of 19-year-old Adam Petty _ in the same corner
_ May 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't look for the skid marks and they had painted the
wall, so I didn't see the spot on the wall, anyway,'' Stewart said.
``To be honest, the first time around there I was just trying to
get a tachometer reading. I kind of made sure I was getting a tach
reading.''
</P>
<P>
   When he toured the 1.058-mile oval at NHIS for the last time
Sunday, and led the field through that fateful corner under caution
on Lap 273, Stewart admitted, ``It was kind of hard to see out of
the car because of the raindrops on the windshield. But there were
periods of the day where I caught myself looking over there. It was
just hard. It wasn't so much what happened, it's the end result
that bothered me.''
</P>
<P>
   The rain proved heaven-sent for Stewart after the driver of the
No. 20 Home Depot Pontiac sweated out two delays and gambled on
fuel mileage to put himself in a position to be declared the winner
of the 300-lap race (which drew 101,000) when NASCAR officials
called it 27 laps from the finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to dedicate this win to Kenny Irwin,'' said a
glassy-eyed Stewart, his voice cracking. ``We were teammates and I
knew him and raced with him for the last nine years. We weren't
always on the best terms with each other, but we always respected
each other in a race car and what each other could do in a race
car.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't the first time I've made this quote, but he is part
of the reason I got to Winston Cup because he made me become a
better race car driver. I had to beat him every week, and he was as
tough as anybody around, week in and week out, no matter whether it
was a sprint car, Silver Crown (car), or a midget.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the guy that I had to beat every week to win the
race.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory, Stewart's second at NHIS after a 1998 Indy Racing
League triumph, was especially redemptive for crew chief Greg
Zipadelli, a native of Berlin, Conn. Zipadelli took responsibility
for a fuel shortage that cost Stewart a victory here in last year's
race when he ran out of gas with two laps to go and finished 10th
behind three-time Loudon winner Jeff Burton.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, it seemed Zipadelli was doomed to suffer a similar fate
when Stewart pitted out of sequence with the leaders on Lap 28. He
then inherited the lead on Lap 87 when Geoffrey Bodine pitted under
green. Then Zipadelli and Stewart were forced to agonize over their
next move when the race was red-flagged for almost 52 minutes by
rain on Lap 132 _ 18 laps from the halfway mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``That first red flag, I'm sure that probably took three or four
years off Greg Zipadelli's life,'' Stewart said, ``because you're
leading the race. What do you do? Do you come in and pit under the
yellow like everybody else? Do you stay out and hope that when it
goes back to green you are only going to run 18 laps to get to the
halfway and it rains, or what?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a tough situation for him,'' he added. ``Luckily,
all I have to do is drive the race car. He is the guy who's got to
have all the weight on his shoulders of whether it is the right
call or the wrong call.''
</P>
<P>
   In this case, Zipadelli opted to keep Stewart out to preserve
their track position, until they were forced to surrender it with a
green-flag pit on Lap 187. He wound up falling out of the Top 20,
but slowly worked his way to the front under a series of green-flag
stops by the lead pack. Stewart, who led twice for a total of 156
laps, inherited the lead for good when Bobby Labonte pitted under
green on Lap 218.
</P>
<P>
   With runner-up Joe Nemechek also in need of fuel to make it to
the finish, and third-place finisher Mark Martin ready to go the
distance, Stewart and Co. knew they were going to need a miracle to
pull out their third NASCAR victory of the season.
</P>
<P>
   When the dark and swollen clouds began weeping on Lap 268,
Stewart knew that Irwin had delivered some raindrops that induced
the fifth and final caution of the day. Five laps later, NASCAR
officials red-flagged the race for the second and final time under
a steady rain.
</P>
<P>
   The shower had a cleansing effect on Stewart and Zipadelli, who
were able to wash their hands of last year's messy outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trust me, I was happy to see that rain come,'' said Stewart,
who won a rained-out race at Michigan June 11. ``The rain was what
hurt us to begin with, and the rain came back and justified itself.
Do I feel bad about winning a race this way? Absolutely not. We
were the fastest car all day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
