<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAKEFIELD'S KNUCKLER HAS KEPT RED SOX AFLOAT 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-WAKEFIELD-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The odd man out is in again.
</P>
<P>
   Three months after the Red Sox abruptly exiled Tim Wakefield
from the starting rotation, the knuckleballer Sunday officially
reclaimed his job by discombobulating the Braves for his third
straight win as a temp worker among Boston's beleaguered corps of
starters.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, he stopped short of saying he told us so. But in
containing the Braves by yielding only two runs over seven innings
and helping the Sox dodge a demoralizing sweep before the All-Star
break, Wakefield submitted powerful evidence to support his prior
protests that he merits a starter's job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I'm wearing one hat, and mentally it's a lot easier to
know what your role is,'' Wakefield said after manager Jimy
Williams announced the once-shunned knuckleballer will join the
Brothers Martinez, Pete Schourek, and Jeff Fassero as the team's
starters after the break.
</P>
<P>
   Wakefield made no secret of his anger over being yanked from his
starting role when the Sox signed the lefthanded Schourek after he
was released by the Pirates just before the season started. And
Wakefield complained last month about being bounced from long
relief to a setup role and finally to a mop-up assignment in a 22-1
loss to the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Wakefield had answered the mop-up call after throwing 58 pitches
in relief just two days earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've worn almost every hat you can think of here,'' he said.
``I don't frown upon that. It's just nice to be in a consistent
role.''
</P>
<P>
   Consistency was the key to beating the Braves, as Wakefield
confounded the heart of Atlanta's order with his 65-mile-per-hour
floater. The first five batters in the Braves lineup went 2 for 15,
with slugger Andres Galarraga eking out a harmless single in the
fourth inning and Quilvio Veras poking a Wall-ball single in the
fifth that drove in Javy Lopez.
</P>
<P>
   In improving his record to 5-5, Wakefield lowered his ERA to
4.98, though he has posted a 3.54 ERA in his last three starts. He
walked only one and left it to Rich Garces and Derek Lowe to stifle
the Braves in the eighth and ninth, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has pitched very well for us as a starter, he really has,''
Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Pitching coach Joe Kerrigan attributed Wakefield's victory to
his mastery of the delicate mechanics of delivering the
knuckleball. ``He changed speeds . . . very well,'' Kerrigan said.
``He kept a good delivery throughout, and kept a good flight on his
knuckleball.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerrigan indicated Wakefield could be pivotal to the team's
second-half plans. ``He's in a good groove now,'' he said, ``and we
want to keep him in a good groove.''
</P>
<P>
   That's comforting to Wakefield, though he appeared resigned to
the possibility of future upheaval. ``The way the last couple of
years have gone here, I don't know what to expect hardly anymore,''
he said. ``But hopefully I can wear the one hat I'm wearing now and
help the club do what it can to win from that aspect.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he can't help looking over his shoulder. ``It's just
something I have to live with,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-00 0059EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
