<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-IRWIN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUICK EXIT SUITED DRIVERS AND CREWS 
</HEADLINE>
 REACTION-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHIRA SPRINGER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUDON, N.H. _ When light rain led to a red flag before the
halfway point of the New England 300, some race teams kept moving.
They packed up their haulers and left New Hampshire International
Speedway. The Kellogg's transporter was the first to go Sunday,
knowing the No. 5 car, driven by Terry Labonte, sustained too much
damage in an early wreck to continue. As the rain tapered off,
other teams that dropped out of the race because of accidents
prepared to vacate the premises. The John Deere hauler closed its
back door. The K-Mart/Route 66 hauler flashed its brake lights as
it prepared to back away.
</P>
<P>
   Another red flag for rain with 27 laps remaining allowed the
mass moving efforts to continue. Crew members rolled water coolers,
used gas containers, tool boxes, and extra tires off Pit Road. Just
the barest of mechanical essentials remained as drivers and crew
waited to learn whether the race would continue.
</P>
<P>
   On race day, it's customary for drivers and crew to make quick
exits. But Sunday, there was added motivation. The death of driver
Kenny Irwin in a Friday practice session made the weekend longer.
The tragedy dominated conversations around the track, especially
since it came eight weeks after the death of Adam Petty at NHIS.
And although NASCAR did not interrupt the racing schedule, the
drivers were clearly disturbed, even distracted, by the fatality.
</P>
<P>
   ``I say the track looks wet,'' said driver Jerry Nadeau, during
the second and final stoppage that gave him a career-best
fourth-place finish. ``Let's just call this thing and go home. I
hope this rain stays. I think everybody's ready to get out of here
this weekend. It's been a tough weekend for everybody here. All our
hearts and prayers go out to Kenny's family.''
</P>
<P>
   The somber atmosphere that set in Friday never lifted. The only
way for the racers and their crews to gain some distance from death
was to leave NHIS. Loading haulers that faced Turn 3 where Irwin
and Petty crashed, it was difficult for crew members to put the
deaths behind them while competing at NHIS.
</P>
<P>
   David Lippard, who works on Dale Earnhardt Jr.'s No. 8 Budweiser
Chevy, mentioned that the fatal crashes will give the track a
stigma in the short term. As they were packing, some race team
members got ``eerie'' and ``strange'' feelings looking at Turn 3.
But as the years go by, Lippard predicted memories of the tragedies
on Turn 3 will fade.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to put it behind you,'' said Charlie McDonell, a
member of the Square D/Cooper Lighting crew. ``As soon as we leave
the track, we try to put racing out of our minds. You want to move
on (from the deaths) and the easiest way to move on is to go home.
You try not to think about it too much at home. It's easier to
forget about it when you're there.''
</P>
<P>
   Even drivers who thought they could gain a better finishing
position and points if the race continued were glad to get going
home. Mike Skinner praised his crew for piecing the No. 31 Lowe's
Chevrolet back together after an early accident, but lamented that
their efforts gained only an extra nine points. Many teams in the
same position likely would have placed the wrecked vehicle on a
trailer and carried it home. Still, despite the time invested in
repairing the car, Skinner was anxious to leave NHIS.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be glad to get away from here,'' he said. ``This has not
been good to us this year. This place has been pretty treacherous
for some guys and it's really a shame. I hate it.''
</P>
<P>
   Under a dark, gray sky spitting rain, the last haulers left NHIS
and completed the quick exodus. The longest and saddest weekend of
the year for NASCAR Winston Cup teams was over. But with Irwin's
funeral scheduled for Wednesday in Indianapolis, the entire racing
community is in for a long week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
