<SLUG> BC-CAR-NE300-MARTIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME RUNS OUT FOR MARTIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUDON, N.H. _ He had spent much of the race outrunning
misfortune. When the rains came to the New England 300 on Lap 273,
Mark Martin was sitting pretty. The Daytona Beach, Fla., resident
was in third place, with first-place Tony Stewart and second-place
Joe Nemechek running out of fuel.
</P>
<P>
   Martin boldly declared in an interview during the rain delay
that if the rain stopped and the race began again he would triumph.
But the light drizzle quickly became a steady downpour, and Martin
knew long before the race officially was called that he would not
get a chance to make good on his declaration.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for someone who had to settle for third, Martin was upbeat,
and added that a victory probably would have been a stroke of luck,
since Stewart had run a more dominant race.
</P>
<P>
   ``After they (put out the caution flag), I was thinking that I
had nothing to gain and everything to lose, really,'' said Martin,
who was looking for his second win of the season, having won the
Goody's Body Pain 500 in Martinsville, Va.
</P>
<P>
   He also earned 170 points and five lap-leader bonus points to
move up one spot to sixth in the Winston Cup points standings (he
led from Lap 192 to Lap 204). It was his 11th top-10 finish this
season.
</P>
<P>
   In the standard postrace inspection, an irregularity was found
in Martin's Valvoline Ford. NASCAR officials said Sunday night his
third-place finish would stand and the issue would be addressed
this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started off wallowing in mediocrity and we progressively,
with the Valvoline team, made it better with each pit stop,'' said
Martin, who said it didn't bother him that the ending denied him
his first triumph at New Hampshire International Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the last stop we were actually cutting some really good
laps,'' he added. ``Though we didn't really need to, we were
sitting in a real good position with enough gas to go all the way.
Everybody behind us wasn't able to keep up with us and two guys in
front of us had to stop for gas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a pretty straightforward deal, just sit there and hope
the light sprinkles stay that way. Great strategy by the team,
great fuel mileage. That was our only chance to win and we were set
up for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin reiterated his belief that if the race had continued, he
would have been sitting in Victory Lane. But he added, ``It would
sorta have been robbery. (Tony Stewart) was the class of the
field.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, you get the feeling he wished Mother Nature had
cooperated more. ``Some people were going to be frustrated,''
Martin said, ``but it certainly wouldn't have been us. That's how
it goes in racing. Somebody is always frustrated, but I think you
would have seen much greater frustration in (Stewart's) crowd. I've
been there before.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin, who began the race from third position, has run well at
NHIS; Sunday marked his ninth top-10 finish in 11 races at Loudon,
more than any other driver.
</P>
<P>
   He also has finished in the top 5 in his last four races, after
finishing 32d or lower in three of his previous five races. He said
that is why he wasn't somber after he didn't get the break he
wanted with the rain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little bit more grateful when things go good right now
than I was three months ago,'' said Martin, the winningest driver
in the NASCAR Busch Series. A victory Sunday would have been his
32d in NASCAR. ``I feel right now that third place is good.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many drivers, Martin said he thought about Kenny Irwin, who
was killed in practice Friday, during the race. ``I looked at the
spot (where Irwin crashed),'' he said. ``The spot was painted on
the wall now, but I know where the cracks are. (I looked) more than
once in the race.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
