<SLUG> BC-CAR-NE300-BAHRE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAHRE DEFENDS NHIS TRACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUDON, N.H. _ The longest race weekend yet at New Hampshire
International Speedway was finally nearing an end and track owner
Bob Bahre soon would close it out the same way he finishes most
race weekends: by getting in his car and driving home to South
Paris, Maine.
</P>
<P>
   For the second straight NASCAR event at the track, the weekend
started with a driver killed when he slammed into the concrete wall
in Turn 3 during a practice run.
</P>
<P>
   Winston Cup driver Kenny Irwin crashed and died late Friday
morning in much the same manner that Busch Series driver Adam Petty
crashed and died May 12.
</P>
<P>
   The deaths stunned the racing community and had drivers and crew
members and the media questioning whether there is something wrong
with the cars or the track.
</P>
<P>
   Bahre, as he did earlier in the weekend, defended his track.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the track is fine,'' he said. ``It was good for 10
years and you have trouble one year. I think that should be the
answer.''
</P>
<P>
   The deaths were the first in NASCAR-sanctioned events at the
track since it opened in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   That they happened on the same spot on the track, in scarily
similar fashion and within eight weeks of each other, raised
concerns throughout the NASCAR garage area.
</P>
<P>
   Drivers and crew members talked of stuck throttles and
mechanical problems and NASCAR promised to look at that issue
again.
</P>
<P>
   And drivers and crew members brought up the tight corners at the
ends of this track and how there is little time to recover if there
is a problem, partly because there is little banking in those
corners. They talked of the styrofoam barriers that are used at
some tracks to protect cars from some corners and how NASCAR should
perhaps consider such barriers here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barricades would just blow all to pieces,'' Bahre said. ``All
they do is just fly everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Other tracks are at least as flat, Bahre said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's flatter tracks than this,'' he said. ``Milwaukee is
perfectly flat. There's Phoenix, which is flatter. You've got
Martinsville, Christ, you've got flat tracks.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Helton, NASCAR's chief operating officer, said Saturday
that he thinks fingers should not be pointed at the track.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think every facility we go to is unique and has its own
different characteristics,'' he said. ``I don't know why we've had
two accidents here in such a short period of time that are very
similar to each other, but those answers are tough to come up
with.''
</P>
<P>
   He gave no indication that the organization will study the
facility.
</P>
<P>
   If NASCAR does check out the track, Bahre said, he certainly
will listen.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my opinion the track is fine, but if NASCAR says to me we
want this done or that done, it will be done,'' Bahre said. ``I
talk to NASCAR quite often, it's all up to them. But as far as when
anything happens, if a skier gets killed going down a hill, people
(complain) the tree shouldn't have been there, you know what I
mean? Nothing's ever going to be perfect in life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't get me wrong. I'm not saying this is right by any means,
what happened. But at the same time, things happen. Look at
Daytona, they had two deaths in one weekend (in 1994). At a race
two weeks ago at a half-mile track in the Midwest a guy got
killed.''
</P>
<P>
   That said, this was one rough weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good to have it behind you,'' Bahre said. ``This is kind
of behind us and you pray to God nothing ever happens again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
