<SLUG> BC-CAR-NE300-NEMECHEK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERE'S A SWITCH _ NEMECHEK IS 2D 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUDON, N.H. _ Last season's Dura-Lube/ K-Mart 300 victory at
New Hampshire International Speedway was the first of Joe
Nemechek's Winston Cup career.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday at NHIS, Nemechek couldn't overcome the weather nor
winner Tony Stewart, and settled for a second-place finish in the
rain-shortened New England 300, pocketing $107,550 for his efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Starting 30th in his Oakwood Homes Chevrolet, Nemechek made up
steady ground and led the race for three laps, 187-189. He took
over second on Lap 220, and trailed only Stewart when the race was
called with 27 laps remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only time we led was when we started making green-flag pit
stops,'' said Nemechek, from Lakeland, Fla. ``Tony was doing
exactly what I would have done in the lead. I was trying to run as
hard as I could. He knows you've got to run as hard as you can
every lap. There's no conserving. You've got to get as many guys
down a lap as you can. When he pitted, I kept my pace until we had
to pit.''
</P>
<P>
   It helped that Nemechek switched engines Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our motor shop was working on the engine in the morning, and
we overcame some odds by doing what we did,'' he said. ``We didn't
use the same engine that we had used in the qualifier. We had a
good feeling with the engine, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of those close-but-not-enough days. I was in
control all day, we passed a lot of cars early, and Tony was tough.
I wasn't quite sure if I had anything left, our cars were quite
comparable. I wish I could have run with him more by putting more
pressure on him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony could get through traffic better and I would get held up.
He would get that distance. I was held up more than he was.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither driver had much gas left when the race was winding down.
``That was the big question, we think we would have had enough to
get to a couple of laps from the end with the gas we had,''
Nemechek said. ``I'm sure we had enough to go all the way, we were
in a lot better shape than Tony was, and a lot better than some of
the cars behind us.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't sure how we would do with the gas, so I focused on
Tony in trying to run faster laps. I was sure that there would be
rain on the 190th lap. We pretty much expected it to come at that
time. I never asked if we could make it, though.''
</P>
<P>
   It's been an interesting year for Nemechek, who finished fifth
at the Cracker Barrel in Atlanta and seventh at the Coca-Cola 600
in Charlotte, N.C. He also has had an eighth and two ninths. But
there were times Nemechek didn't even finish, suffering two
accidents as well as engine and oil pressure problems.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, there was also the issue of maintaining his focus. The
death of Kenny Irwin, killed during a practice lap Friday, hit very
close to home for Nemechek. His brother, John, died while racing at
Miami Homestead in March, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're out there focusing on what you have to do, you try
to block out everything you can as perfectly as you can,'' Nemechek
said. ``The accident happened this week and it hit no one harder
than it did me. I keep asking myself why these things are happening
to these young men. I've been thinking about it since it
happened.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
