<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAIL-MAHONY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDINAL PREACHES TO INMATES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 &HT;    By ERIK NELSON  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Following the example of Pope John Paul II, who
led thousands of Roman Catholic clerics into prisons worldwide,
Cardinal Roger Mahony preached the words of St. Paul to about 240
inmates in the Los Angeles County Men's Central Jail on Sunday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   Even the apostle ``was wrestling with the fact that he is a weak
man, he is a sinner, and he has many faults and failures,'' the
cardinal said in his English and Spanish sermon to the inmates in
jumpsuits of royal blue, lime-green and white.
</P>
<P>
   Mahony urged the inmates, although they dwell behind locked
gates, to ``open wide the doors of our hearts and our lives'' to
divine help.
</P>
<P>
   ``The amazing thing is Jesus does not force himself into our
lives,'' said Mahony, who celebrated Mass and distributed Communion
wafers with the bishops of Orange County and Salt Lake City. ``He
stands at the door to our lives and knocks.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles County Sheriff Lee Baca called the day ``a wonderful
opportunity for inmates to reflect on their lives and get in touch
with their spirituality.'' He said the church's worldwide interest
in prisoners helps show inmates that their lives have value.
</P>
<P>
   After the Mass in the concrete-walled chapel, the serene
countenances and messages of the cardinal and bishops were replaced
by the stern faces and orders of sheriff's deputies. The host of
deputies, who serve as jail guards, commanded the inmates to stand
and walk single file from the chapel.
</P>
<P>
   The special celebration in jail was part of the Roman Catholic
observation of this year as a time for reinvigorating the church's
vision, according to a printed statement released by Mahony.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the inmates left with a card commemorating the day as
the Jubilee in the Prisons of the World. The back of the card shows
the pope offering forgiveness to the man convicted of shooting him
in 1981, Mehmet Ali Agca. The photograph is framed by the words
``justice,'' ``conversion'' and ``forgiveness'' in several
languages, including English and Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   Catholic clergy, including bishops from around the country who
had been attending a conference in Los Angeles, visited jails and
prisons throughout the Southland.
</P>
<P>
   Mahony faced a calm and quiet congregation in which several men
lifted their palms skyward during prayers. One inmate sketched a
portrait of the cardinal. Mahony said, ``I like that because it
shows me as much younger than I am.''
</P>
<P>
   But the celebration was canceled at the North County
Correctional Facility in Lancaster because a brawl erupted there
the previous night between African-Americans and Latinos, according
to spokesmen for the Archdiocese of Los Angeles and the Sheriff's
Department.
</P>
<P>
   Eight inmates suffered minor injuries in the disturbance at 8:20
p.m. Saturday, said sheriff's Deputy Carlos Lopez. Guards fired
rubber pellets and crowd-control gas to stop the fight, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Rome, the pope celebrated Mass behind bars, the Associated
Press reported. About 75 prisoners and twice as many guards
surrounded John Paul II in Regina Coeli, the city's oldest prison.
He appealed to authorities for a sign of clemency. Italian
officials have been grappling with clemency as a form of relief for
overcrowding.
</P>
<P>
   ``Punishment, prison only make sense if, while affirming the
needs of justice and discouraging crime, they serve man's
renewal,'' AP quoted the pope.
</P>
<P>
   Mahony's message was similar: ``We are called to stand in
solidarity with those who are incarcerated and with the victims of
crime and their family members.'' Catholic parishioners need ``to
assess how they can more actively assist victims of violent crime,
pTUZilrs and their respective family members in order to facilitate
the restoration of our communities,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the same light, society at large must promote more
effective alternatives to our current criminal justice system.
Revenge must give way to restoration so that the possibility of
healing can be actualized.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
