<HEADLINE>
ERSTAD HELPS ANGELS WIN FOURTH STRAIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GORDON VERRELL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ What kind of season is Darin Erstad having? In
the seventh inning Sunday evening at Edison Field, the Anaheim
Angels left fielder grounded out. And he received a loud, standing
ovation from the 23,820 fans.
</P>
<P>
   It was the only time the Colorado Rockies got Erstad out and
even then, his grounder to short drove home a run in the Angels'
10-4 win, their season-high fourth in a row.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels arrive at the All-Star break a season-best six games
above .500 and, better yet, with big hopes for the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said all along, this team has yet to play its best
ball,'' said Erstad, who had two doubles and two singles, drove in
two runs, scored three runs and stole a base.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're clicking right now,'' Erstad went on. ``We're heading in
the right direction and we'll have some fresh bodies when we come
back (after the All-Star Game).''
</P>
<P>
   If any are even half as fresh as Erstad's, well. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't found a thing this guy can't do,'' manager Mike
Scioscia said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at his run production,'' Scioscia said, ``his home runs,
his stolen bases, his tremendous defense, the way he hits in the
clutch. It's contagious. Everybody feeds off what he's doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Erstad heads off to Atlanta for Tuesday's All-Star Game with a
major- league-leading 144 hits, the most since Ralph Garr's
pre-All-Star Game total of 149 in 1974, and only four shy of his
entire 1999 total of 148; a major-league-leading 47 multihit games,
including 13 in his past 18 games; and a .384 batting average,
second in the majors only to Boston's Nomar Garciaparra (.389).
</P>
<P>
   ``Phenomenal,'' Scioscia said. ``Man, he's exciting to watch.
But, I know this: He'd trade his All-Star appearance for a playoff
appearance.''
</P>
<P>
   That's down the line, of course, but the Angels at least are
talking about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't come close to our expectations,'' Erstad said.
``There are two very good teams in front of us. We can't slip or
falter in any way.''
</P>
<P>
   Angels starter Kent Bottenfield did a little of both early
Sunday evening, but he got it together well enough to pitch into
the eighth inning and emerge with his fifth win in 12 decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows he can bend and not break,'' Scioscia said after
Bottenfield twice let early leads get away. ``But he didn't panic.
He made his pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I'm not far off my game,'' said Bottenfield, ``but it
was an emotional roller coaster. It was frustrating, but things are
starting to feel normal. Pitching into the eighth (which he hadn't
done in almost two months) was a big thing for me emotionally.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels opened the first with four successive hits off
Colorado starter Masato Yoshii (4-9), including three doubles in a
row by Erstad, Kevin Stocker and Mo Vaughn. That provided
Bottenfield with a 3-0 lead, which lasted all the way until the
second inning. The reeling Rockies, losers of seven in a row, tied
the score with four consecutive hits of their own.
</P>
<P>
   Garret Anderson's home run - his 26th, which established an
Angels record for most homers before the All-Star break - with two
outs in the third put the Angels on top again 4-3, only for
Colorado to tie the score in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, in the bottom of the fourth, the Angels knocked out
Yoshii, scoring three times. This time Bottenfield, after giving up
eight hits the first four innings, allowed only two more hits
before leaving after 7 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Fittingly, it was Erstad's third of four hits, a double to
center, that knocked in the go-ahead run in the Angels' fourth.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels added one more run in the sixth - on a run-scoring
double by Stocker off Colorado reliever Gabe White, which snapped
his franchise- record scoreless streak at 29 innings - and two more
in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   The second run in the seventh was set up by Orlando Palmeiro's
grounder to first, which moved Adam Kennedy to third. That enabled
him to score the Angels' final run on Erstad's sharp grounder to
short.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was huge,'' Erstad said afterward. ``Whenever we get guys
in scoring position, we've got to score them ... you've got to
pound that last nail in the coffin, and that's how you do it. I tip
my hat to Orlando.''
</P>
<P>
   He even does that well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
