<HEADLINE>
CANADA CAN'T PLAY THROUGH U.S. PAYNE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE IRVINE  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ALAMITOS, Calif. _ U.S. goalkeeper Nicolle Payne admitted
she was uncomfortable nearly the entire match Sunday when the
American national team met Canada in a tight game for the Holiday
Cup championship.
</P>
<P>
   But not nearly as uncomfortable as she would have been if she
was sitting on the sideline watching Brenda Villa score three goals
as the U.S. held off their arch-rivals 5-4 to win the tournament
title before 2,200 at the U.S. National Aquatic Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because we never had a big lead, I never was comfortable,''
said Payne, who had 13 saves, including eight in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Payne, a four-time national champion at UCLA, began the
tournament as the team's backup goalkeeper to Bernice Orwig, who
was in goal for April's Olympic Qualification Tournament in Italy.
Payne, the team's goalie in wins over Australia and Kazakhstan
during round-robin play, ended the six-day tournament cradling the
hardware honoring the Holiday Cup's most outstanding goalkeeper and
celebrating six consecutive victories for the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a hard year with a lot of ups and downs,'' said
Payne, who was the team's starting goalkeeper for a couple of
years, including during the 1999 Fina World Cup, before being
unseated by Orwig. ``I want to be out there. But I'm also a team
person. It sucks we both can't be out there. If I'm not out there,
I at least want to push Bernie and make her the best goalkeeper she
can be.''
</P>
<P>
   The Holiday Cup championship can be categorized as an up for
Payne and the U.S. team. But U.S. coach Guy Baker said the 6-0
record against the five other teams in the Olympic field doesn't
make the Americans the Sydney favorite.
</P>
<P>
   ``Australia and Holland are still the favorites,'' Baker said.
``They have the resumes. But we're gonna show up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
