<SLUG> BC-AIDS-MEETING-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-ART-790(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.C.)  
 MBEKI'S SPEECH DISAPPOINTS SCIENTISTS AT AIDS CONFERENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Corrects spelling of Charles van der Horst's name throughout) 
 (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888 603-1036
or 888 346-9867.) 
 By RACHEL L. SWARNS and LAWRENCE K. ALTMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DURBAN, South Africa _ Opening the first international
conference on AIDS in a developing country, South African President
Thabo Mbeki Sunday singled out extreme poverty, rather than the
disease ravaging his country and continent, as the leading killer
both here and across Africa.
</P>
<P>
   South Africa is the country with the largest number of people
infected with HIV, the AIDS virus _ 4.2 million _ and its
president, who has become embroiled in international controversy
over the causes of the disease, pledged to intensify his response.
But he dashed the hopes of thousands of participants _ and noisy
protesters _ who wanted to hear him state clearly that HIV causes
AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Mbeki skirted the controversy that has arisen because
he has questioned the use of certain drugs in treating HIV, and has
even questioned whether the virus causes AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Among the many researchers he has contacted in his quest to
understand the epidemic are two U.S. biochemists, Peter Duesberg
and David Rasnick, who argue that poverty and malnutrition, not
HIV, cause AIDS. When word of this consultation became public,
international consternation arose.
</P>
<P>
   As Mbeki described his attempts to understand how one of the
worst epidemics in history has enveloped his country just as it
freed itself from apartheid, he reflected on AIDS and a long list
of other diseases afflicting his country.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I listened and heard the whole story told about our own
country, it seemed to me that we could not blame everything on a
single virus,'' Mbeki said.
</P>
<P>
   The 13th international conference on AIDS is being held as U.N.
officials have been intensifying the alarm about HIV, which infects
34.3 million people in the world, mostly in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes after Mbeki finished talking, Dr. Peter Piot, the head
of UNAIDS, a U.N. program that monitors the spread of AIDS, said it
will take at least $3 billion a year to deliver the basic measures
in Africa and tens of billions of dollars more each year to provide
in Africa the standard drugs used to treat the disease in developed
countries.
</P>
<P>
   The $3 billion figure is ten times what is now being spent in
Africa, Piot said. UNAIDS estimates that 90 percent of people with
HIV do not know they are infected.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need billions, not millions, to fight AIDS in the world,''
and ``we can't fight an epidemic of this magnitude with peanuts,''
Piot said.
</P>
<P>
   In news conferences and interviews, Piot said he welcomed a
pledge of $500 million from the World Bank this weekend as a
positive step. He said the remainder needs to come from the
affected African countries and the developed countries.
</P>
<P>
   Piot urged developed countries to cancel the $15 billion in debt
repayment that African countries have incurred each year and return
it so countries can use the money for health care and social
services for AIDS and other diseases.
</P>
<P>
   But political will is as important as money in stopping the AIDS
epidemic, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past six years, scientists and AIDS activists have
repeatedly criticized South African leaders for their lack of
leadership in combatting the AIDS epidemic. In 1993, HIV infected 4
percent of South Africa's adult population. Now, it is 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night, as conference participants drifted out of the
cricket grounds where Mbeki spoke, many left feeling disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We, the majority of South African scientists, would have liked
a clear, unequivocal statement about the relationship between HIV
and AIDS rather than the hints he made,'' said Alan Whiteside, who
heads the AIDS research program at the University of Natal in
Durban.
</P>
<P>
   Whiteside and others said they were encouraged by Mbeki's pledge
to intensify his recently announced program to encourage safe sex
and to sponsor additional research into drug therapy and a possible
vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of people conducted a protest rally at City Hall hours
before the meeting opened, with Winnie Madikizela-Mandela and
others in the crowd berating the government for failing to speak
frankly about the link between HIV and AIDS and lagging in its
efforts to fight the epidemic.
</P>
<P>
   ``AIDS exists, HIV causes AIDS,'' Madikizela-Mandela said. ``We
cannot proclaim this century the African century and then ignore
the AIDS pandemic as some political leaders are.''
</P>
<P>
   Mbeki did speak about the heavy toll of HIV and AIDS on young
people. He also spoke about the toll from malaria, cholera,
syphilis, Vitamin A deficiency, and ``other illnesses with
complicated Latin names'' as among the diseases of poverty.
</P>
<P>
   The text of Mbeki's remarks released in advance of his speech
said: ``The world's biggest killer and the greatest cause of ill
health and suffering across the globe, including South Africa, is
extreme poverty.''
</P>
<P>
   When he spoke, he omitted that passage, but referred explicitly
to a 1995 report by the World Health Organization that described
poverty as the world's largest killer. ``Five years later,'' he
added, ``the essential elements of this story have not changed.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A strong hint that Mbeki would disappoint most AIDS conference
participants in not saying that HIV causes AIDS came earlier in the
day when scientists canceled a news conference because of what they
said was pressure from the South African government.
</P>
<P>
   The news conference had been scheduled to discuss a statement
signed by 5,000 scientists in the world and known as the Durban
Declaration. It affirmed that scientific evidence supporting the
link between HIV and AIDS is ``clear cut, exhaustive and
unambiguous'' and was published in the July 6 issue of the
scientific journal, Nature, after review by scientific peers.
</P>
<P>
   But the news conference was unexpectedly canceled minutes before
it was to begin. The reason was that ``the South African government
put pressure on us'' and threatened to dismiss any signatory who
worked for the government, said Dr. Charles van der Horst, a
professor of medicine at the University of North Carolina who
signed the Durban Declaration.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, van der Horst declined to name the government
official who made the call and said the South African scientist who
received it was a representative of the Durban Declaration. The
unidentified official spoke on behalf of Mbeki, van der Horst said
he was told.
</P>
<P>
   Tasneem Carrima, a spokesman for Mbeki, denied knowledge of any
such threat. ``We certainly would not threaten anybody,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The declaration came in response to Mbeki's decision to appoint
a panel to review the claims of dissidents who do not believe that
HIV causes AIDS, van der Horst said. The panel included such
dissidents and experts who signed the Durban Declaration.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought no one would give the denialists credence, and we
were wrong,'' van der Horst said.
</P>
<P>
   Van der Horst criticized the scientific community for not having
published a summary statement earlier of all the scientific
evidence that HIV causes AIDS. Now, by giving a platform to a small
group of dissidents, Mbeki has helped to divert efforts to fight
AIDS, Van der Horst said.
</P>
<P>
   Becoming embroiled in new arguments over the causes of AIDS
diverts attention and resources from finding a solution, several
scientists say.
</P>
<P>
   The declaration was intended as a scientific statement because
it was published in a scientific journal, van der Horst said.
However, he said, the South African government viewed the
declaration as a political statement. After the declaration was
released last week, Mbeki's spokesman, Parks Mankahlana, said it
should be thrown in the dustbin.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Mbeki's government tempered its stringent criticism
of anti-HIV drug therapy by announcing that it had reversed its
view about AZT, which it had deemed unsafe for pregnant women.
</P>
<P>
   In discussing his administration's plan to battle AIDS and
responding to critics, Mbeki said ``there is no substance to the
allegation that there is any hesitation on the part of our
government to confront the challenge of HIV/AIDS.''
</P>
<P>
   Piot said that underdeveloped countries, though poor, will have
to spend more on AIDS because ``it is about the survival of the
nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Mbeki and Piot are leaving the conference early to attend a
meeting of the Organization of African Unity in Lome, Togo, where
AIDS is to be discussed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
