<HEADLINE>
FOSTER CARE SPENDING ON GIFTS QUESTIONED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 &HT;    By TROY ANDERSON  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS AA0WeH k+$ 9Y &QC; 19Q pa!l0Los Angeles County
for the first time has decided to give 675 children leaving foster
care on their 18th birthday a valuable going-away gift: new laptop
computers and 500 telephone cards.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say`:)e $2.5 million worth of computers and phone cards
paid for with a windfall $3.5 million surplus could be better spent
by a county that hasn't computerized some of iM7 +:n vital records.
</P>
<P>
   But county officials defended their decision, saying the
computers will help the college-bound teens enter society as
adults.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this day and age, computers are important in the lives of
young people,'' said Anita Bock, director of the county Department
of Children and Family Services. ``There is a growing recognition
that if we don't help these children with relatively minor expenses
now, they end up on welfare or in prison, and we all know what the
cost of that is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think children in foster care deserve every chance that
other children in America have to succeed,'' said Bock, who took
over  &LR; -Q/Y8Irt[Y7t la.] Uul &UR;
</P>
<P>
   The decision to buy computers comes despite a critical grand
jury report that found the department lacks computer-based and
manual systems to maintain ``even the most basic data, such as
up-to-date lists of certified foster families and their
addresses.''
</P>
<P>
   Some say the county is too quick to spend money.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goodness,'' said Jon Coupal, president of the Howard Jarvis
Taxpayers A &UR; rJtion. ``This is reflective of the use-it-or-lose-it
mentality of government. Private business does not work this way.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they have ongoing needs, they should be able to put it in a
reserve account and use it for worthwhile projects.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the youngsters &QC; M(ceivZ7g a ,+WW.KHjK-.ZYV$CHWV.ZY$)YK+
