<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSING-AZR </SLUG>
  
BC-HOUSING-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    SHELTER INSPIRES VALLEY OFFICIALS(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By william Hermann(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE - Envy tinged the voice of Maricopa County Supervisor
Mary Rose Wilcox last week as she gazed around a modern, sunlit
building here.
</P>
<P>
   ``(beginitalic)This(enditalic) is a homeless shelter?'' she
murmured as fellow Supervisor Jan Brewer stood nearby, shaking her
head in disbelief at the Montgomery Street Inn, a shelter for
homeless men.
</P>
<P>
   The spacious central dining hall features skylights in a high
ceiling. Men live in spotlessly clean, curtained cubicles.
Restrooms are immaculate.
</P>
<P>
   ``How did you get the capital to build this?'' asked Wilcox, who
with Brewer and other Valley leaders came to observe the shelter
and meet with Santa Clara County officials.
</P>
<P>
   Christine Burroughs, director of the charitable group InnVision,
smiled. ``All of us'' - she gestured at about 20 other Santa Clara
officials - ``pooled our knowledge and resources to make this and
places like it possible,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The visiting Valley officials want to make it possible in their
county, too. They've been agonizing over how to deal with the
Phoenix area's own growing homeless population, now numbering about
15,000.
</P>
<P>
   Most immediately, Valley leaders are trying to figure out how to
replace the aging, crowded Central Arizona Shelter Services
building in downtown Phoenix. It is the Valley's largest shelter,
but its decrepit condition and the fact that it stands in the way
of downtown redevelopment make moving it a top priority.
</P>
<P>
   But efforts to move CASS ``have been a mess,'' Wilcox said.
``There is controversy over where to put it, and even a greater
question over who will pay for it - the state, the county, the
city-who?''
</P>
<P>
   Former Phoenix Mayor Terry Goddard, now with the U.S. Department
of Housing and Urban Development, said haphazard efforts to move
CASS are symptoms of a greater problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't had a comprehensive approach to fighting
homelessness here,'' Goddard said. ``There are many city, county,
state, private agency folks helping the homeless, but they haven't
worked very well together. Now, they're making a good beginning
effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix officials once coordinated regional applications to HUD
for funds to fight homelessness Valley-wide, Goddard said, but gave
up that role last year. Now the Maricopa Association of Governments
is beginning to knit together efforts of local governments and
agencies to deal with homeless issues.
</P>
<P>
   But Goddard and many officials think local efforts need help.
Hence, the trip to California.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Clara and Alameda counties have been recognized by HUD as
among the most successful in the nation at taking a comprehensive
approach to homeless issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have brought every agency-government, church, private-to
the table,'' Goddard said. ``They have extraordinary non-profit and
governmental agency cooperation. Everyone involved is at the table,
enthusiastic, and they are there with money.''
</P>
<P>
   The trip to California included key players in Valley efforts to
end homelessness, among them the two county supervisors, former
Arizona Supreme Court Chief Justice Frank Gordon, officials from
Phoenix, Tempe and Mesa, a Catholic agency director, and
private-sector representatives. Gordon will lead MAG's efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to bring in all the Valley cities in, need the Board
of Supervisors to be the driver on this effort, but we particularly
need to get private industry to come in with significant funds,''
Gordon said. ``We saw how Santa Clara County worked with industry
to create a $20million trust fund. That should be an example for
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Guy Mikkelsen, head of the Catholic Diocese of Phoenix
Foundation for Senior Living, said, ``We've all been dealing with
homeless problems piecemeal. Terry has been trying impress upon us
the competitive nature of grants and how we have to work together
to secure federal funds. People now see that.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilcox said, ``I've been talking with Arnold Ramirez, who is
here for Phoenix, and we're going to get together and look at the
county and city as one entity instead of two.''
</P>
<P>
   Brewer said the responsibility for moving CASS ``is one we all
must shoulder.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The county should be the facilitator,'' she said. ``Part of
the financial solution may be using dollars available through HUD.
Other money should be raised from the private sector. Everyone must
step to the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're doing it up here,'' Brewer said. ``We can do it too.''
</P>
<P>
   Reach the reporter at William.Hermann(a)Arizona &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Republic.com or (602-444-4875.
</P>
