A7561 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-COALITION-BOS &LR;      07-10 1131
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-COALITION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFECTIONS FELL BARAK'S COALITION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Prime Minister Ehud Barak's governing coalition has
collapsed on the eve of his departure for a Camp David summit and a
historic opportunity to clinch a far-reaching Israeli-Palestinian
peace deal.
</P>
<P>
   Three right-wing and religious parties, including Barak's
largest coalition partner, announced they were quitting the
government, reducing Barak's support in Parliament from a 68-52
majority to a 48-72 minority.
</P>
<P>
   Several key ministers in Barak's Cabinet handed in letters of
resignation. Foreign Minister David Levy announced he would boycott
the US-hosted talks.
</P>
<P>
   The defection, analysts said, was triggered by Barak's failure
to build a consensus before the summit, and by a perception in the
conservative wing of the coalition that he would turn over too much
West Bank land to the Palestinians at the bargaining table.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the crisis that swirled around him, Barak vowed to leave
for Tuesday's summit at the Maryland presidential retreat with
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing on national television Sunday night, Barak appealed to
Israelis, saying, ``I ask you to stand behind me . . . and join me
in the big prayer of us all, the prayer to see peace and security
for Israel at a time when we are facing the most important and
greatest challenge ever to stand before us.''
</P>
<P>
   Adding more drama to the pre-summit political tempest, Barak and
his Labor/One Israel Party government are set Monday to face a
previously scheduled no confidence vote. The measure, introduced by
the conservative Likud party opposition, requires 61 votes in the
120-member Knesset to topple Barak and force early elections.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts on Israel Radio confidently predicted that Barak would
thwart the measure by cobbling together support from leftist
Israeli and Arab Israeli parliamentary members.
</P>
<P>
   Both Barak and Arafat are hemmed in by domestic political
pressures. Barak's troubles broke wide open in Israel's unruly
political arena Sunday. But Arafat also has mounting pressure on
him to deliver the benefits of peace as frustration mounts in the
West Bank and Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
   Tension flared in Gaza Sunday after Israeli soldiers stationed
at a settlement fired on a passing taxi, killing a Palestinian
woman and severely wounding her infant son and her husband. Two
other civilians also were wounded. The Israeli military apologized
to the Palestinian Authority over the incident, saying shots had
been fired on the settlement, and the soldiers believed the taxi to
be the source of the shooting. Palestinian officials disputed the
Israeli version of events, saying that the Israeli soldiers fired
without provocation on innocent civilians.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said the Middle East ``can move forward toward
peace, or can slide back into turmoil'' depending on the outcome of
these talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the parties do not seize this moment to make more progress,
there will be more hostility and more bitterness _ perhaps even
more violence,'' the president wrote in Newsweek magazine. ``While
there clearly is no guarantee of success, not to try would
guarantee failure.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Barak and Arafat go into the talks looking over their
shoulders, knowing that even if they can reach a deal they may not
be able to sell it to their constituents back home. Barak,
especially, will be restricted at the talks by the domestic
political crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli newspaper reports in the days running up to the summit
said Barak was prepared to cede more than 80 percent of the West
Bank to Palestinians _ an amount that falls short of Palestinian
expectations yet is seen as a dangerous betrayal by Israeli
conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians currently have full or partial control over
roughly 40 percent of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   The rebelling members of Barak's coalition say the West Bank,
which was captured by Israel in the 1967 Six-Day War, is the
biblical birthright of the Jews and crucial to the security of
Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, a 35-year veteran of Israel's military and its most
highly decorated soldier, fired back at his critics, saying, ``No
one will teach me what security is.''
</P>
<P>
   But Barak's leadership style _ as a general who hunkers down and
makes his own decisions without informing even his allies of the
details _ appears to have backfired.
</P>
<P>
   Interior Minister Natan Sharansky, head of a right-leaning
Russian immigrant party, was the first coalition partner to quit
Sunday. He told reporters, ``I've just now turned in my resignation
letter to the prime minister. As I told him this morning, I believe
it's a big mistake that he travels to Washington without drafting a
joint stance of coalition members. As a result of this, there were
all sorts of understandings with the Palestinians which are not
acceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   Just hours later, the powerful ultra-Orthodox Shas Party
announced it too was leaving the government. The National Religious
Party was the next to vow to defect.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no support for your trip,'' Shas Party chairman Eli
Yishai told Barak in comments to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   By law, Cabinet resignations take effect after 48 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Levy, Barak's foreign minister, also turned down an invitation
to join Barak at the summit. Analysts said Levy was angry that he
was marginalized by Barak during secret negotiations with the
Palestinians that reportedly led up to the summit.
</P>
<P>
   Israel and the Palestinians are heading to the United States for
the summit in an effort to finalize a deal by a self-imposed Sept.
13 deadline to have resolved the most difficult issues surrounding
the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   The issues include not only the final borders, but the status of
Jerusalem, which both sides see as their capital, the future of
Jewish settlements built in the West Bank, and the fate of some 3
million Palestinian refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, elected last year with a sweeping majority who supported
his avowal to reach a peace agreement, has promised to hold a
referendum on any deal before he signs it.
</P>
<P>
   So it seems Barak may be willing and able to go over the heads
of his coalition partners in bringing a momentous peace deal with
Palestinians directly to the voters themselves.
</P>
<P>
   And Barak has been publicly confident that if an agreement is
reached at Camp David, it will be approved by an overwhelming
majority of Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   He has also objected to right-wing criticisms that he should
have informed Israel of the precise ``red line,'' or limits of
proposed borders, ahead of the talks. To do so, he said, would
weaken Israel's negotiating position.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
