BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE--AZR(a) 
 &HT;    NEW &AMP; NOTABLE BOOK REVIEWS(a) 
 &HT;    (Duplication warning: Moving in ``E'' and ``L'' categories) 
 &HT;    ((For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By ANNE STEPHENSON(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 Special for The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are Anne Stephenson's capsule reviews of new book:
</P>
<P>
   ``Jim the Boy''
</P>
<P>
   ByTony Earley
</P>
<P>
   (Little, Brown, $23.95)
</P>
<P>
   It's difficult to describe a book like this, a small gem that
appears without fanfare and quietly puts other novels to shame.
It's the story of 10-year-old Jim Glass, whose father died a week
before he was born and who has been raised by his mother and her
three unmarried brothers, known collectively to Jim as ``the
uncles.'' They are a makeshift but solid family, working their
North Carolina farm during the years of the Great Depression. The
action, like the book cover, is deceptively simple, involving a new
suitor for Jim's mother, a new friend for Jim at school and a trip
with one of his uncles that opens Jim's eyes to the world beyond
the small town of Aliceville. Earley, who writes beautifully and
yet with studied restraint, creates a tangible world with these
characters and--bO,Y &UR; .H:hY deep 9
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-00 0803EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000710.0044 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 08:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7563 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l BC-KIDSBOOKS-AZR &LR;      07-10 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDSBOOKS-AZR </SLUG>
  
 BC-KNOWLEDGE-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    CHILDREN'S BOOKS HOLD REAL ANSWERS(a) 
 &HT;    (Duplication warning: Moving in the ``E'' and ``L'' categories) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By RICHARD NILSEN(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We all have our embarrassing little secrets. Mine is that I read
children's books.
</P>
<P>
   I started when I was a small boy, raiding our tiny elementary
school library for such kinder classics as Roy Chapman Andrew's
(beginitalic)All About Dinosaurs, (enditalic)and have continued to
this day.
</P>
<P>
   It was never the fictional or fairy tale books I latched onto
but the histories, biographies, science and natural history books.
Herbert S. Zim was my god.
</P>
<P>
   The books were filled with the answers to the questions I had
when I was in third grade. Why do some whales have teeth and others
baleen? How does an airplane stay in the air? Why is an egg shaped
that way?
</P>
<P>
   I still have questions, and books still provide answers. Or when
they don't give me answers, they show me the path to find my own
answer.
</P>
<P>
   But sometimes jumping straight into a serious adult tome is
confusing. The experts who write them know much more than I do. And
they don't care about my ignorance. As a result, they can write
well beyond my poor ability to understand them on first go-round.
They are either written with the assumption that you already have
the rudiments, or they are polemical and assume you know the
disputed territory, or they are specialist books filled with a new
vocabulary you haven't learned yet.
</P>
<P>
   That's where children's books come in.
</P>
<P>
   Children's books give you the simplified, coherent version that
the adult books won't deign to provide.
</P>
<P>
   I am aware that the version the children's book gives is often
distorted, grotesquely simplified and sometimes just plain wrong.
But that doesn't matter: They provide a start, a map to the subject
at hand and give you an orientation that can later be fleshed out,
made more subtle and transcended. But you have to begin somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   It is important to realize that knowledge is not merely a
collection of facts. We are bombarded with facts daily, and it
hasn't made any of us smarter. It just means we have more to
forget. And we do.
</P>
<P>
   Knowledge is a set of interrelationships between facts. The
interrelationship has a shape and coherence that cannot be
constructed from the facts alone.
</P>
<P>
   I am reminded over and over about Einstein and facts. ``If I
need a fact, I can look it up,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   You can understand information by two different metaphors. I
choose what I call the ``tree of knowledge.'' It has roots and
branches and creates a unified, simple idea. There may be many
leaves on the tree, but if you keep the shape of the tree in mind,
the leaves - the facts - will turn out to be just where they need
to be.
</P>
<P>
   The other metaphor - the one we come across daily in TV
newscasts, magazine articles and written driving exams - is what I
call ``fact confetti.'' This is the blizzard of unconnected data
that piles up across our road. Get me a snowplow.
</P>
<P>
   If you think of history as a bunch of dates and names - 1588,
1492, June 6, A.D.79 - it's no wonder you have trouble remembering
it. But if you know the great flow, the big picture, all the
details make sense where they come.
</P>
<P>
   They are more than merely dates associated with the Spanish
Armada, the expulsion of Jews from Spain, D-Day or the destruction
of Pompeii, they are part of the inevitable flow of history.
</P>
<P>
   If you have a systemic view of anatomy, no bone will be
unconnected to its neighbor. If you know the division between
bivalves and univalves, the shells you find at the beach have an
instant home - a kind of mailbox in your brain - where they belong
and fit comfortably.
</P>
<P>
   I often have found that if I have forgotten a fact, I can
re-create it accurately by knowing its context. It is better to
know how the French Revolution fits into the change from the Age of
Enlightenment to the Age of Romanticism. If you feel the larger
flow, then you remember that the French Revolution (beginitalic)has
(enditalic)to come after the American one.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, once you have created enough of these ``trees of
knowledge'' on a large number of subjects, then you start seeing
the forest instead of the trees, and it becomes easier and easier
to fit a new shrub into the even larger system. All with almost
none of the pain of trying to learn facts by rote.
</P>
<P>
   Children's books give you a sense of the flow and very few
facts. If later you discover that the tree of knowledge you gained
from the kid's book is flawed, you can trim it or replant it, but
it has served its purpose. It has got you in the door.
</P>
<P>
   And, if you never get beyond a children's book, well, you still
know more than most people.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Contact the reporter at Richard.Nilsen(a)Arizona &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Republic.com or call (602) 444-8823.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Bustos/The Arizona Republic
</P>
</TEXT>
