<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 08:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7564 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-R-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBAC     07-10 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 16)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; THE COLONY OF UNREQUITED DREAMS &LR;  By Wayne Johnston. Anchor,
$14. The protagonist of this biographical novel is the weedy but
ambitious Joe Smallwood, who helped steer the incorporation of the
vast, mysterious island of Newfoundland into Canada and became the
province's first premier. ``Johnston's eloquent anti-epic is in its
thorny way a respectful tribute to a place more willful than even
its toughest inhabitants,'' Luc Sante wrote in The New York Times
Book Review in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NO OTHER BOOK: Selected Essays &LR;  By Randall Jarrell. Edited by
Brad Leithauser. Perennial/HarperCollins, $15. This collection of
the poet's major critical essays contains many valuations and
opinions _ about the pre-eminence of Frost, Eliot and Stevens in
the 20th-century pantheon of American poets, for example _ that
were once considered provocative but have become orthodoxy today.
``He was astute, insightful, passionate, sympathetic and remarkably
prophetic,'' Brooke Allen wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   In  &UR; THE BROKEN ESTATE: Essays on Literature and Belief &LR; , by
James Wood (Modern Library, $14.95), a combative critic explores
the transition from religious belief to literary belief in the 19th
century, and the effects of that shift on practitioners of fiction
from Melville to Pynchon. ``It is the excess, the polemical drive,
that makes him exhilarating to read, often to be instructed by,
sometimes to argue with,'' William H. Pritchard wrote in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MY RUSSIAN &LR;  By Deirdre McNamer. Ballantine, $14. After her
husband is wounded by an intruder and her lover, a Russian
gardener, drops out of sight, this novel's middle-aged heroine
assumes another identity to spy on her own life and try to correct
its course. ``McNamer is a careful writer, a master of the small,
telling observation,'' Susan Bolotin wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; JUNETEENTH &LR;  By Ralph Ellison. Edited by John F. Callahan.
Vintage International, $14. This tale of a racist white senator
raised as black, assembled from voluminous notes after Ellison's
death in 1994, never coheres as his second novel, Louis Menand
wrote last year. As a stew of various African-American oral
traditions, however, ``it is an interesting experiment'' that
features ``some quite Joycean riffs.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE MAJORS: In Pursuit of Golf's Holy Grail &LR;  By John Feinstein.
Back Bay/Little, Brown, $14.95. A reporter surveys 1998's four
major championships _ the Masters, the U.S. Open, the British Open
and the PGA Championship _ and the human dramas among both winners
and losers. ``If you want to know how touring pros think, on and
off the course,'' Dave Anderson wrote last year, ``this is the
book.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE MEME MACHINE &LR;  By Susan Blackmore. Oxford University,
$14.95. A psychologist sets out a Darwinian theory of cultural
evolution in which ``replicators'' _ words, beliefs and other
packets of shared data _ behave as biological genes to drive human
behavior. Last year in The New York Times Book Review, Robert
Wright called this an ``earnest and engaging, if not wholly
persuasive, book.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRUMPET &LR;  By Jackie Kay. Vintage Contemporaries, $13. This
Scottish novel about a famous trumpet player, which features
several narrators, is evidently inspired by the life of the
American jazz musician Billy Tipton, who passed as a man until her
death in 1989. The book ``leaves us with a broad landscape of sweet
tolerance and familial love,'' Aoibheann Sweeney wrote in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NO ONE LEFT TO LIE TO: The Triangulations of William Jefferson
Clinton &LR;  By Christopher Hitchens. Verso, $10. An unabashed Clinton
hater makes his case with a blunt assessment of the president's
personal flaws and amazing manipulative skills. Even if his attack
is obsessive, Karen Lehrman said last year, ``Hitchens' brave
willingness to show all the sordid scenarios in which our emperor
has removed his clothes is beyond refreshing.''
</P>
<P>
   In  &UR; UNCOVERING CLINTON: A Reporter's Story &LR; , by Michael Isikoff
(Three Rivers, $14), the journalist responsible for many of the
revelations about Bill Clinton's sexual indiscretions defends his
work and explains how he lost scoops because of his editors'
hesitations. ``Isikoff makes a plausible case ... for continuing to
pursue a story that could possibly have brought down a president,''
Tom Goldstein wrote in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SURRENDER, DOROTHY &LR;  By Meg Wolitzer. Washington Square/Pocket
Books, $12.95. This novel explores the aftershocks of a woman's
sudden death on her friends and family, in particular the strange
jealousies that emerge among the survivors. In 1999 the reviewer
Sylvia Brownrigg admired the author's ``knack for wry comedy'' and
her ``easy and astute'' observations about her characters' lives.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE BOY IN THE LAKE &LR;  By Eric Swanson. St. Martin's Griffin,
$11.95. In this elegiac novel, a New York therapist returns to his
Ohio hometown after his grandmother's death and tries to make up
with a boyhood lover whom he had cruelly betrayed. ``Swanson writes
surely, sometimes beautifully,'' Peter Kurth wrote last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
