<HEADLINE>
BEST SELLERS: PAPERBACK BOOKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For release on Sunday, July 16)  
(Eds: This file is the abbreviated best-seller list for paperback
books. See BESTSELLERS-PAPER-L-NYT for the full version that
includes how many weeks each book has been on the list.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rankings reflect sales figures for the week ending July 1 at
almost 4,000 bookstores plus wholesalers serving 60,000 other
retailers, statistically weighted to represent sales in all such
outlets nationwide. The number of titles within the two
subdivisions of nonfiction can change from week to week, reflecting
changes in book buying.
</P>
<P>
   An (x) following a book's ranking indicates that a book's sales
are barely distinguishable from those of the book above. A (b)
indicates that some bookstores report receiving bulk orders for a
book.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FICTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. TEARS OF THE MOON, by Nora Roberts. (Jove, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   An Irish songwriter, shut off from the world, finds hope
</P>
<P>
   and happiness with a tomboy.
</P>
<P>
   2. THE POISONWOOD BIBLE, by Barbara Kingsolver.
</P>
<P>
   (Perennial/HarperCollins, $14.) Five female characters
</P>
<P>
   narrate a novel set in the Belgian Congo during that
</P>
<P>
   country's fight for independence.
</P>
<P>
   3. WHILE I WAS GONE, by Sue Miller. (Ballantine, $12.95.)
</P>
<P>
   A small-town veterinarian, the wife of a minister, begins
</P>
<P>
   a flirtation with an old friend from her bohemian past.
</P>
<P>
   4. ASHES TO ASHES, by Tami Hoag. (Bantam, $7.99.) Kate
</P>
<P>
   Conlan, a former FBI agent, tracks a serial killer in
</P>
<P>
   Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   5. HANNIBAL, by Thomas Harris. (Dell, $7.99.) Seven
</P>
<P>
   years after his escape, the fiendish psychiatrist
</P>
<P>
   Hannibal Lecter is still at large.
</P>
<P>
   6. TOM CLANCY'S OP-CENTER: Divide and Conquer, created
</P>
<P>
   by Tom Clancy and Steve Pieczenik; written by Jeff
</P>
<P>
   Rovin. (Berkley, $7.99.) Traitors try to oust the
</P>
<P>
   president.
</P>
<P>
   7. IRISH HEARTS, by Nora Roberts. (Silhouette, $7.50.)
</P>
<P>
   Two previously published novels, now in one volume, about
</P>
<P>
   Irishwomen's lives in America.
</P>
<P>
   8. LIGHTNING STRIKES, by V.C. Andrews. (Pocket Star,
</P>
<P>
   $7.99.) A drama student goes to live with her great-aunt,
</P>
<P>
   whose estate is filled with terrors.
</P>
<P>
   9. ACTS OF MALICE, by Perri O'Shaughnessy. (Island, $7.50.)
</P>
<P>
   Nina Reilly defends a man accused of murdering his brother
</P>
<P>
   on the ski slopes of Lake Tahoe.
</P>
<P>
   10. IRISH REBEL, by Nora Roberts. (Silhouette, $4.50.)
</P>
<P>
   The latest novel in a series about Irish families in
</P>
<P>
   America.
</P>
<P>
   11. ECLIPSE BAY, by Jayne Ann Krentz. (Jove, $7.50.)
</P>
<P>
   A man and a woman whose Oregon families are engaged
</P>
<P>
   in a longtime feud, fall in love.
</P>
<P>
   12. HARRY POTTER AND THE SORCERER'S STONE, by J.K.
</P>
<P>
   Rowling. (Scholastic, $5.99.) A British boy, neglected
</P>
<P>
   by his relatives, finds his fortune attending a school
</P>
<P>
   for witchcraft.
</P>
<P>
   13. THE SAVING GRACES, by Patricia Gaffney. (HarperTorch,
</P>
<P>
   $6.99.) The close friendship that binds four women is
</P>
<P>
   put to the test.
</P>
<P>
   14. ROBERT LUDLUM'S THE HADES FACTOR, by Robert Ludlum and
</P>
<P>
   Gayle Lynds. (St Martin's Griffin, $15.95.) Fighting a
</P>
<P>
   doomsday virus.
</P>
<P>
   15. THE GIRLS' GUIDE TO HUNTING AND FISHING, by Melissa
</P>
<P>
   Bank. (Penguin, $12.95.) The love life of a young New York
</P>
<P>
   woman.
</P>
<P>
   16.(x) FROM THE HEART, by Nora Roberts. (Berkley, $14.95.)
</P>
<P>
   Three novels about torrid love affairs.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NONFICTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. THE PERFECT STORM, by Sebastian Junger.
</P>
<P>
   (Perennial/HarperCollins, $14; HarperPaperbacks, $6.99.)
</P>
<P>
   The story of the nor'easter of 1991, focusing on a
</P>
<P>
   single crew.
</P>
<P>
   2. THE SEAT OF THE SOUL, by Gary Zukav. (Fireside/S&AMP;S,
</P>
<P>
   $12.) How daily activities can be enhanced by feelings
</P>
<P>
   of meaning and purpose. (b)
</P>
<P>
   3. THE HUNGRY OCEAN, by Linda Greenlaw. (Hyperion, $14.)
</P>
<P>
   A sea captain's account of her 30-day swordfishing
</P>
<P>
   voyage off the northeast coast.
</P>
<P>
   4. GIRL, INTERRUPTED, by Susanna Kaysen. (Vintage, $12.)
</P>
<P>
   A memoir of mental illness.
</P>
<P>
   5. A CHILD CALLED ``IT,'' by Dave Pelzer. (Health
</P>
<P>
   Communications, $9.95.) The autobiography of a man who
</P>
<P>
   survived his mother's abuse. (b)
</P>
<P>
   6.(x) ANGELA'S ASHES, by Frank McCourt. (Touchstone/S&AMP;S,
</P>
<P>
   $14 and $7.99.) An Irish-American writer recalls his
</P>
<P>
   childhood amid the miseries of Limerick.
</P>
<P>
   7.(x) A WALK IN THE WOODS, by Bill Bryson. (Broadway, $13.)
</P>
<P>
   A journalist finds beauty and humor while hiking the
</P>
<P>
   Appalachian Trail.
</P>
<P>
   8. I'M A STRANGER HERE MYSELF, by Bill Bryson. (Broadway,
</P>
<P>
   $14.) The author describes what it's like to return to
</P>
<P>
   the United States after living abroad for two decades.
</P>
<P>
   9.(x) THE LEXUS AND THE OLIVE TREE, by Thomas L. Friedman.
</P>
<P>
   (Anchor, $15.) A journalist explains the instant electronic
</P>
<P>
   global economy.
</P>
<P>
   10.(x) THE LOST BOY, by Dave Pelzer. (Health Communications,
</P>
<P>
   $10.95.) The author of ``A Child Called `It''' recalls
</P>
<P>
   his life in foster homes. (b)
</P>
<P>
   11. THE ELEGANT UNIVERSE, by Brian Greene. (Vintage,
</P>
<P>
   $15.) A presentation of superstring theory, which
</P>
<P>
   is an attempt to mediate between quantum mechanics and
</P>
<P>
   general relativity.
</P>
<P>
   12.(x) THE FIRST WORLD WAR, by John Keegan. (Vintage, $16.)
</P>
<P>
   A historian recounts the 1914-18 conflict from the
</P>
<P>
   viewpoint of the strategists and the men in the trenches.
</P>
<P>
   13.(x) GUNS, GERMS AND STEEL, by Jared Diamond. (Norton,
</P>
<P>
   $14.95.) A physiologist attributes Western dominance
</P>
<P>
   to geography. (b)
</P>
<P>
   14.(x) EVERY MAN A TIGER, by Tom Clancy with Chuck Horner.
</P>
<P>
   (Berkley, $16.95.) The novelist and a retired Air Force
</P>
<P>
   general examine the Gulf war.
</P>
<P>
   15. TRAVELING MERCIES, by Anne Lamott. (Anchor, $13.)
</P>
<P>
   A chronicle of the author's journey toward faith and
</P>
<P>
   spirituality.
</P>
<P>
   16.(x) I AIN'T GOT TIME TO BLEED, by Jesse Ventura.
</P>
<P>
   (Signet, $6.99.) Reflections on politics, professional
</P>
<P>
   wrestling and other subjects by the governor of Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ADVICE, HOW-TO AND MISCELLANEOUS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. TAKE TIME FOR YOUR LIFE, by Cheryl Richardson.
</P>
<P>
   (Broadway, $13.) A seven-step program for enhancing
</P>
<P>
   one's social, financial and spiritual well-being. (b)
</P>
<P>
   2. DR. ATKINS' NEW DIET REVOLUTION, by Robert C. Atkins.
</P>
<P>
   (Avon, $14 and $6.99.) A physician recommends ways to
</P>
<P>
   lose weight and achieve a healthy body. (b)
</P>
<P>
   3. RICH DAD, POOR DAD, by Robert T. Kiyosaki with Sharon
</P>
<P>
   L. Lechter. (Warner, $15.95.) Teaching one's children
</P>
<P>
   how to get rich and stay rich.
</P>
<P>
   4. CHICKEN SOUP FOR THE TEENAGE SOUL III, compiled by
</P>
<P>
   Jack Canfield, Mark Victor Hansen and Kimberly Kirberger.
</P>
<P>
   (Health Communications, $12.95.) Inspirational stories. (b)
</P>
