<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 09:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7613 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-R-MEXICO-DEMOCRACY-RE     07-10 1195
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-MEXICO-DEMOCRACY-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO'S VOTERS SPOKE. NOW THE VICTOR MUST ACT. 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 By GINGER THOMPSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ On the night that Vicente Fox wrested control of
the Mexican presidency from the ruling Institutional Revolutionary
Party, the jubilant victor rushed out to celebrate with throngs of
supporters who had gathered at the monument of the Angel of
Independence in the capital.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of miles away in a rural village in the eastern state
of Veracruz, a small group of potato farmers gathered around a
black-and-white television set to watch grainy images of the
celebration. Sometimes it was hard for them to hear Fox above the
chants from the crowd around him. But what the crowd had to say
came through loud and clear. ``Vicente no nos falles,'' the
televised crowd blared.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vicente, don't fail us.''
</P>
<P>
   The words stirred the farmers in Veracruz, and they picked up
the chant. That simple plea, said one farmer, summed up the deep
sense of betrayal people have long felt toward their government and
their desperation for change. But there was also an edgy challenge
in the plea.
</P>
<P>
   Mexicans will no longer hand over their votes and expect little
in return, the farmers said. And what they most expect from Fox are
programs and reforms that will help the nation's new democracy
expand beyond elections.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment of their greatest expectation, however, some
voters do not quite realize that the new president's powers have
also been radically reshaped _ in some ways weakened _ by some of
the same currents that carried him to victory. He is not part of
the one-party apparatus that for 71 years monopolized power in
Mexico but so often failed its people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Fox has made a lot of promises to the people, that he
would move the country forward,'' said Alvaro Gonzalez Arenas, 24.
``We have put our faith in him; faith that we are finally going to
be free of corruption and that we will be able to live with
dignity.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the first step in the development of a democracy _ free
and fair elections _ was accomplished here last Sunday in contests
that displayed an extraordinary level of civility and respect.
</P>
<P>
   But democracy, as shown from Central America to the former
Soviet Union, requires more than fair elections. Those in power
must prove able to work in cooperation with their opponents. In
Fox's case, only then can he take on Mexico's urgent tasks:
creating a credible justice system that protects civilians from
crime and corruption, and anti-poverty programs to lift the poor;
and opening education and employment opportunities to the best and
the brightest, rather than the best and most well-connected. Such
goals are extraordinarily complex, of course, and have been set
before.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have felt so betrayed by promises from candidates that
were never intended to be fulfilled and they not only stopped
believing in the government, but they stopped believing in
themselves,'' said Julio Faesler, a congressman and member of Fox's
National Action Party. ``It took a great leap of faith, and a lot
of internal courage for people to trust in something other than the
PRI. And living up to that confidence will not be easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Showing that he plans to work hard to fulfill his campaign
promises, Fox has barely taken a moment to rest since his victory.
But when he assumes power on Dec. 1, some analysts say he will be
in a weaker position than his PRI predecessors. He will not have
the support of the vast PRI machinery _ its political bosses, its
labor union and farmers' cooperative leaders and the directors of
the wealthiest social welfare programs. These were an important
part of the muscle that could support, and often impose, the will
of a PRI president.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; BC-MEXICO-DEMOCRACY-REVIEW-2NDTAKE-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; MEXICO CITY: PRI president. &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And, unlike all PRI presidents until the midterm elections in
1997, Fox will not be able to count on enough votes in Congress to
override his opposition. He will have to reach for support across
party lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has to be a statesman and a mobilizer and an organizer of
the Mexican people,'' said Roberto Mangabeira Unger, an expert on
Latin American politics and a professor of law at Harvard
University. ``If he fails to do that, he will allow the powerful
organized interests to strike back at him, and to limit the margin
of innovation for his government, and to create the stage on which
a new opposition to his government can arise.''
</P>
<P>
   During his campaign, Fox was brash and prone to hurling insults,
and he paid a price: he could not establish partnerships with
logical allies, particularly the left-wing Democratic Revolutionary
Party.
</P>
<P>
   But Mangabeira said those are mostly ``superficial weaknesses,''
because Fox was elected president by a decisive margin in the midst
of a national feeling of rebirth. The challenge will be whether he
can turn the enthusiasm into bold political practice.
</P>
<P>
   One political analyst, Federico Estevez of the Autonomous
Technological Institute of Mexico, said Fox is uniquely well suited
for the challenges ahead _ primarily because he is much more a
pragmatist than an ideologue. For example, he is a devout Catholic
who has said he personally opposes abortion but has also said he
would consider signing legislation to legalize the procedure if he
thought it reflected the will of most Mexicans.
</P>
<P>
   And even though the president-elect could not win over all of
the Mexican left, he was able to lure several strategists from the
main leftist party to his campaign. In choosing his cabinet, Fox
plans to enlist international headhunting firms, and he has
promised to make his government one that reflects the range of
Mexico's political parties and regions.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Fox, who once managed the sale of Coca-Cola across
Latin America, has used his marketing experience to promote his
image and ideas. ``He is a magnificent salesman,'' Estevez said.
``And on top of that, he knows how to inspire people.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox has already signaled that he may use the first months of his
administration to push for approval of some of his most
controversial proposals. Last week, he announced plans to rebuild
the nation's federal law enforcement system. And he said he would
travel to the United States to press for a less restricted flow of
Mexican workers across the border.
</P>
<P>
   ``He announces his plans ahead of time,'' said Estevez,
``something that shows he's already treating the public to the kind
of transparent agenda they expect of him, and one that they would
have never gotten before under the PRI.''
</P>
<P>
   Even one of Fox's closest campaign advisers worried, though,
about whether public expectations had been set too high. ``Feelings
of optimism are volatile,'' Adolfo Aguilar Zinser wrote in a column
in the newspaper Reforma. ``If they do not turn into concrete
efforts, they turn bitter and dissipate.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us to accomplish our goals,'' he added, ``it will be
necessary to transform our political culture, to respect plurality
and to build, among ourselves, bridges and more bridges.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-00 0936EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
