<DOCNO> NYT20000710.0058 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 09:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7615 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-BEIRUT-RETURN-REVIEW-     07-10 0613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEIRUT-RETURN-REVIEW-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 BEIRUT: his permits.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Over and over, old friends and new acquaintances, using phrases
like ``rotten'' and ``crooked,'' told me that, fundamentally,
nothing has changed in Lebanon; that politics and economics remain,
as one put it, ``parasitical, feudal and entirely rapacious.''
</P>
<P>
   But of course some things have changed in the decade since the
war ended. By 1990, the paroxysm of violence that had torn Lebanon
since the mid-1970s had turned on itself, so badly that many
Lebanese were desperate to restore an ordinary sense of business
and life. So they welcomed the calm that Syrian control brought
them.
</P>
<P>
   Today, most visibly, the presence of armed militias in which
gunmen ruled has been ended, and that is no small thing. (They are
officially disarmed, except for Hezbollah in the South, although
much of the weaponry is just hidden away.) The remaining
Palestinians are disenfranchised, confined to their camps. The
ability of the Maronite Catholic elite to either dominate the
country or to establish an autonomous entity has been ended.
Perhaps most important for the future is the rise of the Shiite
Muslim movement Hezbollah, or Party of God, to power and
respectability. Politically, Syria calls all the shots now.
</P>
<P>
   But what has not changed is the strict division along religious
lines that defines _ and essentially undermines _ Lebanon as a
country.
</P>
<P>
   When modern Lebanon was formed in 1943 out of a French mandate
granted after World War I, power was apportioned by religion,
mainly to protect the Maronites; they were to hold the presidency,
with other offices apportioned to Sunni Moslems, Shites, Druse and
13 smaller sects.
</P>
<P>
   And that has always been the paradox of Lebanon: What has
enabled its people to survive and even prosper through unbelievably
difficult times, like the civil war, are the tight bonds of family,
village, clan and religion. But the same narrow loyalties prevent a
national social contract.
</P>
<P>
   The headquarters for the small band of foreign journalists
throughout those war years was the shabby, beloved Commodore Hotel,
presided over by its suave, impeccably-dressed manager, Fouad
Saleh, who could accomplish anything. The parrot at the bar
imitated incoming shellfire, Fat Tommy the cat slept wedged in the
warmth between the Associated Press and Reuters news wires, and the
telexes, magically, always worked. Guests checking in were asked,
``Shelling side or sniper side?''
</P>
<P>
   One night during the Israeli siege of Beirut in 1982, a
desperately needed truckload of bottled water materialized, bribed
through Israeli lines near the airport. ``You see, we are really
all Levantine together,'' smiled the man from the Democratic Front
for the Liberation of Palestine next to me at the bar.
</P>
<P>
   But in the final five years of the war, when erstwhile allies
turned on each other in a frenzy _ Shiites against Palestinians,
Hezbollah against its Shiite rival Amal, Christians against
Christians, the Lebanese army against Christians _ the Commodore
was destroyed in street fighting between the Druze and a Sunni
militia, the Murabitoun. A Druse gunman carried off the parrot to
an unknown fate.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Commodore has been rebuilt as a fancy Meridien, with a
Benihana Japanese steakhouse. Just off the lobby is a place called
the ``News Bar,'' with a carpet embroidered to imitate newspaper
front pages. When I looked in the other day, it was empty.
</P>
<P>
   Fouad Saleh died a few years back, I was told, and, because of
his mixed marriage, neither the Muslim nor the Christian cemetery
would accept his body. Fouad, the ultimate fixer, had been beaten
at last by Lebanon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-00 0938EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
