</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Colorado may force new religion-schools challenge
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In God Colorado's state board of education may trust, but not,
apparently, in the law.
</P>
<P>
   The board has voted 5-1 to encourage the state's schools to post
the ``In God we trust'' motto in their classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   This just days after the U.S. Supreme Court made it plain once
again, in a case barring student prayer over public address systems
at football games, that the Constitution won't brook any of the
various devices politicians have come up with to sneak religion
into public school classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   That principle has been imbedded in constitutional law since
1963 and the court has defended it against every dodge contrived to
subvert it, from pitches for nonsectarian prayer to efforts to
chase off biology with biblical creationism.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Colorado board is trying to bootleg religion into public
schools under cover of a phrase that has been on U.S. currency
since 1864.
</P>
<P>
   The board slyly argues that it has no religious intent but only
means to champion a national heritage. Wink-wink, nudge-nudge.
</P>
<P>
   Lower federal courts have endorsed the motto in its current,
limited uses, but the Supreme Court has never taken up the issue or
shown any keenness to.
</P>
<P>
   That could change now. The first Colorado district that posts
the motto is likely to draw a legal challenge and, ironically, by
trying to weasel the motto into classrooms, the Colorado board
could put even its use on currency into legal jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   And to what end?
</P>
<P>
   The board's chairman, Clair Orr, said, ``How long can we remain
a free nation if our youth do not have civic virtue and good moral
character...?''
</P>
<P>
   A fair question, implying a good point. But the nation got along
well enough before the declaration was made official by President
Dwight Eisenhower in 1956 and was wedged into the Pledge of
Allegiance. It literally passes through our hands ever day. If
exposure to it carried any big magic we would already be among the
most virtuous and moral of peoples, but from the evidence of our
prisons we may not be.
</P>
<P>
   There is an insistent, naive assumption that just by reciting
rote prayers or seeing the Ten Commandments on a wall or hearing
Christianity piped over a P.A., today's youth -- wrongly presumed
wastrel _ would be set aright.
</P>
<P>
   The faith in such nostrums is, in about equal parts, touching
and frustrating. You would think that Colorado of all places would
be skeptical. The school massacre, at Columbine, occurred in a
community and among a youth generally accounted churched beyond the
usual.
</P>
<P>
   The Colorado board might profitably pause to think about just
what example it is itself setting for the youth its members say
they are so worried about.
</P>
<P>
   The message of the board's resolution is that adults in a
position of public responsibility think that, instead of working
for the common good in ways faithful to law, it is OK for them to
finagle a way around the clear purpose of the law just to get their
way.
</P>
<P>
   And the civic virtue in that would be...?
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is a columnist for Cox Newspapers. He is based in
Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
