A7633 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN12-CO     07-10 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: What's the Rx for high drug prices?
 &HT;    For release July 12, 2000.
 &HT;    By HOWARD KLEINBERG
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you believe that either presidential candidate, Al Gore or
George W. Bush, has a medical prescription plan that has any chance
of traveling, even slightly as proposed, through the labyrinth of
the lobbyist-dominated Congress, then I have a bridge in Brooklyn I
want to sell you -- again.
</P>
<P>
   It makes for great listening from the stump and, I suppose, it
does position each candidate on the issue. But, don't expect the
winner to deliver; he won't, he can't. The system won't allow it.
</P>
<P>
   And I'm not so certain that I agree that the government should
be subsidizing the consumers for the outrageous prices charged for
their prescriptions.
</P>
<P>
   Pharmaceutical companies don't want the federal government
establishing any kind of price controls, and they argue against it
by citing that any cutback in prices would affect their research
and development divisions, thereby slowing the pursuit of greater
life-saving compounds.
</P>
<P>
   In looking at quarterly earnings reports of the major
pharmaceuticals, I'm not certain they're pouring such a huge
percentage of their revenue into R&AMP;D. As an example, in the last
earnings report of Merck &AMP; Co., a total of $2.68 billion was spent
on R&AMP;D in the 12 months ending Dec. 31, 1999, against a total
revenue of $32.7 billion. At the same time, selling, general and
administrative expenses ran $5.2 billion, or almost twice that of
R&AMP;D.
</P>
<P>
   To understand more about the pharmaceuticals, you have to look
beyond our borders. In countries such as Canada and Mexico, the
drug companies are required to negotiate with those governments on
price controls. That's why the same drug is so much cheaper in
Canada than it is in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   An example cited recently was the cost for the breast-cancer
drug tamoxifen: a three-month supply in Vermont costs $390, just
$50 in adjacent Quebec.
</P>
<P>
   When the pharmaceutical companies are forced to adhere to
government restrictions elsewhere, they get even by charging U.S.
customers considerably more. What they don't get in big profits in
Canada, they get here _ we consumers, in a way, are subsidizing the
Canadian consumer.
</P>
<P>
   Each time I listen to pharmaceutical company representatives
fall back on their old ``we need the money for R&AMP;D so that we can
make your lives better in the future'' argument, I think of the
national magazines.
</P>
<P>
   When was the last time you picked up a national magazine and did
not find at least one three-page advertisement for a particular
drug? The first two are glitzy and in color and the third, a
micro-type explanation of the drug's constraints, dangers,
elements: May cause dizziness, nausea, dry mouth, wet mouth, high
blood pressure, low blood pressure, diarrhea, constipation...
</P>
<P>
   These advertisements cost a fortune (I assume they fall within
the ``selling, general and administrative'' segments of the drug
companies' budgets) and I've often wondered to what end.
</P>
<P>
   If I see an ad for Claritin in Time Magazine, so what? I can't
write a prescription. Yes, I can request it from my doctor, but
likely he's already been lobbied by the drug company's ``detail''
person (that's the industry name for it) and been given a supply to
hand out as samples prior to filling your prescription. If another
antihistamine product is favored by the doctor, he or she likely
will insist on that.
</P>
<P>
   (We won't dwell on what other perks are given doctors by the
drug companies.)
</P>
<P>
   While the huge advertising campaigns certainly plant the message
in the mind of the consumer, I see it as a double effort _ money
that could otherwise be spent on more R&AMP;D or, better yet, on
reducing costs to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The drug companies live in fear of price control, but if they
continue to siphon the life savings of American consumers while
adhering to price constraints elsewhere, then there is a legitimate
argument to rein them in here before we all go broke, or don't take
necessary medicine because of the cost.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, heady profit-demanding holders of pharmaceutical
stock, you have to buy prescription drugs yourselves _ if not now,
later.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
