   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THE-PILL (San Antonio) _ The pill, the oral contraceptive that
uses hormones to block ovulation, turns 40 this year. Approved for
use in this country by the Food and Drug Administration in 1960, it
was introduced by G.D. Searle &AMP; Co. under the name Enovid. Most
women applaud its protection. By MARINA PISANO.
</P>
<P>
   GAY-HIV (Durban, South Africa) _ While the overall rate of new
HIV infections in the United States remains stable, more than 7
percent of young gay men in U.S cities are turning up infected,
another troubling sign that efforts to further halt the spread of
the virus might be faltering, the CDC reports. By ULYSSES TORASSA.
</P>
<P>
   HORSE-DENTIST (San Antonio) _ Dr. Clay Stubbs isn't your typical
dentist. He doesn't have Muzak in his waiting room. He doesn't have
a comfortable reclining chair for his patients. And he doesn't give
out toothbrushes embossed with his phone number at the end of each
visit. Stubbs is an equine dentist _ a small but growing group of
veterinarians who specialize in treating equine molar maladies. By
WILLIAM LUTHER.
</P>
<P>
   DEER-GLUT (San Antonio) _ In the wild or in the suburbs, the
only way to consistently control the overpopulation of deer remains
a timely, continuing harvest of surplus animals, especially does.
That is better than Nature's way of solving the glut _ starvation
and suffering. By RON STRAIT.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL-CONTRIBUTIONS (san Francisco) _ Four years ago,
California voters bucked the political establishment and passed a
ballot measure setting stringent limits on contributions to state
candidates and campaigns. The measure, Proposition 208, allowed
donors to give no more than $100 to local officials, $250 to
legislators and $500 to statewide candidates _ or double that
amount if the candidates agreed to voluntary spending limits. A
court challenge to the measure goes to trial Tuesday. By ZACHARY
COILE.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT(``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   RALPH-FIENNES (Toronto) _ Ralph Fiennes craves challenges. Since
his Oscar-nominated supporting role in ``Schindler's List,'' he has
tackled: a morally conflicted game show contestant pressured in
``Quiz Show''; his role of a romantic, corrupt man dying encased in
bandages in ``The English Patient''; a foppish, tormented minister
in ``Oscar and Lucinda.'' Fiennes says his three roles in
``Sunshine,'' an epic of a century in the history of a Hungarian
Jewish family, are the most challenging he has faced. By LOUIS B.
PARKS.
</P>
<P>
   X-MEN (Houston) _ Since writer Stan Lee launched a comics
revolution in the '60s while exhorting fans to ``Face Front,''
Marvel has dominated a market in which superheroes rule. But even
as it leaped tall buildings beyond its rivals, Marvel never could
turn its comics icons into film stars as big as rival DC's Superman
or Batman. With the release of ``X-Men,'' that could change. By
BRUCE WESTBROOK.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   WORKING-COLUMN (Houston) _ Too many times retailers don't give
enough thought to their sales force. They give them drug tests, put
aprons on them and send them out to ``help'' the customers. So it
was encouraging to talk to some retailers who have thought about
the importance of good pay, good training and treating people well.
By L.M. SIXEL.
</P>
<P>
   UNIVISION (Los Angeles) _ The unlikely pairing of San Antonio's
golden-tongued, bilingual former mayor and a media-shy, monolingual
Hollywood agent has been a happy marriage for shareholders of the
nation's most powerful Spanish-language communications company,
Unvision Communications Inc. By JEANNE RUSSELL.
</P>
<P>
   FAILING-DOT-COMS (San Francisco) _ A cottage industry of sorts
has cropped up around the burnt edges of the Internet in recent
weeks, populated by dealmakers mining for gold among the failed or
failing dot-coms. Some openly call themselves vulture capitalists.
They want to buy a company, relaunch it in their own image or sell
it for parts. The vulture is a failed dot-com's last resort. By
ALAN T. SARACEVIC.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   OLY-FENCING (Austin, Texas0 _ As the U.S. National
Championships/Olympic Fencing Trials wound down Sunday at the
Austin Convention Center, optimism was high that what the U.S. team
lacks in numbers it will more than make up for in performance. By
MARK WANGRIN.
</P>
