<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 11:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7671 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-PITCHERS-VS-HITTERS-C     07-10 2194
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PITCHERS-VS-HITTERS-CENTERPIECE-ADV09-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV09 
 PITCHERS VS. HITTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 9, or thereafter.)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's CENTERPIECE news service. For more
information about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _
or becoming a client of CENTERPIECE _ contact one of the New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the
text.) 
 (ART ADV: Photos of Braves' pitchers Greg Maddux and Tom Glavine,
and Red Sox shortstop Nomar Garciaparra and Yankees' center fielder
Bernie Williams are available on Newscom or by calling William
Gonzalez at 212-499-3355.) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY  
 c.2000 The New York Times Magazine  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ask a baseball pitcher why so many home runs are hit these days
and you will hear an impassioned speech from a member of an
oppressed minority. You will hear how umpires are calling a
fist-size strike zone, architects are designing ballparks that
couldn't hold a Crackerjack box, the mounds are lower and, of
course, the baseball is different _ smoother, denser, more
slippery.
</P>
<P>
   Ask an infielder, an outfielder or any player except a pitcher
about the inordinate increase in home runs and a royal smirk often
precedes the response. You are informed the hitters are stronger
than they used to be, train daily and capitalize on modern
technology like watching videotape between at-bats to find a
pitcher's weaknesses.
</P>
<P>
   These conflicting views on the home run explosion underscore the
hard, immutable boundary that exists between the two sides. The
social dynamic of all teams breaks down along certain lines _
Christian players pray before games, Latinos are drawn together by
a common language _ but no division is more powerful than the one
between pitchers and everybody else.
</P>
<P>
   The players themselves, all of them, acknowledge the split, and
offer pop-psychological theories. ``It's the difference between
left-brained and right-brained people,'' says Phil Garner, a former
infielder who now manages the Detroit Tigers. ``Pitchers are more
esoteric, thinkers, artsy-craftsy type guys _ they're the
sculptors, we're the hammer-and-nail guys.'' Tom Glavine, the
Atlanta pitcher, says, through a jesting smile, that hitters ``are
intimidated by our intelligence and our perspective on the game.''
</P>
<P>
   In the best of circumstances, these differences are fodder for
clubhouse gags. But they can be the source of real conflict,
particularly in an era when pitchers, even good ones, are getting
pounded and their roles are becoming ever more compartmentalized.
Increasingly, it's a hitter's game, not just on the field but off.
</P>
<P>
   Pitchers and hitters start out the same. In Little League and
right on through college, the best players usually pitch and then
play shortstop when they're not on the mound. It's not really until
the minor leagues that the responsibilities of pitchers and
everybody else diverge _ position players must take the field every
day and push through the grueling season.
</P>
<P>
   Relievers are segregated in the bullpen, getting the call when
needed, and the starters grow accustomed to playing only one out of
five games, at most. The rhythms of the jobs lead to entirely
different lifestyles. Take a head count in the hotel bar at last
call, and chances are the majority of ballplayers will be pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   The Toronto left-hander (and former Yankee) David Wells takes
full advantage of his schedule and makes no secret of the fact that
he likes to go drinking and stay out late. His old manager with
Detroit, Sparky Anderson, had a standing arrangement with Wells;
out of every five days, the left-hander owed the team two _ the day
he was pitching and the one before.
</P>
<P>
   Merv Rettenmund had a long career as an outfielder, including
some years with the Orioles, before becoming a hitting coach. ``We
had pitchers in Baltimore _ I'm not going to name them _ but let's
just say that the first couple of days after they pitched, they
were under the weather,'' Rettenmund says. ``And a position player
can't be like that. You have to grind it, day in and day out.''
</P>
<P>
   When Davey Johnson managed the Mets in the late 1980s, he was
particularly sensitive to the influence that pitchers had on their
other teammates. Johnson would take Howard Johnson and Lenny
Dykstra aside and suggest that maybe it wasn't such a good idea to
go out after games with Ron Darling or Bob Ojeda. It's a standing
joke in baseball circles that position players cannot keep up with
pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the bar scene isn't exactly what it used to be.
Nowadays, some pitchers turn in early _ so they can make their tee
times. On any given club, it's a sure bet that the best golfers are
pitchers. While everyday players think of life on the road almost
entirely in terms of airports, hotels and stadiums, many pitchers
can recite a list of the best golf courses in every big-league
city. Atlanta's famed starting rotation, anchored by Tom Glavine
and Greg Maddux, is renowned for its obsession with golf. They play
all season long _ the only good excuse for missing it is if you
have to pitch that day. On their days off, a lot of starting
pitchers have to show up only 90 minutes before a game, and they're
usually the first to duck out after the game. Even when they're in
the clubhouse together, position players and pitchers tend to stick
to their own kind.
</P>
<P>
   Because of their looser schedule, pitchers are less affected by
the day-to-day conformity of the clubhouse and can get away more
easily with strange, even freakish behavior. Take, for example,
Fritz Peterson and Mike Kekich, who were Yankee teammates back in
1973. In one of the more memorable off-the-field scandals of
baseball history, Peterson and Kekich essentially swapped their
lives _ wives, kids, dogs, the works. It's no coincidence that the
first tell-all books that pierced the veil of clubhouse
confidentiality _ Jim Brosnan's ``Long Season'' and Jim Bouton's
``Ball Four'' _ were written by pitchers. They simply had more time
to observe and reflect on their teammates and take notes.
</P>
<P>
   When they take the field together, pitchers and the rest of
their teammates bury their differences. Or at least they try to.
Inevitably, there is second-guessing. Glavine says he will see a
teammate swing at and miss a hittable pitch _ the type of pitch
Glavine couldn't get away with _ and he will wonder, for an
instant, ``Why couldn't he hit that?'' Similarly, Paul O'Neill,
standing in right field, gets impatient when he watches a pitcher
struggle with his control. ``It looks so easy from out there,''
O'Neill says. ``That's the first thing they tell you in Little
League _ everything starts with throwing the ball over the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   More intense conflict arises when the opposing pitcher hits a
batter or aggressively throws inside. With a few notable
exceptions, like Pedro Martinez of the Red Sox, pitchers have lost
the battle for the inside half of the strike zone. Hitters are more
sensitive than ever about being brushed back or struck by a pitch.
There is a very simple code that governs how a pitcher is supposed
to react when one of his own teammates is hit _ he is supposed to
drill one of the other team's hitters with a fastball aimed at the
backside. If a pitcher fails to retaliate, clubhouse friction is
inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, in a game against Seattle, Yankee hitters were
repeatedly hit or brushed back, and the left-hander Andy Pettitte
didn't respond. There was so much tension that a team meeting was
called the next day. According to David Cone, the most divisive
issue between pitchers and hitters is the intimidation factor. ``If
there's no retaliation or sense of protection, or disagreement
about what needs to be done, that's a major problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The flip side of this is that hitters are infuriated when one of
their own pitchers instigates a bean-ball war purely out of
personal frustration. While with the Baltimore Orioles two years
ago, Armando Benitez allowed a pivotal home run against the Yankees
and then on the very next pitch drilled Tino Martinez. A nasty
brawl ensued, which was not surprising. What was surprising was
that while blows were being exchanged, some Orioles players were
actually apologizing to the Yankees on the field about what Benitez
had done.
</P>
<P>
   On the day they're scheduled to start, pitchers get a lot of
leeway from their teammates. This selfishness, however, is not
supposed to spill over onto the field. Earlier in his career, the
Dodgers' Kevin Brown reacted furiously whenever something went
wrong, stomping around the mound if an infielder misplayed a
grounder or if he allowed a cheap hit. After a poor outing, he'd
often tear up the clubhouse. As dominant as Brown could be on the
mound _ and former teammates in Texas and Baltimore were awed by
his talent _ many couldn't stand playing with him.
</P>
<P>
   Because their roles are inherently part time, pitchers are
rarely named captain, or assume much of a leadership position. A
team leader ``has to be a guy who is in the heat every day,'' says
Rettenmund. ``He's one of the guys who's going to fail a lot and
help everybody else deal with that. If you have a pitcher who's a
team leader, it's not a healthy situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Most pitchers, in fact, have to be very careful about what they
say. Early in 1996, when the Orioles were playing poorly, the
pitcher Mike Mussina sharply criticized the team's performance. The
next day, Ripken beckoned Mussina to shortstop during batting
practice and, as Ripken practiced fielding grounders, he suggested
it was a bad idea for Mussina to speak in this way for two reasons
_ team conflicts should be kept private, and Mussina is not a
position player.
</P>
<P>
   For these reasons, few pitchers graduate into the managerial
ranks. The conventional wisdom is that ex-pitchers will have
trouble gaining the respect of their everyday players. A handful
are successful: Larry Dierker has managed the Houston Astros to
division titles the last three years. More typical is the case of
the former pitcher Phil Regan, who lasted just one year as the
Orioles' manager, in 1995. When he ripped them in team meetings,
some veterans used to flash double-L finger signs to each other:
Little League.
</P>
<P>
   When ex-hitters become managers, some, like Lou Piniella of
Seattle, never develop an understanding for pitchers. Hitters like
Ken Griffey Jr. and Edgar Martinez have responded to his intensity.
Pitchers have not. Piniella ``is the manager who hates pitchers,''
says Jeff Nelson, a Yankees reliever who used to pitch for Seattle.
``It's not hard to understand why that is.''
</P>
<P>
   Piniella was a great hitter for 18 seasons; his professional
responsibility was to loathe pitchers. How could he just shut that
off? ``He just doesn't have patience,'' Nelson says. ``He doesn't
understand pitchers. He tells you, 'Throw the ball over the plate.'
You feel like saying: 'Is that what I'm supposed to do? I didn't
know that. I thought I was supposed to come out here and walk
everyone.'''
</P>
<P>
   Ted Williams, the Hall of Fame slugger, briefly managed the
Washington Senators but was never much of a success, in part
because he just couldn't handle a pitching staff. His theory was
that his pitchers should throw sliders, because that was the pitch
that gave him the most trouble when he was a player. So the
Senators unloaded one of their best starters, Joe Coleman, because
he didn't throw sliders, and Coleman went on to have several good
seasons for Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   As a manager, Pete Rose had similar problems relating to
pitchers, although at least he knew enough not to meddle too much.
When Jim Kaat was hired as the pitching coach for the Cincinnati
Reds, Rose was blunt, Kaat recalls: ``He told me: 'I don't know
anything about pitching. I know about hitting. You take care of the
pitching.'''
</P>
<P>
   The gulf between pitchers and position players is part of the
reason so many managers are ex-catchers _ they can deal with both
sides. They are everyday players, but they are heavily invested in
the fate of the pitchers. They can tolerate their idiosyncrasies.
Over the last four years, just five managers have taken their teams
to the World Series; four of them were catchers at least part of
their careers: Joe Torre, Bobby Cox of Atlanta, Bruce Bochy of San
Diego and Jim Leyland of Florida. ``Catchers have to have empathy
for pitchers,'' Cone says. ``They have no choice.''
</P>
<P>
   (Buster Olney covers the Yankees for The New York Times.)
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
