<DOCNO> NYT20000710.0084 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 12:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7687 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-DEER-GLUT-HNS &LR;      07-10 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEER-GLUT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     DEER GLUT SPELLS TROUBLE FOR SUBURBS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RON STRAIT  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ White-tailed deer, by human standards, are
unreasonable, obnoxious creatures.
</P>
<P>
   You can't talk politely to deer and explain, kindly and gently,
that to be sociable they must curb some of their appetites _
appetites that go beyond nibbling weeds and extend to munching
expensive landscape plants and completing uncounted acts of
procreation.
</P>
<P>
   Where too many deer and too many humans come together, social
problems arise. To a point, deer become domesticated and humans go
wild.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Jim Trotter. He understands the misunderstandings that arise
between deer and humans.
</P>
<P>
   Trotter is chairman of the deer committee for Fair Oaks Ranch, a
5,000-acre community of 5,000 residents on Interstate 10 between
San Antonio and Boerne.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that the South Texas ranch also has 2,500
resident deer. The deer are eating themselves into valuable
shrubbery and out of a welcome with many of the community's human
residents. As the deer population grows, the number of disgruntled
residents goes up, so the Fair Oaks Ranch deer committee was formed
to look for solutions.
</P>
<P>
   What really got the ball rolling in earnest last week was the
situation at Lakeway, a 5,000-acre community on the shores of Lake
Travis west of Austin. Lakeway has suffered for several years with
a deer population approaching 3,000 animals.
</P>
<P>
   In June, desperate city officials resolved: Shoot the deer.
</P>
<P>
   The vote to bring in hired guns was not the first option to be
considered, but the deer-human conflict factor was too much for
leaders to take. Taxpayers demanded an option that would work.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998 the city's sanitation crews removed about 700 deer
carcasses in Lakeway, most resulting from collisions with vehicles.
Officials estimate that the total vehicular damages were about $1
million.
</P>
<P>
   While concerned voices had stopped short of talking politely to
the deer, the kind-and-gentle crowd did have a say early on. The
city spent about $65,000 trapping and hauling away 650 deer. Some
died in transit.
</P>
<P>
   However, back at Lakeway, those deer appetites kicked in. The
deer population recovered quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Lakeway and Fair Oaks Ranch are not alone in the deer problem.
Texas and many other states are saturated with deer, and surplus
deer have no place to go. By law, a deer cannot be transported to
another place unless that area is short of deer. Few, if any, such
places exist.
</P>
<P>
   And that leaves Trotter, as well as Lakeway and other locales,
in a hard spot: too many deer, more on the way and no place to put
them.
</P>
<P>
   The solution for the suburban deer glut is simple but messy. In
the Fair Oaks Ranch case, get the population to a reasonable number
(500 deer or so) and keep it there through prescribed harvesting
(quota killing).
</P>
<P>
   However, solving the Texas deer glut won't be pretty or cheap,
regardless of method. Using Fair Oaks Ranch as an example:
</P>
<P>
   _ Shooting deer and processing the meat for human consumption
costs about $250 per animal. Cutting the deer population by 1,250
would cost more than $300,000. (Cutting it to 500 would cost
$500,000.)
</P>
<P>
   _ If permitted, transferring 1,250 deer would be cheaper
($125,000) but not nearly as humane as a quick, painless death.
(About 25 percent of the deer that survive a long trailer ride die
within 90 days of the transplant.)
</P>
<P>
   _ Deer birth control doesn't work.
</P>
<P>
   _ High-fencing 5,000 acres would cost a minimum of $150,000 _ if
all the red tape could be hashed out. A high fence might slow the
influx of new deer, but it wouldn't do anything about the 2,500
animals left proliferating inside.
</P>
<P>
   The well-fed, protected animals would remain sexually active,
and the population of 2,500 deer would grow _ until it crashes.
</P>
<P>
   One solution might be for state officials to eliminate bag
limits on does so that hunters could thin rural populations and
suburban deer would have somewhere to be sent.
</P>
<P>
   In the wild or in the suburbs, the only way to consistently
control the deer population remains a timely, continuing harvest of
surplus animals, especially does.
</P>
<P>
   In confined spaces such as Fair Oaks Ranch and Lakeway, that
means hired exterminators and/or high fences and higher costs.
Those are some human solutions.
</P>
<P>
   Nature's way of solving such problems isn't nearly as pretty.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
