<DOCNO> NYT20000710.0085 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 12:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7688 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-RALPH-FIENNES-HNS &LR;      07-10 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RALPH-FIENNES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     THE MANY FACES OF RALPH FIENNES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By LOUIS B. PARKS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Ralph Fiennes craves challenges.
</P>
<P>
   Since his Oscar-nominated supporting role as a brutal,
conflicted Nazi in ``Schindler's List,'' he has tackled: a morally
conflicted game show contestant pressured into cheating in ``Quiz
Show''; a pusher of addictive emotional experiences in the
futuristic ``Strange Days''; his best-actor-nominated role of a
romantic, corrupt man dying encased in bandages in ``The English
Patient''; a foppish, tormented minister with a gambling problem in
``Oscar and Lucinda.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet even Fiennes says his work in ``Sunshine,'' an epic of a
century in the history of a Hungarian Jewish family, is the most
challenging he's faced.
</P>
<P>
   Fiennes has three roles, each directly related to the others but
different, in Sunshine.
</P>
<P>
   First, there is Ignatz Sonnenschein (Hungarian for Sunshine), a
young judge so eager to advance in the empire that he changes his
Jewish name to Sors.
</P>
<P>
   Years later in the story, Fiennes reappears as Ignatz's son,
Adam, who overcomes anti-Jewish prejudice to become his country's
fencing champion.
</P>
<P>
   Following World War II, when Adam's son Ivan returns to the
family to become _ for a while _ a Communist avenger, that, too, is
Fiennes.
</P>
<P>
   It's a bravura performance that was complicated by overlapping
shooting schedules and complex costume and makeup changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no words to describe it, really,'' said Rosemary
Harris, who co-stars with Fiennes. ``I don't know another actor who
could have done (this) with the commitment he gave to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ralph was able to just pour his emotions out without any
trouble - and let you pour yours out. His lack of conceit and pride
and how he kept all the threads (of the story straight). ''Fiennes
had seen `Sunshine' six times before last fall's premiere screening
at the Toronto Film Festival, but he was thrilled to see it again
with the festival audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was wonderful,'' Fiennes said the following morning in a
Toronto hotel. ``I love the film. I think it's an extraordinary
film.''
</P>
<P>
   Fiennes knew going in that with his parts dominating the
three-hour film and three distinct characters to learn (and
sometimes to play on the same day), it would be a grueling shoot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an amazing journey through the lives of three
generations of this family,'' he said. ``I wanted to do it
immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   Like ``Dr. Zhivago,'' ``Sunshine'' uses a family saga to put a
personal face on history.
</P>
<P>
   Directed and co-written by Istvan Szabo, the director of Colonel
Redl and Mephisto, the film covers roughly 1870 to the present,
taking the middle-class Sonnenschein/Sors family through Hungary's
monarchy, two world wars, communism, a military dictatorship, the
Nazi influence and a shaky democracy.
</P>
<P>
   In each period the family faces new problems. Fiennes'
characters respond differently because each has a different
personality. But Fiennes' playing them all gives the story
continuity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one actor, I think, gives it a continuum, an arch all the
way through,'' said Fiennes, who took a lower-than-usual salary
because he wanted to do the role and work with Szabo. ``If you had
three different actors, you might as well have done three different
films.''
</P>
<P>
   While wanting each role to be distinctive, Fiennes was
determined to keep the personalities subtle and not exaggerate them
to create obvious oddities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would not work if you tried too hard to be different _ if
you tried to go too far in terms of physicality or makeup, so that
the audience would be alienated by the effort you were making to be
different,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, when asked what his characters share, Fiennes took a long
pause before answering.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what to say to that,'' he said, then continued
reluctantly.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, they're all men who are a bit unsure of who they are.
They're struggling to assert their sense of identity in different
ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Fiennes, 37, seems much more at home playing a part than talking
about it. In Toronto, dressed in a flannel shirt over a casual
dress shirt, tan slacks and leather loafers, he seemed far more at
ease being interviewed than he was a few years ago. But he still
looked like he'd rather be back in Hungary than talk about himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I have become more comfortable,'' he said. ``The kind of
questions you get asked you're not asked every day. It often throws
me. And I have felt a little invaded. I don't know what to say.''
</P>
<P>
   He has found personal questions especially threatening.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I've been oversensitive, sometimes, about it. Maybe.''
</P>
<P>
   Fiennes prefers to stay out of the limelight, seeing it as a
disadvantage for an actor to become more well-known than his roles.
</P>
<P>
   One thing hasn't changed about Fiennes in interviews: Like many
British actors with a lot of stage experience, he refuses to be
pretentious about the art of acting or mysterious about the
process.
</P>
<P>
   Suggest that an actor might learn something about himself from
the roles he plays, and he looks like he just bit into a lemon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, you can,'' he said. ``But I mean, I don't think acting's
a therapy.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of it's just playing. It's only an extension of the simple
childhood instinct to put on dress-up clothes and just play.
Cowboys and Indians.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're talking about it like it's some kind of therapy. I
can't approach a piece of work like that. I see a part; I see a
story; I pretend to be this person.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not thinking, like, does it make me feel more myself? In
fact, I think it's not good for actors to analyze what they do too
much. The actors I admire are very practical in their approach.
Someone like Judi Dench just gets on, does it and goes home. There
isn't a churning over or internal `is this part affecting me?'
</P>
<P>
   ``It's quite nice to escape into a part sometimes, because you
have a beginning, middle and an end. Life's much more confusing:
The script (or real life) is being written as you go along.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-00 1224EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
