<DOCNO> NYT20000710.0086 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 12:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7689 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-HINES-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-10 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HINES-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BUSH'S VP PICK WILL REVEAL MORE THAN A NAME 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By CRAGG HINES  
 &HT;     c.2000 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Does George W. Bush have the courage to select Gov.
Tom Ridge of Pennsylvania as his vice presidential running mate? It
may be Bush's toughest call of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   As Colin Powell _ definitively and disappointingly _ has ruled
himself out of the running, Ridge emerges head and shoulders above
the remaining Republican field, with the exception of a couple of
dark horses including Sen. Richard Lugar of Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   Ridge's political calculus is almost too good to be true _ a
Republican Roman Catholic who supports some abortion rights, a
Vietnam-era veteran who actually fought in Southeast Asia and a
working-class guy with Washington experience (U.S. House,
1983-1995) who comes from the heart of the most important
electoral-vote belt.
</P>
<P>
   The catch is, of course, the part about ``some abortion
rights.'' Ridge opposes government funding for abortions, backs
waiting periods, supports required parental consent for abortions
for minors and draws the line at so-called partial-birth abortions,
but he supports the broad principle of Roe vs. Wade.
</P>
<P>
   To hard-line, anti-abortion Republicans this is apostasy, and
some of them are threatening to bolt if Ridge is on the ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Bolt and do what? Stay home or vote for Pat Buchanan so it will
be easier for Al Gore to add at least four more years to the
current Democratic run in the White House? These Shiite Republicans
give sanctimony a bad name.
</P>
<P>
   One problem is that the anti-abortion folks have never been
convinced that the Bush men, despite their current vows of
faithfulness to the cause, are true believers. They recall that
former President Bush was once a poster boy for Planned Parenthood
and that his about-face on the issue came in the dark of night
after Ronald Reagan tapped him as running mate in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   The former president sometimes likes to be a bit revisionist on
this point, so let's briefly restate the record. As he was battling
Reagan for the Republican nomination in 1980, the elder Bush
expressed his personal opposition to abortion but supported the
1973 Supreme Court decision legalizing the procedure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I happen to think it was right,'' the elder Bush told Rolling
Stone in an interview published in the March 20, 1980, edition.
This meant the future president had about the same position as
Teddy Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the Bush women, who with winks, nods and obscure
hand signals have let it be known that they just may have a
different view from the boys on abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Late last year, Barbara Bush, the governor's sainted mother,
went so far as to say in an ABC News interview that abortion should
not be addressed in the national Republican platform at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Listen to your mama,'' urged Republicans for Choice in ads
that have fallen on deaf ears at the Governor's Mansion in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   To add an openly somewhat pro-choice Ridge to this possibly
irresolute mix would have the Phyllis Schlaflys of the world
ranting in double time.
</P>
<P>
   There's no question that the anti-abortion forces could make a
lot of noise at the Republican National Convention. But if George
W. Bush cannot face them down and turn their frothing to his
advantage, then he's a poorer politician than his reputation would
indicate.
</P>
<P>
   What better sign could Bush offer to the moderates and
independents who, if they vote, are likely to decide this national
race?
</P>
<P>
   Bush would maintain his own opposition to abortion, no matter
how troglodytic, but also demonstrate he is not a captive of the
narrow, single-issue lobby that has dominated Republican
intra-party affairs for two decades.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's high command may have convinced the Texas governor that
he's already solid enough with these key middle-road voters that
there's no need to risk ticking off the abortion opponents _ and
that anyway they can paint Al Gore into a liberal corner in
September and October.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush brass may be arguing for some pale, supposedly safe
ultra-clone of Bush, specifically Gov. Frank Keating of Oklahoma.
He's also Roman Catholic but anti-abortion, so, unlike Ridge, he
won't get his bishop's knickers in a twist.
</P>
<P>
   History shows that the selection is not likely to have much
effect on the outcome of the presidential race, so George W. Bush
can pick anyone he wants as a running mate. But Bush will be
telling us a lot when he does.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL; (
</P>
<P>
   (Contact Cragg Hines by e-mail at cragg.hines(at)chron.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
