<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 12:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7691 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-WORKING-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-10 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKING-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     WHEN WORKERS ARE EMPOWERED 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By L.M. SIXEL  
 &HT;     c.2000 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Too many times retailers don't give enough thought to
their sales force.
</P>
<P>
   They give them drug tests, put aprons on them and send them out
to ``help'' the customers.
</P>
<P>
   So it was encouraging to talk to a couple of retailers who have
thought about the importance of good pay, good training and
treating people well.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Executive Officer Garrett Boone and President Kip Tindell
were in north Houston recently to open their newest Container
Store.
</P>
<P>
   The owners figure one great person is three times as productive
as a good person. So they try to keep the stars. No one earns less
than $10 an hour, and the average full-time employee earns in the
$30,000s, plus receives an array of benefits the owners describe as
``good but not as good as Microsoft.'' Some sales employees - and
this is without commissions - earn up to $50,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Employees also receive a minimum of 185 hours of training the
first year. The retail industry average is eight hours.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for the extensive training? The products are
difficult to sell, said Tindell, flashing a Nalgene bottle. The
small bottle is $1.99, twice what you'd pay at a drugstore. But it
doesn't leak, even in pressurized situations.
</P>
<P>
   When employees spot customers looking at the bottles and tell
them about its non-leaking virtues, 95 percent of customers buy it,
he said. But that human contact is critical.
</P>
<P>
   The good pay, training and empowerment have keep turnover
relatively low at 15 to 25 percent a year, compared with the
industry figure of close to 100 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The owners of the 21-store Dallas-based chain also believe in
sharing information. At every store they pass out figures on sales
totals vs.
</P>
<P>
   sales goals on a daily, weekly, monthly and annual basis - and
how the figures compare with last year's.
</P>
<P>
   No other retailers do that, Boone said. They may tell employees
how their store is stacking up from the year before, but they are
``scared to death'' to give out such sensitive information for the
entire chain.
</P>
<P>
   But Boone found that his 2,200 employees get a companywide
perspective when they can examine sales data and compare amount of
purchases per customer across the chain.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're wide-eyed radicals about this,'' Tindell said. Without
the information, employees get tunnel vision, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the information falls into the wrong hands. About 15
copycat stores have popped up, Tindell said, and he suspects that
some of the information that the Container Store shares with
employees - expansion plans, new product considerations and legal
issues - has made its way to competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Even Boone and Tindell have a limit on openness. Tindell put his
foot down when asked how much the privately held chain earned last
year.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to its openness, the Container Store uses on-the-job
training to help create conscientious employees. Several times a
year, employees are sent to other stores to work a week or two.
</P>
<P>
   It's a good way of exchanging ideas. Houston employees who go to
Fort Worth for a week, for example, give employees at the chain's
lowest-performing store (``every day in Houston is Fort Worth's
best Saturday'') great ideas, Boone said.
</P>
<P>
   You'd be hard-pressed to find another retailer that flies its
clerks and warehouse employees around the country and puts them up
in hotels so they can work in another store, said Tindell.
</P>
<P>
   I returned to the north Houston Container Store several days
after interviewing the bosses to ask employees how they felt about
working there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all managers here,'' said Jeff Greenwood, recalling a
day when a customer from League City called after returning home to
complain that one of the items she purchased hadn't made it home
with her.
</P>
<P>
   Greenwood, a sales associate, shipped another one to her -
without getting permission first.
</P>
<P>
   It's a liberating feeling, he said, to work for a company that
lets him solve problems as they come up. A lot of companies won't
even allow you to make a return, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another employee, Will Richardson, used a word I don't hear
often when someone other than the CEO describes his job. Richardson
used ``we'' when he talked about the Container Store, as in: ``We
try to give customers a lot of individual attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe if more employees used ``we'' instead of ``them,''
shopping would be more pleasurable and fulfilling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
