<DOCNO> NYT20000710.0088 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 12:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7692 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-X-MEN-HNS &LR;      07-10 1767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-X-MEN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     MARVEL AGE OF MOVIES MAY BE DAWNING 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BRUCE WESTBROOK  
 &HT;     c.2000 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since writer Stan Lee launched a comics revolution in the '60s
while exhorting fans to ``Face front!,'' Marvel has dominated a
market in which superheroes rule.
</P>
<P>
   But even as it leaped tall buildings beyond its rivals, Marvel
never could turn its comics icons into film stars as big as rival
DC's Superman or Batman.
</P>
<P>
   With the release of X-Men, that could change. As hype-loving Lee
might say, the Marvel age of movies could be upon us, and, for all
True Believers, ``X'' could mark the spot.
</P>
<P>
   But not so fast. Though X-Men titles are Marvel's top sellers,
and fans anxiously await the release of the film this week, those
same fans have reason to be wary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fans have been talking about an X-Men movie for years, and yet
many have expected it to be awful,'' said John Simons, co-owner of
Midnight Comics in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's skeptical because of Marvel's track record
onscreen,'' said Michael Steenbergen, manager of Bedrock City Comic
Co., also in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``But at the same time, everybody wants to see it.''
</P>
<P>
   That's because the cast and the trailers look so good. Despite
their concerns, X-fans have hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're buzzing about this one,'' Simons said. ``The fans know
about Marvel's record in movies, but this one looks like it could
turn that around.''
</P>
<P>
   Created in 1963 by Lee and artist Jack Kirby, the X-Men are
among the first superheroes of the so-called ``Marvel Age of
Comics,'' as Lee zealously dubbed it. Two years earlier, he and
Kirby launched the Fantastic Four, a book that continues to this
day. Yet the FF's only screen appearance was a '90s movie so cheap
and dismal it was never released.
</P>
<P>
   For TV or direct-to-video release, Marvel's Captain America,
Doctor Strange and the Punisher also fell victim to poor concepts
and cheap execution.
</P>
<P>
   The line has had some TV success in live-action (The Incredible
Hulk) and cartoons (Spider-Man and His Amazing Friends). Its Blade
comic, while not a major title, also sparked a modest hit movie.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing from Marvel has come close to the megamillions DC
has earned with its films based on Batman and Superman.
</P>
<P>
   That's why X-fans are anxious, concerned and fiercely protective
_ and why early looks at X-Men have stirred heated debate along
with fresh hope.
</P>
<P>
   Take the uniforms. Instead of the comics' colorful threads, the
movie's X-team will wear simple black-leather duds emblazoned with
tastefully tiny Xs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some fans have complained about the new uniforms, which tone
down the long-underwear style of most superheroes in comic books,''
Steenbergen said.
</P>
<P>
   But longtime X-Men writer Chris Claremont understands that a
film ``can't slavishly reproduce what's on the page. It must
translate for a medium with sound and movement.''
</P>
<P>
   Chief translator for the $75 million film from Fox is director
Bryan Singer (The Usual Suspects). But looming more largely behind
Marvel's push in Hollywood is Avi Arad, CEO and president of Marvel
Studios, the company's film and TV division.
</P>
<P>
   The uniform change was crucial, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We decided to go with a style of uniform that's not as
outlandish as you have in comics or animation,'' Arad said. ``We
still maintain the sci-fi aspect of comics while giving it a
realistic dignity.''
</P>
<P>
   Claremont agrees. From what he's seen, the filmmakers made the
right choices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides, these uniforms look a lot more comfortable than
Michael Keaton's outfit did in Batman,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In other ways, X-Men closely follows the characters and story
lines Claremont developed while writing X-Men comics in the '70s
and '80s. (He recently returned to X-writer duties.)Like the
comics, X-Men has a team of young adventurers under the guidance of
Professor Charles Xavier (Patrick Stewart), also known as
``Professor X.''
</P>
<P>
   Xavier's ``students'' have varied superpowers, but they all stem
from the same thing: genetic mutation.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Spider-Man, who developed the ability to climb walls
after being bitten by a radioactive spider, or the Fantastic Four,
who turned invisible or elastic after being bombarded by space
rays, the X-Men can pass through walls or command lightning because
they're a new form of humans who have special powers at birth.
</P>
<P>
   Claremont seized on this distinction to make the X-Men outcasts,
applying racial prejudices of the '60s and McCarthyism of the '50s
to the X-Men's world.
</P>
<P>
   It's a world in which all mutants - good or evil - are
mistrusted by society at large and a senator (Bruce Davison in the
film) can make hay with a hate campaign.
</P>
<P>
   That makes the X-Men a melodramatic metaphor for the price of
intolerance. They strive mightily to protect humanity from sinister
forces _ such as belligerent mutant Magneto (Ian McKellen) _ even
while humans scorn them.
</P>
<P>
   Xavier's team has had many members over the years, but in the
film its chief heroes include: Storm (Halle Berry), who can control
weather; Wolverine (Hugh Jackman), the most popular X-Man, who has
long claws and fast-healing powers; Rogue (Anna Paquin), who
absorbs powers; Cyclops (James Marsden), who can wield force blasts
from his eyes; Jean Grey, first known as Marvel Girl (Famke
Janssen), who blends telekinesis with telepathy, Xavier's chief
strength.
</P>
<P>
   Led by master of magnetism Magneto, their opponents include
shape-shifter Mystique (Rebecca Romijn-Stamos), big-hopping Toad
(Ray Park) and ferocious Sabretooth (Tyler Mane).
</P>
<P>
   Claremont likes that cast, but he once had others in mind. While
waiting long years for an X-movie, he envisioned Robert Duvall as
Xavier and Bob Hoskins as Wolverine.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that was 15 years ago,'' he said. ``Everybody gets older _
unlike in the comics.''
</P>
<P>
   True. Xavier, Cyclops and Grey have hardly aged since they first
appeared in '63. (Teammates Beast, Iceman and Angel didn't make the
movie team.)Yet in a way, they almost died.
</P>
<P>
   As characters, the X-Men disappeared for years. The original
book lasted just 66 issues, then became dormant. Old stories were
merely reprinted.
</P>
<P>
   That changed in 1975, when Claremont launched a new X-team
combining several original members with newcomers such as Storm and
Wolverine.
</P>
<P>
   Those new X-Men mutated into huge sensations, spawning spinoff
books and maintaining top-seller status even as Marvel slid into
bankruptcy (due to noncomics investments) in 1996. (It's since
recovered.)
</P>
<P>
   Recent X comics have included the X-Men, the Uncanny X-Men,
X-Force, Mutant X, X-Man, Generation X, books based on Wolverine,
Bishop, Cable and many miniseries, including three prequels to the
film.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to mention older spinoffs such as the New Mutants,
Power Pack and Alpha Flight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people complain there are too many titles to keep up
with,'' Simons said. ``Even so, it's amazing how the X-Men are able
to support an entire line of comics.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that other superheroes of New York-based Marvel will be
neglected in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Arad, based in Los Angeles, is wheeling and dealing with many
studios to put an entire slate of Marvel movies and series on
screens big and small.
</P>
<P>
   Next up will be Spider-Man, to be directed by Sam Raimi
(Darkman). It's being cast now for release in November 2001.
</P>
<P>
   (Freddie Prinze Jr. and Tobey McGuire are among candidates to
play Peter Parker, aka Spider-Man.)Next will come The Fantastic
Four, The Incredible Hulk, Blade II, The Silver Surfer, Iron Man,
Morbius, Ghost Rider and others. Two X-sequels could also arise;
the cast already is signed.
</P>
<P>
   But first things first _ and Arad thinks X-Men is a good place
to start.
</P>
<P>
   ``X-Men will be a very good jump-start for all of those
projects,'' he said. ``Fans will see a movie that takes the
characters seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Why the sudden push toward Marvel movie mania? Three letters:
CGI.
</P>
<P>
   Computer-generated images are crucial in depicting the Marvel
universe, Arad said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They allow you to build incredible backgrounds, as you saw in
The Phantom Menace, and to show incredible powers. This will be a
golden age for sci-fi type pictures in stylized worlds.''
</P>
<P>
   He said a Spider-Man movie ``would have been a disaster six or
seven years ago. Many things just weren't doable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, with CGI, you'll see things in X-Men that you couldn't do
a few years ago. We're very excited.''
</P>
<P>
   One boost for Marvel's movie fortunes is the fact that many of
today's filmmakers grew up on its comics.
</P>
<P>
   Directors such as Raimi, James Cameron and Christopher Columbus
are big fans. Cameron tried for years to spin a Spider-Man flick
until Raimi got the nod.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes comics don't get much respect,'' Arad said. ``But
these filmmakers respect them as a form of storytelling.''
</P>
<P>
   So does Kelley Hall, who teaches courses on comics and society
at DePauw University in Greencastle, Ind. Hall has read a
novelization of X-Men and feels it has ``a good sense of capturing
the comics' social themes.''
</P>
<P>
   She cites the AIDS issue as an example.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the '80s people wanted gays to be registered as a
protection from AIDS. That kind of thing comes up in the movie with
the idea of registering mutants.''
</P>
<P>
   ``From a mutant perspective, the idea is, `We were born this
way. We can't control it. It's the way we are, and you shouldn't
discriminate against us based on a genetic mutation.' ''Claremont
feels social issues account for the books' popularity among their
core audience: teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The X-Men are outcasts, and feeling like an outcast is what
every teen-ager goes through,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Such relevance separated Marvel from DC when Lee launched
Marvel's new brand of humanized heroes in the '60s.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fundamental difference between Marvel and DC was: Superman
and Batman occasionally played at being Clark Kent and Bruce Wayne,
while Peter Parker was an ordinary guy who had this night job as
Spider-Man _ which was really cool, but didn't make him any less
the nerd in school,'' Claremont said. ``It was something every teen
could empathize with.''
</P>
<P>
   Having read the X-Men script and been an adviser for the film,
Claremont is certain it will maintain his outcast sensibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's also an A-list movie with Oscar winners before and behind
the camera. It's got as good of an ensemble as you can ask for.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give me a film with Ian McKellen and Patrick Stewart facing
off, and I'm in heaven. I'm there.''
</P>
<P>
   And ``X'' marks the spot.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-00 1227EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
