<HEADER>
A7699 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-MOST-ACCURATE-CLOCK-P     07-10 1255
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOST-ACCURATE-CLOCK-POPMECH-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEASURING MINUTIAE, WITHOUT A SECOND TO SPARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's POPULAR MECHANICS NEWS SERVICE. For more
information about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _
or becoming a client of POPULAR MECHANICS NEWS SERVICE _ contact
one of the New York Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at
the end of the text.) 
 (ART ADV: A photo of Dawn Meekhof and Stephen Jefferts with the F-1
clock is available on Newscom or by calling William Gonzalez at
212-499-3355.)
 By JIM WILSON 
 c.2000 Hearst Communications Inc.   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's hard to suppress a smile when you are introduced to Dawn
Meekhof. Her pretty alabaster face is painted crimson with skier's
sunburn. It seems that the builder of the world's most accurate
clock lost track of time on the slopes near her Boulder, Colo.,
laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   The clock in our heads is a notoriously bad timepiece. It runs
too fast on vacations, too slow in traffic jams and stops entirely
in dentist chairs. On the job, Meekhof and her colleague Stephen
Jefferts deal with a more objective measure of time.
</P>
<P>
   The two National Institute of Standards and Technology
physicists have spent the last four years building the world's most
precise clock. Known as NIST F-1, it is accurate to 1 second in 20
million years. Around Christmas time F-1 became the new standard
for defining Coordinated Universal Time.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting on a vibration-isolating lab bench, F-1 looks more like
a science experiment than a clock. There isn't a pendulum or main
spring in sight. What you do see are lots of lasers.
</P>
<P>
   One set acts as a refrigerant and chills to nearly absolute zero
the cesium atoms that F-1 uses to calculate time. A second set of
lasers forms a sort of Ping-Pong paddle that sets them in motion.
The remaining laser is used to measure the changes that take place
within these atoms as they travel through a tube filled with
microwave energy. Using this complex apparatus, Meekhof and
Jefferts can calculate the length of a second more precisely than
ever before.
</P>
<P>
   The operation of the F-1 clock is a marvel. First, a gas
containing atoms of cesium is introduced into a vacuum microwave
cavity that is housed in a silver stovepipe-like structure. When
the cavity is filled with gas, a half dozen laser beams placed at
right angles to each other are then directed at the center of the
chamber.
</P>
<P>
   Tuned to the infrared range, the laser light is invisible to the
eye. Nevertheless, it exerts sufficient pressure to limit the
motion of the atoms. Motion is heat. With the pressure of the laser
light limiting their motion, the atoms very quickly cool to within
a few millionths of a degree of absolute zero, -459.7 degrees
Fahrenheit, the point at which motion stops.
</P>
<P>
   Two vertically aimed lasers _ the Ping-Pong paddle, so to speak
_ set the frigid cesium ball in play by providing just enough
energy to send it moving slowly up the cavity. Like a rock tossed
into the air, the ball of cesium atoms feels the tug of gravity and
falls back through the cavity. Because this trajectory resembles
the movement of water in a fountain, F-1 is called a fountain
clock.
</P>
<P>
   The accuracy of F-1 is tied to the length of time the cesium
atoms remain in free fall. In F-1 the trip covers 6 feet and lasts
about 1 second. During this comparatively long period of time,
Meekhof and her colleagues slice a second with unprecedented
precision. ``The more time we have, the more accurately we can
measure the frequency of the cesium atoms,'' explains Meekhof.
</P>
<P>
   Frequency is the rate at which a phenomenon repeats. The
frequency source for the first nonsolar timepieces, water clocks,
was a steady drip into a catch basin. The more water that
collected, the more time had passed.
</P>
<P>
   Monks in the Middle Ages adapted this scheme to create the first
alarm clock so they could rise for their pre-dawn prayers. Pendulum
clocks became the height of accurate time in 1655 and remained the
standard through the 1940s. Within a decade they were replaced by
quartz oscillators, like those now used in digital wristwatches,
and then came the first atomic clocks.
</P>
<P>
   Like the first atomic clocks, F-1 takes advantage of a
phenomenon known as resonance. Every element has characteristic
frequencies at which it absorbs and emits electromagnetic
radiation. These ``resonant'' frequencies are inherently stable
over time.
</P>
<P>
   In 1967 the world's timekeepers met in France for the Conference
Generale des Poids et Mesures and agreed to establish the basic
unit of time _ the second _ as equal to 9,192,631,770 vibrations of
a cesium-133 atom.
</P>
<P>
   During their brief trip in F-1's vacuum chamber, the chilled
cesium atoms are bombarded with microwave energy. ``Depending on
the frequency of the microwave signal, the atomic state of the
atoms might or might not be altered,'' says Meekhof.
</P>
<P>
   At the finish line, another laser is directed at the cesium
atoms. Only those whose atomic states have been altered by the
microwaves emit light. The photons or tiny packets of light are
then measured by a detector.
</P>
<P>
   ``This procedure is repeated many times while the microwave
energy in the cavity is tuned to different frequencies. Eventually,
a microwave frequency is achieved that alters the states of most of
the cesium atoms and maximizes their fluorescence,'' Meekhof
explains. ``This frequency is the natural resonance frequency for
the cesium atom. F-1's cooler and slower atoms allow more time for
the microwaves to interrogate the atoms and determine their
characteristic frequency, thus providing a more sharply defined
signal.''
</P>
<P>
   Although F-1 sets the standard for time, it does not run
continuously. Instead, it operates about one week per month and is
used to calibrate the timepieces that generate the timing signals
that NIST transmits throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
   High-accuracy timekeeping is becoming increasingly important.
Electrical power utilities need split-second timing to maintain the
stability of their distribution systems and locate faults after
lightning storms.
</P>
<P>
   Long-baseline interferometry, which astronomers use to make
highly accurate observations of distant objects, needs extremely
accurate atomic reference clocks. Some global positioning satellite
applications require timing to within 100-billionths of a second.
</P>
<P>
   You don't need to be a scientist or engineer to take advantage
of the precision of F-1. The signals are out there for anyone to
use. To set your wristwatch to the world's most accurate timepiece,
tune a shortwave radio to 2.5, 5, 10, 15 or 20 megahertz and listen
for the tone. Or, you can synchronize the clock in your computer
with F-1 via the Internet. NIST's Time and Frequency Division
provides free software at www.bldrdoc.gov.
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on the
POPULAR MECHANICS news service and other features.
</P>
