<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 12:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7701 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-TECHWATCH-BRIEFS-POPM     07-10 0987
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHWATCH-BRIEFS-POPMECH-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECHNOLOGY WATCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's POPULAR MECHANICS NEWS SERVICE. For more
information about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _
or becoming a client of POPULAR MECHANICS NEWS SERVICE _ contact
one of the New York Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at
the end of the text.) 
 (ART ADV: A photo of a student adjusting a laser-heating lathe and
one of the frame of a Piper Super Cub are available on Newscom or
by calling William Gonzalez at 212-499-3355.)
 c.2000 Hearst Communications Inc.   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DRUGS HAVE A SLIPPERY FUTURE
</P>
<P>
   Dusting large molecules with the nanotech equivalent of slippery
talc will make it possible to ``slide'' drugs into the blood and
the brain. Cornell University researchers are developing a
microscopic polymeric sphere that could be impregnated with drugs
and then injected into the body where it would slowly release them.
</P>
<P>
   The silicates cause the larger polymer chains that control drug
release to slide about. ``We have demonstrated that the transport
of small molecules can be controlled and changed,'' says Cornell's
Emmanuel P. Giannelis. ``The next step is to incorporate active
agents and watch how they are being released,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   RESETTING BIOLOGICAL CLOCKS
</P>
<P>
   Cloning could be the key to resetting the biological clock and
reversing the effects of Parkinson's, Alzheimer's and other
age-related diseases.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually all types of body cells, except reproductive cells,
contain an aging clock. It consists of a strand of DNA on the end
of all chromosomes. These ends are called telomeres. Every time a
cell divides, some of this tail is used up. When it runs out, the
cell ceases dividing and it dies.
</P>
<P>
   Advanced Cell Technologies of Worcester, Mass., says it has
cloned human stem cells whose DNA clocks have been reset. Since
stem cells can grow up to become different types of cells, experts
familiar with ACT's work say youthful clones could be used to
replace aging organs.
</P>
<P>
   SCALPEL SEEKS CANCER CELLS
</P>
<P>
   For physicians removing cancerous brain tumors, knowing when to
stop cutting is as important as knowing where to cut. Remove too
much tissue and the patient may be left disabled.
</P>
<P>
   A new rapid-reading diagnostic system developed at Sandia
National Laboratory in Albuquerque, N.M., will shut off laser
scalpels when they come near healthy cells.
</P>
<P>
   The tiny laser directs a vertical laser beam on individual cells
as they are pushed into a small cavity by a micropump. Cancerous
cells stand out because they contain more protein.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment the smart scalpel is strictly experimental.
</P>
<P>
   LASER-ASSISTED MACHINING
</P>
<P>
   Small lots of precision ceramic parts could be made for half
their current cost with a new laser-heating technique. As the part
is machined, the laser heats the ceramic to about 1,800 degrees to
make it softer and more ductile.
</P>
<P>
   The trick is to precisely control the strength of the laser so
that it heats only a tiny portion of material, says Yung C. Shin,
the Purdue University professor who developed the technique. The
soft, red-hot ceramic is then removed with a cubic boron-nitride
cutting tool that digs into a small layer of the heated area.
</P>
<P>
   ``We heat a very small, shallow layer of the surface, and then
we remove it immediately so that the inteirior is not damaged by
heat,'' Shin explains. ``We are trying to understand what we call
the thermomechanical behavior of ceramics. It's a very challenging
issue.'' The technique could be commercialized within a year.
</P>
<P>
   NEW LIFE FOR SUPER CUBS
</P>
<P>
   Despite being out of production, the Piper Super Cub remains one
of America's favorite planes. The informal count is about 12,000.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Budde wants to keep the Cubs flying forever. His company,
AirFrames Inc., (www.supercubs.com) has begun manufacturing
replacement fuselages. Selling for $10,250, they feature
all-chromemoly tubes and fittings, improved door mechanisms, an
extended baggage area and shoulder harness attachment tubes, among
other improvements.
</P>
<P>
   ``About half the orders are from people building new planes,''
he says. ``Our fuselage is acceptable to the FAA and can receive a
standard airworthiness certificate.''
</P>
<P>
   EXPERTS DISCOUNT ALLEN LIFE
</P>
<P>
   Alien life is more likely to resemble the stuff you scrub off
the tiles in your shower than Klingons, Wookies or Romulans, say
University of Washington scientists. After extensively examining
the oldest
</P>
<P>
   Earth fossils, paleontologist Peter Ward and astronomer Donald
Brownlee have concluded the odds of intelligent life developing are
so unfavorable that Earth may actually be unique.
</P>
<P>
   Their argument, detailed in their book ``Rare Earth,'' suggests
that life as we know it is the product of a series of factors,
among them:
</P>
<P>
   1) Sufficient mass to create enough gravity to anchor an
atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   2) A stable orbit.
</P>
<P>
   3) Plate tectonics that act as a sort of atmospheric thermostat,
build land masses and enhance biotic diversity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Earth is a very charmed planet,'' says Brownlee. ``We know of
no other body that is remotely like earth.''
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
