<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 12:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7749 &Cx1f; tad-z
r w BC-GRASSPEA-$ADV16-COX     07-10 1086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRASSPEA-$ADV16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GENETIC ENGINEERING ELIMINATES CRIPPLING PLANT TOXIN
 &HT;    For release Sunday, July 16.
 &HT;    Eds: a botanical sketch of grasspea is available on the Internet
at www.fao.org/docrep/t0646e/T0646E0W.GIF. Sketches labeled ``A,''
``A1'' and ``A2'' are relevant to this story.
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A small dryland pea that often saves the world's
poorest people from starvation _ and then leaves thousands
paralyzed for life _ has been genetically changed to eliminate its
crippling trait.
</P>
<P>
   Tough enough to withstand droughts that kill practically all
other crops, the plant offers a devilish choice to millions of poor
farmers and their families during drought-induced famine. If they
eat it, they may not starve. Yet with every meal, they know that
some will be left permanently crippled.
</P>
<P>
   Known by several names, including grasspea and chickling pea, it
is grown primarily for livestock feed.
</P>
<P>
   A grasspea nerve poison, which apparently does not affect farm
animals, is believed responsible for more than 100,000 cases of
paralysis, especially in Ethiopia, India and Pakistan. Eating
grasspea can lead to retardation and death in young children.
</P>
<P>
   Plant breeders at an international research station in Syria
used a type of genetic manipulation known as ``somoclonal
variation'' to reduce the plant's production of the nerve toxin to
safe levels.
</P>
<P>
   Seeds of the new plant _ still tough, still nutritious and,
according to one scientist, still ``quite delicious'' _ are being
distributed to farmers in several countries in the hope that as
they grow the new strains and save seed, it will rapidly displace
its toxic predecessor. Because the new strains do not readily cross
with existing grasspeas, researchers are not concerned that the
harmful trait will reappear.
</P>
<P>
   Development of the safe grasspea came at the end of a 15-year
search by plant breeders at the International Center for
Agricultural Research in the Dry Areas (ICARDA) in Aleppo, Syria.
</P>
<P>
   The center is part of an international plant breeding network
that is funded by the United Nations, the World Bank and several
national foreign aid agencies, including the U.S. Agency for
International Development.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 3.7 million acres of grasspea, which has grass-like
stems and leaves but is a legume just like soybeans and black-eyed
peas, are grown around the world, said John H. Dodds, assistant
director general of ICARDA. The crop's popularity as livestock
forage results from its ability to produce up to 1,000 pounds of
the small peas per acre during years when total rainfall is less
than eight inches. That is too little moisture to keep most crops
alive, to say nothing of productive.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows why sustained human consumption of grasspea leaves
some persons crippled and others unaffected or why victims are most
often men and boys, Dodds said.
</P>
<P>
   However, in the middle 1980s, scientists at ICARDA began
searching seed banks for a strain of the pea that did not produce
harmful levels of the poison. Several thousand varieties were
tested and all were found toxic, Dodds said.
</P>
<P>
   At about the same time, some plant geneticists were becoming
interested in somoclonal variation, a technique that enables plant
breeders to ``trap'' naturally occurring mutations that ordinarily
would not survive from one generation of plants to the next.
</P>
<P>
   ICARDA decided to try the technique to find a nontoxic grasspea.
</P>
<P>
   Millions of cell cultures, each involving only a few cells taken
from grasspea leaves, stems, husks and other non-seed parts of the
plant, were placed in special laboratory media and grown into
mature plants.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, mutations that occur in non-seed tissues are not
passed to subsequent generations. However, when mature plants are
produced as ``clones'' of a few individual cells, they can carry
the mutations with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been no foreign DNA introduced with this
technique,'' explained Elizabeth Earle, a professor of plant
breeding at Cornell University. ``You get the spontaneous variation
arising from the tissue culture, and in some case the variations
are heritable.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they've managed to (eliminate the grasspea toxin with
somoclonal variation), then that's a nice accomplishment,'' she
added.
</P>
<P>
   The process, a sort of poor person's genetic engineering, does
not require the expensive _ and often controversial _ biochemical
gene transplantation techniques involved in production of so-called
``genetically modified organisms.'' Rather, it involves years of
hit-or-miss examinations of the cell culture progeny to determine
if the desired trait spontaneously arose in any of the cloned
plants.
</P>
<P>
   ``We screened tens of thousands of these cloned plants and,
bingo, we found some of them that don't have the toxin or have
very, very low levels of the toxin,'' said Dodds.
</P>
<P>
   Seeds from those plants pass the desirable traits to succeeding
generations.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Rose, executive director of Future Harvest, a non-profit
organization devoted to encouraging food and environmental
research, said the research ``demonstrates the critical importance
of international agricultural partnerships to find solutions to the
dilemmas of hunger in developing countries.''
</P>
<P>
   Dodds said ICARDA is now working with national governments and
nonprofit organizations to distribute the new seed to a handful of
farmers in each of thousands of villages.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who's been eating grasspea probably has an income of
less than a dollar a day, he said. ``These are not farmers who go
out and buy commercial seed. They get their seed by saving seed
each year.''
</P>
<P>
   But in one respect, he said, they are like all farmers all over
the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they see their neighbors growing something that is better
than what they have, they're going to get ahold of it,'' he said.
``They are going to buy it from the other farmer or they are going
to steal it or whatever, but they're going to get ahold of it.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that ``seed tracer experiments'' show that when 10 or 15
subsistence farmers are given an improved seed variety one year,
150 to 200 farmers in the same community will be planting that seed
the following year.
</P>
<P>
   ``After that,'' he said, ``it's off and running.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www.futureharvest.org, www.cgiar.org/icarda
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Nesmith's e.mail address is jeffn(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
