<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; ATTENTION EDITORS: The articles described below moved MONDAY,
JULY 10, 2000, in the 'l' news file. The material was filed by The
New York Times Syndicate for use by LIFEBEAT clients.
Nonsubscribers can use these articles only by special arrangement
with the Syndicate. For purchase information, see end of text. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WHAT'S THE BEST THING ABOUT STRESS? THERE'S PLENTY OF IT
</P>
<P>
   STRESS-HEALTH-LIFEBEAT _ People say they want less stress in
their lives, but the evidence _ starting with the growing number of
people who refuse to leave home without a beeper, Palm Pilot, cell
phone (preferably with call waiting) and laptop computer (with
extra batteries) _ makes it clear that many people really want to
be tied in knots. The latest form of one-upsmanship is the
``I'm-busier-than-you-are'' syndrome or ``YOU slept FOUR hours last
night? I only slept THREE!'' By Joanne Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   BAGELS HAVE BECOME AS AMERICAN AS APPLE PIE
</P>
<P>
   BAGELS-LIFEBEAT _ Once the domain of New York Jews, bagels have
infiltrated MacDonald's and Dunkin' Donuts _ which means they've
arrived. According to the American Bagel Association, 1,500 new
bagel establishments opened during 1996, bringing the total to over
4,500 nationwide. Why the rise of a loopy-looking loaf? It's true
that without butter or cream cheese, they're low-fat, but (who eats
them without butter or cream cheese?) One professor speculates that
maybe bagels have become popular because ``You can eat them with
one hand and while walking. No utensils are needed.'' Or maybe it
had something to do with ``Seinfeld.'' By Eve Glicksman.
</P>
<P>
   YOUR TICKET TO AMUSEMENT PARK SAFETY
</P>
<P>
   AMUSEMENT-PARK-DANGER-LIFEBEAT _ The number of injuries linked
to accidents at amusement parks, carnivals and county fairs is
rising. In 1998, about 9,200 people were treated in emergency rooms
for ride-related injuries, a 25 percent jump from 1994.
Unfortunately, even the kiddie rides are potentially dangerous.
It's shocking but true: No federally regulated inspection programs
exist for amusement parks, inspection laws vary from state to state
and even from county to county and some states (including Missouri,
the District of Columbia and Utah) require no inspection programs
at all. Parents must be proactive in keeping their children safe.
By Kim Simonovitch.
</P>
<P>
   AGING BOOMERS CAN PREVENT ARTHRITIS
</P>
<P>
   OSTEOARTHRITIS-HEALTH-LIFEBEAT _ Osteoarthritis, characterized
by painful, stiff joints, is the most common form of arthritis and
the leading cause of disability in the United States. Currently, it
affects 21 million people. With baby boomers moving into their
forties and fifties, this number is likely to go up. However,
experts claim that osteoarthritis is not a normal consequence of
aging and can be prevented and treated. The earlier the problem is
addressed, the better the outcome is likely to be. By Ken McAlpine.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
