 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A few months back, with considerable fanfare, Time Inc. started
a magazine called Real Simple, aimed, in the words of its founding
editor, Susan Wyland, at ``helping you simplify every aspect of
your life, your home, food, money, clothes, health, looks, work,
family and holidays.''
</P>
<P>
   Real Simple has had, let us say, a real hard time since it was
launched. Critics complained that it was hard to tell
advertisements from content, that it was unfocused, that it was too
much like ``Martha Stewart Living.'' Last month, Wyland resigned.
</P>
<P>
   But I suspect that the real problem with Real Simple has nothing
to do with the editor. I suspect that the real problem is that no
one in its potential market is remotely interested in reducing
stress and detangling life.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, yes, that's what we all say we're after. But the evidence _
starting with the growing number of people who refuse to leave home
without a beeper, Palm Pilot, cell phone (preferably with call
waiting) and laptop computer (with extra batteries) _ makes it
clear that we really want to be tied in knots.
</P>
<P>
   And not just knots: bigger knots than the next guy's. Your
colleagues are type A personalities? Well, you'll accept nothing
less than type AA. Call it stress envy.
</P>
<P>
   If status in the greedy 1980s was conferred on the basis of how
much you had, and in the busy '90s on the basis of how much you had
to do, then in 2000 it is awarded on the basis of how hassled you
are about what you have and what you have to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stress has become the badge of honor of the millennium,'' said
Arlene Kagle, a psychologist who practices in Manhattan and in
Dutchess County, N.Y. ``It's almost as if we're not allowed to
enjoy what we're doing anymore. We're annoyed by what we're doing,
as if our lives are getting in the way of something that's more
important.''
</P>
<P>
   We lost the idea of the Sabbath as a day of rest long ago. Now
we have lost evenings, nights and weekends as well: we're too busy
banking online or buying clothes off the Internet. Then we complain
_ that is to say, brag _ that we're just so wound up and tense we
can barely sleep: four hours a night at most, and don't be getting
me jealous by insisting that you get only three.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thinking goes that you're only important and successful if
more people can speak to you than you can deal with,'' said Allen
Adamson, the managing director of Landor, a corporate consultancy
in Manhattan. ``Who wants to meet with someone who, when you ask
what time he's available, says, `I can see you any time this
afternoon'? Lawyers and investment bankers are the most
competitive. They'll say: `You think you're stressed? Well, let me
tell you about my day.'''
</P>
<P>
   Even though he is neither a lawyer nor an investment banker _
actually he's president of the League of American Theater Owners
and Producers _ Jed Bernstein would like you to know about his
crazy, action-packed day, but he doesn't want to do the talking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although I might take pride in the fact that I'm putting in my
time and working the long hours, it would be embarrassing for me to
say so,'' he said. ``It would feel like a point of weakness to say
that my status is tied up in the fact that I worked a 19-hour day
when you worked only a 16-hour day. And that in itself becomes
stressful: how to get the word out without being the one to tell
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Bernstein is rare in his discretion. The only thing stressed
people dependably have time to talk about is how stressed they are
_ and what they don't have time for: sex, vacations or a meal with
you.
</P>
<P>
   ``A low-level executive friend of mine said, `I'd love to have
dinner, but I'm so overwhelmed that I can't even think about
scheduling it until the middle of July,''' said Marc Simone, a New
York radio and cable television host. ``And I said, `Call me in the
middle of July.' An hour later the chairman of the board of the
same company called and said: `What are you doing tonight? Let's
have dinner.'''
</P>
<P>
   Most people have never been around anyone as important as that
board chairman, Simone said, ``so they have this soap opera version
of it'': entourages, dashing about, phones ringing like Playskool
toys. Such people tend to lard their conversations with adverbs.
They aren't just stressed; they're very stressed, they're terribly
stressed. ``They'll say: `I'm never home,''' Simone said. ```I'm
never there. You'll never get me.''' So they'll give you a cell
phone number, and they don't realize that all they sound like is a
bookie or a drug dealer. They honestly think if they met Jack
Welch, he'd say, `Oh, I'm never home _ I'll give you my cell phone
number.'''
</P>
<P>
   What has me concerned is what I think of as trickle-down stress.
Last week, as I was putting my 6-year-old daughter to bed, she
said: ``I don't think I can sleep tonight, Mommy. I have such a day
tomorrow. First I have show and tell, then the boys from St.
David's school are coming to visit my class, then I have my
knitting class after school, and then at night we're going to the
ballet.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a tiny pause before she brightened and said proudly,
``I think my day is going to be even harder than yours.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah? We'll just see about that, cookie.
</P>
<P>
   (Joanne Kaufman writes humor articles for Parenting magazine,
among others.)
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------------------------
</P>
