<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 13:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7772 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-OSTEOARTHRITIS-HEALTH     07-10 1825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTEOARTHRITIS-HEALTH-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 
 AGING BABY BOOMERS CAN PREVENT ARTHRITIS
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's LIFEBEAT service. For more information about
purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of LIFEBEAT _ contact one of the New York Times Syndicate
sales representatives listed at the end of the text.)  By KEN MCALPINE 
 c.2000 Ken McAlpine 
<TEXT>
 &UR; World rights &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features
<P>
   Odd that in an age when the most innocuous health detail
(``Study shows that corn kernels get caught between your teeth'')
quickly flares into a global conflagration (``World Health
Organization Moves to Ban Summer Barbecues''), that something so
widespread has been almost universally ignored.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, it is a little strange,'' says Dr. John Klippel. ``Part
of the problem may be that people think there's very little that
can be done about it _ that it's just aches and pains they'll have
to live with. It would be nice if people paid more attention to
what is a very common problem, especially since it's a problem that
they can do something about.''
</P>
<P>
   Medical Director of the Arthritis Foundation, Klippel is
intimately familiar with osteoarthritis. He knows that it is the
most common form of arthritis and the leading cause of disability
in the United States, affecting 21 million people. He knows that
arthritis experts have predicted that within the next 20 years,
59.4 million Americans will have some form of arthritis, a hefty
increase in which osteoarthritis may play a leading role. He knows
that baby boomers, now moving into their 40s and 50s (which is when
the signs of osteoarthritis start showing up), are front-running
candidates, and for reasons you might not expect.
</P>
<P>
   He knows this doesn't have to be so.
</P>
<P>
   ``Osteoarthritis is not a normal consequence of aging,'' states
Klippel. ``Everyone has the right to have healthy, pain-free joints
forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Undue joint stiffness in the morning when you wake up
(osteoarthritis almost always shows up in the weight-bearing joints
_ knees, hips, back; it rarely affects the wrists, elbows or
ankles) or sit for a long time? Grating noises when you move your
knee? Pain in your outer hip or inner thigh? This advice might be
for you.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not something you want to ignore,'' says Klippel.
``The earlier you address osteoarthritis, the greater the
likelihood you're going to have a good outcome with the disease.''
</P>
<P>
   Understanding (and a trip to the doctor for diagnosis) being the
first step, here are the osteoarthritis crib notes.
</P>
<P>
   Osteoarthritis occurs when the cartilage in your joints breaks
down. Your cartilage, in its heyday, is a firm, rubbery material
that covers the end of bones, cushioning shock and providing a
smooth, gliding surface the bones can move across. Unfortunately,
these tiny buffers are subject to more than their share of abuse.
</P>
<P>
   It's true that the degeneration of cartilage can be hereditary,
a genetic defect causing the cartilage to wear away more easily.
Skeletal defects (bow legs or knock knees), or an adjacent diseased
bone can cause cartilage to deteriorate, too, and cartilage also
inevitably wears away as we age.
</P>
<P>
   But it's also true that the main reason osteoarthritis is so
common is that never before has the American cartiliginous system
been subject to so much stress. To put it bluntly, many of us are
too fat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in an epidemic of obesity right now,'' says Dr. Thomas
Namey, a rheumatologist, professor and chief of sports medicine at
the University of Tennessee Medical Center in Knoxville. ``If
you're heavy, you're loading your joints unnecessarily, and that's
very clearly a major cause of osteoarthritis ''
</P>
<P>
   No real surprise, for overweight folks the best way to address
osteoarthritis is to lose weight, and the best way to do that is
through diet and exercise. Unfortunately, when your joints ache,
movement is not your first inclination.
</P>
<P>
   ``The natural tendency when people start experiencing the aches
and pains of osteoarthritis is to head for the couch,'' says
Klippel. ``Which is the worst thing they can do.''
</P>
<P>
   There are two reasons for this. First, it's difficult to lose
weight sitting still. Second, exercise helps slow the progression
of osteoarthritis (there is no cure, though there is some promising
research _ more on that in a minute) and ease the aches by
enhancing flexibility and strengthening the supporting muscles in
the joints. In fact, exercise and the use of pain relievers
(acetaminophen, aspirin and various prescriptions) are the two
simple, and in most cases effective tools used to combat the
problem. Very few osteoarthritis patients ever need surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Right about now, folks who are diligent about exercising and
diet are experiencing the warm glow of smugness. I'm not fat. I'm
not old. I'm not interested.
</P>
<P>
   Well, osteoarthritis isn't as simple as that. The plumping of
America isn't the only reason osteoarthritis is becoming rapidly
more common. (On the conservative end, Klippel predicts a 20
percent increase in the next decade; more radical types predict a
near epidemic). Nor does it explain why a 30-year-old snowboarder
has ostearthritic knees that would make residents at the Happy
Acres Retirement Home wince.
</P>
<P>
   What's happening is simple. As active Americans move to new
heights of participation (and risk), the number of joint injuries
is skyrocketing, and injury to a joint often leads to
osteoarthritis. You may be 20 and a poster child for ESPN2, but if
you've had surgery to repair cartilage in ligaments in both knees
you may be headed down the same path as someone twice your age and
weight.
</P>
<P>
   And even if active sorts aren't falling off their mountain bikes
or wrenching their knees on the ski slopes, they may, with good
intentions, be grinding toward osteoarthritis anyhow. Researchers
aren't certain of the tie-in, but there's reason to believe the
stresses of some sports may wear cartilage away faster than others,
so leading to osteoarthritis.
</P>
<P>
   Both Klippel and Namey are quick to point out that no one is
discouraging exercise. Exercise is a must _ not only for warding
off or managing osteoarthritis, but for your health. But they also
believe that the wise application of exercise now can help you
avoid osteoarthritis later.
</P>
<P>
   ``We encourage exercise,'' says Klippel. ``But you need to pay a
little bit of attention to making sure that exercise is sensible.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of this is plain common sense. If you weigh 280 pounds,
running 10 miles a day is probably not for you (``How many large
human beings do you see running at 70?'' asks Namey). Twist and
turn sports _ tennis, ice skating, skiing _ also pose a risk.
Basketball causes more joint injuries than skiing, snowboarding and
in-line skating combined. (Because their joints have more natural
range of motion, women are more susceptible to joint injury than
men.)
</P>
<P>
   It may not sound sexy, but if you're in your 20s, 30s or 40s,
anything you can do now to spare your joints injury and undue
impact may help you to prevent osteoarthritis later.
</P>
<P>
   ``Especially as we age, I think we need to focus more on
low-impact sports,'' says Namey. ``Swimmers and cyclists don't get
osteoarthritis.''
</P>
<P>
   Swimming, cycling, walking, yoga, tai chi (these two are great
because they also increase balance and coordination), weight
lifting with machines (which control your movements vs. free
weights, where improper technique can lead to joint injury), are
fine exercises all. At the gym, says Namey, the stair stepper,
cross-country ski machine and exercise bike put less strain on your
knees than the treadmill. Seemingly small nuances can make a
difference, too. A bad fit in running shoes can throw off joint
alignment and lead to injury.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best things you can do _ whether you already have
osteoarthritis, or are hoping to avoid it _ is to strengthen the
muscles that support the joints. Stronger muscles around the joint
help keep it stable. Studies have shown that folks with weak
quadriceps (thigh) muscles are more likely to develop
osteoarthritis of the knee. If they already have osteoarthritis
there, weak quads greatly increase the odds it will get worse
faster.
</P>
<P>
   This makes weight training a great idea, especially as we move
into middle age.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we turn about 50, we really start loosing muscle mass,
especially in the legs,'' says Klippel.
</P>
<P>
   It's not all black and white either. Klippel was once an avid
marathon runner, for which he doesn't apologize. Certainly the
pounding may have upped his odds of getting osteoarthritis, but the
strong quad muscles he developed through running may explain why,
in his mid-50s, he doesn't have osteoarthritis in his knees.
</P>
<P>
   Klippel still runs some, but these days he spends more time
biking, swimming, kayaking, playing tennis and lifting weights _
mixing different sports is a great way to spread stresses around,
plus it's more fun.
</P>
<P>
   Wise exercise and a sound diet aren't the only tools available
when it comes to managing osteoarthritis, though at the moment they
are the most tried and true. Research indicates that the
antioxidant vitamins _ C, E and beta carotene _ may play a
protective role for osteoarthritis. Just take the recommended daily
allowance, says Klippel. And Namey doesn't discount the possibility
that glucosamine, an over-the-counter nutritional supplement, might
help. Recent studies indicate it may actually help maintain and
repair damaged cartilage. There are other exciting whiffs of a
possible cure.
</P>
<P>
   Currently under way, a major clinical trial is looking at
doxycycline, a promising and inexpensive ($10-$20 a month)
antibiotic that may stop the progression of osteoarthritis.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly it's puzzling that osteoarthritis is still so
universally ignored. As Namey says, ``Nothing makes you realize you
have osteoarthritis more than the inability to do the things you
like.''
</P>
<P>
   FOR MORE INFORMATION
</P>
<P>
   For free information on osteoarthritis, contact the Arthritis
Foundation at 1-800-283-7800 or www.arthritis.org.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken McAlpine often writes about health and fitness for
``Southwest Spirit'' and ``Outside'' magazines.)
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on LIFEBEAT
and other features. &QL;
</P>
