<HEADLINE>
PLAN TO RETIRE AT 56 IS DUBIOUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. In addition to my 401(k) contributions, I add $6,000 a year
to my taxable investment accounts. I currently have assets totaling
$727,000, but plan to purchase a home next year for approximately
$300,000. What securities do you recommend liquidating to purchase
the home? Or should I take out a 10-year mortgage? If I retire at
56, I will need to live off savings until I can withdraw from my
401(k) at 59 1/2. Should I change my fund allocations?
</P>
<P>
   R.B., Stoughton, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The plan seems pretty dubious to me. Let's assume you decide
to make a $200,000 down payment on your home, leaving you with
$527,000. After a decade of growth with the contributions you
outline, you would have $1,372,674. Of this, $408,451 would be in
taxable accounts _ which should be sufficient to supply your needs
until you can draw on the 401(k) accumulation. (In both of these
projections, I used a 7 percent projected annual return from
investments, based on your predilection for money market and other
fixed-income investments.)
</P>
<P>
   Now, after subtracting your savings, you have a current income
of $95,500 (not counting whatever bonuses you may earn). If
inflation averages 3.5 percent for the next decade, you will need
$134,712 to buy the goods and services $95,500 buys today.
Disregarding which pool you used to supply the funds, your
$1,372,674 total accumulation would be inadequate to long support a
sequence of withdrawals at a $134,712 level; for example, if your
portfolio earned the same 7 percent, you would run out of money in
less than 18 years _ at the tender age of 74. And that doesn't even
begin focusing on the effect of post-retirement inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Now, of course, there are some things you can do to improve the
situation. Most obvious is to adjust your portfolio so that you
have a heavier stock exposure and a much lighter commitment to
money markets and bonds. Second, if you resolved to add all or most
of your bonuses to the retirement pool, obviously the picture would
be brighter. Third, if you treat your savings as a percentage of
income, increasing the level as your income rises, that would be
another improvement. And fourth, most people find that they require
less money in retirement than they did in their working years, so
you might be able to reduce your retirement budget to less than the
equivalent of $95,500 in today's money.
</P>
<P>
   Let's get to some specifics. First, to make a $200,000 down
payment on your home, I suggest you sell your entire position in
government-backed bonds, taking the $16,000 loss on the
transaction. You could then sell about $16,000 worth of your
Perkinelmer stock, with the capital loss from the bonds more or
less offsetting your gains from the stock sale. (In all likelihood,
you could sell more than $16,000 worth of Perkinelmer with no tax
consequence, but I can't calculate it without knowing your tax
basis on those shares.)
</P>
<P>
   If you took a $100,000 mortgage, your payment would be about
$1,200, plus taxes (a calculation that assumes a 7.8 percent
interest rate). Since that figure is probably close to what you are
paying in rent, the change from renter to homeowner should be more
or less a wash. (But you probably shouldn't deduct the amount of
your mortgage payment from your cost of living at age 56, since
property tax increases over the course of that decade would come
fairly close to the reduced housing expense once the mortgage is
paid off.)
</P>
<P>
   As for your investment vehicles, you have $418,000, or more than
57 percent of your total portfolio, in fixed-income investments. If
you followed my suggestion about financing your home purchase, you
would have $230,000, or 43.6 percent of a $527,000 portfolio on the
fixed-income side. But if you decided to retain only your $75,000
money-market position, which I deem to be emergency savings, as a
fixed-income investment, that side of the portfolio would be
reduced to 14.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   If you made this move, you could probably boost your expectation
of long-term total returns to 9 percent or a bit higher. This would
improve the situation, providing a balance (on paper, of course) or
$1,642,407 at age 56. Since that's still not enough to prudently
finance a solid retirement, you can fairly confidently assume the
higher risk that goes with stock holdings _ the longer you plan to
hold stocks, the less the risk factor should bother you.
</P>
<P>
   Although it has nothing to do with eligibility to withdraw funds
from your 401(k) account, I made some projections based on
retirement at age 59 1/2, which seems more plausible. By then, with
a 9 percent earnings assumption, you would accumulate $2,337,868.
At that stage with the same 3.5 percent inflation you would need
$151,949 to provide the equivalent of a current $95,500 lifestyle.
Quite by coincidence, if your projected savings pool were then in a
fixed-income portfolio yielding 6.5 percent, it would bring you
$151,961. Send me the extra $13 (just kidding).
</P>
<P>
   Of course that would leave you no protection against inflation.
But if you added some of your bonuses to your retirement savings
and increased the dollar value of your savings to maintain the same
savings percentage as your income rises, you should have
considerably more than that $2.3 million, and that money could be
left in growth securities to protect you from future inflation.
Moreover, 6.5 years later you would have the kick added by both
Social Security and that pension. And finally, since you would then
have sufficient funds to last you many years, you would not have to
worry if you were depleting your accumulation during your 80s or
90s.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Am I amassing too much in my 401(k) plans? Should I take some
money I save and put it in a Roth IRA? I am recently married and
have no kids, but I have earmarked the $120,000 in common stocks
and the Massachusetts Investors fund to supplement my husband's
salary in three to four years when I stay home with the children we
plan to have.
</P>
<P>
   S.N., Portland, Ore. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I don't think you are saving too much, especially in view of
the fact you anticipate a gap in your working years to raise
children _ a practice I view as a wonderful investment in your
family, even if it slows down your retirement savings. In three
years, presuming ongoing contributions at current levels and 10
percent portfolio earnings, you would have about $241,622, and
during your years off you can presume that the internal growth of
your 401(k) accounts will keep you on track. (In that calculation,
I used your total portfolio summary, rather than the values listed
above, which were calculated from current prices; the actual
projection would be higher, since your portfolio has improved since
your letter was written.)
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, I'd like to see you and your husband with some
emergency savings. But you could view the other investments as
fulfilling that need, and your current 401(k) with its 100 percent
employer match is simply too good a deal to pass up. So I would
continue with your current contributions to your 401(k).
</P>
<P>
   (I don't know if you and your husband keep your finances
separate. If you don't mind mingling your money, and if your
employer would continue matches if you made larger contributions to
the 401(k) account, it would make sense to increase your
contributions and for your husband to decrease his by the same
amount, thus leaving the two of you with the same joint take-home
pay, but with more money going into the retirement accounts.)
</P>
<P>
   I do suggest one change. All of the money in your other
investments is in stocks and a stock fund. Since you plan to call
on this money in three to four years, financial specialists would
view this as short-term money. It is unwise to leave money that's
to be used for a short-term purpose in long-term investments such
as stocks.
</P>
<P>
   I suggest that, with a view to the tax implications, you begin
winding down that portfolio. If the tax implications aren't
onerous, I'd sell the entire portfolio now, putting the proceeds in
a two-year CD. But if you have significant capital gains in that
portfolio, you might be better off selling about a third this year,
another third next year, and the remainder the following year, thus
spreading out the tax liability.
</P>
<P>
   While the employer match to your 401(k) makes the Roth IRA
alternative unattractive in your case, that option may be a good
one for your husband, whose employer makes no 401(k) match. You'll
have to look over your total tax situation to decide whether the
future benefits of a Roth IRA outweigh the cost of adding $2,000 a
year to your taxable income. For most people of your ages, the Roth
comes out on top. If you do make that move, you will want to invest
the Roth money in the most aggressive securities with which you are
comfortable; since the accumulation in a Roth IRA will eventually
come out tax-free, that's where you want your holdings with the
greatest potential for gain.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Hooker can be reached at The Boston Globe, P.O. Box
2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
