<DOCNO> NYT20000710.0103 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 13:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7779 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-MONEY-TRAUSCH-BOS &LR;      07-10 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEY-TRAUSCH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
24/7 EXCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN TRAUSCH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; OK, people, let's turn off the cell phones. It's summer. It's
hot. It's vacation time, and God knows we could use the break
because a lot of us have been cranky since March.
</P>
<P>
   Hit that red key with authority, throw the thing into a drawer,
along with the laptop and the beeper, and head for the beach
unencumbered by technology. Last one to unplug is a rotten egg!
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't,'' says public relations kahuna George Regan, calling
from a golf course on the Cape. ``It's an addiction. It's like
being on a drug. I've been doing this since I was 24. I was Kevin
White's press secretary.''
</P>
<P>
   Gloria Larson, partner at Foley, Hoag &AMP; Eliot, is just as bad.
``I've been fighting it, but so far have made no inroads. On a
picture-perfect day on St. Bart's I was on a four-hour conference
call. I'd take a book to the beach and around noon I'd say, `Oh
it's time to escape the noonday sun.' Then I'd go back to the room
and return 18 phone calls. It's a personality problem. It's on a
DNA chip.''
</P>
<P>
   Pat Moscaritolo, president and chief executive of the Greater
Boston Convention &AMP; Visitors Bureau, sets no example of
uncontrolled joie de vivre for the tourists, either. He takes his
laptop and cell phone wherever he goes so he can check in with the
office to find out what he's missing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the rule today, not the exception,'' he says. ``If you're
in business, your clients expect you to keep in touch. And you can,
because with e-mail you can check in 24 hours a day no matter what
continent you're on.''
</P>
<P>
   Is this efficiency or an update of Dante? Maybe it's time to
find a nice cave and move in for a couple of weeks. Pack nothing
that blinks or beeps. Send no pigeons to the office. Live on the
edge _ give up CNBC.
</P>
<P>
   Not likely, says Moscaritolo _ if there were a cave experience
it would probably be tied to a business trip because vacations are
often ``add ons'' today, afterthoughts following a convention or
other work-related travel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing the re-engineering of life,'' he says. ``In the
1950s, the factories closed up and the family piled in the station
wagon for vacation. Today, Mom comes to Boston for a medical
meeting and extends her stay a few days so that Dad and the kids
can fly up to do the museums. Later in the summer, Dad attends a
telecommunications meeting in another city and Mom flies up with
the kids for a few days. It's very hard to get everyone on the same
page for a vacation. The kids are busy, too, with their schedules
and don't want to go away.''
</P>
<P>
   So, buckle little Johnny firmly into his car seat and tell him
he's going to have fun at the cottage on the lake or else. How bad
could it be, once he stops screaming for his soccer team?
</P>
<P>
   How much would the economy suffer if America blew the whistle on
work the way the French do in August? What if we as a nation
decided to bring back that unfettered ``can't be reached until
after Labor Day'' vacation?
</P>
<P>
   ``All the cardiologists would go broke,'' says David Porter, who
runs Baystate Financial Services in Boston. When he goes on an
11-day baseball park tour with his son this summer, he will check
his e-mail every night and carry his cell phone. ``I can call
anywhere in the country with no roaming charges.'' Porter, who has
a house in Maine, has also installed a phone line at his dock.
</P>
<P>
   ``The electronics drive this,'' he says. ``People want instant
access to things.''
</P>
<P>
   Do we, really, or did progress simply drop on our heads? Are we
more like the sorcerer's apprentice than we would like to admit?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's insecurity,'' says one businessman of his compulsion to
stay connected. ``It's nervousness.''
</P>
<P>
   We could all take a page from Paul Guzzi, president and chief
executive of the Greater Boston Chamber of Commerce, who has
attained the serenity of the Buddha when it comes to getting away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know whether it's age or mellowing or just having
confidence in other people, but I feel no need to stay in touch,''
he says. ``If there's an emergency, people know how to contact me.
This is a very different attitude for me than in my past work
lives.''
</P>
<P>
   The man gets the golden inner tube award. And he says he knows
other executives who think the same way. Here's hoping they start a
movement _ as long as nobody has to use a cell phone to do it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Susan Trausch is a member of the Globe staff. She can be reached
by e-mail at trausch(at)globe.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
