<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENERGY CRISIS? THERE'S ANGER TO SPARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Everybody seems to agree that something must be done about the
fuel crisis, but what?
</P>
<P>
   Beg the OPEC countries to squeeze out a few billion more
barrels? Dig deep under the ocean floor for new sources of oil?
</P>
<P>
   These are stopgap solutions. The world supply of oil won't last
forever. The long-term answer lies in exploiting as many energy
sources as possible _ solar power, wind power, water power, steam
power, nuclear power, crystal power, Power Bars, the power to cloud
men's minds _ as well as certain hitherto little-considered power
sources, such as anger.
</P>
<P>
   Anger. Why not?
</P>
<P>
   It may sound crazy, but people probably said the same about
hydro power when it was first proposed, and look at the Hoover Dam.
</P>
<P>
   Every minute of every day, we, as a nation, generate massive
amounts of anger. Where does it go? Anybody who's studied
elementary physics knows all that energy doesn't just disappear. It
wafts around in the atmosphere, looking for trouble. Why not find a
way to harness its power for good instead of evil? And save money,
besides.
</P>
<P>
   Already teams of researchers are working quietly, as quietly as
possible given the circumstances, to find ways of using the power
of anger.
</P>
<P>
   It's the perfect energy source. It's cheap, convenient, and
environmentally sound.
</P>
<P>
   Best of all, it's renewable. No matter what happens, we never
seem to run out of anger.
</P>
<P>
   Of course anger isn't always safe _ or clean. It's often
dangerous and messy, but every power source has its drawbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Converting anger to usable energy presents problems, not all of
them technological. Researchers have found some potential power
sources unwilling to cooperate. They understandably fear they'll
spontaneously combust, or that their brain waves will be twisted by
the powers of darkness, or that crop circles will appear on their
lawns and they'll end up on the cover of The Weekly World News, or
featured on ``Unexplained Mysteries.''
</P>
<P>
   Recent experiments involving guests on ``The Ricki Lake Show''
generated uneven results. Researchers found that some of these
subjects weren't really angry at all, but were faking it to get on
TV and embarrass their families. However, a minority of guests who
were genuinely mad generated enough energy to power a Belgian
waffle iron for almost three minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, some likely energy sources have turned nasty when
approached, frightening researchers, and frustrating them, too,
because they hate to see so much potential power going to waste.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for science, there's plenty of anger in the air just
about everyplace these days. At ATMs. In supermarkets. In doctors'
offices. Remember your last visit to the dermatologist? The anger
generated by you and all the other patients stuck there for hours
in the waiting room could have fueled a bus trip to Hartford and
back.
</P>
<P>
   With gasoline prices so high, there are lots of angry drivers on
the road, even more than usual. One team of scientists is working
on the high-priority project of converting road rage into energy to
fuel automobiles. Every driver soon could be his or her own power
source, lending new meaning to the term ``human dynamo.''
</P>
<P>
   These researchers have been a little reluctant to test their
findings on highways because they have yet to find a way to store
accumulated anger energy. With no way to store power, drivers would
need to be in a constant fit to get their cars to move. But isn't
that the way it works now?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Diane White is a Boston Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
