<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-GUIDE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVIES RECENTLY REVIEWED IN THE BOSTON GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   !! 1/2 ``Jesus' Son'' Filmmaker Alison Maclean renders the
druggy odyssey of Billy Crudup's sweet void watchable and often
entertaining by surrounding him with pungent characters, especially
Samantha Morton's cocaine addict, Jack Black's manic hospital
orderly, and Holly Hunter's tender dance partner. But you never
quite lose sight of the fact that the film needs diversions to keep
from imploding. (R)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
!! 1/2 ``The Kid'' Charm succumbs to sentimentality in this story
of a prosperous but unhappy 40-year-old who's paid a visit by his
8-year-old self in the interests of
</P>
<P>
   self-therapy. Bruce Willis brings deft economy to the
character's grown-up consternation, and Spencer Breslin holds his
own as the boy with a lot on his mind _ but the
</P>
<P>
   ones you really feel for are the women waiting for the guy to
grow up. (PG)
</P>
<P>
   (FU) !! 1/2 ``Scary Movie'' There's nowhere this
envelope-pushing gross-out parody won't go, no taboo or bodily
orifice beyond its rude and sometimes very funny reach as it sends
up the ``Scream'' movies, ``The Matrix,'' ``The Blair Witch
Project,'' and ``The Sixth Sense.'' But there's also no escaping
the fact that this comedy by Keenen Ivory Wayans and his brothers
Shawn and Marlon is pretty flimsy. (R) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   !! 1/2 ``Trixie'' As a Chicago working-class girl who talks in
malapropisms, longs to be a detective, and gets involved in the
murder of an over-the-hill cabaret singer at a seedy resort, Emily
Watson almost carries this Alan Rudolph film past its limitations.
It never quite becomes the screwball noir it wants to be, but
nobody makes idiosyncratic mood pieces quite like Rudolph, and Nick
Nolte, Lesley Ann Warren, and Nathan Lane are three more reasons to
cut it some slack. (R)
</P>
</TEXT>
