<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 13:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7790 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-CONSUMER-COLUMN-ART-B     07-10 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMER-COLUMN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLINE FIRMS TRY TO EASE CHOOSING SERVICE PROVIDERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A graphic is being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
888-346-9867 or 888-603-1036.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MOHL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Time is the biggest enemy of most consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Most people want to find the right credit card or the best
long-distance provider, but because of the time it takes to do the
research they often end up staying with their existing company or
going with the intriguing offer that comes in the mail.
</P>
<P>
   Three Web sites _ Lowermybills.com of Los Angeles,
Omnichoice.com of Wayne, Pa., and GetConnected.com of Boston _ are
among many trying to make choosing a service provider easy, or at
least easier.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Essential.com of Burlington or Servisense of Newton,
which actually sell a stable of services to customers and bill them
directly, these three companies serve strictly as information
intermediaries. They attempt to give you the information you need
to make a wise choice.
</P>
<P>
   Lowermybills is the most ambitious, enlisting other Web sites
such as E-Loan and energyguide.com to provide information in more
than 10 categories, ranging from electricity to credit cards.
Omnichoice and GetConnected have a slightly narrower reach,
focusing primarily on telecommunications services.
</P>
<P>
   The three companies have different philosophies. Lowermybills
asks visitors to its site few questions about their usage patterns
and tends to provide a generic, edited list of solutions to any
query. Ask about high-speed Internet access, for example, and
Lowermybills gives you seven service options from three companies.
All of the companies provided digital subscriber line, or DSL,
service. None offered cable modems.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not really interested in all of the companies out
there,'' said chief executive Matthew Coffin. ``People only want up
to about six choices. Anything beyond that is seen as an
annoyance.''
</P>
<P>
   Omnichoice tries to customize its answers for each customer. It
asks users to answer questions that narrow the range of options and
then ranks the answers one through 10. ``We give you an answer, not
a bunch of options,'' said Tom Borger, chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   GetConnected's philosophy seems to be a blend of what
Lowermybills and Omnichoice do. It lets the user decide whether he
wants a large unedited list of options or a smaller list whittled
down to fit certain preferences.
</P>
<P>
   All of the sites would be useful to people who are moving, who
are dissatisfied with their current providers, who are thinking
about buying a cellular phone and want to explore their options, or
who just want to see if there's a better deal out there for long
distance.
</P>
<P>
   For example, I'm looking for a credit card with no annual fee
that maximizes rewards. Lowermybills turned me on to the American
Express platinum cash rebate card, which offers 2 percent cash back
when you carry a balance and 1.5 percent when you don't. Not bad.
</P>
<P>
   But I also discovered that some of these sites are prisoners of
their own business models. They have to be national in scope to
bring in a large volume of customers, but going national sometimes
means being out of touch locally.
</P>
<P>
   Lowermybills, for example, offers an auto insurance category
through Insweb.com that allows users to shop for the best deal. In
Massachusetts, however, all rates are set by state regulators and
the only pricing variable is the size of good-driver or group
discounts.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Lowermybills/Insweb site doesn't analyze the various
discounts. With only two participating Massachusetts auto insurers,
the site is practically useless to Bay State residents. (To its
credit, the site didn't pretend it was useful but it did make me
spend 15 minutes filling out forms only to be told I couldn't be
helped.)
</P>
<P>
   All three sites make their money when consumers go through them
to sign up with one of the providers. Each Web site insists its
information is unbiased, offering information on service providers
even if the provider isn't paying the Web site a referral fee. ``If
it's out there, we want to offer it,'' said Adam Mersky, a
spokesman for GetConnected.
</P>
<P>
   But you have to wonder sometimes. Neither Omnichoice nor
Lowermybills listed AT&AMP;T, formerly MediaOne, as a high-speed
Internet service option in Massachusetts. Tell that to the
company's thousands of customers in this area. (Both companies told
me they plan to add MediaOne in the future.)
</P>
<P>
   The sites also seem to have a hard time taking into account
issues beyond price. How do you evaluate a company's reputation for
service and reliability? How do you factor in the convenience and
cost savings of bundling many services together with one provider?
</P>
<P>
   Of the three sites I reviewed, I preferred Omnichoice's
approach. But I felt GetConnected did the best overall job.
GetConnected seemed to offer the most comprehensive information and
offered other helpful extras as well. It had a feature on bundled
services and even let users rate service providers so other
visitors to the Web site could get a sense of reliability.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Odds &AMP; Ends
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Driving, movies. The American Automobile Association had two
interesting items in its July newsletter to members. One item
reported that the average cost of driving a car is now 49.1 cents
per mile, up 2.1 cents from last year, primarily because of higher
fuel prices and rising new vehicle depreciation and finance costs.
The newsletter also offered members discounted movie ticket
packets: $24 gets you four tickets to a Showcase Cinema and $21
gets you four tickets to a General Cinema. At the new Fenway
General Cinema, where adult tickets cost $9, the discount amounts
to $15.
</P>
<P>
   Item pricing. Last week's column on the item-pricing debate
generated responses across the lot. Some readers passed along the
names of other retailers that don't item price (Wal-Mart); others
suggested alternative approaches (bar code readers every 20 feet);
and some suggested government shouldn't be involved at all. Bill
Beasley, who used to live in Michigan, said he didn't sense great
support for item-pricing there, despite the attorney general's
claims to the contrary. By the way, the Michigan attorney general
last week called OfficeMax the worst-ever violator of the state's
item-pricing law and prepared to sue.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Mohl can be reached at 617-474-2510, by e-mail at
mohl(at)globe.com, or at The Boston Globe, P.O. Box 2378, Boston,
MA 02107-2378.
</P>
</TEXT>
