<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-DEMANDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN MEXICO, THE CHANGE IS JUST BEGINNING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Anyone who thinks last Sunday's historic elections
were only about presidential politics should try telling that to
Guadalupe Gutierrez Cantu.
</P>
<P>
   The 42-year-old housewife spent nearly a half-hour on Wednesday
afternoon arguing with a sales clerk at a Mexico City department
store. Her complaint: That her credit card was being wrongly
rejected by the store's computers.
</P>
<P>
   Gutierrez wouldn't give up. She insisted the problem was with
the store's system, not her card, and lectured a manager on the
basics of customer service. Finally, he checked with her bank. She
was right.
</P>
<P>
   When asked by a stranger who witnessed the scene whom she voted
for for president, Gutierrez answered Vicente Fox, the conservative
opposition candidate whose victory last week ousted the ruling
party for the first time in more than seven decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the way he talks and he doesn't put up with any
games,'' Gutierrez said. ``Mexicans are tired of being told what's
good and bad. We're ready to have more control over our own
lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to Mexico 2000. This country of traditions, rituals, and
authoritarian governments is giving way to a new attitude that
demands accountability, responsiveness, and, above all, change.
Last week's historic vote was perhaps the most dramatic expression
that Mexicans no longer want to be told what to do by their
government. But banks, churches, telephone companies, cable TV
operators, and car dealers had better take notice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an extremely liberating feeling, like a great weight has
been lifted from our chest,'' said Homero Aridjis, the renowned
Mexican poet. ``There is a new sense of control and it's the kind
of revolution that will be felt throughout the society.''
</P>
<P>
   To Aridjis and other of his countrymen, Mexico's electoral
revolt at the ballot box was driven by a collective shame over the
condition of the country and a frustration with the oligarchy of
elite, closely related families that for years has controlled the
ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mexico is a country that moves slowly to act,'' the poet
added. ``It took us 300 years to revolt against Spain, another 100
before we overthrew a dictator in the Mexican Revolution, and
another 70 years before we stood up against the PRI. This time it
was a rebellion by the middle class.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week's revolt was stunning for its complete rejection of
the PRI, which not only lost its first presidential race ever, but
also lost its majority in both houses of Congress, was badly beaten
in the Mexico City mayor's race, and beaten as well in two
gubernatorial contests.
</P>
<P>
   But the victory by Fox's National Action Party, or PAN, may be
less about partisanship than the results suggest, said Roderic Ai
Camp, a Mexico specialist at Claremont McKenna College in
California, and it could provide a key lesson for the candidates in
this year's US presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   The PAN is Mexico's second largest political party, with a core
of roughly 20 percent of Mexico's 59 million voters. Fox's campaign
received 42 percent of votes, meaning that most of his support came
from the PRI and other party members.
</P>
<P>
   ``This says that you can join a political movement instead of a
party and change results, even presidents,'' Camp said. ``It'll
change the way people look at participating in politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Since its creation in 1929 as an alliance of competing factions
from the Mexican Revolution, the PRI has dictated nearly every
facet of Mexican life. It tried to shut out the Roman Catholic
Church. Through its control of government, it created petroleum,
telephone, and banking monopolies that predetermined prices for
customers. And it demanded votes rather than court them.
</P>
<P>
   The first signs of modern civil unrest against this rigid system
appeared in 1968, when hundreds of students protested against
President Gustavo Diaz Ordaz just before the opening of the Olympic
Games in Mexico City. The government killed hundreds of protesters
in a massacre that is still remembered annually.
</P>
<P>
   A more recent episode of widespread unhappiness with the PRI
government, as noted by Susan Eckstein, Boston University
sociologist and Mexico specialist, was the massive 1985 earthquake
that killed thousands in the capital. Government delays in
reconstructing damaged homes left scores of angry families
homeless.
</P>
<P>
   ``The victims refused to listen to the government and formed
their own groups that demanded they listen to their demands for
more low-income housing,'' said Eckstein, an author who has written
on social movements in Latin America. ``People realize they are no
longer dependents of the party or the government or any other
institution that doesn't respond to their needs.''
</P>
<P>
   Other factors have also contributed to building the new Mexico,
but none more important than information. The country's two main
television networks, Televisa and Azteca, compete fiercely against
each other daily to uncover government mistakes or neglect.
</P>
<P>
   Talk radio has flooded Mexican airwaves. Mexico's newspapers,
once safely in the pocket of government officials, are much more
aggressive today. And the Internet now allows quick access to
everything, from the indigenous Zapatista rebels in Chiapas state
to government statistics that once took months to wrestle away from
stingy bureaucrats.
</P>
<P>
   Businesses have also changed for the more demanding Mexican
customer. Banks now lure new customers with promotions for new cars
or computers. There are now as many Wal-Marts, Price Clubs, and
Sam's in Mexico City as there are in some US cities. And telephone
service, which was privatized about 20 years ago, offers clients a
choice in long distance and cellular companies.
</P>
<P>
   Not everything is perfect. Credit remains both hard to get and
prohibitively expensive _ with annual interest rates on a credit
card around 30 percent _ for most residents. And Mexico's
overpriced gasoline still comes from a state-run monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   And, for all its new attitudes and promise of a new,
customer-oriented society, Mexico remains a traditional and
conservative country, one that takes change at its own pace, even
with a charismatic, boot-wearing, straight-talking rancher and
former Coca-Cola executive leading the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the same values about families and work, but now we
have choices, especially in our government,'' said Aridjis, the
poet. ``And now we'll demand accountability and attention, not just
from our president but from everyone else in Mexico.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
