<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-CONSERVATIVE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW, TELEGENIC PRESENCE GIVES CONSERVATIVES HOPE IN CANADA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. JOHN'S, Newfoundland _ Canada's conservative movement, long
dismissed as toothless, is suddenly flashing sharp fangs with the
emergence of a vigorous, telegenic, and articulate new leader at
the helm of what may prove to be Canada's first formidable modern
political party of the right.
</P>
<P>
   Stockwell Day, 49, the former provincial treasurer of Alberta,
who until six months ago was a virtual unknown outside of his home
province, scored an upset victory Saturday to win control of the
Canadian Alliance, the fledgling party that already is the second
most powerful in Canada _ after the governing Liberal Party _ since
it inherited the parliamentary seats of the defunct Reform Party.
</P>
<P>
   With the emergence of a conservative leader attractive enough to
capture significant numbers of votes across Canada, not just in the
right-leaning western provinces, the country appears headed for its
most bruising political showdown in years. Day will challenge Prime
Minister Jean Chretien, a 66-year-old Quebecer, in national
elections expected to be called this fall or early next spring.
</P>
<P>
   Chretien's allies wasted no time Sunday casting the upstart as a
Bible-thumping, gay-bashing, ``American-style'' right-winger. Day
makes no secret of his deep Christian faith, but the ``homophobic''
tag _ much ballyhooed in the media _ seems to be based entirely on
his rather mild opposition to gay marriage, which is hardly a
burning issue in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Strangely, perhaps, Day's muscular good looks have made the
long-married, strait-laced father of three a popular pinup for
homosexual men. According to press reports, photos of Day in
tight-fitting martial arts garb _ he is a fitness zealot _ are all
the rage in gay bars and gyms across Canada, with no irony
intended.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, because of his charisma and ability to communicate,
many analysts compare Day to former prime minister Pierre Elliott
Trudeau, although there is no similarity in their politics.
</P>
<P>
   Day is a fiscal conservative who wants to slash government
expenditures in a country where a national health system, generous
European-style welfare programs and other social spending mean that
Canadians fork out far more in taxes than their neighbors in the
United States. He also wants to beef up the country's
disintegrating military forces and toughen the criminal code.
</P>
<P>
   ``My message has been consistent,'' Day said. ``Tax reform for
families, individuals, and business. Increased health funding, and
resources to the armed forces. Fix the criminal justice system.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Canadian media have reported almost obsessively on Day's
reservations about gay marriage and his religious objections to
abortion (he has stated repeatedly that he has no interest in
making abortion, legal in Canada, into a political issue). Fairly
typical of the news coverage was last week's issue of Maclean's,
the country's leading newsmagazine, which ran a photograph of Day
on the cover under the big headline, ``How Scary?''
</P>
<P>
   The second paragraph in the article stated, ``There's something,
well, vaguely American about him. He owns a .38 handgun.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Day's charisma and physical vigor make him a formidable
threat to Chretien. The prime minister has held power since 1993
and has said repeatedly that he will seek a third term, despite
public opinion surveys showing that Canadians are growing weary of
his competent but noticeably uninspired leadership and the fact
that many powerful figures within the Liberal Party are urging
Chretien to step aside in favor of a younger candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Conventional wisdom has it that a serious conservative like Day
has no chance of winning a national election in Canada, a country
whose citizens seem to think that big government social spending,
high taxes, and light criminal penalties prove that their country
is more compassionate and enlightened than the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But, until a few weeks ago, conventional wisdom also held that
an obscure provincial treasurer from Alberta's Bible Belt had no
chance of defeating Preston Manning, 58, the prairie populist who
more or less singlehandedly created both the Canadian Alliance and
its predecessor party, the Western-based Reform Party.
</P>
<P>
   Although Manning is deeply respected within conservative
circles, his squeaky voice and preachy manner made him unpalatable
to many voters, especially in the crucial province of Ontario,
which holds 103 of the 301 seats in the House of Commons.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, alliance members seem to have acted with their heads
instead of their hearts, defying predictions and ousting Manning in
favor of the younger candidate because Day seems truly capable of
winning votes across Canada, rather than just whining about Liberal
Party dominance.
</P>
<P>
   ``He comes across as an approachable, sincere kind of person,''
said Thomas Flanagan, a professor of politics at the University of
Calgary. ``It doen't hurt that he's telegenic with a young, fresh
face.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-00 1333EDT &QL; 
