<HEADER>
A7794 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-SHIPS-SLAVES-BOS &LR;      07-10 0946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHIPS-SLAVES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VESSELS OF A PAINFUL PAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAMAL E. WATSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Darnell Williams won't be among the millions of
spectators gathered around Boston Harbor this week to view the
colorful Tall Ships.
</P>
<P>
   Williams will boycott the event because, when he looks at the
great vessels, he doesn't see majesty; he sees haunting icons of
the slave trade. When the trade reached its peak, an armada of
sailing ships plied the Atlantic Ocean bound for the Americas, with
human cargo chained below deck.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a person of conscience, you look at these ships and it
forces you to think'' of the tens of millions who died during the
Middle Passage, said Williams, who heads the NAACP's Springfield,
Mass. chapter. ``These ships drum up negative images of how our
people arrived in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams is not alone in his opposition to Sail Boston 2000, the
11-day spectacle featuring 134 ships from 92 countries and expected
to attract 3 million visitors to the city. Dozens of New England
blacks interviewed in recent weeks by the Globe have also expressed
similar discomfort with the celebration.
</P>
<P>
   But those sentiments are by no means unanimous. Richard Neuman
of Harvard University's W.E.B Du Bois Research Institute says that
while he understands how the ships could symbolize slavery to some
blacks, to others, they represent a ``little-known, strong heritage
of free black sailors to whom the ships have become a memorial.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Johnson Jr., a professor of Africana Studies at the
University of Massachussetts at Boston, agrees with Neuman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at the Tall Ships from the perspective of those
African-Americans who engaged in maritime occupations,'' said
Johnson, pointing out the accomplishments of Louis Temple, a New
Bedford blacksmith who invented the toggle harpoon. ``This issue is
not black and white, although I can certainly understand the
sensitivity to the Tall Ships by some.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee Charlton, president of the New Bedford NAACP, and Sail
Boston 2000 organizers are quick to point out that all of the ships
featured in this year's festivities were built after 1940, more
than 100 years after the transport of slaves to the United States
ended.
</P>
<P>
   But don't tell that to George Lindsey, 67, a retired
schoolteacher who lives in Boston. He is angered by what he says
the ships represent.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is purely a symbolic issue for me,'' he said. ``When it
comes to black folks, there's a lack of sensitivity for our history
and culture. We're still dealing with the fallout from slavery and
these ships are just horrible, horrible, reminders.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Carolyn Richardson, 28, of Boston. ``It's appropriate that
as a society we become aware of the issues that offend people,''
she said. ``It's not a matter of being politically correct. It's
about being respectful. If there are some blacks who find the ships
offensive, I think they shouldn't sail.''
</P>
<P>
   That kind of comment frustrates Sail Boston 2000 officials.
After scattered protests during the Tall Ships celebration in 1992,
organizers said they made a concerted effort to reach out to
minorities. More than half of this year's vendors at commemoration
events are operated by minorities, and a minority-owned
communications firm has been hired to spread the word about the
Tall Ships in neighborhoods largely populated by black and Latino
residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sail Boston is proud to boast the inclusion of all minority
groups in all aspects of the Sail Boston 2000 experience,'' said a
statement by Dusty Rhodes, president of Sail Boston 2000. ``As the
majority of the events involved in Sail Boston 2000 are free, Sail
Boston welcomes people of all socioeconomic backgrounds to
experience the glory of the Tall Ships.''
</P>
<P>
   But Colette Phillips, who was hired to help publicize the event
throughout the minority community, said that she is aware that a
``perception problem'' exists among many blacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand the concerns,'' she said. ``But we're trying to
get people to realize that this is a multicultural event. It's
bigger than any one of us, and the goal here is to celebrate global
diversity.''
</P>
<P>
   But to Charlton, opposition to this year's festivities makes no
sense. He's an admirer of the Tall Ships and watched them sail into
Boston in 1992 during the 500th anniversary commemoration of
Christopher Columbus's voyage across the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, Tall Ships was a means of commerce, so some were used to
transport slaves. But I don't know how you could be opposed to all
Tall Ships because of that fact,'' he said. ``Hitler supported the
Volkswagen, and I happen to love the car. Does that make me a
supporter of Hitler? Of course not.''
</P>
<P>
   Other blacks said that the time spent protesting the Tall Ships'
arrival, could be better utilized rallying for other causes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can understand wanting to take down the Confederate flag in
South Carolina, but I don't understand how you can knock the whole
Tall Ship industry,'' said John Bynoe, who heads the Massachusetts
Prince Hall Grand Lodge, the largest black Masonic group in the
country.``I personally think the ships are beautiful. The issue of
slavery has never crossed my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who will not be attending the Tall Ships festivities said
that they will take time to educate their children about the evils
of slavery in America.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is that when the average black person thinks
of the Fourth of July or these other freedom celebrations, it's not
a time for us to celebrate,'' said Williams. ``It is more a
recognition of a period of dehumanization and degradation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
