<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-TOWN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALL TOWN REMAINS COOL ON PRESIDENTIAL CHOICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By YVONNE ABRAHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEBSTER GROVES, Mo. _ They're pretty good at picking presidents
around here. And they're none too happy with the choice they face
this year.
</P>
<P>
   This quaint community, a mostly middle-class suburb 15 miles
southwest of St. Louis, is in the middle of America, geographically
and ideologically. It is also a bellwether: As Webster Groves goes,
so goes St. Louis County. As St. Louis County goes, so goes
Missouri. And as Missouri has gone, so has the nation in all but
two presidential elections in the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   It is the kind of place where elections are won and lost, a
place where either presidential candidate can hope to win. And so
far this year, the news from Webster Groves isn't especially
pleasant for Al Gore or George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   People here are lamenting the slim pickings. Few are smitten by
Vice President Gore, the presumptive Democratic nominee, or the
Texas governor, his likely Republican opponent, although Bush seems
to have gained some local advantage by being the fresher face on
the national political scene. Phrases like ``lesser of two evils''
and ``least offensive'' are sprinkled into conversations about how
folks may vote. Party loyalists still seem inclined to line up,
although without joy, behind the standard-bearers. But swing
voters, and there are many, often seem at a loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep wishing that Bush seemed more intelligent and Al Gore
seemed like more of a leader,'' said Barbara Martin Smith, 55, an
artist and independent-minded voter who lives in the neighborhood
where her father and grandfather grew up. ``I'm not pleased with
either of them, and I don't know who I'd vote for if I had to
choose between them. And that's disturbing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the two parties aren't that different, and the
candidates aren't much of a choice,'' said restaurateur Tom Clary,
43.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that people here are cynical about politicians. They've
gotten excited about candidates in the past _ choosing Ronald
Reagan by landslide margins in 1980 and 1984, and giving Bill
Clinton a solid win in 1992 (although a less ringing reelection
vote in 1996).
</P>
<P>
   Nor are they distracted from the current race by other concerns.
Times are good here, as with the middle class in much of the
country. The stores and restaurants on Lockwood Avenue and Big Bend
Boulevard are thriving, houses are being renovated or rebuilt.
</P>
<P>
   And voters here, unlike many of their peers across the nation,
are paying attention. Voter turnout is historically high, civic
involvement sacrosanct. The desire to participate is rooted in a
sense of place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I get much more mail from my constituents than the
average state rep receives,'' said Emmy McClelland, a Republican
legislator whose district includes the town. ``And they're not just
little postcards with signatures. It's very thoughtful letters.''
</P>
<P>
   When folks ask the what-school-did-you-go-to question here, they
mean high school, not college. Children in this town of 25,000 can
live as simply as their parents did. Bicycles lie unlocked under
huge trees outside flag-festooned Victorian houses. Each year,
crowds line the streets for the grand Fourth of July parade, where
prizes are given for best lawn decoration and float. (This year's
theme was ``your favorite decade.'') Summer means candy bars from
Straub's and afternoon pilgrimages to Hogoboom's for sno-cones. The
whole place has the feel of a Saturday Evening Post cover.
</P>
<P>
   Houses here may cost $70,000 for a modest one-floor brick
cottage, or $2 million for a big Victorian with a long driveway.
Most residents have white-collar jobs in management, technology, or
the professions. About 10 percent have service industry jobs. The
average annual salary was about $58,000, according to the 1990
census, a figure that Mayor Gerry Welch said would probably jump
with this year's survey.
</P>
<P>
   About 10 percent of the city's population is African-American.
Hispanic and Asian residents each make up less than 1 percent of
the town's population. Politics, not population, shifts in Webster
Groves.
</P>
<P>
   Residents have been following the news closely enough to know of
Bush's defense of executions in Texas, and of renewed calls for
investigations into Gore's 1996 campaign fund-raising. They know of
Bush's plan to allow workers to invest a percentage of their Social
Security payroll taxes in the stock market, and of his admiration
for Supreme Court Justices Antonin Scalia and Clarence Thomas. Some
know of Gore's concern for the environment and of his plan to
include prescription benefits in Medicare coverage.
</P>
<P>
   But so far, it's not what the candidates are offering, or even
who they are that animates these voters. It's who Bush and Gore are
not. Few of the residents interviewed at the end of June said they
would cast a vote for either candidate on his own merits. Plenty
said they'd be voting against Gore or against Bush, and, in what is
perhaps bad news for Gore, against Clinton. That would seem to give
Bush the edge in Webster Groves, but largely by default. (Some of
those who despised what the Clinton administration had become
allowed that either candidate would be an improvement).
</P>
<P>
   ``My biggest problem is, they're all really rich white men. I
fear this is just a big fun power thing for them,'' said Bill
Reyland, 33, a musician who said he was concerned about the
candidates' views on abortion, gun control, education, and their
plans for providing for people as they get older.
</P>
<P>
   Reyland said, ``Bush is very aggressive, and that's a good
attitude. He seems like a tough guy who won't take anything from
anybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore's not convincing at all,'' Reyland said. ``He doesn't
seem to have any enthusiasm for it. It's not that `Gore is a boring
person thing.' He doesn't seem to be making the hard sell. Bush is
out there with his fist in the air.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Reyland's indecision, that comment was one of the
strongest in Bush's favor of two dozen lengthy interviews in the
town. More typical was John Streeter, a retired Air Force pilot,
who was far more vehement in his contempt for Gore than his
cautious approbation of Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Gore is a liar who has no integrity and is
poll-driven. And that about takes care of it. He would do anything
to be elected,'' said Streeter, 71, who typically votes Republican
although he said he may have voted for Harry Truman, a fellow
Missourian, in 1948.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see any negatives on Bush's side,'' Streeter said.
``He seems to be straightforward. He has a nice personality, and I
haven't heard anything negative about him, so I'd say he has more
integrity than Gore.'' When pushed, he added that he liked Bush
because he had experience as a governor, ``whereas Gore has never
governed anything or done anything other than be a senator and vice
president in a horrible administration.''
</P>
<P>
   At the O. T. Hodges Chili Parlor, where a group of retired and
semiretired men meet each weekday morning for eggs, and merciless,
indiscriminate ribbing, it was the same story. Some of them are
unreconstructed liberals, some are devout Republicans, and some,
like retired sporting goods store owner and current school sports
coach Lee Keefer, swing back and forth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a Republican, but I voted for Clinton. Twice. That's how .
. . stupid I am,'' said Keefer, 67. ``I won't go for Gore.
Basically, I'm not that much in favor of either man, but Bush could
do a better job.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore is ``a coattail man!'' said Bill Wright, who once owned a
machine tool company, and said he had always voted Republican,
except, maybe, in 1948. (His breakfast companions guffawed,
incredulous, at that.) Wright said he'd be for Bush, for sure.
</P>
<P>
   Among stalwart Democrats, Gore engendered similarly
underwhelming endorsements. Joseph Beck, 55, a voice coach who said
Clinton and Gore had handled the economy ``magnificently,'' said he
would definitely vote for Gore, but added that the vice president
``doesn't seem to lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``On a visceral basis, Bush seems like a leader,'' Beck said.
``Though he still hasn't gotten rid of that smirk.''
</P>
<P>
   Sally Beck, his wife, was far less ambivalent although not
enthusiastic, about the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore has been a consistent person, and he seems decent,'' she
said. ``What you see is what you get.''
</P>
<P>
   Sally Beck's view of Gore seems, on the basis of several days of
interviews, unusually positive in Webster Groves. Even in the
town's African-American community, which is usually staunchly
Democratic, there was little enthusiasm for Gore. It was all about
keeping Bush out of the White House.
</P>
<P>
   In barber Lee Moss's Hair Salon, there's been a lot of talk
lately of the recent execution of Gary Graham, an African-American
and the latest to face execution in Texas, where Bush governs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like Mr. Bush, and I don't like his stand on the death
penalty,'' said Moss, 58. ``The death penalty always is, if you
have money, you have ways to escape it. Only the poor people get
the death penalty.''
</P>
<P>
   So, Moss said, he and most of his customers would go for Gore,
although he added that many of his younger customers are more
affluent and oblivious to racial history than are voters of his
generation. In the current election, he said, the votes of blacks
should not be taken for granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``African-Americans take Gore because . . . basically, people
like Clinton, regardless of what he did, and Al Gore is on his
coattails,'' Moss said.
</P>
<P>
   For Otha Lee Davis, 55, owner of Lee's BBQ Plus, even such faint
praise for the vice president didn't come easily.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a registered Democrat, but I really haven't decided yet,''
said Davis, who is African-American. ``I'm not necessarily a big
fan of either guy. Gore doesn't strike me as presidential. Bush, I
kinda think he's been forced on the people. He's not thinking, `I
can help America.' He's saying, `I can help Bush.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, too, was insincere, Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Several voters waxed nostalgic for such charismatic characters
as John F. Kennedy, the young Clinton's idol, and a more recent
contender.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five months ago, I already had my mind made up,'' said Judy
Casanova, a 55-year-old realtor. ``I would have voted for John
McCain hands down.''
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona senator might have lost Missouri's primary to Bush
on March 7 by a whopping 23 percentage points, but some of the
Webster Groves residents interviewed, including two stalwart
Democrats, said he was their kind of candidate.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who lost to Bush in Webster Groves by fewer than 70
votes, isn't in the running anymore. Instead, voters here in
America's middle feel they must choose between two men for whom
they feel no strong allegiance.
</P>
<P>
   As Davis, the owner of Lee's BBQ Plus put it: ``At (election)
time, I'm gonna have to go for the lesser of two evils.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-00 1339EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000710.0116 </DOCNO>
