u a BC-FLEEING-DOCTOR-ART-BO     07-10 0605
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLEEING-DOCTOR-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (a and f coding)  
 HELPING OTHERS QUIT THE MEDICAL FIELD  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE BARNARD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ For at least one doctor-turned-entrepreneur,
physicians' career angst has become a business opportunity in
itself.
</P>
<P>
   As a psychiatric resident at Beth Israel Hospital, Gigi Hirsch
counseled doctors who felt stuck in the wrong career. Then she
realized she was one of them. She left medical practice in 1997 to
found MD IntelliNet, a company that specializes in what she has
dubbed ``physician human capital.''
</P>
<P>
   Running the firm out of her Brookline home, Hirsch, 45, links
doctors with jobs outside traditional physician roles and advises
companies on how to market new products and technologies to
doctors.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first hung out my shingle, some physicians who came to
see me gave me fake names,'' she said in an interview at Zaftigs,
the Harvard Street hangout that serves as her auxiliary office.
``They're not used to talking about career problems. They don't
want to be seen as `not coping well.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Managed care is not the root cause of many doctors'
dissatisfaction, she said. Rather, it has ``brought a lot of career
issues out of the closet'' by destroying the promise of delayed
gratification in the form of money, status and respect.
</P>
<P>
   Many disillusioned doctors stick with the profession, she said,
because their identity is tied to the ``Dr.'' title, or because the
average medical school graduate owes $80,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to be treated by a doctor who doesn't want to
be a doctor,'' Hirsch said. ``It's kind of an ugly thing and no one
wants to talk about this.''
</P>
<P>
   Unsatisfied doctors are more likely to be targeted by
malpractice suits and to file expensive disability claims, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   While there are growing opportunities for doctors in other
fields, it can be surprisingly hard for them to get hired, she
said. Many find networking distasteful, thinking their credentials
speak for themselves. And worse, doctors have an awful reputation
in the business world: arrogant, headstrong, demanding.
</P>
<P>
   But if they do it right, she said, they can ``leverage'' their
medical skills to get relatively high-level jobs in their new
field.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Silverstein, 45, still uses his analytical skills to
``diagnose'' problems, but at Boston Consulting Group, his patients
are now companies, not people. And Rod Altman, a former emergency
room doctor, said his new job in a venture capital firm _ dividing
finite capital among competing start-up proposals _ reminds him a
lot of triage.
</P>
<P>
   Those two got business degrees to move out of medicine, but one
of Hirsch's clients, Ilene Cohen, 44, took a more unusual route:
She taught herself HTML, the Web-design programming language, took
a programming course at Boston University, and was hired by a
medical software company. What she lacked in experience, she made
up for by knowing what doctors would look for in a program.
</P>
<P>
   Hirsch, who has consulted for 1,600 physicians since 1992, also
advises doctors on how to get into part-time activities such as
lecturing, patient advocacy, starting a business, and advising drug
companies. Avoiding conflicts of interest is up to the individual,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   As for her own business venture, Hirsch declined to say whether
it was profitable. ``It's growing,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Globe correspondent Kathryn Tong contributed to this story.
</P>
</TEXT>
