<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT YOUR ORDINARY MIDEAST SUMMIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- Inevitably, President Clinton finds himself this
week between Barak and a hard place.
</P>
<P>
   This is not your typical Middle East summit. Expectations should
always be beside the point in this age of hype, but they are
unusually so this week in Maryland's Catoctin Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Much more unusually, sticking points in negotiating positions
about the endgame between the Palestinians and the Israelis are
also beside the point. The basic outlines of the peace that is
possible at Camp David are not a secret. Hammering out details
would not cause any mature negotiator to break a sweat.Instead,
this is going to be a summit about will: who wants peace, who wants
a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   This is also going to be a summit about the consequences of
failure. The American role will be to get Ehud Barak and Yasser
Arafat focused on what they can reasonably expect if this more bold
than desperate gamble flops.
</P>
<P>
   The presemt moment has been coming ever since the Israeli prime
minister was elected after he appealed for a mandate to make peace.
In another sense it has been coming every since Barak's predecessor
and mentor, the late Yitzhak Rabin, decided to break through the
diplomatic impasses and reach an interim arrangement with Arafat
seven years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Rabin is said to have made a point to Barak at that
time that Barak made to close associates following his own
election: Now we are going to find out if the Palestinians really
want to stop the strife.
</P>
<P>
   That is not posture; it is truth. The courage shown by Rabin in
Oslo and by Barak in office has nearly eliminated doubt about
Israel's willingness to negotiate a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   The question now is whether the Palestinians can match this
courage. The reason the tea leaves are not auspicious this weekend
is that Arafat resisted coming here. Behind his assertion that the
preparations had not been thorough enough lies the question of
whether he and his supporters have the will to make the same
courageous move toward the Israelis that the Israelis have made
toward them. With the will, ways already exist to deal with
refugees, water, land, settlements, even Jerusalem; without the
will, the details won't matter.
</P>
<P>
   Facing death, Syria's President Hafez Assad was unable to reach
beyond his past. He dumped his mess into the lap of his unprepared
son.
</P>
<P>
   Now in shaky health himself, Arafat faces a similar choice, with
the important difference that having begun genuine diplomacy in the
1990s, he knew that a moment like the present loomed.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton's task this week will be primarily to describe
in detail the wrong road that may lie ahead.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a mystery. Stalemate, like failure to convene the
summit and permit continued drift, would call Arafat's bluff in
setting a deadline roughly 60 days hence, after which he would
unilaterally declare statehood on existing lands. If that were to
happen, Israel would almost certainly retaliate by formally
annexing land containing Jewish settlements on the West Bank,
setting the stage for a substantial escalation in tension and
probably violence.
</P>
<P>
   For both sides, it would be a hideous future. For the
Palestinians, there would be sovereignty over a ``nation'' that
would be crippled economically, impotent militarily, and bereft of
any hope of assistance, and US support for the Palestinian cause
would all but collapse. For Israel, there would be no end to the
costs of occupation and strife. And for Barak, his government
crumbling from the defection of coalition partners, a probably
shotgun marriage with the opposition Likud Party would strip him of
his mandate to take bold steps for peace.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's message will be that the future could be this bad, if
not worse. In their heads, both sides understand, but the US hope
is that detailed exposure to a post-failure world will change
hearts.
</P>
<P>
   Especially Arafat's. The days of holding out in the expectation
of more US pressure on Israel are over. However impatient his
people are, failure to negotiate this month will lead to even more
deprivation, this time with no end in sight.
</P>
<P>
   Against that certainty, he can grasp the opportunity, for
example, for sovereignty over 90 percent of the West Bank, or hold
out for the pre-1967 war borders forever without prospect of
success. He can maintain effective control in the Arab
neighborhoods of East Jerusalem and establish a capitol in the
adjacent neighborhood of Abu Dis, or he can hold out for all of
East Jerusalem, without prospect of success.
</P>
<P>
   Given the grim outlook, it goes without saying that Clinton was
correct in going for broke this summer. It was unavoidable.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has already gone for broke. It is now time to find out if
the Palestinians have a similar ability to see beyond the prison
walls of the status quo and take a similar risk. Israel is less
interested in Arafat's detailed ideas on a final deal than in
finding out at last if he is willing to make one.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-00 1343EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
