<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 13:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7803 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-UNIVISION-HNS &LR;      07-10 1441
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNIVISION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ODD COUPLE LEAD HISPANIC TV COMPANY TO PROMINENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JEANNE RUSSELL  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The unlikely pairing of the golden-tongued,
bilingual former politician and a media-shy, monolingual Hollywood
agent has been a happy marriage for shareholders of the nation's
most powerful Spanish-language communications company.
</P>
<P>
   When Henry Cisneros escaped the public glare as mayor of San
Antonio and secretary of Housing and Urban Development in President
Clinton's first term to become president of Univision
Communications Inc., his political charm became a true Midas touch.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has an uncanny ability to package ideas eloquently and to
convince people it's the right thing to do,'' said Adolfo Aguilar,
president of San Antonio advertising agency Creative Civilizations.
</P>
<P>
   Univision first turned a profit in 1996, the year it went public
and four years after A. Jerrold Perenchio bought it. Since Cisneros
joined the company in 1997, the price of its stock has jumped more
than fivefold. Stock values nearly tripled in 1999 alone.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers point to evidence of the company's savvy: Teens like
its programs better than MTV, young men choose it over ESPN, and
more Americans get their news from Univision than from CNN.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts view Univision as the country's second-fastest growing
media company, second only to America Online/Time Warner, though
the much smaller Spanish-language broadcast company is seldom
mentioned in the same breath.
</P>
<P>
   They see the Hispanic market as an unexploited dragon capable of
breathing fire when fully awakened.
</P>
<P>
   The fastest-growing minority in the United States, Hispanics are
expected to account for one in five Americans by 2005. Although
their per-capita income is about $10,000 lower than the $39,900
national average, by 2010 their buying power is expected to more
than double to $940 billion.
</P>
<P>
   And Hispanics are famously brand-loyal, making Univision's 92
percent hold on Spanish-language television viewers all the more
lucrative. Cisneros earned a $1 million bonus to sign on at
Univision in 1997 and is now a multimillionaire.
</P>
<P>
   Last year at Univision, he earned $4.5 million, including a base
salary of $600,000, plus $600,000 in bonuses and $3.3 million from
the sale of stock options.
</P>
<P>
   He can cash in additional stock options for about $5.2 million,
according to a proxy statement filed with the U.S. Securities and
Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
   As the Big Four networks struggle to stay relevant, Los
Angeles-based Univision enjoys a virtual lock on Spanish-language
television. It plays a critical role in shaping the identity and
opinions of viewers scattered across this nation and from different
countries of origin, with news and entertainment programs that
inform viewers about Cubans in Miami, Puerto Ricans in New York,
and Salvadorans in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Some have suggested that in this position, Cisneros has a
greater ability to craft public opinion that in any of his
political posts. But of course Univision is foremost a business,
and Cisneros' primary job is to ensure that stock prices and
revenues rise, said America Rodriguez, a professor of
communications at the University of Texas and author of the book
``Making Latino News: Race, Language, Class.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying he's not interested in promoting ethnic
identity. I think that's not his primary job,'' Rodriguez said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investors love companies that are leaders in their field,''
said Gordon Hodge, a California-based analyst with Thomas Weisel
Partners. ``From that standpoint, Univision has been a terrific
investment.''
</P>
<P>
   Behind the charismatic Cisneros is Perenchio, Univision's
chairman and the owner of almost 20 percent of the company's
shares. He is an Italian-American who seldom, if ever, consents to
interviews, and has been known to penalize top executives who do.
</P>
<P>
   Both Cisneros and Perenchio declined, through a New York
publicist, to be interviewed for this story.
</P>
<P>
   Perenchio, a hard-charging, prototypical Hollywood agent of the
type popularized in the movie ``Jerry Maguire,'' once promoted
Muhammad Ali, and was an early player in pay-per-view television.
He's one of California's largest political donors, a man with no
clear political stripe who stays in the shadows _ a ``ghost'' in
the words of Maria del Pilar Marrero, the political editor at La
Opinion, Los Angeles' largest Spanish-language newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Most analysts agree that Univision's dominance dates to a smart
deal Perenchio struck when he bought the company in 1992, sealing
an agreement for first dibs in the United States for programs from
Mexico TV giant Televisa and Venezuela's Venevision until 2017.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime you can produce for pesos and sell for dollars you're
going to make money,'' said Felix Gutierrez, now director of the
Freedom Forum in San Francisco. Gutierrez is a former academic who
studied Univision's predecessor in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Univision's advertising sales could reach the $1 billion mark
this year.
</P>
<P>
   And the gap between Univision's revenue and what it could earn
if its revenue equated with its audience share is estimated at $1
billion. Advertisers are famously reluctant to pay as much to
Spanish-language media as they are for English-language ads.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts see fertile terrain for growth, saying that the
disparity can't last forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over time, we believe that gap can close,'' said Paul Sweeney,
a New York-based analyst for Credit Suisse First Boston. ``I'm not
sure over what time.''
</P>
<P>
   Hodge said advertisers' negative perceptions about
Spanish-language media are already being overcome, though, citing
the example of Hispanic Broadcasting, a Dallas-based radio station.
</P>
<P>
   In Miami, Hispanic Broadcasting's radio station now commands
higher advertising rates than English-language stations, Hodge
said.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros' prominence helped when he personally called on top
advertisers to demand parity for Spanish-language television ads.
</P>
<P>
   ``Henry Cisneros has done a great job of getting in front of the
key U.S. companies and really telling this story _ the Hispanic
story,'' said Jessica Reif, a New York-based analyst for Merrill
Lynch. ``While Univision management has gotten in through sort of
normal channels, Henry has gotten in through the chairman or CEO
level.''
</P>
<P>
   Hodge called Cisneros ``a terrific ambassador for Univision, but
also for Hispanic advertising'' with connections to Fortune 500
companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been able to access some of these decision-makers and
convince them to at least look at the facts,'' Hodge said.
</P>
<P>
   The company raised advertising rates about 33 percent last year,
and most advertisers paid up.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a bold, a very bold step,'' said Adolfo Aguilar,
president of Creative Civilization, and past president of the
Association of Hispanic Advertising Agencies. ``It demonstrated we
must stand up for what is right and we must charge what is fair.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While Wall Street has applauded the Perenchio-Cisneros marriage,
it is a study in opposites.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros was the top-ranking Hispanic in the Democratic Party
when he went to work for Perenchio. (Cisneros's political career
hit a snag when he pleaded guilty in federal court to one
misdemeanor count of failing to report payments he made to a former
mistress during questioning by FBI agents who were conducting a
background check into his nomination to the Cabinet.)
</P>
<P>
   Perenchio donated heavily to former California Gov. Pete Wilson,
a Republican who backed a measure seen as anti-immigrant. On the
other hand, he was the largest donor for the campaign to defeat
Proposition 227, an initiative aimed at eliminating bilingual
education in California.
</P>
<P>
   The company's policy is to talk about stars and shows, but not
issues.
</P>
<P>
   So when Perenchio tapped the country's most visible Hispanic to
be Univision's public face, he demanded that Cisneros, like other
top executives, stay out of the news.
</P>
<P>
   Perenchio previously has enforced his no-comment mandate, firing
one employee who gave an interview, and fining network President
Ray Rodriguez $25,000 for a similar offense, according to the Wall
Street Journal.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, teased by talk that Cisneros was house-hunting in San
Antonio, supporters have lobbied him to help re-energize the
state's Democratic Party, perhaps by running for governor or
senator. And Cisneros was on the wish list to head the beleaguered
Los Angeles school system, but stated that he was not a candidate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-00 1344EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
