<DOCNO> NYT20000710.0120 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 13:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7805 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-JEFFERS-BOS &LR;      07-10 1137
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-JEFFERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROVER CLEVELAND: HALF-FORGOTTEN, HONEST TO THE CORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID M. SHRIBMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
AN HONEST PRESIDENT 
The Life and Presidencies of Grover Cleveland 
By H. Paul Jeffers. Avon. 384 pp. $27. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He is the only president to serve two non-consecutive terms. He
is the first president to be married in the White House, and the
father of the first child to be born there. He is the only Democrat
to be elected president between James Buchanan, who served before
the Civil War, and Woodrow Wilson, who brought the United States
into World War I.
</P>
<P>
   Grover Cleveland is the forgotten two-term American president.
The other two-full-termers _ George Washington, Thomas Jefferson,
James Madison, James Monroe, Andrew Jackson, Ulysses S. Grant,
Wilson, Franklin D. Roosevelt, Dwight Eisenhower, Ronald Reagan,
and, nearing the finish, Bill Clinton _ are vivid characters, each
a part of American folklore, each a part of American memory. But
Cleveland remains unknown, remembered if at all as the father of
Baby Ruth, the presidential daughter who lent her name to a candy
bar. (Even that is misunderstood; most contemporary Americans
believe the confection was named for a certain home-run titan.)
</P>
<P>
   Now H. Paul Jeffers, a Vermont native and prolific writer, has
taken on the task of presenting a 19th-century president to a
21st-century audience. It is an ambitious, audacious task _ this is
an era when few Americans know the identity of their own
representative on Capitol Hill _ but it is a worthy one, too.
Grover, we hardly knew ye. We hardly knew ye existed.
</P>
<P>
   But Cleveland was a giant in his time, and not only
metaphorically. He was, to be sure, large and imposing, casting a
big shadow over New York state and the United States for more than
a decade. He was also something of a boy wonder. He was a dutiful,
slightly iconoclastic mayor of Buffalo who in less than a year in
office found himself nominated for, and elected, governor and then,
about 15 minutes later (actually about two years) was elected
president. Clinton's rise to the presidency (a term as attorney
general, four elections as governor) was leisurely by comparison.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffers's volume is called ``An Honest President,'' and that
title lends an antiquarian feel to the book, as honest presidents
have not exactly been a dime a dozen in recent decades. No matter.
Grover Cleveland was an honest man, which is why he rose so fast.
He first attracted attention as a stand-up mayor who took on the
schemers on the Common Council, then teamed up with Republican
Theodore Roosevelt to battle appalling conditions in the
cigar-making industry, and finally took on Tammany leader John
Kelly. On the day he was elected governor, Cleveland wrote his
brother that he regarded election as ``a business engagement
between the people of the State and myself, in which the obligation
of my side is to perform the duties assigned me with an eye single
to the interest of my employers.'' We could do worse. We have.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland's honesty is best portrayed in the (dreaded and
gloomy) area of the private conduct of public figures. This is a
topic with which contemporary readers have some sad familiarity.
The truth in Cleveland's case is that he fathered a child out of
wedlock. When his friend Charles W. Goodyear asked him what the
Democratic Party should say about the matter, Cleveland issued a
telegram with six words for the ages: WHATEVER YOU DO, TELL THE
TRUTH.
</P>
<P>
   Full stop.
</P>
<P>
   Only it didn't stop there. (It never does.) The election of 1884
was probably the most sordid of all time. The Republican cry was
simple: ``Ma! Ma! Where's My Pa?'' The Democratic response,
targeted at the GOP nominee: ``Blaine, Blaine, James G. Blaine, the
continental liar from the State of Maine.'' In this mudfest,
Cleveland prevailed, but not before the Republicans, with an eye
toward the reformers and Roman Catholics in the Democratic
coalition, described their rivals as the party of ``rum, Romanism,
and rebellion.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland was an outsider like few others; until he was elected
president he had never so much as set a foot in Washington. He
shied away from patronage and even retained some Republican
officeholders. He wrote a scathing letter to a fellow Democratic
politician who pushed to win a federal job for an obviously corrupt
party worker: ``The idea that this administration, pledged to give
the people better officers and engaged in a hand-to-hand fight with
the bad elements of both parties, should be betrayed by those who
ought to be worthy of implicit trust, is atrocious, and such
treason to the people and to the party ought to be punished by
imprisonment.''
</P>
<P>
   And in an inaugural address he delivered from memory _ imagine
the next president trying that! _ Cleveland declared: ``The people
demand reform in the administration of the government, and the
application of business principles to public affairs.''
</P>
<P>
   Things did not always go so well in the White House. Cleveland
bungled in his effort to repeal the Bland-Allison Act, which
required Washington to buy and coin as much silver as possible, by
failing to pressure his Democratic congressional allies. Generally
a reformer, he lobbied for and signed legislation in 1887 to create
the Interstate Commerce Commission. But his first term had a black
mark: He supported legislation restricting the movement of Chinese
into the United States, saying that blending races was ``unwise,
impolitic, and injurious to both nations.'' Cleveland did not
campaign in the 1888 election and was defeated by William Henry
Harrison. ``Well,'' Cleveland said, ``it's all up.'' Not so fast.
The Clevelands returned four years later, just in time for a deep
recession, growing economic tension, and labor strife that flared
in the bloody Pullman strike. Cleveland was honest, but he was not
lucky.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffers is an amiable tour guide throughout the ups and downs of
Cleveland's public career, and his biography is pleasant,
easygoing, and engaging, though not especially challenging _ either
to the reader or to Cleveland himself. The constant reference to
Cleveland simply as ``Grover'' undermines the authority of the
volume; no serious modern biographer, for example, would constantly
refer to President Kennedy as ``Jack.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Jeffers has performed a public service in retrieving
Cleveland from the remainder pile of presidents. In his first
presidential campaign, Joseph Pulitzer's New York World provided
four reasons for supporting Cleveland: ``1. He is an honest man. 2.
He is an honest man. 3. He is an honest man. 4. He is an honest
man.'' He was, for those four reasons, an unusual man, too.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   David M. Shribman is the Globe's Washington bureau chief.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-00 1344EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
