<DOCNO> NYT20000710.0121 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 13:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7807 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-DANCE-NICHOLAS-BOS &LR;      07-10 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DANCE-NICHOLAS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DANCING IN THE DARK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK FEENEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Millions of people know the names Fred Astaire and Gene Kelly.
How many recognize the name Harold Nicholas?
</P>
<P>
   Yet as Astaire and Kelly knew perfectly well, Nicholas, who died
Monday in New York at 79, was every bit their artistic peer. That
so few people today recognize his name, or that of his brother and
dance partner, Fayard, is because of a very old and very familiar
story: great American talent having careers deformed, deferred, or
denied because of race.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to many black entertainers of their era, the Nicholas
Brothers fared well. They worked steadily, both here and abroad.
Revered within the dance world, they were frequently feted over the
past two decades. Their reputation extended far enough into the
culture at large that the Kennedy Center included them among its
select roster of honorees in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   What makes their case special is the near-stupefying disparity
between the level of their abilities and the level of recognition
those abilities earned them. On screen, they were not allowed to
speak or sing (this even though Harold Nicholas was a vocalist
talented enough that Harold Arlen chose him to introduce ``Come
Rain or Come Shine''). Until their last film together, ``The
Pirate,'' when they got to dance with Kelly, they weren't even
allowed to appear on camera with anyone white.
</P>
<P>
   The brothers debuted as a team in 1930 and during the next 20
years performed in more than a dozen films and made countless stage
appearances. Their physiology-mocking, gravity-defying act blended
jazz, tap, acrobatics, ballet, and sheer, stunning showmanship to
create what was surely the most electrifying attraction American
dance has known.
</P>
<P>
   Mikhail Baryshnikov called the brothers ``the most amazing
dancers I have ever seen.'' George Balanchine, who cast them in two
Broadway musicals in the 1930s, spoke with pride of having worked
with ``the great Nicholas Brothers.'' Astaire considered their
``Jumpin' Jive'' sequence from ``Stormy Weather'' the greatest of
all movie dance numbers.
</P>
<P>
   It's a commonplace that Astaire and Kelly are two of American
culture's most glorious ornaments. What's less often remarked upon
is that a considerable part of their genius was an ability to
bridge Old World and New. Astaire was born ``Austerlitz'' (the name
of a great victory for Napoleon as well as for Terpsichore), and
his sister married an English lord. As for Kelly, his best-known
role was as ``An American in Paris,'' after all, and he owed much
of his early success to the patent Irishness of his dark good looks
and sunny charm.
</P>
<P>
   The artistry of Astaire and Kelly was only a few (dance) steps
away from that of their European forebears. The artistry of the
Nicholas Brothers was unthinkable anywhere but in America. No one
elsewhere had ever danced like this: wild yet controlled, eruptive
yet graceful, kinetic yet fluid, gymnastic yet musical. There is no
clearer demonstration that ``dance,'' ``leap,'' ``slide,''
``flip,'' and ``split'' began as verbs, not nouns, than Harold
Nicholas and his brother in motion. And in that motion the
phenomenal velocity of 20th-century America found matchless
flesh-and-blood expression.
</P>
<P>
   The sheer energy of the Nicholas Brothers gives their numbers a
contemporary feel that the passage of six decades has not dimmed.
They seem as up to the minute as Allen Iverson (who in fact looks a
little like Harold in his prime) slashing his way to the basket or
the daring, jerky steps of hip-hop.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps this is what makes the brothers' career such a poignant
example of what prejudice can do. To see a film of John Bubbles or
Bill Robinson dancing, to hear a recording of Paul Robeson singing,
is to visit not just another era but another world. The injustices
visited upon them seem as abstract to us, as alien, as their
performing styles. Precisely because the Nicholas Brothers' work
manages somehow to seem of our own time, what they suffered feels
all the more shocking.
</P>
<P>
   To see the Nicholas Brothers on screen is as thrilling an
experience as film has to offer. Does that sound like an
exaggeration? Go rent ``Stormy Weather'' or ``The Pirate'' _ or
even ``Sun Valley Serenade'' or ``Orchestra Wives'' _ fast-forward
to their scene and see for yourself. Yet precisely because what
they did reminds us of what racism prevented them from doing
further, to see them dance is also among the most heartbreaking
experiences film has to offer.
</P>
<P>
   As long as people move their bodies to music, what the Nicholas
Brothers did will provide a unique joy and exhilaration. As long as
people's hearts are moved by injustice, what was done to Harold and
Fayard Nicholas will also provide a lesson, one no less chastening
for being anything but unique.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-00 1345EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000710.0122 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 13:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7810 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-MURDER-BOS &LR;      07-10 1877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-MURDER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO. 1 WITH A BULLET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (First of two parts.)
</P>
<P>
   In the liner notes to his excellent new box set ``Love, God,
Murder,'' Johnny Cash writes, ``The first murder recorded in the
history of man was when Cain killed his brother Abel. No doubt
people wrote and sang songs about it, and we've been doing it ever
since.'' Cash should know. He dedicates an entire disc _ 16 songs _
to those who kill, such as the doomed narrator of his classic
``Folsom Prison Blues,'' who famously intones, ``I shot a man in
Reno, just to watch him die.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 50 years after Cash first sang that chilling line, we
remain fascinated by music with a body count. One need look no
further than the album that has ruled the top of the Billboard
charts for more than a month: ``The Marshall Mathers LP.'' In five
weeks, Eminem's latest CD has sold 5 million copies, despite _ or
perhaps because of _ blood-drenched lyrics in which he murders his
mother, his wife, and just about anyone else who crosses his
twisted path.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for all the controversy, Eminem (who is scheduled to perform
at the Worcester Centrum Centre July 20 and 21, when the ``Up in
Smoke'' tour, also featuring Dr. Dre, Snoop Dogg, and Ice Cube,
rolls into town) is hardly the first artist to make music _ and
money _ spinning various tales of homicidal mayhem.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he's merely the latest practitioner in a long tradition
that includes just about every singer and/or songwriter of the past
century _ from Kurt Weill's ``Mack the Knife'' and Cole Porter's
``Miss Otis Regrets'' to Bob Marley's ``I Shot the Sheriff'' and
the Beatles ``Maxwell's Silver Hammer.'' As old as folk songs and
as recent as Macy Gray's ``I've Committed Murder,'' the taking of a
life has always been a source of musical inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Violence has a long history in music in general, and in
American music in particular,'' said Christopher John Farley,
senior writer and music critic for Time. ``You can go back to
Robert Johnson in the 1930s, and he has songs about shooting and
murdering people. It's part of the American tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   In a nation born out of revolution, murder is as much a part of
our psyche as are the bursting bombs and red glare of the rockets
in the national anthem. If violence is our unspoken fetish, then
murder is the money shot. It titillates us as much as it repels us,
and with every outrage there's a vicarious thrill.
</P>
<P>
   And since most of us will probably never murder anyone, the
heady rush of the forbidden, if only in song, is too seductive for
most to resist. As Cash puts it, ``We, the people, put ourselves in
the shoes of the singer. We want to feel his pain, his loneliness.
We want to be part of that rebellion.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's wish fulfillment. Don't you wish you could just take
somebody out and not have to pay the price for it?'' said Dan
Epstein, author of ``20th Century Pop Culture.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Forever a fascination &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``People have been killing each other forever, and have been
singing about it for nearly as long,'' he said. ``And there's
always been a part of us that been fascinated with death and
murder.''
</P>
<P>
   But to hear some folks talk about it, you would think rap
artists, some of whom color their rhymes with blood-soaked images
of kill-or-be-killed street life, were the first to set murder to
music. But the morbid subject is as old as some of the great
operas, and folk songs such as ``Stagger Lee,'' made famous by
Lloyd Price.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could probably trace it back to old Celtic folk ballads of
the 1700s and 1800s, where there were lots of murders with people
getting their heads chopped off,'' said David Browne, Entertainment
Weekly music critic. ``It's just a classic tradition in music, and
some of these old songs can be pretty grisly, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Murder was a staple in such cheesy '70s pop songs as Vicki
Lawrence's ``The Night the Lights Went Out in Georgia,'' Cher's
``Dark Lady,'' and R. Dean Taylor's ``Indiana Wants Me.'' There
have been songs of murder by such artists as the Grateful Dead,
Neil Young, Guns N' Roses, Queen, Dwight Yoakam, Nick Cave (who had
an album called ``Murder Ballads''), D'Angelo _ you can pretty much
pick a genre, and find songs littered with bodies.
</P>
<P>
   But it's been a long bloody journey from the plainspeak of
shooting a man to the slam poetry of bustin' a cap in someone's
head. Comparing, say, the woman who shoots her cheating lover in
``Frankie and Johnny,'' written in 1870, to Eminem cutting his
wife's throat (complete with gurgling sound effects) on ``Kim,'' is
like comparing the genteel Brewster sisters poisoning lonely old
men in ``Arsenic and Old Lace'' with the sociopathic title
character of ``Henry: Portrait of a Serial Killer.''
</P>
<P>
   But what's also changed, some say, is the personal nature, with
their ripped-from-the-evening-news authenticity, of some of today's
murder songs. It's one thing to hear Cash coldly sing about
shooting his woman in ``Delia's Gone,'' when you know that offstage
he's married to June Carter; it's quite another to hear Eminem rap
about murdering his wife, Kim, when everyone knows he's in a
volatile marriage with a woman named Kim.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's different about violence in music is that _ unlike,
say, violence in movies, or violence in books, where it seems the
author is commenting on violence _ in music when you hear the
singer's voice and hear him saying these things, one immediately
associates the artists themselves with the actual story,'' Farley
said. ``That's why people get excited when Eminem raps about
killing his wife. If he'd written a book about it, and changed the
name in a Philip Roth-ian kind of way, we'd probably say, `Oh, it's
just a novel, it's fine by us.' But since music has more of a
connection to the artist, it alarms us more.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
When trouble becomes you &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Further exacerbating the outrage is the tendency of some of
today's hip-hop stars to get into real-life trouble with the law.
In the past year, such artists as Jay-Z, DMX, Black Rob, and Mr.
Slim Shady himself, Eminem, have all faced legal problems stemming
from weapons and/or assault charges. With hip-hop's all-important
``keep it real'' edict, some artists seem to be practicing too hard
what they preach.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always got the sense back then that Johnny Cash was
singing in the voice of some kind of character,'' Browne said.
``But even though Eminem adopts the Slim Shady character, you don't
necessarily feel that he's playing a role. You could never picture
Garth Brooks or the Dixie Chicks'' _ both of whom had their own
murder songs with ``The Thunder Rolls'' and ``Goodbye Earl,''
respectively _ ``actually killing somebody, but Eminem and some
other rappers make you feel they really could.''
</P>
<P>
   Farley also pointed out that, save for Eminem, all of today's
hardcore rappers are black males, which adds the element of racial
discomfort to the mix in discussions about violence and music.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's still a basic fear of black culture in American
society. Blacks are still viewed as `the other,' and things which
are intimately connected to the core of our culture are viewed with
fear by the larger culture,'' he said. ``So when people like DMX or
Jay-Z have lyrics with violence in them, they're taken more
seriously because there's a fear of that type of person in American
society to begin with.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Britney Spears sings a song about murder, no one's going to
take her seriously,'' Farley said. ``The Dixie Chicks singing about
murdering someone did cause a certain amount of controversy, but I
ain't afraid of the Dixie Chicks, and I doubt most people are. But
it's different when it's DMX just because he's a man with black
skin instead of three cute blond white girls _ although DMX is a
short guy who really isn't much more fearsome than the Dixie
Chicks.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Degrees of murder &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If public perceptions of artists' intentions are not created
equal, neither are all murder songs. Yes, songs like ``Goodbye
Earl,'' Aerosmith's ``Janie's Got a Gun,'' and Eve's ``Love Is
Blind'' all highlight killing. But each concerns a victim of
violence _ or someone seeking vengeance _ finally striking back at
abusers. Here, murder seems almost justifiable, the final act of a
desperate person driven to extremes by years of brutalization.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are songs like Bruce Springsteen's grim ``Nebraska,''
inspired by Charles Starkweather's killing spree in the 1950s.
Though the killer expresses no remorse for his crimes, he's about
to be executed. His misdeeds do not go unpunished, and the
punishment is as harsh and irreversible as his crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in many of today's murder songs, there is a general lack of
contrition or consequence. In most of Cash's murder songs, his
killers are commenting on their misdeeds from a prison cell, and
often from death row.
</P>
<P>
   In his own essay about Cash, filmmaker Quentin Tarantino _ whose
films including ``Reservoir Dogs'' and ``Pulp Fiction'' have
sparked their own debates about violence in pop culture _ comments
that Cash's songs ``rarely take place during the high times.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a man faces a rope or 99 years in a cage for the choices
he made, when he tells the story of those choices,'' Tarantino
writes, ``he tells it not with bravado, but with an overwhelming
sense of regret.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A song like `Folsom Prison Blues' with the ultimate badass
line _ `I shot a man in Reno just to watch him die _ at the same
time has the next line, `When I hear that lonely whistle, I hang my
head and cry.' There's an immediate sense that he has (messed) up
his life completely by being the ultimate badass,'' Dan Epstein
said. ``That's the sort of thing that's missing from Eminem's
oeuvre; there's no sense of regret, no reference to how if he kills
somebody, he'll have to pay a legal or karmic price for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's completely over-the-top sensationalism,'' he said. ``It's
like `The Texas Chain Saw Massacre' _ this is violence, there is no
moral, there's nothing else going on here except it's designed to
get a rise out of you.''
</P>
<P>
   Which, for better and mostly worst, is exactly what Eminem does.
The rapper himself has admitted numerous times that his shtick is
ticking people off by saying the most outrageous, reprehensible
things. Having pushed the envelope so far on just his second major
release _ what's left after you've murdered your wife and mother? _
one wonders where he, and his inevitable musical progeny, will go
next.
</P>
<P>
   But even if Eminem decided to flip the script, and use his
considerable talents in a less brutal, predictable way, there will
always be someone else somewhere crafting a lyric, weaving a
melody, looping a beat, and capturing one of our oldest, darkest
impulse in song.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always going to be somebody who's going to try to push
it to the next level somehow, because they know it's going to
sell,'' Epstein said. ``Unfortunately, this is part of our legacy
as humans _ we kill each other. But because we also have an
artistic bent, we sing about it as well.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
NEXT WEEK: Murder isn't the only violent topic in today's music. A
new generation of bands is finding fans with songs about anger and
outrage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-00 1347EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000710.0123 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7811 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-TIPS-BOS &LR;      07-10 0291
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TIPS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOKS RECENTLY REVIEWED IN THE BOSTON GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Circus Fire'' by Stewart O'Nan (Doubleday, $24.95). A fine
fiction writer turns his attention to examining the big-top fire in
Hartford in 1944 that killed more than 160 people and forever
changed thousands of lives. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Obedient Father'' by Akhil Sharma (Farrar, Straus &AMP;
Giroux, $23). A novel about the dark side of politics in India, and
the even darker side of the man at the story's core. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Feast of Love'' by Charles Baxter (Pantheon, $24). Think
of ``A Midsummer Night's Dream'' transferred to the flatlands of
Michigan, with a ventriloquist's touch sprinkled in, and you have
the setting for a delightfully poetic tale. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Chief'' by David Nasaw (Houghton Mifflin, $35).
Exhaustively researched and straightforwardly told, the life of
William Randolph Hearst emerges from the shadow of ``Citizen
Kane.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``How to Read and Why'' by Harold Bloom (Scribner, $25). The
eminent critic shares his thoughts on favorite books _ not in
deep-dish essays, but in epigrammatic reader's notes. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Plowing the Dark'' by Richard Powers (Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux,
$25). Perhaps his best-executed story yet, crammed with erudition
and cutting-edge science but unmistakably human. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``From Dawn to Decadence'' by Jacques Barzun (HarperCollins,
$36). A magisterial survey of the West's past 500 years, as
readable as it is learned. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Papal Sin'' by Garry Wills (Doubleday, $25). Concentrating
mostly on the past century and a half, a Roman Catholic indicts the
``structure of deceit'' he sees in his church's confrontation with
modernity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
