<HEADLINE>
GLOBE COLUMNIST JACOBY SUSPENDED 4 MONTHS FOR `MISCONDUCT' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (e and k coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe suspended editorial page columnist Jeff Jacoby
for four months without pay Friday after concluding that his July 3
column on the fate of the signers of the Declaration of
Independence constituted ``serious journalistic misconduct.''
</P>
<P>
   Editorial page editor Renee Loth, who determined Jacoby's
punishment along with publisher Richard H. Gilman, stopped short of
calling his action ``plagiarism.'' But the paper found that his
July 3 column was based on accounts that have appeared ``in other
publications and books and on Web sites for years'' and failed to
alert readers to those other sources, according to a Globe
statement released Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot look the other way if any of our columnists,
reporters, or writers borrow without attribution from the works of
others, even in an attempt to improve upon it,'' said Gilman in the
statement. ``The Globe will not equivocate in abiding by the
highest journalistic standards and ethics.''
</P>
<P>
   In a brief interview Friday, Jacoby, who carved out a niche as
the conservative voice on the Globe op-ed page, said, ``I've got 6
1/2 years of columns behind me at The Boston Globe, and I invite
anybody to judge my integrity and the care that I take in my work
from the body of work I've produced.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been aware from the outset that I have to be extremely
aware of my column,'' he added, noting that his politics are at
odds with the paper's more liberal opinion pages.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the suspension seemed harsh, Loth said, ``it was a
serious violation of the relationship between the Globe and its
readers. . . . We considered mitigating factors as well as the blow
this is to the Globe's credibility, and we came up with a balanced
response that's proportionate.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacoby becomes the third prominent Globe columnist to face major
sanctions in the past two years. In June 1998, award-winning Metro
columnist Patricia Smith resigned after admitting to fabricating
some characters and quotations. Two months later, veteran Metro
columnist Mike Barnicle resigned after being unable to verify facts
in a 1995 column. At the time, he was under suspension for a column
that contained jokes from George Carlin's book ``BrainDroppings.''
</P>
<P>
   One mitigating factor in Jacoby's favor was an e-mail he
circulated on July 2 containing his July 3 column. It included an
introduction stating the column ``is not a mere rewrite of an
anonymous piece that has been making the rounds on the Internet,''
but an attempt to correct errors in that piece. That e-mail, which
was received by Boston Phoenix media critic Dan Kennedy among
others, suggests Jacoby was not simply trying to replicate the
original story, but to improve upon it.
</P>
<P>
   However, Loth said Jacoby's practice of circulating his column
before publication without Globe permission was factored into his
punishment.
</P>
<P>
   Globe ombudsman Jack Thomas said that as of Friday he had
received more than 125 e-mails and calls concerning Jacoby's July 3
column.
</P>
<P>
   In a response to readers questioning the origin of the piece,
Jacoby wrote in a message now posted on Jim Romenesko's MediaNews
(www.poynter.org) Web site that ``knowing that previous treatments
of the lives-of-the-signers theme contained mistakes and
exaggerations, I tried to take pains not to repeat anything untrue.
. . . In retrospect, I wish I had noted in the column that I am
only the latest in a long line to write about the fate of the
signers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
