<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-VIDEOS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON'S TITLE SHOT, SPIELBERG'S DVD THRILLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL BLOWEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW RELEASES: ``The Hurricane'' (DVD) _ Denzel Washington
deserved the Oscar for best actor for his performance as Rubin
``Hurricane'' Carter, the boxer unjustly imprisoned for a multiple
homicide. The problem is that the film misses out on the mental and
physical toughness Carter developed in order to survive, as well as
the abominable conditions of the prison where he remade himself.
They reached too hard to make Carter's wrenching story palatable to
a large audience instead of digging deeper and harder into his fall
and subsequent resurrection.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jaws'' (DVD) _ Steven Spielberg's terrifying tale of shark
attacks is given new life in the spectacular DVD edition of the
1975 film. John Williams's finest score and a grizzled performance
by Robert Shaw make this a great film that retains its thrills.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GATHERING NO MOSS: The Rolling Stones' ``Gimme Shelter,'' the
1970 documentary by directors Albert and David Maysles and
Charlotte Zwerin, will be rereleased next month for the art market.
Peter Becker, president of Criterion, says the company returned to
the original 16mm elements and painstakingly struck a new print for
the limited theatrical run. The original score, featuring
``Satisfaction'' and a bevy of other Stones hits, was remixed using
Dolby noise reduction. Following the theatrical release, sometime
in the fall, it will be sold by Criterion and Home Vision on DVD.
The home version will include unreleased performances from the
concert that were cut from the original film, including Santana
performing ``Evil Ways.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``GUNS'' AND BETTER: ``The Guns of Navarone'' was nominated for
seven Oscars, including best picture, after its 1961 release. The
film is about the exploits of a handful of saboteurs who have to
destroy giant guns the Nazis have emplaced on a Greek island.
Gregory Peck, David Niven, and Anthony Quinn head an impressive
cast. The DVD includes a documentary with fresh interviews with
director J. Lee Thompson, who replaced Alexander Mackendrick within
a fortnight of beginning production, and comments by Peck, Quinn,
and others. Thompson explains that the spectacular storm sequence
was filmed indoors on a London sound stage. The score by Dimitri
Tiomkin sounds even better on the new disc.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COMING ATTRACTIONS: July 18: ``Ride With the Devil,'' ``What
Planet Are You From?'' (DVD), ``Identification of a Woman,''
``Angela's Ashes,'' ``Diamonds,'' ``Behind Locked Doors,'' ``Il
Bidone'' (DVD), ``The Ninth Gate,'' ``The War Zone.'' July 25:
``Magnolia'' (DVD), ``The Beach,'' ``The Perfect Tenant,''
``Drowning Mona,'' ``Bruce Brown Surf Collection,'' ``The Secret of
Roan Inish'' (DVD), ``Space Jam'' (DVD). Aug. 1: ``The Brothers
Quay Collection'' (DVD). Aug. 8: ``Reindeer Games.'' ``Holy
Smoke,'' ``The Grandfather.'' Aug. 15: ``It's the Rage.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
