<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR TUESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Tuesday, July 11:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-ISRAEL (Jerusalem) _ Israel's prime minister, Ehud
Barak, is expected to survive a right-wing no-confidence vote. He
speaks to parliament just before leaving for a summit at Camp
David. Regardless of what happens there, he could well have to deal
with early elections when he returns. By William A. Orme Jr.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Washington) _ Developments on the eve of the
Middle East summit at Camp David. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   And
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-ISSUES (Washington) _ A look at the main issues under
discussion during the summit. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-WEIZMAN (Jerusalem) _ After 50 years in public life, Ezer
Weizman resigns president of Israel, a largely ceremonial post.
This follows a government report that detailed his receipt of more
than $300,000 from two businessmen a decade ago. Former Prime
Minister Shimon Peres may succeed him, but that is up to
parliament. By Joel Greenberg.
</P>
<P>
   SYRIA-VOTE (Beirut) _ Syrians flock to the polls to endorse
their new president, Bashar al-Assad, in a referendum precisely one
month after the death of his father. Many were pricking their
fingers and smearing blood over the green ``yes'' circle. By John
Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-UNREST (Belfast, Northern Ireland) _ Portadown,
Northern Ireland, braces for a shutdown as the Orange Order, a
traditional Protestant organization, pushes its supporters across
the province to tie up traffic, demonstrate and otherwise disrupt
life between 4 p.m. and 8 p.m. It could be a test of what kind of
threat the hard right poses to the peacemakers. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-AIDS (Durban, South Africa) _ The minister of health
lashes out at critics of President Mbeki and his position on HIV
not causing AIDS. By Rachel Swarns.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-PAROLE (Paris) _ France has been caught up in a debate
over whether a criminal, Patrick Henry, whose murder case led to
the abolishment of the death penalty, should be paroled after 24
years in jail. On Monday, the justice minister rejected Henry's bid
for freedom. Henry's 1977 case played a vital role in France's
eventual decision to end the death penalty in 1981. By Suzanne
Daley.
</P>
<P>
   OKINAWA-CURFEW (Tokyo) _ After a hit-and-run accident involving
a staff sergeant early Sunday, the U.S. military has indefinitely
banned the drinking of alcoholic beverages between midnight and 5
a.m. for soldiers stationed in Okinawa and prohibited all personnel
from leaving their bases during those hours. Okinawa will be the
site of a G8 Summit starting July 21. By Stephanie Strom. (450
words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-GOVS (State College, Pa.) _ President Clinton addresses
the National Governors' Association. By Marc Lacey.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   RACE-POLL (Undated) _ Results of The New York Times poll on
race. By Kevin Sack. (1200 words)
</P>
<P>
   AME-BISHOP (Cincinnati, Ohio) _ Delegates to the African
Methodist Episcopal Church's general conference may elect a woman,
or two, for the first time to be a bishop of the 2.3-million member
denomination. By Laurie Goodstein.
</P>
<P>
   HOCKEY-BEATING (Boston) _ Follow on man charged with beating
another father to death at a youth hockey game in a dispute over
rough play. By Fox Butterfield.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-MILITARY (Undated) _ A portrait of Vice President Al Gore's
Vietnam years. A special report by Melinda Henneberger. (4200
words)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-GUARD (Undated) _ A look at Gov. George W. Bush and his
National Guard service. By Nicholas D. Kristof. (1100 words)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH (Baltimore) _ George W. Bush speaks before the NAACP annual
convention. By Alison Mitchell. (1100 words)
</P>
<P>
   GORE (Dateline to kum) _ Campaign day: Al Gore bashes the
Republican Congress. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS (Undated) _ News and notes from the hustings.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   JDS-UNIPHASE-JDS (Undated) _ JDS Uniphase, a fiber-optics
company that has been a Wall Street favorite of late, has agreed to
agreed to buy supplier SDL Inc. for $41 billion in stock, in what
may be the largest technology deal on record. JDS Uniphase is
paying a nearly 50 percent premium for SDL, which makes pump lasers
that strengthen the signals running through fiber-optic networks.
Looking at why these companies are so valuable. By Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-U.S.-FLIGHTS (Washington) _ The long rivalry between New
York and Chicago has a new front: the Transportation Department is
expected to decide this summer which city will become the take-off
point for a lucrative set of new flights to China. The decision has
added importance because of the increase in travel that is expected
follow China's likely entrance into the World Trade Organization.
Doing New York's bidding is Delta Air Lines, which wants to fly to
Beijing from JFK. Delta executives argue that New York's size and
economic importance so outweigh Chicago's as to make the decision
an easy one. American Airlines, which would fly from O'Hare to
Shanghai, responds that Chicago's location trumps demographics.
This contest, however, comes with a twist: Chicago and New York
could both end up losing, and the airlines' carping may be hurting
both of their cases. By David Leonhardt.
</P>
<P>
   EARNINGS-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ As the second-quarter earnings
season gets into full swing this week, with reports expected from
General Electric, Motorola, Yahoo and J.P. Morgan, the outlook is
the best it has been for years. But a look back at 1994 shows that
even great earnings news may not lift stock prices much when the
Federal Reserve is still intent on raising interest rates to slow
growth. By Jonathan Fuerbringer.
</P>
<P>
   TOYSMART-PRIVACY (Undated) _ The Federal Trade Commission sues
to stop Toysmart.com's effort to sell thousands of customer names
and data despite an earlier pledge by the company, now in
bankruptcy protection, never to do so. By Matt Richtel.
</P>
<P>
   HONEYWELL-OUTLOOK (Undated) _ Honeywell International says
earnings for this year and 2001 will be below estimates following
last month's warning of an earnings shortfall because of lower
sales and higher costs. The company plans to eliminate
underperforming units, cut another 5 percent of its roughly 100,000
workers and take a charge of $75 million to $100 million. By
Claudia H. Deutsch.
</P>
<P>
   EADS-STOCK (Frankfurt, Germany) _ Shares of the newly formed
European aerospace giant EADS _ a combination of three Airbus
partners, Dasa of Germany, Casa of Spain and Aerospatiale of France
_ have an unspectacular debut in Paris, Frankfurt and Madrid. By
Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   SKOREA-BANKS (Seoul, South Korea) _ Bank unions agree to
last-minute talks in an effort to prevent a strike scheduled to
begin on Tuesday. Korean regulators threaten to punish bank workers
who walk off their jobs. By Samuel en.
</P>
<P>
   TIMES-EARNINGS (New York) _ The New York Times Co. will report
second-quarter earnings later Monday. The consensus forecast is 56
cents a share. By Felicity Barringer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
