   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MAKING HISTORY IN MEXICO: ADIOS, PRI. OLE! PAN &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MEXICOLE!-VOTE-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For once, hyperbole is appropriate. In confounding pollsters and
pundits by choosing Vicente Fox as their next president last
Sunday, Mexicans did far more than change their government. They
ended seven decades of rule by the Institutional Revolutionary
Party (PRI), put a whole era in Mexico's history behind them and
turned their country into a real democracy at last. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (975 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KEEPING A LID ON JAPAN'S WAR CRIMES WON'T STOP THE STINK &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; JAPAN-WAR-SLAVES-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``If it smells, put a lid on it,'' goes an old Japanese proverb.
But it is the wrong prescription for the 30-odd lawsuits that have
been lodged in California against Japanese companies such as
Mitsubishi and Mitsui on behalf of many Asians and some Allied
prisoners of war who were forced into slave labor during the Second
World War. For moral, and commercial reasons, Japan should
compensate the victims of its sordid history _ and quickly. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors...and California) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (625 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TIME'S RUNNING OUT FOR INDONESIA'S FIRST DEMOCRATIC PRESIDENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GUS-DUR-LASTCHANCE-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The task is vast. Last October Abdurrahman Wahid won the
presidency of one of the world's largest countries, spread across
17,000 islands and with numerous ethnic groups. After a 30-year
dictatorship, Indonesia was rife with corruption. On top of all
that, the country's first democratically elected president
inherited a collapsing economy. Oh, and did we mention that
President Wahid _ affectionately known as Gus Dur _ is half-blind
and weakened by a near-fatal stroke two years ago? All of which
makes it scarcely surprising that Wahid is finding it hard to get
his country moving firmly in a better direction. Yet patience in
Indonesia is running out. Some of the explanation doubtless lies in
unreasonable expectations of this saintly Muslim cleric. Much,
however, is his own fault. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (950 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; USA &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE NAFTA-IZATION OF MEXICAN-AMERICAN RELATIONS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TEXMEX-POLITICS-ECONOMIST-300&AMP;add &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Americans may come to look back on 2000 as a
decisive political year. The reason will not be the election of
President Gore or President Bush, but rather the election of
President Fox. The victory of Vicente Fox in Mexico seems like a
vindication of Americans' belief in the possibility of worldwide
political progress. More importantly, this week's election marks
the moment when the worldwide trend towards greater democratization
washed back over the Rio Grande. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary, Political Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: 75-word optional trim; 1,050 words uncut) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PUMP FICTION: WHINY AMERICA'S GAS `CRISIS' NONSENSE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHINY-GAS-GUZZLERS-ECONOMIST-900&AMP;add &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Freedom is one of those words that politicians bandy
around a great deal over the July 4th holiday. Few practical
freedoms seem to matter to Americans more than the ability to drive
their own set of wheels whenever they want, whenever they want _
and to have cheap gasoline to do it. Unfortunately, gas is suddenly
not nearly as cheap as Americans would like; and even though this
is probably a temporary phenomenon, it is already causing a
political fuss. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: Two optional trims, totaling 225 words; 1,225 uncut) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TIRED INTERNS SEEK REMEDY FOR OVERWORK, UNDERAPPRECIATION &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; YOUNG-DOCS-UNIONIZE-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ America's 400 teaching hospitals may not immediately
resemble ``Tom Brown's Schooldays,'' but for young resident
doctors, life at a 19th-century English public school might seem
familiar. Young trainee doctors are expected to work until they
drop, often completing 100-hour weeks; many complain of
mistreatment or harassment. Indeed, senior physicians have enormous
power over a trainee's future career. But pressure for change may
be mounting. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (750 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; QUIPS, QUIRKS AND QUOTES FROM THIS WEEK'S CAMPAIGN TRAIL &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN-TRAIL-MIX-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary, Political, Humor Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (425 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; U.S. FORESTS: WHERE THERE'S SMOKE, THERE'S CONTROVERSY &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SAFER-FOREST-FIRES-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ This year's devastating fires in New Mexico, Arizona
and Colorado are worse than anything nature has produced for a long
time past. Drought and strong winds propelled them; but the biggest
fires were begun by government workers, in ``controlled burns''
gone awry. This raises new, and troubling, questions about the
stewardship of America's forests. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Southwest U.S. Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (725 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KING ABDULLAH'S GROWING PAINS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ABDULLAH-REPORTCARD-ECONOMIST-850&AMP;add &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AMMAN _ Ask the King of Jordan what knowledge he most lacked
when he unexpectedly came to the throne last year and he explains
how difficult he has found it to work out the hidden agendas and
personal rivalries among his advisers, ministers and court
officials. In other words, although he does not put it so bluntly,
Abdullah II knew little about Jordanian politics. A lifelong
soldier, he had served as crown prince for only a week before his
father, King Hussein, died. How is he coming along as a
politician? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: 50-word optional trim; 1,000 words uncut) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ECONOMICS &AMP; FINANCE &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SHOULD ESTATE TAXES BE ABOLISHED? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TAX-THE-DEAD?-ECONOMIST-850&AMP;add &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ America's House of Representatives voted last month
to phase out the country's estate tax over the next ten years. If
the law passes the Senate and has enough support to override a
threatened veto by President Bill Clinton (unlikely but possible),
America could become one of the handful of rich countries without
an inheritance or estate tax, at least at the federal level. Should
the dead pay taxes? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary, Financial Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: Story stands alone in 850 words; 1,050 uncut) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OPEC; SAUDI ARABIA LIFTS THE VEIL OF PRETENSE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OPEC-FUTURE?-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Could this week mark the great schism that
eventually tears apart OPEC? Only time will tell. But what is clear
is that Saudi Arabia has decided to lift the veil of pretense and
admit that the cartel is mere window-dressing for its political and
economic agenda, a convenient fiction to be tolerated in good times
but disregarded in crisis. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (850 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INDUSTRIAL JAPAN'S `FORGOTTEN HOLOCAUST' &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; JAPBIZ-WARCRIMES-ECONOMIST-575&AMP;add &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TOKYO _ ``The shame of our history is now going abroad,'' says
Tadashi Kosho, who has spent his life studying the use of slave
labor by Japanese companies during the Second World War. Enter
Edward Fagan, a New York lawyer and world-class embarrasser. The
man who shamed Swiss bankers and German industrialists into
stumping up billions of dollars for their wartime offenses now
plans to take on the might of Japanese industry. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: 200-word optional trim; 1,125 words uncut) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &AMP; TECHNOLOGY &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (UNDATED) _ The growing realism of computer games makes it even
harder for players to tear themselves away from their screens to
attend to their daily lives. For some players, however, the
distraction of having to earn a living may now be a thing of the
past. They have learned to make real money in the imaginary world
of online fantasy games. How did things become so deadly serious? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (550 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOREOVER &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; `BOWLING ALONE': WHAT'S MISSING IN AMERICAN SOCIETY &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WE-BOWL-ALONE-USA-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Americans used to bowl in leagues. Now they bowl
alone. In New London, Conn., they bowl alone while watching giant
television screens, thus further reducing their changes of forming
meaningful social connections. For Harvard political scientist
Robert Putnam, bowling alone is an extended metaphor for much that
ails both modern America and modern Americans. In his ambitious new
book, ``Bowling Alone,'' he argues that while America has recently
witnessed record growth in physical and human capital, its stock of
``social capital'' _ informal social connectedness and formal civic
engagement _ has fallen dangerously low. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary, Book Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (750 words) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
