<SLUG> BC-ECONOMIST-ADVISORY </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   These excellent articles are from the current ECONOMIST magazine
(week beginning 8 JULY 2000); they have all moved to the ``k''
commentary category code. &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (ATTN. EDITORS: The following material from the New York Times
Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist. Nonsubscribers
can use these articles only by special arrangement. For purchase
information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MAKING HISTORY IN MEXICO: ADIOS, PRI. OLE! PAN &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MEXICOLE!-VOTE-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For once, hyperbole is appropriate. In confounding pollsters and
pundits by choosing Vicente Fox as their next president last
Sunday, Mexicans did far more than change their government. They
ended seven decades of rule by the Institutional Revolutionary
Party (PRI), put a whole era in Mexico's history behind them and
turned their country into a real democracy at last. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (975 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KEEPING A LID ON JAPAN'S WAR CRIMES WON'T STOP THE STINK &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; JAPAN-WAR-SLAVES-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``If it smells, put a lid on it,'' goes an old Japanese proverb.
But it is the wrong prescription for the 30-odd lawsuits that have
been lodged in California against Japanese companies such as
Mitsubishi and Mitsui on behalf of many Asians and some Allied
prisoners of war who were forced into slave labor during the Second
World War. For moral, and commercial reasons, Japan should
compensate the victims of its sordid history _ and quickly. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors...and California) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (625 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TIME'S RUNNING OUT FOR INDONESIA'S FIRST DEMOCRATIC PRESIDENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GUS-DUR-LASTCHANCE-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The task is vast. Last October Abdurrahman Wahid won the
presidency of one of the world's largest countries, spread across
17,000 islands and with numerous ethnic groups. After a 30-year
dictatorship, Indonesia was rife with corruption. On top of all
that, the country's first democratically elected president
inherited a collapsing economy. Oh, and did we mention that
President Wahid _ affectionately known as Gus Dur _ is half-blind
and weakened by a near-fatal stroke two years ago? All of which
makes it scarcely surprising that Wahid is finding it hard to get
his country moving firmly in a better direction. Yet patience in
Indonesia is running out. Some of the explanation doubtless lies in
unreasonable expectations of this saintly Muslim cleric. Much,
however, is his own fault. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (950 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; USA &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE NAFTA-IZATION OF MEXICAN-AMERICAN RELATIONS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TEXMEX-POLITICS-ECONOMIST-300&AMP;add &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Americans may come to look back on 2000 as a
decisive political year. The reason will not be the election of
President Gore or President Bush, but rather the election of
President Fox. The victory of Vicente Fox in Mexico seems like a
vindication of Americans' belief in the possibility of worldwide
political progress. More importantly, this week's election marks
the moment when the worldwide trend towards greater democratization
washed back over the Rio Grande. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary, Political Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: 75-word optional trim; 1,050 words uncut) &QL;
</P>
