 ART ADV.: Photos with FLEEING-MEDICINE and FLEEING-DOCTOR, and
graphics with MONEY-CREDIT and CONSUMER-COLUMN are being
transmitted to NYT Photo Service subscribers.  
 For Immediate Release  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following FEATURE stories for
use by NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, please contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta
 &LR; at the Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of
graphics or photos please call  &UR; 888-346-9867  &LR; or  &UR; 888-603-1036 &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-CONSERVATIVE (St. John's, Newfoundland) _ Canada's
conservative movement, long dismissed as toothless, is suddenly
flashing sharp fangs with the emergence of a vigorous, telegenic,
and articulate new leader at the helm of what may prove to be
Canada's first formidable modern political party of the right. By
Colin Nickerson. 895 words.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-DEMANDS (Mexico City) _ By tossing out the world's
longest-ruling poltical party, Mexicans raise new questions about
what they will demand next. By Richard Chacon. 1150 words.
</P>
<P>
   DENMARK-JAZZ (Copenhagen) _ Inside a Danish jazz club, an
American legend plays _ and opines on why Europe is a better home
for US indigenous music than its homeland. By Kevin Cullen. 750
words. (i and e coding)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS (p) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GOP-RELIGION (Washington) _ This month Republicans converge on
Philadelphia to begin their quadrennial national convention _ and a
quadrennial debate over religious conservatives in the GOP
coalition. By David Shribman. 1400 words.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-TOWN (Webster Groves, Mo.) _ In the geographic and
ideological center of the country, folks are unimpressed by either
presidential candidate, but inclined, in the main, to lean to Bush.
They pine for McCain. By Yvonne Abraham. 1890 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SHIPS-SLAVES (Boston) _ Darnell Williams won't be among the
millions of spectators viewing the Tall Ships. He'll boycott the
event because, when he looks at the great vessels, he doesn't see
majesty. He sees haunting icons of the slave trade. By Jamal E.
Watson. 1100 words.
</P>
<P>
   NY-GIULIANI (New York) _ In the city where he has been the
feared and mostly respected ruler for seven years, Rudolph Giuliani
is increasingly under siege. By Fred Kaplan. 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   FLEEING-MEDICINE (Undated) _ Managed-care frustrations _ coupled
with exploding opportunities in e-health, biotech and finance _ are
spurring more and more physicians to try out careers in other
fields. By Anne Barnard and Kathryn Tong. 1700 words. PHOTO (a, f
coding)
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   FLEEING-DOCTOR (Boston) _ After stints in ER medicine and
psychiatry, Gigi Hirsch now helps doctors find new careers in
business. By Anne Barnard. 580 words. PHOTO (a, f coding)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (k) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   OLIPHANT-COLUMN (Washington) _ This is not your typical Middle
East summit. By Thomas Oliphant.
</P>
<P>
   WHITE-COLUMN (Undated) _ What energy crisis? By Diane White. (l)
</P>
<P>
   (Eds.: Robert Jordan is writing on a local topic; his column
will not move.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS (e) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MEDIA-JACOBY (Undated) -- The Boston Globe suspends editorial
page columnist Jeff Jacoby for four months without pay for
``serious journalistic misconduct.'' By Mark Jurkowitz. (e and k
coding)
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-PATERNITI (Undated) _ ``Driving Mr. Albert'' is
entertaining, absurd, real, weird, deep, informative, silly, and
slightly overdone. Above all, though, in a world in which it seems
that all the good ideas have been taken, it is singular. By Michael
Prager. 1180 words.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-JEFFERS (Undated) _ Grover Cleveland is the forgotten
two-term American president, remembered if at all as the father of
Baby Ruth, the presidential daughter who lent her name to a candy
bar. By David M. Shribman. 1170 words.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-TIPS (Undated) _ What's hot on the just-published list.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-MURDER (Undated) _ The controversy over Eminem's violent
lyrics is just the latest example of murder in music. From Robert
Johnson to Cole Porter, music and murder are longtime companions.
By Renee Graham. 1900 words.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-GUIDE (Undated) _ Globe critics review current movies.
