r k BC-MEXICOLE!-VOTE-ECONOM     07-10 1113
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICOLE!-VOTE-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING HISTORY IN MEXICO: ADIOS, PRI. OLE! PAN  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 975-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   For once, hyperbole is appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   In confounding pollsters and pundits by choosing Vicente Fox as
their next president last Sunday, Mexicans did far more than change
their government. They ended seven decades of rule by the
Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI), put a whole era in
Mexico's history behind them and turned their country into a real
democracy at last.
</P>
<P>
   All that is to be celebrated, but so too is the peaceful manner
of the PRI's defeat.
</P>
<P>
   It was always far more than a political party. It was a system
of government and of social organization which had its roots in
every corner of Mexican life. After slowly withering for the past
two decades, one-party rule is now dead.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in Mexico's history, one regime has given way
to another without large-scale bloodshed. For that, and for
overseeing the essential final stage of that process, much credit
goes to President Ernesto Zedillo.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did he create an independent electoral authority, which
ensured that last Sunday's vote was the cleanest ever in Mexico,
passing any reasonable test of freedom and fairness. His swift
acknowledgment on election night of Fox's victory also avoided any
possibility that lingering uncertainty might lead to violence.
</P>
<P>
   It helped, too, that Fox won by a clear margin of some seven
percentage points. That was a personal triumph: his stubborn
campaigning and charisma drew support from far beyond his own
conservative National Action Party (PAN).
</P>
<P>
   Both the victor and his voters carry messages about the deeper
meaning of Mexico's election.
</P>
<P>
   Fox is in many ways an untypical Mexican politician. Of
immigrant descent (with an Irish grandfather and a Spanish mother),
he is a Jesuit-educated Catholic, a man who in a different country
would be a Christian Democrat, but who has built bridges to the
left with some populist touches.
</P>
<P>
   He is also a rugged individualist, a businessman whose career
has included a stint running Coca-Cola's Mexican operation. Those
who voted for Fox were disproportionately young, urban and
better-educated.
</P>
<P>
   In a real sense, therefore, his victory personifies the dynamic,
emerging Mexico being molded by the North American Free-Trade
Agreement (NAFTA) _ a Mexico which, for all its social problems and
inequalities, is now less suspicious of the free market and of the
United States than it has been in the recent past.
</P>
<P>
   But this was a vote, too, against the PRI. Despite the reforms
of the past three presidents, and despite Zedillo's success in
restoring economic growth after the peso's collapse in 1994-95,
average real incomes in Mexico are still below their 1982 level,
and inequality, corruption and crime have flourished.
</P>
<P>
   Fox now carries a heavy burden of expectations _ not least
because, under the PRI, Mexico made kings of its presidents for
their six-year terms (and nobodies thereafter).
</P>
<P>
   In office, he will command enormous powers of patronage. He
should resist the temptation to use them, and instead devolve power
away from the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   That means, for example, turning Mexican federalism from fiction
to fact by fulfilling his promise to give more power to the states
and to municipal governments, though without creating new fiscal
burdens.
</P>
<P>
   Fox this week promised to make tackling corruption his priority.
That is needed and welcome, but reform of the PRI state should mean
more than that. It means turning a venal bureaucracy into a
professional civil service, instilling a new ethos of independence
into a politicized judiciary, and drumming both professionalism and
integrity into corrupt and incompetent police forces.
</P>
<P>
   The new president faces other challenges, too. Sustaining
economic growth, especially given the likelihood of a slowdown in
the United States, which takes 90 percent of Mexico's exports, will
require further reform _ urgently so in the energy sector, which
remains a state monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   During the campaign, Fox backed away from earlier plans to
privatize Pemex, the state oil company. But, rightly, he wants to
end its monopoly, and to open up the electricity market too.
</P>
<P>
   The third challenge lies in turning the state into an instrument
of social progress. Mexico needs to spend more, but more wisely, on
education and health. That means raising taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Past governments have depended too much on milking Pemex. But
the most effective tax reform would involve abolishing VAT
exemptions, such as those on food. This would hit the poor hard;
they will need help.
</P>
<P>
   Fourth, many Mexicans who might otherwise be sympathetic to Fox
are scared by his social conservatism, his opposition to abortion
and his party's clerical roots. He needs to reassure them that he
will not be illiberal in such matters.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his clear mandate for change, Fox faces some big
handicaps. Unlike his predecessors, he did not win a majority of
the votes cast. And although the PAN has displaced the PRI as the
largest party in Congress, it lacks an overall majority.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the PRI still controls many state governments. Fox
could face sabotage from officials who fear they might suffer in a
clean-up.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, more than most parties, the PRI may find that its
traditional strength will be sapped by opposition. And by
signalling his intention to form a government of national unity, in
which he may include individuals from all parties, Fox is doing
more than send a message of continuity to the markets.
</P>
<P>
   He may be trying to redraw Mexico's political map. Fox's
election thus promises many welcome changes. But there are some
risks. One lies in the fact that Fox is not due to take office
until Dec. 1. That five-month gap is a legacy of the old system,
and it has often bred turbulence.
</P>
<P>
   Encouragingly, Fox and Zedillo have both pledged to do
everything they can to ensure a smooth handover. Even so, Mexico's
democratic era will start not a moment too soon. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
