<HEADLINE>
PUMP FICTION: WHINY AMERICA'S GAS `CRISIS' NONSENSE  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors...NOTE: Two trims, 225; 1,225 uncut)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 1,000-word (trimmed) material from
The New York Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The
Economist. Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special
arrangement. For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or
Debra Weydert at 732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (NOTE: TWO HELPFUL OPTIONAL TRIMS _ TOTALING 225 WORDS _ AT 900 AND
1,000. TOTAL UNCUT IS 1,225 WORDS.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Freedom is one of those words that politicians bandy
around a great deal over the July 4th holiday. Few practical
freedoms seem to matter to Americans more than the ability to drive
their own set of wheels wherever they want, whenever they want _
and to have cheap gasoline to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, gas is suddenly not nearly as cheap as Americans
would like; and even though this is probably a temporary
phenomenon, it is already causing a political fuss.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, prices at the pump have soared to record highs
(in nominal terms at least). In parts of the country, they have
gone past $2 a gallon.
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers have been full of pictures of mournful car drivers
staring at gas pump nozzles and faded images of their parents
queuing for gas during the Carter years.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders in Congress want to scrap the tiny federal
tax on gasoline (about 18 cents a gallon) altogether. Indiana and
Illinois have suspended their tiny state taxes. Both Al Gore and
George W. Bush have responded to the ``crisis'' by saying how much
they hate high gas prices.
</P>
<P>
   In one way, the American motorist's outrage has already cured
itself. The high level of gas prices in America is the chief reason
why Saudi Arabia shocked the oil markets this week by announcing
unilaterally that it would release more oil shortly.
</P>
<P>
   In part, this was a simple commercial decision: the American
economy is the goose that lays the golden egg for OPEC, and
sustained high energy prices threaten to drag the miracle economy
into recession.
</P>
<P>
   Another part of the answer, though, lies in politics: Saudi
Arabia relies heavily on American goodwill and soldiers for
protection from Iraqi bogeyman Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   Although this dependence embarrasses the Saudis in front of
militant brethren like Iran, it is also why they always take the
angry phone calls from Bill Richardson, America's energy secretary,
demanding lower prices.
</P>
<P>
   Does this mean that energy policy will soon fade from the
political landscape? Not necessarily. One reason is that drivers
may not see much relief before the summer is over.
</P>
<P>
   Unless this week's news prompts a split in the cartel and so a
collapse in crude-oil prices, retail-gasoline prices in America may
not drop dramatically before the end of the summer driving season.
</P>
<P>
   There is also likely to be another burst of consumer outrage as
America's overloaded and decaying electricity grid succumbs to
blackouts, like the one that plunged parts of Northern California's
Silicon Valley into darkness a few weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Colder weather will bring little relief: natural-gas prices are
also soaring, and low stocks of heating oil suggest a possible
repeat of last year's winter oil-price crunch.
</P>
<P>
   This week President Bill Clinton vowed to create a
home-heating-oil reserve for the Northeastern states.
</P>
<P>
   In Gore's case in particular, there are good reasons to keep oil
prices in the spotlight: they provide an easy link to Bush's ties
to the oil industry, which is currently making record profits. Gore
has already come out fighting, blaming the price spike on the Big
Oil pals of his rival.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has ordered the Federal Trade
Commission to investigate possible price-gouging in Midwestern
states, where price hikes have been steepest.
</P>
<P>
   Forced into a corner, Bush has also meekly voiced support for
the FTC enquiry. He himself pins the blame for the recent price
increases on costly environmental mandates for cleaner gas ordered
by the federal government (by implication: Gore). In this, he has
just been joined by the state of Wisconsin, which has filed a
federal lawsuit to overturn the federal orders.
</P>
<P>
   Both candidates are being outstandingly hypocritical. For Bush,
who has openly campaigned to defend the interests of the oil
industry, to go suddenly weak at the knees about high oil prices is
bizarre.
</P>
<P>
   How Gore, the author of ``Earth in the Balance'' and a keen
proponent of ridding the world of the internal-combustion engine,
can piously insist that he also believes in low energy prices
beggars belief.
</P>
<P>
   To be fair, it is not just the two candidates who are talking
rot. The energy industry has once again issued warnings that
America must no longer remain ``hostage'' to foreign oil: it thus
needs not only subsidies but also permission to drill in pristine
wilderness.
</P>
<P>
   Such arguments ignore the fact that the crude-oil market is
global: no American firm is selling its crude any lower than the
world price. And even if America pumped all the oil trapped in
forbidden areas, it would not attain the volumes necessary to
dictate world prices.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, what outrages the rest of the world is not how high
American gasoline prices are, but how low.
</P>
<P>
   Today's ``shocking'' prices for gas, adjusted for inflation, are
lower than the prices Americans paid for gas during the oil shock
of two decades ago, and far less than what European or Japanese
drivers pay now.
</P>
<P>
   America guzzles more gas per person than any other big country,
and uses more energy to produce each unit of economic output than
most of its rivals.
</P>
<P>
   If America's politicians were really serious about reducing
OPEC's sway over America, they would consider three things. The
first is tougher fuel-economy rules. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM _ 75 WORDS _ BEGINS HERE AT 900) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The Sierra Club, an influential green lobby, talks about finding
oil by ``drilling under Detroit.'' The group wants Congress to
stiffen the Corporate Average Fuel Economy (CAFE) standards, which
have led to a steady improvement in the fuel efficiency of cars.
</P>
<P>
   Greens grouse that light trucks and sport-utility vehicles
(SUVs), which now make up about half of the vehicles sold in the
country, are not subject to the same CAFE standards as cars. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   A second, better way to improve fuel efficiency and reduce
reliance on oil would be to increase taxes (or add a tax based on
the carbon content of fuels). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM _ 150 WORDS _ BEGINS HERE AT 1,000) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Since the oil shocks of the 1970s, Europe's energy efficiency
has soared, and now stands about 50 percent higher than America's.
</P>
<P>
   One anecdote is revealing: the average fuel economy of Ford's
cars sold in Europe is far higher than that of those it sells in
America. As a result of its diminished reliance on the mucky stuff,
Europe has weathered the recent surge in the world oil price much
better than America.
</P>
<P>
   A comprehensive carbon tax that took in other fuels, such as
coal, would be much greener than just gasoline taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is supposed to be a passionate believer in them. Yet even
when Bush's campaign has mockingly produced specific passages from
Gore's book about carbon taxes, the vice president has refused to
admit that they would drive up fuel prices. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF SECOND TRIM. STORY CONTINUES TO 1,225) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The final option is to do more about public transport. Americans
undoubtedly love to drive. But there is also a distinct lack of
alternatives: outside the older cities on either coast, public
transport in America is usually a farce.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has just put forward his ``Keep America Moving'' scheme,
which he claims is a $25-billion plan to improve, integrate and
expand such public-transport systems as light rail and bus
networks.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has derided these proposals as a mere rehash of tired
Clinton policies. But they are better than anything he has put
forward. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-00 1430EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
