<HEADLINE>
QUIPS, QUIRKS AND QUOTES FROM THIS WEEK'S CAMPAIGN TRAIL  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Political, Commentary, Humor Editors)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 425-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   &UR; FEUD OF THE WEEK: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore accused George W. Bush of lacking compassion for the
disabled. Bush accused the Gore campaign of ``blatant
misrepresentation.'' According to American Disabled for Attendant
Programs Today, a pressure group, Bush has not supported any
disabled programs as governor of Texas, even his father's Americans
with Disabilities Act. Gore's support is also described as
``lukewarm.'' (Salon.com, June 30) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HAPPY BIRTHDAY: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Bush used his 54th birthday on July 6 to add to Republican
coffers. Laura Bush has sent party donors a birthday card (in red,
white and blue, with an outline of Texas and a winding road to the
White House) which she asks to be returned to the governor with a
donation of between $54 and $540. ``If you wish, write George a
personal message,'' she adds. (U.S. News and World Report, July
10) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POSITIVE CAMPAIGNING?: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Gore is a ``gee whiz techo-twit''; Bush is ``beyond satire. How
do you satirize satire?'' (Ralph Nader, Washington Post, July 2) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HISTORICAL REFERENCE OF THE WEEK: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``This was Potemkin (village) legislation. It was designed to
make it appear that they have a plan.'' (Gore on the Republicans'
Medicare bill, Washington Post, July 4) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPENDING SPREE: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Since Bush announced his candidacy in March 1999, he has spent
$1.3 million per week. Of the $73 million that Bush raised for his
primary campaign, nearly $22 million went to campaign advertising.
Travel expenses were over $6 million and direct mail cost $4
million. (Center for Responsive Politics) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BODY-BUILDER: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``Making decisions is a little bit like working out with
weights. When you start working out, you may get sore and the gains
don't come very quickly, but if you hang in there, then you begin
to build up and get stronger. I think there is a decision-making
muscle, and I think it gets stronger the more you use it.'' (Al
Gore, U.S. News &AMP; World Report, July 10) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PHEW!: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Ross Perot announced that he would not run for the presidential
nomination of the Reform Party. His spokesman admitted that he had
only considered running in order to prevent Pat Buchanan getting
it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HUBRIS OF THE WEEK?: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``You can change all the chairs you want on the deck, but if
you're on the HMS Titanic, you're going down.'' (Bush campaign
official on the Gore campaign's attempts to reorganize itself,
Washington Post, July 2) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
