<HEADER>
A7875 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-DENMARK-JAZZ-BOS &LR;      07-10 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DENMARK-JAZZ-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL THAT JAZZ, BUT NOT IN THE STATES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COPENHAGEN _ Pushing 70, Ed Thigpen can still play a mean set of
drums.
</P>
<P>
   Which is no surprise, given that he once backed Ella Fitzgerald,
and that he was part of a trio that included Oscar Peterson on
piano and Ray Brown on bass.
</P>
<P>
   Like many aging jazzmen, Thigpen is a gentleman, a dignified
ambassador for his music. But when people here notice his accent
and remark that he is an American, Thigpen gently corrects them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I consider myself an international,'' the courtly drummer said
while sipping spring water at the Copenhagen JazzHouse between
sets.
</P>
<P>
   Thigpen has made Europe in general, and Denmark in particular,
his home for almost 30 years. Europe is a common choice for jazz
artists who say the music is appreciated more outside their _ and
jazz's _ homeland in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``The US denies itself its own heritage,'' Thigpen said.
</P>
<P>
   For black jazz artists, in particular, Europe offers a more
tolerant venue. But race is only one part of the equation. Respect,
says Thigpen, is key. So is the quality of life.
</P>
<P>
   Thigpen admires the socialism of West European democracies such
as Denmark, where people fork over roughly half of their income to
pay for a generous welfare system that dramatically narrows the gap
between rich and poor, and that ensures decent housing, education,
and health care for all.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're more civilized over here,'' Thigpen said, shrugging.
</P>
<P>
   Take, for example, the way Carlsberg, the biggest brewer in
Denmark, underwrites the arts. Carlsberg Breweries, which also owns
the other big beer here, Tuborg, donates about $21 million annually
to Danish arts and sciences. An arm of the brewery, the New
Carlsberg Foundation, donates about $7 million to visual arts each
year.
</P>
<P>
   Carlsberg not only sponsors the annual jazz festival here,
Tuborg also subsidizes the JazzHouse to showcase jazz throughout
the year.
</P>
<P>
   It was poignantly ironic that last week, Ed Thigpen and his band
played a tribute at the JazzHouse to Ernie Wilkins, a St. Louis
native and jazzman who lived, played and recently died in
Copenhagen. Like the legendary Miles Davis, Wilkins hailed from the
home of the King of Beers in America, but while Anheuser-Busch, the
brewers of Budweiser, dwarfs Carlsberg in profits, it doesn't
support jazz like the Danish brewers do, Thigpen said.
</P>
<P>
   ``American business looks at the arts differently than
Europeans, and that's one reason you see jazz supported more over
here, not just by business, but by the government, too,'' Thigpen
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Danish parliament has voted to fund more jazz venues and to
provide more support for existing ones, like JazzHouse. JazzHouse
managers say the club is secure at least for another three years
thanks to the government support.
</P>
<P>
   Danish jazz fans say government support, combined with business
philanthropy, is essential. Annette Flicker, a Dane who is married
to an American lawyer, said Copenhagen's jazz scene in the 1960s
and 1970s rivaled any other spot in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gordon Dexter played here, Kenny Drew. We had a place called
Jazzhouse Montmartre, and Stan Getz started it,'' said Flicker, 56.
</P>
<P>
   But in the 1980s, the once-flourishing jazz scene withered, and
many clubs closed. Now only a handful, like the upscale JazzHouse
and the down-and-dirty La Fontaine, provide a nightly fix for jazz
addicts such as Jens Esmann, 54.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't what it used to be, but on a night like tonight, when
you can see the great Ed Thigpen, no one's complaining.''
</P>
<P>
   Flicker said Danish jazz fans have a special place in their
heart for Thigpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ed moved here about 30 years ago and married a Danish girl.
Not long after, she died, and he was left to bring up the kids
alone. A lot of jazz fans feared that Ed would go back to America
to raise his kids, but he didn't. He stayed here. And he's much
loved for that, and for his music,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   As if on cue, Ed Thigpen called his Danish band on stage and
invoked the name of that gentle man from St. Louis named Ernie
Wilkins.
</P>
<P>
   ``God rest his soul,'' Thigpen said.
</P>
<P>
   And then the band began to wail.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-00 1432EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
