</P>
<P>
   In fact, compared with the Delphic proclamations that the Saudis
usually issue, this week's announcement was unmistakably clear.
</P>
<P>
   Saudi Arabia has dropped the pretense that OPEC is a consensual
body, and is ready to push the market in the direction that best
serves its own interests _ even if that means risking a collapse in
the cartel.
</P>
<P>
   What has forced the Saudi hand? In recent months the problem has
been a shortage not of oil on world markets, but of gasoline in
America's domestic petrol market, which is the world's biggest
single market for oil.
</P>
<P>
   America's record-high gas prices are largely caused not by any
actions by OPEC, but by domestic factors _ such as bottlenecks at
domestic refineries and tough new environmental standards on
gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Saudis cannot afford to appear as America's
lackeys, they listen carefully to its concerns. The desert kingdom
depends on the United States both for its biggest market and for
its defense.
</P>
<P>
   The raging energy debate in the United States alarms the Saudis.
It has already become a hot political issue.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Saudis fear that it might tip the economy into
recession. They gritted their teeth through two recent OPEC summits
as the cartel's small fry kept them from raising output as much as
they would have liked.
</P>
<P>
   And, explains Roger Diwan of the Petroleum Finance Company, an
industry consultancy, they looked ahead and saw that worse may be
in store. He points to low stocks of heating oil in America.
</P>
<P>
   Unless crude-oil prices drop soon, this may presage another
energy crisis this winter. Adding urgency to the Saudi decision are
signs from elsewhere in the world that sky-high oil prices are
doing damage.
</P>
<P>
   Leo Drollas of the London-based Center for Global Energy Studies
blames current high prices for the unusual decline in oil demand
over the past year in Europe's four biggest economies. He reckons
that they may choke Asia's economic recovery too.
</P>
<P>
   Others worry that Iraq, always unpredictable, might use the
tight supply situation to its advantage in coming months, as winter
approaches.
</P>
<P>
   Such conspiracy theorists suggest that Iraq might seize the
chance of peak demand during northern winter months to hold the
world hostage by suddenly taking its oil off the market in order to
win some concessions on, say, U.N. sanctions policy.
</P>
<P>
   If such an unlikely event were indeed to happen, the world's oil
market would have only one savior: Saudi Arabia. That is because it
is the only country with any significant amount of spare capacity.
</P>
<P>
   Important though its vast reserves and its huge production may
be, it is this ability to bring on fresh barrels in a crisis that
gives it so much power.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Saudi Arabia's rulers have been reluctant to wield
that market power too openly, and have instead used OPEC as cover.
This time, though they still talk of ``coordination with OPEC,''
they seem willing to call the shots.
</P>
<P>
   If they are to be taken at their word, however, they need soon
to produce the promised 500,000 barrels, or the world's oil markets
will be thrown into even greater turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   The OPEC cartel will surely survive, but whether anybody will
again take it so seriously is another matter. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-00 1435EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
