<HEADER>
A7903 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-WE-BOWL-ALONE-USA-ECO     07-10 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WE-BOWL-ALONE-USA-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BOWLING ALONE': WHAT'S MISSING IN AMERICAN SOCIETY  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary, Book Editors)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 750-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ ``Bowling Alone'' is an ambitious book. Even before
its publication, its central thesis had been well chewed over in
America. Both major presidential candidates had consulted its
author; so had Bill Clinton. The cognoscenti were sure they knew
what Robert Putnam was saying.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the book has finally appeared, amplifying and
reinforcing a famous article from the Journal of Democracy in 1995,
the danger is that its potential audience _ wise before the event _
will not bother to read it. That would be a pity.
</P>
<P>
   If Putnam, a Harvard political scientist, is right, his findings
constitute the greatest challenge now facing America's political
classes.
</P>
<P>
   If he is wrong, his book will nevertheless afford the reader a
rich and subtle portrait of modern America (with an unexpected
nugget of information on almost every page).
</P>
<P>
   Either way, ``Bowling Alone'' is a prodigious achievement.
Putnam's scholarship is wide-ranging, his intelligence luminous,
his tone modest, his prose unpretentious and frequently funny.
</P>
<P>
   On top of all that, the professor is probably right. He argues
that while America has recently witnessed record growth in physical
and human capital, its stock of ``social capital'' _ informal
social connectedness and formal civic engagement _ has fallen
dangerously low.
</P>
<P>
   Americans used to bowl in leagues. Now they bowl alone. In New
London, Conn., they bowl alone while watching giant television
screens, thus further reducing their chances of forming meaningful
social connections.
</P>
<P>
   For Putnam, bowling alone is an extended metaphor for much that
ails both modern America and modern Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence for Americans' growing social isolation is strong:
families dine together a third less often than they did even in
1980; electoral turnout has fallen precipitously, even though
blacks in the South are now free to vote, and do.
</P>
<P>
   The underlying causes include pressures of time and money,
long-distance commuting, compulsive television-viewing and, most
important of all, the gradual replacement of the long ``civic
generation'' _ those tempered by the Great Depression and the
Second World War _ by waves of laid-back, solipsistic baby-boomers
and ``generation X'ers.''
</P>
<P>
   The evidence for isolation can be ambiguous, it is true. The
risk of caricature is always present and what is social isolation
to one person may be new forms of interaction to another.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Putnam's passion for social capital, hard as it may be to
define, is easily explained. Innumerable recent studies show that
it is at least as vital as physical and human capital for the
well-being of individual citizens and whole nations.
</P>
<P>
   Socially disconnected individuals, neither supported by dense
social networks nor contributing to them, are unhealthier,
unhappier and commit more crimes. They are also often poorer and
much less good at nurturing and educating their children.
</P>
<P>
   Putnam is too polite to say so, but he clearly feels the whole
country is becoming like those American states that are already
conspicuously lacking in social capital, notably Mississippi,
Louisiana and other states in the old Confederacy.
</P>
<P>
   Putnam concludes with a range of practical proposals, albeit
rather vague ones.
</P>
<P>
   He suggests that American policymakers _ and business and
religious leaders _ factor social capital into their plans and
decisions. Will whatever I or my company proposes to do serve to
build social capital or destroy it?
</P>
<P>
   He challenges employers ``to ensure that by 2010 America's
workplace will be substantially more family-friendly and
community-congenial'' than it is now, and he challenges the
nation's planners and developers to ensure that Americans spend
less time on the road commuting and more time connecting with their
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   He also maintains that ``a mounting body of evidence confirms
that community service programs really do strengthen the civic
muscles of participants, especially if the service is meaningful,
regular, and woven into the fabric of the school curriculum.''
</P>
<P>
   Putnam cheerfully admits to being a missionary. Inevitably, a
book cast in such an ambitious mold fails to fill all of it. Many
of Putnam's prescriptions, as he himself acknowledges, are lacking
in detail and definition.
</P>
<P>
   More seriously, he fails to develop the distinction between
strictly local social capital and forms of what might be called
``like-minded social capital'' transcending local and even national
boundaries. The one may languish while the other flourishes.
</P>
<P>
   All the same, ``Bowling Alone'' is a book that civic-minded
Americans, of whom there are still many, ignore at their peril. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITOR'S NOTE: ``BOWLING ALONE.'' By Robert D. Putnam. Simon &AMP;
Schuster; 542 pages; $26.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
