<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 14:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7905 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-ECOM-FASHION-DESIGNER     07-10 1411
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOM-FASHION-DESIGNERS-ON-WEB-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESIGNER'S TIPTOEING ONTO THE INTERNET, CLAD MOSTLY ACCESSORIES  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The
New York Times Syndicate's E-COMMERCE NEWS SERVICE. The weekly
package of articles offers an in-depth look at how the business of
electronic commerce is changing our lives. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of E-COMMERCE NEWS SERVICE _ contact one of the New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the
text.)
 &HT;    (ART ADV: Art is available in JPEG format by calling William
Gonzalez at 212-499-3355.) 
 &HT;    
 By DONNA WILKINSON  
 c.2000 The New York Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Designer fashion, unlike books or CDs, has not been an easy sell
on the Web. For starters, there is the sizing and fit challenge _
how do you persuade consumers to buy high-end clothing without
trying it on? There is the touch-and-feel problem how do you convey
the look and texture of new fabrics and materials? Then there are
limitations to graphic presentations, conflicts about distributing
products and, beyond that, intangible issues like, how do you sell
something as ephemeral as style?
</P>
<P>
   The surprising news is that online apparel sales are increasing,
particularly among consumers in their mid-20s to mid-40s.
</P>
<P>
   The NPD Group, a market research company in Port Washington,
N.Y., reports that Internet apparel sales for 1999 reached $1.1
billion and are expected to double this year. But, at just less
than 1 percent of the $184 billion in yearly total sales, it is a
small piece of the pie, and is dominated by sites such as Gap.com,
LandsEnd.com and JCrew.com.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, buying khakis online is one thing; buying a couture
ensemble is quite another.
</P>
<P>
   While designer apparel can be purchased on upscale department
store and luxury sites, designers themselves have been reluctant to
dive into the waters of e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Helmut Lang was the first designer to introduce his
fall collection on the Internet, and many designers have used their
sites to promote their clothing and products. But only a handful
are selling anything directly.
</P>
<P>
   That is why the fashion community was abuzz in February when the
Internet-shy Ralph Lauren signed a multimillion-dollar deal with
NBC and ValueVision (which operates the Home Shopping Network) to
form a new company, RL Media, which will develop Polo.com, a
lifestyle Web site that will sell a range of the designer's
products _ clothing and household accouterments _ later this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The deal is unique because it is a joint venture between three
different companies,'' said Ken Cassar, a senior retail analyst for
Jupiter Communications, an Internet research company in New York.
``NBC ponied up advertising time, Ralph Lauren ponied up his brand
name and ValueVision ponied up $50 million in actual cash. The deal
offers Ralph Lauren the potential of going a little bit more mass
market.''
</P>
<P>
   On a smaller scale, Nicole Miller is one of the few designers
who has achieved some success selling direct. Her site, at
www.nicolemiller.com, offers accessories, some evening wear and
bridesmaids' dresses, but no clothing from Miller's collection yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think e-commerce has been all that great in the
clothing area, so we'll be adding things slowly,'' Miller said.
``As far as my collection, that's going to be harder to sell online
because in fashion, you're dealing with new fabrics every year. And
people want to know what the fabrics feel like.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller is right to be cautious, analysts say. The recent demise
of the luxury clothing site Boo.com, sponsored by, among others,
Bernard Arnault, the Benetton family, J.P. Morgan &AMP; Co. and
Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co., shows the unpredictability of selling
high-end apparel on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   When image is everything, the Web poses special risks. Graphic
limitations of the Web can make it hard for designers to get across
the high-gloss image that is vital to preserving ``their brand
equity,'' explained Evie Black Dykema, an analyst with Forrester
Research, a research firm in Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   For high-end designers, profits and image are intertwined.
</P>
<P>
   ``Selling style is different from selling CD's or books,''
Dykema said. ``Sales are not the first focus necessarily. Gucci,
for instance, will spend $5 million on a campaign that may generate
$50,000 in sales because the campaign's aura extends beyond the
sales of clothing. Image is absolutely key, and going online may
hurt that image. So designers may have a very long-term perspective
in that sense and aren't as opportunistic perhaps.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller is not the only one who is taking it slowly. This month,
Lang's site, www.helmutlang.com, will begin selling his new
fragrance but no clothing or accessories. Dolce &AMP; Gabbana's site,
www.dolcegabbana.it, which has been up since March, is purely
informational.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no plans to sell apparel in the immediate future
directly on our site,'' Stefano Gabbana said.
</P>
<P>
   Vera Wang's new site, www.verawang.com, will at first feature
her bridal collection, store locations and text to promote her
first book, ``Vera Wang Weddings,'' which will be published in
2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a five-year plan, and selling is a longer-term goal,''
said Chet Hazzard, the president and chief operating officer of
Vera Wang. ``We want to provide high-quality applications like
video, audio, interactive chats with Vera, articles and fashion
shows. Vera is very interested in this. She knows this is the
future. We want to make sure we do it right.''
</P>
<P>
   Most designers realize that high fashion's prices have limited
mass-market appeal. ``We really don't believe a bride is going to
buy a bridal dress on the Internet,'' Hazzard said. ``It's a very
expensive purchase _ it's not something you buy from a picture.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``There are some luxury sites that tell you they sell
$7,000 earrings. I'd like to know how many. I'm not saying they
didn't get one customer to buy them, but Vera and I look at things
in a very practical way. Would Vera buy a $7,000 pair of earrings
on the Internet? No.''
</P>
<P>
   But designers are coming to the belief that they can use the Web
to sell more everyday products.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking at bridesmaids' apparel, bridal accessories, a
gift registry, jewelry, stationery, fragrance, body, bath and
home,'' Hazzard said. Gabbana also said that accessories might make
more sense for online sales.
</P>
<P>
   Some fashion insiders may be in a wait-and-see mode about what
other major brands are doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the world of fashion and high-end retail, there is a
significant lemming effect,'' said Cassar, the analyst. ``When both
Ralph Lauren and Tommy Hilfiger are selling directly on the Web,
everyone else will have no choice but to follow suit.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if a designer decides not to sell online, having a strong
Web presence is good.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a great advertising vehicle for us _ we get about
10,000 catalog requests a week,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, she said, ``I believe people like the retail
shopping experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Many agree. ``The brick-and-mortar department and retail stores
will continue to be the primary outlet for purchases of luxury
products,'' Cassar said. But the Web can attract high-fashion
customers to retail stores. ``As designers build
informational-communication sites, they will initiate a dialogue
with the consumer, and they will then pass the consumer along to
the department store or to their own retail stores for the
transaction.''
</P>
<P>
   But ultimately,'' Cassar added, ``designer fashion is show
business, something that plays better in the physical world.''
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on E-COMMERCE
NEWS SERVICE and other features.
