<P>
   The New York Times News Service plans the following  &UR; Science
Times &LR;  stories for papers of Tuesday, July 11:
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GENES-FOOD (Undated) _ The academies of science of the
United States, China, Brazil, and other countries reaffirm the
importance of genetically modified agriculture for the Third World
and plead for more understanding and research. By Carol Kaesuk
Yoon. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-AIDS-CONFERENCE (Durban, South Africa) _ Development at the
AIDS conference. By Lawrence K. Altman. (1200 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-OKLA-CANCER (Undated) _ Federal officials shut down all
government sponsored clinical trials involving human subjects at
the University of Oklahoma College of Medicine in Tulsa after 26
patients died. The patients, all suffering from melanoma, were
injected with a vaccine. There is no proof the vaccine caused the
deaths but procedures were not followed.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-TICK-BITE (Undated) _ Scientists are studying the chemical
weapons in tick saliva hoping to discover a tick vaccine and drugs
for controlling clotting and inflamation. By Andrew C. Revkin.
(2220 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SPACE-STATION (Undated) _ Construction of what is to become
the largest structure that humans have ever put into space has been
on hold, awaiting the late arrival of the station's critical
Russian-made command and living section. The long-overdue service
module, called Zvezda, which means ``star'' in Russian, is to
rocket into orbit Wednesday and put an end to the hiatus of almost
two years in building what is to become a sprawling international
research complex in space. By Warren E. Leary. (1975 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ARCTIC-ICE (Oslo, Norway) _ Melting Arctic caps may yield
environmental disaster, but have some economic benefits. Scientist
theorize the extent of the damage and the future of the caps and
explore a new theory in which the caps melt each summer. By Walter
Gibbs. (1347 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GREAT-LAKES (Alpena, Mich.) _ Alien species such as sea
lamprey are killing off native species like Lake trout in the Great
Lakes. Biologist and wildlife mangers are trying to save the
ecological future of the Great Lakes. By David Binder. (2190 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CONCH-SHELLS (Undated) _ The remarkable strength of conch
shells. Scientists are studying them to discover nature's
evolutionary engineering that could inspire tougher ceramics that
could be used in furnaces and combustion engines. By Kenneth Chang.
(448 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-QUANTUM-EXPERIMENTS (Undated) _ How the fuzziness of the
atomic world, described by the equations of quantum mechanics,
solidifies into the larger, everyday world is a long-standing
puzzle, that physicists have been able to ignore until now. But now
scientists have pushed the eerie phenomena of quantum mechanics
much closer to the everyday world with an experiment that is a
simplified version of the concept of Schroedinger's cat. By Kenneth
Chang. (1475 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WATCH (Undated) _ News and notes on science: Items on the
discovery of the tomato growth gene, the migration of butterflies
through the Sierra Nevada with a warning for motorists and the
deaths of tigers at a zoo in India. By Henry Fountain. (680 words)
</P>
<P>
   NOUR-AFRICAN-WOMEN (Boston) _ A conversation with Nawal Nour,
who has set up the African Women's Health Practices at Brigham and
Women's to deal with the special gynecologic needs of the large
immigrant community. Many of there have undergone the ritual of
female circumcision. By Claudia Dreifus. (1600 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ALLERGY (Undated) _ There are promising results from new
experimental trials of anti-IgE, which targets the antibody IgE and
can stop allergy attacks at their source. By Randi Hutter Epstein.
(950 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-PATENTS (Undated) _ Sometimes the treatment can be more
harmful, and demoralizing, for the patient than he or she can bear.
A case in point: the many who had to stop eating to stop the
aspiration of fluids into their lungs. By Sandeep Jauhar. (700
words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ The Personal Health column: The
benefits of drinking large quantities of water are vast, and even
include reducing jet lag. First of two articles. By Jane E. Brody.
(1230 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-YOUNG-DOCTORS (Undated) _ The shock of baby-faced doctors:
almost half of practicing doctors are under 45, and the greatest
proportion is between 35 to 44. Some people are unprepared to take
advice from a younger person: we are used to taking care of younger
people, not having younger people take care of us. By Alcia Ault.
(900 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-VITAL-SIGNS (Undated) _ News and notes of health and
fitness:
</P>
<P>
   _ A report in Neurology urges doctors to have greater vigilance
in diagnosing the West Nile virus, and says earlier diagnosis can
reduce its harm to patients and can also provide information on the
outbreak of the disease. (255 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ Researchers at the University of California at Irvine say they
have developed a chemical that works like scorpion venom, but
instead of harming people, it may one day help doctors who perform
organ transplants or treat autoimmune diseases like lupus and
arthritis. (190 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ Minocycline, a common antibotic, slowed down the course of
Huntington's disease in mice and could help with other diseases
including Alzheimers. (210 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ Generally, as people age, they get psychologically better.
Researchers found that psychological health steadily increased from
age 30. (265 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ A journal reports that blood samples taken from the ear lobe
were less painful than those taken from the thumb. Doctors theorize
that there are fewer pain receptors. (190 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ A science question answered: Growing roses
from seed. By C. Claiborne Ray. (295 words)
</P>
