A7968 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BIGBUGS-COX     07-10 0292
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIGBUGS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Giant bugs, roomful of live insects delight children
 &HT;    By Sofia Villalobos
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio - A Chinese praying mantis more than 21 feet long
extending its sharp forearms to catch prey is making its home at
the Boonshoft Museum of Discovery through Sept. 10.
</P>
<P>
   The ``What Bugs Us'' exhibit from Kokoro Ltd. in Tokyo, Japan,
includes robotic insects more than 600 times life size and a
roomful of live insects, including the walking stick and hissing
cockroaches, plus an array of close-up bug pictures accompanied by
educational information.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hear shrieks of delight from the children since the
displays are fun and colorful,'' public relations coordinator
Catherine Mauch said.
</P>
<P>
   Large models of a grasshopper and a spider show the differences
in body structure between insects and arachnids. Some models, like
the locust, span their wings robotically, but children can manually
control the giant head exhibits of a bee, dragonfly and a mosquito
as it illustrates its bite on human skin.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like we're the bugs and they're the people,'' Alissa
Ayers, 10, of Kettering said as she toured the museum recently with
her classmates from the Early Beginnings Child Care and Learning
Center.
</P>
<P>
   The display permits bug fanatics to discover not only how
insects move, but what they eat, their environments and their basic
textures, shapes and colors.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is pretty cool because they look real, they move and they
make us look like ants to them,'' said Logan Smith, 6, of
Bellbrook, one of Alissa's classmates.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Sofia Villalobos at sofiavillalobos(at)coxohio.com or at
225-2235.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
