<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 15:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7977 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-YOUNG-DOCTORS-ART     07-10 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-YOUNG-DOCTORS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ESSAY: BABY-FACED DOCTORS, WHITE-HAIRED PATIENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT1 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 (The Science Times)  
 By ALICIA AULT    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sooner or later, we all meet up with a jarring reminder that we
are not as young as we think. Increasingly, the jolt hits
middle-age types when a doctor walks through the door: He or she is
not Marcus Welby, in keeping with the demographics of the medical
profession.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 621,000 doctors practicing in hospitals or offices in
1998, the year for which the most recent data are available, almost
half were under age 45, according to the American Medical
Association. The greatest proportion _ about 189,108 _ were 35 to
44.
</P>
<P>
   The shock of dealing with baby-faced doctors may not go beyond
the reflexive brain flash ``She/he looks like a child!'' when the
doctor speaks with authority, professionalism and calmness.
</P>
<P>
   The patients of Dr. Valerie Asher, an ear, nose and throat
specialist in a group practice in Silver Spring, Md., for example,
say she exudes a confidence that belies her age, 39. ``It helps
that I'm tall and I've been a bossy person my whole life,'' Asher
said.
</P>
<P>
   It was that persona that Chris Dowd, 47, saw when doctor and
patient met. ``She was a very succinct, efficient professional,''
said Dowd, of Potomac, Md. ``There was never any question in my
mind that she didn't know precisely what she was doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the fact that Asher, who took time off between her
undergraduate and medical school years at Yale, has been in
practice only since 1995 did not faze Dowd or her 51-year-old
husband, Dan, another patient.
</P>
<P>
   That is not uncommon, said Asher. ``Most of the aging baby
boomers I see are delighted,'' she said. ``They think that I'm
ahead of the curve, compared to someone ahead of their
generation.''
</P>
<P>
   But psychologists say that for many 40- and 50-year-olds that is
not always the case. A younger doctor, psychologists say, can
trigger insecurities about age, mortality, and achievements, as
well as care-giving and advice-taking roles.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Loranger, 36, said she was uneasy last fall when she first
saw her then 2-year-old daughter's new pediatrician, Dr. Karen
Fratantoni, 29. ``She just looked really young,'' said Loranger, a
public relations specialist on maternity leave with her second
child. ``At first, I was like, hmmmm. I questioned it.''
</P>
<P>
   Loranger, of Wheaton, Md., wanted to know why her daughter was
having repeated, stubborn ear infections, but she was worried about
Fratantoni's track record. Fratantoni, however, got to the bottom
of the problem quickly, and Loranger said she has been impressed
since then.
</P>
<P>
   Mid-lifers may also question whether a 30-year-old doctor has
enough clinical or life experience to relate to patients
meaningfully. Ben Sapers, a 33-year-old primary-care doctor who
completed his training last summer, said such concern reflects a
dim understanding of medical education today.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the time I finished my residency, I'd seen at least a dozen
people die in front of me,'' said Sapers, of Harvard Vanguard
Medical Associates in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Holly Moss, 30, a specialist who helps children and families
cope with hospital stays, has been practicing for five years. Moss
counsels terminally ill children and their parents at Primary
Children's Medical Center in Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   Parents who meet her see a young woman, she said. ``At first
they are skeptical,'' she said. ``But when I start talking about
the issues and concerns, and anticipate the issues they will have,
they become very receptive.''
</P>
<P>
   She also plays with the children, cajoling them with games,
jokes, costumes _ whatever it takes. With some parents though, Moss
said, that playful mode can undermine her authority, as when a set
of parents decided she was not old enough to talk to their
14-year-old about another child's death.
</P>
<P>
   `` `I just didn't think you had it in you, and I didn't trust
you because you seemed so young, and you don't have your own
children,''' Moss recalled the mother saying.
</P>
<P>
   Some people are unprepared to take advice from a younger person,
said Dr. Nancy Schlossberg, a psychologist and professor emeritus
at the University of Maryland who has written several books about
coping with change. ``We are used to taking care of younger people,
not having younger people take care of us,'' Schlossberg said.
</P>
<P>
   The comfort level may be higher with a younger surgeon, who is
perceived as having steadier hands and more familiarity with the
latest techniques. But it may lessen when the problem is more
personal. A 50-year-old might not feel comfortable, for example,
discussing sexual dysfunction with a 32-year-old, Schlossberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Older doctors are generally better at reading patients'
emotional concerns, said Dr. Zeev Neuwirth, a family therapist and
medical educator at Lenox Hill Hospital in Manhattan. But, said
Neuwirth, 38, most newly minted physicians have razor-sharp
technical skills and a solid grounding in relating to their
patients.
</P>
<P>
   And, Dowd said, youth does not always mean inexperience. ``It
kind of gets my back up when people say you are too young to know
what you're talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
