<DOCNO> NYT20000710.0186 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 15:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7981 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     07-10 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARTISAN POLITICS RUNS DEEP IN THE DEATH PENALTY DEBATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If there had been any doubt that a partisan political subtext
lurks beneath the current hysteria over capital punishment, the
doubt was erased with this headline: ``White House plans to delay
execution.''
</P>
<P>
   Provided by The New York Times and published in Friday's Fort
Worth Star-Telegram, the story said that President Clinton is
expected to grant a reprieve to a killer who was convicted in 1993
of three drug-related murders in Texas and is scheduled for
execution Aug. 5. The delay would allow the Justice Department to
finalize clemency procedures for federal Death Row inmates.
</P>
<P>
   The Constitution empowers the president to grant pardons and
reprieves in federal cases _ 21 prisoners are awaiting execution
for federal crimes _ but there is no formal policy under which
condemned prisoners can seek presidential clemency. The lack of a
policy posed no problem in recent years _ maybe because the U.S.
government hasn't executed anyone since the Kennedy administration.
</P>
<P>
   But now, with a scheduled execution drawing near and the
anti-death penalty forces on the warpath, Clinton has reportedly
decided that the government must have a policy in place before he
can allow a cold-blooded killer to face the executioner. Clinton
decided this, by the way, even though a federal judge had already
rejected lawyers' arguments that it would be inappropriate to
execute multiple murderer Juan Raul Garza before clemency rules are
finalized, according to The Times.
</P>
<P>
   It is possible, of course, that Clinton simply wants to shield
himself from the sort of criticism heaped upon Texas Gov. George W.
Bush regarding the Lone Star State's clemency process. Although
Texas governors have no constitutional authority to overturn death
sentences, Bush has nonetheless taken the heat for a state system
that calls for members of an appointed board to rule on clemency
requests.
</P>
<P>
   Far more likely, though, is the possibility that Clinton sees in
this situation an opportunity to help Vice President Al Gore in his
presidential campaign against Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has been hard-pressed to score any political points on the
capital punishment issue because both he and Clinton have been
enthusiastic death-penalty advocates throughout their public lives.
But by bending over backward to make sure that the government is
more than fair with Garza, Clinton can market the impression that
his administration is committed to Death Row fairness _ and that
the Clinton-Gore policy on clemency is therefore superior to the
Texas policy.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, delaying Garza's execution would almost certainly keep
him out of the death chamber until after the November election.
Leave it to Clinton to devise a gambit that allows him and his
sidekick Gore to be simultaneously for and against the death
penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and there's another reason for holding up Garza's
appointment with the lethal needle, according to The Times. Clinton
is concerned about geographical and ethnic imbalance in federal
death sentences.
</P>
<P>
   The president set the stage during his White House news
conference last week when he said he was worried that a defendant's
chances of being sentenced to death might hinge on ``where you
committed the crime.''
</P>
<P>
   The implication: If federal prosecutors in certain parts of the
country are inclined to seek the death penalty for capital crimes
and those in other parts of the country are not, then defendants in
areas with aggressive prosecutors are being treated unfairly.
</P>
<P>
   There's some liberal logic for you.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Clinton's objective here is a tricky one. He wants
to help Gore by exploiting criticism of Bush's support for capital
punishment while avoiding charges of hypocrisy _ an understandable
concern, seeing as how the former Arkansas governor left the
presidential campaign trail in 1992 to oversee an execution and two
years later signed federal legislation expanding the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Just a guess: This is one trick that even Slick Willie can't
pull off.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787 or
billthompson &LR; star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
