<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S DOING IN PORTLAND, ME.  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by WAY TO GO! clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement. For purchase information,
see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 (Color slides and B&AMP;W map available.) 
 FROM THE NEW YORK TIMES 
 By WAYNE CURTIS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    The spirited waterfront city of Portland, Me., has quietly
emerged from the shadows in the past few years. Residents these
days don't need to explain to visitors quite so often that, well,
the Trail Blazers play basketball in that other Portland.
 &HT;    Two decades ago entrepreneurs reinvigorated the Victorian Old
Port neighborhood, known for its exceptional brick architecture.
The revival recently moved uptown to Congress Street, where an arts
district is taking root, helped by the Maine College of Art's
decision to fill an empty Beaux-Arts department store with students
after its owners decamped to a mall.
 &HT;    On the streets this summer you're likely to overhear Portlanders
talking of soaring real-estate values and of Web entrepreneurs who
have started to trickle in.
 &HT;    Portland, Maine's largest city, once had easy access to European
trade routes in its favor; now it has lifestyle. Situated on Casco
Bay, which is often speckled with colorful sailboats on summer
weekends, it's a tidy and compact city, where you can walk almost
everywhere. Yet it's imbued with far more urban energy than one
would expect for a city of 65,000.
 &HT;    The optimism is sometimes tinged with nervousness. Portlanders
have been comfortable in the shadows, thank you very much, and
there's growing concern that too much attention will bring
unwelcome change.
 EVENTS  
 &HT;    This month Portland's harbor will take on a 19th-century air
when more than two dozen tall ships from around the world will
converge here, the final port in Operation Sail 2000, (207)
541-7400, which began in Puerto Rico in May. The Portland
festivities begin with a ship parade at noon on July 28, when the
tall ships will be greeted with gun salutes as they pass sites of
two 19th-century forts.
 &HT;    Among the best vantage points is the pathway along the Eastern
Prom, which runs northward along the harbor from near the Casco Bay
Lines ferry terminal. The three-day event will also include
fireworks, musical performances at stages along the waterfront,
ship tours and maritime exhibits at museums in and around the city.
 &HT;    The Yarmouth Clam Festival, (207) 846-3984, takes place July 21
to 23 in the village of Yarmouth, about 15 minutes' drive north of
Portland. It's an old-fashioned community festival, and this year
will feature pageantry imported from the medieval festival in
Cortona, Italy, including a crossbow contest and a parade with
costumed performers, Carnival rides, old-fashioned games and
splendidly caloric foods round out the event; admission is free.
 &HT;    The Portland Museum of Art, 7 Congress Square, (800) 639-4067,
is displaying more than 50 works by N. C. Wyeth, the patriarch of
the Wyeth clan (1882-1945), through Oct. 15. Wyeth is best known
for his vivid illustrations of books like ``Treasure Island,'' but
he also painted privately, dabbling in styles ranging from
Impressionism to Realism. The exhibition's emphasis is on the
paintings, but a number of Wyeth's illustrations are also on view.
 &HT;    The Center for Cultural Exchange, 1 Longfellow Square, (207)
761-1545, presents a series of global music concerts and dances
each week throughout the summer. At 7 p.m. this Saturday the Saigon
Water Puppets of Vietnam will perform at the center, to the
accompaniment of music played on centuries-old instruments. Tickets
are $10, $5 for children.
 &HT;    The colorful Maine Festival, (207) 772-9012, runs from Aug. 4 to
6, with an eclectic assortment of Maine musicians, poets, dancers,
artists and craftsmen. The sprawling festival attracts about 20,000
visitors during its three-day run at the Thomas Point Beach
campground in Brunswick, at the north end of Casco Bay, 26 miles
north of Portland. Tickets are $12 at the gate, $10 in advance,
with discounts for seniors and children.
 SIGHTSEEING  
 &HT;    A superb spot to get the lay of the land is atop the Portland
Observatory, 138 Congress St., (207) 774-5561, on Munjoy Hill, one
of the downtown residential neighborhoods. The 86-foot cone-shaped
tower was built in 1807 as a perch to notify Portlanders of
incoming ships via a system of flags. It reopened on June 10 after
a five-year renovation, and the observation deck offers a
vertiginous view of the city, harbor and islands. Open daily; $3.
 &HT;    The best way to tour Portland is on foot, for a better
appreciation of the brick sidewalks, granite curbs, architectural
details and the sound of gulls wheeling overhead.
 &HT;    The Old Port district, home to dozens of boutiques and
restaurants, has some fine examples of Victorian commercial
architecture, most of them dating from after 1866, when the last
great fire swept through the city.
 &HT;    Greater Portland Landmarks, 165 State St., (207) 774-5561,
publishes self-guided walking tours of four neighborhoods, for
$1.25 each. The organization also conducts daily guided walking
tours, beginning at 10:30 a.m. and lasting for about an hour and a
half, between July 5 and Oct. 9. The starting point for the tours
is the Convention and Visitors Bureau of Greater Portland, 305
Commercial St., (207) 772-5800.
 &HT;    In the city's West End, one of Portland's grand 19th-century
neighborhoods of architecturally eclectic houses, is the
Morse-Libby House, 109 Danforth St., (207) 772-4841, one of the
nation's pre-eminent examples of Italianate Victorian architecture.
Guided tours through this opulent brownstone mansion suggest a
lavishness that might arouse envy in Donald Trump. The house is
open Tuesday through Sunday; $7.
 &HT;    Along the waterfront on Commercial Street, a fleet of
sightseeing boats offers excursions through the dozens of islands
that dot the bay. Among the more intriguing destinations is the
17-acre Eagle Island, the former summer home of the Arctic explorer
Robert E. Peary.
 &HT;    The four-hour trip includes an hour-and-20-minute stop on the
island (take a picnic), where Peary's home, a 1904 shingle and
stone summer cottage, is open to the public. Eagle Island Tours,
Long Wharf, (207) 774-6498, offers one trip daily at 10 a.m., with
reservations suggested. The price is $18, $10.50 for children.
 &HT;    Fifteen minutes from downtown is the Portland Head Light, 1000
Shore Road, Cape Elizabeth; (207) 799-2661. It may look instantly
familiar _ it appears frequently in calendars and ads. The light
dates from 1791 (President George Washington appointed the first
keeper), and the present lightkeeper's house, the third on the
site, was built in 1891.
 &HT;    The light is still operational and so isn't open to the public,
but travelers can stroll the expansive park grounds overlooking the
harbor's entrance and visit the museum at the keeper's house. The
park is free; the museum, open daily, is $2, $1 for children.
 &HT;    On sweltering days, visitors might opt for a trip 20 miles south
to Old Orchard Beach, home to a seven-mile sandy strand edged by
chilly ocean waters, carnival rides and food vendors.
 WHERE TO STAY  
 &HT;    The stylishly funky Pomegranate Inn, 49 Neal St., (207)
772-1006, fax (207) 773-4426, in the West End, was built in 1884.
It has eight guest rooms, all above average in size, decorated with
antiques, modern art and vibrantly painted walls. Doubles are $135
to $225, including breakfast.
 &HT;    Barbara Hathaway has converted a regal 1821 brick house into the
welcoming Danforth Inn, 163 Danforth St.; (207) 879-8755, fax (207)
879-8754. The 10 guest rooms vary in size (some are in the former
servants' quarters), but all are comfortable and attractive. Room 1
has a private sitting room and second-floor deck; guests have
access to the billiard room in the basement. Doubles are $135 to
$285, including breakfast.
 &HT;    Budget: The Percy Inn, 15 Pine St., (207) 871-7638, fax (207)
775-2599, is in a narrow 1830 brick row house in the city's West
End and has two guest rooms and three suites furnished in early
Federal style. All rooms are up a steep winding staircase. Those
facing the street are a bit noisy, but brighter and more spacious
than those facing the rear. Doubles are $89 to $169, with
breakfast.
 &HT;    The Inn at Park Spring, 135 Spring St., (800) 437-8511 or (207)
774-1059 has six guest rooms in a cozy 1835 brick house near the
art museum and within strolling distance of the Old Port and city
restaurants. Summer rates for two are $135 to $145, including
breakfast.
 &HT;    Luxury: About 15 minutes southeast of Portland is the Black
Point Inn, 510 Black Point Road, Prouts Neck, Scarborough, (800)
258-0003, fax (207) 883-9976, a compound of shingled 19th-century
buildings on nine acres overlooking the ocean.
 &HT;    Built as a summer resort in 1873, the inn features 85 guest
rooms in five buildings. Most rooms are in the main lodge, and are
generous in size and furnished in a cheerful summer-cottage style.
Summer rates from $345 for two, including breakfast and dinner.
 WHERE TO EAT  
 &HT;    Cravings for basic boiled lobster are probably better indulged
elsewhere along the Maine coast, at rustic lobster shacks, at
picnic tables atop a pier. In Portland, the fare is more creative.
 &HT;    Natasha's, 40 Portland St., (207) 774-4004, features new
American fare in an echo-y industrial space, with a menu that
features Thai noodles with vegetarian pot stickers, grilled pork
loin with po blano jam, and ravioli stuffed with lobster and crab.
Open Tuesday to Saturday for dinner, daily for breakfast and lunch.
Dinner for two with wine, about $60.
 &HT;    At Ribollita, 41 Middle St., (207) 774-2972, Kevin Quiet, the
chef and owner, offers a menu of handmade pasta and other
Mediterranean-influenced dishes. Among the options: ravioli with
white beans and Romano cheese served with a hazelnut brown butter,
and oven-poached sole with crabmeat mascarpone tortellini. Open for
dinner Tuesday to Saturday; dinner for two, with wine, is about
$70.
 &HT;    Bella Cucina, 653 Congress St., (207) 828-4033, combines
romantic and hip in a storefront restaurant that's awash in mellow
tones. The restaurant bills its fare as country Italian, and serves
up a good selection of fresh seafood and vegetarian options.
 &HT;    The menu changes according to availability of ingredients;
expect entrees like a grilled salmon medallion in a
parmesan-hazelnut crust, or a rabbit, duck and pork ragu served
over pasta with wood-grilled peppers. Open nightly; dinner $75 for
two, with wine.
 &HT;    The informal and eclectic Katahdin, 106 High St., (207)
774-1740, is near the art museum and offers budget blue-plate
specials along with more refined fare. The seafood is particularly
good, with dishes ranging from yellowfin tuna with a green onion
wasabi sauce to grilled sea scallops. The bar has been mixing
martinis since well before the martini bar was rediscovered. Open
nightly, Tuesday through Saturday; dinner for two, with martinis:
$75.
 &HT;    Silly's, 40 Washington Ave., (207) 772-0360, will satisfy
aficionados of kitsch (especially Elvis kitsch) and zesty finger
food. It's a boisterous neighborhood joint; the pizzas are popular,
as are the lamb shish kebab roll-ups with feta cheese. Hand-cut
fries and a milkshake nicely fill out a meal, not to mention the
customer. Open daily except Sunday for lunch and dinner: about $15
to $20 for two. 
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (Wayne Curtis is the author of ``Maine: Off the Beaten Path''
(Globe Pequot).)
 &HT;    -----
 c.2000 Wayne Curtis 
