<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASK THE TRAVEL EXPERT 
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by WAY TO GO! clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement. For purchase information,
see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: The word AT in parentheses has been used in an e-mail
address instead of the symbol, which many computer systems at
newspapers can't interpret.)  
 &HT;    
 By WILLIAM T. TOMICKI 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;     Q:  I'm looking for a sleek and modern hotel in the heart of
Seattle. Any suggestions?
 &HT;     A:  Plush chenille pillows, intimate lighting and an impressive
24-hour concierge service are just a handful of the special touches
that guests can expect at the new W Hotel in Seattle.
 &HT;    Part of the brand-driven W hotel chain launched by Starwood
Hotels and Resorts, the W Seattle is a unique refuge for business
and leisure travelers who have a penchant for hip hotels that
combine sophisticated urban style with relaxed elegance.
 &HT;    Guests love amenities such as high-speed Internet access, luxe
bedding, in-room CD players, 24-hour fitness center and quirky
munchie-bar offerings such as candy necklaces and pez dispensers.
 &HT;    Many of the rooms have office facilities, including scanners,
printers and fax machines. Rates start at $239 to $259 per night.
For more information or reservations, call (877) W Hotels.
 &HT;     Q:  My wife and I have noticed that cruise ships seem to be
getting bigger. We love the features and activities found on big
ships, but we like the intimacy found on smaller ships. Can we have
our cake and eat it too?
 &HT;     A:  It's true that some of the new cruise ships are so huge
that the enjoyment of being ``at sea'' is lost.
 &HT;    Multideck atriums on some ships feel more like airline terminals
and aren't conducive to meaningful conversation. Dining elbow to
elbow with hundreds of shipmates in a cavernous space in the ship's
belly is often little more than a tedious banquet.
 &HT;    Holland America Line seems to have gotten the message, and the
MS Volendam is the first of the company's new generation of luxury
cruise ships. With a passenger capacity of 1,440, the Volendam is
isn't a small vessel, yet its design gives it the intimate feel of
a much smaller ship. Public rooms are plentiful, but each is
creatively distinct in its ambiance.
 &HT;    So cleverly has Holland America crafted the scale of the
Volendam that, combined with its exquisite furnishings, flattering
lighting and $2 million worth of art, passengers have the
impression they are pampered guests on a private yacht.
 &HT;    Those who desire something other than the dramatic two-deck
747-seat Rotterdam Dining Room are free to reserve a private table
at the beautiful 88-seat Marco Polo Restaurant.
 &HT;    While the opportunity to enlarge its already legendary Ocean Spa
and increase the number of its verandah minisuites by 40 percent
were just two of Holland America's persuasive arguments to build a
large ship, the company's commitment to intimate scale and quality
design has retained the romance of cruising.
 &HT;    Economies of scale dictate that ships will get bigger as
passenger demand continues to grow, but the new MS Volendam is an
eloquent example of how small a big ship can be. For more
information, contact your travel professional, or call (877)
SAIL-HAL (724-5425).
 &HT;     Q:  Where can I go to find good travel information on the Web?
 &HT;     A:  Online travel is the largest internet commerce category on
the Web today as more and more browsers discover how easy it is to
plan travel 24 hours a day from the comfort of their homes or
offices.
 &HT;    However, it is important to choose reputable sites that deliver
reliable and worthwhile services to consumers.
 &HT;    Expedia.com is the online travel-industry leader with over $400
million in sales in the last quarter of this year alone. Touches
such as e-mailing customers to inform them of travel delays and
cancellations have helped the company obtain its leading edge.
 &HT;    They also have chosen to offer travel options for a wide variety
of budgets and are committed to finding the best value for your
dollar. However, they operate on the premise that you get what you
pay for. Take a look: www.expedia.com.
 &HT;     Q:  I finally have the opportunity to visit the Amazon rain
forests _ something I have wanted to do my whole life _ but I'm a
little concerned about traveling there alone.
 &HT;    Can you suggest a place where I can really experience the Amazon
without worrying about being taken advantage of or feeling like an
obvious tourist?
 &HT;     A:  Located on the eastern edge of the Andes Mountains in
Ecuador, a small village houses a collection of cabins that should
suit your needs.
 &HT;    Operated by Beny Ammeter, a Swiss expatriate, La Casa del Suizo
is a small group of cabins that overlooks the Napo River and the
expansive rain forest.
 &HT;    Guests are immediately plunged into the Quichua Indian culture
as soon as they arrive at the resort _ by canoe _ and visit the
village to mingle with the locals; watch blowpipe demonstrations;
learn to make the local alcoholic drink, chicha; and hike through
the awe-inspiring rain forest.
 &HT;    For more infomation, visit www.casadelsuizo.com on the Web.
 &HT;    This trip, and more like it, can be found in the Spring/Summer
2000 Specialty Travel Index, $10 per year for two issues. Send
orders to info(AT)specialitytravel.com.
 &HT;     Q:  My husband and I are taking our children to Chicago this
summer. Where do you suggest we take them? As a mom, I'm obligated
to ask for something somewhat educational.
 &HT;     A:  One way to beat the heat is to spend the day at Chicago's
John G. Shedd Aquarium. The aquarium opened its newest exhibit last
month, Amazon Rising: Seasons of the River. Visitors journey
through the annual cycles of the Amazon River basin, which features
over 250 exotic species of animals and explains how they adapt to
the extreme conditions of this ever-changing ecosystem.
 &HT;    Some of the astounding animals your children will see include
the Goliath bird-eating spiders; a green anaconda; and the world's
smallest monkey, the pygmy marmoset.
 &HT;    Also, be sure to visit the aquarium's other current exhibits _
the Oceanarium and the Seahorse Symphony. For adults, the aquarium
will be open until 10 p.m. on Thursday nights for Jazzin' at the
Shedd.
 &HT;    For more information, call (312) 939-2438, or visit
www.sheddaquarium.org. Advance tickets are available through
Ticketmaster at (312) 559-0200.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Readers are invited to submit questions to William Tomicki, P.O.
Box 5148, Santa Barbara, Calif. 93150. Although he cannot answer
each query individually, selected questions will be included in his
column. Mr. Tomicki, who logs over 150,000 miles each year, is the
publisher of ENTREE, a travel newsletter. 
 &HT;    
 c.2000 William T. Tomicki 
