<SLUG> BC-SAFETY-ABROAD-TRAVEL-SHOPPING-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOPPING AROUND: SAFETY ABROAD  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by WAY TO GO! clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement. For purchase information,
see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 By EVERETT POTTER 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    When the Department of State issued a ``Worldwide Caution'' on
June 27, 2000, it was a telling reminder that the world of
terrorism doesn't relax when Americans take their summer vacations.
 &HT;    The caution urged American ``citizens worldwide of the need to
remain vigilant with regard to their personal security. This Public
Announcement is not in response to a particular threat or event but
to emphasize our ongoing concern for the security of Americans
overseas.''
 &HT;    Indeed, unlike past cautions, which have been linked to specific
terrorist events, this one was much broader. Yet it did single out
one date.
 &HT;    ``Periods on or around significant dates, such as the August 7
anniversary of the bombings of the U.S. Embassies in Nairobi,
Kenya, and Dar es Salaam, Tanzania, may be chosen as opportunities
for further terrorist acts. As a result, security continues to be a
prime concern at U.S. government facilities worldwide.''
 &HT;    Anyone heading abroad would do well to visit the Department of
State's Web site, http://travel.state.gov, and have a look at the
Consular Information Sheets, Public Announcements, Travel Warnings.
 &HT;    There's a Consular Information Sheet for every country in the
world. These reports include information on the location of the
U.S. Embassy or Consulate, health conditions, minor political
disturbances, entry regulations as well as crime and security
information.
 &HT;    As the State Department notes, these reports ``generally do not
include advice, but present information in a factual manner so the
traveler can make his or her own decisions concerning travel to a
particular country.''
 &HT;    But if there is an area of a given country where there is some
kind of trouble, it's typically listed under a subhead of ``crime''
or ``security.''
 &HT;    Take a country such as Mexico, which draws many Americans.
Currently, that country's Consular Information Sheet states that
``crime in Mexico continues at high levels, and it is increasingly
violent, especially in Mexico City, Tijuana and Ciudad Juarez. Low
apprehension and conviction rates of criminals contribute to the
high crime rate. Other metropolitan areas have lower, but still
serious levels of crime. Travelers should leave valuables and
irreplaceable items in a safe place, or not bring them at all. All
visitors are encouraged to make use of hotel safes when available,
avoid wearing obviously expensive jewelry or designer clothing, and
carry only the cash or credit cards that will be needed on each
outing.''
 &HT;    Obviously, much of this is common sense while traveling, but
given the heightened crime, it bears repeating. For the Bahamas,
the State Department says, ``Visitors should store
passport/identity documents, airline tickets, unused credit cards
and extra cash in hotel safes, and avoid wearing expensive jewelry,
particularly Rolex watches, which have been targeted increasingly
by criminals. Visitors should not travel alone on deserted areas of
beaches or poorly-lit areas at night.''
 &HT;    Even Singapore, which is generally considered one of the safest
places in the world, merits advice: ``Petty crimes such as
pickpocketing and purse or briefcase snatching occur in tourist
areas, hotels and at the airport.''
 &HT;    In the same reports, the government also looks at ``Aviation
Safety Oversight.'' Austria, for example, is in ``compliance with
international safety standards,'' as is most of Western Europe. But
Russia is a different story, and the Department of State says,
``Air travel within Russia can at times be unreliable.''
 &HT;    Travel Warnings are issued when the State Department decides,
``based on all relevant information, to recommend that Americans
avoid travel to a certain country.'' These countries currently
include Afghanistan, Albania, Algeria, Angola, Bosnia-Herzegovina,
Burundi, Cambodia, Central African Republic, Colombia, Congo,
Democratic Republic of Congo, Eritrea, Ethiopia, Fiji,
Guinea-Bissau, Iran, Iraq, Lebanon, Liberia, Libya, Montserrat,
Nigeria, Pakistan, Serbia-Montenegro, Sierra Leone, Somalia, Sudan,
Tajikistan and Yemen.
 &HT;    These countries are seen as potentially dangerous places for
Americans, and the State Department recommends that Americans avoid
going there.
 &HT;    The Fiji warning, issued on June 28, says, ``The Department of
State urges U.S. citizens to defer non-essential travel to Fiji
because of continued uncertainty and instability resulting from the
ongoing political crisis.''
 &HT;    It goes on to say that U.S. citizens who remain ``should
exercise a high level of caution, avoid demonstrations or public
meetings, maintain adequate stocks of food and water, and monitor
the local radio closely for breaking developments.''
 &HT;    That's hardly a recipe for a nice tropical vacation.
 &HT;    Finally, there are Public Announcements. These are issued for
``terrorist threats and other relatively short-term and/or
transnational conditions posing significant risks to the security
of American travelers.''
 &HT;    The public announcement for Indonesia and East Timor, issued on
June 1, says, ``all American citizens traveling in these areas
should be aware of their surroundings and use common sense to avoid
situations and locations that could be inherently dangerous.''
 &HT;    Travelers who want a broader perspective can consult the Web
sites of such governments as Great Britain (www.fco.gov.uk), Canada
(www.dfait-maeci.gc.ca) or Australia (www.dfat.gov.au/consular) and
make up their own mind about whether it's really safe to go.
 &HT;    For those without access to the Internet, the Department of
State's ``A Safe Trip Abroad'' and other travel-related documents
can be obtained from the Superintendent of Documents, U.S.
Government Printing Office, Washington, D.C. 20402; (202) 512-1800.
 ---- 
 c.2000 Everett Potter 
