<HEADER>
A7988 &Cx1f; tab-z
u t BC-FILM-FEST-FOR-SENIORS     07-10 1376
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-FEST-FOR-SENIORS-TRAVEL-MATURE-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MATURE TRAVELER: THE PALM SPRINGS FILM FESTIVAL  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by WAY TO GO! clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement. For purchase information,
see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 PLEASE NOTE: Optional trim indicators have been included to make
cutting this article for length an easier task.) 
 &HT;    
 (Color slide included.) 
 By ADELE MALOTT 
 Condensed from The Mature Traveler Newsletter 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    Hold it! Someone is rattling a candy wrapper. Another person is
digging around in a paper bag. Fifteen heads turn and indignantly
whisper a collective ``Sshhhh'' to the noisy movie-goers. All eyes
are on the Festival Theater's large screen, where the introductory
credits of the opening film are rolling. Only a handful of the
theater's 548 seats are empty.
 &HT;    Beverly Shaver of El Cerrito, Calif., is among the more than 500
film buffs in the darkened theater who have embarked on a glittery
five-day program sponsored by Elderhostel Inc. The program is
linked to the Palm Springs International Film Festival.
 &HT;    Half the movie-goers are Californians. The rest _ from the
Midwest and East _ realize that the place to be in January is
sun-blessed Southern California.
 &HT;    Elderhostel, which has been known to lodge its participants in
spartan dormitory accommodations, now houses its travelers to Palm
Springs in four-star inns and resorts with luxurious pools and
spas.
 &HT;    
 GOLDEN ADOLESCENCE  
 &HT;    Apart from the weather and celebrity-studded glamour of this
elite oasis in the desert, the lure of this particular film program
is the chance for seniors to recall their golden period of
adolescence. ``A time when it took a quarter for admission and 10
cents for popcorn to sit, bewitched, in a dark theater from noon
Saturdays until well after the street lights lit our way home,''
Shaver says.
 &HT;    Ardent devotees of the film fest will view two scheduled films
each morning and also will sample from among 184 full-length
features shown in the afternoons and evenings for general festival
audiences. Elderhostelers get a discounted price of $6 for the
additional films.
 &HT;    A number of directors, cinematographers, writers and actors will
be present at select screenings to comment on their films.
Discussions and critiquing sessions also will be held at the
hotels.
 &HT;    Elderhostel travelers play an important role in assessing the
films, says program director Donna McLain. Their reactions will
provide feedback to film makers as well as influence buying
decisions of distributors who have come shopping at the festival.
And more than 30 of the festival's films have been submitted to the
Motion Picture Academy as candidates for Oscars.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS HERE.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    The Festival Theater is brand new and has been reserved
exclusively for Elderhostel in the mornings. Every seat provides
full-screen views as well as deep cushioned comfort. The Dolby
Digital Sound System produces crisp audio so that even the
hearing-impaired catch every word.
 &HT;    Subtitles (about half of the festival's films are foreign) are
fully explanatory, clearly visible and remain long enough to be
read. Shaver says, ``The buzz among the hostelers reflects
incredulity at the technical quality of this film experience, and a
despondent sense that we will never again be satisfied with our
local theaters.''
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS HERE.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Background briefings for each film begin at 8:30 a.m., the first
showing is at 9 a.m.; the second, about 11:15. In between, McLain
and her 12 coordinators distribute tickets for afternoon and
evening films, operate a curbside lost-and-found area, answer
questions, take money and signups for sightseeing excursions and
replace meal tickets for those lost or mislaid.
 &HT;    The films selected by the festival's officials are of
outstanding quality. They are a feast of different accents that
bring to life the universal language of film.
 &HT;    The Elderhostel attendees are enchanted by plucky, lovable
72-year-old Mattie Rigbee (played by Ellen Burstyn) in ``Walking
Across Egypt,'' a world premiere, and empathize with her feisty
resistance to moving into a ``senior home.''
 &HT;    On the third day, as the hostelers settle down for ``Ikinai,''
there is a ripple of excitement as the Japanese production team
files down to their row of reserved seats. The film has the
audience alternately spellbound and dissolving into helpless
hilarity.
 &HT;    It portrays nine lugubrious men assembling on a tour bus in
Okinawa. All hopelessly in debt, they plan to die in an accidental
crash, enabling their dependents to claim large insurance payments.
 &HT;    At the last minute, though, a bouncy young woman climbs aboard
the bus using a tour voucher bought by her uncle who is too ill to
go. The ensuing action is quirky, unpredictable, wildly comic and
inspired. The production team earns a standing ovation.
 &HT;    The post-film discussion with the director illuminates some
uniquely Japanese values and customs which the movie-goers hadn't
understood.
 &HT;    Probably the most memorable film of the week _ also a world
premiere _ is ``Pink Pumpkins at Dawn,'' which deals insightfully
with gun-toting homicidal adolescents.
 &HT;    Made on a shoestring budget by a 29-year-old director and
starring little-known actors, the film traces the development and
fate of an appealing, but terribly damaged teen-ager.
 &HT;    The post-film discussion with director Rick Onorato is
emotional, high decibel and deadly serious. Afterward, clusters of
hostelers linger, reluctant to let go without reaching some kind of
closure on a topic of intense concern.
 &HT;    By the final day, most program participants have seen 10 to 12
films. But there are also those for whom the movies are close to a
secular religion _ marathoners who have managed to attend more than
20 films. The latter are glassy-eyed but euphoric.
 &HT;    More than half the group has taken time out for tours of the
mysterious desert and local museums. A few intrepid golfers sneaked
off to take advantage of a Thursday $10 green fee at the Bob Hope
Classic course.
 &HT;    Every boutique and trendy specialty shop lining Palm Canyon
Drive has been combed for treasures, and many Elderhostelers are
departing with bulging shopping bags.
 &HT;    
 WHAT'S INCLUDED  
 &HT;    The program described here cost $475 and included meals from
Sunday dinner through Friday breakfast, two films each morning, a
dinner dance and all the lectures and discussions.
 &HT;    The program will be offered again in January 2001 in conjunction
with the 122th International Film Festival. Hostelships covering
all but $75 of the fee are available for those on limited incomes.
For more information, write to Elderhostel, 75 Federal St., Boston,
Mass. 02210-1941; or call (877) 426-8056.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Readers are invited to submit questions and comments to Adele
Malott, c/o The New York Times Syndicate, 122 East 42nd St., 14th
Floor, New York, N.Y. 10168. Send Adele a postcard from your trip
with ideas, questions and information on the bargains you find for
seniors.
 &HT;    Questions may also be sent to Adele by electronic mail. The
address is MatureTrav(at)aol.com. (For (AT) use the symbol on your
keyboard.)
 &HT;    Adele Malott is the publisher of THE MATURE TRAVELER: Travel
Bonanzas for 49ers-Plus, a newsletter for mature travelers.
 &HT;    
