<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE NEWS AND NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Science Times) 
 By HENRY FOUNTAIN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   How Tomatoes Grow
</P>
<P>
   In the campy 1970s horror spoof ``Attack of the Killer
Tomatoes,'' the planet is threatened by giant mutated tomatoes
(much as the average garden is threatened by overgrown tomato
plants about this time of year). The good guys won in the film, of
course, but things might have been easier had they known about some
research at Cornell.
</P>
<P>
   Long before the age of the two-pound beefsteak, tomatoes were
much smaller. In fact, the precursor to the domesticated tomato
produced fruit that were less than a half-inch in diameter and
weighed a fraction of an ounce. But through domestication, tomatoes
grew in size.
</P>
<P>
   The Cornell researchers, reporting in the journal Science, have
uncovered the gene responsible for this evolutionary size growth.
</P>
<P>
   The area of the tomato plant chromosome responsible for this
growth had been identified previously, but the new research
pinpoints the specific gene. The finding may help in understanding
the function of genes that control quantitative traits _ that is,
ones that vary by degree, rather than all or nothing.
</P>
<P>
   In the film, the tomatoes are defeated through the playing of an
awful teen-age love ballad, which causes the killer fruit to shrink
(after which they are stomped into puree). The Cornell researchers
found a different way to get the same result: They took the
size-growth gene from a wild tomato plant and inserted it into a
domesticated one, and the new fruits were much smaller.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Deaths Investigated
</P>
<P>
   Veterinarians are still trying to figure out exactly what killed
10 Bengal tigers at a zoo in eastern India last week.
</P>
<P>
   The animals, seven of which were rare white tigers, died within
about 36 hours last Wednesday and Thursday at the Nandankanan zoo
near Bhubaneshwar, the capital of Orissa.
</P>
<P>
   Initial reports said the tigers died of trypanosomiasis, or
sleeping sickness, a parasitic infection. But there were
conflicting accounts that medication the animals received may have
been to blame. The Indian government established a team of six
veterinary experts to investigate.
</P>
<P>
   The zoo had housed 56 Bengal tigers, including 32 white ones,
the largest collection of white tigers in captivity (the white fur
is the result of a recessive gene).
</P>
<P>
   India has an estimated 3,500 wild tigers. The animals are
considered endangered, and India has set up a nationwide network of
preserves to help protect them. Still, 200 to 300 are lost yearly,
either from habitat lost to development or from poaching. Tiger
bones have long been used in traditional Chinese medicine to treat
rheumatism and arthritis, among other conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Butterfly Warning
</P>
<P>
   Travel alert for tourists motoring through the Sierra Nevada:
Make sure the windshield washer tank is full before heading up that
mountain pass.
</P>
<P>
   An ecologist at the University of California at Davis says that
the summer bug-smashing season could be particularly intense this
year and that the culprit is the California tortoise shell
butterfly.
</P>
<P>
   The insects, which have wings that are orange and black on top
and brown underneath, are due for an outbreak this year, according
to the scientist, Dr. Art Shapiro, who has studied butterfly
populations for nearly three decades.
</P>
<P>
   The tortoise shell migrates from coastal and foothill regions of
California into the higher Sierra, and by middle to late July new
offspring emerge and head even higher up in the hills, above the
tree line.
</P>
<P>
   According to Shapiro, large numbers of the insects were spotted
over the Memorial Day weekend, but the situation may get far worse
this month. This summer may be as bad as one in the early 1970s,
when millions of butterflies splattered onto car windshields and
piles of dead insects littered the roadsides. It was a pain for
motorists, but local birds had a field day.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
