<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 16:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7991 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-VITAL-SIGNS-NYT &LR;      07-10 1191
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-VITAL-SIGNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH AND FITNESS NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Science Times) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UPDATE: Vigilance Urged in Detecting Nile Virus
</P>
<P>
   West Nile virus, the mosquito-borne illness that for a year has
scared people in and around New York, is harder to detect than
generally realized, researchers say.
</P>
<P>
   A report in the current issue of Neurology urged greater
vigilance in diagnosing the disease, citing two patients who
exhibited unusual symptoms and so were found to have the disease
only after a delay.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, a 69-year-old Long Island man was given a
misdiagnosis of Guillain-Barre syndrome after entering a hospital
and reporting progressive weakness. West Nile was not diagnosed for
several weeks, and by then he was severely paralyzed and on a
respirator.
</P>
<P>
   In a second case, a healthy 15-year-old boy was hospitalized
after three days of fever, headache, vomiting and confusion, the
journal said. Although he did not show symptoms of West Nile,
spinal fluid and blood tests later showed he had the disease. The
boy eventually recovered.
</P>
<P>
   Although there is no specific treatment for the disease, doctors
who are aware that a patient has it can take measures to reduce its
harm.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, 7 people died of the disease in the New York region,
and 62 were made ill. This year, no cases have been confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, one of the authors, Dr. Charles Nichter of
Columbia and Bronx-Lebanon Hospital, said that alerting doctors to
the difficulties of diagnosing West Nile would not only help them
treat patients but would also let health officials get a better
handle on the extent of the outbreak.
</P>
<P>
   RISKS AND REMEDIES: The Kinder Side of a Scorpion Sting
</P>
<P>
   The only things scorpions inspire in most people are fear and a
desire to get out of the way of their poison-tipped stingers.
</P>
<P>
   But researchers at the University of California at Irvine say
they have developed a chemical that works like scorpion venom, but
instead of harming people, it may one day help doctors who perform
organ transplants or treat autoimmune diseases like lupus and
arthritis.
</P>
<P>
   The findings were reported last week in The Proceedings of the
National Academy of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
   The author of the study, Dr. Heike Wulff, a pharmaceutical
chemist, said in an interview that the synthetic chemical, TRAM-34,
had not been modeled on scorpion venom, but was inspired by
discoveries about how the poison affected the cells of scorpion
victims.
</P>
<P>
   The venom inactivates some cell functions, including the immune
response system, but is not usually fatal.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, the drugs, like cyclosporin, now given to suppress the
immune response in transplant and other patients also have
detrimental effects, like gastrointestinal and urinary tract
problems.
</P>
<P>
   TRAM-34 appears to be more adept at suppressing T-cells, part of
the body's arsenal against foreign objects, without hurting the
production of enzymes and other important cellular functions.
</P>
<P>
   Wulff said the findings were preliminary, and he could not
predict when the chemical might be tested on people.
</P>
<P>
   THERAPIES: An Old Antibiotic Generates New Hopes
</P>
<P>
   A common antibiotic that has been around for decades may help
people who suffer from Huntington's disease, a debilitating
hereditary ailment.
</P>
<P>
   Although researchers emphasized that much study remained to be
done, they said the drug, minocycline, a relative of tetracycline,
did much to slow the course of the disease in mice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a cure,'' cautioned Dr. Robert Friedlander of Brigham
and Women's Hospital, who described his findings in the current
issue of Nature Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   But use of the drug prolonged the lives of the mice by 14
percent, Friedlander said.
</P>
<P>
   Huntington's disease is characterized by involuntary movement of
the limbs and cognitive problems. Some 30,000 people have it, while
another 150,000 are at risk of inheriting it.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers believe the drug may help stop production of two
enzymes _ caspase -1 and -3 _ associated with Huntington's.
</P>
<P>
   Friedlander said he got the idea to try the antibiotic after
reading about Finnish scientists who used it to help people who had
had strokes, in which the caspase enzymes also appear to play a
role.
</P>
<P>
   He said his study suggested that minocycline could also help
with other diseases, including Alzheimer's.
</P>
<P>
   MENTAL HEALTH: Older and Better, With Firmer Footing
</P>
<P>
   You're not getting older, you're getting better. At least
psychologically.
</P>
<P>
   That's the argument put forth in a new study by a University of
California psychologist, who says most people become better
adjusted as they age. Which is not to say they are necessarily any
happier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really, there's not a direct connection between psychological
health and happiness,'' said the psychologist, Dr. Constance Jones,
the author of the report in the current issue of Psychology and
Aging. ``Psychological health, actually, is a more complicated
construct.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones, an associate professor at the university's Fresno campus,
came to her conclusions after studying evaluations of 236 people
done over a 50-year period. Participants were interviewed at ages
14, 18, 30, 40, 50 and 62.
</P>
<P>
   Interviewers gauged psychological health by trying to determine
if subjects were responsible and dependable, whether they were
productive and whether they had good relationships.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found from analyzing our three groups that psychological
health steadily increased from 30 years of age,'' the authors
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Jones said, this applies to the average person, with
the normal levels of anxiety and other neuroses. People who have
serious psychological problems will not necessarily see
improvements as they age.
</P>
<P>
   Jones also found that, contrary to general belief, psychological
health in adolescence was not shaky.
</P>
<P>
   And the more balanced the adolescent, she said, the better the
outlook for the adult.
</P>
<P>
   IN PRACTICE: For a Drop of Blood, Take It in the Ear
</P>
<P>
   The next time a doctor wants to take a blood sample from your
thumb, tell him to stick it in the ear.
</P>
<P>
   The idea here is not to encourage impoliteness but to reduce
pain. Reporting in The British Medical Journal, a group of doctors
in England said they had determined that taking a blood sample from
the ear lobe instead of the thumb was less painful.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors measuring glucose levels conducted an experiment on 60
patients. Thirty were lanced on the side of the thumb (a technique
adopted over the years when doctors realized that the area was less
sensitive than other digits), while the rest were lanced on the ear
lobe. The wound was then squeezed to force out a drop of blood.
</P>
<P>
   Patients were then asked to assess the pain using a standard
technique, and the results clearly favored the ear lobe, the study
said.
</P>
<P>
   The reason was unclear. The doctors theorized that the density
of pain receptors in the ear lobe might be lower than in the thumb.
But they also said further research was needed into the effect of
repeated ear lobe punctures on patients who require frequent
glucose screening.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
