<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-BRODY-HEALTH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERSONAL HEALTH: FOR LIFELONG GAINS, JUST ADD WATER 
</HEADLINE>
   EDITORS: This is the first of two columns on the body's need for
water. Next week: safety standards for the water supply.  
(The Science Times) 
 By JANE E. BRODY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   You've heard it by now a million times: drink at least eight
glasses of water a day. And, to be sure, water, as a beverage, has
become much more popular in recent years. Nearly everywhere you go,
you're likely to see someone carrying a water bottle. Even many
backpacks and some belt pouches are now equipped with holders for
water bottles.
</P>
<P>
   And maybe you are among the smart ones who know the value of
being well hydrated, especially, but not only, in warm weather and
when physically active.
</P>
<P>
   But at the same time, concerns about water safety have
skyrocketed. Sales of bottled water, which may or may not be safer
than what comes from your tap, are soaring. So are sales of home
water treatment systems, from inexpensive carafes and faucet
attachments that filter water through activated carbon to much more
costly countertop and under-the-sink units permanently connected to
the sink's water supply.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, if you are an avid water drinker, you are in the
minority. The average American consumes a bit more than half the
recommended amount of water each day and an equal amount of
dehydrating beverages, which include any drink with caffeine or
alcohol. In effect, these cancel each other out because for every
dehydrating drink consumed, an additional glass of water should be
drunk.
</P>
<P>
   Every system in your body, from brain to bowel, depends on
water. As IDEA, an international health and fitness organization,
has pointed out, ``Water regulates body temperature, transports
nutrients and oxygen, carries away waste, helps detoxify the
kidneys and liver, dissolves vitamins and minerals and cushions the
body from injury. Every day you lose on average 10 to 12 cups of
water that needs to be replaced to maintain your body's important
fluid balance.''
</P>
<P>
   The average adult body contains 40 to 50 quarts of water. Your
blood is 83 percent water; muscles are 75 percent water; the brain
is 74 percent water and even bone is 22 percent water.
</P>
<P>
   Water lubricates every joint in your body and keeps soft tissues
from sticking together. When you become dehydrated, your body and
brain become sluggish, your blood thickens and your heart is forced
to work overly hard.
</P>
<P>
   Water is essential to the workings of the digestive tract, from
the digestion and absorption of food and nutrients to the
elimination of digestive wastes. Fiber alone is not enough to aid
normal bowel function. Without adequate water, fiber, which
increases the water-holding capacity of the stool, can be
constipating.
</P>
<P>
   Water is also the body's air-conditioning system. When you
become too warm, the loss of water through the pores of the skin,
sweat glands and lungs prevents the body from building up too much
internal heat. Athletes who fail to drink enough during a
prolonged, grueling activity can reach potentially lethal body
temperatures, which is what happened to Alberto Salazar upon
winning the Boston Marathon in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   He required emergency administration of six liters of
intravenous fluids to replenish his loss of water and salts. Three
years earlier after a particularly challenging race, his body
temperature had soared to 107 degrees and he was administered last
rites. The loss of just 15 percent to 20 percent of the body's
water is fatal.
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to be aware of perspiration to be losing a great
deal of water. And even if you are completely inactive, your body
produces heat through metabolic processes that it may have to
dissipate through ``insensible'' perspiration.
</P>
<P>
   Skin cells, too, need water to look healthy. Yet millions of
appearance-conscious American women walk around like dried prunes,
afraid to drink water lest they become bloated or have to use the
bathroom. However, it is not water that is bloating but rather the
excess salts and carbohydrates consumed that hold water in the
body.
</P>
<P>
   As for bathrooms, I've learned not to be shy and have yet to be
denied the use of someone's or someplace's bathroom. At public
events when the line for the ladies' room has become unconscionably
long, I've been among women who've commandeered the men's room.
</P>
<P>
   Don't rely on thirst to tell you when to drink. By the time you
feel thirsty, you're already mildly dehydrated. Even mild
dehydration can impair physical and mental performance. Know the
symptoms of dehydration: headache, lethargy, dizziness, mental
fuzziness and loss of appetite. One of my tennis partners who
perspires heavily when he plays suffers a daylong headache if he
fails to drink enough. He has learned to drink 16 ounces of water
before playing, another 16 while playing, and 16 more afterward.
</P>
<P>
   There is no set amount of hydrating drinks a person should
consume. Eight eight-ounce glasses should be the minimum for the
average person. IDEA suggests that you calculate your basic fluid
need by dividing your weight in half to get the number of ounces to
consume each day. However, if you are physically active, if the
weather is hot and humid, if you are at a high altitude or if you
have a cold or fever, you're likely to need considerably more fluid
than the minimum.
</P>
<P>
   The American Dietetic Association recommends consuming at least
two cups of fluids two hours before physical exertion, followed by
another two cups of water about 15 to 20 minutes before your
activity and further drinks every 15 to 20 minutes during the
activity.
</P>
<P>
   As for the need for sports drinks that contain electrolytes
(sodium and other minerals that are lost through sweat), that
depends on the duration of your activity and how heavily you
perspire.
</P>
<P>
   A heavy workout lasting more than an hour, or exercise done in
extreme environmental conditions (like high-altitude hiking or
singles tennis at 90 degrees) may warrant a sports drink to replace
lost electrolytes as well as water. But because many of these
drinks are overly sweetened, which would delay water absorption,
they are best ``chased'' with an equal amount of water.
</P>
<P>
   Water _ plain, flavored, even lightly carbonated _ is the best
replacement fluid under most circumstances. Decaffeinated coffee,
tea or sugar-free soft drinks and diluted fruit juice will also
work. But any beverage that contains a fair amount of sugar or
salt, or any caffeine or alcohol-containing drink, is likely to
increase, not satisfy, your water need.
</P>
<P>
   Foods that are mostly water, like watermelon, which is 98
percent water, can also be a help as long as they are not too rich
in carbohydrates or salt.
</P>
<P>
   How can you get in all the water you need? By having water handy
wherever you happen to be. I'm a big fan of insulated, handled,
quart-sized cups, which I keep at my desk, in my car and wherever I
sit to read.
</P>
<P>
   I also pack a water bottle into my briefcase and carry one on my
belt pouch. On airplanes, where the atmosphere is as dry as the
Sahara, I book an aisle seat and drink eight ounces of water for
every hour in the air. And, the extra water helps to reduce jet lag
and the fatigue of travel.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-00 1608EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
