<DOCNO> NYT20000710.0197 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 16:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7997 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-PATIENTS-NYT &LR;      07-10 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-PATIENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A REMEDY NOT WORTH THE PAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Science Times) 
 By SANDEEP JAUHAR    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Do you want to keep eating, even if it means dying of pneumonia?
That was the question I posed to Mr. C. as he ate the rest of his
lunch. Yes, he replied without hesitation.
</P>
<P>
   A wizened 77-year-old with fiery eyes, he had been admitted to
the hospital short of breath. It wasn't clear why. He did not smoke
and had no cough. There was nothing suggesting asthma, pneumonia,
congestive heart failure or other common causes of shortness of
breath.
</P>
<P>
   His chest X-ray gave it away. Littering both lung bases were
opaque speckles that turned out to be barium, a metal that exposes
internal organs on X-rays.
</P>
<P>
   But why was it in his lungs? He had undergone a
barium-swallowing test a few months earlier when doctors suspected
he was aspirating food into his lungs. To rule out esophageal
narrowing, a common cause of swallowing difficulties, he swallowed
barium and had X-rays. It went down his lungs, and stayed there.
</P>
<P>
   His breathing trouble, I suspected, was caused by intermittent
aspiration of barium, food or whatever else. I told him he should
strictly regulate his diet, avoiding thin liquids that are easily
aspirated. He would have to eat sitting up, and in small bites. But
he said he had already found such a diet too burdensome.
</P>
<P>
   When a person swallows, both voluntary and involuntary
mechanisms ensure the food ends up in the stomach and not the
lungs. First, the tongue pushes the chewed-up food to the back of
the throat, where sensory receptors cause muscles in the pharynx to
contract. As the muscles contract, the epiglottis, a flap of
cartilage, flexes protectively into place over the larynx,
preventing food from entering the windpipe. The food is propelled
into the esophagus, where contractions usher it down to the lower
esophageal sphincter, which allows entry into the stomach.
</P>
<P>
   Several things can disrupt this complex reflex. Cancer or
blockages can narrow the opening so that food does not pass easily
to the stomach but backs up in the pharynx, where it can be
aspirated into the lungs. Muscular dystrophy, polymyositis and
scleroderma can paralyze the pharyngeal muscles.
</P>
<P>
   Neurological dysfunction, too, from nerve diseases like polio
and Lou Gehrig's disease, or brain disorders, like Alzheimer's
dementia or strokes, can disrupt the complex signaling.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for Mr. C.'s swallowing trouble wasn't obvious. A
brain scan revealed no strokes. There was no constriction. Nerve
studies were normal. In the end, we were faced with a condition we
could neither explain nor treat very effectively. The safest
treatment was to stop him from eating and insert a feeding tube.
But he so loved to eat _ it was one of the few remaining pleasures
in his life. He even raved about the hospital food. I presented the
option to him. He said he wasn't interested. It was too high a
price to pay, even for a longer life.
</P>
<P>
   Swallowing dysfunction is one of the most common problems in a
hospital, and it is becoming more prevalent as life spans increase.
This year, an editorial in The New England Journal of Medicine
criticized as futile and harmful the routine placement of feeding
tubes into patients with advanced dementia who stop eating. On the
other hand, it said, careful hand-feeding of such patients is an
act of nurturing.
</P>
<P>
   But feeding someone who cannot eat, by any means necessary, is
almost a reflexive act. New York state law says tube feeding can be
withheld only if there is clear and convincing evidence that the
patient never wants it. The default position is to feed.
</P>
<P>
   The paradigm is shifting, but the process will be slow. Families
will have to accept that feeding cannot sustain life in the face of
terminal diseases. And nursing homes, already short-staffed, will
have to figure out a way to hand-feed their patients efficiently.
</P>
<P>
   But what about the patients like Mr. C., dying not because they
are starving but because they are eating?
</P>
<P>
   I remember a 60-year-old lawyer I took care of last year. He was
admitted to the hospital because of severe emphysema. A protracted
stay in the intensive care unit left him dependent on a ventilator,
with a breathing tube. The tube (and his illness) had so impaired
his swallowing that he aspirated whenever he was fed. He constantly
got pneumonia.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone thought he needed a feeding tube, but his private
doctor, intelligent and experienced, insisted we feed him. ``You
must feed him,'' he reminded the nurses, ``if he is to learn to
eat.'' One day I told the doctor hand-feeding didn't seem to be
working. Wouldn't a feeding tube be useful to help the patient
regain his strength? ``I know this patient and who he was,'' the
doctor replied. ``A feeding tube will kill him.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
