<HEADER>
A8001 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN-COX     07-10 0664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Crackers got their name from Florida cow hunters
 &HT;    (''Dispatches from Dreamsville'' is an occasional series in
which readers share with Cox Newspapers senior writer Joe Murray
their memories of growing up in small-town America. Back then, or
at least the way we remember it, life was like a dream.)
 &HT;    By Colonel Rod Hendrick
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I am a Florida Cracker, a pedigreed Florida Cracker. I got
papers to prove it, a birth certificate. I was born down in the
bottom of the state, about 30 miles south of Miami, in Homestead. I
got lucky and was born right on my birthday, which makes it easy to
remember.
</P>
<P>
   Many folks in the South know what a Cracker is, but a lot of
them don't know how Crackers got their name.
</P>
<P>
   Right after the War Between the States, Southerners were in a
migration in the Deep South, especially with the carpetbaggers
forcing their will on the defeated Confederacy.
</P>
<P>
   Fleeing for their lives and leaving their homes behind them,
these are the pioneers who became the backbone and spine and spirit
of the great State of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Many came south carrying all their possessions in a mule-drawn
wagon _ axes and saws and things to make a life in a hostile
wilderness. There were no stores in many areas, so if you didn't
bring it with you, you just didn't have it. You made do with living
off the land.
</P>
<P>
   The reason Floridians are called Crackers, so the tales goes, is
that when the pioneers came to Florida they found thousands of wild
cattle roaming the free range. These cattle had been left by the
Spaniards and multiplied into a strong breed that could live off
the land. They belonged to whoever could round them up.
</P>
<P>
   Florida has now, and always has had, more cows than Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Think about it: In West Texas it takes 30 acres of desert to
support a cow; in Florida one acre of lush green grass in the
summer months will support half a dozen cows.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike Texas, Florida had palmetto thickets and dense woods.
Lariats would not work here as they would in the wide-open spaces
of the Texas range.
</P>
<P>
   What worked in the wilds of the Florida swamps were bullwhips.
Cow hunters could go into a palmetto thicket and drive a cow out
with a bullwhip.
</P>
<P>
   It was the sound of the cracking whip that led to the name of
Cracker for the cow hunters of Florida. This eventually spread to
all Floridians.
</P>
<P>
   With no railroads in those early days, it was necessary for
these pioneers to drive their cattle to market.
</P>
<P>
   One such market was in Fort Myers. They drove these cattle from
west of Lake Okeechobee to the west coast over a trail called the
Old Cracker Trail.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the Spanish-American War, the United Stated Army
had thousands of troops stationed there waiting to go to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   One of the young Army boys who was waiting to be shipped out
wrote to his family and advised his kin not to worry about him
anymore.
</P>
<P>
   He explained that the Army had been feeding him Florida beef
every day for the past few weeks and that the meat was so tough he
was now bulletproof.
</P>
<P>
   Only one out of every three people who live in Florida is a
native.
</P>
<P>
   Florida is growing faster than China, we like to say.
</P>
<P>
   So if you want to be a Cracker, just go get yourself a straw
hat, a mess of collard greens and slow down a notch or two.
</P>
<P>
   Get yourself a good rod and reel, and go fishing. Find some guy
named Gator or Skeeter and buy him a cold drink.
</P>
<P>
   You will be well on your way to becoming Crackerfied.
</P>
<P>
   Rod Hendrick, who goes by the honorary title of colonel, is a
writer, humorist and storytelling comedian living in Hernando, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   If you have a story to share, send it to ``Dispatches from
Dreamsville,'' c/o Joe Murray, Cox Newspapers, P.O. Box 151108,
Lufkin, Texas, 75915; email, jmurray(at)txucom.net. If your article
is used, you will receive $25.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
