<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release on Sunday, July 16) 
 By PAUL FREIREICH    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Getting to Stromboli
</P>
<P>
   Q. After several tantalizing glimpses of Stromboli from cruise
ships, I at last got there in 1998. The trip, however, was arduous,
involving planes, train and hydrofoil. Is there a less grueling way
now? Jan E. Adlmann, Santa Fe, N.M.
</P>
<P>
   A. The island of Stromboli, about 40 miles north of Sicily, has
been in continuous eruption for 2,000 to 2,500 years _ and even
more, according to some volcanologists. Over the course of each
hour, there are several small gas explosions of glowing lava
fragments. But violent eruptions are rare; the most recent of note
was in 1996 when four people were hurt.
</P>
<P>
   To reach Stromboli from the United States, you still have to fly
to Rome first. If you want to avoid multiple stops and to go to
Stromboli without stopping at the other Lipari Islands first, fly
to Naples or Reggio di Calabria and then take a boat.
</P>
<P>
   The Siremar ferry line departs from Naples for Stromboli daily
except Wednesday at 9 p.m. and arrives as a new day is dawning, at
5 a.m. Ticket prices range from $33.40 for unreserved deck space to
$56.50 for reserved space in an enclosed lounge-like area, at 2,034
lire to the dollar. Among the sources for a ticket is the Ontano
agency in Naples, (39-081) 580 0340, fax (39-081) 580 0341. By
hydrofoil, it's faster _ four hours _ but perhaps not so romantic.
Departures are at 8:30 a.m. and 2:30 p.m. and the fare is $51.65.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the hydrofoils from Reggio di Calabria, which is across
the Strait of Messina from Sicily, go directly to Stromboli. They
leave at 7, 7:25, 8:55 and 10:45 a.m. and take about two hours. The
fare is $17.70.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Information on hydrofoil service, which is operated by SNAV, can
be found on the Web at www.snavali &QC; .com, but may require a measure
of competence in Italian (for starters, click on ``ali-scafi,''
which means hydrofoils). Or try (39-081) 761-2348, fax (39-081)
761-2141. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To refresh your memory of Stromboli, take a look at these rich
resources, which include video clips with audio: stromboli.net and
volcano.und.nodak.edu.
</P>
<P>
   Archery in London
</P>
<P>
   Q. My 7-year-old nephew will accompany us to central London, and
he likes archery. Are there schools or ranges there where he can
practice and learn? _ Ruth A. Unterberg, New York, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   A. Though many clubs do not accept children younger than 12,
archery instruction for a 7-year-old is not out of the question in
the view of some instructors. But the problem may be having to go
to the outskirts of London to find such instruction.
</P>
<P>
   Here are two possibilities for experienced instructors who have
taught adults and children. The charge includes a bow, arrows, a
tab (which protects the fingers) and a bracer (which protects the
forearm of the hand holding the bow).
</P>
<P>
   Falcon Junior Archery Club, Royal Arsenal Sport and Recreation
Association, Church Manor Way, Abbeywood, London SE2 0EZ. The
club's chairman and senior coach, Edward Hart, teaches once a week
for two to three hours. After three sessions students are generally
``fairly consistent, but not necessarily proficient,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lessons are given at a field that is a drive of 30 to 40 minutes
from central London. The charge for private instruction is a total
of $36, at 66 pence to the dollar, said Hart, who has taught
archers in county-level competitions. He can be reached at (44-208)
311 3416.
</P>
<P>
   At the Falcon Junior Club, students start out with a solid
fiberglass training bow (like an American longbow) or a recurve
bow, similar to that used in Olympic events.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Bradford is an instructor and coach based at 62 Hook Rise
North, Tolworth, Surrey KT6 7JY; (44-208) 397 2603; e-mail
ted(at)theglade.co.uk. With children up to the age of 10 or 11, he
said, ``I don't insist on perfect application until they start
asking questions.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradford, who has taught archers competing in international
competitions, said that lessons would not exceed an hour and that a
7-year-old would probably start with a fiberglass bow. Private
instruction for a 7-year-old, given at an outdoor site, is roughly
$6 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   For general information about archery in Britain, call the Grand
National Archery Society at (44-195) 267 7888 or visit
www.gnas.org.
</P>
<P>
   By Rail in Provence
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am planning to spend some time this September in the south
of France, particularly Nice. I have read about a narrow gauge
railroad from Nice north through the Var Valley. The train is
called Chemin de Fer de Provence. Can you provide information,
including schedule and stops? _ G.G., Tiburon, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   A. The railroad runs 93 miles between Nice, on the Riviera, and
Digne-les-Bain. Of special interest is a 12-mile stretch between
Puget-Theniers and Annot. During the warmer months, one can take an
hourlong ride aboard the Train des Pignes using equipment built
between 1888 and 1912.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The regular train between Nice and Digne-les-Bain operates four
times a day in each direction and is well suited for travelers who
are not in a hurry: It takes three hours and makes 21 stops. From
Nice, departures are at 6:42 and 9 a.m. and at 12:43, 5 and 6:35
p.m. From Digne-les-Bain, departures are at 7 and 10:33 a.m. and at
1:58 and 5:25 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   As its name suggests, Digne-les-Bain is a spa. Every August, the
town celebrates the lavender for which towns in the region are
known. From the fourth to the eighth, Digne-les-Bain stages the
Corso de la Lavande, a parade of floats saluting lavender, with
musical performances and fireworks. From the 17th to the 22nd, it's
the Journees Lavande, which features music as well as ethnic food.
Information: (33-4) 92.36.62.62.
</P>
<P>
   The town is also the home of the cathedrals of St.-Jerome and
Notre-Dame du Bourg and of a collection of Tibetan mementoes at the
Fondation Alexandra David-Neel (27, avenue Marechal Juin). Tours
there run 90 minutes and are free.
</P>
<P>
   Excursions aboard old train equipment run on Sundays, starting
in mid-May. The trips remaining this season are next Sunday as well
as on Aug. 6, 13, 20 and 27, Sept. 10, 17 and 24 and Oct. 8, 15 and
22.
</P>
<P>
   Diesel trains leave Nice at 9:10 a.m., arriving at
Puget-Theniers at 10:45. Ten minutes later a steam locomotive takes
over for the ride to Annot, a small town with winding lanes,
arcades and a Romanesque church. The train leaves for Nice at 3:30
and arrives at 6:30. For the entire run, the fare is $26, at 7
francs to the dollar; for just the steam engine part, it's $13.
Train information: (33-4) 97.03.80.87.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
