<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MENTION-GAME-1,200&AMP;ADD-NEWHOUSE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNREALITY SHOW: IN 2000 VEEPSTAKES, TO BE MENTIONED IS THE GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (Attention editors: For information about purchasing this article
as a ``separate-buy,'' contact Debra Weydert of the New York Times
Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697; e-mail:
weyded(at)nytimes.com.)
 (ART ADV: With illustration depicting vice-presidential sweepstakes
as a card game, moving as a photo (NNS1). 
 By MILES BENSON   
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It's time to play the mentioning game, otherwise
known as: Who wants to be vice president?
</P>
<P>
   The list of potential candidates named in news reports lengthens
daily, it seems.
</P>
<P>
   To be ``mentioned'' as a possible running mate for Al Gore or
George W. Bush is a badge of distinction, a boost for the careers
of the politically ambitious, even those who haven't the remotest
chance of actually being chosen as second banana.
</P>
<P>
   So how come they get mentioned anyway?
</P>
<P>
   Ahhh, that's what makes it a game _ one that can be played right
up to the national conventions of the two major parties.
Presidential candidates usually wait until then to name their
hand-picked running mates, but that doesn't deter the mentioners in
politics and the press.
</P>
<P>
   ``With five 24-hour-a-day cable rumor-mongering services, there
are more `mentioners' than ever,'' said Stephen Hess, a political
analyst at the Brookings Institution. ``So it ain't difficult to
get your name on that circuit.''
</P>
<P>
   A search of the electronic archiving service Lexis-Nexis over a
recent 60-day period shows just how crowded the candidate field has
become.
</P>
<P>
   If you count the number of mentions in newspapers, newsmagazines
or on television, the clear front-runner to be Al Gore's Democratic
running mate is former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey, whom Gore
chewed up in the primaries. Bradley turns up 742 times.
</P>
<P>
   Next is Energy Secretary Bill Richardson of New Mexico, who
would be the first Hispanic on a major party's national ticket. He
has 642 mentions. Unfortunately for Richardson, most of the recent
stories also mentioned that his chances virtually vanished in the
scandal over nuclear secrets lost in his department under his
watch.
</P>
<P>
   On the Republican side, the most mentioned man is Arizona Sen.
John McCain,who gave Bush a scare in the primaries and has been the
subject of vice presidential speculation in more than 1,000
stories.
</P>
<P>
   First runner-up is Pennsylvania Gov. Tom Ridge, a dazzling
campaigner with a war record, and a Catholic, which political
analysts consider a plus. But most of the stories also mention that
Ridge is pro-choice, which could send Bush's pro-life supporters
screaming from the convention.
</P>
<P>
   The same problem poses an obstacle for New Jersey Gov. Christie
Todd Whitman, with 17 mentions. The leading name among Republican
women is Elizabeth Dole, mentioned in 198 stories as a Bush running
mate.
</P>
<P>
   Jesse Ventura, the Reform Party governor of Minnesota, a former
pro wrestler, has been mentioned 338 times as a possible choice _
to run with Gore or Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Some names emerge because of polls taken to determine who might
be the most help to the presidential candidate in certain states.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press recently published a poll about vice
presidential running mates for both Bush and Gore by Intersurvey, a
Menlo Park, Calif., research firm. The poll surveyed 6,788 adults
chosen at random. It suggested that Bush, running with retired Gen.
Colin Powell, would be elected president with an average of 62
percent of the vote over Gore teamed with any of a half-dozen
possible running mates. Teamed with McCain, Bush would win with 58
percent of the vote. The only running mate who would lift Gore to
victory, according to the poll, was Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   These findings are studied by political analysts and
journalists, who mention them, thereby adding them to the
background din of speculation.
</P>
<P>
   There are rules, of a sort.
</P>
<P>
   It's necessary to have some credentials to be among the
mentioned. ``You've got to be somebody who holds the type of
position putting you in the on-deck circle,'' Hess said.
</P>
<P>
   This would include members of the Senate, well-known members of
the House of Representatives, Cabinet officers, governors and
``assorted others of that ilk, all of whom have friends or shills,
usually called press secretaries, who have friends in the media,''
Hess said. ``Your folks sort of spread the word of why you'd make
sense. Before you know it, they're throwing your name back and
forth on television and in the papers.''
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally names are floated as trial balloons by the
presidential candidates' staffs. Sometimes genuine leaks occur,
revealing that someone has been contacted by the person the
presidential candidate has charged with the vice presidential
talent hunt _ Warren Christopher, the former secretary of state,
for Gore, and Richard Cheney, the former defense secretary, for
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   More often it works like this, said Frank Luntz, a Republican
pollster and senior analyst for ``YRock.com.,'' a political Web
site:
</P>
<P>
   ``The potential candidate asks his political adviser to call his
favorite reporter to mention that he heard the candidate's name
referred to either over food or drinks at a gathering of political
operatives for the presidential campaign. It's as convoluted as
Tinkers to Evers to Chance, but just as effective. What's cool
about this is that everyone's in on it, but it's how this whole
process starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Or, if you are the presidential candidate and you have a good
friend for whom you want to provide publicity, you will mention
this person's name. It is a premium plum in politics to be
mentioned by Al Gore. To come off his lips is worth a front page
story and a 6 p.m. TV feature.''
</P>
<P>
   Presidential candidates themselves drop hints about their lists
all the time.
</P>
<P>
   Bush recently said of New Jersey's Whitman: ``She's on the
list.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about that on the ABC News program ``Face the Nation'' on
a recent Sunday, Whitman responded with the modest aplomb of an
accomplished political player.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, that's very nice of him and I think that's reflective of
all the good things that have been happening here in the state of
New Jersey and if he were to offer, I'd be crazy not to consider it
very seriously, but I'm not counting on it.''
</P>
<P>
   On the same Sunday morning, different channel, Florida Sen. Bob
Graham was enjoying mention on another TV show, NBC's ``Meet the
Press,'' because a poll showed Gore would rise to contention in
that important state if Graham were his running mate, and because
it is known that Christopher has been in touch with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very flattering to be considered for such a high
position,'' Graham said. ``I have a job. I'm very appreciative that
the people of Florida have given me this opportunity to represent
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes a name is floated because journalists ask various
constituent groups whom they want and don't want, said David Keene,
a veteran political operative who heads the American Conservative
Union.
</P>
<P>
   ``But nobody really has a clue how the choice will be made,''
Keene said.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Sabato, a University of Virginia political scientist who
closely monitors presidential politics, said there are really two
processes at work in each party's veepstakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``One is pure speculation engaged in by reporters and people
like me who don't have a clue,'' Sabato said, echoing Keene. ``We
are simply looking at the map and trying to identify logical
candidates who would help a nominee.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other process is the one that really matters, the one
engaged in by the presidential candidate and his senior staff. It's
like they say, the people who know aren't talking and people who
are talking don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   One interesting historical fact, Sabato said, is how often
presidential candidates blunder when they choose a running mate who
they believe will help them win the election.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Quayle, Geraldine Ferraro, Spiro Agnew, Thomas Eagleton and
William Miller were ``major goofs,'' Sabato said.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle, an Indiana senator when he was chosen by George W.
Bush's father, brought no visible electoral strength to the ticket
but generated controversy over whether family connections eased his
entry into the National Guard, enabling him to avoid going to
Vietnam. Later he misspelled ``potato'' on national television,
becoming an object of laughter and ridicule.
</P>
<P>
   Walter Mondale, the Democratic presidential candidate in 1984,
chose Rep. Geraldine Ferraro of New York as his running mate. But
the first woman to grace a major party's national ticket became a
drag on the ticket when questions were raised about her husband's
business dealings.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Nixon's vice president, Spiro Agnew, resigned in
disgrace after it became known that he had accepted bribes as
governor of Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   George McGovern, the Democratic presidential nominee in 1972,
chose Sen. Thomas Eagleton of Missouri, then hastily replaced him
when it was revealed that Eagleton had been treated for depression
with shock therapy.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, a little known congressman from New York, was Barry
Goldwater's choice for vice president in 1964, contributing nothing
to offset Goldwater's landslide defeat by Lyndon Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``And there were many more,'' Sabato said. ``In fact, you could
make the case that presidential candidates made serious errors at
least one out of every four times they picked vice presidential
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``So if the candidates make illogical choices one out of four
times, then how could anyone be certain that a logical process will
help them guess the identity of the eventual nominee?''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the game goes on.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a partial list of other Republicans and how many times
they have were mentioned in the 60-day Lexis-Nexis search as
potential running mates for Bush: Ret. Gen Colin Powell, 482; Sen.
Fred Thompson of Tennessee, 222; Michigan Gov. John Engler, 184;
Florida Sen. Connie Mack, 160; House Budget Committee Chairman John
Kasich of Ohio, 153; Oklahoma Gov. Frank Keating, 127; former Sen.
John Danforth, 85; former Education Secretary William Bennett, 36;
California Rep. Chris Cox, 23.
</P>
<P>
   Some other Democrats mentioned with regularity were Nebraska
Sen. Bob Kerrey, 260; California Gov. Gray Davis, 260; California
Sen. Dianne Feinstein, 254; Indiana Sen. Evan Bayh, 189; Illinois
Sen. Richard Durbin, 137; former Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin,
127; HUD Secretary Andrew Cuomo, 122; Massachusetts Sen. John
Kerry, 120; former Maine Sen. George Mitchell, 76; Maryland Lt.
Gov. Kathleen Kennedy Townsend, 65; and Connecticut Sen. Joseph
Lieberman, 50.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
