<DOCNO> NYT20000710.0202 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 16:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8011 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-GREAT-LAKES-ART-9     07-10 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-GREAT-LAKES-ART-960(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE GREAT LAKES, AN ENDLESS BATTLE AGAINST MARINE INVADERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV:  Graphic  is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(The Science Times) 
 By DAVID BINDER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALPENA, Mich. _ Engaged in daily combat on many fronts are
swarms of invader species that number in the millions throughout
the Great Lakes _ among them the Eurasian ruffe, the round goby,
the zebra mussel and the sea lamprey _ and hundreds of
single-minded biologists and wildlife managers who are trying to
destroy them.
</P>
<P>
   Well behind the battle fronts are commanders, often with
conflicting agendas, from dozens of local, regional and federal
agencies, American and Canadian, and their constituents _ big
shippers and industries, sport and commercial fisherman,
environmentalists and the general public.
</P>
<P>
   At stake is the ecological future of the Great Lakes,
collectively the world's largest body of fresh water. Under the
impact of wave after wave of alien invasions, most brought in the
ballast tanks of freighters arriving from across the Atlantic, the
lakes are ``really in turmoil,'' said David Jude, a research
scientist at the University of Michigan. The alien incursions are
killing off native species and, in some areas, changing the very
face of the lakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably 90 percent of the animals present in Lake Erie were
not there 15 years ago,'' said Dr. Hugh MacIsaac, a professor of
ecology at the University of Windsor, Ontario, and the same could
be said of most of the other Great Lakes.
</P>
<P>
   As of 1997, Canada and the United States had spent $30 million
on research into alien species, said Tracy Mehan, director of the
Michigan Office of the Great Lakes. And since 1970, $300 million
has been spent on actual operations aimed at eradicating a single
species, lampreys.
</P>
<P>
   But all this money has been like artillery barrages against a
well-entrenched enemy that constantly brings in reinforcements.
Just as scientists seem to gain control of one invader, a new alien
species appears.
</P>
<P>
   The newest threat is the spiny water flea, Bythotrephes
cederstroemi, which clogs anglers' fishing lines. reels and nets
with their gooey bodies hooked together in crystalline masses. But
it is only one of a long line of invaders.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists believe the biggest threat, sea lampreys (Petromyzon
marinus), first reached the western lakes as early as the 1920s by
way of the Welland Canal, which connects the Erie Canal _ and
beyond it the Hudson River _ with Lake Erie. Still earlier, in the
1820s, the European weed purple loosestrife (Lythrum salicaria)
arrived, infesting and corrupting wetlands.
</P>
<P>
   By the time many of the alien species arrived, human settlement
had already severely damaged the delicately balanced ecosystems of
the inland lakes, which are only 10,000 years old. People
overfished, dammed up many of the lakes' 5,747 tributaries, drained
wetlands and polluted the water with industrial waste and sewage.
</P>
<P>
   But all this was nothing compared with the damage wrought by the
sudden profusion of alien species unintentionally imported by ships
from overseas. By 1997 the list of so-called exotics _ ranging from
bacteria to plants, fleas to fish _ numbered 139. Now it is up to
145.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a war, started by man,'' Jude said. ``And we're losing
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Imported species can proliferate with remarkable speed.
</P>
<P>
   In April 1990, Jude discovered a strange fish during a study,
financed by the Michigan Department of Natural Resources, at the
intake tube of a Detroit Edison power plant on the St. Clair River,
an important link between Lake Erie and Lake Huron. A university
colleague identified it as a round goby (Neogobius melanostomus),
an aggressive bottom dweller originating in the Caspian, Black and
Azov Seas that can spawn up to five times a year.
</P>
<P>
   Within four years round gobies and their cousins, the tubenose
gobies(Proterorhinus marmoratus), had spread to Lake Huron and Lake
Michigan and into streams.
</P>
<P>
   To amuse colleagues, Jude composed an 11-verse ballad, ``The
Galloping Goby Blues,'' portraying the goby as the fish that
swallowed the Great Lakes. He sang a sample:
</P>
<P>
   Round gobies now rule among the rocks
</P>
<P>
   They can live out of water, they'll bite you in your socks
</P>
<P>
   And if we don't stop them soon, there'll only be bad news
</P>
<P>
   I've got those egg-suckin', fish- chewin', galloping goby blues.
</P>
<P>
   Although Jude still follows the goby, after a recent bid for
more research money was rejected, he turned his attention to lake
trout, the main predator of the lakes and the native species most
endangered by sea lampreys.
</P>
<P>
   The proliferation of the goby and other alien species is caused
mainly by bilge water discharges from the ocean-going ships that
have been entering the Great Lakes through the St. Lawrence Seaway
for the last 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   To combat the problem, the federal government adopted a law in
1993 requiring overseas shippers to exchange their ballast water in
the Atlantic, before entering the Great Lakes. Canada has similar,
but voluntary, guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   The ballast exchange, however, leaves residual alien species
unscathed in the 100 to 200 tons of unpumpable sludge at the bottom
of ballast tanks of the 500 or so foreign vessels that traverse the
lakes annually.
</P>
<P>
   Industry officials oppose proposals that would require shippers
to treat bilge with ultraviolet rays, heat, chemicals or biocides
like glutaraldehyde. A coalition of 72 port representatives,
shippers, trade unions and other interested groups has formed to
fight ballast-sterilization legislation submitted in January by a
Michigan state senator, Ken Sikkema.
</P>
<P>
   On a broader level, the Great Lakes Fisheries Commission,
established by the United States and Canada in 1955, sent letters
in April to Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and Lloyd
Axworthy, Canada's minister of foreign affairs, saying that the
ballast water exchange programs ``need to be revised or replaced.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   About the same time, working in the combat zone _ the mouth of
the Thunder Bay River, which flows through the shipping port of
Alpena to Lake Huron _ Anjanette Hintz, a federal Fish and Wildlife
Service worker, was trawling in a small boat for exotic species.
She had her sights sets on another nuisance fish, the perchlike
Eurasian ruffe (Gymnocephalus Cernuus).
</P>
<P>
   In five passes that consumed the better part of a day, Hintz
dragged up only one ruffe, a year-old female that was about to
spawn. But dredged up from 20 feet below _ along with submerged
logs, clusters of zebra mussels, a beer can, a fat carp, a
bluegill, a bullhead, some trout perch and other minnows _ were
three round gobies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't really know where the ruffe goes in spring,'' she
explained. ``They like the Thunder Bay because it is deep and dark.
We are trying to develop a small enough acoustic sensor to track
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Hintz has been tracking the exotics since she started with the
service here in 1994. The first ruffe arrived the next year, and
last summer she caught 400 of them with trawl nets and
electroshocking.
</P>
<P>
   As with the gobies, the ruffe originated in the Black and
Caspian Seas. They were first detected in Duluth Harbor in 1986 and
have since spread through other Great Lakes. The ruffe was
designated an aquatic nuisance species by the federal government in
1992.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Busiahn, who works for the wildlife service in Ashland,
Wis., called the explosively growing ruffe population ``a serious
threat to North American fishery resources.'' The fish compete with
native yellow perch and walleyed pike, and consume the eggs of the
commercially important whitefish, among other species.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, gobies feed voraciously and pose a threat to native
species by competing for food, including fish eggs and zooplankton.
(The only plus attributed to gobies is that they also eat zebra
mussels.)
</P>
<P>
   Scientists have concluded that some gobies have spread by
anglers who acquired them at one site for bait and then dumped the
excess overboard in other waters.
</P>
<P>
   What to do?
</P>
<P>
   So far the biologists have succeeded only in intensive
surveillance of the latest invaders and in spreading the word among
sports fishermen and commercial bait dealers to kill them and
report them.
</P>
<P>
   There are proposals to design nesting shelters attractive to the
invaders where they and their offspring could be trapped and
destroyed; to create barriers to migration; to foster likely
predators like the largemouth bass; and to spread a relatively
benign but costly compound proven successful in controlling sea
lampreys, TFM, to destroy ruffe and gobies. There have been strong
objections to some of these by environmental groups.
</P>
<P>
   The most promising technology for combatting invaders may lie in
the realm of pheromones, the odors that the fish generate,
especially in turbid waters, to attract sex partners, to warn of
danger or, like canines, to mark hospitable territory.
</P>
<P>
   One scientist who has pioneered pheromone research in fish is
Dr. Peter Sorensen of the University of Minnesota. In 1995, he and
his associates succeeded in identifying the migratory pheromone of
the sea lamprey, which is so efficient at following chemical traces
through the water that Sorensen once described it as ``a swimming
nose.''
</P>
<P>
   The elusive scent consisted of two bile acids exuded from the
gall bladder in feces. Sea lampreys mark favored spawning streams
with this substance, allowing them to locate the streams at a great
distance from open waters. Three years later, in 1998, Sorensen and
his team isolated the sex pheromone in the urine of male lampreys.
</P>
<P>
   Sorensen said he and his colleagues were also ``fairly far
along'' in learning how to calibrate pheromone densities from
stream to stream with what he called ``enzyme immunoassays.'' This
may make it possible one day to neutralize popular spawning sites,
or to attract vast numbers of males to selected ``manageable''
streams where they can be trapped and sterilized. This would
provide scientists the equivalent of ``shooting fish in a barrel,''
Sorensen said.
</P>
<P>
   The principal measures against lampreys, short of catching and
eating them (Henry I of England died in 1135 after consuming some),
have included applying lampricides to larval habitats, trapping
them at barriers and releasing sterilized males at spawning time in
the spring.
</P>
<P>
   This spring, the wildlife service trapped over 2,400 lampreys at
a $240,000 barrier equipped with electrodes on the Ocqueoc River
near here _ one of 19 barriers on American and Canadian streams. An
estimated 56 percent of the spawning run is trapped. Sterilized
with the chemical compound bisazir, males compete successfully for
females but are unable to fertilize them.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Fishery Commission, lampreys destroy lake
trout, whitefish and chub by attaching themselves to their bodies,
rasping holes and sucking the life out of them. Fishermen once
harvested 15 million pounds of trout annually from the lakes. Since
1973 the much smaller harvest has depended on restocked trout _ 2.6
million a year by Michigan at a cost of $3 million.
</P>
<P>
   There have been successes against predators. Forty years ago,
after lampreys and overfishing caused the collapse of the predator
lake trout, the population of another invader, the herringlike
alewives, surged. Millions of them started washing up dead on the
beaches of Lake Michigan. The huge die-off during spring spawning
season was attributed to ``winter thermal stress, high abundance
and shortage of food'' for the alewives, said Gavin Christie of the
Fishery Commission.
</P>
<P>
   But now, restocked trout, together with large stocks of chinook
and coho salmon introduced for sport fishing, have ``pushed
alewives just about up against the wall in Lake Huron,'' said James
Johnson of the Michigan Department of Resources station.
</P>
<P>
   The restocked trout, however, seldom reproduce, Johnson said,
and they remain vulnerable to lampreys, which account for 50
percent of lake trout mortality in Huron.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to go after the lamprey, Roger Bergstedt, head of
the U.S. Geological Survey's biological research station at Hammond
Bay, Mich., has spent eight years mapping 12,000 lamprey larval
habitats in St. Mary's River, which links Lake Superior to Lake
Huron. The work was part of an American-Canadian program to put
lampricides in the roughly 300 tributary streams where the lampreys
spawn.
</P>
<P>
   Applying lampricides to 30 hot spots, Bergstedt reduced the
population to about 10 percent of its peak, he believes. Last year
$4.5 million was spent on lampricide.
</P>
<P>
   Calling the effort ``highly successful,'' Bergstedt said the
future focus would be on ``new weapons in this war to reduce
reliance on chemical control, like pheromones.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
