<SLUG> BC-JOHNSON-RACES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICHAEL JOHNSON, AT 32, STILL THE MAN TO BEAT
</HEADLINE>
 (Repeating for all needing) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On a track in South Africa in the middle of March, Michael
Johnson ran the 200 meters in 19.71 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Too fast, the Baylor ex assessed. And in short order, he headed
home, cancelling his race appearances, even the one in Waco at the
meet named in hishonor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in South Africa for three weeks,'' Johnson explained.
``I went there to see where I was, and I found out there that I was
way ahead of where I needed to be. So there was no need to compete
at that point.''
</P>
<P>
   Experience remains the best teacher, and Johnson has been a
straight-A student. At the age of 32, therefore, he headed home in
April not to race, but to become a new father and to do the things
that he knew from experience that he must do.
</P>
<P>
   His new son was born on May 6. The U.S. Olympic Track and Field
Trials begin in Sacramento, Calif., on Friday. The Sydney Olympics
open in less than 10 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Johnson, again, has the clock on his side.
</P>
<P>
   Four years older, four years wiser, Johnson is still the man to
beat in the Olympic 200 and 400 meters.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, it is different than it was in 1996. Going into those
Olympic Trials, Johnson was toying with history. Now, he heads for
Sacramento not only owning gold medals in both events but also the
world records.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be easier from a mental standpoint,'' he said. ``I've
done it before. It's familiar territory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether I can do it again physically _ I think I can _ that
will be the mystery this time. I'm four years older. But I look at
it as I've got four more years of experience.''
</P>
<P>
   His golden reign has brought him wealth and fame. He signed a
$12-million endorsement deal with Nike after the Atlanta Games. In
October of 1998, he married Kerry Doyen. In May, their first child,
Sebastian, was born.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's the exact same thing as '96,'' Johnson argued. ``It's
the Olympic Games. There's nothing better. You're going to face the
best competitors at their best in an Olympic year. Nobody's giving
you anything. That's the motivation. That's the challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, but Johnson's primary antagonist has already been
tagged and identified by a curious public. Maurice Greene of Kansas
City, Kan., holds the world record (9.79) in the 100-meter dash and
won the 200 at last year's world championships.
</P>
<P>
   The two have spent the summer running in measured circles. At
the Prefontaine Classic in Eugene, Ore., last month, Greene ran the
200. Johnson opted for the 400. Greene has barked that he thinks
Johnson is ducking him, a charge at which His Goldenness scoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Once, Johnson himself was the new gun in town. Carl Lewis
eventually gave Michael his grudging due.
</P>
<P>
   Now Johnson is the sprints' old gunslinger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yep, that's me,'' he said, smiling at the thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's great. That's the thing I'm most proud of. There's
always someone new, but I'm always right here. I'm always the guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've handled it the same way, and I'm going to continue
handling it the same way. I'm going to keep my mouth shut and let
my legs do the talking.''
</P>
<P>
   If Greene and Johnson meet, it figures to be in the finals of
the Olympic Trials' 200 on Sunday, July 23 _ Greene's 26th
birthday.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as the matchup, no, I don't get as excited as the fans
do,'' Johnson said, ``because I know more than the fans do. I know
that Maurice has never beaten Ato Boldon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't look at it like the fans look at it. I've got to look
at what Michael's got to go out there and do. Maurice Greene is the
world record holder in the 100, and off pure speculation he might
be the guy who can beat Michael Johnson. But that's what the fans
are looking at.''
</P>
<P>
   What Johnson knows _ and what Greene melted under at the '96
trials _ are the pressures that the next two weeks will hold. It's
been said that U.S. track and field has the fairest unjust system
of selecting an Olympic team in the world.
</P>
<P>
   In some events, notably in the sprints, the trials talent pool
is deep. It takes a patient intensity just to reach the finals.
Only the three fastest _ and often the strongest _ survive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like running the rounds,'' Johnson said. ``It adds a degree
of strategy to the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, there is work to do in the days ahead. Johnson is
convinced that his world record in the 400 _ 43.18 set in the
Seville World Championships last August _ can be lowered under 43
seconds.
</P>
<P>
   If Greene stands in the way in the 200, so be it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that the public is looking for someone to beat me,''
Johnson offered. ``It's what we're all looking for _ a great race.
Great competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Atlanta, it was ridiculous how far I beat everybody. Nobody
wants to see that again. They want to see a race. And I don't blame
anyone for hoping Maurice is that guy.''
</P>
<P>
   At age 32, however, four years older and wiser than in Atlanta,
Michael Johnson has experience and the clock on his side.
</P>
<P>
   What doeshewant to see in the 200-meter finals?
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to see the tops of two guys' heads while I'm standing
on top of the podium,'' Johnson answered. ``That's what I want to
see.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
