r l BC-ZEN-TEX     07-10 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZEN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOLLOWERS OF MANY FAITHS SEEK ZEN'S SPIRITUAL CALM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JAIME JORDAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Pei-Fang Chuang once tried religion as a
means of finding what was missing in her life.
</P>
<P>
   At 18, she accompanied a friend to church for the first time and
she remembers crying and crying as she was filled with the
overwhelming joy of hearing the congregation praise God.
</P>
<P>
   ``On that day, I got baptized,'' said Chuang, now 25.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, she continued to pray, but she felt that irritating
void creeping back into her life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I didn't find what I was looking for,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Then she found Zen.
</P>
<P>
   The name Zen means ``to meditate peacefully,'' or seeking the
truth by meditation, as a means of achieving a harmonious
relationship between nature and human beings. It was introduced
from China to Japan, and spread along with Buddhism, according to
Zen Master Miao Tien, in an article titled ``The General Concept of
Zen.''
</P>
<P>
   In America, it has been used by Christians, Jews and others to
achieve harmony and balance in a chaotic world.
</P>
<P>
   Zen, considered by many practitioners to be a branch of
Buddhism, is not considered a religion, say experts. But many
practitioners of Zen who also have religious affiliations have said
that the contemplative aspects of meditation have supplemented
their religious relationships.
</P>
<P>
   And for those who are not involved in organized religion, the
meditation techniques are said to bring better health and greater
insight.
</P>
<P>
   Chuang started the Zen Club when she came to UT-Arlington from
Taiwan in 1999 to study anthropology. Now the club has grown to
more than 40 members, meeting at least weekly to practice
meditation techniques and discuss the benefits of practicing Zen.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Reyes, 36, an assistant professor of computer science and
engineering began investigating Zen when he was working on his
Ph.D.
</P>
<P>
   ``My main goal is to not have to work so hard in order to
accomplish goals,'' he said. ``I need wisdom. I need to be able to
perceive what is an appropriate goal and pursue that. In order to
do that, I need to have a mind that is at peace, not so distracted,
easy to focus.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, when days at school get tough or when he has his hands full
with his two daughters, ages 8 and 11, Reyes takes time to slow his
thoughts and clean the clutter out of his mind.
</P>
<P>
   He devotes at least half an hour each day to meditation. He has
seen benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``The basic, the big win for me is, really, that I don't have to
have my way all the time,'' he said. ``That is probably the
greatest advantage I've garnered from studying this. Being
sensitive to perceiving God's will and allowing his will to happen
without me getting in the way.''
</P>
<P>
   As a Christian studying Zen, Reyes has had to cope with a few
paradoxes, such as Buddhist teachings about reincarnation. Reyes
says, however, that he goes to the Zen Club meetings to learn
breathing and meditation techniques and he ignores anything that is
out of sync with his Christian beliefs. In fact, learning to be
still and quiet has enhanced his relationship with God, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's calming down and realizing I'm not really in control of
anything and the very best I can do is realize that God has been
merciful to me and let his will be done because he is much wiser
than me.''
</P>
<P>
   Because there is little indoctrination associated with the
practice of Zen, there is little conflict between religious
practitioners who also participate in Zen, said Mackenzie Brown,
professor and chairman of the religion department at Trinity
University.
</P>
<P>
   ``The general attitude of Zen tradition and masters, certainly
in the West, is there would be no conflict in engaging in these
sorts of practices and engaging in Christian practices and the
like,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Although at a Zen monastery one would see a very regimented
service, many Westerners seek Zen because there are so few rules
and regulations, Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The emphasis of Zen is experience rather than doctrinal or
book learning,'' he said. ``Doctrines are almost irrelevant. You
don't study as much as you will practice. Practice along with
letting that flow into every area of one's life so every act is an
act of meditation.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown said any attempt to articulate the meaning of Zen is
secondary.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have people who are hungry for some sort of spiritual
experience, especially among younger people like college students,
if they are a little bit bored or disillusioned by church
experiences growing up or synagogue experiences growing up with its
exposition of a fair amount of doctrine, Zen is ideal,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are purifying our minds and making our bodies healthy,
mentally and physically,'' Chuang said. ``It's holistic. It just
changes your life.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
