<HEADER>
A8029 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-CHINA-$ADV16-N     07-10 1150
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-CHINA-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRINGING TREASURES BACK TO CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, July 16) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ A much-needed little antiquities museum has been
created in Beijing by a most improbable source: a giant state
corporation that was long notorious for its global weapons sales
and was until recently a branch of the People's Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   The new Poly Art Museum's attractions include its manageable
size _ for now, just one large room stocked with choice ancient
bronzes and a small side room with a few sublime Buddhist statues _
and its highly selective approach to acquisition. The brazenly
Epicurean philosophy is detailed in a brochure in which the museum
resolves ``to eschew quantity and comprehensiveness, confining
ourselves rather to the pursuit of the exquisite, the rare and the
fine.''
</P>
<P>
   I don't know what serious scholars might think of this approach,
but for this borderline antiquities-philistine who nods off at the
sight of long cases filled with objects, the museum offered
unexpected delights.
</P>
<P>
   True to its word, the Poly museum is exhibiting no more than
about 100 objects, each with some wonderful aspect and each given
plenty of space, with labels both in Chinese and in English.
</P>
<P>
   Situated in an unprepossessing office building at a busy
intersection, the museum had kept such a low profile after its
opening last year that few even knew of its existence. But in early
May, it suddenly thrust itself into the news when it spent $4
million to buy three bronze animal heads at auctions in Hong Kong.
The heads had been part of a zodiac fountain at the Old Summer
Palace near Beijing, designed by a European Jesuit in the mid-18th
century, and were looted by French and English troops when they
razed the estate in 1860.
</P>
<P>
   The pillaging of the emperor's summer home was a humiliating
moment in Chinese history, and this spring, when Sotheby's and
Christie's put these bronze heads and a similarly stolen vase on
auction in Hong Kong, nationalistic voices were raised in
objection. The Poly Museum helped save the day, buying the heads at
what many considered an extravagant price of $4 million and
announcing their ``return to the motherland.''
</P>
<P>
   This ``political purchase'' was a departure for the museum,
which has focused on far older relics, and the pieces themselves
are more important as historical symbols than as art. But with the
enormous public interest that was generated by the dispute, the
museum is making space for its new monkey, ox and tiger heads.
</P>
<P>
   The purchases were in line with one part of the museum's
mission: to bring back Chinese treasures that have been smuggled or
sold out of the country. The parent company, the China Poly Group
Corp., has officially separated from the military and now describes
itself as a huge government-owned conglomerate involved in real
estate, industry, high technology and tourism. With this museum it
is trying out what is a new concept for China: corporate
philanthropy.
</P>
<P>
   The company has spent untold millions to build a collection from
scratch over the last two years, mainly in Hong Kong and Taiwan,
where newly discovered relics tend to appear on the market after
being smuggled out of China. Some of the most stunning bronzes on
display were almost certainly unearthed and smuggled out in just
the past several years, museum officials believe.
</P>
<P>
   Because the museum is reversing, ever so slightly, the flood of
relics leaving the country, it was able to enlist one of China's
premier archaeologists as a consultant: Yu Weichao, who recently
retired as head of the National Museum of Chinese History in
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a very cheerful job, buying these items back from
overseas,'' Yu said. ``But I think the Chinese people will be happy
to know that at least we're getting them back.''
</P>
<P>
   Recently Yu gave me a quick tour of the exhibition, barely
containing his enthusiasm as his eyes almost fondled each piece.
</P>
<P>
   The most rare and valuable single bronze, he said _ and I would
add a most fascinating object to scrutinize _ is the ornate bronze
ceremonial wine vessel prominently displayed near the entrance,
with the face of a deity and various birds and other figures and a
gorgeous blue-green patina. Unusually well preserved and made with
exceptional skill, it dates from the Western Zhou period, from the
11th to 8th centuries B.C., and was probably unearthed in Shaanxi
province in the recent past, Yu said. The museum bought it from a
Hong Kong dealer.
</P>
<P>
   Yu dwelled lovingly on a set of eight ritual bronze bells,
graduated in size. Inside each bell is a narrow groove, hollowed
out to perfect the tone, and depending where it is struck, each has
two clear tones. An inscription in ancient Chinese characters
resembles pictographs much more than modern Chinese writing; they
are fun to examine in themselves. The inscription commemorates the
previous three generations of the family of nobleman who had the
bells made and used them to make music some 2,800 years ago in what
is now Shaanxi.
</P>
<P>
   My eyes were drawn to a gold-covered long-necked dragon head,
which around 2,000 years ago formed part of the frame for a royal
canopy and offered an elegant contrast to the many bronze and
bronze-with-copper-inlay vessels. ``My feeling is simply that this
is an exquisitely beautiful piece,'' Yu said, dropping all pretense
of archaeological objectivity.
</P>
<P>
   In a small side room, the museum displays a few of the stone
carvings of Buddhist figures that have been unearthed in Shandong
province over the last quarter century, part of an extraordinary
find known as the Qingzhou sculptures, after a county at the center
of the excavations. Stolen examples of these serene and graceful
figures, created during the northern Wei dynasty in the sixth
century, have started appearing in museums and collections abroad,
but the Poly Art Museum collected its examples inside China.
</P>
<P>
   For now, museum officials say, they plan to keep building their
collections of bronzes and stone carvings, and may soon branch into
ceramics and add another exhibition hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're only one company, so there are only so many things we
can buy,'' said Ma Baoping, assistant director of the museum and a
former army officer with a nose for art. ``It's beyond us to buy
every stolen object that comes up for sale, and I hope that other
Chinese companies and collectors, including overseas Chinese
collectors, will join with us to help bring these treasures back
into Chinese hands.''
</P>
<P>
   The museum is on the second floor of the Poly Plaza commercial
building, 14 Dong-zhimen Nandajie, at the intersection of
Dongzhimen Avenue with the Second Ring Road, across from the
Swissotel. For some months to come, it will be open only on Tuesday
and Thursday from 10 a.m. to 3 p.m. Admission is $2.40; telephone
(86-10) 6500-8117.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-00 1634EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
