<DOCNO> NYT20000710.0209 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 16:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8030 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-CONCH-SHELLS-NYT &LR;      07-10 0453
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-CONCH-SHELLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONCH SHELL   AS A MODEL   FOR TOUGHER   CERAMICS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ohio)   By KENNETH CHANG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like plywood, a conch shell is stronger than its parts.
</P>
<P>
   The spiral-shaped shell is 99 percent aragonite _ a mineral made
of calcium, carbon and oxygen _ but is up to 1,000 times as tough
as pure aragonite. For creatures desiring to eat the conch, that's
a formidable fortress to breach.
</P>
<P>
   The strength comes from nature's evolutionary engineering and
could inspire tougher ceramics.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are, we believe, valuable lessons to be learned in the
design of materials from the evolutionary processes that have taken
place,'' said Dr. Arthur Heuer, a professor of material sciences
and engineering at Case Western Reserve University in Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   In the June 29 issue of the journal Nature, researchers led by
Heuer and Dr. Roberto Ballarini, a professor of civil engineering
at Case Western, described in detail the shell of the queen conch,
which lives in the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   To the naked eye, a chip of conch shell looks unremarkable.
``You would think it was a homogenous piece of chalk,'' Ballarini
said.
</P>
<P>
   Under high-power electron microscopes, the view is more
intricate. The shell consists of layers of rods of aragonite that
crisscross at right angles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to think of it as ceramic plywood,'' Heuer said.
</P>
<P>
   Like wood, each shell layer, about a 25th of an inch thick,
cracks easily when bent along the direction of the rods, the
equivalent of along the grain of wood, but it is very strong when
bent in the perpendicular direction, the equivalent of against the
grain of wood.
</P>
<P>
   The layered crisscross structure strengthens the shell in all
directions. When the shell is bent, tiny cracks accumulate within
individual layers, but the cracks don't propagate all the way
through _ and the shell stays in one piece. ``It doesn't fail,''
Heuer said, ``and that's not a bad definition of a tough
material.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike plywood, though, each aragonite rod is, in turn, also
reinforced.
</P>
<P>
   ``One big rod is made of a bunch of smaller rods,'' Ballarini
said, ``and the smaller rod is made of even smaller rods, which is
made out of even smaller rods.''
</P>
<P>
   A protein secreted by the conch _ the remaining 1 percent of the
shell _ glues the rods together.
</P>
<P>
   If ceramics could be made as tough as conch shells, they would
find new uses in combustion engines, furnaces, body armor and other
applications for which they are now too brittle.
</P>
<P>
   But the layered, crisscross structure is not easy to mimic,
because of the wide range of rod sizes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hard part would be producing such structures in
cost-effective ways,'' Ballarini said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
