<P>
   GORE-MILITARY (Undated) _ A look at the military service of Al
Gore: In some ways, Army Private Al Gore was never and could never
have been just one of the guys, another grunt. Recruiters were
afraid to even sign him up without calling in a supervisor, once
they heard his name and caught on that he was that anti-war Sen.
Albert Gore's son, just out of Harvard. No less than the Army's
highest-ranking officer, Gen. William Westmoreland, singled him out
during a visit to Fort Rucker, Ala., where Pvt. Gore was stationed
for more than a year. The Army chief of staff stopped in the middle
of an official farewell ceremony to pull the young man aside for a
private chat _ and kept Gore's superior officers waiting, and
watching, while he asked one of the lowest-ranking guys on base for
his thoughts on why so many young people opposed the war. Yet there
is no evidence that Gore sought special treatment, or that the
extra notice he got anyway provided any real protection. On the
contrary, within the parameters of his job as an Army journalist,
Gore probably assumed more risk than he had to, choppering around
South Vietnam interviewing soldiers who had just seen action. By
Melinda Henneberger.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH (Baltimore) _ ``For my party, there's no escaping the
reality that the Party of Lincoln has not always carried the mantle
of Lincoln,'' George W. Bush told the annual gathering of the
NAACP. Bush didn't announce any initiatives to address racism, but
instead talked about his plans to improve education, highlighting
his record in Texas where black fourth-graders have the highest
math test scores in the nation. By Alison Mitchell.
