<HEADER>
A8050 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-BIZMAGS11     07-10 0527
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZMAGS11 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Silicon Valley lets the chips fall where they may
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Life in Silicon Valley may be getting a little too
tightly wound. Business Week (July 17) says the valley's
win-at-all-cost mentality is showing ``increasingly dark
implications for the Valleyite's professional and personal life.''
</P>
<P>
   A backlash against the highly competitive mentality that evolved
there is reflected in companies that would rather not locate there,
as well as burned-out executives anxious to flee the valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Silicon Valley, companies throttle and plot against each
other with remorseless glee,'' says Business Week. ``As the dot-com
meltdown of the last two months worsens, the hypercompetition is
going to get a lot feistier.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not over til it's over
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the Federal Reserve passed up a chance to raise interest
rates last month. But that doesn't mean the Fed's campaign to slow
the economy is complete, says Barron's (July 9).
</P>
<P>
   Fed Gov. Edward Gramlich said in an interview, however, that
future rate hikes can be kept to a minimum as long as American
workers become more and more productive and wage increases remain
under control.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine also notes that while the first half of the year
was downright ugly for stocks, history shows that a tough first
half typically presages ``kinder treatment in the second.``
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the last 20 years, a losing first half was followed by a
down market in the second half only once, in 1981,'' the investment
weekly says.
</P>
<P>
   Now for Act II
</P>
<P>
   Act I of the Internet revolution belonged to the dot-coms with
big visions and small bank accounts. Now, says Forbes (July 24),
it's time for Act II, which will be led by big companies that move
their operations to the Web. They are managed by the ``E Gang.''
</P>
<P>
   Among them is Delta Air Lines, led by Chief Executive Officer
Leo F. Mullin. The other E-Gang companies are General Electric,
Charles Schwab, Cisco Systems, Hewlett-Packard, Nordstrom, Lands
End, Wal-Mart, Enron, General Motors, Merck-Medco Managed Care and
DoveBid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Together, the companies. . . employ almost one million people
and have more than $400 billion in revenues. They aren't playing
for paper options or the fast flip. Their drive is to serve
customers, eliminate inefficiency and spark new growth,'' says
Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   The millionaire employee
</P>
<P>
   How do you discipline a millionaire employee? It can be a
problem, says Harvard Business Review (July/August), which notes
that ``millions of millionaire employees'' work in America's new
stock-driven economy.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is not their behavior, although they can be
``demanding, fickle, uncommitted.'' It's keeping them from leaving,
since they don't have to work. In the end, the business quarterly
says, this may be the best thing that has happened to American
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Millionaires force companies to be far more creative than ever
about their products and services _ how else to keep the work
interesting,'' the Harvard Business Review says.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
