<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER11 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   OUTREACH TO CRITICAL AUDIENCE
</P>
<P>
   Death penalty protesters interrupted an introduction for George
W. Bush on Monday at the NAACP national convention in Baltimore,
with one shouting, ``An innocent man was murdered by Governor
Bush.'' Security forces led the four or five protesters out after
they waved signs with pictures of Gary Graham, who was executed
June 22 in Texas. In his speech, Bush appeared to acknowledge the
protesters, saying, ``For those of you who support me _ I see a
couple here, maybe more than a couple _ I hope you will not change
your opinion. For those of you who don't, I hope you ... give me
the chance to tell what is in my heart.'' He added that he
recognizes that ``the party of Lincoln has not always carried the
mantle of Lincoln.''
</P>
<P>
   ENVIROS GO AFTER GORE
</P>
<P>
   Environmental demonstrators chained themselves together in front
of the entrance to Al Gore's campaign office in Knoxville, Tenn.,
today and hung protest banners on the building. Gore promotes
himself as a friend of the environment and is author of ``Earth in
the Balance.'' But the protesters said they saw little difference
between him and George W. Bush. About 100 members of the group
Earth First! danced and chanted in the foyer of the campaign
offices _ 160 miles east of Gore's national headquarters in
Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   ENDURING STAR POWER
</P>
<P>
   With George W. Bush's unusual decision to arrive at the
convention later in the week, John McCain will be in the spotlight
for the first few days. McCain will pull in to Philadelphia on July
29, packed with many of the same journalists who covered his
insurgent campaign. His schedule includes time with just about
every media outlet from major networks to MTV to Comedy Central. A
spokesman says he plans to use the convention as a ``bully pulpit''
for his favorite issue, campaign finance reform. And if you somehow
miss him, wife Cindy has agreed to carry a minicam for ABC's ``Good
Morning America.''
</P>
<P>
   TAX CUTS ON RADAR SCREEN
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore, in a twist on Harry Truman's winning campaign slogan,
says he will spend this week running against the
``do-nothing-for-people Congress'' and its ally George W. Bush.
Gore also for the first time offered unequivocal support for
President Clinton's proposed legislative swap in which Democrats
would accept the Republicans' bill to reduce taxes for most married
couples in return for passage of their party's Medicare
prescription drug plan. Just a couple of weeks ago, Gore doubled
his proposal to $500 billion over 10 years, closer to the $1.3
trillion plan offered by Bush.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN LIMITS HARD TO SETTLE
</P>
<P>
   Twelve years after California voters first approved caps on
campaign contributions, reform proponents and politicians are still
arguing over how high to set those limits. A federal court judge is
scheduled Tuesday to consider once again whether limits set by
Proposition 208, imposed by voters in 1996, unconstitutionally bars
candidates from conducting effective campaigns. A bill signed by
Gov. Gray Davis last week will take the issue to voters again in
November, this time in a measure to approve higher campaign
contributions than those imposed by Proposition 208.
</P>
<P>
   BUCHANAN FOE BOUNCED
</P>
<P>
   Pat Buchanan's campaign has forced the removal of Russell Verney
as chairman of the Reform Party's convention credentials committee
in an effort to prevent allies of Ross Perot from blocking
Buchanan's nomination as the party's presidential candidate.
Verney, who headed the party during the 1996 Perot campaign and was
one of the driving forces in the party's founding, ``basically
decided to spearhead the anti-Buchanan efforts,'' said Angela
``Bay'' Buchanan, the candidate's sister and senior adviser. She
said Verney had encouraged as many as 25 challenges from state
delegations to the August convention in a tactic designed to turn
the nominating process into ``chaos.''
</P>
<P>
   DESPITE FEC, FULL STEAM AHEAD
</P>
<P>
   House Republican campaign officials are preparing to defy the
Federal Election Commission and inject huge amounts of party money
into key congressional races this fall without waiting for a
Supreme Court appeal that will determine whether the practice is
legal. Federal law now limits national parties to direct
expenditures of no more than $33,780 in House races and restricts
the kinds of ads they may run. Last month, the FEC issued an
unusually stern warning to the political parties that it would seek
retroactive fines if they ignored the federal spending limit while
the case is on appeal.
</P>
<P>
   GORE'S CONVENTION
</P>
<P>
   Howard Wolfson, spokesman for Hillary Clinton's Senate campaign,
denied there was tension between her camp and Al Gore's about her
role in the Democratic convention next month. Asked if there was
friction, Wolfson said: ``Not at all.'' He also said, ``It's the
vice president's convention, and we're going to do everything we
can to make sure it goes as well as possible for him, and that's
our goal.''
</P>
<P>
   ARSENIC AND OLD STANDARDS
</P>
<P>
   The Sierra Club wants several House members to pay a political
price for blocking rules that would update the standard for arsenic
levels in drinking water. The standard is currently set on data
collected in 1942. The organization is running ads for at least a
week in the districts of Reps. Marion Berry (D-Ark.), Jay Dickey
(R-Ark.), Robin Hayes (R-N.C.), Anne Northup (R-Ky.), E. Clay Shaw
(R-Fla.), Tom Tancredo (R-Colo.) and Charles Taylor (R-N.C.),
criticizing them for the vote.
</P>
<P>
   AND BRING YOUR GUITARS
</P>
<P>
   Outgoing Commerce Secretary William Daley is taking three of his
top aides when he heads to Nashville in a few days to take over Al
Gore's presidential Gore campaign: his chief of staff, David Lane;
executive assistant Shirley Rothlisberger; and Graham Streett, his
deputy chief of staff and troubleshooter. And Daley is eyeing some
other veteran Gore staffers to see if they'll make the move to
Music City, according to the Wasup at the Penn State Conference
Center in University Park, Pa., for meetings about such topics as
farm conservation and transforming state government.
</P>
<P>
   NO V.P. INTEREST THERE . . .
</P>
<P>
   California Gov. Gray Davis said he'd turn Al Gore down if he's
asked to be his running mate. ``I would say no,'' Davis said,
adding that his answer would not change, even if Gore said the
party and country needed him on the ticket. ``I still believe the
best thing I could for the country is to elect Al Gore and the best
way to elect Al Gore is to carry California and remain his chief
spokesman,'' Da
</P>
</TEXT>
