<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 17:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8059 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-10 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HOORAY FOR HARRY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Silence descended upon much of America this
weekend. It was the sound of millions of children _ and adults _
reading a book.
</P>
<P>
   It was a very special book, to be sure, but a book full of all
those printed words that are supposedly doomed to obsolescence in
the modern tech-world.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth installment in the seven-part Harry Potter series is
magically living up to its high expectations, both in the literary
and commercial sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire,'' delivered promptly to
my door Saturday from Amazon.com via FedEx, just as promised, has
already virtually sold out its first printing of 3.8 million copies
in this country. The American publisher, Scholastic, hastily
ordered the printing of another 2 million copies.
</P>
<P>
   And it is great reading. J.K. Rowling, the author, is a gifted
story-teller who cleverly mixes wondrous whimsy and dramatic, scary
adventure. Her newest book is both familiar and fresh, in which our
hero and his buddies return to the customary oddities at Hogwarts
School for Witchcraft and Wizardry.
</P>
<P>
   But they also confront new magical creatures like the Merpeople
(mermaids plus mermen), new spells like the Jolly-Legs Jinx, nasty
new villains like the Death Eaters and new, tougher mental and
physical challenges. They read advanced magic texts like ``Madcap
Magic for Wacky Warlocks''' and learn to handle skrewts, nifflers
and potions of armadillo bile and mashed scarab beetles.
</P>
<P>
   Harry, 14, is now in his fourth year in training to be a wizard
and evolving nicely from the frightened, naive orphan of the first
book into a confident teen-ager ready to take on what life throws
him. And it throws him a lot.
</P>
<P>
   His story is already a classic in the making _ it appeals across
generational lines with imaginative concepts, beautiful writing and
a timeless moral message.
</P>
<P>
   Children can identify with Potter, who is described wryly as
having ``a knack for attracting a lot of trouble.'' His travails
range from the scorn of classmates who sometimes resent his fame
and don't believe him, to near-death at the hands of evil Lord
Voldemort, the most powerful dark wizard in a century.
</P>
<P>
   Adults can identify with him too. The Ministry of Magic, the
wizards' governing body, could move to Washington any day and be
right at home.
</P>
<P>
   His mentor, Hogwarts headmaster Albus Dumbledore, the most
powerful good wizard of his time, is frustrated by stupid ministry
bureaucrats who refuse to accept the growing danger posed by
Voldemort.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the ministry is preoccupied with such vital tasks as
standardizing the thickness of cauldrons to reduce the number of
leakages. And when magic goes awry, as it sometimes does, the
ministry sends out its version of spin doctors, called the
Accidental Magic Reversal Squad.
</P>
<P>
   A nasty reporter, a sneaky witch who writes puff pieces about
the wizards she likes and rotten stuff about those she doesn't,
complicates this scene. Ah, our kind is everywhere. Guess which
bespectacled 14-year-old she doesn't like?
</P>
<P>
   Conservative religious leaders complain that the Potter books
advocate witchcraft and some school districts have denied children
the freedom to read them. This is outrageous nonsense; the
continuing theme here is the conflict between good and evil, the
importance of fair play and standing up to evil and the triumph (so
far, barely) of good.
</P>
<P>
   Harry's adventures this time are even more hair-raising than
before, and expand the cast of characters from England throughout
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Hogwarts hosts a Triwizard Tournament, in which the school
competes against Beauxbatons and Durmstrang, rival wizard schools
based somewhere in or near France and Bulgaria. The Goblet of Fire
unexpectedly picks Harry to compete against the foreign teams'
champions in three tasks, which involve outwitting horrible
monsters and similar magical monkey business.
</P>
<P>
   Harry is both clever and brave, although not always efficient.
</P>
<P>
   But the last task has been booby-trapped by Voldemort and is
nearly Harry's undoing. The conclusion is complicated and
breath-taking in the audacity of its repeated surprises; my lips
are sealed so that readers may discover the exciting details for
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Rowling has said that this book, expanding Harry's horizon
beyond England throughout Europe and resurrecting Voldemort to his
full powers, lays the foundation for the next three books. She is
heading her wizards into a terrible global confrontation that will
determine whether the secret masters of magic exist to terrorize
the world's muggles (nonwizards like us) or to help them.
</P>
<P>
   Her last chapter is titled, ``The Beginning,'' signaling the
mortal struggle ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Harry will be at the center of it all. He can't help it. It is
his destiny, as invented by Rowling and cheered on by us.
</P>
<P>
   ``It matters not what someone is born but what they grow to
be,'' Dumbledore observes wisely.
</P>
<P>
   What a book. Move over, ``Mary Poppins,'' ``Alice in
Wonderland,'' ``Wind In the Willows,'' ``Wizard of Oz,'' ``Peter
Pan,'' ``Winnie the Pooh.''
</P>
<P>
   You've got worthy company.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address means(at)
hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
