<HEADER>
A8064 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-BBO-ALLSTAR-DEBATE     07-10 1223
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ALLSTAR-DEBATE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Debate still rages over ballplayers in different eras
 &HT;    By Tim Tucker
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA He was a Detroit Tigers batboy 75 years ago. He is an
avid Atlanta Braves fan today. And so we turn to Jimmy Lanier _
``Jimmy my boy,'' family friend Ty Cobb always called him _ for
perspective on baseball's perpetual debate:
</P>
<P>
   Are ballplayers today as good as _ better than? _ they used to
be?
</P>
<P>
   Or were they better, after all, in the good old days?
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly think about that all the time,'' the 85-year-old
Lanier said.
</P>
<P>
   He thinks about the profound differences between eras _ the
differences in equipment, facilities, training, travel, everything.
He notes, unapprovingly, that players sit out more games with
injuries these days. He considers, with regret, the escalation of
relief pitching and the demise of the complete game. He remembers,
vividly, the game as it was played 7 1/2 decades ago, when he was a
Tigers batboy in 1925-26, and every decade since.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one thing I've been blessed with _ a good memory,'' he
said. ``I can see the Detroit team of 1925 come right out on the
field today, as if it's in front of me. I can see Johnny Bassler
behind the plate, Lu Blue on first, Frank O'Rourke on second,
Jackie Tavener at shortstop, Fred Haney on third.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can see the finest outfield in the American League _ Mr.
Cobb, Harry Heilmann, Heinie Manush. And I can see me wearing Mr.
Haney's old uniform, which they gave me because he was the smallest
player on the team. It was big and baggy on me, although my mother
had tried to cut it down.''
</P>
<P>
   Fast-forward 75 years, and Lanier's view of the 2000 Braves,
whom he regularly watches on television, is just as clear: ``I
think they have a great team; I think they can win it all if they
get some of their pitchers going.''
</P>
<P>
   Bridging baseball's eras, Lanier _ a retired sales manager who
has lived in Atlanta for nearly 50 years _ draws upon what he saw
as a pre-teen batboy and what he has seen as a fan ever since to
offer his verdict on the game's perpetual debate:
</P>
<P>
   ``All these young stars today are so wonderful, and the playing
conditions are so much better now. But the players in Mr. Cobb's
day had all the abilities they have now, all of the same basic
abilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if you would take the 2000 Braves and put them in
Detroit in 1925, with all the conditions of that day, and if you
would take the 1925 Tigers and switch them over to today's
equipment and conditions, there wouldn't be much difference
(between the teams), in my opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   There you have it.
</P>
<P>
   But, alas, there is no final word on this subject.
</P>
<P>
   There never will be.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could argue these points day in and day out for the next
20 years,'' Hall of Fame pitcher Phil Niekro, 61, said, ``and I
don't know if anyone is going to come up with the correct answer.''
</P>
<P>
   From Hank Aaron, 66, the very topic elicits a knowing chuckle.
``This is the talk in every era,'' he said. ``When I was chasing
Babe's record, that's all I heard _ the difference between the
eras.''
</P>
<P>
   And so it continues, that fun and futile question of how today's
best players rank against yesterday's, that fun and futile question
of how to reconcile the irreconcilable differences of time. How
does Randy Johnson stack up with Sandy Koufax? Mark McGwire with
Aaron? Ken Griffey Jr. with Joe DiMaggio? This generation of stars,
collectively, with other generations?
</P>
<P>
   The argument that today's players are better than any previous
era's players almost always starts this way: Athletes are bigger,
faster, stronger, better-conditioned in all sports, and baseball
surely is no exception.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not one of those guys who says, `They don't play it like
they used to,' '' said 76-year-old Ernie Johnson, the retired
Braves broadcaster and former big-league pitcher. ``I think
everyone is getting better in all sports.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys are better athleteregimens. Some former players
envy the weight rooms and the personal trainers; some wonder about
the influence and danger of muscle-building drugs and supplements.
</P>
<P>
   Niekro recalls the extent of his offseason conditioning program:
``Show up at the ballpark a couple of weeks before spring training
and play some Ping-Pong.'' Aaron notes that one hurdle to
year-round conditioning in previous eras was economics: ``Hell, I
remember four or five years in a row, maybe longer, that as soon as
the season was over, I had to get a job. Now, as soon as the season
is over, players might take a scenic cruise somewhere, then get
back to lifting weights.''
</P>
<P>
   Bigger. Stronger. More athletic. No arguments so far.
</P>
<P>
   The argument that today's players are not as good as another
generation's players usually starts with the distinction between
being a great aas good as it used to be,' '' Rawlings said. ``But
my reading of history is . . . it seems every generation says that.
I just think that's silly.''
</P>
<P>
   On ESPN.com, senior writer Rob Neyer recently compared Bonds _
TSN's No. 34, SABR's No. 65 _ with Ted Williams and Stan Musial,
offensively and defensively, and concluded: ``Is Barry Bonds the
greatest left fielder who ever lived? I would argue that if he's
not now, by the time his career is over, he will be.''
</P>
<P>
   In a book published last year, ``Baseball's All-Time Best
Hitters,'' Michael Schell deduced that the greatest hitter ever is
not Williams or Cobb or Ruth but an active player _ Tony Gwynn.
</P>
<P>
   Feel free, of course, to disagree.
</P>
<P>
   One thing that will not settle these arguments is raw
statistics; they only intensify the debate. Clearly, a 40-home run
season is not nearly the feat now that it was 20 years ago, and a
60-home run season is not nearly the feat now that it was in 1927,
when Babe Ruth hit more homers than any other American League team.
Conversely, a 3.00 ERA is much more impressive now than in 1968,
when the major-league average was 2.99. It is all relative.
</P>
<P>
   And yet the attempt to compare eras is irresistible.
</P>
<P>
   It seems apparent that the few great pitchers of this era would
have been even better in eras when the parks were bigger, the ball
less lively, the hitters less juiced and the mound higher. Of
course, they would have had to learn to go nine innings.
</P>
<P>
   It seems apparent, too, that the great hitters of past eras
would have been even better in this one, facing expansion-diluted
pitching staffs in a hitter-friendly environment. Of course, they
would have had to face setup men and closers, rather than the
starting pitcher four times a game.
</P>
<P>
   It seems apparent that there are more great defensive plays than
ever before, or does it just seem that way because we see all of
them on ``SportsCenter'' and ``Baseball Tonight''?
</P>
<P>
   Truth is, it is getting harder to wage baseball's perpetual
debate.
</P>
<P>
   Hall of Fame pitcher Jim Palmer, 54, noting the unprecedented
level of offense in today's game, said: ``Roger Kahn wrote in
``Boys of Summer'' that what's great about baseball is you can
always compare one generation to another. I don't really think you
can anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   We'll keep trying, of course.
</P>
<P>
   And it can be confusing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today,'' Jimmy Lanier said, ``even the batboys look like
ballplayers.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
