<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8065 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-CHUCK-AND-BUCK-FEATUR     07-10 1364
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHUCK-AND-BUCK-FEATURE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WRITER TRIES TO BUCK THE TRENDS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GLENN WHIPP 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thirty-year-old screenwriter Mike White never lacked for work
after graduating from Wesleyan University in Connecticut, but the
jobs he managed to secure weren't exactly what he had in mind. One
was a ``Die Hard'' spin-off for Roseanne where she saved the world
from mall-mauling terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   He also wrote the MTV/Paramount teen comedy ``Dead Man on
Campus,'' a movie he doesn't like much since he was kicked off the
set after the first day for giving the director too many
suggestions.
</P>
<P>
   White then spent two years as a supervising producer for
television's ``Dawson's Creek,'' writing nine episodes. The pay was
good, but he hated his work. Any time he tried to give one of the
show's characters the tiniest quirk or imperfection, he'd be
overruled. Ambivalence was a no-no. Each ambiguous note needed to
be ironed out before the episode ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so frustrating,'' the Pasadena-born White says. ``It
made me just want to write a character that no one wanted to be and
have that be the centerpiece of a story, a really ambiguous story
with a really ambivalent character. I just wanted to make some
mischief.''
</P>
<P>
   White has done just that with ``Chuck and Buck,'' a dark,
heartfelt buddy movie that subverts traditional film conventions
about obsession, growing up and man-child characters. The movie,
directed by Miguel Arteta (``Star Maps''), also flouts standard
practice in its cast, which is dominated by behind-the-scenes
talent. Among those involved: Chris and Paul Weitz, who directed
``American Pie'' and wrote ``Antz'' and the upcoming ``Nutty
Professor II: The Klumps,'' as well as talent manager Beth Colt and
White himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chuck and Buck'' premiered at the Sundance Film Festival in
January and was snapped up immediately by Artisan Entertainment.
White plays Buck, a strange childlike man who, after the death of
his mother, becomes fixated on his boyhood buddy, Chuck (Chris
Weitz). Buck has never moved past the day when Chuck moved away,
while Chuck, in the intervening 16 years, has become a successful
record executive with a beautiful house, car and fiancee. When
their worlds collide, both Chuck and Buck must confront their
respective _ and very different _ memories of their boyhood
friendship.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a movie about unlikely heroes,'' director Arteta says.
``I think Mike was in some kind of rebellion when he wrote it, kind
of like Alan Ball, another television writer, was when he wrote
`American Beauty.' Here, Mike has busted out and written about this
needy man-child and made a hero out of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Since White dresses like Buck (he has a closet full of striped
T-shirts straight out of ``The Brady Bunch'') and possesses a
similar impish personality, most people who see the movie assume
White is Buck. Or at least Buck minus a few of the more serious
neuroses. (``I'm a quirky guy; I can't hide,'' White says.)
</P>
<P>
   But given the level of his success, White is probably much
closer to the prosperous Chuck. After working as a supervising
producer on the acclaimed, lamentably canceled NBC series ``Freaks
and Geeks,'' White is currently writing two television pilots for
Brillstein-Grey, as well as feature scripts for MTV Films, director
Tim Burton and Adam Sandler.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many respects, Chuck is me, the guy trying to keep up
appearances and be the successful person,'' White says. ``And all
the while, I'm thinking, `Wait, there's this twisted side of
myself, both creatively and personally, that needs to be
acknowledged.'''
</P>
<P>
   Enter ``Chuck and Buck.'' Although aspects of the movie sound
like typical indie-film fare, the movie gently defies any attempt
at categorization. The likable, sympathetic Buck is a stalker, but
he doesn't carry a gun and, as White notes, ``He doesn't get thrown
out of an attic window and impaled on a stake below at the end of
the movie.'' The movie even has a happy ending, albeit (of course)
an ambivalent one.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest twist in the movie is its hopeful spirit,'' Chris
Weitz says. ``You have the feeling at the end that everybody is
going to be OK, which flies in the face of indie cool.''
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean the movie is without some disturbing moments.
Buck's peculiar sexuality is unmistakable here; he isn't a neutered
man-child like cinematic predecessors Forrest Gump and Dustin
Hoffman's Raymond Babbitt in ``Rain Man.'' Neither is he an idiot
savant. He writes a play, and it stinks. He also does some
inappropriate things and behaves at times in _ yes _ a very
ambiguous manner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buck is a real person with all the inherent imperfections,''
Arteta says. ``He's not sanitized and safe like Forrest Gump.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds White: ``Really, I just wanted to call a spade a spade.
Look at a black comedy like 'The Cable Guy,' which is like the most
homoerotic comedy of all time. But movies like that never get
around the hinting and playing with the undertones. I wanted to
take those undertones and put them front and center.''
</P>
<P>
   And in doing so, White ended up putting himself front and center
when Arteta cast him in the role. White, who acted at Wesleyan,
always hoped to play Buck, and Arteta supported the notion, even
when it meant that the movie might not receive financing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could have made this film a lot faster and for a lot more
money if we had cast famous actors,'' Arteta says. ``Investors
wanted somebody like Jon Favreau. We entertained that for a short
time but felt the story should be the star.''
</P>
<P>
   So Arteta, following the advice of directing idol Sam Fuller
(``I can still see his cigar coming toward my face,'' Arteta says),
cast on hunches, signing up friends like the Weitz brothers and
veteran Latina actress Lupe Ontiveros. When White heard that Arteta
was casting non-professional actors, he called the director and
asked why he hadn't been given the part yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Mike was wondering what the hell Miguel was thinking
when he heard that he put Chris and I in the movie,'' says Paul
Weitz, who plays an amateur actor and Chuck look-alike in the
movie. ``And I understand that. If I had written this movie, I
would have been kicking and screaming.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe me, I was,'' White says, hearing Weitz's comments.
``It would have been one thing to pass me over because Joaquin
Phoenix wanted the part, but if those guys were going to be in the
movie, then there was no reason for me to balk at the challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like I have this burning desire to act,'' White
continues, ``but after putting my heart into this movie, it was
just hard to let it go. I wanted to be part of the process. And
playing Buck, the central character, I knew I could have a hand in
the tone of the movie. So if it succeeded or failed, it would be as
much on me as anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   But White has found he got more than he bargained for. Playing
Buck has made him the lightning rod for people's reactions to the
film _ both positive and negative. People want to ask him
questions, take issue with characters' actions or simply tell him
their life story. White found this out the hard way after ``Chuck
and Buck'' screened at Sundance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember walking into the theater that first night and it
was packed with my peers and people I knew, and my father _ who's a
minister _ was there,'' White says. ``And I was thinking, `What
have I done? This movie is too mischievous. People are going to
realize I'm insane.'
</P>
<P>
   ``So I lasted about 45 minutes; then I ran into the street. And
it was snow and cold and I don't smoke, but I found a cigarette. I
had this parka pulled over my head, so I was anonymous, and when
people came out of the theater, there were these guys who had all
these issues with the movie. And I thought, 'This is where it
begins. My life is never going to be the same.'''
</P>
<P>
   And his father's reaction?
</P>
<P>
   ``He liked it,'' White says. ``He's a big cheerleader. But he
did wonder why I had to play such a strange character. He said,
'Here's your chance to be Robert Redford and instead you play this
bizarre man. You blew it.''' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
