<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 17:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8071 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-OLD-RECORD-ALBUMS-ESS     07-10 1317
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLD-RECORD-ALBUMS-ESSAY-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A VINYL FAREWELL (OR HOW I CAME TO TOSS OUT MY OLD RECORDS) 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following ``separate-buy'' article from The
Boston Globe Magazine can be purchased _ the cost is not
prohibitive _ by special arrangement. For purchase information, see
end of text. 
 By PETER IVAN HOFFMAN  
 c.2000 Peter Ivan Hoffman   
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features  
<TEXT>
<P>
   I am tossing my old record albums.
</P>
<P>
   Every baby boomer can feel the sting of this phrase, the gravity
of the decision. Even those who have internalized the 1970s mantra
``let it go,'' combined it with the '90s credo ``we have to move
on,'' and have unsentimentally pared down their lives to the
Restoration Hardware and Eddie Bauer essentials can appreciate this
particularly painful form of separation anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   Albums. The very word is a dead giveaway to a person's
generation. If at a music store you find yourself saying, ``Do you
have the new Ben Folds Five alb ... uh, CD?'' you're a boomer. If
the word ``disc'' or ``CD'' rolls right off your tongue, you're a
definite X. If you never even heard of a Shure or Pickering
tone-arm cartridge, you're a Y _ or whatever name sticks to the
generation after X.
</P>
<P>
   Even as we began amassing CD collections, we boomers invariably
toted our prized LPs from one home to another, like a child taking
an armful of stuffed animals from room to room. Album retention is
deeply embedded in our psyches. It's an aural fixation that Gen
Xers and their even younger counterparts can't fathom, first
because they don't have albums and, second, as they tell us
Methuselahs, because every old album can be found on CD anyway _ or
downloaded from some distant Internet redoubt. Which is not only
untrue, it completely misses the point.
</P>
<P>
   Our hundreds and even thousands of vinyl discs are practically
living organisms to us. We've spent countless hours removing dust
from their skins, carefully holding them by the edges as we replace
them in their sleeves. These albums were temperamental,
inconvenient, high-maintenance creatures of great and often
irritating fragility. Whereas CDs are metallic digital clones made
up of strings of ones and zeros in invisible mathematical
configurations, albums were physical, tactile entities that
demanded care, sensitivity, commitment.
</P>
<P>
   Our record albums saw us through decades. Each one, like an
individual person, carried its particular history. CDs always have
a nice day and don't care what you do to them. Albums are moody and
could easily end up injured or broken. CDs, gleaming and cold and
technocratic, glint like the steely eyes of a corporate takeover
executive and have the survival ability of roaches.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, to this day, those old vinyl stalwarts maintain a
warmer, richer sonic ambience than even the most artfully mastered
CDs. While CDs are more technically accurate in their reproduction
of music, with a greater dynamic range than records, albums had
that ineffable quality of human depth _ even sensuality _ that CDs
never seem to capture. The sound of a record simply had more
character.
</P>
<P>
   We may have shed most of the merchandise we acquired over the
years: Qiana shirts, lava lamps, and black-light posters. But our
album collection remained an inviolate part of our lives, through
dorm rooms to first apartments to first homes, through various
marriages and living arrangements and divorces. And through it all,
each album assumed a set of snaps, crackles and pops that ranged
from irritating to infuriating, but somehow we got used to them and
ultimately accepted them. Albums were like a collection of familiar
friends: You lived with the flaws and learned to love the records
all the more because of them.
</P>
<P>
   After a few playings, albums became as individual to us as DNA.
Within my record collection, for example, there was the loud,
familiar clicking near the English muffin line in Simon and
Garfunkel's ``Punky's Dilemma'' on their Bookends album. There was
the telltale skip at the beginning of ``Lay Lady Lay'' on Bob
Dylan's Greatest Hits album _ ``Lay acro ... acro ... acro ... acro
...'' _ which always needed a little nudge of the turntable arm to
get it back on track. The subtle series of pops at the transition
point in my copy of Sgt. Pepper's ``A Day in the Life'' soon became
an embedded aesthetic element of the song. Recently, when I heard
it on CD, it seemed to be missing something; my music memory had
integrated the flaws.
</P>
<P>
   I began tossing the albums in batches this past fall, and as I
did, I began to ruminate on my life in ways more poignant (and
somewhat more maudlin) than I could have anticipated. Or perhaps I
did expect to relive the pleasures and the pain, and that was what
made me so hesitant to finally do the deed: To consider each LP was
to confront my history in ways both aural and visual. Over the
course of a month, I privately eulogized each one before dropping
it into the trash bin. More than 2,000 bit the dust before I
finished. I tossed them slowly, with days of reflection in between,
before relegating them to rock 'n' roll heaven.
</P>
<P>
   I savored the associations of time and place that came and went
with each. The Beatles, the Moody Blues, Aaron Copland, Quicksilver
Messenger Service, Jefferson Airplane, the Monkees, Culture Club,
Bill Evans, Barry White, Van Morrison, Woodstock, the Animals,
Cream ... even Gary Lewis and the Playboys. I never anticipated
that this process, which started out to be so cleansing, would
become so unexpectedly grim. How do you say goodbye to Frank Zappa?
</P>
<P>
   Bidding adieu to a huge collection of record albums that have
gone unplayed for years is a symbolic act of leaving one's past
behind. These albums saw many of us through the better part of
three decades. Throwing out even a dozen records represents a
decade's worth of flashbacks in one dizzying moment. Perhaps it's
because our record albums had the power to understand us better
than any person ever could. In our most confusing years,
adolescence and early adulthood, music was our confessor, our
teacher. Such was the power of music that it could look into the
very corner of our souls.
</P>
<P>
   And that, finally, was why I procrastinated. It took me years to
start the process of tossing out my LPs and replacing them with
CDs. Gone are the album covers with the photographs and
illustrations that could instantly transport me back: Bob Dylan
walking down a windy New York street with a pretty girl beside him,
or the Siamese-twin heads of Paul Simon and Art Garfunkel sprouting
from what appeared to be one black turtleneck. Or the
phantasmagoric Magical Mystery Tour cover. Let's face it: A
scaled-down Big Brother and the Holding Company CD in its flimsy
plastic case looks like it needs to be reconstituted. And as for
Sticky Fingers ...
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, I tell myself, I'll have more space. I'll be
traveling lighter. It's time to move on. Why lug a sackful of
20th-century rocks into the new millennium? But as I tossed out my
collection, I saw that a part of me was being lost as well. In the
end, it turned out that my records had been playing me all along.
This ungainly collection of faded cardboard sleeves and their
timeworn vinyl inhabitants had become the one thing I hadn't
expected: witnesses to a life.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITORS: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on other
features. &QL;
</P>
