<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8073 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-HORSE-DENTIST-HNS &LR;      07-10 0595
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HORSE-DENTIST-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NEW SPECIALTY FOR DENTISTS: THE HORSE, OF COURSE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By WILLIAM LUTHER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Dr. Clay Stubbs isn't the typical dentist.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't have Muzak in his waiting room. He doesn't have a
comfortable reclining chair for his patients. And he doesn't give
out toothbrushes embossed with his phone number at the end of each
visit.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he almost always makes his patients wait outside.
</P>
<P>
   They have to stand up during exams. And he blindfolds them while
he works on their teeth.
</P>
<P>
   Stubbs is an equine dentist, a small but growing group of
veterinarians who specialize in treating equine molar maladies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really, competent horse dentistry is a really new
profession,'' said Stubbs, whose office and home is just near
Johnson City, some 50 miles north of San Antonio. ``There's only a
handful of us who do equine dentistry full time, and I think I know
all of them.''
</P>
<P>
   The full-time dentistry profession is so small that most horse
owners haven't even heard about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up around horses, and I knew I had to get (their teeth)
floated, but I never thought I would be going to a horse dentist,''
Alex ``Sandy'' Logan said during his first visit to Stubbs' office
with his two horses, Cappie and Connie.
</P>
<P>
   Logan's wife, Becky, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our kids thought it was pretty funny we were bringing (our
horses) to a dentist. They said, `You've really lost it now,''' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   A 1965 graduate of the Texas A&AMP;M veterinary school, Stubbs
didn't start out to be an equine dentist. He spent most of his
career doing what most doctors do _ establishing a successful
general practice.
</P>
<P>
   All was going well until the economic downturn of the 1980s and
family problems forced him to sell his clinics.
</P>
<P>
   At 50, Stubbs said to himself: ``If I'm going to be working
until I'm 90, then I better be doing something I like.''
</P>
<P>
   That led him to specialize in horse dentistry.
</P>
<P>
   The first thing Stubbs did was improve floating of horse teeth.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike human teeth, horse teeth are designed to wear with age.
</P>
<P>
   ``A tooth can be 3 to 4 1/2 inches long,'' Texas A&AMP;M Professor
Leon Scrutchfield said of young horses' teeth. ``And when they are
20 years old, they can be an inch.''
</P>
<P>
   This wearing creates sharp points, which cause sores inside the
horse's mouth, according to Scrutchfield, who is the head of Field
Services at the A&AMP;M College of Veterinary Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Floating a horse's teeth _ a masonry term, which refers to
creating a level row of bricks _ involves grinding off those points
to create a level row of teeth.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, these points were ground off with nothing more than
a hand rasp, requiring a strong hand and a lot of time.
</P>
<P>
   Now Stubbs uses an air-driven file he designed and patented that
runs at 8,000 oscillations per minute.
</P>
<P>
   Stubbs says his file is easier on the horse, does the job better
and saves time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm making some money for the first time in my life because of
this specialization,'' Stubbs said, noting that owners don't mind
paying for his services because they see almost immediate
improvements in their horse's attitude and performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'm most proud of, though, is developing the tools to do
a full exam,'' Stubbs said. ``I sell everything you need to do
dentistry.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say he's definitely a pioneer,'' Scrutchfield said. ``Not
only is Dr. Stubbs good at what he's doing, he has been innovative
in developing new instruments.''
</P>
</TEXT>
