<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, July 11, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Noticeably less humid air will flow into the Northeast as a cold
front pushes farther offshore. Colder air aloft will lead to
billowy clouds forming over the higher terrain, and there will be a
few showers in northern New England.
</P>
<P>
   The boundary with a sultry air mass over the southern half of
the nation will be active, with several large thunderstorms from
the Middle Atlantic coast to southern Iowa. The return flow of
milder, moist air into the upper Plains will produce a batch of
thundershowers from Nebraska to the Dakotas.
</P>
<P>
   Torrid conditions will stretch from the southern Plains to the
deserts of the Southwest. Afternoon thunderstorms will erupt over
the southern Rockies, and a few will form along the Front Range.
The Northwest will notice a warming trend as sunshine returns to
most sections and temperatures rise above seasonal levels. Fog will
be nestled along parts of the West Coast.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: LONG-LASTING SMOKE
</P>
<P>
   The view of Fairbanks, Alaska, on Sunday resembled a smoggy East
Coast city with a veil of smoke hovering over the town. This past
weekend marked the beginning of the third week of hazy conditions
over interior southern Alaska, a result of recent forest fires. On
Sunday, a new twist was added to the unusual scene as clusters of
thunderstorms blossomed in the warm air mass. By midafternoon, more
than 1,600 lightning strikes had been detected, leading to more
forest fires and additional smoke, which should keep the skies
dull. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
