<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 17:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8080 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TUFF-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      07-10 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TUFF-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TUFF': AN INSIDER BATTLES THE INNER-CITY TRAP 
</HEADLINE>
   (Editors: Publication notes appear at end of review.)  
 By RICHARD BERNSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The eponymous Tuff of Paul Beatty's new novel is a smart
small-time hoodlum from the streets of East Harlem who sees things
as they are and whose dreams that they might be different smash up
against the jagged edges of reality. He is 19, married and the
father of a small boy, and he is surrounded by a cast of characters
who, like Tuff himself, are outside the usual categories.
</P>
<P>
   His best friend is a disabled anti-Semitic black Muslim who is
always coming up with get-rich schemes, legal and otherwise. His
father is a cant-spouting former Black Panther who begins poetry
readings by firing shotgun shells into the auditorium ceiling. His
self-appointed mentor is a black rabbi named Spencer Throckmorton,
who converted to Judaism to marry his college sweetheart and became
a rabbi even though she later left him. Tuff, whose real name is
Winston Foshay, decides about midway through Beatty's satirical
ghetto romp to run for city council, raising money by working in a
three-card monte scam in midtown Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tuff,'' in other words, is an extravagant, satirical cri de
coeur from the inner city, centering on that most common of all
sociological concepts, the young black urban male, which is
Beatty's principal literary subject. This gifted writer's first
novel, ``The White Boy Shuffle,'' was about one Gunnar Kaufman, who
in moving from middle-class Santa Monica to meaner, grittier
Hillside, Calif., has to learn to handle himself in the urban
arena. Beatty's new book shifts the scene from Los Angeles to New
York, and from a neophyte home boy to a native son, but it stays
within the genre of comic parody, with its poison darts aimed both
at the black urban male himself and the sociologists who have
conceptualized him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tuff'' is a funny book, and Beatty's blunt, impious,
streetwise eloquence has a kind of transfixing power. The serious
point, though never put in serious political-science language by
Beatty, would seem to be the subtle power of the inner city trap,
with Winston and his friends hemmed in by stiff-necked
victim-culture ideologues in one corner, self-defeating in-group
machismo in another and an indifferent economic system in the
third.
</P>
<P>
   The main ingredient of ``Tuff'' is portraiture, word-rich,
profanity- and caricature-drenched tableaus of Winston and the
off-kilter world in which he dwells. Skillfully drawn as those
tableaus are, one yearns for Beatty to advance beyond his absurdist
color photos of Winston's world, to do something more than slash
our conventional notions into scraps.
</P>
<P>
   Advance to what exactly is difficult to say. Maybe something
deeper and more affecting than Winston's insouciant, self-defeating
confrontation with the limitations of his world. Beatty's
genre-busting technique, his mingling of parody with naturalism,
seems aimed at avoiding stock situations, ghetto stereotypes. His
book is a kind of anti-``Shaft'' in this sense, and that is most
welcome. But his unwillingness to shed the transgressive comic mode
also subjects his narrative to a talky, meandering quality and a
tendency to end up not in ghetto stereotypes but in ghetto
slapstick.
</P>
<P>
   We first meet Winston waking up from a faint in a Brooklyn
tenement that has just been the scene of some drug-gang murders.
That Winston fainted, and that his childhood memories are of being
teased because of his bulk, lead the reader into mistaking him for
a hapless figure, too flabby for the mean streets. Winston is fat
but far from hapless. He casually steps around the corpses, joins
up with his best friend, whose name is Fariq, and heads toward East
Harlem, where he is a man who knows his way around.
</P>
<P>
   ``If all the world's a stage, the stoop at 258 East 109th Street
was his proscenium of Ghetto Tragedy,'' Beatty's narrator says.
Soon Winston has laid out an auxiliary policeman with a punch to
the chin and shot his dog. Then he tells one of his friends, an
unregenerate leftist revolutionary named Inez Yomura, what it's
like to stab somebody.
</P>
<P>
   Winston, talking the talk of the street, refers to himself and
to almost everybody with the most insulting racial epithet in the
language, appropriated by the hip-hop culture as a kind of
insider's insignia. Beatty's attempt in his portrayal of Winston
parallels Winston's own almost pornographic use of the word, and of
the sexual and racial meanness of his nonstop patter. You feel the
impulse to dislike Winston, to judge him, but you can't, partly
because he has charm, partly because he sees so clearly and partly
because he does want a way out.
</P>
<P>
   The satirical heart of ``Tuff'' comes when Winston, given the
absence of legal ways out, decides to turn his life around by
running for city council. His elderly friend Inez gives him $15,000
of the reparation money she got for being held in a Japanese
internment camp during World War II, but his campaign is
half-hearted and despairing from the beginning, and Beatty mines it
mostly for its satirical potential. One of Winston's opponents, for
example, a book writer and ex-astronaut named German Jordan,
complains at a debate that despite all he's done for the
neighborhood, he still doesn't feel safe parking his Mercedes
there. Then he calls on his constituents ``to start imagining
ourselves beyond race.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'd been to outer space, written books, had dollars, drove
a Mercedes-Benz, I'd imagine myself beyond race too,'' Winston
says, in one of the few statements from him that would be quotable
in this newspaper. But German Jordan is so much a straw man that
the answer Beatty puts into Winston's mouth does not have much
grip, serious or satirical. Beatty sustains his book's verbal
vitality to the end, but you wonder whether, having created this
raucous group of rugged individuals, he himself knew exactly what
to do with them.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `TUFF'  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Paul Beatty  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   259 pages. Alfred A. Knopf. $23.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
