<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8083 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e pat_nytimes     07-10 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 pat_nytimes
 Nintendo Still Going Strong 
 (Latest)  
 By DAVID BLOOM  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;  &QL;  &QL;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hard to believe, but at the rate things are going, Nintendo may
start challenging McDonald's for most served. The company recently
passed the 100 million mark in the number of Game Boy handheld
systems sold since the device debuted in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   At around $70 apiece, that's $7 billion in sales before a single
game cartridge or add-on accessory is sold. And with more Pokemon
Game Boy titles coming among the scores of new games expected from
dozens of developers, there's little reason to think the machines
will stop succeeding.
</P>
<P>
   As it is, Nintendo has shrugged off one seemingly attractive
challenger, SNK's NeoGeo Pocket Color (available at www.snk.com),
which has struggled to attract any consumer interest 13 months
after its debut.
</P>
<P>
   Game Boy may face stiffer competition, at least in the long
term, from the Palm- and Pocket PC-based handheld organizers that
are proving big hits in the marketplace (Father's Day found Palm
device makers unable to keep up with demand, for instance). Go to
www.palm.com, www.handspring.com and the sites of PC and
electronics makers such as Compaq, Hewlett-Packard and Casio for
more information on any of these.
</P>
<P>
   Games are becoming a good-sized sector in the software offerings
for these machines, but their prices are far beyond the $70 or so
it costs for a Game Boy Color. Think of it as the difference
between playing games on a PC versus a console like the N64 or
PlayStation; one is a relatively complex and costly machine that
does a lot of different things while the other is simple, cheap and
does a few things well.
</P>
<P>
   A just-debuted, teen-oriented challenger, the Cybiko (at
www.cybiko.com), may prove to be a worthy opponent, particularly
because it offers delightfully simple wireless networking that lets
kids play each other or chat as long as they're within 300 feet of
each other.
</P>
<P>
   I've tested the machines and found they connect simply and
reliably with each other and provide simple ways to do a lot of
things teens in particular will think are cool, like matching up
people with similar interests and finding gaming opponents.
</P>
<P>
   It has a built-in organizer and other capabilities (much as does
the NeoGeo) and comes with an artificial life game, CyLandia. It
also links to your computer for easy updates and backups, and
Cybiko provides a free e- mail account through its Website.
</P>
<P>
   As a further enticement, Cybiko's parent company gives away a
free, downloadable game from the Internet every day to take
advantage of that power. It's a bit pricey, at $129, and the
monochrome screen is definitely behind the technology curve, but in
all, it's a fine package that holds a lot of promise.
</P>
<P>
   Nintendo's response to these challengers won't come until next
year probably, when it finally releases the Game Boy Advance, which
will jump to a far more powerful 32-bit brain (the current
processor is only 8 bits). The company has talked about providing
wireless Web connections, cell-phone capabilities and more through
the Advance.
</P>
<P>
   And interestingly, a 32-bit brain would put the Advance at the
same power level, more or less, as the original PlayStation, in a
compact, handheld box.
</P>
<P>
   Nintendo's latest word is that the Advance will debut in Japan
by year's end, but company officials have largely been mum about
details for the American market. With the Game Boy selling 17.5
million units last year alone, the company is in no hurry to put
its cash cow out to pasture.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, the original PlayStation will be getting a facelift
(and serious liposuction) after its powerful successor, the
PlayStation 2, hits American markets in October.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent Japan press conference, Sony officials unveiled the
PS One, which has all the connections and capabilities of the
original PlayStation, in a package about a third the size.
</P>
<P>
   The machine is designed for mobile uses such as in the car, and
will eventually have available add-ons such as a cell phone link
for Internet gaming and a clip-on LCD screen.
</P>
<P>
   Those attachments are many months away, but Sony finally is
beginning to do the same marketing-minded variations on a theme for
the PlayStation that they've applied with such verve and success on
all their consumer electronics products (think 200 kinds of Walkman
as interpreted on the old gray PlayStation box).
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Daily News Web site at http://www.DailyNews.com.)
</P>
