<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 17:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8086 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-STRANGER-REVIEW-NY     07-10 1069
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-STRANGER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`STRANGER WITH A CAMERA': ONE MAN IN APPALACHIA WOULDN'T STAND FOR
IT 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Broadcast notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
 By JULIE SALAMON c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Elizabeth Barret was a candidate for homecoming queen in her
small Kentucky town in 1967 when she heard about the killing. A
local man, respected but eccentric, had fatally shot a Canadian man
for taking pictures of an impoverished miner and his baby.
</P>
<P>
   Some 30 years later, Barret could not remember what she thought
then about the killing itself, but she did remember this: ``I
didn't want the rest of the world to think of us as hillbillies, to
see us as ignorant, backward or violent.''
</P>
<P>
   She would become a documentary filmmaker, making a career trying
to show another side of her Kentucky home. In films like ``Quilting
Women,'' ``Hand-Carved'' and ``Coal Mining Women,'' she has aimed
to preserve Appalachian customs and history and to counter the
stereotype of primitive shanty dwellers. But her work only
heightened her memory of the killing. She empathized with Hugh
O'Connor, the dead Canadian, who had been a respected documentary
filmmaker, a colleague to others. By all accounts, and she listened
to many, O'Connor's intentions had been honorable, not
exploitative. Yet as a local herself she also understood the
resentment that led Hobart Ison, the killer, to explode.
</P>
<P>
   She did what artists do: she used what was nagging her in her
work. The result is ``Stranger With a Camera,'' a thoughtful and
disturbing documentary about what happened to O'Connor and why. But
Barret's film has another important agenda. ``Can filmmakers show
poverty without shaming the people we portray?'' she asks, raising
the general question of exploitation. The issue is especially
relevant today, with the blurring of entertainment and news and
with video cameras everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   She has composed her investigation as a haunting narrative, but
without losing sight of reportorial fairness. She interviewed
witnesses to the murder, including both the O'Connor and Ison
families, townspeople and reporters who covered the story
(including Calvin Trillin, reading chilling excerpts from his 1969
article about the killing in The New Yorker).
</P>
<P>
   The film emerges as a provocative moral inquiry but also as a
vivid portrait of a place and time, informed by Barret's gentle,
personal rumination (with a beautifully written narration by Fenton
Johnson, a Kentucky novelist).
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps beginning with Walker Evans' famous Depression-era
images, Appalachia's poor people became irresistible subjects for
photographers. It seemed ennobling to expose the poverty, and the
worn faces and shanties also happened to make powerful pictures.
</P>
<P>
   By the 1960s, a time of national prosperity and mounting
interest in documentary journalism, Appalachia was a hot spot for
reporters. There was good copy and even better images of poverty
amid plenty: gap-toothed coal miners living in shacks, lovely
rolling hills littered with the hulks of wrecked cars.
</P>
<P>
   President Johnson sat on the front porch of a humble house and
declared his War on Poverty. After that, says a local newspaper
publisher interviewed for Barret's film, ``Almost every time you
looked out there was a newspaper reporter or magazine reporter or
television reporter or crew coming through.'' Barret shows us
headlines from The New York Times (``Poverty, Squalor and Idleness
Prevail in Mountain Area'') and CBS news film from a report by
Charles Kuralt, which showed poor rural children singing Christmas
carols.
</P>
<P>
   Barret, who grew up on the prosperous side of the tracks,
recalls feeling embarrassed for those children, who didn't live far
from her. But then she lets us hear from the local newspaper
publisher, who insists that the reports were necessary because the
area's troubles were real. ``The nation really needed to know and
we needed the help of the nation,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Hugh O'Connor and Hobart Ison came to symbolize the two camps:
journalists seeking to right wrongs by exposing them and civilians
who felt they were being snooped on by outsiders who edited their
stories to suit a particular narrative, even if it wasn't the
entire truth.
</P>
<P>
   Barret manages to make both of them sympathetic, though it's
more of a stretch for Ison, who vented his outrage (even if it's
made understandable) with unacceptable violence. But, as someone
says, he was a man of his time and place.
</P>
<P>
   The Ison family went to eastern Kentucky at the end of the 19th
century and bought lots of land. Hobart's bond to that land was
fierce, his relatives explain. He didn't seem to have much else.
His fiancee broke their engagement, whereupon he locked the cozy
house he had built for them and let it stand unused, a monument to
his failed romance. Besides his land, he loved his guns; he would
go as far as Alaska to hunt. Even his family did not know him well,
just that he would help anyone who asked but had no tolerance for
trespassers.
</P>
<P>
   In Ison's eyes, O'Connor was the ultimate trespasser. Hired to
make a film about poverty in America, the Canadian documentary
maker had stopped with his crew at a shanty owned by Ison, who
rented several such houses _ and asked the miner living there if he
could film him with his baby. The miner agreed. Word travels fast
in the country and Ison heard what was going on. He drove over and
fired several shots. Two were lodged in the camera, and one
exploded in O'Connor's chest.
</P>
<P>
   Reading from his New Yorker article, Trillin describes the
moment: ``O'Connor briefly looked down in amazement and saw a hole
in his chest, and he looked up in despair, and said, `Why did you
have to do that?'''
</P>
<P>
   With heart-wrenching acuity, Barret has explained why.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `STRANGER WITH A CAMERA' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   10 p.m. ET Tuesday on PBS (Channel 13, New York)
</P>
<P>
   Dee Davis, executive producer; Elizabeth Barret, producer and
director; Judi Jennings, co-producer; Lucy Massie Phenix, editor
and director of editing; Peter Pearce and Martin Duckworth, camera.
A co-production of Appalshop and Kentucky Educational Television,
produced in association with ITVS. For POV: Cara Mertes, executive
producer. Produced by American Documentary Inc.; Ellen Schneider,
executive director; Ward Chamberlin, chief executive officer.
Narrated by Fenton Johnson. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
