<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-FENCING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     U.S. TEAM HAS BIG HOPES IN OLYMPIC FENCING 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK WANGRIN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The few. The proud. The U.S. fencing team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of these Olympics, what makes them so special, is that we
had to qualify,'' said Cliff Bayer of New York, who will make the
trip to Sydney, Australia, in September to compete in the men's
foil at the Summer Games. ``Instead of the 15 we had in Atlanta,
we'll only have eight. But the good thing is everybody has a
legitimate chance of a good result. I don't think that's happened
before.''
</P>
<P>
   At the U.S. National Championships/Olympic Fencing Trials at the
Austin Convention Center last weekend, optimism was high that what
the U.S. team lacks in numbers it will more than make up for in
performance.
</P>
<P>
   There is a legitimate chance for three medals in Sydney _ 1996
Olympian Bayer, women's foil fencer Iris Zimmerman of Rush, N.Y.,
and the women's foil team _ with hope that Iris' sister Felicia
Zimmerman in women's foil and Tamir Bloom of New York in men's epee
could also finish high. The U.S. team has won only one medal in the
past 40 years, a bronze by Peter Westbrook in the saber competition
in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Since fencing was first held in 1900 the U.S. team has won only
five individual and three team Olympic medals, none of them gold.
The 2000 competition is expected to be dominated by fencers from
the typically strong nations of Italy, Germany, France, Hungary,
Poland, Cuba, Russia and China, but the Olympics format will allow
for some surprises.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most competitions, the field is small. Only about 40
fencers will compete in each of the five weapons _ men's foil, epee
and saber and women's foil and epee _ and there will be
single-elimination bouts. At the national championships, there were
about 150 fencers in each class who were required to advance out of
round-robin pool competition before facing off in a
double-elimination tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Each bout at the Olympics will be decided by the first fencer to
reach 15 points, or touches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very simple, yes,'' said U.S. co-coach Yefim Litvan. ``But
very tough. You need a little luck _ and God has to like you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pretty crazy format,'' Bayer said. ``There are 30
people who can win. You have to turn yourself into a complete
psychopath to go out and win.''
</P>
<P>
   Rounding out the team are Ann Marsh of Buffalo, N.Y., and
alternate Erinn Smart of Brooklyn, N.Y., in the women's foil,
Arlene Stevens of Rochester, N.Y., in the women's epee, and Keeth
Smart of Brooklyn and Akhnaten Spencer of New York in the men's
saber.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
