   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-SUMMIT _ WASHINGTON _ President Clinton will open a Camp
David summit Tuesday between Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat. As they were in 1978 when
President Jimmy Carter brokered the historic Camp David accords
that began the peace process, the stakes this time are high for all
those involved. (Deans, Cox News Service). 25.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-BARAK _ JERUSALEM _ If anyone thought Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak would let a little political trouble keep him
from going to the Camp David summit, they should look at their
calendars. Three days ago was the deadline he set for withdrawing
Israeli troops from Lebanon, but he had already beat that date by
six weeks. He's back in commando mode, challenging the conventional
wisdom and refusing to interrupt his ``mission'' _ the word he uses
for his peace efforts. Almost exactly a year since he took office,
Barak Monday appeared to have staved off parliamentary attempts to
pull down his government and headed off for a date with President
Clinton, Yasser Arafat and, some speculate, his place in history.
Newspapers and some in the Israeli public Monday decried the
erstwhile allies that had abandoned Barak on the eve of the summit.
Some compared him to Israeli founding father David Ben-Gurion, who
charged ahead even when fearful allies hesitated. (Kaplow, Cox News
Service). 25.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-SPACE _ MOSCOW _ Rejecting last minute evidence of
potential safety risks, the United States and Russia are prepared
to launch the key module of the controversial International Space
Station, hoping to jump-start the 16-year-old project that would
allow humans to permanently live and work in space. (Coker, Cox
News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDS NOTE TIME ELEMENT: The scheduled launch in Russia will take
place about 1 a.m. Eastern time on Wednesday. Thus, this setup
story should run Tuesday.
</P>
