Journal-Constitution). 12.
</P>
<P>
   APPLIED _ SAN FRANCISCO _ When it comes to semiconductors,
smaller is usually better _ except when it comes to making them,
that is. For years, semiconductor makers have been inching toward a
new production process that would double the number of chips they
could produce on a single wafer _ the thin waffle-like disks of
silicon where semiconductors get their start. But until now, they
haven't had all the equipment needed for mass production. Today,
Applied Materials Inc. is expected to introduce the first complete
line of equipment to make chips on bigger and higher capacity 300
millimeter silicon wafers, which could finally get the chip
industry on the fast track to building more efficient
effectivefactories. (Keefe, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
