<P>
   SUMMER-KIDS _Time was when summer for a teen-ager meant mixing
sodas at the corner drugstore, mowing lawns, attending summer
school or hanging out at the pool. Although plenty of kids are
still engaging in traditional summer activities, ``thinking about
it'' has become a high priority for baby boomer parents anxious to
make sure their kids have opportunities they didn't have. They're
determined their youngsters will have a leg up when it's time for
applications and resumes. And when they talk about their kids
seeing the ``real world,'' they're more likely to be referring to
Australia or Africa than the inside of a factory. (Dayton Daily
News)
</P>
<P>
   PRACTICAL-MAN _ The practical man got soaked last week. At the
movies. He thought he was going to see The Perfect Storm _ a
tough-minded sea-going tragedy based on a gripping book of the same
name. But it
</P>
<P>
   turned out to be The Perfect Corn _ a sappy sea-going snoozer
based on a dozen other cheesy melodramas he's moped through in his
moviegoing life. (Practical Man, Palm Beach Post). 50 inches.
</P>
<P>
   LILLYLINENS _ It's a hot one in Palm Beach, but Lilly Pulitzer
Rousseau is keeping cool at home, her island retreat with the thick
tropical jungle, the one she playfully calls ``the Palm Beach
Taj.'' There's going to be a party on this night to celebrate some
family
</P>
<P>
   birthdays, and she plans to be ready for a summery fiesta, right
down to the margarita machine. (Graulich, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   CLERMONT _ CLERMONT _ If you are looking for a pleasant,
inexpensive, fun-Disneyfied weekend getaway, within three hours'
drive of Palm Beach
</P>
<P>
   County, then take the high ground. Here, within a few minutes'
drive of each other, are three inexpensive
</P>
<P>
   tourist attractions, an atmce again tackle the issue of the
rights of Gays within the denomination. Church members are also
expected to debate and vote on a number of other issues that may
have more resonance on the local level than the sometimes fuzzy
issue of homosexuality. Delegates plan to break into small groups
to discuss racism, violence, ethnic diversity, liturgy and
end-of-life issues. The meeting ends on Thursday. (GWhite, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
<P>
   BIGBUGS _ A Chinese praying mantis more than 21 feet long
extending its sharp forearms to catch prey is making its home at
the Boonshoft Museum of Discovery through Sept. 10. The ``What Bugs
Us'' exhibit from Kokoro Ltd. in Tokyo, Japan, includes robotic
insects more than 600 times life size and a roomful of live
insects, including the walking stick and hissing cockroaches, plus
an array of close-up bug pictures accompanied by educational
information. (Dayton Daily News) WITH PHOTOS. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   OSTEOPOROSIS _ The best predictor of osteoporosis, the
bone-thinning disease that afflicts millions of women and some men,
is heredity. Talking to a Decatur, Ga., woman and her mother who
are a good example and to doctors about new research into
prevention, treatment. (Guthrie, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 30.
WITH GRAPHIC, PHOTOS.
