<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8102 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-BARAK-0711-CO     07-10 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-BARAK-0711-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BARAK SURVIVES VOTE, GOES TO SUMMIT WEAK BUT DETERMINED
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service(at)
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Bounding up the steps to his jet, Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak Monday looked happy to leave troubles at home
and eager to make a mark on history.
</P>
<P>
   He was headed to Camp David for Tuesday's scheduled start of a
summit with President Clinton and Palestinian President Yasser
Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   He had just survived a parliamentary no-confidence vote, which
had been raised by those opposed to holding the summit. His
government coalition had fallen apart the day before, when three
parties against the summit resigned.
</P>
<P>
   The no-confidence motion received 54 votes in favor and only 52
against, but abstentions and absences kept it short of the 61 votes
that could have ultimately made Barak's government fall and face
new elections.
</P>
<P>
   Highlighting the dissension, heckling members of parliament
interrupted an address by Barak. They forced him to stop for
minutes at a time as they sometimes laughed and joked with each
other.
</P>
<P>
   But at Ben-Gurion International Airport, Barak was finally able
to deliverhis pitch without interruption.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difficulties of peace are better than the agonies of
war,'' Barak said, quoting the late Israeli Prime Minister Menachem
Begin, who made peace with Egypt at Camp David 22 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear the real voice of the Israeli citizens and they are
bolstering me with their support,'' Barak said.
</P>
<P>
   The 58-year-old prime minister just completed a year in office
Friday. His popularity is sagging and his government is hobbled.
Cabinet ministers double and triple their duties to fill in for
others who had resigned.
</P>
<P>
   But, if anyone doubts Barak's determination to get to this
summit, they should note that Friday was also his self-imposed
deadline for pulling Israeli troops out of Lebanon. He had beaten
that deadline, to the amazement of the world, six weeks earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Now Israel's most decorated soldier is back in commando mode,
talking about the ``mission'' to make peace and the need to keep
his eyes on the ``target.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He thinks what he is facing is in the magnitude of the
founding fathers of Israel,'' said Dan Pattir, a Barak supporter
who was Begin's spokesman at Camp David. ``He's in a tough
situation. On the other hand, he likes to act against the odds.''
</P>
<P>
   Pattir pointed out that Barak might not come home with a deal.
In fact, he said, he could just be trying to make it clear that
Israel wants peace.
</P>
<P>
   Or, Barak could return with a deal and put it to a public
referendum that re-solidifies his hold on power. Analysts disagree
on whether Barak's government problems will restrict him in the
talks, or make him feel he has little to lose by making a deal.
</P>
<P>
   Ariel Sharon, leader of the opposition Likud Party, which
opposes the summit, chided Barak as ``prime minister of almost no
one.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Barak could take heart in an opinion poll Monday in the
Yedioth Ahronoth newspaper showing that, despite his coalition's
collapse, 52 percent of Israelis favored the summit. Further, 53
percent recognized that concessions would have to be made to the
Palestinians. The nationwide survey of 502 adults had an error
margin of plus or minus 4.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Camp David-II already had one newspaper columnist comparing him
to Israeli founding father David Ben-Gurion. Others said his
political problems were a result of the same arrogance and
confidence that make Barak a leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barak's clumsy political moves and his mistaken tendency to
rely only on himself rightly raise serious concerns,'' wrote Hemi
Shalev, of the Ma'ariv daily. But, he added, ``He has courage. He
always has had. He goes for it, and big-time, whatever 'it' may
be.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the heckles of the parliament, Barak declared that ``the
moment of truth is upon us.''
</P>
<P>
   He called his critics the same ``false prophets'' who opposed
Begin's trip to the first Camp David summit and who told Barak he
could not pull the troops out of Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   On the dark airport runway, Barak spoke again and sang the
Israeli national anthem while standing next to his foreign
minister, David Levy. Even Levy, once a confidante, is boycotting
the talks.
</P>
<P>
   Barak shook his hand warmly, hugged wife Nava Barak, then turned
and trotted alone up the steps to the airplane.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Kaplow can be e-mailed at: larryk(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
