<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8104 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-SUMMER-KIDS-COX     07-10 1365
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUMMER-KIDS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Summer doesn't necessarily mean working teen-agers
 &HT;    By Meredith Moss
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio - Time was when summer for a teen-ager meant mixing
sodas at the corner drugstore, mowing lawns, attending summer
school or hanging out at the pool.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we were old enough to work, we'd hunt for summer jobs in
a factory or some type of business,'' recalls Don Eifert, a retired
high school guidance counselor who in his teens worked in a steel
plant in Coldwater, a Meadow Gold creamery in New Bremen and in the
millwright shop at NCR.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard but it was a good thing because I learned what the
real world was about,'' says Eifert. ``You did it and didn't think
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Although plenty of kids are still engaging in traditional summer
activities, ``thinking about it'' has become a high priority for
baby boomer parents anxious to make sure their kids have
opportunities they didn't have. They're determined their youngsters
will have a leg up when it's time for applications and resumes. And
when they talk about their kids seeing the ``real world,'' they're
more likely to be referring to Australia or Africa than the inside
of a factory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see a lot more parents pointing their children to some type
of educational activity in the summer,'' says Eifert, who worked at
Colonel White, Oakwood and Hillel Academy high schools during his
35-year career. ``It might be an educational camp on a college
campus or a travel program.'' Admissions officers and employers, he
adds, often look at how students choose to spend summer months.
</P>
<P>
   Pick up one of the books on summer options for teens and you'll
get some idea of the range of summer programs. Kids can sign on for
wilderness travel in Central America, study Spanish in Biarritz, go
sailing in the British Virgin Islands and do community service on a
reservation in South Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   Susie Katz, a Kettering mother of two, says one of the reasons
she and her husband have worked hard is to give their children
opportunities to experience the ``bigger world.''
</P>
<P>
   Daughter Alex, 20, has spent two summers in Israel, taken art
history and international studies courses at Georgetown University
in Washington, studied art in Nice and worked as a nanny in Geneva,
Switzerland. This summer she's working at the Smithsonian
Institution in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of my friends thought I was excessive and that our kids
should be working to learn the value of a dollar,'' says Katz, who
spent her own teen summers in school because her parents both
worked and couldn't afford expensive excursions. ``I feel you have
your whole adult life to work so if your family is in a situation
where they can access these kinds of programs, they should.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are plenty of other ways to teach children the value of
a dollar that don't commit them to slinging hamburgers all summer
long.''
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca Jacobs, 22, says taking classes in Colorado, Washington,
D.C., and Oxford, England, has taught her how to adjust to new
surroundings and new people.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to learn to rely on yourself and to figure out things
on your own,'' says the recent Washington University grad from
Vandalia. ``I learned how to get to London on the bus; I had to
figure out the Metro in Paris. There was a bus strike in Rome and I
had to find a hotel overnight. It gave me self-confidence to
realize I could do all that.''
</P>
<P>
   Donna Moosbrugger, who has been a senior counselor at Butler
High School in Vandalia for 23 years, says the biggest change she's
seen is the new emphasis on sports camps.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are quarterback camps, camps for volleyball players,
team camps,'' she says. ``It's about improving skills and being fit
and I think it's fine for the most part.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank Mannarino, a sports medicine doctor who spent last week in
Wilmington, N.C., with his daughter's high school basketball team,
says he played sports as a teen in New Jersey, but he didn't do it
in such an organized way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see a big need for kids to be working in the summer,''
he adds. ``I don't think they should be idle and if they don't have
other activities, they should get a job, but if they have a major
commitment to something else, that's great.''
</P>
<P>
   Some teens opt for paid or unpaid internships.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Saphire of Dayton, Pete Gambill of Vandalia and Terry Posey
Jr. of Tipp City have been interning for U.S. Rep. Tony Hall
(D-Dayton) in Washington this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It puts all the book learning I've been doing into practice,''
says Saphire, who says interns answer phones, open mail, do
legislative research, give tours and answers letters from
constituents.
</P>
<P>
   Gambill views summer as a time to extend his horizons. ``The
world is getting smaller and people want to be a part of things
that are bigger than the towns they grew up in,'' he says, adding
he's made a point of working for role models he admires.
</P>
<P>
   Oakwood High School art teacher Kaye Carlile spent eight summers
escorting groups of her students to Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did everything from picnicking in the vineyards of Tuscany
to visiting to the Louvre in Paris and riding donkeys to the top of
Santorini, a little Greek Island,'' says Carlile, who believes it's
important for kids to realize that ``although people are unique
from country to country, we are all very much alike.''
</P>
<P>
   Times were different, she says, when she was growing up in Tipp
City.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to the end of the street and hiked at a nearby farm.
Today's kids are boarding a trans-Atlantic plane and hiking through
Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   Parents, counselors and teens all stress it's important to check
out a summer program thoroughly before signing up. And while many
programs are costly, it is possible to seek out scholarships or
part-time jobs to help pay the tab.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the Muse Machine's Lorenzo Bassani Visual Arts
Scholarship, Stivers art student William Penn of Dayton was able to
attend a two-week visual arts seminar in Colorado Springs this
summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``My whole drawing technique changed there,'' says Penn, 17.
``They made me do a whole different thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Although many summer programs are worthwhile, Don Eifert says he
hates to see too much pressure put on high school students to build
for their futures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Working a hard job is physical but I didn't feel the kind of
pressure that the kids feel today,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Carlile also expresses concern that many youths and teen-agers
are so heavily scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Summer should be a balance between doing something enriching _
like special lessons or travel _ and having the opportunity for
spontaneous adventure and self-discovery,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need to have some time when you get up in the morning and
say, 'What am I going to do today?'''
</P>
<P>
   Contact Meredith Moss at meredithmoss(at)coxohio.com or at
225-2440.
</P>
<P>
   THINKING ABOUT SUMMER 2001
</P>
<P>
   Here are some resources for summer programs for teens and
collegians:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  High school guidance counselors typically receive lots of
information on summer programs and can also put you in touch with
students at your school who have participated in them.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Pay a visit to the library or bookstore. Here's a sampling of
helpful books:
</P>
<P>
   ``Summer Opportunities for Kids and Teenagers'' (Peterson's,
$29.95) lists a wide range of programs including academic, travel,
internships and summer specialty camps. The giant book _ it's 1,650
pages _ arranges topics by states and countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Yale Daily News Guide to Summer Programs'' by Sara
Schwebel (Kaplan, $22) has a large section for arts and music
programs and also includes study abroad. Other sections range from
community service and leadership programs to athletic and outdoor
adventure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ACA Accredited Camps'' features 2,200 day, resident and
trip and travel camps (American Camping Association, $19.95).
</P>
<P>
   ``America's Top Internships'' (Princeton Review, $21) includes
more than 18,000 internship positions.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Web site: Check out Peterson's Education SuperSite for 2,400
summer programs for kids and teens: www.petersons.com
</P>
