<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8110 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r p BC-POLITICAL-CONTRIBUTIO     07-10 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-CONTRIBUTIONS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CAMPAIGN FINANCE MEASURE TO GET ANOTHER COURT HEARING 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ZACHARY COILE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Four years ago, California voters bucked the
political establishment and passed a ballot measure setting
stringent limits on contributions to state candidates and
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, Proposition 208, allowed donors to give no more
than $100 to local officials, $250 to legislators and $500 to
statewide candidates, or double that amount if the candidates
agreed to voluntary spending limits.
</P>
<P>
   But the initiative met the same fate as nearly every other
attempt by voters to change the system by which campaigns are
funded in California: It was tossed out by a federal judge as
unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the same judge who rejected the 1996 initiative is
scheduled to begin hearing arguments in a second trial over
Proposition 208 in U.S. District Court in Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   An appeals court sent it back for a second trial so more
testimony could be heard.
</P>
<P>
   Proposition 208 was the law of land for just more than a year.
Shortly after it went into effect in January 1997, the major
political parties, unions and several conservative groups filed
suit, arguing the measure discriminates against some candidates and
restricts political speech.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Lawrence K. Karlton of Sacramento ultimately
agreed. After a three-week trial, he issued a preliminary
injunction, blocking the measure.
</P>
<P>
   The judge's decision created a political vacuum, leaving no
restrictions on contributions in a state that has become a showcase
for the pervasiveness and influence of money in politics.
</P>
<P>
   With the second trial looming and the future of Proposition 208
in doubt, the Legislature scrambled this week to put a new campaign
finance measure on the Nov. 7 ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Gray Davis, a Democrat, supports the initiative, but reform
advocates have blasted it as an effort to repeal Proposition 208
and replace it with a package of weaker restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole proposition is drafted by politicians for
politicians,'' said former Secretary of State Tony Miller, a
proponent of Proposition 208. ``They are protecting themselves,
notwithstanding what the people did in 1996.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's trial pits the state Fair Political Practices
Commission and reform activists, who are defending the 1996
measure, against some of the state's most influential political
groups: the Democratic and Republican state parties, several labor
unions, the California Pro-Life Council and others who filed suit
in 1997 to block the measure.
</P>
<P>
   Since the court threw out Proposition 208 in January 1998, state
legislators and top elected officials have been raking in
substantial campaign donations. Davis alone reported raising $13.2
million in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Despite voter support for contribution limits, the courts have
been hostile to such restrictions, saying they limit political free
speech. Before Proposition 208, two other California measures were
largely invalidated by the courts.
</P>
<P>
   ``There obviously is public interest in the imposition of these
kinds of limits,'' said Lawrence T. Woodlock, senior counsel to the
Fair Political Practices Commission. ``I suspect there is some
frustration on the part of members of the public that they keep
voting these things in and the courts keep throwing them out.
Sooner or later one of the measures is going to stick.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Proposition 208 was approved in November 1996 with 61 percent of
the vote. The measure, co-sponsored by Common Cause, the League of
Women Voters, the American Association of Retired Persons and
United We Stand, a Ross Perot spinoff group, called for:
</P>
<P>
   _ Restricting fund-raising to within one year of the primary for
statewide candidates and within six months of the primary for
legislative races.
</P>
<P>
   _ Limiting contributions to political action committees, or
PACs, to $500 per calendar year, and gifts to political parties to
$5,000 per calendar year.
</P>
<P>
   _ Setting voluntary spending limits of $14 million for the
governor's race, $3.5 million for other statewide offices, $700,000
for state Senate races and $350,000 for Assembly races.
</P>
<P>
   _ Allowing donors to give no more than $100 to local officials,
$250 to legislators and $500 to statewide candidates, or double if
the candidates agreed to voluntary spending limits.
</P>
<P>
   In his 1997 decision, Karlton found that restrictions on when
candidates could raise money unfairly hindered their ability to
seek contributions via direct mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``The effect of the initiative is not only to significantly
reduce a California candidate's ability to deliver his or her
message, but in fact to make it impossible for the ordinary
candidate to mount an effective campaign for office,'' the judge
wrote in his 43-page decision.
</P>
<P>
   The Fair Political Practices Commission appealed to the 9th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals, which sent the case back to the judge for
a second trial, for more testimony.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
