<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8128 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e BC-JASON-BIGGS-IN-LOSER-     07-10 1192
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JASON-BIGGS-IN-LOSER-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOSER TAKE ALL: JASON BIGGS IS A WINNING `LOSER' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Jason Biggs in a scene from ``Loser.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    Talk about the perfect storm.
 &HT;    ```American Pie' put me on the map and it got the storm going,
got it brewing,'' says actor Jason Biggs, who so memorably shared
an intimate moment with a warm apple pie in last summer's sleeper
hit. ``I've got two movies out this summer and I'm working on two
more movies. Everything is heating up even more.
 &HT;    ``It's really, really exciting and it's really cool,'' the young
actor says. ``I'll tell you what, I don't mind these conditions. I
hope it doesn't stop storming for a long time, man _ I hope I don't
see the sun for a while.''
 &HT;    Biggs may not be quite ready to give George Clooney a run for
his money, either as a hunk or as a box-office draw, but he's
getting there. With dark hair and a broad smile that make him
resemble a young Adam Sandler, Biggs chased ``American Pie'' with
this summer's dreadful ``Boys and Girls,'' scoring the film's only
positive notices with his entertaining turn as Freddie Prinze Jr.'s
quirky, advice-spouting college sidekick.
 &HT;    And on July 21 Biggs will sweep back into theaters with
``Loser,'' a romantic comedy from Amy Heckerling, the director of
``Fast Times at Ridgemont High'' (1982) and ``Clueless'' (1995).
Biggs plays Paul Tannek, a good-natured small-town kid struggling
to hold his own at college in New York, a task made harder by
Paul's knack for hideous hats, pratfalls and abuse from others.
 &HT;    Along the way, he falls for Dora _ played by Biggs' ``American
Pie'' co-star Mena Suvari _ a student with precious little money, a
lot of attitude and the hots for an English-literature professor
(Greg Kinnear). Paul and Dora are perfect for each other, of
course, but that's something they need to discover for themselves.
 &HT;    ``I want to say it was easy to play a dork,'' the amiable Biggs
says by telephone from Los Angeles' Four Seasons hotel, where he's
busily promoting ``Loser.'' ``Is that weird? `Yeah, it was a piece
of cake!'
 &HT;    ``In `American Pie' and here again in `Loser' I'm playing that
guy who is kind of the outsider, who is kind of dorky,'' he
explains. ``The cool thing about it in both cases for me, and the
challenge for me, is that the audience has to like these guys, root
for them and sympathize with them, or else the movie doesn't work.
 &HT;    ``I could certainly relate to Paul, to an extent,'' Biggs adds.
``I think everyone can. Maybe I'm just saying that to make myself
feel better, but I can relate to feeling like an outsider at times.
I certainly felt that way in high school and especially when I went
off to college (New York University for a semester, then New
Jersey's Montclair State University for a few weeks).
 &HT;    ``I still feel like an outsider at times.''
 &HT;    To Hollywood, however, Biggs is rapidly becoming an insider. He
assumes leading-man status with ``Loser.'' He's the guy, the male
star. He's the loser.
 &HT;    ``It's cool,'' he admits, ``but I've never looked at it, and nor
do I now, as `I want this rested on my shoulders. It's my name, my
movie, I'm the lead, blah, blah, blah.' To me, yeah, I'm playing
the titular loser, but it's Amy's film, and Mena is as much a part
of it as I am.
 &HT;    ``That Amy, who also wrote the script for the movie, wanted me
to play her guy, her loser who she wanted to bring to life on
screen through me, was just such a thrill,'' Biggs says. ``I'd pay
to work with her. There's also Greg Kinnear and Jimmi Simpson,
Thomas Sadoski and Zak Orth, who play my roommates.
 &HT;    ``Yeah, I'm the loser, but there's no `Loser' without everyone
else.''
 &HT;    Biggs will turn up next in a dramatic role, co-starring as the
boyfriend of deeply troubled Christina Ricci in the upcoming
adaptation of Elizabeth Wurtzel's ``Prozac Nation.'' Then he'll
take the lead in ``Saving Silverman,'' a comedy about a recently
engaged young man (Biggs) whose friends (Jack Black and Steve Zahn)
try to convince their pal that his fiancee (Amanda Peet) is an evil
shrew. Down the line, of course, he's likely to pocket a small
fortune for ``American Pie 2.''
 &HT;    Many actors in Biggs' enviable position have blown the
opportunity. They've sold out for huge paychecks. They've become
major jerks. Or both. Or worse.
 &HT;    Biggs, who grew up in Hasbrouck Heights, N.J., and counts among
his earlier credits the television shows ``Drexel's Class''
(1991-1992), ``As the World Turns'' (1994-1995) and ``Total
Security'' (1997), as well as the Broadway play ``Conversations
with My Father'' on Broadway, vows that temptation won't get the
better of him.
 &HT;    ``Money?'' he says. ``I'm doing well for my age. I don't need to
sell out for big paychecks at this point in my career. Hopefully I
never will. I'm doing fine. Because of `American Pie,' I can be a
bit pickier about my roles.
 &HT;    ``It sounds trite, but I'm all about my work,'' he says. ``I'm
about making the right choices, having fun with my characters and
working with the right people. I don't want to do a crappy movie
for a big paycheck _ I'd rather do an awesome movie for nothing.''
 &HT;    Biggs also would rather not evolve into a jerk, if it's all the
same.
 &HT;    ``I'd like to think I've got my head on pretty straight,'' says
the actor, who is single and lives in Los Angeles. ``As far as ego
and becoming a hard person to deal with, I attribute my not falling
into that to the way I was raised. I'm a firm believer in karma _
what goes around comes around.
 &HT;    ``I have no desire to be a jerk, to be that guy who is hard to
deal with,'' Biggs says. ``I want to have fun. I want to be the guy
everyone talks about as, `Wow, man, he's cool. He's nice. And he's
great to work with.'
 &HT;    ``It would make me feel good to think other people think that.''
 c.2000 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
