<SLUG> BC-DURAN-DURAN-IS-BACK-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROCKING ON: DURAN DURAN MAY BE DOWN, BUT THEY'RE NOT OUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of the rock band Duran Duran, including
members Simon LeBon, Nick Rhodes and Warren Cuccurullo.) 
 By GARY GRAFF  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    It's been nearly 20 years since Duran Duran blew out of England
to declare that ``This is planet Earth'' and become the 'N Sync of
the 1980s.
 &HT;    But though those heady days are long gone, the group has
released its 11th album, ``Pop Trash,'' and its members say they're
still ``Hungry Like the Wolf.''
 &HT;    ``I think we've had a hard time since the sort of hysteria and
screaming of the mid-'80s,'' keyboardist Nick Rhodes says. ``We
really lost a lot of ground with the more serious end of the music
press.
 &HT;    ``I think music lovers stuck with us because they liked the
music, they liked the songs,'' Rhodes says. ``They saw where we
were coming from and really listened to the records _ they knew
there was plenty of depth in there and interesting ideas and some
good tunes, and they stuck with it.
 &HT;    ``But I think a lot of the media just thought, `OK, this is for
girls now. This isn't something for a serious audience,''' he
concludes. ``It was a double-edged sword: It helped propel us into
a much stronger position with a bigger audience, but at the same
time I think we lost a lot of the momentum we had for, I suppose,
what is normally termed credibility _ although I'm not sure that
word means anything.''
 &HT;    Credibility is, in fact, what Duran Duran had at the outset of
its career in 1980, when the group's original lineup came together
and recorded bouncy, danceable pop songs such as ``Girls on Film''
and ``Planet Earth'' that _ in addition to the group's haute
fashion and stylish videos _ were considered cutting-edge pop at
the dawn of the MTV age.
 &HT;    But within two years Duran's cult appeal went widescreen with
hits such as ``Hungry Like the Wolf,'' ``Rio,'' ``Save a Prayer''
and ``Union of the Snake,'' and the group was the object of the
same kind of screaming, teen-oriented mass adulation that the
Backstreet Boys and 'N Sync experience today. Rolling Stone
magazine even dubbed the quintet ``The Fab Five'' in recognition of
their Beatles-like popularity.
 &HT;    ``We got a ride and we thought it was going to slow down any
minute,'' the 38-year-old Rhodes says. ``But it didn't slow down
for five years.''
 &HT;    The group actually put the brakes on itself, dividing into two
separate camps to form the side groups Power Station and Arcadia.
Members began to drop out along the way _ first guitarist Andy
Taylor and drummer Roger Taylor, then bassist John Taylor in 1997.
Rhodes and frontman Simon LeBon now comprise the band, along with
former Frank Zappa and Missing Persons guitarist Warren Cuccurullo,
who joined during 1987.
 &HT;    Beside those departures, Duran Duran also suffered the
inevitable backlash that comes with great success. A series of
albums during the late 1980s and early 1990s were met with
indifference, as their fans moved on to other pop heroes and then
to heavier modern-rock heroes such as Nirvana and Pearl Jam.
 &HT;    The group enjoyed a spike during 1993 with two Top 10 singles _
``Ordinary World'' and ``Come Undone'' _ but hasn't made the charts
since.
 &HT;    ``We came out of being a nostalgia item and became a current
item, which was very important for us,'' the 41-year-old LeBon
says. ``But we never stopped working _ we tried and tried and tried
again to become current. There's never been a comeback as far as
we're concerned.''
 &HT;    Likewise, the group has purposefully avoided becoming part of
the 1980s pop revues that dot the concert landscape, especially
during the summer season.
 &HT;    ``Oh my God, I can't think of anything worse,'' Rhodes says with
a laugh. ``We're not a nostalgia act. I have no problem with anyone
from the '80s, '90s or '70s going out and earning a living and
giving people a good time at a show. That's fine _ just not our
thing.
 &HT;    ``We acknowledge that we came out of the '80s,'' he adds, ``but
then so did Prince. So did Madonna. So did U2. So did Depeche Mode.
A lot of interesting things came out that are still relevant and
creative and fresh.''
 &HT;    With ``Pop Trash,'' Duran Duran is trying to rebound from the
commercial and creative disappointment of its 1997 album
``Medazzaland,'' which led to the group's departure from its
longtime label, Capitol Records, and its eventual signing with
Hollywood Records, the musical arm of the Disney empire.
 &HT;    ``We had a bad taste in our mouth after the `Medazzaland'
debacle,'' LeBon says. ``We basically lost the interest of our
record company _ they didn't want to put more money behind it and
promote it.
 &HT;    ``But while there's the temptation to try to pass the buck and
blame other people,'' the singer adds, ``in the back of your mind
you think, `Yeah, if it had been a stronger piece of work, maybe
things would have gone better.'''
 &HT;    LeBon, Rhodes and Cuccurullo had reason to be optimistic about
``Pop Trash,'' however. They were excited about the album's first
single, ``Someone Else Not Me,'' which had been conceived during a
promotional video shoot for ``Medazzaland,'' while the three
musicians jammed on a riff Cucurullo began playing during a break
in the session.
 &HT;    ``We put it away,'' LeBon says, ``and after (`Medazzaland') came
out and we toured and everything, we went back in and the first
thing we started working on was that song. It was a good starting
point, and really set a standard for the rest of the album that
inspired us.''
 &HT;    Duran Duran also received an unexpected gift in the form of the
song ``Pop Trash Movie,'' which ultimately gave the album its
title. Rhodes and Cuccurullo had written it for Blondie's reunion
album, and went so far as to conceal it from LeBon, for fear that
he'd want to keep it for Duran Duran.
 &HT;    But when Blondie wound up not using the song, all three were
quick to snap it up for their own album.
 &HT;    ``I was rubbing my hands with glee and said, `Well, I'll have
that,''' says LeBon, who ceded most of the lyric writing on ``Pop
Trash'' to Rhodes. ``I hadn't heard it. It's a great song, and they
knew damn well if I'd have ever heard it before it went to Blondie,
I'd have wanted it. They were being clever.
 &HT;    ``But I think Duran Duran's done a better job with it.''
 &HT;    Rhodes agrees.
 &HT;    ``In a way, all the irony and humor of it suited us in exactly
the same way it suited Blondie,'' he says. ``I often see many
parallels with some of the things they'd done and some of the
things we'd done. We stayed together, but we had our down periods,
too _ although perhaps not as gruesome as theirs.
 &HT;    ``But I think they were very innovative, with a lot of good
ideas,'' he says, ``and perhaps didn't get the credit they
deserved. They wrote some amazing songs.''
 &HT;    The same, of course, might be said of Duran Duran. But while the
days of the Fab Five may be long gone, Rhodes says the remaining
three see enough evidence of their impact to feel redeemed.
 &HT;    ``We've learned that success isn't measured by how many records
you sell,'' the keyboardist says. ``But I still get the greatest
kick out of seeing someone dance to one of our songs. To me, that's
as important as anyone buying the record.''
 c.2000 Gary Graff  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Gary Graff is a Beverly Hills, Mich.-based free-lance
writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Pop Trash,'' consult the
official Duran Duran Web site at www.duranduran.com. And don't
forget to visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
