<HEADER>
A8130 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e BC-THE-WEITZ-BROTHERS-IN     07-10 1386
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THE-WEITZ-BROTHERS-IN-CHUCK-&AMP;-BUCK-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROTHER ACT: THE WEITZ BROTHERS ARE HOLLYWOOD'S LATEST FRATERNAL
FILMMAKERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Chris Weitz with Michael White in a
scene from ``Chuck &AMP; Buck.'') 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago. 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    ``These days we get paid for what used to earn us trips to the
principal's office,'' Chris Weitz says.
 &HT;    It's 1 p.m. at the Los Angeles offices shared by Weitz and his
brother Paul, and the telephone won't stop ringing. It hasn't, in
fact, since last summer, when their movie ``American Pie'' _ Chris
co-produced, Paul directed _ became an unexpected $100 million
box-office hit.
 &HT;    Move over, Coen brothers. Get nervous, Wachowskis. The Weitzes
are in town.
 &HT;    And they're busy, too. Right now they're editing ``Down to
Earth,'' their remake of ``Here Comes Mr. Jordan'' (1941), starring
Chris Rock, which will debut this fall. By then ``Nutty Professor
II: The Klumps,'' which they helped pen, should be climbing the
box-office charts. And they're producing the inevitable ``American
Pie II,'' which should begin annoying parents sometime next summer.
 &HT;    Oh, and then there's the independent film ``Chuck &AMP; Buck,''
opening nationwide on July 21, in which the two actually make their
acting debuts.
 &HT;    If there's anything in the genes, they should do all right:
Their mother is Susan Kohner, who was nominated for an Oscar for
``Imitation of Life'' (1959).
 &HT;    ``It was weird for us to act, but I knew my vanity would
overcome my fear,'' Chris Weitz says. ``Plus I've known the film's
director, Miguel Arteta, since college. He asked me to do this
almost as a dare.
 &HT;    ``And once they cast me, they needed someone who would look like
me.''
 &HT;    The film is the story of Buck (Mike White), a misfit, stuck in
childhood, who lives with his mother and spends his days eating
candy and playing teen-age records. When his mother dies, Buck
meets up with his old friend Chuck (Chris Weitz) at the funeral.
 &HT;    Chuck is an agent, living in Los Angeles with his beautiful
fiancee, but Buck can't get over the fact that they're not buddies
the way they used to be. So he moves to Los Angeles and starts
stalking poor Chuck.
 &HT;    When he's rebuffed, he writes a play based on their lives called
``Hank &AMP; Frank,'' and casts a Buck look-alike (Paul Weitz) as one
of the leads.
 &HT;    ``The only trick I learned from our films was not to do too
much,'' Chris says. ``You should pare it down and let the audience
bring their own stuff to it. So most of my impulses to overact were
put aside.''
 &HT;    Particularly difficult was a semi-explicit gay love scene for
Chris.
 &HT;    ``I was nervous about stinking it up,'' he says. ``It's not a
lifestyle choice I'm familiar with, but I've never had a problem
with it, either. I've always been Mr. Politically Correct _ and now
I had to live up to my political credo.
 &HT;    ``Frankly, it wasn't as weird as a heterosexual love scene,'' he
says with a laugh, ``which is more complicated because I've done
that in real life.''
 &HT;    Both brothers claim that they didn't miss directing.
 &HT;    ``We watched our friend Miguel get more and more haggard,'' Paul
recalls. ``We would say, `Ah, that's not our problem.' When `cut'
was yelled, we'd say, `Adios!'''
 &HT;    That isn't the case with ``Down to Earth,'' on which the two are
co-writers and co-directors. It's a zany, off-the-wall comedy which
the brothers can't describe without finishing one another's
thoughts.
 &HT;    ``Chris Rock is a screw-up of a stand-up comic who is booed off
the stage at the Apollo,'' Chris says.
 &HT;    ``This screw-up angel played by Eugene Levy can't stand the
sight of blood,'' Paul chimes in, ``so he takes Chris before a
truck hits him.''
 &HT;    Rock ends up in heaven _ but not just any heaven.
 &HT;    ``Our version of heaven has a velvet rope, like when you're
trying to get into a disco,'' Paul says.
 &HT;    ``It's a 1950s supper club that stretches into infinity,'' Chris
says.
 &HT;    But it turns out that Rock's character would have survived the
accident, and so he's returned to earth ... this time in the body
of a white billionaire.
 &HT;    It's a funny concept, one which sold almost instantly _ as does
practically anything the Weitzes write, nowadays.
 &HT;    ``The funny thing is that we can't even believe it,'' Chris
says. ``We're the guys who were winging it on `American Pie.' We're
the guys who had never made a film before.''
 &HT;    ``Execs would show up to the set of `American Pie' and ask, `Do
you know what you're doing, boys?''' Paul recalls.
 &HT;    Apparently they do. The success of ``American Pie'' has made
them Hollywood's flavor of the month, which is all the more
surprising for two young men who grew up in New York, far from the
movie industry _ despite the fact that their grandfather, Paul
Kohner, was an influential Hollywood agent, representing John
Huston among others.
 &HT;    ``Strangely, show biz wasn't all around us,'' Paul says. ``Or
maybe we didn't get it. People with thick European accents like
Ingmar Bergman and Billy Wilder were cronies of our grandfather,
but we didn't realize they were great filmmakers. We were
clueless.''
 &HT;    They didn't show any especial filmmaking aptitude in their
youth, he recalls.
 &HT;    ``I tried to make a film in college and almost had a nervous
breakdown,'' Paul says. ``I didn't have any talent. I pulled the
plug on myself.''
 &HT;    Instead, the two decided to try their hand as screenwriters. A
short stint executive-producing and writing ABC's retread of
``Fantasy Island'' put them on the map, and established connections
which led to scripting chores on ``Antz'' (1998) and ``Madeline''
(1998).
 &HT;    The Weitzes then used the success of ``Antz'' to wangle the
director's chair for ``American Pie'' _ which, they admit, was
something of a shot in the dark.
 &HT;    ``I always heard good directors vomit on the way to the set the
first day,'' Paul says. ``I kept hoping and waiting to feel my
stomach churn, but it never happened. So naturally, I was very
worried.
 &HT;    ``But I guess it worked out OK,'' he says. ``I didn't do a
miserable job _ which is something I only realized in the editing
room, when the shots could actually be cut together.''
 &HT;    The two have plenty of irons in the fire _ among other things,
they're currently writing a script about the Culinary Institute of
America _ but will find time to see ``Nutty Professor II,'' if only
to see how much of their script remains in the final picture, which
was worked on by several other writers.
 &HT;    ``Frankly, we don't know how it turned out,'' Paul admits. ``As
happens on most of these things, writers come in and out. But it
was great to write for Eddie Murphy.
 &HT;    ``We actually met with Eddie, who gave us good advice,'' Paul
adds. ``He said, `Always make it fun. But when the character is the
midst of a horrifying situation, let him keep some dignity.''
 &HT;    ``So that's our rule,'' Chris says. ``We try to inject as much
emotion into a situation as possible, and then let the comedy take
care of itself.''
 c.2000 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Cindy Pearlman is a Chicago-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
