<SLUG> BC-FAREWELL-TO-KATHIE-LEE-GIFFORD-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLEEPING IN: KATHIE LEE GIFFORD SAYS GOODBYE TO `REGIS AND KATHIE
LEE' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Kathie Lee Gifford with Regis Philbin in
a scene from ``Live With Regis and Kathie Lee.'') 
 By SIMON HOUPT  
 c.2000 TV Guide Canada  
 Not to be published in Canada before July 23, 2000. 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The only thing we know for certain is that there will be tears.
</P>
<P>
   When Kathie Lee Gifford steps off the set of ``Live with Regis
and Kathie Lee'' for the last time on July 28, she will bring down
the curtain on one of the unlikeliest successes in television
talk-show history.
</P>
<P>
   The producers of ``Live With'' are planning a weeklong
commemoration of the 15 years Gifford has spent next to Regis
Philbin. Perhaps they'll treat us to some moments from the early
years when their New York-based chatfest was called simply ``The
Morning Show,'' before it was rechristened to take advantage of the
co-hosts' increasing popularity.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe we'll see Kathie Lee and Reege, our favorite dysfunctional
duo, taking each other down a notch while co-hosting the 1991 Miss
America Pageant. We'll definitely get some clips of them snapping
at each other through the years _ let's face it, that was one of
the main reasons we watched the show every morning.
</P>
<P>
   After all is said and done, though, there will be tears. You
don't end a 15-year relationship _ even one as famously
antagonistic as Philbin and Gifford's _ without some misty eyes in
the house.
</P>
<P>
   When the show began in 1985, Philbin was the household name. He
had already been a television talk-show staple for more than 20
years, beginning as a sidekick to Joey Bishop and later becoming a
well-known personality in his own right.
</P>
<P>
   Gifford, meanwhile, was nothing more than a substitute host on
``Good Morning America.'' She was hired as a second banana to
Philbin, but it didn't take long for their vinegar-and-honey
chemistry to take them to the top of the ratings.
</P>
<P>
   He was the man-about-town, telling us about the hot new
restaurants and the great shows on Broadway starring all of his
friends. She was the doting mother of two who emerged from her
Connecticut hideaway every morning just long enough to get on his
nerves.
</P>
<P>
   For awhile that's how it stayed. But in recent years each has
found new fame and fortune.
</P>
<P>
   True, there were some stumbles along the way _ after launching a
popular clothing line, Gifford weathered allegations of profiting
from sweatshops. But she's a fighter: In the end, labor advocates
cheered her for helping to shine the spotlight on sweatshop
practices around the world. She even rose above her husband's
infidelity, keeping her marriage together through a furious storm
of tabloid coverage.
</P>
<P>
   And now, at age 46, Gifford is widening her horizons. After
years of flirting with live performance, she finally made her
Broadway debut last December, replacing Carol Burnett one night a
week in the Stephen Sondheim revue ``Putting It Together.'' A new
CD on her own record label features Gifford warbling cabaret-style
renditions of songs such as Van Morrison's ``Moondance,'' Irving
Berlin's ``I Got Lost in His Arms'' and a few of her own
Broadway-style compositions.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, of course, Philbin has been keeping himself busy with
a little prime-time game show.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a good time for me to leave,'' Gifford said recently.
``Regis won't even notice I'm gone.''
</P>
<P>
   If not, he must have gone deaf and blind. In addition to five
days of farewell shows, the airwaves will be flooded with Gifford
during her final week. She'll bounce from Letterman on Wednesday to
her alma-mater ``Good Morning America'' on Thursday. On Friday,
after her final show, she'll stop by for a chat with the ladies on
``The View.''
</P>
<P>
   Philbin has been instrumental in the search for her replacement.
Co-host chemistry is the key ingredient to the unscripted,
unrehearsed ``Live With,'' so it's not going to be easy to find
someone to sit next to Philbin for an hour each day and fill in his
pauses.
</P>
<P>
   Since Gifford announced at the end of February that this would
be her final season, executive producer Michael Gelman has brought
a regular stream of hopefuls through the ``Live With'' studio in
New York, each blessed with a brief shot at the big time.
</P>
<P>
   Last month former weathergirl Jillian Barberie spent an hour at
Philbin's side, throwing around sexual innuendo in an on-air tryout
that many felt went over the top. ``Live With'' might go for her if
the show wants to attract a younger audience, but it seems more
likely that someone of an older, more conservative vintage will get
the nod.
</P>
<P>
   New York television personality Kathleen Murphy is considered a
front-runner. ``The View's'' resident comedian, Joy Behar, has
expressed interest, as have Cybill Shepherd and former ``Good
Morning America'' co-host Joan Lunden.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, so has Darva Conger, the emergency-room nurse who
became a Playboy model after her notoriously brief television
marriage to Rick Rockwell on Fox's disastrous ``Who Wants to Marry
a Multi-Millionaire?'' That would make for an interesting
spectacle: a millionaire-maker on the left and a
millionaire-marrier on the right.
</P>
<P>
   Insiders at ``Live With'' say the decision won't be made until
toward the end of the year. It's going to be a long, hot summer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Simon Houpt is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Live With Regis and Kathie
Lee,'' consult the official Web site at www.regisandkathielee.com.
And don't forget to visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-00 1819EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
