<HEADER>
A8138 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SCI-OKLA-CANCER-NYT &LR;      07-10 0527
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-OKLA-CANCER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAFETY CONCERNS HALT OKLAHOMA CANCER RESEARCH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Okla)   By PHILIP J. HILTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Medical experiments involving people at the University of
Oklahoma Health Sciences Center at Tulsa have been suspended on the
orders of federal investigators who found numerous safety and
ethics violations. The action was taken by the Office for Human
Research Protections of the Department of Health and Human
Services, after an investigation showed that about 100 patients in
one experiment were injected with a vaccine that had been made by
unqualified laboratory workers and had never been safety-tested,
and other violations. The suspension was first reported Monday in
USA Today.
</P>
<P>
   The order, issued on June 29, halted about 75 experiments at the
Tulsa center involving humans. The investigation first focused on
one experiment, in which patients with the fatal skin cancer
melanoma were given a test vaccine. In reviewing that experiment,
federal and university officials found that the center's
Institutional Review Board was routinely violating federal safety
and ethics rules.
</P>
<P>
   After hearing of problems in the melanoma experiment, the
university conducted its own investigation and brought in a
consulting firm. In March the firm recommended that the experiment,
run by Dr. Michael McGee, be shut down immediately because of
safety questions, and that the vaccine used in it be quarantined
and either destroyed or labeled ``not for use in humans.''The
experiment was halted on March 9.
</P>
<P>
   But federal investigators found that university officials had
failed to tell the patients of the vaccine's safety problems and
misrepresented the reason the experiment was being halted. The
researchers also failed to report the safety problems to the
members of the Institutional Review Board and federal officials, as
the federal rules require.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to concerns about the safety of the vaccine,
investigators found that in recruiting patients for the study,
health center doctors misled candidates by stating that the
experiment might reduce the size of their tumors, when in fact the
study was intended only to test the toxicity of the vaccine, not to
treat patients. The doctors also failed to warn patients of the
risks of suspending their regular treatments in favor of the
non-treatment vaccine tests.
</P>
<P>
   About 100 patients were enrolled in that study, and 26 died. It
is believed that most or all died of their disease, not of the
untested vaccine. But that is unclear because researchers at the
center did not carry out the necessary checks to see whether there
were negative reactions to the vaccine, a federal official said.
</P>
<P>
   After its inquiry, the university removed McGee as vice chairman
of the department of surgery. ``We're trying to understand what
happened here, why there was a breakdown in communications and
monitoring,'' Ken Lackey, president of the Tulsa campus told The
Associated Press. McGee's office referred calls to the university.
</P>
<P>
   The university also removed Dr. Daniel Plunket as head of the
Institutional Review Board, which itself has been disbanded.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-00 1820EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
