<DOCNO> NYT20000710.0261 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8140 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BIGBROTHER11-COX     07-10 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIGBROTHER11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Plunging viewership for reality TV show Big Brother
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Reality bites.
</P>
<P>
   Or too much of it does.
</P>
<P>
   That seems to be an early message of the plunging viewership for
CBS' ``Big Brother,'' the spy-cam ``reality'' show whose ratings
have gone from curiosity-seeking great to ho-hum middling in less
than a week.
</P>
<P>
   Since ``Big Brother'' debuted to 22.4 million viewers last
Wednesday _ when it followed the highest-rated night ever for CBS'
six-week-old island-reality hit ``Saviour'' _ its ratings have
dropped dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Brother'' lured only 11.5 million viewers on Thursday, 8.9
million on Friday and 6.5 million on Saturday, when the show
finished third in its timeslot, behind ABC's movie repeat of
``Ground Control'' and Fox's long-running ``Cops.''
</P>
<P>
   In metro Atlanta, 186,000 households watched the premiere, but
that number dropped to 67,000 by Saturday. ``Big Brother'' finished
sixth in its time period on Friday. Patti Cohen, WGCL programming
and research director, believes the numbers will rise as storylines
develop, adding, ``I'm not worried.''
</P>
<P>
   Some ratings erosion was expected: unlike the weekly, top-ranked
``Survivor'' series, ``Big Brother'' airs a more viewer-demanding
five nights a week (Mondays, Tuesdays, Thursdays-Saturdays at 8).
</P>
<P>
   Also, the European import began slowly in the Netherlands,
Germany and Spain, three countries where it went on to be a hit
once viewers started to vote the 10 contestants out of the house.
</P>
<P>
   The five women and five men inside the ``Big Brother'' house on
a CBS studio lot in Los Angeles will pick two of their own for
possible banishment this Thursday. Viewers will then vote by phone
(an as-yet unlisted 900 number), with the results and eviction
airing live the following week. Last one left after three months
wins $500,000.
</P>
<P>
   But it's clear ``Big Brother'' will not have the immediate
impact of ``Survivor,'' the biggest summer hit ever, or ABC's ``Who
Wants to Be a Millionaire,'' which premiered last summer and is
credited with kicking off the current reality craze.
</P>
<P>
   Stakes are high for CBS. It paid $20 million for the Dutch
production company concept and scheduled it for 89 nights, through
September.
</P>
<P>
   CBS is playing down the ratings drop now _ it is pleased ``Big
Brother'' culls far more younger viewers than the network is used
to _ but that is a long way from the exuberance expressed by CBS TV
president Les Moonves before the show's debut, when he said he'd
air it ``six nights a week'' if numbers went high enough.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is simple: both the TV show and it's accompanying
live, all-day-every-day Web site (www.bigbrother2000.com) have
suffered from deadly dull reality. It didn't help that the first
episode, in which viewership sunk during the second half hour,
aired 50 minutes of hyped prelude before the contestants even
showed up. So far, neither the network nor net-tracking companies
have released the number of hits the 24/7 website has received
since it went live soon after last Wednesday's premiere episode.
</P>
<P>
   But now that everyone is bunked inside the two-bedroom house,
viewers so far have been treated to little more than second-rate
kvetching (Karen on her husband: ``He thinks that if he gets a job
and brings home money and puts it in the checking account and
everybody has food, that's a father, that's a husband'') and
third-rate chores (Monday's Web site featured someone watering
tomatoes and someone else washing dishes).
</P>
<P>
   Lesson for programmers: viewers aren't interested in watching
people more bored than they are.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Brother''
</P>
<P>
   8 tonight on CBS
</P>
