<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8142 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-BRIEFS-$ADV16-     07-10 1277
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-BRIEFS-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, July 16) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sharks (in a Tank) In Charleston Harbor
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to Charleston can explore Southern aquatic life at the
South Carolina Aquarium, which opened on May 19. The aquarium,
which juts into Charleston Harbor for 200 feet, will showcase
plants and animals from five major regions of the Appalachian
Watershed: The mountains, the Piedmont, the Coastal Plain, the
coast and the ocean. The focal point of the 93,000-square-foot
aquarium will be a two-story Great Ocean Tank Exhibit featuring
about 800 animals, including sea turtles, sharks, stingrays and
coral.
</P>
<P>
   The Blackwater Swamp Exhibit replicates the atmosphere of a
cypress-tupelo swamp at twilight, using a spongy floor, fog, and
twinkling lights to simulate fireflies. A 2,500-square-foot salt
marsh, complete with palmettos, sandpipers and fiddler crabs,
anchors the Coastal Gallery, which also boasts lively baby
alligators.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   From an outdoor terrace, visitors can view river otters,
dolphins and migrating birds, and watch the docking and unloading
of giant container ships. The aquarium, 100 Aquarium Wharf, is open
every day but Christmas. Hours vary throughout the year. Admission:
$14, less for children and seniors. Information: (843) 720-1990.
</P>
<P>
   A Nantucket Elephant Has a Growth Spurt
</P>
<P>
   It long ago overcame the image of its name, so much so that the
White Elephant Hotel, which has overlooked Nantucket Harbor in
Massachusetts for nearly 80 years at 50 Easton St., has reopened
after a renovation that nearly doubled its size. The hotel, closed
since October, welcomed guests on June 22 to a new wing and larger
rooms. Despite the increase in size, the hotel has the same number
of rooms, 54, plus 12 cottages. It is owned by Stephen and Jill
Karp, owners of the Wauwinet, also in Nantucket. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The new wing is covered in cedar shingles to match the other
structures, and has an airy porch. It has 40 rooms, while the old
main building now has only 14 _ all doubled in size, with sitting
areas and two bathrooms each.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Both buildings have rattan chairs with leather seats and beds
with leather headboards, hand-painted lamps and linenlike fabrics
in neutral colors; many rooms have fireplaces. The bathrooms have
white ceramic tile and marble counters. All rooms have DVD players
and high-speed Internet connections, as does the business center. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Summer rates, which include full breakfast at the hotel's
refurbished Brant Point Grill, start at $450 for standard doubles
and $465 for suites. Reservations: (800) 475-2637, fax (508)
325-1195.
</P>
<P>
   Higher Prices Forecast For Business Travelers
</P>
<P>
   Runzheimer International, a Rochester, Wis., management
consulting firm, is predicting that business travel costs next year
will increase by 7 percent _ the biggest such rise it has ever
forecast.
</P>
<P>
   That includes increases of 6.8 percent in air fares, 8 percent
in hotel rates, and 10 percent in car rentals and restaurant bills.
The reason for the record forecast, Runzheimer said, is ``our
belief that inflation, high demand and constrained inventories of
seats, rooms and cars will occur simultaneously in late 2000.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Overall travel prices held steady through the first five months
of this year, however. The AAA's leisure travel index, published on
May 30, found that even though air fares were up 6 percent since
November 1999, overall costs _ that is, the combined national
average for air fares, lodging, food and car rental _ rose only
about 1 percent, to $410.60 in May from $406.02 last November. The
reason the increase was not higher, the AAA said, is that air fares
(which account for 47 percent of the total travel dollar) and
car-rental costs were offset by hotel and restaurant costs that
remained the same as a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty Acres of Culture In the Heart of Arizona
</P>
<P>
   Residents of Sedona, Ariz., have banded together to put their
town on the artistic map with an ambitious cultural park of more
than 50 acres. Ten years in the making and still a work in progress
(over $8 million has been raised so far), the Sedona Cultural Park
aims to meld nature conservation, arts education and cultural
events. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece of the park is its hillside amphitheater, the
Georgia Frontiere Performing Arts Pavilion, (800) 780-2787, which
opened on May 26 with a performance by the Phoenix Symphony. The
design, by Jensvold-Thompson Architects, a California firm,
features three wooden arches that rise 60 feet above the stage and
frame not only the cultural action but also a view beyond to
Boynton Canyon and red rock formations, including Capital Butte.
Its backers hope the spot will become a summer home to orchestral
performances, theater, and folk and jazz concerts; this summer's
schedule includes six weeks of theater by Shakespeare Sedona ending
July 30, and an outdoor Jazz on the Rocks Festival on Sept. 23.
</P>
<P>
   The park also houses a digital media center, part of the Sedona
campus of Yavapai College, and the Red Rock Information Center,
which, in cooperation with the United States Forest Service, will
help introduce visitors to the natural surroundings, including the
hiking trails of the adjacent Coconino National Forest. The park's
Center for Education and the Arts, a partnership of Arizona
colleges, universities and school districts, is developing a range
of on-site and in-school programs. Eventually planned, should money
allow, is an arts village that would be home to galleries,
restaurants, studios, museums and indoor performance stages.
</P>
<P>
   No Vacation for Houses of Parliament
</P>
<P>
   The Palace of Westminster will be open for public tours for the
first time while Parliament is in recess, from Aug. 7 to Sept. 16.
Until now visitors have been allowed only when Parliament has been
in session, and have been confined to the public gallery unless
special access was arranged through a member of Parliament or a
foreign embassy.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The palace, also known as the Houses of Parliament, opened in
1852 after the previous Palace of Westminster was destroyed by fire
in 1834. A 75-minute guided tour will pass through the chambers of
the House of Commons and the House of Lords; the room where the
queen dons her robes for the opening of Parliament; the Prince's
Chamber, which reflects the taste of Queen Victoria's husband,
Prince Albert, chairman of the commission responsible for the
design of the building; and other sections.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Visitors will learn about the history of Parliament back to the
12th century and the roles of the Houses of Parliament. Arcane
rituals _ like the role of Black Rod, Gentleman Usher and
Sergeant-at-Arms, who is responsible for the security of the House
of Lords, and plays a prominent part in the annual state opening of
Parliament _ will be explained. Tour members will see the two
dispatch boxes from where the prime minister and the leader of the
opposition party address the house and battle out their
differences. A highlight is the throne in the House of Lords where
the monarch sits at the state opening of a new session of
Parliament. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Also on view will be an exhibition in Westminster Hall, ``Voters
of the Future,'' showing the history of parliamentary democracy and
the functions of the two Houses of Parliament.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tours start at 9:30 a.m., with the last one at 4:15 p.m. from
Monday to Saturday, except on public holidays. They will cost $5.25
and must be booked through Ticketmaster at (44-207) 344-9966.
Tickets are available up to five days before a visit, and cannot be
bought on the day of the tour.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
