<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8151 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-TOUR-DE-FRANCE-NYT &LR;      07-10 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOUR-DE-FRANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMSTRONG SOARS INTO LEAD BY CLIMBING MOUNTAINS `LIKE AN
AIRPLANE' 
</HEADLINE>
   By SAMUEL ABT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOURDES-HAUTACAM, France _ Lance Armstrong blew apart the Tour
de France in its first day in the mountains Monday, leaving his
major rivals far behind and taking a huge step toward his second
successive victory in the bicycle race.
</P>
<P>
   Clad in the yellow jersey of the leader, Armstrong said, ``It
was a good day, a big day. The legs were good.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed they were. The leader of the U.S. Postal Service team now
is 4 minutes 14 seconds ahead of the rider in second place, Jan
Ullrich, the German leader of Telekom, the winner of the 1997 Tour
and the rival Armstrong seems to respect most.
</P>
<P>
   Such other contenders as Richard Virenque, Abraham Olano, Alex
Zulle, Fernando Escartin, Laurent Jalabert, Bobby Julich and Marco
Pantani are at least seven minutes behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is still in this race,'' Armstrong insisted to
general disbelief. `'There's two weeks to go. They won't give up
till Paris,'' where the Tour ends July 23.
</P>
<P>
   The only feat the Texan did not quite pull off was victory in
the 205-kilometer (127-mile) stage over three major and two minor
climbs in the Pyrenees.
</P>
<P>
   Finishing first in nearly daylong heavy rain was Javier Otxoa, a
Spaniard with Kelme, whose name is usually given as Ochoa except in
the Tour's official rosters. Now in his fourth year as a
professional, the 25-year-old rider scored his first victory by
joining a small breakaway at Kilometer 50, building a big lead and
holding a bit of it until the finish in fog and chilling cold atop
the Hautacam mountain.
</P>
<P>
   The spent Otxoa wobbled home in 6 hours 9 minutes 32 seconds, a
speed of 33 kilometers an hour for this 10th of 21 stages.
Proceedings began in Dax, where the 162-man field was nine starters
larger.
</P>
<P>
   ``He deserved to win,'' Armstrong said, `'and I'm happy for him.
Probably 99 percent of the people here were Spaniards.'' Tens of
thousands of spectators flooded the final road up despite the
weather, which was not as ugly as forecast. The heavy winds and
snow atop the climbs that had been predicted by the French weather
service were nonexistent.
</P>
<P>
   The uglier the better, as far as Armstrong was concerned. He had
been pleased on Sunday when he heard the forecast, noting that he
rode well in bad weather _ at age 21 he won the world road race
championship in 1993 in heavy rain in Oslo _ while cold and heavy
winds would trouble the lighter Spanish climbers.
</P>
<P>
   Except for Otxoa, their main problem was Armstrong. Riding with
determination and ease, he sped away from a clutch of Spaniards and
other contenders to finish alone, 42 seconds behind in second
place. Armstrong started the final 13.5-kilometer climb, on a
gradient of nearly 8 percent, almost nine minutes down on the
Spaniard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Armstrong went like an airplane,'' Virenque, a member of the
group Armstrong deserted, said in wonder.
</P>
<P>
   The new man in the yellow jersey, replacing Alberto Elli, an
Italian with Telekom who is now 57th, had his own explanation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very strong,'' he said, a rare confession despite his
impressive showing in the mountains of his final preparatory race
last month. ``But this was a tactical race.
</P>
<P>
   ``The important part of the race began on the Aubisque,'' two
climbs from the end. Speaking of his team, he continued: ``We were
maybe too aggressive in pulling at the start of the Aubisque.'' He
had six of his eight teammates with him there but they faded one by
one up the 16.5-kilometer climb on a 7.1 percent gradient.
</P>
<P>
   Halfway to the top, Armstrong was without support while Ullrich,
Zulle and Pantani had at least one teammate to pace each of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``My only choice was to wait,'' Armstrong said. Ahead, Virenque
and Escartin were building a lead that topped two minutes. ``It was
a little bit of a crisis for me _ two minutes was a lot to give.''
</P>
<P>
   Still two minutes behind, Armstrong stayed in his group until
the Hautacam ascension 20 kilometers later. ``Everybody was waiting
for an attack by Pantani,'' a renowned climber, ``and sure enough,
he did attack.''
</P>
<P>
   The Texan followed him, then attacked himself. He looked back at
Pantani, asking for a relay, saw that the Italian was spent and
sped off. Soon he caught the Virenque group ahead, moved to its
front and sped off alone again.
</P>
<P>
   Rising occasionally from his saddle to increase his leg thrust,
Armstrong was uncatchable.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, he tried to temper speculation that he would remain
uncatchable all the way to Paris. ``There are still a lot of
mountains,'' he said. ``There's still a lot that can happen.''
</P>
<P>
   He said much the same last year after he won the first mountain
stage, leaving his foes demoralized, on his way to easy victory.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
