<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8158 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-MISSILE-DEFENSE-HNS &LR;      07-10 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSILE-DEFENSE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     MISSILE DEFENSE SUPPORTERS BRUSH OFF FAILED TEST  
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Supporters of the proposed National Missile Defense
program said Monday that the system's embarrassing flop last
weekend didn't mean that the weapon was fundamentally flawed and
that the $36 billion-plus program should press ahead despite the
failure.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Kyl, R-Ariz., one of the weapon's most ardent
supporters on Capitol Hill, called the test ``disappointing,'' but
added that ``the primary failure had to do with a technology that
is not a new technology, that is, separating a booster from its
payload.''
</P>
<P>
   Kyl said the failure of the intercepting missile's ``kill
vehicle'' to separate from its rocket was ``a failure of old
technology We've done this hundreds of times.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing about this latest test that would be
definitive about not proceeding with National Missile Defense,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Baker Spring, a missile defense expert with the Heritage
Foundation, a conservative think tank, said the test failure wasn't
an indictment of the National Missile Defense program which is
designed to allow the U.S. military to destroy an incoming
ballistic missile in mid-flight by smashing it with the kill
vehicle, essentially a 130-pound battering ram.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was not something to do with missile defense technology
and the relatively sophisticated elements of that technology,''
Spring said. ``The rocket booster they used in the test was a
well-known quantity and something they used on a number of
occasions,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Bob Smith, R-N.H., another supporter of the program, said
that despite the test failure, ``I have seen enough of the science
and technology of this system to know that it will work.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Curt Weldon, R-Pa., an ardent proponent, said that even
with the failure it should be ``full steam ahead on missile
defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Preliminary indications blamed Saturday's test flop on the
failure of the interceptor rocket _ a Minuteman intercontinental
missile refurbished by Lockheed Martin Corp. _ to jettison its
``kill vehicle.''
</P>
<P>
   During the test, a key dry run for the National Missile Defense
system, an intercontinental ballistic missile with a fake warhead
was launched from Vandenberg AFB, Calif., at 12:19 a.m. EDT
Saturday morning. Twenty minutes later, the interceptor was
launched from Kwajalein Atoll in the Pacific Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Failure of the kill vehicle to separate from the interceptor's
second stage rocket would represent a glitch in old-line technology
that has been in use since manned space flight began nearly 40
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The result was that the interceptor didn't come close to hitting
its target.
</P>
<P>
   The test cost the Pentagon $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   Air Force Lt. Col. Rick Lehner, a spokesman for the Ballistic
Missile Defense Organization, which is managing the NMD system,
said it appears that the kill vehicle never received the electronic
signal from the rocket booster to separate, fly solo and ram the
dummy warhead.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Adams, a spokesman for Lockheed Martin's space unit, in
Sunnyvale, Calif., stressed that the boosters on the Minuteman have
been ``tested and retested'' and that they have a long history of
successfully sending payloads aloft into space.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have not been any problems in the past with these
boosters. They have been very reliable and there has been a high
degree of confidence in these systems,'' Adams said.
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia Taylor, a spokeswoman for The Boeing Co., in Anaheim,
Calif., which is the lead contractor on National Missile Defense,
said the company was working with the Pentagon, Lockheed Martin and
other subcontractors to determine whether the failure was due to a
malfunctioning piece of equipment, a computer software glitch or
perhaps some combination.
</P>
<P>
   A government official who attended the interceptor launch said
Pentagon officials know that the rocket booster and kill vehicle
electronically communicated successfully throughout the test's
short duration.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we don't know is why the booster didn't tell the kill
vehicle to initiate the separation sequence. The problem could be
something as simple as a chip that went bad,'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the program assert the failure of a tried and true
technology _ booster-payload separation _ underscores their view
that the United States wouldn't be able to rely on NMD in time of
national crisis.
</P>
<P>
   John Pike, a space expert with the Federation of American
Scientists, a non-profit think tank, said NMD ``has all the
fragility of normal technology plus the special fragilities of
missile defense technologies. This is complex system and a lot of
things have to work right for it to work at all.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to protecting U.S. cities against a ballistic
missile attack from so-called ``rogue'' countries such as North
Korea and Iran, the system is being designed to provide protection
against an accidental nuclear missile launch in Russia, sparked by
decaying Soviet-era equipment or a weapon that falls into the hands
of a terrorist.
</P>
<P>
   Program supporters had hoped for a successful test intercept to
make their case that National Missile Defense should move forward.
Thus far, the testing results are poor. In addition to the recent
failure, the system scored a bullseye in a test last October but
then missed in a January test.
</P>
<P>
   The program is on a tight deadline. Defense Secretary William
Cohen is scheduled to make a recommendation to President Clinton
next month about whether the weapon is ready to move from the
laboratory to the battlefield.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton in turn must give his approval no later than November or
December if the Pentagon is to meet a deployment date of 2005, the
date when U.S. intelligence officials believe North Korea might
possess a missile capable of striking the United States.
</P>
<P>
   According to current Pentagon plans, if Clinton gives the green
light, the $36 billion-plus program will be constructed in several
phases. At first, the anti-missile system will use 20 interceptors
based in Alaska by 2005. But by 2007, the Pentagon plans to add
another 80 interceptor missiles. The cost could grow substantially
if the military adds additional interceptors and another launch
site.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Eric Rosenberg can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address eric(at)hearstdc.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
