<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8182 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-ANDERSON-COLUMN-N     07-10 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: BEANBALLS, CLEMENS AND PIAZZA 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   His name is Clemens, not Clemency. The first time Roger Clemens
pitched batting practice in spring training a year ago, Derek Jeter
stepped into the cage with his bat while wearing a catcher's mask,
chest protector and shin guards. Off to the side, Chuck Knoblauch
was dressed the same way.
</P>
<P>
   On the mound, Clemens laughed. So did the other Yankees who knew
his reputation for ``throwing inside,'' the current politically
correct euphemism for the beanball, the knockdown pitch.
</P>
<P>
   But the Yankees had never laughed when Clemens was an opposing
pitcher. In a 1998 incident, Clemens, then with the Toronto Blue
Jays, plunked Scott Brosius, prompting a scrum. Knoblauch had
always wondered if his Texas A&AMP;M background had provoked Clemens,
from the rival University of Texas, to throw inside just for the
fun of it.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens even drilled his former Boston Red Sox teammate, Mo
Vaughn, for digging in too close to the plate. When the Mets
repeatedly tried to pick Clemens off second base a year ago, he
told their infielders, ``Do that once more and I'll put one in your
ear'' _ a throwback line similar to the old ``stick it in his ear''
expression.
</P>
<P>
   So when Clemens' fastball smashed into Mike Piazza's helmet
Saturday night at Yankee Stadium, Clemens' intentions were
instantly suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Early last week Clemens had even predicted that he would be
``more aggressive'' in pitching to Piazza, who in 12 at-bats
against Clemens had seven hits, including three home runs. And
suddenly the Mets' catcher was sprawled in the dirt, dizzy with a
concussion.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Piazza branded the pitch ``definitely
intentional.'' Clemens repeated that he was just ``trying to pitch
him inside.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Mets thought they could prove in court that Clemens had
intentionally tried to hit Piazza in the head with a weapon (a
90-plus mile-per-hour fastball), the 37-year-old Yankee could be
charged with assault; Marty McSorley of the Boston Bruins is
awaiting trial in Vancouver for assault with a weapon in flattening
Donald Brashear of the Canucks with his stick.
</P>
<P>
   But only Clemens knows if he was intentionally trying to hit
Piazza on the helmet or in the head.
</P>
<P>
   Considering Clemens' reputation, the belief here is that, yes,
he was trying to intimidate Piazza by firing a flaming fastball
near his head, just as the 6-foot-4-inch, 238-pound right-hander
has intimidated so many other batters.
</P>
<P>
   But was he trying to hit Piazza in the helmet? No.
</P>
<P>
   Was he really aiming lower, hoping to hit Piazza in the back or
the ribs and the pitch sailed a little higher? Maybe.
</P>
<P>
   Would he have done it over the weekend in Shea Stadium, where a
pitcher has to bat? Maybe not.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever his intentions, if Clemens' fastball had somehow hit
Piazza in the head, especially the temple, he could have killed the
Mets' catcher. In 1920, another Yankee right-hander with a
knockdown reputation, Carl Mays, fired a fastball that struck Ray
Chapman, a Cleveland Indians shortstop, in the head. He died 14
hours later _ baseball's only fatality.
</P>
<P>
   But there's no way to tell yet if Piazza, scratched from Tuesday
night's All-Star Game, will be the same slugger who was batting
.348 with 24 homers and 72 runs batted in. He knows it will take
time for him to be completely comfortable in the batter's box.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Medwick was never completely comfortable after being beaned
in the era before batters wore helmets. With the St. Louis
Cardinals in 1937, Medwick had a triple crown season: .374, 31
homers, 154 RBIs and he's in the Hall of Fame. But soon after Larry
MacPhail, the Brooklyn Dodgers boss, obtained him in a 1940 trade,
he was beaned by Cardinal right-hander Bob Bowman.
</P>
<P>
   Police and the umpires stopped Leo Durocher, the Dodgers
manager, and several players from charging the mound. When Bowman
later departed through the Dodger dugout, MacPhail, with a swing
from his Ebbets Field box seat, knocked his cap off.
</P>
<P>
   Medwick returned to bat .301 with 17 homers and 86 RBIs that
season, followed by .318 with 18 homers and 88 RBIs in 1941 (when
the Dodgers won the pennant) and .300 with 96 RBIs but only 4
homers in 1942. But he never led the league again. He never was the
same hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, Piazza was wearing a helmet with an ear flap. It
may have saved his career, if not his life.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
