<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 18:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8185 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-SUMMIT-0711-C     07-10 1195
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-SUMMIT-0711-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   CLINTON, AT CAMP DAVID, HOPES TO CLOSE THE ELUSIVE CIRCLE OF
MIDEAST PEACE
</P>
<P>
   By BOB DEANS
</P>
<P>
   2000 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When he opens the second Camp David summit on
Tuesday, President Clinton will be trying to close the elusive
circle of Mideast peace begun on the same ground two decades ago by
President Jimmy Carter.
</P>
<P>
   More than walking in history's shadow, Clinton hopes to burnish
his own scandal-tainted legacy by seizing what's likely to be his
last clean shot at a big picture foreign policy win.
</P>
<P>
   After seven years spent learning the issues and getting to know
the personalities involved in the Israeli-Palestinian conflict,
Clinton is under no illusions about the difficulty of the talks
he's signed on to host in the days ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this were easy,'' he told reporters on Monday, ``it would
have been done a long time ago.''
</P>
<P>
   With just six months left in office, though, Clinton is gambling
that he can mix U.S. power and prestige with personal diplomacy to
help press Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat to complete a peace process that Carter set in motion
in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is difficult. It is perhaps the most difficult of all the
peace problems in the world,'' said Clinton. ``But, both Prime
Minister Barak and Chairman Arafat have the vision, the knowledge,
the experience and the ability _ and the sheer guts _ to do what it
takes, I think, to reach an agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   The quest for peace between Israelis and Palestinians has become
a search for the diplomatic Holy Grail among two generations of
American policymakers.
</P>
<P>
   It's seen as the key to ending half a century of enmity between
modern Israel, the Jewish state forged in the aftermath of the
Holocaust, and all of its Arab neighbors. The conflict has ensured
instability in a region that is at once the cradle of civilization,
birthplace of three of the world's great religions and home to
two-thirds of all the known crude oil reserves on earth.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton himself has already hosted two major Mideast peace
summits.
</P>
<P>
   His first, a nine-day marathon between Arafat and Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu in the fall of 1998 at the Wye River
Plantation in rural Maryland, produced an accord whose provisions
the parties only partly carried out, a major foreign policy
frustration for Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   His second, a weeklong set of talks between Barak and Syrian
Foreign Minister Farouk Sharaa last January in Shepardstown, West
Va., produced no agreement and precious little progress between two
countries that remain technically at war.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Clinton has held more than a dozen one-on-one
summits _ at the White House and in Jerusalem, Geneva, Oslo and
even the Gaza strip _ with Mideast leaders, hoping to press the
tortured peace process forward.
</P>
<P>
   Closing out his presidency with an Israeli-Palestinian peace
accord under his belt wouldn't erase the stain of the Monica
Lewinsky scandal from Clinton's biography, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   It would, though, go a long way toward mitigating his reputation
as a political underachiever and cementing his legacy as a
president willing to invest U.S. resources in trying to resolve
seemingly intractable conflicts from the Balkans and Northern
Ireland to South Asia and the Korean Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is his last big chance to get something historians will
remember,'' said Dan Thomas, professor of political science at
Warburg College, in Waverly, Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, who is completing a book entitled ``Clinton and the
Public Mind,'' said there's little hope the Republican-led Congress
would permit the president a major domestic policy achievement in
an election year.
</P>
<P>
   ``He realizes that he's pretty much a lame duck,'' said Thomas,
``so this is it.''
</P>
<P>
   Both politically and strategically, Carter faced a very
different set of circumstances in September,1978, when he spent 13
days holed up with Egyptian President Anwar al-Sadat and Israeli
Prime Minister Menachem Begin at Camp David.
</P>
<P>
   Carter, for one thing, had two years remaining in office. He
used that time to help win congressional backing for the historic
peace accord he brokered between Egypt and Israel _ and the $4
billion in annual aid to those countries that was part of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   If Arafat and Barak strike a deal at Camp David, much of the
tough work of implementing the agreement would likely be left to
Clinton's successor.
</P>
<P>
   The geopolitical stakes were also different. Carter would soon
face an oil shock that ravaged the U.S. economy, the capture of
American diplomats by Iranian revolutionaries and the Soviet
invasion of Afghanistan. Each of those events shook this country
and underscored the precarious nature of U.S. interests in the
volatile Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   No such dire consequences are anticipated in the region in the
months ahead _ regardless of the outcome of this week's summit.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton hopes, however, to pick up the string left dangling ever
since the Camp David accords laid out a roadmap for a broader
Mideast peace. Begin and Sadat agreed, after all, to convene
Israeli-Palestinian negotiations aimed at resolving their dispute
``in all its aspects'' within five years.
</P>
<P>
   Similar language was enshrined again in October, 1993. Then, in
a peace treaty signed on the White House lawn just eight months
after Clinton took office, Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister
Yitzhak Rabin pledged to negotiate a comprehensive land-for-peace
agreement by 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Intent and implementation quickly parted ways, though, after
Rabin was assassinated by a Jewish zealot who feared the prime
minister was embarked on a mission to sell Israeli security short.
</P>
<P>
   It was at a memorial service to Rabin last fall that Clinton
pressed Barak and Arafat to work in earnest for a peace agreement.
They've set a Sept. 13 target date for completing the deal.
</P>
<P>
   That would require agreement on the most difficult issues
between the two sides, including the question of Palestinian
statehood, borders, the future of Jerusalem and the right of
Palestinian refugees to return to their former homelands, now
occupied by Israel.
</P>
<P>
   As he sat Sunday in his regular pew at the Foundry United
Methodist Church, two blocks from the White House, Clinton soaked
up allusions to the Holy Land and the ancient conflicts he seeks to
resolve. There was the Old Testament lesson, and its reference to
Jerusalem, the holy citadel where, according to Psalm 48, ``God has
shown himself a sure defense.''
</P>
<P>
   There was the spectacular stained glass rendition of the birth
of Christ in nearby Bethlehem, just outside of Jerusalem and under
Palestinian control.
</P>
<P>
   There were two tall red banners, flanking the altar and the
choir pews, each adorned with a single white dove.
</P>
<P>
   And there were the words to the closing hymn, ``God of Grace and
God of Glory,'' which Clinton appeared to be singing, containing
the third-stanza admonition, fateful perhaps, ``Cure thy children's
warring madness.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Deans can be e-mailed at: Bobdeans(at)coxnewscom
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
