<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS SISTERS WOW WIMBLEDOM AND THEMSELVES 
</HEADLINE>
   By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ Venus Williams kept pointing at the clock,
and Serena kept taking her time, but once the two sisters arrived
at the champions dinner Sunday night, they shimmered in perfect
harmony.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was stunning,'' Venus Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I passed by a mirror, and I was like, Whoa,'' Serena added.
</P>
<P>
   It seems Venus and Serena Willams don't have daily affirmations,
they have them hourly. Together, the queens of self-esteem exited
the All England Club Monday after adding the doubles title to the
singles championship Venus Williams won on Saturday. In their
eye-catching wake, they left some of the best players in the world
searching their pockets for some confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just for us to come back like this, I can only imagine what
people are thinking,'' said Serena Williams, who, like her sister,
missed most of the spring because of injury. ``Obviously, they're
probably going to go home and practice harder. But you know what?
We are, too. We come at it really serious. And we mean business.''
</P>
<P>
   In one fortnight, Venus Williams bludgeoned the instinctive
talents out of Martina Hingis' game and then overwhelmed Lindsay
Davenport's power with her own. After missing two months with a
knee injury, Serena Williams came to the All England Club without a
warmup match. But she dropped just one service game in four rounds,
took less than hour to dismantle most of her opponents and
discovered the only obstacle in her journey to the title was her
big sister in the semifinal.
</P>
<P>
   As a seal of proof to their dominance, the two won their doubles
match after being awaken by an 8:30 a.m. phone call this morning.
It was their mother calling from Florida, but Venus Williams
admitted that she was too groggy to be coherent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was somewhat in a coma,'' said Venus Williams after falling
asleep at 2 a.m. following the champions dinner. ``I couldn't
think, so I said, `I've got to call you back.' I haven't spoken to
her since.''
</P>
<P>
   Just four hours after the wake-up call, Venus and Serena
Williams walked out on Centre Court to play their rain-delayed
doubles championship title. Almost in their sleep, the unranked,
unseeded wild-card entrants into the competition defeated Julie
Halard-Decugis and Ai Sugiyama, 6-3, 6-2, for the title. After the
sisters embraced at the net, they held up the trophy to provide one
last Wimbledon snapshot of their invincibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's getting pretty scary,'' Venus Williams said of their
dominance, ``but we like it.''
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the Tour seems a bit unsettled by their surge.
Hingis once had the genius to diffuse any opponent's power. Two
years ago, her confidence was unrivaled and her cunning was her
ally. When her body was stretched to its limit and her will was
worn down, Hingis' spirits were broken after her semifinal loss to
Venus Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be enough just with my abilities I had at the
time,'' said Hingis. ``It has changed so much since the Williamses
started playing better. I guess as the No. 1, you're supposed to
win a Grand Slam. But now someone else probably deserves to be No.
1.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the goal of the Williams sisters, both of them. Whatever
tension existed when Serena Williams had a Grand Slam title and her
big sister didn't, it seems to have been diluted by Venus'
Wimbledon win.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're both even again,'' Venus said. ``Now, we're both going
for our second one.''
</P>
<P>
   As they sat side by side in an interview room Monday, they were
very straightforward when asked about their plans for the immediate
future.
</P>
<P>
   ``To win the U.S. Open,'' Venus said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, for me too,'' Serena chimed in.
</P>
<P>
   The competition between them has the potential to leave everyone
else drifting like satellites around their world if they ever reach
their goal of becoming No. 1 and No. 2. What once seemed
far-fetched isn't such a wild idea anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're both going to try and get as many wins as we can,''
Venus Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really greedy,'' Serena Williams added.
</P>
<P>
   This is how they were all day. Venus Williams would answer a
question, then the little sister would tag-along in response. When
asked who would star in the sisters' home-designed tennis
newsletter, Venus looked at Serena to cue her reply.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be about Wimbledon, and what I think happened
this year,'' Serena Williams said. ``Pete Sampras won his 13th
Grand Slam, and I don't know, I think Venus might get the cover
story. That was a pretty big happening.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have pull,'' Venus said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM. STORY CAN END HERE.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   It was the same way Sunday night. The big sister kept pushing
the little sister to get herself together.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took two hours for me to get ready, and I wasn't even the
Wimbledon ladies champion,'' Serena Williams said. ``So it was
pretty ridiculous. Venus was rushing me.''
</P>
<P>
   For a fortnight, one pushed the other to reach goals that only
feed their confidence. For the sisters, it's full-steam ahead.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
