<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8188 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-MOUNT-SAINT-HE     07-10 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-MOUNT-SAINT-HELENS-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATURE REBOUNDS AT MOUNT ST. HELENS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 16)  
 By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Mount St. Helens erupted early on the morning of May 18,
1980, the devastation was immense. In the span of a few seconds,
1,312 feet of rock were cleaved off the top of the mountain, and
the flow of mud, lava and boulders covered the earth 20 miles away.
Dozens of square miles were transformed into a barren, burned gray
moonscape, and 57 people and thousands of animals perished. Today,
20 years later, nature has rebounded in surprising ways on the
mountain, in southwest Washington State. There are some fledgling
plants, trees and berry bushes, most from seeds reintroduced to the
area by wandering elk. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other animals _ frogs, salamanders, beavers _ have come back,
too. While the area still shows evidence of breathtaking
incineration, there are now literally hundreds of research plots,
where scientists are carefully chronicling the amazing process,
known as recolonization, under which nature is springing back to
life.The delicate question is, How much of a tourist attraction
should all this be?
</P>
<P>
   Many tourism boosters in the area are lobbying for greater
visitor access to the mountain, formally known as the Mount St.
Helens National Volcanic Monument. Among other things, they'd like
to extend the main road that snakes through the monument to provide
access from the east. (The road currently provides access from
Interstate 5 to the west, ending at a federal observatory near the
crater.) They have talked of marketing the mountain and the
surrounding area as a multiday vacation destination with hiking,
camping, biking and kayaking _ not, as most visitors make it now, a
detour of a half-day or so to learn about the volcano and gape at
nature's awesome power.
</P>
<P>
   Whether such an effort to expand tourism could succeed is an
open question, and some scientists say that because of the
fragility of the recovering landscape it's best to keep an informal
lid on the number of visitors by holding off on such promotions.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The most immediate issue concerning tourism centers on the main
visitors center, known as Silver Lake. It is a few miles off the
Interstate near Castle Rock, Wash., and is thus a popular spot for
motorists between Portland and Seattle to stop and learn about the
blast. (The Spirit Lake Memorial Highway leads from there to the
mountain, about 40 miles away.)  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last winter, citing budget cutbacks, the Forest Service closed
the center for a few months. But when it announced in March that
the center would not reopen at all this year, local officials were
angry, citing the upcoming 20th anniversary. Under pressure from
the state's Congressional delegation, the Forest Service agreed to
reopen the center for the year, but its future remains uncertain,
and the federal government is even considering privatization. This
is largely because of shortfalls in the Recreation Fee
Demonstration Program, which the Congress started four years ago
with the aim of making some federal recreation sites
self-sufficient. The program generated about $2.3 million at Mount
St. Helens in 1998, but last year, when poorer summer weather
reduced the number of visitors, dropped to about $1.4 million, not
enough to make the monument self-sustaining. There are four other
visitors centers of various sizes around the monument, two operated
by the Forest Service, one by Cowlitz County, and one by
Weyerhaeuser, the timber company. The official total for visitors
to the monument last year was 1.5 million, but that might overstate
the case a bit: the Forest Service counts someone who stops at all
three of their visitors centers as three visitors. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At the mountain, a network of good hiking trails has been
formed, carefully laid out not to interfere with the regeneration
taking place all around. These include the Ptarmigan Trail, which
leads to the summit (8,363 feet these days), and the 28-mile Loowit
Trail, which essentially circles the volcano and provides a
fascinating glimpse of the destruction along with some lands that
were, given the vagaries of the winds and the lava flow that day,
relatively untouched. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Access to the crater itself remains forbidden, with good reason:
it's still steaming in there.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the visitors centers, old photographs depict the cheerful
bygone days, with a lodge and the beautifully snowcapped cone of a
peak, a startling contrast to today's desolate landscape. The lodge
lies buried below hundreds of feet of debris from avalanches and
mud flow, and the peak is a gaping, jagged shadow of its former
self.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Camping sites are available in the monument, with prices ranging
from $11 to $20, according to a spokeswoman at the visitors center.
The main information number is (360) 247-3900. On the Web,
information can be retrieved at www.fs.fed.us./gpnf/mshnvm. Two
other sites with tourism information about the area are
www.mountsthelens.com and www.cowlitzcounty.org/tourism. Or
telephone the Mount St. Helens Information Resource Center, (360)
274-3406.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
