<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 18:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8202 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-ISRAEL-BOS &LR;      07-10 0383
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-ISRAEL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEAKENED PEACEMAKER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The government did not fall, and I am continuing on to Camp
David,'' Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak said Monday after
surviving a no-confidence vote in the Knesset, Israel's parliament.
</P>
<P>
   It was the former general's way of saying that neither
defections from his government's majority nor the tally in the
failed no-confidence vote (54 in favor, 52 against, short of the 60
needed to pass) would deter him from pursuing peace with the
Palestinians, as he had promised a year ago in his electoral
campaign. Admirable as Barak's resolute stance may be, he
nevertheless arrives at Camp David for what he calls ``the moment
of truth'' in a politically weakened condition.
</P>
<P>
   Everything will depend on the terms of any accord reached in the
coming days of top-level negotiations with Yasser Arafat and
President Clinton. If Barak does return home with the text of a
deal, he may present the agreement for a vote in the Knesset, and
then, if the Knesset endorses the deal, it would be put to a
national referendum. Barak could also choose to deposit the text of
an accord with the Knesset but then proceed directly to a national
referendum without asking Knesset members to endorse it.
</P>
<P>
   In either case, the rest of Israel will have to ratify any
agreement Barak strikes with Arafat. The effect of the defections
from his coalition and the close no-confidence vote is to reduce
his margin for maneuver at Camp David and perhaps diminish his
ability to draw on his reputation as Israel's most decorated
soldier when the time comes to market a peace deal to the Israeli
public.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat, who has his own critics to worry about, will also have
to make compromises if any deal is to be struck. More than ever
now, any such deal will have to pass muster with a majority of
Israelis. Barak must come away with an accord that protects
Israel's long-term security. Accordingly, it may be easier for
Israelis to accept revised municipal boundaries for Jerusalem than
a complete ceding of sovereignty in the Jordan River valley.
</P>
<P>
   A success at Camp David is still possible, but historic
compromises are best made by leaders who are not politically weak
at home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-00 1859EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
