<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-AIDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTH AFRICAN'S OBSTINACY ON AIDS DISAPPOINTS EXPERTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also SCI-AIDS-CONFERENCE.) 
 By RACHEL L. SWARNS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DURBAN, South Africa _ Striking a defiant and combative tone,
the South African government on Monday lashed out at its
increasingly vocal critics at the 13th International Aids
conference, saying there was no need for President Thabo Mbeki to
affirm that the human immunodeficiency virus, HIV, causes AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   The government was responding to the chorus of criticism from
prominent scientists, physicians and activists here who on Monday
expressed their disappointment with Mbeki. He opened the conference
on Sunday night with a speech in which he described extreme
poverty, rather than AIDS, as the biggest killer in this country.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, Mbeki has consulted with two American
researchers who argue that poverty and malnutrition _ and not HIV _
cause AIDS, an argument that most established scientists say was
debunked years ago. Monday, in panel sessions and interviews,
several participants said the president had squandered a golden
opportunity to clarify his position and to take a leadership role
in fighting the disease and preventing the spread of the virus,
which has infected 4 million people here.
</P>
<P>
   Health Minister Manto Tshabalala-Msimang dismissed the criticism
and accused the news media of distorting Mbeki's message. ``The
president of this country has never denied either the existence of
AIDS nor this causal connection between HIV and AIDS,'' she said at
a news conference Monday afternoon. ``But we reiterate our view
that it is inappropriate to blame everything around this epidemic
on the HIV virus.''
</P>
<P>
   Tshabalala-Msimang added that ``clearly, the relationship
between HIV and other social ills afflicting our society such as
poverty and disease'' is complex.
</P>
<P>
   But in the corridors and halls of the conference here, many
participants remained perplexed and confused by the president's
reluctance to say what so many people wanted to hear. Some wondered
whether he was too proud to back down. Others wondered whether
Mbeki, who is an economist and an intellectual, simply remained
unconvinced of the links between HIV and AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   No one disputes the link between poverty and HIV and AIDS.
Prostitutes, migrant laborers, the uneducated and victims of sexual
violence are more vulnerable to infection. And poor people
typically lack access to drugs that might prolong their lives.
</P>
<P>
   But scientists and researchers fear that Mbeki's heavy emphasis
on poverty may confuse people and cause them to continue risky
sexual behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Wainberg, the president of the International Aids Society,
the co-organizer of this conference, described Mbeki's speech,
which was broadcast live on national television, as a ``lost
opportunity.'' American officials said privately that they feared
that Mbeki had raised broader questions about the quality of his
leadership.
</P>
<P>
   A South African judge, Edwin Cameron, received a standing
ovation after he delivered the conference's opening speech Monday
and condemned Mbeki for wasting time on discredited theories while
people were dying.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has shaken almost everyone responsible for engaging the
epidemic,'' Cameron, who is infected with HIV, said of Mbeki's
stance. ``It has created an air of unbelief among scientists,
confusion among those at risk of HIV, and consternation among AIDS
workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally yearned for an unequivocal assertion by our
president of HIV as a virally specific condition, a specific
condition that is sexually transmitted.''
</P>
<P>
   The health minister emphasized Monday that Mbeki was committed
to combating the disease vigorously by encouraging safe sex and by
sponsoring research on drug therapies and a possible vaccine, which
has been applauded by researchers here.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Awa Coll-Seck, the director of the United Nations'
department of AIDS policy, said she was encouraged to hear Mbeki
mention the program in his speech on Sunday night. But Coll-Seck,
who is from Senegal, said she feared that the safe-sex message
might get lost in the emphasis on poverty.
</P>
<P>
   And she said she had hoped for more from Mbeki, who helped lead
the battle against apartheid and now champions the causes of an
African continent threatened by AIDS. ``I was discouraged,''
Coll-Seck said. ``We were expecting him to be a leader.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
