<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-AIDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MBEKI'S BLINDERS ON AIDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The tragedy of President Thako Mbeki's speech Sunday is that it
reinforces a culture of denial and confusion in South Africa that
will impede efforts to prevent the spread of AIDS. Twenty percent
of adult South Africans are living with the HIV virus, which causes
AIDS, and many more will become infected because the government is
unwilling to make HIV prevention a national crusade.
</P>
<P>
   Mbeki, in his speech before an international conference,
acknowledged the link between HIV and AIDS, but he insisted that
extreme poverty was the greatest public health problem facing his
country and the rest of Africa. Poverty is endemic through the
continent, but it is not the reason that many people fear a
population decline in some of the most fecund nations on earth.
Beyond the horror of killing people, AIDS will exacerbate poverty
by striking down millions in their most productive years.
</P>
<P>
   Mbeki has raised doubts about AZT and other drugs that have been
effective controlling the virus in wealthy nations. He is right
that these medicines are too expensive and the regimen too complex
for the limited public health infrastructure of his country. And it
would be a triumph for humanity if scientists could develop a
vaccine against HIV, as he proposes, but many doubt one will be
available soon.
</P>
<P>
   However, Mbeki ignores the reality that AIDS exists independent
of economic circumstances. American gays were as affluent as the
rest of US society in the 1980s, when the virus raced through their
ranks. When it become clear that the disease could be prevented,
they conducted an effective public health campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The opening of South Africa after the dismantling of apartheid
has encouraged the spread of HIV among heterosexuals. The ``safe
sex'' message of the 1980s among gay Americans needs to be adapted
to South African society. Uganda's success in limiting infection
rates ought to provide a model.
</P>
<P>
   More foreign aid for prevention is needed, but extra money will
be ineffective if the government does not have a sound strategy to
use it. Unless Mbeki mobilizes his government to educate his
people, millions are doomed to die in their prime.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
