<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOYSMART-INJUNCTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FTC SEEKS INJUNCTION AGAINST TOYSMART 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHANIE STOUGHTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Federal Trade Commission filed a complaint against
Toysmart.com Inc. Monday, seeking to block the bankrupt online
retailer from selling confidential information on its consumers.
</P>
<P>
   In a strongly worded statement, the federal agency accused the
Waltham, Mass. toy seller of violating federal law by putting its
customer list up for sale after vowing it would never share that
information.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even failing dot-coms must abide by their promise to protect
the privacy rights of their customers,'' FTC Chairman Robert
Pitofsky said. ``The FTC seeks to ensure these promises are kept.''
</P>
<P>
   The agency's five commissioners voted unanimously on Friday to
approve a staff recommendation that the FTC attempt to prevent the
sale. The agency's complaint was filed in U.S. District Court in
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Though Pitofsky's tough statement appears to leave little wiggle
room, a source close to the discussions said the two sides have
talked about a settlement in which Toysmart.com can sell the data
if ``appropriate protections'' are put in place.
</P>
<P>
   FTC and Toysmart.com officials declined to commment on the
specifics of ongoing discussions. ``I think the complaint speaks
for itself,'' said Eric London, an agency spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Murphy, a Boston attorney representing Toysmart.com, was
similarly vague. ``We are in negotiations with the FTC to resolve
everyone's concerns,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer privacy advocates are unlikely to be pleased with any
sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would encourage the FTC to enforce the privacy statement
that Toysmart has issued, which said no information would be shared
with any third party,'' said Dave Steer, a spokesman for TRUSTe, an
e-commerce industry watchdog in San Jose, Calif. ``Anything shy of
that promise is a compromise.''
</P>
<P>
   After receiving an anonymous tip, TRUSTe asked the federal
agency to take a closer look at Toysmart.com's actions. TRUSTe
offers a privacy-seal program that includes 2,000 Web sites as
members. But companies can display TRUSTe's logo only if they
comply with certain guidelines designed to protect consumer's
privacy.
</P>
<P>
   As of Monday, Toysmart.com had not removed TRUSTe's seal from
the bottom of its Web home page.
</P>
<P>
   Toysmart.com announced in May that it would collapse after its
majority investor, Walt Disney Co., pulled its support. Last month,
the company filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection. And now, it
hopes to sell its assets, including its customer information, to
pay back more than $20 million in debt.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear how many customer records Toysmart.com had in its
database, but the company's Web site has attracted millions of
visitors.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC's court actions are being closely monitored by consumer
advocates and state authorities worried that Web businesses are
learning too much about their shoppers _ and are not properly
protecting that information.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer privacy advocates hope to prevent failed Web retailers
from selling the names, home addresses, e-mail addresses and
shopping habits of customers. That trend, however, is expected to
continue as the dot-com shakeout continues.
</P>
<P>
   TRUSTe officials have also looked into Craftshop.com, Boo.com
and several other dot-com failures. But they decided to target
Toysmart.com after the online retailer purchased a newspaper
advertisement to announce the sale of its assets.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been very public about their intentions,'' Steer said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-00 1901EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
