<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 19:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8215 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-BARAK-BOS &LR;      07-10 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-BARAK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARAK HEADS FOR US AFTER SURVIVING CHALLENGE IN KNESSET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ After narrowly surviving an attempt Monday to topple
his government, Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak immediately
boarded a jet to take him to an historic summit with Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat Tuesday at Camp David.
</P>
<P>
   The talks in the woods of the Maryland retreat, hosted by
President Clinton, offer what is widely seen as the last best
chance for the peace process to succeed and a momentous opportunity
to draw final borders between Israel and an emerging Palestinian
state.
</P>
<P>
   ``The moment of truth is upon us,'' Barak said as he battled to
survive a ``no confidence'' vote in the Israeli parliament during a
debate that was unruly and emotionally charged even by Israeli
standards.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition Likud Party received more votes _ 54-52 in favor
of bringing down Barak's One Israel coalition government _ but fell
short of the 61 votes required to carry the motion in the
120-member Knesset. Seven legislators abstained, and seven were
absent.
</P>
<P>
   Shouting over hecklers from Likud and from the conservative and
religious parties who had defected from his coalition, Barak said,
``Just a year ago the public gave us a mandate to lead, not to
protect what exists, but to change the reality from its core and to
assure the future of Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not going alone,'' Barak added. ``With me are almost two
million voters, citizens who want peace.''
</P>
<P>
   But Barak departed for Maryland with his coalition in tatters
and early elections on the horizon. Even if he can hammer out a
peace deal with Arafat, he will have to live up to a campaign
promise to bring the accord to the voters before he signs it.
</P>
<P>
   Likud leader Ariel Sharon, a leading hawk in the Knesset,
thundered that Barak ``wanted to prime minister of everybody.
Within a year, he is prime minister of almost no one.
</P>
<P>
   ``A prime minister who can't make peace in his nation, let alone
his own government, can't make peace with the Arabs.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak finds himself in a position not unlike the one faced last
year by his predecessor and rival, former prime minister Benjamin
Netanyahu of Likud, who battled through four no-confidence votes
before being ousted by a coalition of increasingly rabid opponents.
Netanyahu was forced to call early elections and lost to Barak one
year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Although political observers said Barak has little reason to
fear early elections because Likud is in disarray and the aging
Sharon does not pose a serious threat, the political turmoil left
the prime minister badly weakened.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, his carefully constructed coalition unravelled with
surprising speed when three rightist parties bolted within hours
and left him with a minority government in parliament. A former
general who was Israel's most highly decorated soldier, he has been
criticized for arrogance and for his failure to marshall broad
support on the eve of the summit. Wearing the tight-lipped, almost
smug smile that has become his signature expression, he sat in the
Knesset Monday surrounded by the ministers who had resigned.
</P>
<P>
   But even on this seemingly bleak political terrain, there were
signs that Barak could yet steer a path through the fractious
politics of the parliament and find support with the voters who
elected him last year in a landslide, based largely on his pledge
to obtain a fair peace with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   A poll published in Israel's largest newspaper, Yediot Ahronot,
found that 55 percent of respondents felt Barak should go to Camp
David despite the political uproar. And 53 percent said they felt
Barak has a mandate to make concessions that would return West Bank
land captured from the Palestinians during the 1967 Six Day War in
order to achieve a peace deal.
</P>
<P>
   Several Israeli analysts said the situation is not unlike some
of the most decisive moments that past Israeli leaders have faced.
Prime ministers David Ben Gurion, Menachem Begin, and Yitzhak Rabin
all faced strident opposition as they embarked on fateful
decisions, they noted.
</P>
<P>
   Hirsh Goodman, a senior political analyst for the Jaffee Center
for Strategic Studies in Tel Aviv, said Ben Gurion, Israel's
founding father, had the support of only five of the 11 members of
the ruling council when he set out to declare statehood for Israel
in 1948.
</P>
<P>
   It was then that he made the now-famous statement: ``I don't
know what the people want, I know what they need.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodman said the summit may prove to be the most decisive moment
since the Jewish state was born 52 years ago:
</P>
<P>
   ``What is happening at Camp David is the most profound decision
any prime minister will have to make since the establishment of the
state,'' he said in an interview. ``There was peace with Jordan,
but there was no uprooting of settlements. There was peace with
Egypt, but there was no emotional attachemnt among Israelis to the
Sinai. But now emotionally and ideologically, we are divided. We
are talking about defining the border of Israel, and no amount of
money is going to satisfy those who have to give up their homes in
the West Bank.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak took time Monday to reiterate his core beliefs going into
the talks: that Israel will not completely withdraw to pre-1967
borders; that a united Jerusalem must remain under Israeli
sovereignty; and that Israel would ``not take a moral or legal
responsibility'' for Palestinian refugees who wish to return home
after fleeing or being uprooted during the wars of 1948 and 1967.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat went into the summit talks with pressures of his own. The
Palestinians, who now have full or partial control of only pockets
of West Bank territory, are demanding a contiguous swath of the
West Bank for a future state. He has vowed to declare a Palestinian
state in mid-September whether the peace process has moved forward
or not, and he insists that the capital of the future state must be
in East Jerusalem, which was captured in 1967 and later annexed by
Israel. Arafat has been less clear about demanding a so-called
``right of return'' for the estimated 3 million Palestinian
refugees scattered throughout the Arab world, many still living in
squalid refugee camps.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Wire service material was used to prepare this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
