<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 19:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8222 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a k BC-LEASE-COLUMN-NYTR &LR;      07-10 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEASE-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOKING FOR A HOT INVESTMENT TIP? HAVE A SEAT
</HEADLINE>
  By DARYL LEASE   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now that the hi-tech boom has fizzled out and all the dot.com
geniuses are back to serving me my fries, I'm actively looking for
places to invest the $1.86 I have left in my 401(k).
</P>
<P>
   One afternoon last week, I was ready to hand everything over to
that Russian fellow, Roman Kunikov, who says he's invented
gasoline-powered boots. Perhaps you saw the news coverage:
Supposedly you can strap these boots on _ they look like one-foot
tall metal stilts _ and hover your way down the sidewalk at speeds
up to 25 mph.
</P>
<P>
   At first, this sounded like a wonderful spot to sink my life
savings, but I'm not so sure. For one thing, I'm troubled by
visions of SUV drivers smugly punching buttons to wash these
hovercrafts off their windshields. Plus, none of the stories I read
about these George Jetson boots said anything about gas mileage. As
soon as I invest, I just know I'll start seeing people clomping
down the side of the road in their funny little stilts, looking to
borrow gas from guys with weed-eaters.
</P>
<P>
   I'm really kicking myself for not getting rich off the Internet
when it was still possible. Mike, a friend of mine, used to drop by
my house years ago _ long before Al Gore ``invented'' the Internet
_ and talk excitedly about a new global computer network he'd seen
in grad school.
</P>
<P>
   Like dolts, we blathered on and on about the educational value
of this network.
</P>
<P>
   An information revolution! Like Gutenberg and the printing
press! Power to the people! Yadda yadda yadda.
</P>
<P>
   The really big money, of course, would be in (a) pornography,
(b) Webcams focused on people's toilets, and (c) Web sites where
you can quickly buy and sell stocks for companies that peddle
pornography and videostreams of people sitting on their toilets. If
only we'd known.
</P>
<P>
   Mike now lives in Japan, where he periodically alerts me to
bizarre Pokemon-like trends that might be headed this way. I'm free
to use this information to flee in horror or _ if I'm feeling
adventurous _ invest.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, for instance, he tipped me off to armpit art.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Japan Times, the hottest new beauty trend in
the Land of the Rising Sun focuses on ``an often-ignored erogenous
zone _ the armpit.''
</P>
<P>
   (Remember, you read it here first.)
</P>
<P>
   For 10,000 yen, the Times reports, young ladies can walk into
beauty shops, defuzz their underarms and ``highlight them with
everything from floral designs to sparkling glitter.'' The service
also includes a spritz of deodorant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Designs on smooth, hair-free armpits will really make an
impact,'' says Emiko Ozaki, a spokesman for a chain of 200 beauty
shops. ``In 2000, we will really see skin evolving as a fashion
accessory.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike, my investment counselor, also sent word of a trend a
little closer to home _ an amusement ride that recreates, sort of,
the experience of sitting in an electric chair.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington Post reports that people are eagerly lining up to
hop into the ``Original Shocker,'' an oversized oak throne at a
mall in Rockville, Md.
</P>
<P>
   The chair has, according to The Post, ``leather limb restraints
and a numbing vibration system that seeks to simulate the `13,200
volts' threatened on the side.''
</P>
<P>
   The ride also features a ``heart monitor,'' complete with the
sounds of a beating heart. At the end of the zapping session, the
line on the monitor goes flat and a wisp of smoke drifts up from
beyond the rider's head. (No mention, alas, of whether your armpits
are defuzzed.)
</P>
<P>
   An English company called Nova manufactures the rides, and
they've popped up in various places around the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Now, some folks might call this utterly tasteless _ did I
mention the rider's feet jerk and shake to the sounds of crackling
electricity? _ but you can't argue with success. Plus, as several
onlookers noted, the ride could turn out to be a valuable
educational tool. Giggling kids might walk away with the lesson
that crime doesn't pay.
</P>
<P>
   And that weirdness does. Over the Fourth of July weekend, an
estimated 2,000 people sat in the chair at the Maryland mall. At $1
a ride, I'd say Nova is a sizzling hot investment.
</P>
<P>
   (Daryl Lease is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla. Contact him at daryl.lease(AT)herald-trib.com.The
Herald-Tribune is a member of the New York Times Regional
Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
