   MAIN DISPLAY:
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-U.S.-FLIGHTS (Washington) _ The long rivalry between New
York and Chicago has a new front: the Transportation Department is
expected to decide this summer which city will become the take-off
point for a lucrative set of new flights to China. The decision has
added importance because of the increase in travel that is expected
follow China's likely entrance into the World Trade Organization.
Doing New York's bidding is Delta Air Lines, which wants to fly to
Beijing from JFK. Delta executives argue that New York's size and
economic importance so outweigh Chicago's as to make the decision
an easy one. American Airlines, which would fly from O'Hare to
Shanghai, responds that Chicago's location trumps demographics.
This contest, however, comes with a twist: Chicago and New York
could both end up losing, and the airlines' carping may be hurting
both of their cases. By David Leonhardt.
</P>
<P>
   (With graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   (Will move by 8:30 p.m.)
</P>
<P>
   RIGHT SIDE, CENTER:
</P>
<P>
   CONSECO-WENDT (Undated) _ Gary C. Wendt took the cash up front
when he agreed to become chairman and chief executive of Conseco
Inc., the company disclosed on Monday. Conseco, the troubled
insurance and financial services company, said that it paid Wendt a
signing bonus of $45 million when he joined the company last month.
He was also given 3.2 million shares of stock, now worth $31.2
million, as well as options to buy 10 million more shares. Wendt,
the former chief executive of General Electric Capital, will not
get a salary for the first two years he runs Conseco, but he will
get a bonus of no less than $8 million, and as much as $50 million,
at the end of the two-year period, depending on how high the stock
price is. By Floyd Norris.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move by 9 p.m.)
</P>
<P>
   RIGHT SIDE, BOTTOM:
</P>
<P>
   PHOTO-SUIT (New York) _ The National Basketball Association has
filed suit against The New York Times Co., accusing it of violating
the terms of its photographers' press passes by selling photographs
from the 1999 NBA playoffs. The suit appears to be the first time a
sports league has tried to control the use of the material
journalists' gather at sporting events. It underscores a growing
determination of the owners of entertainment properties to control
their products and any profits that come from them. The Times sold
a package of five photographs of Knick games for $900 on its online
store. By Felicity Barringer.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move by 9 p.m.)
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM CENTER:
</P>
<P>
   EARNINGS-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ As the second-quarter earnings
season gets into full swing this week, with reports expected from
General Electric, Motorola, Yahoo and J.P. Morgan, the outlook is
the best it has been for years. But a look back at 1994 shows that
even great earnings news may not lift stock prices much when the
Federal Reserve is still intent on raising interest rates to slow
growth. By Jonathan Fuerbringer.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move by 8 p.m.)
</P>
