346-9867; e-mail: patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in the ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SALVADOR-GARDEN (San Salvador, El Salvador) _ Like a testament
to life's stubborn triumph, a rose garden filled with thick,
fragrant blossoms rises at the site where soldiers killed six
Jesuit priests at the Jose Simeon Canas Central American University
in 1989. Nearby, a votive candle flickers in the room where the
soldiers then killed a housekeeper and her daughter, hoping to
eliminate any witnesses. It did not work. One woman saw the crime
and helped build a case against the gunmen. More important, more
than a decade since the killings, tens of thousands of people from
around the world have sought out the Jesuit residence's tiny garden
to bear their own witness to the faith of eight people they
consider martyrs who defended the poor during this country's civil
war. A foreign journal by David Gonzalez. (1375 words)
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-POLITICS (Istanbul) _ The increasing likelihood that a
73-year-old former prime minister will go to prison for remarks in
a political speech six years ago is sending a chill through
Turkey's political elite and bringing widespread calls to relax
laws that restrict freedom of speech. An appeals court last week
upheld the one-year sentence and lifetime political ban imposed on
former Prime Minister Necmettin Erbakan on the charge of
``provoking hatred'' in a 1994 speech. Since the ruling, political
leaders have scrambled to diminish the decision's impact on
Turkey's efforts to portray itself as a modern democracy and to
join the European Union. By Douglas Frantz.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-POLITICS (Calgary, Alberta) _ Stockwell Day, the new
leader of Canada's official opposition, offers a conservative face
rarely associated with Canadian politicians: support for a flat
income tax, tougher sentencing for criminals, and beefed up
military spending. But his sudden sweep to national prominence,
culminating with his decisive election Saturday night as leader of
the new Canadian Alliance, seems vaguely familiar, leading some
press commentators to call him the ``Pierre Trudeau of the Right.''
By James Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in the ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   ANTHRAX-VACCINE (Washington) _ Secretary of Defense William S.
Cohen has decided to dramatically reduce the number of American
troops receiving inoculations for anthrax because of the country's
dwindling supply of the vaccine, senior Pentagon officials said on
Monday. By Elaine Sciolino.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-CONVENTION (Undated) _ The schedule for the Republican
convention breaks with tradition. The roll call will be conducted
over several days, as everyone agrees that it's a snoozer. Also the
vice presidential nominee will speak on Wednesday, to keep that day
interesting, leaving George W. Bush to dominate the final night of
coverage. By Peter Marks.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-AIDS-CONFERENCE (Durban, South Africa) _ Scientists at the
13th international conference on AIDS here debated Monday what to
do about one of the most puzzling but potentially important
findings in AIDS, namely that circumcised men are two to eight
times less likely to become infected with the AIDS virus than
uncircumcised men. The finding was first made in Africa more than a
decade ago and has been noted in more than 40 studies since then.
Now many scientists have come to suspect that circumcision is an
important factor in the vast differences among African countries in
rates of infection from HIV, the AIDS virus. By Lawrence K. Altman.
(930 words)
</P>
<P>
   (MOVED)
</P>
</TEXT>
