</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000710.0307 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 19:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8241 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-TED-WILLIAMS-COX     07-10 1871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TED-WILLIAMS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    He's 82, and Ted Williams still can talk about hitting
 &HT;    By Paul Reid
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. - You see Ted Williams sitting there in
his kitchen bathed in the white, blinding light of a Florida
morning, and you grasp all the symbolic transcendent stuff baseball
fans take away from the game.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, baseball's just a game. Our game. And Ted Williams is a
legend. Period.
</P>
<P>
   He's almost 82. It's been 40 years since he took his last swing,
a home run of course. It's been almost 60 years since he set a
record that may never fall: batting .406 in 1941. That's a fair
spell ago. He hit .344, lifetime. If a modern hitter hit .344 once
in his career he'd consider it a year to remember. Williams won all
the awards, was named one of the top athletes of the century in all
the millennium polls.
</P>
<P>
   You see Williams sitting there, squinting into the sun, eyes
clear, chin set, and you can't help but hear old voices, see old
scenes, black and white and grainy at the edge. Old names: Ruth,
Foxx, Gehrig, Hornsby, Cy Young. Mantle, Mays and DiMaggio.
</P>
<P>
   And him. The guy eating a breakfast of fresh melon, fresh mango,
grapefruit, scrambled eggs and sausage, links and patties, big
glass of fresh orange juice, frothy.
</P>
<P>
   Come in, he says. Sit down. Have some breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   Clear voice. Great radio voice. So powerful he wouldn't need
much of a transmitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We make the sausage right here, got a French chef,'' he says
``And the freshest juice in Florida. Sit down. Eat.''
</P>
<P>
   He sweeps a hand toward a chair. Long fingers. Beautiful hands.
Piano hands. Steady.
</P>
<P>
   Sit down, he says. Tell me about yourself.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, oh.
</P>
<P>
   You have been forewarned by George Carter, Williams' houseman,
helper, caregiver. Pal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ted likes to engage you,'' Carter had cautioned. ``He likes a
good discussion. If you show any weakness he'll eat you up. He's
interested in everything, so you better be prepared. The stroke
slowed him down. He tires easily. But watch out.''
</P>
<P>
   Everybody wants a piece of the legend. So George - ex-cop and
ex-sergeant major, U.S. Army - guards the gate. He's built like a
bombard tower. Only someone really dumb or someone Carter truly
loves would ever call him a name. Like Porky, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Porky,'' says Williams, ``I'm gonna have more of this
wonderful sausage this morning, and I don't want to hear anything
about it being bad for my diet.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter smiles.
</P>
<P>
   Williams sits back, squints hard, like a pitcher about to
deliver something nasty. The chin is set. The gaze. Here it comes.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, you know a lot about baseball?'' he asks, and stabs a
sausage link.
</P>
<P>
   The question blows by like a rising fastball. You think, what
kind of fool would answer, sure, Ted. Tons. I know tons about
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Tell me about baseball, you say.
</P>
<P>
   And he does. And more. With the extra sausage links arriving and
Carter pulling his chain, the legend becomes flesh and blood,
human. You get an old man reflecting on a life well lived. But you
don't for a minute forget who's talking here.
</P>
<P>
   On baseball: ``I was in the right place at the right time. I
could swing a bat. I was a lucky kid. This was the Depression, you
know, late '30s. Boy, was I lucky. Did I want to be the greatest
hitter of all time? Yes. Of course. Why do anything if you don't
want to be the best.''
</P>
<P>
   On fishing: ``I was a hunter before I was a fisherman. I think
the most peaceful times of my life were spent at dawn, in a duck
blind somewhere. Manitoba. Minnesota. You wait for the flocks, it's
quiet, a breeze maybe. So quiet. So majestic. But then the great
bird migrations got not so great. The birds disappeared. People did
that, yes? Not hunters, but mankind. What a whacky bunch we humans
are.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started fishing more. I discovered the Atlantic salmon. Now
let me tell you, the Atlantic salmon is an incredible creature. It
swims thousands of miles back to the stream where it was born,
thousands of miles. The young are in danger from day one. Bears,
otters, mink. An epic struggle. And then, off they go to the far
oceans, thousands of miles. Until something tells them it's time to
go home again. Isn't that a miraculous life cycle? Sure, you got
your African lion. Big deal. They hunt, they kill stuff, they eat
stuff, they sleep. I'm not knocking lions, but for all the beauty
and mystery of life, give me an Atlantic salmon.''
</P>
<P>
   It fast becomes obvious that the wonder years never ended for
Williams. He speaks with a childlike sense of curiosity and
amazement. Not because he's an old guy, but because he's young
where it counts. Everything goes under his microscope. There is an
intense concentration about him, perhaps born of being on the
receiving end of more than100,000 major league pitches. Or perhaps
it was there all along, which is why he sent so many of those
pitches into the bleachers. He scrutinizes words and ideas as if
they were sinking curve balls.
</P>
<P>
   On history: ``Tell me. Who was the most influential American of
the century, other than FDR? Come on now. Who? Douglas MacArthur.
He set the pace for the entire postwar world. Imagine if he had
gone into Japan intent on revenge. Imagine Japan collapsing into a
new dictatorship after the war. Sure, he was pompous. But he was
wise. Wise. That's the ticket.''
</P>
<P>
   On heros: ``My heros? Navy and Marine flyers, World War II,
Korea. Joe Foss. On Guadalcanal he went up daily for over a month.
Shot down, what, 20, 25 Jap fighters and bombers. It was just pure
guts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The proudest moment of my life was the day I earned my Navy
wings. What an honor. The best bunch of guys in the world, and I
was one of them. And later, in Korea, with John Glenn. I was his
wingman. I went from props to jets - F-9s - because this guy told
me, Ted, the jets are just so easy to fly. Well, they're easy to
fly unless you're hit, then they drop like a rock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Combat? I was lucky. Sure, I gained perspective. You have to.
It's combat. But don't get me wrong. I didn't come back and play
baseball and think, this is just a game, this isn't combat. It is,
especially when a pitcher is trying to hurt you. You know, every
experience in life has a lesson that can be applied somewhere else
in life. You gotta just keep learning the lessons.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams speaks, remembers, reflects. On jet engines, history,
hunting, hitters, pitchers. Carter tops off the orange juice.
Clocks in the big house chime the hour. Chirp the hour, actually.
Williams loves birds, and his clocks sing the hour -- bluebirds at
10, robins at 11, finches, parakeets, owls. On the hour the house
sounds like an aviary at feeding time. You appreciate bird song
more as you get older, says Williams.
</P>
<P>
   On old age: ``The so-called golden years. What a lot of bull. I
think you ought to get a pill when you turn 72, a pill to take if
and when you think it's time. I call it the Kevorkian pill.''
</P>
<P>
   On the press: ``Those Boston writers could be a bunch of
S.O.B's. And they went after Curt Gowdy, too. They thought Curt
didn't root hard enough for the Red Sox. Well, hell, he was an
announcer not a cheerleader. I forget the names of some of those
writers. But I'll never forget Curt. What does that tell you?
What's important in life? Your friends.''
</P>
<P>
   This from the guy once considered to be testy, aloof and
downright nasty by the Boston press.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm just a lovable old guy, now,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   And the last of the baseball giants. Most have been gone for a
half century or more.
</P>
<P>
   You see him sitting there and you can't help but dream old
dreams. Legends are catalysts: Take a simple game like baseball,
add a kid, add a million kids. Then mix in a legend. You get a
million dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Williams made dreams.
</P>
<P>
   And, he made the most exciting event in baseball look like
ballet. The home run. A Williams home run was an Odyssean event,
parable, biography. The ball lived, soared. Died.
</P>
<P>
   He had to hit a home run in his last at bat. And he did.
September 28, 1960. His last at bat of the game, his season, his
career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jack Fisher was the Baltimore pitcher,'' says Williams. ``I'd
been hitting the ball hard, had already hit a long fly, 380-feet. I
felt pretty good. But the weather was wrong. Misty. Damp wind
blowing a little bit to the east. First pitch, ball one. Then I get
a pitch I know I can hit out. But I missed. Now I'm a little
worried. How could I miss that pitch? But I notice Fisher is
anxious to get that ball back. He's out there on the mound and he
wants that ball. That tells me something. Tells me he's in a hurry
to give me the same pitch. I know it's coming. And sure enough,
here it comes. And there it goes. Goodbye.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodbye it was. He loped around the bases and into the dugout
and was gone. He said goodbye with his bat.
</P>
<P>
   You heard Red Sox radio announcer Curt Gowdy a hundred times in
your youth, imagined that it was your crushing blow he was calling:
``Williams hits a looonng fly ball, deeep to center field. The
outfielders are just looking up at this one. This ball is going,
going...It's...gone.''
</P>
<P>
   You still hear those words when you're at a ball game. You're
grown, you have kids, but you still hear the words.
Going...going.... And you want someone to smack one out of there,
just for the sake of your kid, of course, so your kid can feel the
magic.
</P>
<P>
   A pitch, a swing. By the time you hear the crack of the bat the
ball is already halfway out of the park. You search for it in the
night sky, and there it is, bathed in a million watts of light,
floating lazily toward the black oblivion that waits beyond the
light towers. You have time to savor its flight, time even to
glimpse the offended pitcher as he kicks the dirt. Time to turn to
your kid and ask, do you see it? Time to turn back and behold the
ball as it wanders across the night sky, toward the blackness, then
into it. Going...going....
</P>
<P>
   It's gone, and like childhood or life itself, it was too short.
</P>
<P>
   You tell your kid: Nobody hits them like Williams.
</P>
<P>
   So now, you look at Williams in his kitchen in the glare of a
Florida morning as he, in turn, grasps a ball in his right hand and
beholds it with all the intensity of Hamlet with Yorik's noggin.
Williams sighs and rolls the ball across the table and says: ``I
was a ballplayer.''
</P>
<P>
   That's all: I was a ballplayer.
</P>
<P>
   Like a Ferrari is a car, Ted.
</P>
<P>
   He smiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was lucky,'' he says. ``A kid in the right place at the
right time.''
</P>
<P>
   And then you think a terrible thought. He's almost 82. The
stroke, the maladies of advancing age, the pills and doctors. This
long graceful flight is nearing an end. And those words of long
ago, Going., going...gone take on new and not so pleasant meaning.
</P>
<P>
   It is no consolation that we're all going, going, that sooner or
later we'll all be...ah, but you forgot the obvious. Of course:
Unlike the rest of us, Ted Williams will never, ever, be... gone.
</P>
<P>
   Williams leans across the kitchen table, stabs another sausage
link..
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you want to hear about the time Rogers Hornsby gave me
advice on the art of hitting?'
</P>
<P>
   Anytime, Ted. Anytime.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
