<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 19:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8250 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-10 0631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIAZZA PIE IN THE SKY ABOUT CLEMENS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOARD MANLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Give Mike Piazza some credit.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Clemens hits him in the head with a pitch, and though
visibly dazed from a concussion, Piazza tells the media he thought
Clemens was a great pitcher but he didn't have respect for him.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Piazza thought the beaning was intentional. But
that's not the point.
</P>
<P>
   Clemen's Yankee teammates were noticeably quiet.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees weren't so quiet two years ago when Clemens pitched
for the Toronto Blue Jays.
</P>
<P>
   During a September game in 1998, Clemens hit New York's Scott
Brosius in the back after the Yankees scored three runs in an
inning. The Yankees were already troubled by Clemens hitting Derek
Jeter in spring training and again during the regular season.
Monday, Newsday reprinted comments made by Jeter and Yankees
manager Joe Torre after that 1998 game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt it was on purpose,'' Torre said. ``Roger gets certain
privileges for what he has done for the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Jeter, ``He does it every time. It's no secret. He's been
doing it for years.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens defended his inside pitching to the New York Post and
said that he has never aimed the ball at a batter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned very young that you don't aim the ball,'' Clemens
said. ``I used to aim it and the ball ended up on the Mass Pike.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the injury, Piazza won't play in the All-Star Game,
but he was a commentator for Home Run Derby on ESPN Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   It's been that kind of season.
</P>
<P>
   Weird.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pregame analysis
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ESPN analyst Joe Morgan had a lot to say _ naturally _ about the
All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine Frank Thomas not being on this team when his
team has the best record in baseball,'' Morgan told reporters last
week. ``He's not on this team and he's having a great year. He
would get some MVP votes if people voted today. Winning teams
should have the most players. That's the way I feel because that's
what the game is about. The White Sox have the best record in
baseball and they should be represented that way. The fans this
year did a pretty good job, but you're always going to have some
hiccups _ it's impossible not to.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hall of Fame second baseman did have something positive to
say about the injury-riddled All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always felt that second basemen never get the credit
they're due because they're overshadowed by guys who hit 50 home
runs, but now you have some second basemen who are in that same
vein,'' Morgan said. ``Guys like Craig Biggio, guys who are usually
All-Stars, are not having their usual types of years. If you look
at Jose Vidro, you have to say this guy is unbelievable the way he
has hit and fielded. But it's a tough call to say who's the best.
It's the best crop I've ever seen.
</P>
<P>
   NBC's Bob Costas, who will work his fourth All-Star Game
Tuesday, told reporters that he was a National League years back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really remember beginning in the early '60s and into the
early '70s that the National League was much quicker and much more
progressive about signing black and Latin American stars than the
American League,'' Costas said. ``I was a Yankee fan and I loved
Mickey Mantle, but I always found myself rooting for the National
League in the All-Star Game, because you could just look at it and
see that these guys were fairer. They represented something that
was worth rooting for more than the American League did then. I
think it stood for something symbolically.''
</P>
<P>
   Costas said there is less passion for the All-Star Game these
days.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no one's fault,'' he said. ``It's just a product of all
the changes that have taken place in the game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
