<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8257 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-OPED-BEANBALLS-BOUTON     07-10 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPED-BEANBALLS-BOUTON-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PITCHING WITH A QUESTIONABLE PURPOSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (New York Times OpEd for Tuesday, July 11, and thereafter.)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's OPED news service. For more information
about purchasing this article as a separate-buy' _ or becoming a
client of the OPED news service _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.)  
 By JIM BOUTON    
 c.2000 New York Times    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EGREMONT, Mass. _ We called it ``chin music,'' the high inside
fastball that would flip a batter onto his back and get him
thinking. It was also known as a ``beanball'' or ``purpose pitch''
because it had so many purposes: intimidation of a hot hitter,
retaliation for having had one of your players ``dusted off,''
behavior modification for showboats and hot dogs. The nicknames
alone testify to its significance. In the 1950s, Sal ``The Barber''
Maglie of the New York Giants was famous for giving hitters ``a
close shave.''
</P>
<P>
   Compared with the high inside throwers of my era like Don
Drysdale and Bob Gibson, I was a sissy, even though I threw hard.
Pitching for the Yankees against the Kansas City A's in 1963, I
broke Wayne Causey's wrist with an inside fastball and ran up to
home plate to see how he was. My teammates told me afterward that
this was bad form. Even if it was an accident, they said, you
should never let the other team know. It never hurts to let them
think about it.
</P>
<P>
   Could that be why Roger Clemens didn't rush to home plate to
check on Mike Piazza's condition after he hit the Mets catcher in
the head on Saturday night? Maybe Clemens didn't care, but maybe he
was just following the code. Too often in sports, any sign of
humanity is perceived as weakness.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' players and fans accused Clemens of deliberately
throwing at Piazza's head but Clemens insisted that he was only
trying to brush Piazza back from the plate. How do you know if a
pitcher is intentionally throwing at a batter? Sometimes it's
obvious to umpires and other close observers by the demeanor of the
players or the context. Most of the time it's not obvious, and the
pitcher gets away with it.
</P>
<P>
   During my career, I only threw at one hitter on purpose. This
was during my first year, pitching for the Kearney Yankees in the
Class D Nebraska State League. Everybody on the team, including our
kindly old manager, wanted to nail a guy on the Holdredge White Sox
who actually played with file-sharpened spikes and who we caught
lobbing balls into the air during our infield practice that would
land among us like mortar shots.
</P>
<P>
   On our clubhouse wall someone had drawn the outline of this
player in a batting stance, with sections marked like the cow
illustration in the butcher shop. It was a contest for the
pitchers, with certain areas being worth more points. I faced him
only once, in relief, and threw the first pitch behind his head,
which is what you do when you're serious, because the hitter's
first move is usually back. But the guy froze and the ball hit his
bat and came bouncing back to me for an easy out.
</P>
<P>
   I've never had much respect for pitchers who use high inside
fastballs to intimidate hitters, especially in the American League,
where the designated hitter allows a pitcher to avoid the rough
justice of a turn at bat.
</P>
<P>
   Was Clemens trying to intimidate Piazza or, even worse, trying
to hit him? We know the context was that Piazza had gotten seven
hits, including three home runs, in 12 at-bats against Clemens in
their previous confrontations. Without Piazza in the lineup, the
Mets lost to Clemens for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   But evidently the umpires didn't feel they had enough evidence
to eject Clemens, or even warn him at the time. Everyone has an
opinion about what happened on Saturday night. But only the pitcher
knows for sure.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Bouton pitched for the New York Yankees from 1962 to 1968
and is the author of ``Ball Four.'')
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   EDITORS: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on OPED
articles and other features.
</P>
