<SLUG> BC-HOCKEY-MANSLAUGHTER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODWARD CASE LESSONS APPLIED TO RINK MANSLAUGHTER CHARGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SACHA PFEIFFER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Two killings, two totally different charges.
</P>
<P>
   When baby Matthew Eappen was shaken to death, Louise Woodward,
was accused of first-degree murder, a charge many thought didn't
fit the crime. In the end, the judge in the case reduced the
British au pair's conviction to involuntary manslaughter.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the same district attorney's office -- led by a different
district attorney -- is faced with another crime in which the
killing appears not to have been intentional: the beating death of
Michael Costin by Thomas Junta at a hockey rink in Boston's Reading
suburb.
</P>
<P>
   And this time, Middlesex District Attorney Martha Coakley, one
of the prosecutors in the Woodward case, has charged Junta with
manslaughter, not murder.
</P>
<P>
   It's a decision praised by many defense attorneys, who see the
Reading case as a rare instance of prosecutors resisting the
temptation to ``overcharge'' -- accusing a defendant of the most
serious offense possible to strengthen their position if plea
bargaining enters the picture.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the manslaughter charge has puzzled some of those same
lawyers, who wonder if the facts in the Reading case actually may
have supported a more serious charge. And it has led some legal
observers to conclude that Coakley applied lessons learned in the
Woodward case -- such as the perils of overcharging -- to the
Reading death.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before a prosecutor, particularly in Middlesex County, goes
forward with a higher charge, I think he or she may be inclined to
think long and hard about the appropriateness of the charge because
of the impact of Louise Woodward,'' said Marc Perlin, an associate
dean and professor of law at Suffolk University Law School.
</P>
<P>
   ``So one certainly could conclude that the Louise Woodward
legacy lives on,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For her part, Coakley, through a spokesman, insists that ``there
is no connection'' between the Woodward and Junta charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had absolutely nothing to do with each other,'' said the
spokesman, Anson Kaye. ``Every charging decision is based on the
facts and circumstances of the case at hand.''
</P>
<P>
   The investigation of the Reading case is still in its infancy,
and many of the facts in the case are still under wraps.
</P>
<P>
   Several lawyers interviewed Monday noted that deaths resulting
from fistfights, which is how Costin died, often result in
manslaughter charges.
</P>
<P>
   But Boston attorney Harvey Silverglate, who was a member of
Woodward's defense team, has a different viewpoint.
</P>
<P>
   That the Middlesex DA's office decided to charge Junta with
manslaughter ``is a recognition that they made a mistake charging
Louise with first-degree murder,'' Silverglate said.
</P>
<P>
   He noted, for example, that Coakley said Junta was charged with
manslaughter because there was no indication he intended to kill
Costin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, even in its wildest moments, the DA's office never
claimed, much less believed, that Louise tried to kill the baby,''
Silverglate said. ``So I think that the overcharging legacy of that
case has had some influence.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This certainly does look and smell like a manslaughter case,''
added Boston defense attorney James Sultan, ``but it seems unusual
to me that, given what was apparently a deliberate beating
resulting in death, the DA would charge that right off bat as
manslaughter rather than murder.''
</P>
<P>
   By law, murder is defined as an unlawful killing accompanied by
malice. To prove malice, prosecutors must show one of three things:
intent to kill, intent to cause grievous bodily injury, or intent
to cause an action that a reasonable person would know creates a
substantial likelihood of death or grievous bodily harm.
</P>
<P>
   Murder rises to the level of first-degree if it is done with
deliberate premeditation, extreme atrocity or cruelty, or during
the commission of a felony punishable by life imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
   Manslaughter is an unjustifiable killing that occurs without
malice, such as a death that arises during the heat of passion,
after reasonable provocation, or because of the excessive use of
force or defense. Involuntary manslaughter is a killing that
results from willful, wanton or reckless conduct.
</P>
<P>
   In deciding how to charge Junta, prosecutors had to weigh
allegations that he was ordered out of the rink but returned to
fight with Costa, indicating possible premeditation. Junta is also
alleged to have smashed Costin's head repeatedly on the rink floor,
indicating possible extreme atrocity or cruelty.
</P>
<P>
   Technically, a grand jury could still indict Junta for murder,
``but from a public relations standpoint that would really raise a
tremendous number of questions,'' Sultan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lesson learned from Woodward is that overcharging isn't
always the safe way to go,'' he added. ``It really can mess up the
effective and fair operation of criminal justice system, and there
may well be an attempt here to avoid same mistakes committed
there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
