<HEADER>
A8262 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-WIMBLEDON11-COX     07-10 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIMBLEDON11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Williams sisters finish at Wimbledon with doubles title
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Clarke
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England - Venus wore lavender and Serena wore pink,
and after spending more than two hours getting ready for the
Wimbledon Champions' Dinner, they spent just an hour at the Savoy
Hotel in central London.
</P>
<P>
   They still had work to do Monday after all - rain pushed
Wimbledon into a third week for the women's doubles final - and
needed to get some sleep before playing fourth seeds Ai Sugiyama
and Julie Halard-Decugis at noon.
</P>
<P>
   Venus admitted they've never stayed up later the night before a
final than they did Sunday night. But they don't expect the 2 a.m.
bedtime to become a habit - even though they did win 6-3, 6-2 just
before the rains returned at the All England Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad had left and before I knew it, I said, 'Now Serena, you
need to go to bed as soon as possible,' `` the singles champion
said, giggling, after the doubles match.
</P>
<P>
   ``She took over as the parent,'' sidekick Serena agreed,
laughing.
</P>
<P>
   It was a fun day for the Palm Beach Gardens, Fla., sisters, as
they entertained the crowd on-court for 70 minutes, carried a
silver trophy around for a few more minutes, then signed a few
autographs, did a few interviews, grabbed a check for about
$285,000 and headed to the airport to catch a flight home to
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great because it's a millenium Wimbledon,'' Venus said,
smiling. ``There will not be another millenium Wimbledon for
another millenium.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was a serious day, too.
</P>
<P>
   Winning Wimbledon's singles and doubles crowns together has been
a lifelong goal. They'll add the trophies to Serena's U.S. Open
singles title, and their 1999 U.S. Open and French Open doubles
victories.
</P>
<P>
   They also became the first sisters and the first all-black team
to win women's doubles at Wimbledon. Etienne Dumas, who has worked
with the family for about 10 years, remembers many conversations
with Richard Williams about this day. And he remembers many
practice sessions with the girls when he said, ``OK, you're in the
final of Wimbledon.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very proud at this moment, very very proud,'' Dumas said
after the doubles win. ``History's been made and that's what we
wanted from the beginning. that's what we talked about: We are
going to change history.''
</P>
<P>
   That was apparent in the Centre Court stadium Monday.
Ticketholders from Sunday were admitted, but most returned to work
or simply didn't bother showing up for women's doubles.
</P>
<P>
   The club anticipated that and admitted thousands of others for
just 5 pounds, about $7.50, for the women's doubles and girls'
doubles finals. All the money -- about $40,600 -- will go to a
children's charity.
</P>
<P>
   Fans lined up for the ``People's Monday'' beginning early in the
morning. By 11:30 a.m., they were racing around the grounds,
worried they wouldn't get in. But no one was turned away. And the
tournament's most diverse group of fans was allowed to fill in all
empty seats in the lower bowl 15 minutes before the start of the
match.
</P>
<P>
   They whooped, hollered, did the wave - even getting those in the
Royal Box to join in - and yelled out for Venus and Serena
throughout the match, prompting the umpire to instruct them not to
call out just before the players' serve.
</P>
<P>
   ``People here really support the sport. They're here the first
day and the stadium is packed 'til the last day,'' said Serena, who
wasn't surprised by the crowd. ``It's not like America - where they
come only for the finals, the semis. It's really different.''
</P>
<P>
   After becoming the first doubles team to win on a wild card, the
Williams' now will be ranked in the mid-20s and shouldn't need
another wild card for a long time. But they will be eager to hear
whom Olympics coach Billie Jean King selects to play doubles in
Australia in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Venus, who will be selected to play singles, admitted it would
be hard for her to go if Serena wasn't chosen to play too.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of whether they play in the Olympics, they certainly
look like the future of women's tennis. They burst onto the scene
three years ago with more splash and attitude than game and
aptitude. Now that they've each won a Grand Slam and shown they can
dominate doubles whenever they chose, Chris Evert admits she
worries about the health of the rest of the WTA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   The sisters can understand why.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really amazing because I hadn't played in two months;
Venus has only played four tournaments this year and for us to come
back like this, I can only imagine what people are thinking,''
Serena said. ``Obviously they're probably going to go home and
practice harder, but you know what? We are too. We're really
serious and we mean business.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Venus: ``It's getting pretty scary.''
</P>
<P>
   But they still remain relatively inexperienced. Just 20 and 18,
Venus and Serena haven't played nearly as many matches or
tournaments as their peers. Their games will get so much better
when they reduce their errors, harness their power and master the
mental game.
</P>
<P>
   They can't attain No. 1 in the rankings this year because of the
time they've missed, but they can get into position to pounce on
the spot early next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was one of our goals since we were younger, not just to
win Slams, but to be the best in the world and see our name next to
the No. 1 ranking,'' Serena said. ``That's a personal goal that we
both really want to accomplish in our careers.''
</P>
<P>
   Venus is closer, matching a career-high No. 3 in Monday's
ranking. Serena improved one spot to No. 7. Until they can reach
numbers 1 and 2 (assuring they couldn't meet until a tournament
final), they plan to collect as many rankings points and titles as
possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're both out to get all we can get,'' Serena said. ``We're
both really greedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
