<HEADLINE>
IN REFERENDUM ON BASHAR, SOME IN SYRIA VOTE WITH THEIR BLOOD 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT 2,3 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JOHN KIFNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
  BEIRUT, Lebanon _ Syrians lined up to vote Monday in a referendum
to confirm Bashar Assad as president.
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was hardly a cliffhanger. Indeed, Assad was the sole
candidate, and the swearing-in was already scheduled for Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   He is the son of Hafez Assad, who ruled with an iron fist for 30
years. The election Monday was part of a programmed process by the
governing Baath Party and an inner circle of the late president to
provide the trappings of legitimate succession. Portraits of Bashar
Assad, once a little-known eye doctor, flooded Damascus on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In quick tempo after Assad's death on June 10, the constitution
was amended to make the minimum age for the presidency 34, Bashar
Assad's age. He was also promoted to lieutenant general and
commander of the army, named head of the Baath Party Regional
Command and endorsed for president by acclaim in a parliamentary
session that ran an extra day because so many people wanted to be
recorded in support.
</P>
<P>
   As Prime Minister Mohammed Miro, who was appointed in March with
Bashar Assad's backing, voted, he told reporters, ``The people gave
their opinion before the referendum by choosing Bashar as
president.''
</P>
<P>
   A long-serving previous prime minister, Mahmoud Zubi, committed
suicide on May 21 as security forces arrived to arrest him in what
was generally described as an anticorruption drive spearheaded by
Bashar Assad that purged a number of formerly powerful officials.
</P>
<P>
   The voting Monday _ extended, officials said, for popular demand
_ consisted of marking a ballot in a green circle signifying
approval of Assad or a negative gray circle.
</P>
<P>
   A number of polling places provided an unusual electoral
accessory, an array of safety pins or sewing needles with which
voters could prick their thumbs and mark the circles in blood.
</P>
<P>
   Basil Hassan, 18, voting at a school where he was taking a free
15-day computer course sponsored by Bashar Assad in his only
previous official role as head of the Syrian Computer Society,
marked his ballot with a bloody thumbprint.
</P>
<P>
   ``We already sacrificed a lot of blood for our country in peace
and war,'' Hassan said. ``We will sacrifice more of our blood and
our country for Dr. Bashar. He is a student in his father's school,
and he will continue in his footsteps.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials in one voting place open to foreign reporters looked
shocked when a women marked her ballot in blood in the gray ``no''
circle instead of the green approval circle. She quickly realized
her error, however, and was given another ballot to commend the new
government.
</P>
<P>
   In the polling place where Miro voted, an official assured
reporters that not one of the 435 votes cast in the first four
hours of the referendum had been negative.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Minister Farouk Shara said to reporters after casting
his ballot: ``There has been a lot of betting on the succession,
that the absence of Assad would lead to instability and ambiguity.
We thank God that all these bets have failed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
