<SLUG> BC-EARNINGS-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR INVESTORS, STRONG EARNINGS MAY NOT OFFSET INTEREST RATE
JITTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the second-quarter earnings season gets into full swing this
week _ with reports expected from General Electric, International
Paper, Motorola, Yahoo and  &UR; J. &LR; P. Morgan _ the outlook is the best
it has been in years.
</P>
<P>
   But a look back at 1994 shows that even great earnings news may
not lift stock prices much when the Federal Reserve is still intent
on raising interest rates to slow an overheating economy.
</P>
<P>
   Earnings picked up steam through most of 1994, and the companies
in the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index finished the year with a
16.4 percent gain in operating earnings, well above the average for
the the '90s. Meanwhile, the stock market flagged. The Dow Jones
industrial average eked out a 2.1 percent gain, while the S&AMP;P 500
fell 1.5 percent and the Nasdaq composite dropped 3.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, the outlook for earnings is even better than
it was then. In the first quarter, profits surged 23.6 percent from
the year-earlier quarter, the strongest performance since the last
three months of 1993, according to First Call/Thomson Financial,
which collects Wall Street forecasts for the 500 companies in the
S&AMP;P index. For the second quarter, earnings are expected to
increase 19.2 percent, First Call says. And for the full year,
analysts are forecasting 19.2 percent earnings growth, which would
make this year's gain the strongest since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the three major stock indexes are down or flat for 2000,
after hitting new highs earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed's interest rate increases have taken the rally out of
the market, as they did in 1994. Rising rates threaten to slow
economic growth and, therefore, cut into corporate earnings. They
also can raise borrowing costs for companies. And higher interest
rates, when plugged into many Wall Street valuation formulas,
immediately make stocks look more expensive when compared with
their projected earnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market hasn't made much headway because investors had an
eye on the Fed,'' said Thomas Galvin, chief investment officer of
Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette. Although Galvin says that this year's
stock market performance would have been worse if profits had not
been as strong, he now expects the market to be in a holding
pattern until investors sense that the Fed has taken its foot off
the brake.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is still a fair amount of skepticism that the cool-down
in the economy is not enough for the Fed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The power of the Fed to stymie the market is remarkable given
that the projected earnings growth for this year is stronger than
the actual growth proved to be in each year of the 1995-to-1999
run, when the Nasdaq and the S &AMP; P 500 rose 20 percent or more each
year and the Dow climbed 20 percent or more in four of the five.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Liro, chief economist at Stone &AMP; McCarthy Research
Associates in Princeton, N.J., warns that although earnings growth
will be strong this year, the pace will slow at the end of the year
and will decelerate further early next year. ``I have been fairly
optimistic about earnings and remain so,'' he said. ``But it may
not be good enough for investors to get excited about.''
</P>
<P>
   Another factor that could continue to undermine the stock market
is inflation, which some analysts expect to rise even as the
economy slows. During the stock market rallies since 1995, the rate
of core consumer inflation, which excludes the cost of energy and
food, was in decline. It fell to an annual increase of 1.9 percent
last year from 3 percent in 1995. But for the three months through
May, core inflation rose at a 3.2 percent annual rate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the long haul, what is the most important thing for stock
prices in any given quarter or any given year is the trend in
inflation and the bond yield,'' said Douglas Cliggott, U.S. equity
strategist at J.P. Morgan Securities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Earnings were great in the first quarter and will be darn good
in the second quarter,'' he said. ``But the reason the market
indexes are slightly down is the inflation trend.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas McManus, equity strategist at Banc of America Securities,
sees another dark cloud in the outlook. Wall Street analysts are
overestimating the strength in earnings for the rest of the year,
he says, because they do not realize how far the Federal Reserve
will go to slow the economy and curb inflation.
</P>
<P>
   He is forecasting that the earnings growth rate will decline
sharply this year, falling to 9 percent by the final quarter and to
zero in the first quarter of 2001. That would bring earnings growth
well below the 11 percent average so far in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing that is going to bring inflationary pressures
down is to break through that trend line,'' McManus said. ``And
that is not currently baked into analysts' forecasts.''
</P>
<P>
   But while strong earnings may not be able to drive the stock
market much higher in the face of expected Federal Reserve rate
increases, they are still a good guide to those picking stocks.
McManus says investors should stick to what he calls the
predictable earnings sectors, including utilities, health care,
consumer products and, to a lesser extent, financials.
</P>
<P>
   Galvin urges investors to consider health care and technology
stocks because they performed the best after the Fed took its foot
off the brakes in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Earnings performance is far more important for stock pickers
this year than it was last year, Galvin says. In 1999, companies in
the Nasdaq composite index that reported operating losses had an
average stock gain of 115 percent for the year. Among the companies
that reported profits, the average stock gained 51 percent. So far
this year, companies with losses have stock declines of 11 percent
on average while companies with profits have stock gains of 10
percent on average.
</P>
<P>
   There is some good news in this look back at 1994. It is what
happened in 1995. The Dow average surged 33.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Once it is clear that the Federal Reserve has finished raising
interest rates _ as long as the economy has not been slowed to the
brink or even into a recession _ nice earnings ought to help the
stock market forge ahead again.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is, while some analysts think the pace of economic
growth is slowing enough for the Fed to take its foot off the
brakes, Federal Reserve officials have not given an all-clear
signal yet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
