u f BC-HONEYWELL-OUTLOOK-NYT     07-10 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONEYWELL-OUTLOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITING COSTS, HONEYWELL EXPECTS ADDITIONAL LOWER EARNINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLAUDIA H. DEUTSCH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Honeywell International, citing high raw material costs in some
businesses, slow growth in others and high interest rates in all of
them, told investors Monday that its second-quarter profit would be
75 cents a share, about 3 cents less than the company had predicted
earlier this year. The company also lowered its earnings estimates
for the full year and for 2001.
</P>
<P>
   On June 19, Honeywell warned analysts that the quarter's
earnings would fall short of their expectations. That time,
surprised and angry investors sent Honeywell's shares plummeting by
more than 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   This time, investors seemed to simply shrug as shares of
Honeywell rose 37.5 cents, to $35.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investors priced their disappointments into the stock on June
19, and now they want to take a breather and see what happens,''
said David A. Kiefer, a portfolio manager at Prudential Global
Asset Management, which holds Honeywell stock.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, most analysts kept strong buy recommendations on the
company, in part because the stock is now so cheap.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given where earnings are, and the company's ability to
generate results, the shares should be trading in the mid-40s,''
said Howard A. Rubel, an analyst at Goldman, Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   The earnings shortfall and lagging stock come at an unpropitious
time for Michael R. Bonsignore, Honeywell's chief executive.
Honeywell International was formed last year when Honeywell Inc.,
the Minneapolis company that Bonsignore ran, merged with Allied
Signal Inc. Part of the deal was that Bonsignore would run the
merged company when Lawrence Bossidy, Allied's well-regarded chief,
retired.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our fundamentals are strong,'' said Bonsignore, who became
chief executive in December and chairman in April. But he added
that this was a difficult was for him to get started.
</P>
<P>
   Bonsignore inherited many of the company's problems. Bossidy
invested heavily in pharmaceutical and chip-packaging businesses,
both of which have been bottom-line disasters.
</P>
<P>
   But the merged company has also had disappointing growth in
industrial controls and fire security systems, two businesses that
the old Honeywell brought to the party. And it has not been able to
offset tripling oil prices with price and volume increases in its
chemicals businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are problems on both sides of the portfolio,''
Bonsignore acknowledged Monday. ``And if we hadn't been so
distracted by melding cultures and otherwise making this merger
work, we might have reacted more quickly to oil prices.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts are giving him the benefit of the doubt, at least for a
while. ``We aren't ready to hang him yet,'' said David Bleustein,
an analyst with PaineWebber. ``But if problems surface in 2001,
they will clearly be on Michael Bonsignore's watch.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Bonsignore described several plans to keep that from
happening. He said he would close the chip operation, taking a
charge of $59 million, and would divest pharmaceuticals and
friction materials. Most analysts think he is already negotiating
sales of both.
</P>
<P>
   He said he might spin off part of Honeywell's new microturbine
business to shareholders, a move that could generate a huge amount
of cash. Last month Capstone Microturbine, which also makes
microturbines _ small, clean-burning power generators _ went public
at $16; it now trades in the $60s.
</P>
<P>
   Bonsignore also promised to reduce costs by an additional $100
million a quarter over the next two to three years and to use
attrition to trim 5,000 jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Bonsignore would use the resulting cash to reduce Honeywell's
debt-to-capital ratio, now a troubling 42 percent. He would like to
flesh out the company's core aircraft parts and industrial controls
businesses with more acquisitions. And he wants to buy back stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this price, a share buyback would certainly be a
compelling, high priority use of our cash,'' Bonsignore said.
</P>
</TEXT>
