<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-PAROLE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRENCH KILLER IN PIVOTAL CASE TO STAY IN JAIL 
</HEADLINE>
   By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Patrick Henry, whose trial in 1977 for killing a
7-year-old boy helped lead to abolition of the death penalty in
France, has been refused parole.
</P>
<P>
   In the earlier case, Henry had a passionate young lawyer who put
the guillotine on trial instead. In the end, Henry got a life
sentence and, soon after, France abolished the death penalty
altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, Henry has been back in the headlines, at the heart of a
new debate over whether someone who has committed such a heinous
crime can be rehabilitated.
</P>
<P>
   Now 46, Henry says he is a changed man and he has mustered all
kinds of supporters. When France's justice minister, Elisabeth
Guigou, started considering the case last month she indicated that
she might act in his favor. Monday she said no.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief statement turning down the request, her office said
that she had done an ``in depth'' study of the case, asking for
``numerous opinions'' before making her decision.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the case underscores how far the country has come
in 20 years and how much the eye-for-an eye notions of punishment
have been replaced by a debate over the uses of incarceration and
the best ways to rehabilitate criminals, even those convicted of a
horrible crime.
</P>
<P>
   One of Henry's lawyers in 1977, Robert Bocquillon, said he was
convinced that Henry had completely remade himself in prison,
earning his baccalaureate, a mathematics degree and a degree in
computer programming. He has a job waiting for him when he gets
out.
</P>
<P>
   But by refusing to parole him, Guigou, a socialist, can avoid
what is still a difficult political decision. Polls indicated that
French citizens were, though by only a slight margin, still opposed
to his release.
</P>
<P>
   Henry kidnapped Philippe Bertrand, 7, from outside of his
school, strangled him and took the body to a room he had rented. He
wrapped the body in a blanket and stuffed it under the bed. Within
hours, he called the boy's parents and demanded a ransom of 1
million francs, which they could not pay. During the search for the
boy, Henry even appeared on national television saying people who
kidnap children deserve death.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
