<SLUG> BC-ANTHRAX-VACCINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITING SHORTAGE, PENTAGON CUTS BACK ON ANTHRAX VACCINATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich.)   By ELAINE SCIOLINO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Secretary of Defense William Cohen has decided to
drastically reduce the inoculation of American military personnel
against anthrax because of concerns that the country's supply of
the vaccine is running out, senior Pentagon officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The decision was made after a test of a stockpile of 194,000
doses on guinea pigs in recent weeks indicated that the vaccine had
lost much of its potency and might not be fully effective, they
added.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon will now inoculate only those most at risk of
facing attack by the deadly biological weapon: those who serve on
the ground in South Korea and Kuwait. Both North Korea and Iraq are
believed to have stockpiles of anthrax.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've reached the point where we cannot continue the program
at its current pace,'' said Marine Maj. Gen. Randall L. West, a
senior Pentagon adviser on chemical and biological defense, in a
telephone interview. ``I'm very disappointed we have to slow down
the program. There is still a threat and we are very, very
concerned about it. We need to vaccinate our whole force so that
all of our forces have protection all of the time.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision to limit the anthrax inoculation program coincides
with a firestorm of criticism from members of Congress who have
called for an indefinite suspension of the program, calling it
untested, ineffective and dangerous. On Wednesday, the Senate Armed
Services Committee, and on Thursday, a subcommittee of the House
Armed Services Committee will hold hearings on the vaccination
program.
</P>
<P>
   Between 200 and 300 military personnel have refused to be
vaccinated since the program began and several have been
prosecuted. In March, Air Force Maj. Sonnie Bates was discharged
from the military with a general, but not an honorable, discharge
after he questioned the safety of the anthrax vaccine and refused
an order to take it. Initially he faced a court-martial for
refusing an order.
</P>
<P>
   Some people who have received the vaccination have complained of
fever, muscle pain and dizziness. But the Pentagon and the Food and
Drug Administration insist that the vaccine is both safe and
effective.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to curtail the vaccination program is an
embarrassment both for the Pentagon and Cohen himself. In late
1997, he ordered all 2.4 million active and reserve military
personnel to take the anthrax vaccine by 2003, demonstrating his
personal belief in its safety and efficacy by rolling up his own
sleeve for a vaccination. He, like Gen. Hugh Shelton, the chairman
of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, and other senior Pentagon and
military officials, have received all six doses of the anthrax
vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, about 1.8 million doses of the vaccine have been
given to 445,000 American service personnel. Six vaccinations are
needed to offer full protection.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, the Pentagon administers about 75,000 doses of
the vaccine a month. The number of inoculations will probably come
down to fewer than 20,000 a month, West said.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon has only 165,000 doses of the vaccine left in which
it has ``complete confidence'' and that have passed the test in all
areas, West said. At the current rate of inoculation, the nation's
supply would have run out in about 40 days.
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturing of the vaccine was halted in December after the
Food and Drug Administration found 30 violations in safety,
consistency, record-keeping and sterility in an inspection of the
only plant in the country that makes it.
</P>
<P>
   The financially troubled plant, BioPort Corp. in Lansing, Mich.,
is now scheduled to restart production when the FDA gives final
approval, which is expected to come by the end of the year. Until
mid-1998, the plant was owned by the state of Michigan; it was then
bought by BioPort, a bio-pharmaceutical company. Adm. William J.
Crowe Jr., the former chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff and an
unpaid member of the board of directors of the corporation, has an
11 percent interest in the corporation.
</P>
<P>
   According to an internal Pentagon audit completed in March,
BioPort officials predict a possible $18 million cash shortfall in
2000. Initially, the plant sold the vaccine to the Pentagon for
$2.26 or $4.36 a dose, depending on its year of manufacture. The
price jumped to $10.64 a dose in August as part of a package that
increased the Pentagon's contract with BioPort by $24 million,
including an $18 million advance to help keep the company afloat.
</P>
<P>
   After production was halted, Cohen ordered the vaccinations to
continue, saying that it would be irresponsible to send soldiers
into combat unprotected. The anthrax bacteria generally afflicts
animals, especially sheep and cattle, but dry anthrax spores can be
weaponized. What makes anthrax so dangerous is that it is a
colorless, odorless, tasteless agent that can kill after only one
inhalation.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen has informed Shelton, the chairman of the joint chiefs, of
his decision to curtail the program. The final decision of how much
to cut it will be made in consultation with his top generals and
admirals in the field, a senior Pentagon official said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the ways the Pentagon plans to ration the vaccine is to
stop giving it to service personnel after they have left the Korean
and Persian Gulf areas even if they have not completed the full
series of vaccines, West said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the BioPort plant has other old lots of anthrax vaccine
besides the one that was most recently tested, it takes so long to
test them fully that the FDA has advised the Pentagon to focus its
efforts on helping to get the BioPort plant into production again,
not on testing and re-testing old stockpiles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-00 1936EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
