<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8274 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-WEIZMAN-NYT &LR;      07-10 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-WEIZMAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAINTED BY FINANCIAL MISDEALINGS, WEIZMAN QUITS AS ISRAELI
PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOEL GREENBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
  JERUSALEM _ President Ezer Weizman of Israel resigned Monday,
lowering the curtain on a public career that spanned more than half
a century of war and peacemaking but ended tainted by scandal.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Weizman's letter of resignation was delivered to the speaker of
Parliament, Avraham Burg, who will fill the largely ceremonial post
until Parliament chooses a new president on July 31.
</P>
<P>
   Shimon Peres, a former prime minister and a Nobel Peace Prize
laureate, is the candidate of the governing One Israel Party. His
opponent, representing the rightist Likud Party, is Moshe Katzav, a
former cabinet minister and a longtime legislator.
</P>
<P>
   Weizman, 75, whose second term as president was to have ended in
three years, stepped down early after a report by state prosecutors
that harshly criticized him for financial misdealings and a warning
from Burg that the legislature could move to dismiss Weizman.
</P>
<P>
   The report by the attorney general, issued in May, found that
Weizman had acted improperly when he accepted more than $300,000 in
unreported cash from two executives from 1985 to 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The report said insufficient evidence and the statute of
limitations prevented prosecution for suspected bribery, fraud and
breach of trust. But it asserted that Weizman, who was a minister
and a lawmaker when he received the money, had violated disclosure
rules for officials.
</P>
<P>
   Although he is leaving under a cloud, Weizman, crusty and
outspoken, enjoyed wide popularity in his seven years in office. He
often stepped beyond the bounds of his apolitical post to dispense
advice on peace efforts and to sound off on matters like
homosexuality and the role of women, setting off lively debates.
</P>
<P>
   A hawk-turned-dove who is a former air force chief and defense
minister, Weizman was an architect of the Camp David peace accords
with Egypt in 1978. He advocated talks with the Palestine
Liberation Organization years before the Oslo accords of 1993.
</P>
<P>
   A nephew of Chaim Weizmann, Israel's first president, and a
member of Israel's pioneer generation, Weizman served in the
British Air Force in World War II and helped organize the air wing
of the Haganah, the Jewish armed force during the British Mandate
in Palestine. He commanded the Israeli air force from 1958 to 1966,
building the squadrons that destroyed Egyptian air power on the
first day of the Arab-Israeli war in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving the army, he joined the rightist Herut Party, a
forerunner of Likud. As the Likud's campaign manager in 1977, he
directed Menachem Begin's upset victory, ending 29 years of Labor
Party government.
</P>
<P>
   The landmark visit to Israel of President Anwar el-Sadat of
Egypt in 1977 was the start of Weizman's conversion from hawk to
dove. As defense minister in Begin's cabinet, Weizman played a
pivotal role in the Camp David talks, establishing a quick rapport
with Sadat and prodding fellow Israeli ministers to show more
flexibility in the negotiations, which led to a formal peace treaty
in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Weizman left Begin's government in 1980, dissatisfied with what
he considered the slow pace of peace efforts, particularly talks on
planned Palestinian autonomy in the West Bank and Gaza Strip. In
1984, he ran in elections at the head of a small party that merged
with the Labor Party two years later.
</P>
<P>
   As a minister in a Labor-Likud government in 1989, Weizman
clashed with Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir over meetings that he
reportedly held abroad with the PLO, and he was stripped of his
membership in the decision-making ``inner cabinet.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Weizman announced his retirement from politics, saying
that he could ``no longer contribute'' to peace efforts and that
the Likud government was leading the country toward war. He was
chosen as president a year later.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, hours before he sent off his resignation letter, Weizman
dispensed one last piece of political advice, urging Prime Minister
Ehud Barak to forge ahead with the summit meeting this at Camp
David, Md., with the Palestinians, despite the collapse of Barak's
governing coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Weizman, a former fighter pilot, described peacemaking as a
battle. ``The prime minister,'' Weizman said, ``is acting like a
commander in the field who knows that he may not have enough
troops, but he has a goal to achieve, and he runs forward.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
