<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIBEROPTIC-MERGER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIBEROPTIC MERGER UNITES TWO LEADERS IN MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Leading fiber-optic device maker JDS Uniphase Corp. announced a
$41 billion takeover of Silicon Valley neighor SDL Inc., in a deal
that underscores the superheated market for the basic building
blocks of optical telecommunications networks.
</P>
<P>
   JDS Uniphase is already one of the largest customers for SDL's
so-called pump lasers, which generate light signals used to carry
voice and data calls over strands of glass fiber.
</P>
<P>
   With fiber-optic growth constrained by limited supplies of the
basic pieces of optical networks, the $41 billion acquisition will
help JDS intensify efforts to compete with significant players such
as Corning Inc., Lucent Technologies, and Nortel Networks. The deal
faces probable antitrust scrutiny by US Justice Department
regulators.
</P>
<P>
   Excitement over the prospects for using fiber-optic systems to
meet the Internet age's exploding demands for telecommunications
has boosted Chelmsford-based switch and network builder Sycamore
Networks to a $30 billion-plus market valuation. It also has
spurred the creation of over a dozen optical networking companies
in Massachusetts alone.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent months, ``The attention seems to be turning to
these components guys because there are so few of them,'' said Andy
McCormick, an industry analyst with Aberdeen Group in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Already, tiny companies such as NetOptix in Natick, Mass. and
Coretek in Wilmington, Mass. have fetched over $1 billion apiece in
acquisitions by Corning and Nortel.
</P>
<P>
   The New England optical cluster includes a handful of emerging
component makers, such as Axsun Technologies in Billerica,
Precision Optics in Gardner, and Lightchip Optical Networking in
Salem, N.H. But, McCormick said, ``I don't know of anyone around
here who does anything comparable to what SDL does.''
</P>
<P>
   Todd Dagres, general partner with Battery Ventures in Wellesley,
said the JDS-SDL deal, by underscoring the value of component
makers generally, could help boost those companies' profiles,
valuations, and ability to raise venture capital.
</P>
<P>
   But, Dagres said, ``I don't see any of the guys around here as
having significant intellectual property, and there's nobody around
here who has the product breadth that SDL does.'' SDL holds more
than 120 patents for optical devices.
</P>
<P>
   The deal also was read as validating the roughly $5 billion
Corning has poured into buying up Massachusetts-based optical
component companies in the last two years, including the former
Lasertron in Bedford and NetOptix in Natick.
</P>
<P>
   Corning has been seen as a possible bidder for SDL, and SDL
officials confirmed they were in talks with another company, which
they would not name, before they approached JDS about doing a deal.
Corning is both a customer of and competitor with JDS and SDL in
various markets.
</P>
<P>
   Corning's vice president for corporate communications, Dan
Collins, would not comment on whether Corning had been looking at
SDL. ``We think we are well placed in this marketplace regardless
of this deal,'' Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   The Corning Lasertron plant in Bedford, Mass., which makes pump
lasers that compete with SDL products, is undergoing a $45 million
expansion that is expected to add 300 jobs this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market is exploding, and we really do think that this deal
announced today really underscores the valuation of Lasertron. If
there were any questions about why we were doing''
multibillion-dollar expansions in Massachusetts, Collins said,
``the market has really validated it today.''
</P>
<P>
   The JDS bid for SDL represents a 50 percent premium over SDL's
closing value Friday. The deal calls for SDL owners to get 3.8
shares for each SDL share, valued at just over $440 Friday before
JDS stock slipped in trading Monday.
</P>
<P>
   John Butler, a Prudential Securities Inc. analyst, told
Bloomberg News that the deal reflects ``a need for suppliers in
this industry to scale up quickly in size to meet demand. The best
way to do that is by acquisition. Of the players that are left, the
combination of SDL with JDS Uniphase is the most natural.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Dagres: ``This is two of the bigger players getting
together and trying to establish themselves as a dominant leader in
the market before it matures.''
</P>
<P>
   Shares of JDS, a former maker of gas lasers that has bought over
15 companies in the last five years, have quintupled in value in
the last year, making it the fourth biggest stock in the Nasdaq 100
Index by market valuation. Both JDS and SDL are based in San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   Among other ramifications, the SDL acquisition was seen as
helping JDS become more competitive with Corning in the field of
optic amplifiers, which are placed about every 50 miles on
continental optical networks to boost signals. SDL also is seen as
a leader in developing a new device called Raman amplifiers that
can extend transmission distances on fiber networks.
</P>
<P>
   SDL, which recorded a $29.9 million profit last year, said it
expects sales this year to more than double from last year to just
under $450 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
