<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8278 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-SALVADOR-GARDEN-ART-2     07-10 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALVADOR-GARDEN-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SITE OF JESUIT SLAYINGS IN SAN SALVADOR INSPIRES HOPE IN PILGRAMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT9 is being sent to NYT photo clients. A map is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase
one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(Foreign Journal) 
 By DAVID GONZALEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador _ Like a testament to life's stubborn
triumph, a rose garden filled with thick, fragrant blossoms rises
at the site where soldiers killed six Jesuit priests at the Jose
Simeon Canas Central American University in 1989. Nearby, a votive
candle flickers in the room where the soldiers then killed a
housekeeper and her daughter, hoping to eliminate any witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   It did not work. One woman saw the crime and helped build a case
against the gunmen. More important, more than a decade since the
killings, tens of thousands of people from around the world have
sought out the Jesuit residence's tiny garden to bear their own
witness to the faith of eight people they consider martyrs who
defended the poor during this country's civil war.
</P>
<P>
   Invariably, these pilgrims also trek across town to the chapel
at the Divine Providence Hospital where Archbishop Oscar Arnulfo
Romero, a vocal opponent of the elite and the violent, was shot
dead while celebrating Mass.
</P>
<P>
   They walk through his modest three-room house, where his
bloodied vestments hang in the closet and his bedroom calendar is
forever turned to the month he was killed _ March 1980. Others go
to the countryside to visit the spot where four American
churchwomen were also killed by soldiers in December of that year.
</P>
<P>
   Centuries ago, Spanish conquistadors came here for glory, gold
and God. Now many visitors come to this nation whose name means the
Savior searching for a more elusive treasure along modern-day
Stations of the Cross. They come to conquer their own spiritual
doubts, looking for lessons from priests, nuns and laity whose
embrace of liberation theology's blend of religion and social
activism exacted such a brutal price.
</P>
<P>
   One recent afternoon, the shuffling steps of a dozen Americans
from the University of Scranton blended in with the everyday sounds
of barking dogs, tinny music and food sizzling in the kitchen of
the Jesuit residence.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly, the visitors encircled the garden, where the Rev.
Brendan Lally, the Roman Catholic priest leading the group, quietly
knelt in prayer. Afterward, he plucked a tiny sprig of clover and,
as though it were a relic, tucked it into his pocket.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a sacred place where people gave their lives for
Christ and the Gospel,'' Lally said, ``and their deaths make this a
holy place and an eternal symbol of the work for justice. This is a
faith journey. But it is also an attempt to help us as Catholics
understand more deeply our mission by coming to listen deeply to
the experiences of our brothers in El Salvador and the stories of
the people of El Salvador.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a heartening sight to the Rev. Dean Brackley, a American
theologian who came to El Salvador to replace his fallen Jesuit
brothers at the Central American University. He sees it as a
resurrection of sorts, one that is reflected in the experiences of
the dozens of delegations he ushers through here each year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This place, we export more hope than coffee,'' he said. ``With
all the violence, we still export hope. That is why people still
come.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet as strong as the attraction is for visiting delegations, the
religious movement that attracts them has lost ground here. The
popular church, formed of communities that grounded their political
and social activism for the poor in Scripture, was once virtually
the only nonviolent voice speaking out against the government
during the war. Now it competes to be heard.
</P>
<P>
   The killings of the Jesuits and the two women drew international
scorn for the government and helped to propel the peace effort that
ended the war. But the popularity and influence of the grass-roots
church has since waned.
</P>
<P>
   Former guerrilla leaders now speak freely and have entered
elective politics, evangelical Protestants have recruited thousands
of Salvadorans wary of an activist Catholic clergy and skeptical of
political engagement, and a conservative Catholic hierarchy looks
at adherents of liberation theology as sick brethren in need of
more orthodox spiritual healing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hierarchy represents a line of thinking that does not look
for repercussions or any social or political change,'' said the
Rev. Rafael de Sivatte, chairman of Central American University's
theology department. ``It represents a religion that only deals
with personal change and repentance of sins. It is an internal
religion that looks at the individual with a spirituality that is
very much in the air without reference to reality.''
</P>
<P>
   The church's challenge in peace, he said, is to find the unity
that was forged and tested to the breaking point during the civil
war from 1979 to 1992. Although the conflict has ended, he said,
many Salvadorans still lack jobs, housing and medical care.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to be even firmer than before,'' he said. ``People
have lost their aspirations and are happy with small economic
advances. We have to tell people not to be content with any little
thing. People say if they are working and have a little money, why
should they struggle for others to work? That was a great value we
had in the war. But it is being lost.''
</P>
<P>
   Enough of the popular movement remains in parishes like San
Bartolo in the town of Ilopango, where teachers from the Central
American University offer theology classes to the congregation. The
students, mostly working adults, take part in discussions of social
justice, grounded in the Bible.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to read the newspaper, too, if you read Scripture,''
said Felipe Miando, a truck driver who recently enrolled in the
class. ``We went through a war.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the Bible, the Israelites were subjected to the Roman
Empire,'' he said. ``We were subjected to the empire of the United
States and the rich of El Salvador.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The movement for a more socially relevant religion has also been
buoyed in recent months by the huge crowds that came to San
Salvador to mark the 20th anniversary of Archbishop Romero's
assassination, as well as to commemorate the killings at the
university. Their visits are familiar to Sister Rosa Avalos, who
tends to the chapel where Romero was killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes they come here right from the airport,'' she said.
``They want to know where a prophet, saint and martyr lived.
Sometimes they come to thank God after asking Bishop Romero's
intercession in everything from health, work or some difficulty
they have. Their only recourse is to ask God through him.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside the archbishop's former home, beside a mural of him
smiling by the shore of a lake, dozens of stones are embedded in a
wall, each one thanking the archbishop for answered prayers. But
there are more everyday miracles to be found among the pilgrims who
come here.
</P>
<P>
   For them, the survival of the popular church has been imbued
with a deep meaning that can be personal, political or both. They
go to parishes in poor communities where people share their many
stories and limited food with them. They stand in silence at the
relics of the Jesuit martyrs, including a book whose blood-stained
cover reads ``The Crucified God.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What I want to bring back to Pennsylvania with me is this
spirit of community,'' said Sean Farry, a college administrator who
was making his second trip to El Salvador. ``Here titles are
dropped and you get to know the Salvadoran people. What I find
about them is their spirituality. It strikes me as being part of
their everyday lives and how they rely on their faith. When there
is nothing else to depend on, they can't depend on the government
to help them. They have to turn to God.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Rowland stood inside the university's museum, which is
dedicated to the slain clergy and laity, shaking her head as she
looked at the threadbare clothes, now darkened with blood, that the
Jesuits were wearing when they were shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goodness,'' she whispered. ``They took the time to get
dressed. Good for them.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she had to come here. ``Hopefully, this will make me
more sensitive to other people,'' she said. ``I want to trust
people in a straightforward way. I know I fail miserably in that.''
</P>
<P>
   She looked at a case where tiny jars were filled with soil from
where the priests died.
</P>
<P>
   ``This should never happen again.'' She said. ``But it will.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
