<HEADLINE>
THERMO ELECTRON TO NAME DEKKERS NEW CEO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thermo Electron Corp. is expected to name Marijn Dekkers to help
reshape the company as its new chief operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   The 42-year-old native of the Netherlands, who previously worked
for Honeywell International Inc. and General Electric Co., will
become one of the youngest senior executives to join Thermo as the
company seeks to shed some businesses and sharpen its focus on
monitoring instruments.
</P>
<P>
   Dekkers holds a doctorate in chemical engineering and speaks
four languages (English, Dutch, German and French). He is the first
major outside executive hired by Richard F. Syron, Thermo
Electron's chairman, president and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Dekkers replaces Earl Lewis, who spent 16 years at Thermo
Electron where he was chief operating officer of the Waltham, Mass.
company's instruments division, its single largest unit.
</P>
<P>
   The company said Lewis is leaving Thermo to ``pursue other
interests,'' but declined to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Syron, the hand-picked successor to Thermo Electron's retired
founder George Hatsopoulos, said Dekkers was chosen for his strong
experience in improving the growth and productivity at both GE and
AlliedSignal, the predecessor to Honeywell.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have several major issues to focus on,'' Syron said. ``And
he (Dekkers) will help us improve our information systems, aid us
internationally where we have more than half our sales, and help us
unify the company that is still spinning off some of its
operations.''
</P>
<P>
   Syron noted that Dekkers holds 30 patents for his work at
General Electric, where he spent 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Since Jan. 31, when Thermo Electron announced plans to split
into three businessess and streamline the 23 units it controlled,
the company has completed most of its restructuring. It still plans
to sell its Thermo Fibertek composite-products unit and a new
medical products company to shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Thermo Electron's stock Monday closed at $24 a share, up 50
cents.
</P>
</TEXT>
