<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-ELECTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE MEXICO'S VOTE FOR FOX, PRI STILL CONTROLS CONGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
   By SAM DILLON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ President-elect Vicente Fox' center-right party
made strong advances in the Chamber of Deputies and Senate in the
balloting last week but failed to win a majority in either house
and will need to form legislative coalitions to pass laws,
according to official election results.
</P>
<P>
   The congressional delegation of the governing party, the
Institutional Revolutionary Party, was sharply reduced. But it will
start the legislative session that begins on Sept. 1 with the
largest voting bloc, the results show.
</P>
<P>
   Yet a series of squabbles in which party members have blamed one
another and President Ernesto Zedillo for their defeat raises
doubts about whether the party will vote as a disciplined unit, as
it has in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's National Action Party won 208 seats in the 500-member
Chamber of Deputies, the lower house. The governing party won 209,
and the main leftist grouping, the Party of the Democratic
Revolution, won 53. Five small parties won the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Fox will need to attract 43 votes to reach the majority of 251
needed to pass his budget and other initiatives in the chamber. The
Green Party, which Fox ran with in an election alliance and which
elected 15 members, will almost certainly vote with Fox, said
Jeffrey A. Weldon, a political scientist at the Autonomous
Technological Institute here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fox doesn't have a majority, but he's close enough to build
majorities issue by issue,'' Weldon said. ``He'll be able to
negotiate some kind of coalition for almost everything he wants to
get passed.''
</P>
<P>
   National Action added 86 seats to the delegation that it fielded
after the last federal balloting, in 1997, when the party elected
122 deputies, the results show. The gains by Fox's party and the
smaller parties came at the expense of the governing party, which
lost 30 seats in the voting on July 2, and at the expense of the
leftist party, which lost 72.
</P>
<P>
   In the 128-seat Senate, the governing party won 60 seats,
National Action won 46, Democratic Revolution won 15, the Greens
won five and two small parties won the remaining two, the results
show.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after the balloting, in which National Action got
38.1 percent and the governing party 36.7 percent of the votes for
Senate nationwide, it appeared that National Action would receive
more seats than the governing party.
</P>
<P>
   But under the formula that allocates Senate posts, the governing
party received 14 more seats than National Action, largely because
the the governing party received the most votes for Senate in two
more states than Fox's party and came in second in many more
states.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Electoral Institute released the final returns on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Fox has made conciliatory statements to both the governing party
and to the leftist party since his election. But leaders of both
parties have largely rebuffed his overtures.
</P>
<P>
   The results of the balloting for local posts in Mexico City
could give Fox some leverage, Weldon said.
</P>
<P>
   The leftist party's mayoral candidate, Andres Manuel Lopez, was
elected. But Fox's party won 34 seats in the 66-seat City Council,
so Lopez will need National Action's help in passing all his local
initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   Fox could offer National Action's cooperation in the council in
return for Lopez's help in securing the votes of about 10 leftist
deputies who represent Mexico City in the federal congress, Weldon
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
