A8285 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-BBO-ALL-STARADVANCE-C     07-10 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ALL-STAR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 ADVANCE - COX &HT;    Strange breeze blows over 71st All-Star game
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Cal Ripken won't be here. But Joe Girardi will.
</P>
<P>
   Mark McGwire won't be here. But Mike Sweeney will.
</P>
<P>
   Fred McGriff will be here, and Andres Galarraga will not only be
here but will be an All-Star starter for first time.
</P>
<P>
   A strange breeze blows over Turner Field tonight, where the 71st
All-Star game will be played out in a hundred subplots. The
American League has won the past three and nine of the last 12,
which might interest someone.
</P>
<P>
   But the real drama starts far earlier, when AL starter David
Wells (15-2), who was livid 17 months ago when the New York Yankees
traded him, gets the hook from Yankees manager Joe Torre, who had
to sign off on the trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what I'm capable of doing at any time,'' said Wells,
``and you know, right now if I wanted to, I could strangle Joe.''
</P>
<P>
   Ha-ha.
</P>
<P>
   ``I promised him he'd only pitch seven innings,'' Torre said.
``I've got to wear him out some way.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona left-hander Randy Johnson starts for the National,
though he will only throw one inning, after going seven innings
(122 pitches) while beating Oakland 4-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told our people he could go an inning, which I
appreciate,'' said Atlanta's Bobby Cox, managing his fifth All-Star
team. ``But certainly if Randy Johnson's got an inning in him, you
want him to be the first guy out the chute.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox was up until 1:15 a.m. Monday mending a roster that was
reduced all weekend by injury-related withdrawals of McGwire (knee
tendinitis), Barry Bonds (broken thumb), Mike Piazza (concussion),
Ken Griffey Jr. (knee) and Greg Maddux (bruised shoulder). Javy
Lopez might have earned an invitation, had he not roared off to
Puerto Rico Sunday night, opening the door for Chicago's Girardi.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a lineup really set, etched in stone here about 10 days
ago,'' Cox said. ``Our guys started dropping a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   One guy has stood up since February. Galarraga, after sitting
out the 1999 season to undergo cancer treatment, was named the
starting first baseman in McGwire's place. He has become MLB's
Official Feel-Good Story of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a wonderful human being,'' said Torre, who managed
Galarraga in St. Louis and is a cancer survivor himself. ``It's
scary. There's no question. When you hear the 'C' word and the one
thing you associate with it is death.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It surprised me in spring training, the way I feel, that I got
my timing back so fast,'' Galarraga said. ``To be honest, I think
Bobby Cox didn't have plans for me playing this year.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He thinks the angels are looking out for him,'' Cox said,
``and certainly, that has a lot to do with it.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since 1983, an All-Star game will go on
without Ripken, whose ailing lower back ended his string of 16
straight starts. Torre was already dealing with the withdrawl of
Alex Rodriguez (concussion) but A-Rod is 24. He'll be back. Ripken
is 39. Torre phoned him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He expressed his regrets at not being able to be here for the
first time in 100 years or so,'' Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   But what this attrition also means is 25 players 43 percent of
the combined rosters will be participating in their first All-Star
games. Three of them Kansas City's Jermaine Dye, Boston's Carl
Everett and Oakland's Jason Giambi will be starting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still the All-Star game,'' said Philadelphia catcher Mike
Lieberthal. ``All the deserving players are still here. Hey, there
are more All-Stars out there than there were All-Star slots.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
