<DOCNO> NYT20000710.0335 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8290 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-LINCOLN-CENTER-FESTIV     07-10 1230
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LINCOLN-CENTER-FESTIVAL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LINCOLN CENTER   REACHING OUT TO A WIDER AUDIENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: S.C.)  (ART ADV: Photo, NYT8, is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ROBIN POGREBIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There was a time when the idea of reggae music
pulsing through the hallowed concert halls of Lincoln Center might
have seemed like sacrilege. But as the Lincoln Center Festival
prepares to open its fifth season Tuesday night, such fare is now
almost taken for granted on Manhattan's main cultural campus.
</P>
<P>
   No longer is it surprising to see something like ``Pour
Antigone,'' a dance theater piece by the French choreographer
Mathilde Monnier that explores the dynamics between Greek tragedy
and modern Africa and opens on July 26, alongside the established
Bolshoi Ballet, which starts performances next Tuesday. Or Lev
Dodin's adaptation of Fyodor Abramov's novel ``Brothers and
Sisters'' staged by the Maly Drama Theater of St. Petersburg, a
six-hour epic in Russian with English supertitles and a cast of 40,
juxtaposed with ``Spinning Into Butter,'' a new play about racism
and political correctness by Rebecca Gilman with a cast of 7.
</P>
<P>
   The summer festival is part of a broader effort by Lincoln
Center over the last few years to expand its purview beyond the
classics and to reach out to new audiences year round. In addition
to the festival, Lincoln Center's newer offerings include Jazz at
Lincoln Center, which started as a program called classical jazz
and grew into a full-fledged constituent; New Visions, which
commissions productions as part of the Great Performers series; and
Midsummer Night Swing, dancing to live bands on the Lincoln Center
plaza.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really was the opportunity to do two things: present art
forms that have not been represented and bring in new audiences,
more diverse, less affluent,'' said Nathan Leventhal, president of
Lincoln Center, who will step down in December after nearly 17
years.
</P>
<P>
   Presenting the kind of unconventional programs that might more
typically be found at the Brooklyn Academy of Music requires a
delicate balancing act for Lincoln Center. Loyal audiences and
longtime contributors need to be assured that the institution is
not abandoning its base. Programming executives must contend with
Lincoln Center's 12 constituents, some of whom, like the
Metropolitan Opera and the Philharmonic, have complained in the
past that some events in the summer festival, which is produced by
Lincoln Center itself, encroached on their turf.
</P>
<P>
   ``The constituents have primacy,'' said Beverly Sills,
chairwoman of Lincoln Center. ``We cannot step on their toes, nor
do we want to.''
</P>
<P>
   The festival, which does not release any figures on earnings or
attendance, must also be careful to balance riskier presentations
with more mainstream events, like the Bolshoi and Alvin Ailey
American Dance Theater, that can be counted on to sell out or come
close.
</P>
<P>
   Nigel Redden, the director of the festival, said he was careful
to try to push the boundaries without going overboard. ``There are
some things I wouldn't put in the State Theater,'' he said. ``I
make some attempt to match the spaces with what I believe the
audience potential will be.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year the festival exceeded box office projections for the
first time, in large part because of the publicity generated by
``The Peony Pavilion,'' the Chinese opera that came to the festival
after being scheduled and then canceled by the Chinese authorities
a year before. Box office receipts account for a little more than a
third of the festival's $9 million budget, with the bulk of the
rest coming from donations.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the risks and growing pains attached to programming like
the festival, Sills said Lincoln Center had no choice but to forge
ahead. ``The last decade showed us there was a whole new world
coming in, and we have to be a part of that,'' she said. ``Lincoln
Center cannot turn into 12 museums.''
</P>
<P>
   Some constituents pride themselves on presenting the classics,
while others seek out adventurous programs.
</P>
<P>
   The median age of Lincoln Center's audiences is 50 for song
recitals and 55 for other programs, while the median age at the
Brooklyn Academy is 42 for its Next Wave Festival and 46 for other
events.
</P>
<P>
   So far Lincoln Center's new programming terrain seems to be
bearing fruit. Surveys last summer showed that nearly 20 percent of
the festival audience, almost one-third of whom were under 35, had
never been to Lincoln Center before, and that an additional 25
percent had never been to the festival.
</P>
<P>
   The institution has changed in the eyes of its peers. ``They
have made courageous artistic choices,'' said Joseph V. Melillo,
the executive producer of the Brooklyn Academy.
</P>
<P>
   Encouraging this new thinking has in part been the work of Jane
Moss, the vice president for programming since 1992. ``I had no
interest in coming in and preserving the status quo,'' Moss said.
</P>
<P>
   In particular she has tackled the area of classical music,
trying to broaden the scope of what Lincoln Center includes and to
make the presentations more accessible, using video, for example. A
series on Sibelius included a documentary film. Lincoln Center
recently presented a series featuring archival film of great
pianists from the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   ``The classical music event itself is somewhat anachronistic in
this day and age,'' Moss said. ``In a world that is increasingly
visual, it is a nonvisual activity.''
</P>
<P>
   Moss said she had also devoted considerable energy to building
up Lincoln Center's educational programs, like pre-concert lectures
and post-performance discussions, working to generate publicity
around events to get the word out to nontraditional audiences and
commissioning new work to attract artists who have not been staples
of Lincoln Center.
</P>
<P>
   Through the New Visions series, which started in 1998, the stage
director Peter Sellars created theatrical versions of Bach cantatas
performed by the mezzo-soprano Lorraine Hunt and the Orchestra of
the Age of Enlightenment from London. The choreographer Bill T.
Jones, in collaboration with the soprano Jessye Norman, offered an
original work, ``How! Do! We! Do!''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about replacing, but about adding and expanding,''
Moss said. ``It's exciting to see people discovering this music for
the first time.''
</P>
<P>
   Planning the festival, which runs through July 30, is the job of
Redden, who has been its director since 1998. ``I wanted the
festival to be an ambitious event that would stretch the limits,''
said Redden, who also directs the Spoleto Festival USA in
Charleston, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   A man who relishes the details, Redden was excited about the
7,000 gallons of water that will flood the stage of the New York
State Theater when the United States premiere of the Netherlands
Opera's ``Writing to Vermeer'' opens the festival Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to bringing work of an international scope to New
York, Redden said he was trying to feature culture that was already
in the city but on a bigger platform; thus this season's series on
Caribbean music, including reggae, voodoo, calypso and Creole.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is where Lincoln Center has put itself most on the
line,'' he said. ``It's not high-comfort programming all of the
time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
