<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOYSMART-PRIVACY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRADE COMMISSION SUING TOYSMART FOR TRYING TO SELL WEB CUSTOMER
DATABASE 
</HEADLINE>
   By MATT RICHTEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The federal government on Monday sued to prevent Toysmart.com, a
bankrupt Internet toy retailer, from selling its database of
customer information, asserting the company had assured hundreds of
thousands of online visitors their personal data would never be
shared with a third party.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the Federal Trade Commission said Toysmart.com, in
trying to sell the database among the defunct company's assets, has
compromised not just names, addresses and shopping preferences of
online toy shoppers, but potentially also family profile
information, including names and ages of children. Toysmart, which
is majority-owned by the Walt Disney Co., ceased operations in May
and began soliciting bids for its assets.
</P>
<P>
   The suit has added fuel to an already fiery debate over online
privacy, and about whether Internet retailers should be subject to
government regulation limiting how they handle and protect customer
information. Internet retailers assert they can regulate themselves
by disclosing on their sites whether and how they might use
customer data accrued when visitors join sites or make purchases.
</P>
<P>
   But in the last week, before the FTC acted, privacy advocates
said the Toysmart case represented a nightmare scenario. The
privacy advocates and FTC officials say that online companies that
amass large and potentially valuable customer databases might have
little incentive to adhere to privacy assurances once they go out
of business, in case they are bought or merge with other
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a shakeout of dot-com companies occur, they can't sell out
customer lists they promised to protect like they do other assets,
like paper clips or computer equipment,'' said David Medine,
associate director of Financial Practices for the FTC, the division
that filed the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from Boston-based Toysmart, could not be reached for
comment. The company's bankruptcy lawyer, Harry Murphy, said the
two sides are in settlement discussions and he said he is ``very
hopeful'' a settlement will be reached. Officials from Disney,
which owned a majority of Toysmart and hold three of five board
seats, released a statement, saying they ``favor an outcome that
honors the commitments contained in the Toysmart privacy policy,''
but they declined to be specific about whether that might preclude
the sale of the information.
</P>
<P>
   Medine also said he is optimistic the two sides can reach an
agreement. Parties close to the negotiations said that a settlement
might permit Toysmart to sell the customer database, but only in
the event that the buyer essentially took over the Toysmart
business as a whole and continued to use it as part of a similar
online toy retailer.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there are appropriate protections, there could be room for
transferring the list as part of the overall company,'' Medine
said.
</P>
<P>
   That might not be the case under a law proposed on Monday. Rep.
Spencer Bachus, R-Ala., introduced legislation on Monday that would
make it an unfair business practice subject to civil penalties, if
an online business promises it will not divulge customer
information, then seeks to sell it, including in the case of merger
or bankruptcy, Bachus said.
</P>
<P>
   Toysmart announced on May 22 that it was closing and selling its
assets. The decision came despite the fact that the company was
ranked among the 24th most visited sites in December, with 1.4
million visitors according to Web site traffic monitor Media
Metrix, FTC officials said.
</P>
<P>
   On June 8, the company advertised in The Wall Street Journal
offering for sale both tangible and intangible assets, including
``databases and customer lists.'' A day later, the company filed
for bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   On June 29, the advertisement came to the attention of Truste, a
nonprofit agency that certifies the privacy policy of online
retailers. Toysmart was among roughly 2,000 sites, including major
online search engines, that have received Truste's seal of
approval.
</P>
<P>
   David Steer, spokesman for Truste, said Toysmart's move to sell
information was in violation of the company's Web customer privacy
policy, which states that ``Personal information, voluntarily
submitted by visitors to our site, such as name, address, billing
information and shopping preferences, is never shared with a third
party.'' The notice continues, ``you can rest assured that your
information will never be shared with a third party.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're hiding under a veil of bankruptcy to hoodwink their
customers,'' Steer said.
</P>
<P>
   Steer said he asked the FTC to look into the company, along with
other Internet companies that he had heard also may be planning to
sell customer databases.
</P>
<P>
   Steer and other privacy advocates said the recent failures of
Internet companies puts newfound urgency into the debate over how
companies handle customer information. ``Given the current state of
the e-commerce industry, we are likely to see this happen again and
again as companies try to sell assets to stay afloat,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
