<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSECO-WENDT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW CONSECO CHIEF RECEIVED $45 MILLION IN CASH UP FRONT 
</HEADLINE>
   By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gary C. Wendt took the cash up front when he agreed to become
chairman and chief executive of Conseco Inc., the company disclosed
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Conseco, the troubled insurance and financial services company,
said that it paid Wendt a signing bonus of $45 million when he
joined the company last month. He was also given 3.2 million shares
of stock, now worth $31.2 million, as well as options to buy 10
million more shares.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, he is getting a significant sum of money up front,''
said Kathy Shanley, a fixed-income analyst with Gimme Credit, an
institutional research firm. ``He's not taking any risk by taking
this assignment.''
</P>
<P>
   Wendt, the former chief executive of GE Capital Corp., will not
get a salary for the first two years he runs Conseco, but he will
get a bonus of no less than $8 million, and as much as $50 million,
at the end of the two-year period, depending on how high the stock
price is.
</P>
<P>
   Wendt, 58, gained a wide following at GE, but he faces very
different challenges at Conseco, whose bonds are rated as
speculative, or below investment grade, and whose insurance
operations have a relatively low rating as well. At GE, he
benefited from that company's top-notch credit rating, which meant
it could usually raise capital at a lower cost than competitors had
to pay.
</P>
<P>
   Conseco pays substantially higher costs, which is one reason the
company has said it needs to sell its Conseco Finance subsidiary.
Buyers have not been willing to pay Conseco's asking price,
however, leading to speculation that Wendt may decide to keep the
operation.
</P>
<P>
   Conseco was once a highflying stock, but since the spring of
1998 it has fallen from a high of $58.125 to a low of $4.50 in May.
The stock price was at $5.875 on June 20, 10 days before Wendt's
hiring was announced, and that will be the exercise price for the
options he is being issued. Monday, in trading before the pay
package was announced, Conseco shares were unchanged at $9.75.
</P>
<P>
   Wendt will get the maximum bonus of $50 million in two years
even if he does not come close to restoring Conseco's stock price
to its former glory. The top amount will be paid if the stock price
averages $20 a share _ less than 35 percent of the stock's previous
high _ over a period prior to the end of the two years. The minimum
bonus of $8 million will be paid if the share price is under $10,
with payments between those figures if the stock price is higher
than $10 but less than $20.
</P>
<P>
   Wendt was hired after the company's board ousted Steven Hilbert,
the founder of the company, who received $53 million when he
departed in April. Hilbert remains deeply in debt on
company-guaranteed loans that he took out to buy shares at prices
far above the current level.
</P>
<P>
   Wendt's employment contract covers five years, with the final
three years calling for an annual salary of $1 million, a bonus of
up to $2.8 million, a grant of shares worth $1.5 million at the
time and annual grants of options to buy 500,000 shares of stock.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the employment agreement provides for some smaller
benefits for Wendt. The company, based in Carmel, Ind., will pay
all travel costs for the executive and his family for up to a year,
until they move to Indiana. It will also reimburse him for up to
$10,000 a year to cover any medical expenses not covered by the
company's health plan, pay him an automobile allowance of $600 a
month plus the cost of gasoline, and pay up to $125,000 a year for
the cost of Wendt's life insurance.
</P>
<P>
   General Electric agreed to release Wendt from a non-compete
agreement in return for a warrant allowing it to buy 10.5 million
shares of Conseco at a price of $5.75 a share at any time through
June 28, 2005.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
