   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   COX-CHINA-DIVORCE _ GUANDONG PROVINCE, China _ The southern
province of Guangdong, one of China's most prosperous, has seen a
resurgence of a feudal practice the Communists eliminated 50 years
ago _ concubines. Affairs and divorces have been on the upswing for
years in China, but men in Guangdong have taken marital infidelity
to a new level. They are known to take even two or three
mistresses, set them up in a house and even have children with
them. In the past, wives who wanted a divorce had no viable
recourse because China's marriage laws gave them no financial
rights. Now, a new legal directive in Guangdong which makes it
easier for wives to get a share of what their husband bought for
the other woman has lawyers and scholars debating how far the law
should go into peoples' bedrooms. (Chao, Cox News Service). WITH
PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   (Eds. This is the CoxNet Focus page for the week. The layout is
now available)
</P>
<P>
   COXNET FOCUS 0716: CLASSIC CARS, ANCIENT CITY -- The names come
out a little differently in Arabic. DeSoto becomes something like
``Tozata'' and Chrysler sounds like ``Kleezler.'' But those old
bombs you might find in an auto collector's garage in America make
for colorful and practical transportation in Syria. The country's
streets are flush with fins and crawling with chrome. Stroll the
centuries-old bazaars and you're likely to be passed not only your
father's Oldsmobile, but his father's before him. (Kaplow, Cox
Washington Bureau). Art includes a 3-column color photo of a
classic car sitting in a garage, a 2-column detail shot of a car, a
3-column photo of a Syrian in front of his car and a 2-column color
photo of a Syrian working on his car.
</P>
