</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-EDIT _ If you have a camcorder, chances are you've got
dozens of old tapes gathering dust. Most of the stuff on the tapes
is worthless, but you don't throw the tapes away because of the one
or two treasured scenes mixed in with the dreck. A digital video
editing machine can help you cull the scenes you want from those
you don't want. And once you've retrieved all the good parts, you
can create highlight videos you'll be proud to show. James
Cummings' gadgets column. (Cummings, Dayton Daily News) WITH PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   INFECTION _ The largest international conference on threats from
infectious disease, sponsored every two years by the CDC, opens
this evening in Atlanta. Major topics to be discussed include: the
growing problem of antibiotic resistance, the danger of unpredicted
problems such as West Nile virus, the likelihood of disease
organisms being used as weapons, and the influence of climate
change and major population movements on the development of
diseases. (McKenna, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   PANO-BOYS _ Niko and Pano Karatassos are the future of the
Buckhead Life Restaurant Group. These two young men _ a manager and
a chef _ will one day be the heart, the brains and the soul of this
business that their father, Pano Karatassos, grew in 20 years from
a single white-tablecloth restaurant, Pano's and Paul's. Now with
its diverse roster of 10 brand-name eateries _ including Buckhead
Diner, Atlanta Fish Market and Chops _ Buckhead Life is one of the
top fine-dining restaurant groups in the country. It realized more
than $68 million in sales in 1999 and ranked among the top 100
privately owned companies in Georgia. Yet even as the company
stakes its future on reproducing successful brands, its two sons
may try and push it to the next level. Before they consider taking
over their dad's company, Niko and Pano Karatassos want to open a
place together. And it won't be like anything Buckhead Life has
seen before. (Kessler, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL
</P>
<P>
   COXNET TRAVEL _ (EDS: This is the CoxNet Travel page for the
current week. This layout is now available.)
</P>
<P>
   YO-BROOKLYN _ BROOKLYN, N.Y. _ It wasn't until I plopped down in
a booth at Junior's _ the sprawling, orange-vinyl delicatessen run
by the Rosen family for more than 50 years at the corner of
Flatbush and DeKalb avenues _ that I began to realize what a
melting pot New York's most populous borough is. In Brooklyn,
habitat of Hassids and homeboys, matzah ball soup is served side by
side with collard greens and salmon croquettes. Over a recent long
weekend, I didn't have nearly enough time to eat my way around this
ethnic-food lover's paradise. But I did hopscotch around
sufficiently to see why it's New York's new ground zero of cool,
why trendies from ``The City'' are subwaying over to check out the
clubs and restaurants, the museums and green spaces, the Gothic
architecture and Gotham views. From the BAM Opera House to swanky
Brooklyn Heights to the bombed-out environs of Williamsburg,
Brooklyn is a world unto itself.
</P>
<P>
   Intro teases inside to tour of Brooklyn. (Brock, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   VANGOGH-BOSTON _ BOSTON _ Taking a look at ``Van Gogh: Face to
Face,'' on view at the Museum of Fine Arts here through Sept. 24.
This is the only East Coast stop for this touring exhibit, the
first to focus solely on Van Gogh's portraiture. There are more
than 70 works on view, including several haunting self-portraits.
For those getting excited about the High Museum's mini Van Gogh
exhibit coming September, this show tempts a summer visit to
Beantown. (Longino, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   FASHION
</P>
<P>
   FASHION-CHEAPTHRILLS _ What fashionable finds are there to buy
on a budget of $100? Three stylemaking ladies let us know as they
shop kmart, target and walmart and bring back the goods. (Hill,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTOS.
