<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8298 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-OPERA-WEISGALL-PIRAND     07-10 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPERA-WEISGALL-PIRANDELLO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIX CHARACTERS AND A COMPOSER FOUND IN NEW JERSEY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.J.)   By ANTHONY TOMMASINI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRINCETON, N.J. _ Long before the American composer Hugo
Weisgall died at 84 in 1997, he was regarded by many musicians and
critics as a major figure in 20th-century opera. General audiences
have been slower to catch on. Although Weisgall's operas are the
products of a skilled dramatist, his musical language, steeped in
fitful Expressionism and spiked with elements of 12-tone writing,
is craggy and challenging.
</P>
<P>
   The composer and his supporters were heartened when his 10th
opera, ``Esther,'' was ecstatically received at its premiere in
1993 as part of the 50th-anniversary celebrations of the New York
City Opera. Now the Opera Festival of New Jersey has revived
Weisgall's ``Six Characters in Search of an Author,'' based on the
play by Pirandello. The enthusiastic response to the opening
performance at the McCarter Theater at Princeton University should
encourage Weisgall's champions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Six Characters,'' commissioned by the Alice Ditson Fund at
Columbia University in the mid-1950s, was given its premiere at the
New York City Opera in 1958 and repeated successfully the following
season. Then, inexplicably, it languished unproduced until 1990,
when the resident training company of the Lyric Opera of Chicago
presented an acclaimed performance, later released on Pirandello's
remarkable 1921 play shatters the boundaries between illusion and
reality by boldly manipulating the play-within-a-play convention. A
company of actors is rehearsing ``Mixing It Up,'' a new play that
none of them like, by this pretentious modern playwright named
Pirandello. As they work, six strangers walk onstage from out of
nowhere: a father, a mother in mourning dress, a surly adult son, a
volatile stepdaughter and two silent, sullen young children. They
are, they say, characters from a play left unfinished by its author
and are searching for someone to complete their story. In creating
an operatic version of Pirandello's play, Weisgall and his
librettist, Denis Johnston, an Irish playwright, turned the actors
into singers who were rehearsing an overly complex new opera, ``The
Temptation of St. Anthony,'' by Hugo Weisgall. The six strangers
are characters from an incomplete opera. While generally adhering
to the events of the original, the librettist wisely cut, altered
and rewrote the material to produce an effective libretto.
</P>
<P>
   Weisgall's score is brilliant and haunting. Born in Bohemia, the
son of a cantor, he immigrated as a child to the United States,
where he received his musical education. Yet his works are imbued
with Central European Expressionism. Weisgall ably fashioned the
pungent atonal and thickly chromatic elements of his harmonic
language into music of gritty power and affecting lyricism. Though
not conventionally tuneful, the score is richly melodic.
</P>
<P>
   For example, in Act I the stepdaughter, to audition for the
director, sings a melancholy soliloquy about her life. It's a
mystery why this ravishing solo has not achieved independent life
as a recital work. The soprano Michaela Gurevich sang it here with
dusky sound and sensitivity, though her diction was not always
clear. If you can't understand the words in a Weisgall opera, it's
not the composer's fault, for his skills at prosody were
first-rate.
</P>
<P>
   In general, the production was admirable. The bare look of the
rehearsal stage, by the set designer Ron Kadri, and the 1950s-style
costumes, by Patricia Hibbert, created the right effect.
</P>
<P>
   Only one aspect of the director Albert Takazauckas' work seemed
miscalculated. Though there is bleak humor in Pirandello's ``Six
Characters,'' which the author subtitled ``A Comedy in the
Making,'' the opera does not quite capture it. The opera singers
are comic stereotypes, like the Coloratura (here sung by Alicia
Berneche), a diva with a thick German accent and a little dog named
Toto that she carries in a straw handbag.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, Takazauckas exaggerated the caricatures, turning
the Tenore Buffo (Douglas Perry) and the Basso Cantante (Scott
Altman) into stock figures.
</P>
<P>
   But his handling of the six rootless characters was very
compelling. They were grim, unnerving figures, ageless and bound
forever to their creator's conception.
</P>
<P>
   On opening night the musical performance, conducted by Barbara
Day Turner, was not completely solid. But this was essentially a
strong and sensitive account of the score.
</P>
<P>
   Several singers were standouts. The Accompanist, Kent Smith,
sang with crisp diction and bright sound, and played the difficult
onstage piano part himself. Robert Orth as the Father, Dominic
Inferrera as the Son, and Ryan Allen as the crusty Stage Manager
were all memorable. And it was good to see the veteran
mezzo-soprano Rosalind Elias, 71, make the tormented Mother a
riveting figure.
</P>
<P>
   There will be two more performances, on Sunday and on July 22.
With luck, this revival will prod other companies into presenting
this important work. How about the New York City Opera, where it
received its premiere?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
