<HEADER>
A8316 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROV     07-10 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-art-ADV30-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR RELEASE: SUN., JULY 30, 2000. 
 HOME IMPROVEMENT QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
  By BERNARD GLADSTONE 
 Includes illustration. 
 c.2000 Bernard Gladstone 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: To publish Bernard Gladstone's ``Home Improvement
Questions and Answers'' it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndication Sales. For purchase
information call toll-free 1-888-269-8796.) 
 (The NYTSS sales representative also has information on how to
subscribe to Gladstone's ``Home Improvement Questions and Answers''
weekly column which moves on Wednesdays.) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: I want to build some large plywood ``blocks'' or boxes that
my young son can play with, similar to the kind I've seen him
playing with at nursery school.
 &HT;    These ``blocks'' are hollow cubes about 12 to 15 inches on each
side and light enough to be moved and even stacked up like large
`building blocks,' much like children's small building blocks. When
turned over they can also be used to store small toys or stuffed
animals.
 &HT;    They are apparently made of wood and painted in bright colors,
so I thought of making them of plywood. But in order to make them
sturdy enough for my son to sit or even stand on, I would have to
use plywood at least 1/2 to 3/4 inch thick _ which would make them
too heavy for a youngster to handle.
 &HT;    Any ideas you can offer?
 &HT;    A: Build a framework of lightweight bass wood or balsa wood
first, then cover the outside with thin sheets of 1/4 inch or 1/8
inch plywood. This should be strong enough for your purposes, yet
light enough for a youngster to lift or move around.
 &HT;    Make sure all edges and corners are sanded smooth and rounded
off, and it's also a good idea to cover all these corners with a
self-adhesive tape of some kind.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: After changing a number of hot-water-faucet washers in our
house we notice that when we turn on these faucets to a full flow
the stream gradually lessens to a small trickle.
 &HT;    What can cause this?
 &HT;    A: Some types of faucet washers are made for use only on cold
water faucets and some for hot. If you install the wrong type on
the hot water faucets _ as you apparently did _ the heat from the
water can cause the washer to swell, thus restricting the flow of
water.
 &HT;    Your solution lies in replacing those washers with the proper
type _ the kind made for use on a hot-water faucet.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: My house has wood framed windows that were varnished when the
house was built.
 &HT;    Now there are dark stains on the finish in some places,
apparently due to moisture dripping off the glass during cold
weather.
 &HT;    I am worried about this affecting the wood, so is there anything
I should do to protect it?
 &HT;    A: Water stains such as you describe may be only in the varnish,
not in the wood itself, but it depends on how old the stains are as
well as on the type of wood.
 &HT;    It's possible you can get rid of the stains by removing the old
finish, then revarnishing with two or three coats of a good
waterproof varnish.
 &HT;    However, to prevent this happening again you should do something
about the condensation problem _ perhaps by installing storm sash
on the outside of each window, or possibly by lowering the humidity
inside the house during cold weather.
 &HT;    Also, make sure the bathrooms and kitchen have exhaust fans that
are turned on when those rooms are in use.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: Our Formica kitchen counters are almost 20 years old and are
now quite dull looking. Can I apply several coats of a clear
polyurethane over this plastic laminate to restore the luster, or
is there any other method you can suggest?
 &HT;    A: Coating with a clear polyurethane is possible, but I would
not recommend it. It will change the color by giving it a more
amber cast, and the plastic will have to be sanded down and cleaned
thoroughly first. In addition, it will have to be re-coated
regularly.
 &HT;    You may be better off trying one of the special polishes that
are sold for this purpose in many hardware stores and home centers.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Questions about home-repair problems should be addressed to
Bernard Gladstone, care of The New York Times Syndication Sales
Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168. Questions of general
interest will be answered in this column; Mr. Gladstone regrets
that unpublished letters cannot be answered individually.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    NOTE: Drawing captioned ``MAKING CHILDREN'S PLAY BOXES'' goes
with this column.
 &HT;    CAPTION: Light weight plywood boxes can be assembled by building
a frame first, then covering this with 1/8 inch or 1/4 inch
plywood.
 &HT;     
 -0- 
 c.2000 Bernard Gladstone 
