<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8319 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-BUSH-ART-NYT &LR;      07-10 1179
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP HAS NOT `ALWAYS CARRIED THE MANTLE OF LINCOLN,' BUSH TELLS
NAACP 
</HEADLINE>
  (With BUSH-EXCERPT) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT4 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Gov. George W. Bush told the nation's largest civil
rights organization Monday that ``the party of Lincoln has not
always carried the mantle of Lincoln'' and he pledged that ``strong
civil rights enforcement will be a cornerstone of my
administration.''
</P>
<P>
   In his latest bid to show that he is a different kind of
Republican, the Texas governor quoted Abraham Lincoln's warning to
a divided nation that ``we cannot escape our history.'' He added,
``One hundred and forty years later, that is still true. For our
nation there is no denying the truth that slavery is a blight on
our history. And that racism, despite all the progress, still
exists today.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, to a large extent, simply retailored his standard stump
speech for the thousands of delegates to the annual convention of
the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People, and
he won a polite reception. He did not cover an array of topics of
interest to the delegates, including the death penalty, Supreme
Court nominees and affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   But his appearance provided a contrast with four years ago when
Bob Dole, the Republican nominee, refused an invitation to speak to
the group and accused its president, Kweisi Mfume, of ``trying to
set me up.'' Dole said he would look for audiences that ``I can
relate to.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as Bush was about to be introduced Monday, four
demonstrators rose in the vast Baltimore Convention Center and
began protesting the execution in Texas last month of Gary Graham.
``Remember Grady Graham,'' they shouted. ``An innocent man was
murdered by Governor Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank Humphrey, the presiding officer, ordered the protesters
removed as hymns were played. ``This is our house and we are in
charge here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Graham, the 135th inmate to be executed in Texas since Bush
became governor, went to death proclaiming his innocence. The NAACP
has called his execution a ``gross travesty of justice'' and wants
a national moratorium on all executions.
</P>
<P>
   When he began speaking, Bush quickly drew laughter by
remembering how Jackie Robinson, upset by something John F. Kennedy
once did, called the president a fine man but said he reserved the
right to change his opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``For those of you who support me,'' Bush said, ``I see a couple
here, maybe more than a couple: I hope you won't change your
opinion. And for those of you who don't, I hope that at least you
take Jackie's opinion as your own and give me chance to tell you
what is in my heart.''
</P>
<P>
   He made implicit reference to Dole and drew another round of
applause when he said, ``I recognize the history of the Republican
Party and the NAACP has not been one of regular partnership. But
our nation is harmed when we let our differences separate us and
divide us. So while some in my party have avoided the NAACP and
while some in the NAACP have avoided my party, I'm proud to be
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Black Americans represent one of the Democratic Party's
strongest constituencies and those Republicans who have appeared
before the NAACP have not had an easy time. Bush's father, who was
then the vice president, faced a chorus of boos and hisses in 1983
when he tried to portray the Reagan administration as sensitive to
blacks.
</P>
<P>
   A year later both Bush's father and Ronald Reagan cited
scheduling conflicts in declining invitations to the convention and
sent Elizabeth Dole, then the secretary of transportation. She was
received politely but not enthusiastically. But Bush's father did
speak to the group as a presidential candidate in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's reception was polite, but he did not appear to
have changed many minds. After his speech many listeners complained
about his lack of specificity and said his appearance was about
symbolism more than substance. ``He's speaking to a moderate
element of the Republican Party more than he's talking to us,''
said Thomas L. Jackson, a retired police officer from Ohio. ``What
is compassionate conservatism? What is it? The things he outlined
are pretty vague.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Bledsoe, the president of the Texas branch of the civil
rights organization, said of Bush, ``He reduced some barriers
today, but I don't think he won any support.'' He praised the
governor's tone and self-deprecation but said ``people were crying
out for specifics and substance.''
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Holmes Norton, the nonvoting House member from the
District of Columbia and a Democrat, said: ``It is too late in
American history for us to give any candidate points for showing
up. You have to show up with something.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush spoke of expanding opportunity in American and said ``this
begins by enforcing the civil rights laws.''
</P>
<P>
   He said, ``Discrimination is still a reality even when it takes
different forms. Instead of Jim Crow, there's racial redlining and
profiling. Instead of `separate but equal,' there's separate and
forgotten. Strong civil rights enforcement will be cornerstone of
my administration.'' He did not explain this idea any further.
</P>
<P>
   Bush put his usual emphasis on education and on ending what he
calls ``the soft bigotry of low expectations'' for minority
children. He promoted his plan to give parents in low income areas
vouchers that they could use for private schools if their children
attend poor schools that fail to improve.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor said he wanted his party and the NAACP to
find some common ground. ``This will not be easy work,'' he said.
``But a philosopher once advised when given a choice, prefer the
hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has campaigned often in black and Hispanic neighborhoods,
to underscore his theme that he is a ``compassionate
conservative.'' And his campaign media strategist was on hand
Monday to film the governor's speech to the civil rights group for
possible use in future commercials.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush still has significant differences with the NAACP, and
not just over the death penalty. The group has been leading a
boycott of South Carolina over the confederate flag. During the
Republican primary in South Carolina, Bush declined to take a stand
on whether the Confederate flag should fly over the state Capitol.
He also campaigned at Bob Jones University, which had a ban on
interracial dating.
</P>
<P>
   As a tax-exempt group, the NAACP cannot endorse a presidential
candidate. But Sunday evening, the group's leaders urged members to
mount an ambitious voter registration drive. Julian Bond, the
group's chairman, argued that one more conservative vote on the
Supreme Court could bring a setback for civil rights causes.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Ralph Nader, the Green Party's presidential nominee,
are also scheduled to speak at the NAACP convention.
</P>
<P>
   After his speech Bush went to a $2 million fund-raiser at the
Virginia home of Fred Malek, a longtime Republican backer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-00 2011EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
