<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8320 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CANADA-POLITICS-NYT &LR;      07-10 1086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW CONSERVATIVE LEADER A REMINDER OF TRUDEAU'S ASCENT 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALGARY, Alberta _ Stockwell Day, the new leader of Canada's
opposition going into elections expected next spring, offers a
conservative face rarely associated with Canadian politicians:
support for a flat income tax, tougher sentencing for criminals and
beefed up military spending.
</P>
<P>
   But his sudden sweep to national prominence, culminating with
his decisive election Saturday night as leader of the new Canadian
Alliance Party, seems vaguely familiar, leading some commentators
to call him the ``Pierre Trudeau of the Right.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Trudeau, a Liberal prime minister who came to power on the
wings of ``Trudeaumania'' at age 48, Day, 49, comes along at a time
when more and more Canadians say they are weary of an aging prime
minister, in this case Jean Chretien, 66, who first was elected to
Parliament when John F. Kennedy was in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Posing in a sweat-soaked muscle shirt, playing drums with a jazz
quartet in Montreal or maneuvering a kayak, Day projects physical
energy and the promise of a generational turnover. When Liberals
try to paint him as a right-wing extremist, his aides pull out his
wedding photos, complete with long hair and sideburns, snapped near
the time when Day, by his own admission, was smoking marijuana.
</P>
<P>
   The Alliance is the successor to the Reform Party, a
western-based group, and it has been rapidly growing by depleting
the ranks of the Progressive Conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   A former auctioneer and now master of the sound bite, Canada's
new conservative phenomenon has invited Joe Clark, a former prime
minister and leader of the rival Progressive Conservative Party, to
join forces with the Alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Day, in his victory address Saturday night, said: ``Joe, I reach
out to you once again with respect and sincerity. You served this
country well, but it is only in that TV series, `Survivor,' that
the last person on the island is the winner.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark has vowed to fight on, even though his party suffers
defections almost daily. Most recently, his lone member of
Parliament from Ontario, Jim Jones, announced that he would run for
re-election as a fusion candidate for both parties.
</P>
<P>
   One Liberal strategist, Warren Kinsella, dismisses Day, who was
formerly treasurer of Alberta, as ``Archie Bunker on
Rollerblades.'' But the ruling party appears nervous about his
emergence as the leader of Canada's right.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although opinion polls suggest Jean Chretien's Liberals are
unbeatable, there is a weariness with the prime minister's
unhurried style that a young, energetic leader might be able to
exploit,'' The Toronto Star, Canada's largest-circulation
newspaper, and a traditional Liberal backer, said in an editorial
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   In a Compas poll released Saturday by the National Post, a
conservative newspaper that backs Day, the gap between the Alliance
and the Liberals had been narrowed greatly, with the Liberals
winning 44 percent of voter preferences and the Alliance 25
percent.
</P>
<P>
   In the last election, in 1997, Chretien's Liberals took only 38
percent of the popular vote, but were returned to power because the
conservative vote was split between two parties, delivering almost
all of Ontario's seats to Liberals. Chretien is expected to call an
election next spring, telling a television interviewer two weeks
ago: ``I am not a loser. I love a good fight, and I want to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Turning to the Alliance's proposal to lower Canada's federal
income tax to 17 percent across the board, from a top rate of 29
percent, the prime minister told Canada's parliamentary television
network: ``I think there is more to life than money. There is the
quality of life and the extraordinary quality of Canadian
society.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently fearing election losses in Ontario, Canada's
electoral powerhouse, the Liberal government recently announced a
$500 million aid package to Atlantic Canada, the four eastern
provinces where unemployment rates are above the national average.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any dolt can see that the Liberal caucus, unnerved by the
fresh face of Stockwell Day, knows it can never again win 101 of
Ontario's 103 seats, the only thing that keeps the Chretien
government in power,'' Allan Fotheringham, a veteran political
commentator, wrote in Maclean's magazine.
</P>
<P>
   To the dismay of the Liberals, Day's election represents a
resounding defeat of Preston Manning, a leader of Canadian
conservatives since the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   In a dramatic personal gamble, Manning, a 58-year-old veteran
campaigner, resigned as opposition leader this spring and threw
open to all comers the race for the leadership of the Alliance,
after it succeeded the Reform Party. Membership in the Alliance
tripled in three months, hitting 202,000. But the new members voted
heavily for Day, giving him a 63 to 37 percent victory in
Saturday's runoff.
</P>
<P>
   Liberals preferred Manning, an Albertan with a folksy drawl, who
failed twice in the 1990s to win any seats for the Reform Party
east of the prairies.
</P>
<P>
   In defeat, Manning was gracious, referring in his concession
speech to conservatives' dreams of occupying the official residence
of Canada's prime minister: ``Stock, we are all behind you, 200,000
strong, and tonight I join with all our members in giving you the
mandate to knock on the door of 24 Sussex Drive, on behalf of all
Canadians, and to say, `Mr. Chretien, your time is up.'''
</P>
<P>
   Day not only won decisively, but he spread the party's reach
deep into Ontario. In provisional returns from Saturday's voting,
almost 40 percent more votes were cast in Ontario than in Alberta,
the party's birthplace. Unlike Manning, Day speaks passable French
and seems to have the capability of extending his party's reach
into Canada's other electoral storehouse, Quebec, a province where
anti-Ottawa feelings sometimes mesh with western conservatism.
</P>
<P>
   The strong endorsement of Alberta's former treasurer underscores
how this province has set much of Canada's ideological agenda in
recent years, spurring the rest of the nation to follow its example
in balancing budgets, reducing government debt and cutting taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``For almost half a century since Confederation, the interplay
of Ontario and Quebec has dominated our national politics,'' John
Duffy wrote recently in Saturday Night, a Toronto-based magazine.
``Now the west is asserting itself as a full and equal political
partner in the federation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-00 2012EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
