u f BC-EADS-STOCK-NYT &LR;      07-10 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EADS-STOCK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IPO FOR EUROPE'S SUPERJUMBO JET MAKER STALLS 
</HEADLINE>
   By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ The European Aeronautic Defense and Space
Co., the new conglomerate that controls Airbus Industrie, received
a chilly response from investors Monday when it launched a
long-awaited initial stock offering.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of the company, known as EADS, had already been
discounted by underwriters on Sunday as a result of
lower-than-expected demand. On Monday, shares dropped more than 9
percent from an opening price of 19 euros, or $18.14, to 17.25
euros after the first day of trading on the Frankfurt, Paris and
Madrid exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   The response was a sharp contrast to the high investor appetite
for a slew of other big initial stock offerings from European
companies, such as those by Infineon AG, the computer chip
manufacturer spun off by Siemens AG, and T-Online, the internet
subsidiary of Deutsche Telekom.
</P>
<P>
   Those, and other major offerings, were heavily oversubscribed _
Infineon by 30 times the number of shares offered _ and jumped up
significantly from their opening price after trading began.
</P>
<P>
   Though hardly devastating for EADS, the lack of enthusiasm
inevitably cast a pall over the company's flagship project: its $12
billion plan to build a superjumbo jet, the A3XX, intended to
supersede the Boeing 747.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the nearly $3 billion raised by Monday's initial stock
offering will be pumped into the A3XX, a flying mammoth with enough
room for 550 seats and amenities like a restaurant, bedrooms or
children's play area.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the original goal of EADS to raise 3.5 billion euros,
about $3.3 billion, analysts had predicted the shares would be
offered at 22-24 euros each. But underwriters dropped their
estimate to about 20 euros by the end of last week, and on Sunday
settled on an even lower price: 19 euros for institutional
investors and 18 for individual investors.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the lower offering price, shares still sank when trading
began Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts said the feeble reception had less to do with
worries about the A3XX or with EADS itself than with concerns about
a cyclical downturn in the civilian aircraft industry.
</P>
<P>
   Both Airbus and Boeing have enjoyed big surges in orders in the
last few years, and Airbus has climbed from distant second to
virtually tied with Boeing in new orders.
</P>
<P>
   The fear is that the pace of orders will inevitably taper off
from current levels, and investors do not want to buy up shares if
the industry is about to enter a more sluggish period.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, we are much nearer the top of the cycle than the
bottom, and this is a deeply cyclical industry,'' said Nick
Cunningham, an aerospace analyst at Schroder Salomon Smith Barney
in London. ``There has to be a correction. The real issue is how
deep of a correction and what the effects will be on the different
players.''
</P>
<P>
   Other analysts said investors remain worried about EADS's
complex ownership, which includes a careful balance between French
and German ``co-chairmen'' and an awkward relationship with British
Aerospace, which is not part of EADS, but still owns 20 percent of
Airbus.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the complexity, the French government continues to own
a 20 percent stake in EADS. That has raised concerns among some
experts that the company could still fall victim to politicized
decision-making.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a difficult company _ difficult to manage and difficult
to squeeze out synergies,'' said Klaus Martini, head of European
equities at DWS, the big mutual fund arm of Deutsche Bank AG. ``You
have to deal with a lot of different parties with a lot of
different interests.''
</P>
<P>
   Risks associated with the A3XX have also played into the
worries.
</P>
<P>
   After years of study, Airbus executives announced two weeks ago
that they would proceed with plans to build the new jumbo jet.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing, by contast, has argued for years that there is little
real demand for a new class of jumbo jet. Boeing now seems to be
hedging its bets with plans to develop a stretched version of the
747. Though it is unlikely to be as efficient or innovative as the
A3XX, the stretch-747 would be far cheaper to develop.
</P>
<P>
   Philippe Camus, one of EADS's two co-chief executives, responded
stoicly to the difficulties that confronted Monday's public
offering.
</P>
<P>
   ``You must be humble with the market,'' Camus said in Paris.
``The market indicated to us the price which it was ready to pay.
End of story.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-00 2013EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
