<DOCNO> NYT20000710.0352 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8329 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-IRISH-STRIFE-BOS &LR;      07-10 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRISH-STRIFE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHERN IRELAND COWERS AS PROTESTANTS PROMISE UNREST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ENNISKILLEN, Northern Ireland _ Parts of Northern Ireland came
to a virtual standstill Monday as residents cleared out ahead of
expected protests by the Protestant group the Orange Order.
</P>
<P>
   The Orangemen had vowed to paralyze all of Northern Ireland to
demonstrate their anger over being barred from marching down the
Garvaghy Road in a Catholic neighborhood of Portadown, the most
bitterly divided town in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Businesses closed early, and nearly everyone not taking part in
the protest decided to hunker down in their homes. By 4 p.m.,
Belfast, one of the largest cities in the British isles, was
deserted.
</P>
<P>
   But aside from assorted roadblocks in sections of Belfast, and a
bomb threat in Portadown that paralyzed that town, the disruption
throughout the province was far less than in any of the previous
five years in which the annual standoff in Portadown has fueled
violence throughout Northern Ireland. Police used water cannon to
ward off loyalists who were throwing bricks at them in Portadown.
</P>
<P>
   Senior police officers said that while it was too early to
conclude they had weathered the annual storm of pro-British
loyalist violence, they were encouraged by the relatively small
number of demonstrators who took to the streets Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Orange Order, so named for William of Orange, whose 1690
defeat of Catholic King James II is the main reason they hold some
3,000 parades every year, had asked supporters to flood the streets
between 4 and 8 p.m. Monday, but police said their numbers were far
less than in previous years.
</P>
<P>
   As darkness fell, police said they were coming under attack in
loyalist strongholds, as they have been for the past week. Trucks
were parked across highways, blocking traffic, as demonstrators
wearing orange sashes did not try to hide their allegiance. In
other areas, loyalists used their bodies to block roads.
</P>
<P>
   The violence is expected to peak on Wednesday, which loyalists
call the Glorious 12th, the actual anniversary of King William's
victory over King James at the Battle of the Boyne, which created a
Protestant hegemony in the north of Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   While several Orange parades are prohibited every year, usually
on the grounds that they will cause civil unrest, it is the parade
in Portadown that is the most contentious. Orangemen there are the
most uncompromising of their organization, while the Catholic
nationalist residents in the Garvaghy Road neighborhood refuse to
consent to a parade until the Orangemen sit down and negotiate the
conditions of a march with them.
</P>
<P>
   Orangemen refuse to talk to local residents, but the British
government has made it clear that until the Orangemen agree to talk
to the elected leaders of the Catholic neighborhoood the parade
will be barred. Peter Mandelson, the British secretary of state for
Northern Ireland, said the Orange Order risked ruining its
reputation by continuing to foment violence.
</P>
<P>
   But David Jones, the spokesman for the Portadown lodge of the
Orange Order, insisted that it was the British Parades Commission
which created the problem by barring them from marching their
traditional route down the Garvaghy Road.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said any accompanying violence ``lies at the feet of the
parades commission.'' He said the protests will continue Tuesday,
between 10 a.m and 7 p.m., and will be ``sporadic in nature.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout Northern Ireland, meanwhile, many loyalists who
support the Good Friday Agreement of 1998, which seeks to end the
conflict in Northern Ireland, tried to maintain order. In
particular, members of the Ulster Volunteer Force, the second
largest loyalist paramilitary group, have been out every night the
last week, trying to control violence in their neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Carolyn Howarth, a spokeswoman for the Progressive Unionist
Party, the political wing of the Ulster Volunteer Force, deplored
the violence, saying it was damaging Protestant property and
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't believe that Protestants are hurting each other,''
said Howarth. ``We're playing right into the hands of the
republican agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   In Derry, the car and home of a prominent Protestant activist
was damaged by Protestant extremists. Sadie Logan, a community
liaison with the police, was attacked because she had met with
police in an effort to ensure that protests were peaceful.
</P>
<P>
   ``I come from an Orange family, and I'm ashamed,'' said Logan,
voicing the disgust of most Protestants in Northern Ireland, who
believe the Orangemen in Portadown are bringing their traditions
into disrepute.
</P>
<P>
   Royal Ulster Constabulary Superintendent Ian Hamill, who visited
Logan to comfort her and promise a thorough investigation, said the
attack on her ``had nothing to do with peaceful protest. This was
the work of thugs.''
</P>
<P>
   Here in Enniskillen, one of the more moderate areas of Northern
Ireland, disruption was kept to a minimum, as shops closed earlier
than usual and most people seemed to accept the inconvenience with
good humor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll not complain, going home early,'' said Gary Mulholland,
who got off early from his job at a shoe store. He said he will be
off again Wednesday when Northern Ireland both celebrates and
cowers from the Glorious 12th.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
