<HEADER>
A8353 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      07-10 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: LEBANON AND THE GOBLET OF FIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   By THOMAS L. FRIEDMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon _ If you can't be at Camp David, Beirut is about
as good a vantage point as any for watching the Palestinian-Israeli
summit talks, because Lebanon has many lessons, some obvious, some
subtle, to offer the negotiators.
</P>
<P>
   Lebanon, first off, is a reminder of what happened when Israelis
and Palestinians tried to resolve their differences not with
diplomacy but with brute force during that long hot summer of 1982.
At that time Israel still entertained the fantasy of solving the
Palestinian problem by wiping out the PLO, and the PLO entertained
the fantasy that armed struggle could win back at least all of the
West Bank and East Jerusalem. But the Israeli-Palestinian war in
Lebanon was a war with no winner. All sides lost.
</P>
<P>
   A short time later, Lebanon taught the Israelis another lesson _
that simply because Israel has more power doesn't mean it is in its
interest to cram a deal down the other side's throat. On May 17,
1983, with the help of a very foolish Reagan administration,
Israel's Likud government imposed a peace settlement on Lebanon,
which gave Israel a permanent security presence in South Lebanon.
The Lebanese prime minister at the time literally cried after
signing the treaty. The May 17 agreement, though, was never
implemented. Because it had no legitimacy in Lebanese society it
had no roots, and therefore no staying power. The only thing the
May 17 agreement gave birth to was a war against Israel by the
Hezbollah Shiite guerrillas _ which eventually forced a unilateral
Israeli withdrawal _ and a virulent anti-American campaign that
culminated in the blowing up of a U.S. Marine barracks, killing 241
servicemen.
</P>
<P>
   But what is most intriguing is the latest lesson from Lebanon _
the one being taught by Hezbollah. Who said the following on TV
here the other day? ``The political class in Lebanon got so
self-absorbed in its rules and games that it is not aware of
globalization and competition and the requirements to succeed today
... You cannot work anymore on the assumption that we should not
change our ways to meet the challenges of peace and in order to
become a productive economy.''
</P>
<P>
   No, it wasn't the minister of finance. It was Haj Hussein al
Haj-Hassan, a Hezbollah Parliament member from Baalbek. In the wake
of driving the Israelis out of South Lebanon, Hezbollah has turned
its focus inward to satisfy what it knows its constituency now
wants most _ jobs, better schools, development, an end to
corruption and integration with global trends, not more war.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot imagine how tired people are of this conflict and
all the old political sloganeering,'' remarked Jamil Mroue, editor
of The Beirut Daily Star, ``and the party here that understands
that best is precisely the party that has been most removed from
traditional Lebanese politics _ Hezbollah.''
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah first leapfrogged over the old politics here by not
being afraid of the Israelis, but now, having evicted them from
South Lebanon, Hezbollah is turning its attention to the economic
and social aspirations of its rank and file.
</P>
<P>
   So what's the lesson? Prime Minister Ehud Barak of Israel may be
coming to Camp David without the support of all the traditional,
small-minded ethnic parties in Israel. But I guarantee you, 60 to
70 percent of the Israeli people are with Barak. That is, they are
ready for a real and fair deal, including hard compromises,
provided the bottom line reads ``The End'' _ the end of this
conflict so Israelis can really get on with life.
</P>
<P>
   The divisions in the Israeli Parliament, like those in the
Lebanese Parliament, represent the old politics of ethnic and
religious division. But remember, Barak himself was directly
elected by the Israeli people _ precisely to bring about a final
peace. He still comes to Washington with a strong mandate for that.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of elections, Bashar Assad was ``elected'' president of
Syria Monday night to succeed his father. On the eve of Bashar's
election, what did he do? Give a speech attacking Israel? No, he
ended government controls on auto imports, enabling any Syrian to
import a car.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: I don't know whether Yasser Arafat and Barak will
be able to achieve what they both will consider a fair deal. But I
do know this: If they do, they will each find solid silent
majorities at home to embrace it, because growing underneath the
old politics out here is a new politics. It may not make as much
noise as the old politics, but it has a lot more support than you
think.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
