<HEADLINE>
FAMILY STRATEGY FOR SAN DIEGO 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, July 16) 
 By MARTHA STEVENSON OLSON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   For visitors and San Diegans alike, the city offers some great
attractions: The San Diego Zoo, San Diego Wild Animal Park and
SeaWorld San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   But family outings can quickly get expensive and, without a game
plan, can leave everyone out of sorts and unsatisfied. Doing some
homework before buying tickets and mapping out a route through the
attractions can help save money, time and energy. In San Diego, as
at increasing numbers of theme parks and family-oriented
attractions, it may be worth becoming an annual member, or buying
combination passes, rather than buying separate single tickets,
even if you're planning to visit only once. You won't be able to
put your wallet away _ there are extra-cost features beyond the
entrance gate, not to mention lunch, snacks and souvenirs to buy _
but at least you'll be starting out ahead of the game.
</P>
<P>
   SOME OF THE CHOICES
</P>
<P>
   The San Diego Zoological Society offers an annual membership
that is a bargain: A dual membership is $76 (less for renewals),
and children's memberships are $19 each. (A single adult membership
is $60.) These provide unlimited visits to both the zoo and the
animal park, including free passage on the zoo's aerial tram, the
Skyfari, along with a sheet of coupons and discounts.
</P>
<P>
   With a day's general admission to the zoo running $18, and $8
for children ages 3 to 11, not including the $1.50 cost of a
Skyfari ride, and with a day at the animal park costing $21.95 for
adults and $14.95 for children, the society membership can pay for
itself after one visit to each place. Short-term visitors can also
buy a pass offering one day at the zoo and one day at the animal
park in a five-day period, which costs $38.35 for adults and $23.15
for children.
</P>
<P>
   SeaWorld, with day admission $40 for adults and $30 for children
3 to 11, also offers an annual pass that costs $74.95 for each
adult and $59.95 for children and those 55 and older; it includes
free parking (normally $7 for cars). A Rockin' Summer Nights Pass
can be be obtained with a single day's paid admission, entitling
the holder to return for free after 4 p.m. on any or every night
before Labor Day. And a three-for-one pass allows unlimited
admission during a five-day period to the zoo, the animal park and
SeaWorld for $75 for adults and $55 for children.
</P>
<P>
   Single-day entry fees are sometimes discounted through coupon
promotions with fast-food franchises, newspapers, or other theme
parks. SeaWorld, for example, has a deal with the local Subway
sandwich chain that knocks $5 off a day's admission for up to six
people per coupon. A Southern California Value Pass offers
unlimited admission to SeaWorld and Universal Studios Hollywood
over any 14 consecutive days for $75 adults and $55 children.
</P>
<P>
   At the San Diego Zoo, highlights of the day, including
``enrichment activities,'' when various animals get to play with
something new and different, are posted on a big board at the zoo's
entrance, just in front of the Flamingo Lagoon. The prime
attraction at the zoo these days is Hua Mei, the panda cub born
last August. Zoo gates open at 7:30 a.m. and shut at 9 p.m. through
Labor Day, with the zoo closing at 10 p.m. The panda exhibit is
open from 8 to 11:30 a.m. and from 4 to 8 p.m., with the bonus that
the animals are more likely to be frisky in the cooler hours. Other
nighttime entertainment includes music, magic shows and animal
interactions.
</P>
<P>
   Getting around the zoo's 110 acres can be a challenge. The
easiest option is a Kangaroo Bus Tour pass, which entitles holders
to hop on and off as the bus circles the zoo. The cost is $8, $5
for children 3 to 11. The Skyfari ride, aside from providing a
bird's-eye view of the gorilla enclosure and Balboa Park's ornate
1915 California Tower, connects the entrance side to the western
side of the zoo. Visitors can walk down into Bongo Canyon near the
center of the zoo to see the pandas, and, to save energy, can use
people-moving ramps to get up and out.
</P>
<P>
   There are places to eat and drink throughout and near the park.
Try the snack bars near the entrance, or Albert's Treehouse, a
pleasant, full-service restaurant built on a breezy series of
platforms overlooking Bongo Canyon. Another option is the new Prado
restaurant, an upscale place a short distance from the zoo in
Balboa Park's House of Hospitality. It's possible to leave the zoo
and return the same day by getting your hand stamped at the exit.
</P>
<P>
   OUT OF AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   The Wild Animal Park, on 1,800 acres near Escondido, Calif., 30
miles north of San Diego, presents its own challenges: Its inland
valley gets above 100 degrees most summer days and the lines for
the park's 55-minute railway ride can be long and tedious.
</P>
<P>
   The park is open from 9 a.m. until 10 p.m. through Labor Day,
when it will begin closing again at 5. Heart of Africa, a lakeside
exhibit in the midst of what looks like an African savanna,
features evening performances by Bomani, a dance and drum troupe
from West Africa, and encounters between animals and their keepers.
</P>
<P>
   The newest attraction at the park is Condor Ridge, a rocky
hillside about 10 minutes' walk from the park entrance. Five
California condors, an endangered species brought back from
near-extinction through a captive breeding program (the zoological
society has been a key participant in it) live in a six-story
aviary on the hillside. The huge boulders serve as launching pads
for the birds _ whose wingspans range up to 10 feet _ as well as
places for them to roost.
</P>
<P>
   The best time to visit the ridge is early in the morning, after
the condors are first fed, or very late in the afternoon, when the
setting sun provides a gilded view of the park and the lion
enclosure below. Condor Ridge is also home to other rare and
endangered animals like the desert bighorn sheep and the desert
tortoise.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the lines, most visitors to the park do take the Wgasa
Bush Line Railway, which loops five miles around grazing groups of
giraffe, gazelles, rhinos, elephants and other wildlife from Asia
and Africa.
</P>
<P>
   One way to avoid the wait for the train is to buy a preferred
boarding pass ($4, $3 children) at the railway station and get on
the next train, which otherwise would be free.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors board the train at a different point from where they
get off. Once off, you can walk to the right to the Petting Kraal
and Mombasa Lagoon, or to the left to Lorikeet Landing, where you
can buy food to feed the lorikeets, which are colorful South
American birds about the size of a robin. Also to the left is the
Hidden Jungle exhibit, with its butterflies and cutter ants. Nearby
is the Mombasa Island Cooker, the most diverse of the park's
eateries; it serves Asian and Italian food and salads and has
tables that overlook the lagoon.
</P>
<P>
   A three-minute walk from the lagoon is a meandering path that
passes by a children's playground and into the Heart of Africa, a
simulated East African environment. At Jameson Research Island, set
up like a study camp, there usually is an opportunity to interact
with an animal like an aardvark or an African crested porcupine,
with help from a park educator.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
