<SLUG> BC-BBO-ALLSTAR-MCGRIFF-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta fans give the Crime Dog a warm welcome
 &HT;    By Carlos Frias
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Remember Fred McGriff? The Crime Dog? The resident
home run hitter in Atlanta before Chipper Jones put on 20 pounds of
muscle?
</P>
<P>
   The fans at Turner Field took time to remember Monday evening,
even if just for a brief moment. Prior to the Home Run Derby,
McGriff was interviewed on the field, and the second his likeness
flashed onto the big screen, the fans raised a standing ovation
that made McGriff widen his famous smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans here have always been great to me,'' he said, looking
around the park. ``It's a great city and a great place to host an
All-Star Game.''
</P>
<P>
   McGriff returned to Atlanta as a five-time All-Star Game
veteran, this time representing the Tampa Bay Devil Rays. But few
can forget what he meant to the Braves in five of the franchises'
most memorable years. Among them, he helped Atlanta to the 1995
World Series title, a year after being named the All-Star Game's
MVP in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't know if he will be remembered as one of the players
that helped build the National League's Team of the '90s. He
doesn't know if people will remember he has homered in 36 different
ball parks, one behind McGwire for the Major League record, or with
six more homers in Tampa Bay, he would become only the second
player in history to hit over 200 in each league.
</P>
<P>
   But on a day like today, six years since being named the MVP of
the 1994 All-Star Game for his pinch-hit, two-run homer in the
ninth, the trophy in his den is a nice reminder of what he meant to
the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've still got it at my house,'' he said. ``People can forget
what you did. Records can be broken. But they can't take that away
from me... Maybe I can get another one.''
</P>
<P>
   McGriff's return was not without its share of grumbling. With a
.272 average, 15 home runs and 58 RBI, McGriff's numbers are not as
impressive as those of Chicago's Frank Thomas, who was left off the
team. Thomas is hitting .340 with 25 home runs and 72 RBI.
Anaheim's Mo Vaughn (.297, 21, 62) and Texas' Rafael Palmeiro
(.289, 21, 61) were also bypassed.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Torre, the American League's manager for the All-Star Game,
took some heat for the selection. Torre admitted first base was the
toughest position and said one reason he picked McGriff was
``because he played for Bobby down there and I thought it was a
good spot.''
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Cox, the Braves manager and skipper for the National
League team, admitted they tried to bring McGriff back when Andres
Galarraga was lost for the year, while he received treatment for
the cancerous tumor in his lower back. To see him back in Atlanta
in any aspect, Cox said, is great for the fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's terrific,'' Cox said. ``He's a very popular guy
here. He's had a lot
</P>
<P>
   of success down there in St. Pete. I think Joe made a great pick
for our fans. I know Mac will bevery excited to be here. It means
a lot to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
