<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8372 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-$A     07-10 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-$ADV16-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: park educator.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although SeaWorld San Diego weaves educational and conservation
messages into its programs, it's still an amusement park, with
interactive displays that include dolphin feeding and hands-on
exhibits of starfish and bat rays. And there are several thrill
rides, like whitewater rafting on Shipwreck Rapids and Wild Arctic,
a hair-raising virtual helicopter flight in a simulated polar
storm.
</P>
<P>
   AND NOW, 4D
</P>
<P>
   New this summer is ``Pirates 4D,'' a sensorama movie about a
bunch of hapless pirates. Special effects include, in addition to
the usual 3D in-your-face whangers, such novelties as water
spritzing from the seats, little electric shocks from the seat
backs and warm-water droplets spattering from above (those darned
birds!).
</P>
<P>
   Still, the centerpiece of SeaWorld's attractions are the justly
famous marine mammal shows featuring trained sea lions, dolphins
and Shamu, the orca star. Some lines can be long at the amusement
shows. Build in plenty of waiting time.
</P>
<P>
   Before entering SeaWorld, stop at the guest relations booth for
advice and to make sure the maps given out at the parking lot
kiosks are current (ours wasn't). The maps are supposed to list the
day's special events. As it was, we were advised to pick the shows
we wanted to see and visit the attractions nearby, while generally
circling the park's perimeter.
</P>
<P>
   Directly inside the entry gates is the reservation center, which
can book tours of the park or reserve seats at the daily,
all-you-can-eat Dine With Shamu buffet. After filling your plate,
you eat at poolside tables as Shamu, supervised by trainers,
performs feats like resting his nose on the pool's edge often as
close as a few feet away. Including tax, the cost is $27.47 for
adults and $13.95 for children.
</P>
<P>
   A 90-minute Behind the Scenes tour costs $8 for adults, $7 for
ages 55 and up and children 3 to 11. A Spotlight Tour lasting two
hours features interactions with various animals and costs $22, $18
for children. Petting the bottlenose dolphins is popular, so it's
best to arrive fairly early, bearing dead fish bought nearby.
SeaWorld also has a dolphin interaction pool, where visitors, in
loaned wetsuits and booties, can swim for about 20 minutes with an
actual dolphin. The cost is $125 a person, with admission to the
park required but not included. Reservations are suggested: (877)
436-5746.
</P>
<P>
   The Bayside Skyride, an aerial gondola across part of Mission
Bay and back, and the Skytower ride, a circling observation deck
that climbs the needle at the park's center, are cool and quiet.
The cost is $2.25 each, $3.50 for both.
</P>
<P>
   When planning a visit, remember that theme parks generally are
most crowded on Saturdays, water parks on Sunday. As each weekday
passes, popularity accelerates, with Monday typically the least
crowded, Friday the most crowded. Many parks can provide
information on admission discounts through their general
information line, and it's easier to figure out the numbers before
you get to the admissions gate with impatient children.
</P>
<P>
   SeaWorld Adventure Park San Diego; (619) 226-3901;
www.seaworld.com.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego Zoo. (619) 234-3153; www.sandiegozoo.org.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego Wild Animal Park, Highway 78, Escondido, Calif.; (760)
747-8702; www.sandiegozoo.org.
</P>
<P>
   Southern California's other theme parks also offer various entry
options. The following does not include every theme park in
Southern California or every permutation in the cost of admission.
</P>
<P>
   Disneyland, 1313 Harbor Boulevard, Anaheim; (714) 781-4565;
www.disneyland.com. Open daily; hours vary. Admission is $41 ages
10 and older, $31 ages 3 to 9, $39 ages 60 and older. Parking is
$7.
</P>
<P>
   At the Disneyland gate, one can buy a two-day passport, at $76
for ages 10 and older and $57 for children 3 to 9, with a second
visit within seven days; or a three-day passport, $99 for adults,
$75 for children, allowing three visits within 14 days.
</P>
<P>
   Flex passports must be bought through a travel agent, at
selected Disney stores, or online. A three-day flex passport, at
$76 adults and $57 children, allows three admissions in a five-day
period, with one day's early admission entitling the holder to get
in 90 minutes ahead of the general public. A five-day flex, at $99
adults and $75 children, allows five days at the park within a
seven-day period, with early admission on several of those days.
</P>
<P>
   Legoland California, 1 Legoland Drive, Carlsbad, 35 miles north
of San Die go; (760) 918-5346; www.legoland.com. General admission
is $34 for adults, $29 for children 3 to 16 and seniors 60 and
older. Parking is $7 for most lots; $12 closer to the park.
</P>
<P>
   Annual passes include the Block Party Pass, at $79 for adults,
and $59 for children 3 to 16; it allows unlimited daily admission
excluding weekends in July and August, and Labor Day weekend, as
well as discounts on guest admission and some park merchandise
(excluding, strangely, Lego blocks). The Primo Pass, at $109 for
adults and $89 for children, is for every day and includes free
parking along with a free one-day guest pass. For annual pass
purchases call (877) 434-6526.
</P>
<P>
   Knott's Berry Farm, 8039 Beach Boulevard, Buena Park, 10 miles
north of Anaheim; (714) 220-5200; www.knotts.com.
</P>
<P>
   Open every day except Dec. 25, 9 a.m. to 11 p.m. Sunday through
Thursday, 9 a.m. to midnight Friday and Saturday through Labor Day.
Daily admission is $38 adults and $28 for children 3 to 11, seniors
60 and older, the disabled, and pregnant women; parking is $7.
After 4 p.m., admission is $16.95. Annual passes cost $109 for
adults through age 59, $49 for children and $65 for seniors, and
are good any day.
</P>
<P>
   Knott's Soak City U.S.A., 2052 Entertainment Circle, Chula
Vista, about 12 miles south of San Diego; (619) 661-7373;
www.soakcityusa.com. The Web site also covers another Knott's Soak
City, which is next to Knott's Berry Farm.
</P>
<P>
   Open daily Memorial Day through Labor Day, and weekends in May
and September, possibly through October. Summer hours are 10 a.m.
to 8 p.m.; off-summer closing time is 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   General admission is $19.95, $13.95 for ages 3 to 11, with
$11.95 admission after 3 p.m. Parking is $4 per car. A year's pass,
good for both Buena Park and Chula Vista, is $59.95 for adults and
$49.95 for ages 3 to 11.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
