<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8378 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBO-ALLSTAR-BOS &LR;      07-10 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ALLSTAR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARCIAPARRA GENTLEMANLY ABOUT CHOICE OF JETER TO START 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's a time-tested American sports cliche: Coach's son
gets the nod. Every time.
</P>
<P>
   This is what Nomar Garciaparra faced when he got to Atlanta for
the All-Star Game. Seattle Mariners shortstop Alex Rodriguez was
elected by fans to start the game but is unable to play because of
a concussion. (A-Rod is one of seven fan favorites who won't play.)
It was up to All-Star (and Yankees) manager Joe Torre to choose a
starter from a shortstop trio of Boston's Garciaparra, New York's
Derek Jeter, and Baltimore's Mike Bordick.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Garciaparra is hitting an eye-popping .389 with 12
homers and 55 RBIs, Torre is going with Jeter (.322, 9, 37).
</P>
<P>
   Coach's son gets the nod. Every time.
</P>
<P>
   As ever, Garciaparra took the high road.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unfortunate that A-Rod can't play,'' said the Red Sox
shortstop. ``But as far as who starts, it doesn't matter. I'm a fan
of the game, too, and it's just flattering to even be mentioned
with those guys.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a huge honor,'' acknowledged Jeter. ``You just look at
the shortstop position in the American League. There are so many
deserving players. You can really flip a coin and decide who the
starter is. Maybe it's just my turn in the rotation.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, who is here to watch the game, said, ``I don't know
the procedure and I didn't talk to Mr. Torre about it. They're all
having great years and, basically, it's Mr. Torre's decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre explained, ``Derek Jeter, you know, was right behind Alex
Rodriguez in the voting. I'm a little partial to Derek and, yeah, a
little bit. You know, you have to be around this kid to appreciate
what he's all about. I picked him over Nomar because Nomar started
last year, and I think it's a big thrill for a youngster to start
the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Bordick is the party-crasher in the American League's
super-shortstop club. A-Rod, Nomar, and Jeter are the GQ cover
boys, probably the best trio to play at the position in one era.
Rodriguez has been on four All-Star teams, Garciaparra and Jeter
three each. A-Rod has been voted to start three times, Garciaparra
once. Jeter has yet to win the fan balloting.
</P>
<P>
   A-Rod also was hurt last year when Garciaparra narrowly beat
Jeter in the fan voting (Internet geeks are believed to have pushed
Garciaparra over the top). Garciaparra went 0 for 2 at Fenway Park
(Curt Schilling and Randy Johnson got him out), then took the field
in the bottom of the fourth and saw Jeter running out to replace
him. The public substitution was orchestrated by Torre, who wanted
Garciaparra to get a big hand in front of the home crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had talked about it,'' said Garciaparra. ``Joe told me they
were going to do that and it was a good way to do it. It was classy
on Joe's part. It meant a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeter chuckled and said, ``Hey, it was Boston. That was the only
way to do it so I wouldn't get booed.''
</P>
<P>
   When Jeter went to bat at Fenway, he mimicked Garciaparra's
elaborate batting routine. Then he struck out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him he didn't do it right,'' said Garciaparra. ``If he
did it right, he wouldn't have struck out.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeter said he might imitate Rodriguez. Garciaparra has no plans
to replace Jeter on the field before the start of an inning.
</P>
<P>
   Jeter-for-Rodriguez is one of seven instances in which the
All-Star electee isn't starting because of injury. Other American
League subs-turned-starters are Carl Everett in left field for
Manny Ramirez (hamstring) and Travis Fryman at third base for Cal
Ripken (back). In the National League, it'll be Andres Galarraga at
first base for Mark McGwire (knee tendinitis), Jim Edmonds in
center for Ken Griffey (knee), Vladimir Guerrero in left for Barry
Bonds (broken thumb), and catcher Jason Kendall for Mike Piazza
(concussion courtesy of a Roger Clemens 92 miles per hour
fastball). Also missing is Braves righthander Greg Maddux, who has
been replaced by Cincinnati's Danny Graves, and the inimitable
Pedro Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   Lefthanders David Wells and Randy Johnson are the starting
pitchers for the 71st midsummer joust. Wells is 15-2 with a 3.44
ERA and 100 strikeouts, while Johnson is 14-2 with a 1.80 ERA and
198 strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   Wells said he isn't on a mission to prove the Yankees were wrong
to trade him for Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not here to try to prove a point because of them trading
me,'' said Wells. ``I think I'm going to have success wherever I go
because of the fact that I was determined to go and pitch. I think
the Yankee organization knows, Joe knows that I'm a competitor.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Everett and Garciaparra, the Red Sox will be
represented by closer Derek Lowe. Martinez, due to come off the
disabled list for a start against the Mets Thursday, will not be
eligible to pitch but will be introduced with the American League
squad.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans have won the last three All-Star Games and nine of
the last 12. The AL won last year at Fenway, 4-1. Overall the NL
leads, 40-29-1.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-00 2032EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
