<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HILLARY-CLINTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CLINTON ATTCKS PLANS FOR MORE POWER PLANTS ON HUDSON RIVER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By LARA JAKES  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Hillary Rodham Clinton, who has made lower
utility rates a cornerstone pledge of her campaign for the Senate
in New York, criticized the state government Monday for allowing
the construction of new power plants along with Hudson River
without having a plan to assess demand for the power supply.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing relaxed if guarded during a 105-minute meeting with
editors and reporters of the Albany Times Union, the first lady
said New York's attempt to deregulate utility costs has not been as
successful as neighboring states. Moreover, she said, the state's
Public Service Commission has created a ``bottleneck'' bureaucratic
system that is stunting competition among power companies in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting capped off Clinton's five-day upstate tour, during
which the Democratic candidate called the region's economy her
``No. 1 priority'' if elected. The tour also marked Clinton's first
full year on the campaign trail, which started last July on the
Delaware County farm of Daniel Patrick Moynihan, the retiring
Democratic senator she aims to replace.
</P>
<P>
   She will face Rep. Rick Lazio, a Long Island Republican, in the
Nov. 7 election.
</P>
<P>
   The electricity generating plant issue is of particular interest
in the region because of the recent approval of a power plant for
Athens, which supporters hail for creating jobs but critics assail
for potentially endangering the environment. It puts Clinton in an
awkward position as she simultaneously advocates for the
environment and a stronger upstate economy.
</P>
<P>
   Of the electricity supply, she said: ``I'm not yet convinced
there isn't enough of a supply in the United States and Canada to
meet our needs if we structured it differently.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So I have some questions _ not that I'm against them,'' she
said. ``I'm for power plants, where we need them to create more
energy, but I think there are other ways of doing it than siting
all of these plants along the Hudson, which I don't think is
necessarily in the long-term interests of the Hudson Valley.''
</P>
<P>
   She described the Public Service Commission, which regulates
utilities in New York, as a ``bottleneck that has not been to our
benefit.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spent considerable time Monday outlining her overall
economic plan for upstate New York. That plan includes lowering
regional airfares, wiring businesses for the Internet, promoting
tourism and support for farmers.
</P>
<P>
   She also:
</P>
<P>
   _ Reinforced her commitment for an abortion-rights litmus test
for U.S. Supreme Court nominees and other federal judgeships.
</P>
<P>
   _ Lashed out at Republicans who she said failed to deliver their
share of the bargain in reforming welfare.
</P>
<P>
   _ Called for financial and quality of life incentives to help
recruit and keep military personnel.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also acknowledged her unusually high negative ratings
among voters after 12 months of campaigning. Lazio, who just
entered the election in May, is tied with Clinton in the polls,
while the number of undecided voters in the race continues to grow.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a number of people who just really disagree with me
on the issues, and believe that I feel strongly about the issues
... and feel I'm more of a threat to their position than others
are,'' she said in explanation. ``For some people, it's the
accumulated residue of the last eight years, that they don't know
quite what to make of me and people have talked about me who have
never met me and said things about me that aren't true.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But I really am not either surprised or particularly concerned
by people who are opposed to me,'' she said. ``I think there's
going to be a hard-core group of people who would never vote for me
under any circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   Although her campaign has so far raised $18 million, Clinton
estimated that Lazio and his allies could outspend her by up to
3-to-1 in what is anticipated to be one of the most expensive
Senate races in national history. Lazio has so far raised about $8
million but will almost certainly be helped with millions of
dollars from the state and national GOP committees.
</P>
<P>
   She called herself a ``zealot'' for overhauling campaign finance
laws, even though her own joint fund-raising committee _ which
collects ``soft money,'' which are legal but unregulated donations
_ had around $4 million at the end of March.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Clinton sounded confident in describing her year on the
trail, and of the election's outcome. She is the first first lady
to run for public office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really believe that most New Yorkers agree with me on the
issues,'' she said. ``So my job is to make sure they know where I
stand on the issues as opposed to my opponent. ... And I bring a
commitment to persevere on behalf of what I believe. And I am not a
quitter.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
