<SLUG> BC-HOLLYWOOD-BOWL-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MEETING OF DIVAS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROB LOWMAN 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Audra McDonald joked that Patti LuPone called her a ``devie'' _ a
diva in training _ while LuPone herself was a ``devaah.'' But it
was evident during Friday's Hollywood Bowl concert that the
Broadway superstars formed a mutual admiration society, which made
their spectacular performance even more special.
</P>
<P>
   Though it was conductor John Mauceri's 200th concert with the
Hollywood Bowl Orchestra, the evening was not a trip down memory
lane, but a celebration. And it's hard to think of a better way to
celebrate than with this first-time pairing of LuPone and McDonald,
who was making her Bowl debut.
</P>
<P>
   The orchestra kicked off the proceeding with the overture from
``Gypsy,'' and everything was coming up roses for the rest of the
evening.
</P>
<P>
   LuPone, not shying away from the Barbra Streisand mystique,
followed with a vibrant rendition of ``Don't Rain on My Parade''
from ``Funny Girl.'' Next was Kurt Weill's ``It Never Was You''
from ``Knickerbocker Holiday,'' which led to a Mauceri-arranged,
rather subdued but lovely instrumental version of Weill songs from
``Mack the Knife'' to ``September Song.''
</P>
<P>
   McDonald was up next with a splendid rendition of Harold Arlen's
``A Sleepin' Bee'' (``I'm on an Arlen kick,'' she noted). Within
it, McDonald showed why she's the reigning queen of Broadway _
going from an operatic trill to an almost bluesy growl within a few
notes and making it all seem perfectly natural.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; 5i+k%1
</P>
</TEXT>
