<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HILLARY-CLINTON (Albany, N.Y.) _ Hillary Rodham Clinton, who has
made lower utility rates a cornerstone pledge of her campaign for
the Senate in New York, criticizes the state government for
allowing the construction of new power plants along with Hudson
River without having a plan to assess demand for the power supply.
The Democratic candidate also reaffirms her support for a pro-life
litmus test for Supreme Court nominees. By LARA JAKES. (Already
filed.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-NAACP (Baltimore) _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush is
interrupted by anti-death penalty hecklers as he prepares to
address the NAACP. The Republican presidential hopeful, referring
to his party, tells the civil rights group: ``There is no denying
that the party of Lincoln has not always carried the mantle of
Lincoln.'' By R.G. RATCLIFFE.
</P>
<P>
   GOP-CONVENTION (Washington) _ Republican National Convention
planners are considering spreading out the state nominating roll
call over several nights rather than holding the traditional
lengthy call in one night. Meanwhile, Former President George Bush
will not address the convention, where his son is to be nominated,
and Arizona Sen. John McCain will speak on a night dedicated to
national security issues. By ALAN BERNSTEIN.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MISSILE-DEFENSE (Washington) _ Supporters of the proposed
National Missile Defense program argue that the system's
embarrassing test failure over the weekend wasn't caused by any
fundamental flaw in the weapon. The Pentagon says the test flopped
because the booster rocket _ a Minuteman missile refurbished by
Lockheed Martin Corp. _ failed to jettison its cargo, a ``kill
vehicle'' that was to have homed in on a dummy warhead in outer
space. Sen. John Kyl, R-Ariz., called the test ``disappointing,''
but added that ``the primary failure had to do with a technology
that is not a new technology, that is, separating a booster from
its payload. There is nothing about this latest test that would be
definitive about not proceeding with National Missile Defense.'' By
ERIC ROSENBERG. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   EXECUTION-DELAYED (Washington) _ The White House has issued a
stay of execution for Raul Garza, the convict's lawyer says. The
stay had been widely expected. DEBORAH TEDFORD.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-CONFERENCE (Durban, South Africa) _ An HIV-positive South
African Supreme Court judge blasts South African President Thabo
Mbeki's response to the AIDS crisis. In South Africa, where 5,000
babies are born with the virus each month, most people can't pay
for HIV treatments. By LEIGH HOPPER.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   WACO-TRIAL (Waco, Texas) _ A judge rules that government
attorneys can present jurors with audiotapes of the Branch
Davidians' conversations moments before the compound was consumed
by flames. In the tapes, those speaking can be heard to say ``pour
the fuel'' and ``light the fire,'' lawyers for the government
contend, indicating that the cult followers _ not government agents
_ caused a deadly fire. By JIM HENDERSON.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ Silence descended upon much of
America on Saturday. It was the wonderful sound of children _ and
adults _ reading. The fourth installment of the Harry Potter series
lives up to its high expectations. How does J. K. Rowling do it?
It's no mystery. It's magic. By MARIANNE MEANS. (Already filed.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
