<DOCNO> NYT20000710.0379 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8384 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CHINA-U.S.-FLIGHT-ART     07-10 1118
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-U.S.-FLIGHT-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PASSENGER AND FREIGHT CARRIERS COMPETING FOR AIR ROUTES TO CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) By DAVID LEONHARDT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For more than a century, New York and Chicago have
alternated outdoing each other by building the tallest skyscraper
in the United States. Their art museums have long competed for some
of the world's great paintings. And their sports teams _ be it the
Giants and Bears in football during the 1950s or the Knicks and
Bulls in basketball more recently _ have repeatedly battled for
championships.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes the latest skirmish in a long civic rivalry: the
behind-the-scenes struggle over which city might become the
take-off point for a lucrative set of new flights to China
scheduled to begin next April. The decision is due this summer from
the Transportation Department amid a flurry of subtle lobbying from
members of Congress and former top Clinton administration
officials, and the award is coveted because of the increase in
travel expected to follow once China enters the World Trade
Organization.
</P>
<P>
   In New York's corner is Delta Air Lines, which wants to fly to
Beijing from John F. Kennedy International Airport. With support
from Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and much of the state's congressional
delegation, Delta executives are arguing that New York's size and
economic importance so outweigh Chicago's as to make the decision
an easy one.
</P>
<P>
   ``New York is the most important aviation market on the
planet,'' Leo Mullin, Delta's chief executive, said.
</P>
<P>
   American Airlines, which would fly from Chicago's O'Hare
International Airport to Shanghai, responds that geography trumps
demographics. The Midwest's unofficial capital is an excellent
gathering point for passengers and is a shorter hop over the North
Pole to China, American and its supporters say. New York, important
as it is, is isolated from the rest of the country, they say, a
complaint New Yorkers have heard before.
</P>
<P>
   But even as the Big Apple and the Windy City highlight each
other's flaws, the bickering between Delta and American may help
open the door to another well-connected contender: United Parcel
Service. The U.S. aviation agreement with China, unlike any other
in memory, forces Transportation Department officials to choose
between passenger and cargo carriers, rather than allocating routes
to each separately.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're sort of in new territory, in terms of the department
trying to make an analysis,'' said Will Ris, American's senior vice
president for government affairs.
</P>
<P>
   UPS wants the same right to fly to China that its chief
competitor, Federal Express, already enjoys. With the help of the
Teamsters, its largest union, UPS _ one of the biggest campaign
contributors in the country _ has lined up a list of supporters
that includes more than 300 members of Congress. ``This is our
number one international priority,'' said Tom Weidemeyer, the
president of UPS Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   The company's allies have inundated the Transportation
Department with letters saying that the cargo business needs a new
entrant much more than the passenger business does. Currently,
Federal Express is the only American cargo company to fly directly
to China, although UPS flies to Hong Kong and its partners
distribute packages from there. Northwest Airlines and United
Airlines both now carry passengers to Beijing and Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has not been a more important carrier-selection case
before DOT since deregulation,'' more than two decades ago,
American wrote in its official filing. ``This one transcends
aviation.''
</P>
<P>
   The passenger airlines argue that opening up their market to
greater competition will spur travel between the two countries and
accelerate the kind of political change the United States wants to
see in China. UPS says it can lower the price of shipping goods
between the world's biggest economy and its most populous nation,
which should have a big effect on global trade.
</P>
<P>
   The carriers' deadline for making their official case has
recently passed. A decision is due soon, but it already has taken
longer than other cases because of the complexity of the filings,
analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, nobody really knows quite what's going on right
now,'' said Dale Bumpers, the former senator from Arkansas that
American hired to help its case.
</P>
<P>
   President Bill Clinton and Zhu Rongji, China's premier,
negotiated the new aviation treaty at their April 1999 meeting
here, when Zhu was willing to make concessions in an effort to
convince the Clinton administration to back China's entry into the
World Trade Organization. The pact did not go as far as American
government officials and airline executives would like, but it
allowed for the doubling of flights to about eight each day _ split
equally between American and Chinese airlines. And it gave each
country the right to designate one more airline to fly between the
countries.
</P>
<P>
   Even the airlines that already serve the market have become
involved in the political maneuvering. Currently, Northwest flies
to Beijing and Shanghai from Detroit. United flies from San
Francisco to Beijing and, via Tokyo, to Shanghai. But in a move
that most analysts consider an effort to ward off American's bid
for the new flights, United has announced that it will switch the
Shanghai flights to Chicago next April and no longer make a stop in
Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   The incumbents, including FDX Corp.'s Federal Express, have also
applied for some of the 10 new weekly round trips that the
Transportation Department will hand out. Still, lobbyists expect
the new entrant to get most of them so it can establish itself. In
addition, Polar Air, a small cargo carrier, has applied for the
Chinese routes, but it has little support in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   All along, federal law has barred the companies from directly
lobbying the Transportation Department official who oversees the
process, A. Bradford Mims. At a recent meeting of an international
airline industry group in Sydney, Australia, for instance, Delta's
Mullin said he had a long discussion with Mims, all about rules on
how much noise airplanes can make. ``I didn't mention China once,''
Mullin said. (Through a spokesman, Mims declined to comment.)
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the airlines have hired some of Washington's
best-connected lobbyists. Mickey Kantor, the former Commerce
Secretary and top trade representative in the Clinton
administration, has sent written testimony on behalf of UPS, and
Bumpers helped American, a unit of the AMR Corp., write its
application.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The companies have also asked their outside supporters to write
letters to the Transportation Department, though executives are
barred from asking the politicians to lobby Clinton administration
officials more directly. Hundreds of mayors, governors and members
of Congress have weighed in, breaking down along predictable
geographic lines. Richard Daley, the mayor of Chicago and brother
of Vice President Al Gore's campaign chairman, backs American. Sen.
Charles Schumer, D-New York, supports Delta. For either city, a
victory would mean new jobs, more trade with China and increased
tax revenue.
</P>
<P>
   One of the New Yorkers' biggest advantages is the imbalance that
currently exists between the Midwest and East Coast. Detroit is
already the take-off point for all of Northwest's flights to China.
Once United makes its change, Chicago will have direct flights,
too.
</P>
<P>
   ``That makes American's bid redundant,'' said Jon F. Ask, the
managing director of Global Aviation Associates, a Washington
consulting firm not working for any of the applicants. Meanwhile,
no airline flies between the East Coast and China.
</P>
<P>
   American's executives and their Midwestern supporters respond
that Delta's flight would not actually help many eastern cities
other than New York. Delta flies from only 29 cities to Kennedy
Airport, about 60 fewer than American and its regional partner,
American Eagle, does at O'Hare. As a result, many passengers would
have to make two flights just to get Kennedy, the Chicago's
proponents say.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a resident of Syracuse might have to fly first to
Atlanta and then north to New York to catch Delta's flight to
China. In its filing, UPS argued that many people would instead
choose to fly Northwest through Detroit because it would be a
shorter trip. The congestion in the skies above New York does not
help Delta's case, either.
</P>
<P>
   The more fundamental decision facing Mims and his colleagues at
the Transportation Department, however, is whether they should
award the new route to a passenger airline or a cargo carrier.
Analysts say that decision is a close call.
</P>
<P>
   UPS's strongest argument is that it would become only the second
American shipper to fly to China, while two U.S.-based passenger
airlines do. The company is supported by Northwest and United,
which say they currently lose money on their flights to China.
``The market is terribly overserved,'' Gary Wilson, Northwest's
chairman, said. ``I know everybody views China as a great new
market, but it's been viewed as a great new market for 500 years.''
</P>
<P>
   UPS, however, already flies to Hong Kong, and Chinese partner
companies pick up and drop off packages there. According to an
Arthur Andersen study commissioned by American, that service allows
UPS and DHL, which also lacks direct service, to get packages to
the United States almost as fast as Federal Express.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Weidemeyer, UPS's chairman, said the carrier's broad
support, from politicians in every region in the country, indicate
that it has the best application. Even some members of the New York
House delegation listed by Delta on its Web site as supporters _
Rep. Louise Slaughter, a Democrat from Rochester, for example, _
actually back UPS, according to letters they have written. They say
Delta should receive the new rights only if the administration
decides to select a passenger airline.
</P>
<P>
   The Teamsters have also written letters on behalf of UPS and
with Gore looking to shore up the support of labor leaders angered
by his position on other trade issues, the union could be an
important voice. Even American and Delta acknowledge that UPS has
built the strongest lobbying effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``They do have, probably, a political advantage because of the
number of people they employ and because of the members of Congress
they've signed up,'' Bumpers said. ``They operate not only in every
state, but in every village of every state.''
</P>
<P>
   With all three airlines presenting strong cases, the decision,
in the end, is bound to be influenced by the White House and a host
of considerations particular to each option. American and Delta
officials hope that their backers _ in Chicago and New York
respectively _ will cancel out some of UPS's support, and that the
administration will decide new passenger service is simply more
important.
</P>
<P>
   But only one airline will can win the Chinese routes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing wrong with UPS's proposal or Delta's,'' said
Ris, the lobbyist for American. ``The real problem is that we have
been able to negotiate only one new carrier with China.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
