u p BC-BUSH-NAACP-COX     07-10 0940
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-NAACP-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush gets lukewarm reception at NAACP event
 &HT;    By Jena Heath
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Gov. George W. Bush took his brand of racial
inclusiveness to the NAACP's 91st annual convention Monday, where
he acknowledged the lingering effects of racism and pledged to make
civil rights enforcement a ``cornerstone'' of his administration
should he win the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Bush received a polite_ at moments even warm _ reception from
the nation's largest civil rights group whose members have
traditionally voted Democratic in overwhelming numbers. The
500,000-member National Association for the Advancement of Colored
People is working to register 4 million voters this year.
</P>
<P>
   Bush got his most enthusiastic response when he acknowledged the
frosty relations between the NAACP and the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   ``I recognize that the history of the Republican party and the
NAACP has not been one of regular partnership,'' he said to rousing
applause. ``But our nation is harmed when we let our differences
separate us and divide us. So while some in my party have avoided
the NAACP, and while some in the NAACP have avoided my party, I'm
proud to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, he said: ``For my party, there's no escaping the reality
that the Party of Lincoln has not always carried the mantle of
Lincoln.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush offered no new proposals to strengthen race relations.
Instead, he discussed previously unveiled initiatives, including
ways to help low income people buy homes and allowing parents whose
children attend failing schools to use taxpayer money for private
education. He dubbed these and other ideas his, ``New Prosperity
Initiative.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bush's appearance in Baltimore, home to the NAACP's national
office, was as much about symbolism as it was about substance. In
recent weeks, Bush has been shoring up his, ``compassionate
conservative'' credentials, appearing before two Latino groups _
the League of United Latin American Citizens and the National
Council of La Raza _ and the conservative, African American
Congress on Racial Equality.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is seeking to recapture the moderate mantle he wore before
his speech at South Carolina's Bob Jones University, a
fundamentalist institution that, at the time, banned interracial
dating and has an anti-Catholic philosophy. Bush also angered many
African Americans when he refused to enter the fray over removing
the Confederate flag from the South Carolina statehouse.
</P>
<P>
   Former Maryland legislator Clarence Mitchell III said Bush
deserves credit for his appearance Monday. Mitchell, a former
president of the National Black Caucus of State Legislators whose
family is a Maryland political dynasty, said he believes Bush can
win over a sizeable number of African American voters.
</P>
<P>
   Exit polls showed Bush winning 15 percent of African-Americans'
votes in Texas in 1994. He nearly doubled that, to 27 percent, in
his 1998 re-election.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he gets a lot of points for showing up, for being
here,'' Mitchell said. ``I think he gets further points for what he
said. I mean he's opened the door. He wasn't specific. Nobody was
looking for specifics, but he talked in generalities about those
issues that have caused many people, including myself, to want to
know more.''
</P>
<P>
   Saying that, ``we cannot afford to have an America segregated by
class, by race or by aspiration,'' Bush spoke at length about his
education proposals, asserting that high standards and local
control is the formula to improve education across racial lines.
</P>
<P>
   He also pledged to, ``lift regulations that hamper private and
faith-based programs,'' and suggested offering grants to mentoring
programs and ministries that work with children whose parents are
in prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not calling for government to step back from its
responsibilities, but to share in them,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's remarks were interrupted early on by death penalty
protestors who held signs that said, ``Abolish the Racist Death
Penalty'' and ``George Bush Executed Gary Graham (aka Shaka
Sankoba) An Innocent Man.'' Chanting, ``Remember Gary Graham,'' the
handful of protestors were ushered out of the massive room at the
Baltimore Convention Center after Frank Humphrey, a member of the
NAACP's national board of directors, exhorted them to, ``put down
the signs and take your seats.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also garnered criticism from U.S. Rep. Eddie Bernice
Johnson, D-Dallas, who held a press conference along with state
Rep. Senfronia Thompson, D-Houston, and others to criticize Bush's
record in Texas. Johnson criticized Bush for coining the phrase
compassionate conservative even as he failed to help pass a
hate-crime law in Texas last year.
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Holmes Norton, a Democrat and District of Columbia
delegate, also blasted Bush for failing to talk about the death
penalty and other issues, such as social security, prescription
drugs and how he would approach nominating candidates for at least
three anticipated openings on the Supreme Court. Norton said Bush
needs to do more than show up before minority audiences. He needs
to talk issues and specifics, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He essentially expected us to give him points for coming,''
she said. ``What (Bush) fails to understand is how issue-oriented
the NAACP and African-Americans are. They really take names and
keep score.''
</P>
<P>
   You may contact Jena Heath at jenah(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
