<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 20:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8388 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-NYT &LR;      07-10 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPECTATIONS DIMMED FOR CAMP DAVID PEACE TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (With: MIDEAST-ISRAEL and MIDEAST-ISSUES)  
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Stunned by the political drama in Israel, the
Clinton administration tried Monday to put the best face on
prospects for the Camp David summit despite the weakened position
of Prime Minister Ehud Barak, saying that he still had sufficient
popular support to reach an agreement with the Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat and sell it back home.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who called the Camp David summit meeting after a series
of requests by Barak, praised both Arafat and Barak as leaders who
had the ``vision, the knowledge, the experience and the ability and
the sheer guts to do what it takes.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the administration had not anticipated that Barak would
arrive for the opening of the summit meeting Tuesday dependent for
his political survival on the parliamentary votes of Communist and
Arab parties. There was also surprise among officials here that
Barak's foreign minister, David Levy, apparently piqued at not
being included in the prime minister's inner circle, refused to
come.
</P>
<P>
   The slide in Barak's political fortunes took place as
administration officials were packing their bags for the trip to
Camp David and environs. Some officials were adding last-minute
touches to talking points as the no-confidence vote unfolded in the
Israeli parliament. Much of the State Department's press operations
moved to the second-grade classroom at Thurmont Elementary School
in Thurmont, a town on the edge of Camp David, where the
administration will brief the press on small snippets of
nonsubstantive information.
</P>
<P>
   There were preparations, too, to welcome Barak and Arafat and
their teams of negotiators, limited to about 12 on each side. Barak
was accompanied, among others, by his chief negotiators, Shlomo
Ben-Ami, a popular Labor Party politician.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat headed for Washington with a team representing a wide
spectrum of the Palestinian Authority's political thinking. His
chief negotiator is Abu Ala, the head of the Palestinian assembly
in Ramallah and a veteran from the secret 1993 Oslo proceedings
that set the stage for this Camp David summit.
</P>
<P>
   But almost all the focus Monday was on Barak, who was widely
referred to as a top-flight soldier but a less than top-flight
politician.
</P>
<P>
   Describing the reaction to Barak's tumultuous day in Jerusalem,
one official said, ``This was like lightning on a clear day.''
</P>
<P>
   But turning a seeming negative into a positive, a senior
administration official argued that Barak's predicament
``underscored that the prime minister is willing to take the
political heat for moving forward.''
</P>
<P>
   This in turn would enable Clinton to persuade Arafat that the
prime minister was the ``best'' Israeli leader with whom to deal
because few politicians would be willing to risk their positions
and offer such compromises as Barak, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   In pushing aside the perception of the prime minister's weakness
as he arrived _ an expected 12 hours later than planned because of
the no-confidence vote _ the senior official said that the White
House was unchanged in its view that Barak had the resolve to
complete an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said Monday morning that
Barak enjoyed the support of more than 55 percent of Israelis and
hence would be able to go to the people with an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   But Israeli opinion surveys were quite fickle, an administration
official said, adding that it was a thin reed to hang the future of
an agreement, yet to be negotiated, on polling.
</P>
<P>
   Among diplomats in the region and Middle East experts, there
appeared to be a consensus that the chances for a overall end of
conflict agreement had diminished.
</P>
<P>
   One experienced diplomat in the region said that Barak would
have to fight for the toughest terms he could because any agreement
would be portrayed as a sell-out by the right wing in Israel. At
the same time, Arafat, this diplomat said, would see that the
Israeli leader was ``desperate'' for an accord and would, in turn,
toughen his conditions.
</P>
<P>
   The administration has left itself various possibilities for
claiming success. In announcing the summit last week, Clinton said
that he wanted an agreement on the ``core issues'' that had fueled
the Israeli-Palestinian conflict for more than 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   But he also set a slightly lesser goal, saying that the summit
would be where the two leaders would ``start drawing the contours
of the long-awaited peace,'' a phrase that seemed to indicate an
agreement on some general principles might also be enough.
</P>
<P>
   The collapse of Barak's coalition spurred a serious divisions
within the American Jewish community. One group of American Jewish
leaders, including Leon Levy, a past chairman of the Conference of
Presidents of Major American Jewish Organizations, criticized Barak
for preparing to give what it called lop-sided concessions to
Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   Another group of 315 leaders, including four past chairmen of
the Conference of Presidents, signed a letter Monday saying that
``the overwhelming majority of American Jews and indeed all
Americans support Israel's peace initiative.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-00 2046EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000710.0384 </DOCNO>
