<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 20:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8392 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-FBN-NFL-LEDE-COX     07-10 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-LEDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For the Redskins, high payroll means the future is now
 &HT;    By Ken Sugiura
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Daniel Snyder dropped out of college to start his own
business. At age 31, he became the youngest CEO of a company traded
on the New York Stock Exchange. At 35, he sold his Snyder
Communications company for $2.07 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder's motto isn't ``slow and steady wins the race.'' In May
1999, he dropped $800 million for the Washington Redskins and what
was then Jack Kent Cooke Stadium, now FedEx Field.
</P>
<P>
   So it raised few eyebrows when the Redskins did a cannonball
into this offseason's free-agent pool.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL's 30 teams have a number of philosophies on reaching the
top. In Snyder's first full offseason as owner, the Redskins made
clear their method of business.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears winning right now is very important to them,''
Tennessee Titans general manager Floyd Reese said.
</P>
<P>
   Redskins player personnel director Vinny Cerrato said, ``The
reason you're in the NFL is to win the Super Bowl, and that's what
we're trying to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Rarely, though, has a team tried to win it before training camp.
Washington signed a slew of veteran players to a vault's worth of
contracts. The Redskins snagged the biggest name on the market,
cornerback Deion Sanders, late of the Cowboys, to a seven-year, $56
million contract with a signing bonus of $8 million.
</P>
<P>
   They have been called risky, foolish and short-sighted. They are
being criticized for finagling the salary cap and imperiling their
future. But if the Redskins end up hoisting the Vince Lombardi
Trophy in January, they will be the envy of the league.
</P>
<P>
   Falcons coach Dan Reeves still calls the Super Bowl champion
Rams the team to beat. But Reeves also said, ``It'll be interesting
to see.''
</P>
<P>
   On paper, it's a great collection of names. Defensive end Bruce
Smith, signed from the Buffalo Bills, is a future Hall of Famer.
Safety Mark Carrier has 31 career interceptions and is a three-time
Pro Bowler. Quarterback Jeff George, whisked away from the Vikings,
last year threw for 2,816 yards and 23 touchdowns in only 12 games
_ and he's the backup.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Redskins still have to play the 16-game schedule.
Sanders, because of injuries or his now-complete dalliance with
baseball, has played a full 16-game season only twice. Carrier,
Sanders and George all are 32 and much closer to the end of their
careers than the start. Smith, 37, is older than the owner.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody knows how the parts will fit together. The Redskins only
have to look back to the 1998 season, when they obtained two of the
highest-priced defensive linemen in the league, Dan Wilkinson and
Dana Stubblefield and raised expectations the way they are doing
now. Washington flopped its way to a 6-10 record.
</P>
<P>
   ``You lose six or eight players (each season and) sign six or
eight,'' Reeves said, ``and you don't know what's going to
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Further, the age of Sanders and his free-agent cohorts, not to
mention their big salaries scraping the salary cap ceiling like a
helium balloon, lead some to think that the Redskins have a very
narrow window of opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt you can't give a 32-year-old guy an
eight-year contract and not feel the repercussions of that at some
point,'' Titans GM Reese said.
</P>
<P>
   Cerrato, though, isn't concerned. So long as a top quarterback
is in place, a team will be competitive, he said. The Redskins have
two of them, George and Brad Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers kept their dynasty alive largely because Joe Montana,
who will make the Hall of Fame later this month, was succeeded by
Steve Young, who will join him five years from now. Now that Jeff
Garcia is replacing the retired Young, 49ers' number finally might
be up.
</P>
<P>
   The scarcity of star quarterbacks and the limitations of the
salary cap have turned the peak of the football world into a
slippery place.
</P>
<P>
   Which, perhaps, makes Snyder's win-it-now ambition all the more
logical, and certainly more fun to watch. It would have been easy
to stick with what the Redskins had. They won the NFC East and
drafted Penn State linebacker LaVar Arrington and Alabama offensive
tackle Chris Samuels with the second and third picks in the draft,
respectively. They could have settled for one or two free agents.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Snyder is forcing the action. The Redskins all-star
team will win the Super Bowl or go broke trying.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't have a better person to work for,'' Cerrato said.
</P>
<P>
   The 35-year-old multimillionaire has at least one more admirer
in the football biz.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing you like in our business,'' Reese said, ``you like
somebody that puts together a plan, understands what they're living
with and goes out and does it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-00 2049EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
