u f BC-WARNER-AOL-BOARDS-COX     07-10 0365
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARNER-AOL-BOARDS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Boards of AOL, Time Warner to huddle
 &HT;    By Matt Kempner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Some of today's power hitting at Turner Field won't be
at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   The boards and top executives of both America Online and Time
Warner are in Atlanta to talk about how their businesses will look
after they merge.
</P>
<P>
   While in town, they will be at the stadium named for Time
Warner's vice chairman, watching the All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   The management teams of the two companies have had lots of
meetings to hash out what the new AOL Time Warner will look like.
But this will be the first meeting of both full boards since merger
plans were announced in January.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner declined to comment on specific issues that will be
on the agenda.
</P>
<P>
   For several years, Time Warner's top management has held annual
planning retreats with the company's board.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year,'' company spokesman Ed Adler said, ``part of the
planning will be the planning for post-merger.''
</P>
<P>
   It's likely that board members from both companies will be
briefed on ideas for how AOL and Time Warner businesses can work
together.
</P>
<P>
   Lots of issues have to be worked out as the companies intertwine
AOL's Internet power with Time Warner's print and TV holdings _
including its Atlanta-based Turner Broadcasting System.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a ton of different ways they can develop
synergies,'' said analyst Tom Wolzien, of Sanford C. Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   The merger needs federal regulatory approval, but executives
continue to predict they will complete the deal this fall.
Shareholders approved the merger in separate votes last month.
</P>
<P>
   The new company would have a 16-member board with eight members
designated by AOL and eight by Time Warner. Ted Turner, Time
Warner's vice chairman, would be co-vice chairman of the new board.
</P>
<P>
   Wolzien said the companies might want to solidify ownership of
some Time Warner holdings. For example, 25 percent of HBO is owned
indirectly by AT&AMP;T, and one option might be to buy AT&AMP;T's interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can untangle some of those things,'' Wolzien said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-00 2049EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
