u f BC-CLINTON-OIL-NYT &LR;      07-10 0660
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-OIL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUEL RESERVE ESTABLISHED TO RESTRAIN HEATING OIL PRICES 
</HEADLINE>
   By NEELA BANERJEE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
  Reacting to widespread concern over climbing heating oil prices
and low inventories, President Clinton announced a plan Monday to
establish a 2-million-barrel fuel reserve for the Northeast, where
most of the country's heating oil is consumed.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The plan calls for swapping crude oil from the federal
government's 570-million-barrel strategic petroleum reserve for
heating oil from refineries or marketers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winter may seem far off on this hot day, but if we don't do
something now, reserve stocks of heating oil may not be in place
before the cold weather comes,'' Clinton said. ``The action I take
today will leave us far better prepared to face the winter months,
but it does not relieve Congress of the responsibility to act.''
</P>
<P>
   But some analysts and politicians portrayed the plans to create
a reserve as a symbolic gesture that might temporarily placate
consumers but would not be enough to reverse spiraling prices nor
compensate for a nationwide shortfall in heating oil inventories.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a good first step, but we have a
36-million-barrel shortfall in heating oil,'' said Sen. Charles
Schumer, D-N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could prevent the worst of the price spikes, but it won't
be large enough to deal with the root problem of a supply shortfall
and high demand.''
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally in the summer refineries begin to stockpile
distillate, which includes heating oil and diesel. But thriving
United States companies have been shipping a prodigious amount of
goods around the country, which has led to uncharacteristically
high demand for diesel.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, there are only 103.7 million barrels of distillate
fuel oil stockpiled so far, compared with 137.3 million barrels at
the same time last year, according to the U.S. Energy Information
Administration. In the Northeast, this year's stockpiles are off by
a similar margin.
</P>
<P>
   Low inventories, in turn, have driven heating oil prices up 10
percent in the last month alone. The fear is the prices will
continue to rise and that the Northeast may suffer a repeat of last
winter's troubles, when a heating oil shortage led to a doubling in
fuel prices.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials said that the Defense Energy Supply
Center, a Defense Department unit responsible for military fuel
procurement, will begin seeking offers in about two weeks from
refiners in exchange for the strategic petroleum reserve crude. The
administration said it would try to have the heating oil reserve in
place by October.
</P>
<P>
   But it is uncertain what kind of events or price levels would
lead to the release of the fuel. The administration and Congress
would have to come up with explicit guidelines for a so-called
trigger to distribute the heating oil, which could turn into a
tug-of-war because of impending elections. The government would
also have to trade more than two million barrels of crude to get
the heating oil, because the heating oil costs more than the crude
being offered, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials were also vague about steps the government
could take to soften the blow an even greater number of consumers
will feel this winter from high natural gas prices, which has
doubled from levels a year ago because of higher-than-usual demand.
</P>
<P>
   The administration is trying to persuade Congress to pass an oil
and gas production tax break to increase natural gas supplies. But
even if the administration succeeded, consumers would not enjoy
lower prices until late winter.
</P>
<P>
   The only bit of consolation for consumers came from a decline in
crude oil prices, as the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries seemed to be softening toward Saudi Arabia's plan to
produce an additional 500,000 barrels a day. At the New York
Mercantile Exchange, the benchmark August crude closed at $29.69 a
barrel, down 59 cents from Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-00 2053EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
