<HEADER>
A8397 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-HOMEDEPOT-NYSE-COX     07-10 0501
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMEDEPOT-NYSE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Home Depot charms NYSE crowd
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Home Depot filled Wall Street with its raucous charm
Monday to celebrate the opening of the retailer's 1,000th store.
</P>
<P>
   With the smell of sawdust on the streets outside the New York
Stock Exchange, co-founder and Chief Executive Arthur Blank rang
the market's opening bell. Eleven store employees joined Blank on
the opening platform, along with co-founders Bernie Marcus and Ken
Langone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept asking, `Why me?' when I got picked to do this,'' said
Laura James, an employee at the Home Depot in Snellville. ``This is
awesome ... but things move really fast here,'' said James, who was
winded from a dash to the trading floor to see Blank make the first
ceremonial trade of the day.
</P>
<P>
   Beneath a 2,200-square-foot orange apron, a contingent of nearly
100 Home Depot employees went to work on Broad Street in front of
the NYSE. Pop music blared from loudspeakers as employees in
T-shirts and jeans showed Wall Street workers how to use drills and
sanders. Some passersby frowned and shook their heads at the
H-O-M-E D-E-P-O-T cheers, but most stopped for free aprons and
hats.
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot employees built three gazebos during the celebration.
They will be donated to New York parks.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got married, that was exciting... and when I had
grandchildren, that was exciting, but this is right up there with
all of those,'' said Ralph Armstrong, a Home Depot employee at the
South Attleboro, Mass., store. ``I stuck my head right between
Bernie's and Arthur's (on the bell platform).''
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time Home Depot rang the starting bell, a
ceremony reserved for dignitaries, initial public offerings and
company milestones. The last time Home Depot's co-founders gathered
at the stock exchange was when the company went public in 1981.
With just 16 stores at the time, investors were banking on the
retailer's potential more than its track record, Blank noted after
he left the trading floor Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot, which had sales of $38.4 billion last year, is now
one of the 40 most valuable companies trading on the NYSE, said
Dick Grasso, chairman of the exchange. ``Never in our history has a
company reached something like that in a 20-year time span,''
Grasso said.
</P>
<P>
   Stores opening this week in Mansfield, Ohio; Chicago Ridge,
Ill.; Harriman, N.Y.; and Passaic, N.J., will bring the company's
total to 1,000. With a store currently opening every 43 hours, it
will take Home Depot just over three years to open another 1,000
stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember feeling a sense of awe when we went (public), and
I've tried to keep a sense of humility,'' Blank said. ``This
morning, when I was driving up and I saw (our employees) and the
giant apron hanging outside, I felt a sense of pride _ not that I
was responsible for it so much but just that I was a part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
