<SLUG> BC-OKINAWA-CURFEW-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. IMPOSES CURFEW AND ALCOHOL BAN ON MILITARY ON OKINAWA 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: SUBS 6th graf, The two ..., to correct to Group of 8, sted
seven.) 
By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ In a concession to local concerns about the behavior of
American soldiers stationed in Okinawa, the U.S. military has
indefinitely banned the drinking of alcoholic beverages between
midnight and 5 a.m. and prohibited its personnel from leaving their
bases during those hours.
</P>
<P>
   The curfew was imposed after a hit-and-run accident involving a
staff sergeant stationed at the U.S. Air Force's Kadena Air Base
early Sunday morning. A pedestrian was injured in the accident and
the sergeant was later caught. The authorities investigating the
accident said it appeared that alcohol was involved.
</P>
<P>
   This latest incident follows an apology from the highest-ranking
U.S. military official in Okinawa after a Marine was arrested last
week for allegedly entering a house and molesting a 14-year-old
girl in her bed while she was sleeping.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal of this policy is to enhance discipline among service
members and prevent the recurrence of liberty incidents,'' the
military said in a statement Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese officials have asked the military to take steps to
address the problem of crimes committed by its servicemen, an issue
that has long bedeviled relations between local residents and the
government of the prefecture and between the prefecture and the
central government. ``The fact that another incident of this sort
has occurred at a time when we were already seeking tighter
official discipline is regrettable,'' said the chief cabinet
secretary, Hidenao Nakagawa, during a regularly scheduled news
conference.
</P>
<P>
   The two most recent alleged crimes occurred at a particularly
sensitive time for the Japanese government, which is doing its
utmost to ensure that the Group of 8 summit meeting of world
leaders scheduled for July 21-23 in Okinawa will come off without a
hitch.
</P>
<P>
   Police forces around the country have been staging drills in
preparation for any trouble that might occur, and the national
government has been working feverishly to end a dispute with the
U.S. trade representative over charges imposed by the dominant
telephone carrier.
</P>
<P>
   The incidents have also embarrassed the United States. President
Clinton's participation in the summit meeting will be the first
visit by an American president since the United States returned
Okinawa to Japan in 1972. Last week, Japan was treated to the sight
of Lt. Gen. Earl B. Hailston of the U.S. Marine Corps, the
highest-ranking American officer here, bowing deeply to the
prefecture's governor in a striking display of contrition.
</P>
<P>
   About 26,000 of the 48,000 American military personnel in Japan
are stationed in Okinawa, 1,000 southeast of Tokyo, and residents
of the island have long complained that they are unfairly burdened
with the social and economic costs of the U.S. presence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
