A8404 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-ALLSTARS-NYT &LR;      07-10 0590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ALLSTARS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNKEMPT WELLS LOOKS LIKE A WINNER ON THE MOUND
</HEADLINE>
  By JACK CURRY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The monumental trade between the Yankees and the Blue
Jays took place 17 months ago, when Roger Clemens came to New York
for David Wells and two other players. The Yankees obtained a
five-time Cy Young award winner who won the decisive game of the
1999 World Series and Toronto got a rebellious pitcher who has
actually become heftier.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, there is no disputing the notion that Toronto got the best
of a trade that brought them Wells, Homer Bush and Graeme Lloyd.
The deal was really about Wells and Clemens, and Wells could be
gloating because he is 15-2 this year and was selected by Joe
Torre, his former manager, to start the All-Star Game on Tuesday
night. The National League starter will be Randy Johnson, who is
14-2 with a 1.80 earned run average and 198 strikeouts in 144 and
two-thirds innings.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens did not make the team for the second straight year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't my decision to trade me,'' Wells said. ``Obviously,
they thought it made sense to trade me. You move on. I don't hold
any grudges.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the trade, Wells is 32-12 and Clemens is 20-16. Because
the Yankees won another World Series, they could argue that the
deal was successful because the team achieved its goal. But George
Steinbrenner would surely choose Wells over Clemens if he could
make another trade. Especially since the Yankees' principal owner
has an agreement with Clemens for a two-year extension worth about
$27 million.
</P>
<P>
   When Wells was asked if he was better than Clemens, he smirked
and said: ``I don't worry about it. I move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells has a head that is balder than Mr. Clean and a scraggly
goatee that looks like a thorn bush. He wears a uniform jersey that
could serve as a tent for a few toddlers and pants that are baggy
enough to hold watermelons. But, for all of the attention Wells
receives for his eccentricities, he also has a rubber arm, amazing
control and a passion for winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``He might not be the best dressed pitcher,'' Torre said, ``but
he might be the best pitcher.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if Pedro Martinez, last season's Cy Young award winner, had
been healthy enough to pitch in the game, Torre said he would still
have chosen Wells as the starter because ``you can't count out 15
wins.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells, who has constantly deflected questions about Clemens and
the Yankees, said it would have been unfair to the Blue Jays for
him to pine for New York after a deal that depressed him. Someone
mentioned that the Yankees unloaded Wells to get Clemens, but also
because they were worried Wells would fizzle.
</P>
<P>
   With a bow to the children in attendance, Wells called that
``hog wash.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's a point to prove at any time,'' Wells
said. ``I know what I can do. Right now, I could strangle Joe if I
wanted to.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre, who sat beside Wells on a podium, said, ``Maybe that
would slow you down.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells said it took three days for him to get over the sting of
being traded, a bold declaration because David Cone expressed how
distraught Wells was at the time. Now Wells is with the Blue Jays
and they are tied for first place with the Yankees, mostly because
of a lopsided trade that seemed logical when it was made.
</P>
<P>
   ``When things happen like that, you have to think of it as a
business,'' Wells said. ``New York is where I wanted to play. I
wanted to finish my career there. They traded for Roger Clemens.
You can't cry about it. Life goes on.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-00 2100EDT &QL; 
