<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8409 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-CLANCY-CHARITY-1STLD-     07-10 1267
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLANCY-CHARITY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-860&AMP;ADD(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTHOR'S DREAM TO HELP ILL CHILDREN TURNS INTO LEGAL NIGHTMARE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Colo., Calif., Md.)   (SUBS to change ``was recently convicted of'' to ``is to be
sentenced on Friday for'' in 2nd-to-last graf of first take, and to
rewrite 19th graf of 2nd take, bgng: Gorshow, in her...)  
(ART ADV: Photo NYT 5 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By MICHAEL MOSS and JIM RUTENBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1992, author Tom Clancy embarked on a philanthropic mission
worthy of Jack Ryan, the idealistic hero of his popular
techno-thrillers.
</P>
<P>
   Clancy wanted to help children who had cancer and other grave
illnesses use the nascent technology of the Internet to talk with
one another and learn about their diseases.
</P>
<P>
   The children's health network he imagined would also enable
parents to search out the best doctors, no matter how disadvantaged
or isolated the family might be. And it would let doctors tap into
the same worldwide database to share their expertise and find the
latest research.
</P>
<P>
   Clancy's inspiration was a 6-year-old Long Island, N.Y., boy,
Kyle Haydock, who sent him a fan letter while the boy lay in his
bed at Memorial Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center in New York City,
ravaged by sarcoma. At the height of his fame, Clancy fell hard for
Kyle and befriended him. He showered the boy with gifts, visited
his hospital room and even wheeled him around Disney World. ``This
little guy was a fighter,'' he later wrote in an essay.
</P>
<P>
   After Kyle died in 1991, Clancy set up a foundation and named it
for the boy. He donated more than $4 million from his fortune and
committed one-third of the proceeds from his next Jack Ryan movie,
according to his lawyer and foundation records.
</P>
<P>
   Clancy also used his fame and political connections to persuade
others to donate several million dollars more in cash and services.
The captains of powerful companies like Viacom joined the
foundation's board, as did big-name friends like the actor Tom
Selleck.
</P>
<P>
   But seven years later, Clancy is scuttling the Kyle Foundation,
which despite having spent more than $5 million on travel,
salaries, fund raising and furniture did not even have a Web site
to show for its efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The demise of one of the nation's more than 700,000 charities
typically unfolds without public scrutiny. Nameplates are removed
from doors, checking accounts are closed, and the directors move on
without comment. But the legal mud fight that has broken out in a
Denver courtroom over the failure of the Kyle Foundation offers a
rare glimpse at the inner workings of a celebrity charity.
</P>
<P>
   What went wrong is a matter of heated dispute. Clancy, in court
papers, accuses the woman he hired to run the foundation of
mismanagement and improper expenditures. She vehemently denies that
accusation and says Clancy killed off the project at the very
moment it was about to succeed.
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual step, the IRS is examining the charity's financial
records to decide whether to revoke its tax-deductible status.
Donors would have to pay back taxes on their gifts if they had
reason to know the foundation was not performing its mission.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS, Clancy has said in a letter to the foundation's board,
is ``citing long delay in product rollout, limited charitable work
to date, high foundation expenses for salaries, travel and fund
raising.''
</P>
<P>
   Friends and associates say they do not blame Clancy for
undertaking what they see as a visionary project. Several, however,
faulted him for failing to keep a closer eye on a venture whose
success hinged on the deft use of an infant technology.
</P>
<P>
   A board member who ran a $29 billion computer company said he
twice told Clancy in 1997 that the foundation was floundering and
that its management was weak.
</P>
<P>
   The 53-year-old writer, who is completing his 11th novel,
brushed aside such warnings and did not act until last summer, when
he dispatched an accountant and then a retired Navy vice admiral to
take a closer look at the operation, board members said.
</P>
<P>
   Their reports in hand, Clancy sprang into action.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 11, a Friday morning, he summoned the foundation's
executive director, Katherine Gorshow, to his Maryland home and
demanded that she resign, according to court papers. Then, before
she could fly back to its offices in Englewood, Colo., he sent a
team of former agents from the FBI to secure the premises and
change the locks.
</P>
<P>
   It was an abrupt ending to a partnership that grew from a chance
meeting on the Internet to Gorshow's participation last year as
bridesmaid in Clancy's wedding.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Gorshow is suing the foundation, accusing it of breach of
contract in a state court in Denver, saying in court papers that
she had made ``significant progress'' toward taking the health
network online later this year. Indeed, new backers of the
foundation, including Sybase Inc., a software company, continue to
express enthusiastic support for the project.
</P>
<P>
   Clancy replied in court filings this month that Gorshow misused
foundation money for private purposes, including personal travel.
Gorshow denied the accusations through her lawyers. Clancy declined
to be interviewed for this article, saying, ``I'm gagged.''
</P>
<P>
   Kyle's mother, Eileen Haydock, of Baldwin, N.Y., said she began
having doubts about the foundation several years ago and
discouraged her friends from contributing. Still, Haydock said she
had nothing but admiration for Clancy and his efforts to honor her
son and help sick children. ``I think he felt that he had let down
my son,'' she said, ``and that's not true.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   There was little about Clancy's life that prepared him for
starting a multimillion-dollar foundation. He majored in English at
Loyola College in Baltimore, then sold insurance to tobacco and
corn farmers on the Chesapeake Bay.
</P>
<P>
   The unexpected success in 1985 of his first novel, ``The Hunt
for Red October,'' began a lucrative career that led to a string of
best-selling novels and popular movies made from them.
</P>
<P>
   His financial empire grew to include more than a dozen
businesses that have produced not only his major books like
``Patriot Games'' and ``Clear and Present Danger,'' but also
videogames, military manuals and serial novels written with others.
He bought a share of the Baltimore Orioles baseball team, and under
his latest deal with Putnam Publishing he earns $19 million for
each novel completed, according to court records.
</P>
<P>
   Associates say Clancy's considerable fortune has attracted
people with a host of causes and offbeat investment opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a very, very trusting man,'' said Diana Patin, Clancy's
former, longtime secretary. ``He accepted people as they put
themselves to him.''
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1990s, Clancy and his first wife, Wanda, lost $1.3
million to a coin dealer who is to be sentenced on Friday for
defrauding them and dozens of other Maryland residents. In 1996,
Clancy put $1 million into a company building a space vehicle that
uses a propeller to land like a helicopter. The company has since
scaled back its operations because of a lack of money.
</P>
<P>
   And, more recently, Clancy has helped a former CIA operative
turned cartoonist, Chip Beck, finance his investigation into
whether the U.S. government abandoned some of its troops taken
prisoner in wars fought this century. ``He gives people the chance
to prove themselves,'' Beck said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Clancy had become a fixture on the best-seller list by 1990 when
Kyle caught his attention. The boy's grandfather had read him
Clancy's first novel, and then he ``just about memorized'' a video
of the resulting movie, Clancy wrote in an essay encouraging others
to befriend a sick child. ``Each of them, however ill, is alive and
needful of the same things that we all need: love, friendship,
conversation,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   One of his first acts after creating the Kyle Foundation was to
hire Gorshow, whom he had met online in a discussion group run by
America Online, where she was a volunteer. He had a computer
glitch; she had the solution.
</P>
<P>
   Gorshow had been a college instructor and school administrator,
and she owned a mail-order, bulk-food distribution concern.
</P>
<P>
   In a chronology filed in Denver District Court, Gorshow
describes the foundation, in her first three years with it, as a
shoestring operation run from her home in Oroville, Calif., and
dogged by false starts. But by 1996, her starting salary of $43,000
had risen to $120,000, and fund raising took off when Clancy signed
a pledge to give $5 million in 10 installments, as well as the
future Jack Ryan movie proceeds.
</P>
<P>
   Clancy's enthusiasm for the project helped attract other big
gifts, including $1 million from Viacom, and $750,000 from Lew
Wasserman, the founder of MCA, and the MCA foundation. Aboard a
110-foot yacht off the coast of Vancouver, British Columbia, Clancy
secured $100,000 from John McCaw, cofounder of McCaw Cellular.
</P>
<P>
   While most of the money appears to have come from his
well-heeled friends, Clancy did use his fame to reach out to the
public as well. In November 1997 he appeared on ``Jeopardy,'' where
he announced he would donate his $10,000 consolation prize to the
foundation.
</P>
<P>
   But there were bumps on the implementation side. As the
foundation's executive director, Gorshow said she labored at a wide
range of activities _from securing an Internet address for the Web
site to building a prototype database of information about
pediatric oncology, which involved hiring college students to
translate some foreign-language documents.
</P>
<P>
   One major endeavor turned into a dead end. The foundation had
wanted to put computers in the homes and hospital rooms of sick
children. Gorshow said she discovered that other charities were
trying to do the same thing, and that pilot projects had turned up
a concern: There was not enough time to teach very ill children how
to use the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Other aspects of the original concept fell by the wayside,
including the notion of having cartoon characters answer questions
from children. But even the basic mission _ building a one-stop
directory to a million or so places to get health information _
began to seem elusive to the board.
</P>
<P>
   David R. Dukes, then the co-chairman of Ingram Micro, the
nation's largest wholesale distributor of computers, said he became
so convinced the foundation would not succeed that he resigned from
the board in mid-1997, rather than help the foundation raise more
money.
</P>
<P>
   Dukes said he told Clancy _ in person and later on the phone _
that with Gorshow as the foundation's leader, ``it became clear
this thing would not be able to go forward the way that it ought
to.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But, back at the time,'' Dukes said, ``I think, he was still
very enamored with her, and I'm not sure he wanted to hear that.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Kyle's mother was mystified. She said the foundation did
not respond to her e-mail messages inquiring about its progress,
and that it had become such a puzzle to her that she suggested that
friends seeking to honor Kyle donate to other charities.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Clancy's personal life began intersecting with the
foundation in unusual ways. When he ended a 1995 affair with a
woman he met online, the Manhattan penthouse they had shared was
cleared out by Gorshow and the foundation's director of operations,
according to foundation records.
</P>
<P>
   Three years later, another woman he met online unsuccessfully
sued him for breaking off their engagement. She then alerted
federal and state officials in California to possible mismanagement
of foundation funds, the officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, Clancy's new wife, Alexandra Llewellyn, began
raising her own concerns about the foundation, prompting him to
send her family's accountant to examine the books, an associate of
Clancy said.
</P>
<P>
   The accountant delivered his report in February. Clancy, in his
Feb. 24 letter to the board, listed some of its highlights:
$636,628 spent on travel through 1998, $700,000 on consultants and
$100,154 on a one-time payout last year to Gorshow for accrued
vacation and sick pay.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation, the accountant discovered, had been fined
$20,000 by the IRS for tardy filing of its 1997 tax returns.
</P>
<P>
   Gorshow, in her letter to the board, defended the expenditures,
saying the travel was legitimate and the vacation pay stemmed from
concerns raised by the foundation's auditor.
</P>
<P>
   Clancy asked a retired vice admiral, William McCauley, to assess
whether it was worth putting more money into the Kyle Foundation.
McCauley said he concluded that other medical Web sites had
eclipsed Clancy's dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got co-opted,'' McCauley said.
</P>
<P>
   Others disagree. In January, Sybase had agreed to give the
foundation its novel Web site portal program and the services of
seven engineers to get it online, and as late as March the company
was formulating a commitment it valued at $1 million a year for as
long as a decade. At the same time, a design concern had come up
with a foundation logo and was midway through its $500,000
commitment to creating a Web site for the foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Internet venture experts say that despite the proliferation of
medical information sites in recent years, the idea behind the Kyle
Foundation remains not only viable, but potentially profitable as
well. ``There is definitely need and demand for this type of
project,'' said Deborah Buresh, a director at Shattuck Hammond
Partners, the health care investment-banking division of
PricewaterhouseCoopers Securities.
</P>
<P>
   About $700,000 in foundation money remains, and Clancy has come
up with a much simpler way to spend it. He now plans to endow a
pediatric oncology research chair at the Johns Hopkins University
School of Medicine, to be named after Kyle. Clancy entered into an
agreement with Johns Hopkins that calls for him to add to that sum
until it reaches $2 million over the next three years, the
institution said.
</P>
<P>
   No future movie proceeds are involved.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-00 2104EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000710.0401 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 21:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8414 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBO-ALLSTAR-ORGINS-CO     07-10 2258
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ALLSTAR-ORGINS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rawlings factory brings pride, promise
 &HT;    By Carlos Frias
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Turrialba, Costa Rica
</P>
<P>
   On this side of the Talamanca mountains, the city of San Jose
seems much farther than 46 miles. It seems especially far after the
2 1/2-hour drive up and down winding roads, circling cliffs
hundreds of feet above the verdant, checkerboard plantations.
</P>
<P>
   The drive into the heart of Turrialba is marked by the
occasional cow in the road and dozens of little villages _ La
Pastora, Pejibaye, Santa Terresita _ that exist in people's
vocabulary but not necessarily on road maps. As the city disappears
behind the mountainous horizon, car fumes are replaced by a
perfumed country air, a mixture of fragrances from the diverse
flora of Costa Rica's countryside and the rich, reddish-brown earth
in which virtually anything grows. Coffee. Sugar cane. Home runs.
</P>
<P>
   In this village of fewer than 30,000, east of San Jose and west
of nowhere, beats the heart of America's national pastime. Since
1990, a Rawlings factory on the edge of town has produced all of
the baseballs used in every major-league game, including tonight's
All-Star Game at Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   For this agricultural community, which survived quietly for more
than 100 years on the harvest of coffee and sugar cane, the
production of baseballs has become a source of identity and pride.
However, few claim to know much about the sport, despite the recent
international attention on whether the balls are juiced.
</P>
<P>
   Most important, the new source of employment injected new life
into a town slipping into extinction.
</P>
<P>
   A better life through baseballs
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you see here?''
</P>
<P>
   Marco Vinisio Rodriguez holds up one of the dozens of baseballs
he has stitched that Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The ball is as perfect as it can be at this point in the
process. The red laces hold the seams together tightly and cleanly.
Surely, this ball will end up in a major-leaguer's hands. Vinisio
Rodriguez has some of the finest hands in the factory. He has
refused to take any promotions over the past 11 years and has
chosen to continue stitching laces onto baseballs better and more
efficiently than any other of the 500 workers on the sewing floor
of the Rawlings factory. He has made more than 70 a day and more
than 200 a week.
</P>
<P>
   To any red-blooded American baseball fan, he is holding up the
crude form of what will become the perfect baseball. For Vinisio
Rodriguez, 28, and his workmates, it represents a steady paycheck
and the promise of a better life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, there are a lot of people that look at this and see an
education,'' he said, scanning his eyes over the ball, checking his
work. ``They see a new house. They see food on the table for
another day.''
</P>
<P>
   For Americans, the factory is important because it provides
every baseball used in major-league games and sold in stores. For
Turrialbenos, baseball represents a fountain of employment _ 950
jobs, at the moment _ for a town that once suffered one of the
highest levels of unemployment in the country. ``I ask myself,
`What would happen to those 950 employees if Rawlings wasn't
there?''' said Edgar Mata Dennis, a Turrialba native and the town's
mayor for thetor around town and catch up with buses that had left
them behind.
</P>
<P>
   However, the day a new, more direct road to the coast opened,
traffic through Turrialba all but stopped. Businesses closed.
Hotels emptied. Taxi drivers, like Jose Mata, were forced to find
other means. During the week, aching for passengers, he worked
double shifts, from 6 a.m. to about 1 a.m., and traveled about 45
minutes on the weekends to the next closest town of Cartago to wash
cars. Life became difficult for all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I slept very little. It was hard,'' said Mata, 44, a father of
two. ``Everybody was in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Desperate need for jobs
</P>
<P>
   For many people, the answer was jobs picking coffee beans and
harvesting sugar cane. Even those jobs were not enough to keep
everyone employed, as the prices for these staple crops dropped at
the most inopportune time. Vagrancy and crime increased in a small
town that prides itself on cleanliness and hospitality, a respite
from city life. Some chose to leave their families and walk as far
as 15 miles to work on plantations in other towns, returning to
visit their loved ones only on weekends.
</P>
<P>
   Turrialba was aching for a new source of jobs. Baseball was the
answer.
</P>
<P>
   As tedious and painstaking as stitching more than 200 baseballs
a week might seem to Americans, the alternatives are not good.
</P>
<P>
   For young men who must work to help support their large extended
families, the only previous options were the sugar cane and coffee
fields. Higher education often is not a possibility.
</P>
<P>
   Sugar cane might be the most arduous of crops to harvest. Its
season lasts from February to June, including a suffocating April,
the hottest month of the year in Turrialba, when the temperature
regularly exceeds the high 90s with 90 percent humidity. Before the
harvest, workers burn the leaves off the stalks, which leaves a
messy black soot all over the trees. Still, some of their wiry,
serrated edges remain, and they can slice through skin like paper
cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the sharpest machete, cutting down stalks of cane,
which can be 2-3 inches thick and as hard as bamboo, requires
considerable arm strength. Workers plod through the thick black
mud, hoping that the fire scared off most of the vipers and rats
that inhabit the brush. And it's almost a given that every day,
about 2 p.m., it's going to rain to make the job even more
difficult.
</P>
<P>
   It's a hot, sweaty, sticky, laborious task, and anyone who has
done it agrees that it is sure to shorten a man's life.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Manuel Jimenez Garcia, now 45, remembers creeping out of
his house before dawn on his way to work in the cane fields, past
his wife and eight sleeping children, knowing that he would not see
them until late that night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all grew up cutting cane,'' said Jimenez Garcia, now a
street sweeper in town. ``Anything is better than cutting sugar
cane. It's very hot, very exhausting. It's a hard way of life.''
</P>
<P>
   When Rawlings moved its baseball factory to Costa Rica in 1987
because of government instability in Haiti, Turrialbenos got
another option.
</P>
<P>
   People could get better wages stitching baseballs than they
could working in the fields, where money depends on how much coffee
you pick or how many pounds of cane you cut. And they would be in a
fan-cooled building, sheltered from the beating sun. Few homes or
businesses in Turrialba have air-conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   The stitchers, who undergo three months of paid training before
they move on to making major-league-quality balls, are paid on a
sliding scale, depending on how many balls they make. It includes
incentives after they pass certain marks. Rawlings asks that they
make at least 130 a week. Those who make 150 receive a free meal
ticket and can take Friday off. People in the 200-plus range not
only earn more per ball, but also a bus ticket. Together, they help
make more than 14,000 balls a day and about 2.4 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   A week's work could yield about 28,000 colones, which equals
about $91. Rent in Turrialba costs about $100 a month. Locals were
living a better, easier life, one that was more promising for their
children. The step up is allowing poor workers from bordering
countries, Hondurans and Nicaraguans, to take the lower-echelon
jobs such as working in the coffee and cane fields.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing worse for a community than having a large
portion of its people out of work,'' Mario Rojas said. ``That's
where crime and delinquency take hold.''
</P>
<P>
   Rojas' family has owned more than 2,000 acres of coffee and
sugar cane crops in the valley for the past 52 years. ``People have
to feed themselves,'' he said. ``That's been the most important
thing. (The factory) has been a fountain of employment.''
</P>
<P>
   Jimenez Garcia said two of his children work in the baseball
factory and go to school at night, like many other baseball factory
workers, and have visions of attending the University of Costa
Rica, which has a campus in Turrialba.
</P>
<P>
   His sons are ``really happy there,'' he said. ``It's a lot
better than cutting cane.''
</P>
<P>
   When the company first moved in and also was making low-grade
balls for Little League, people often were allowed to stitch the
balls at home. Until 1994, the company would install in their homes
its special spinning vises, which hold the balls in place while the
workers sew. The major-league balls still were made in the factory.
But many housewives, whose husbands worked in the fields, could
make extra money stitching at home. Those balls now are made in
China.
</P>
<P>
   Now, just as cutting cane had become part of everyone's
histories, so has sewing baseballs. Everyone either has worked in
the complex of beige buildings on the edge of town or knows someone
who has. Those from the area of Turrialba, known for years as
azuqueros, or sugar makers, are getting a new designation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be more accurate to call us boleros (ball makers),''
Vinisio Rodriguez said. ``Don't you think?''
</P>
<P>
   Sport slow to catch on
</P>
<P>
   Why would anyone wear pajama pants to play a sport?
</P>
<P>
   It's the first thing Jose Mata thought when his bosses at
Rawlings handed him a pair of baseball pants. As the company became
a greater part of its new community, it wanted to introduce the
sport that Turrialba is supporting.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, although Costa Rica is wedged between Nicaragua and
Panama, two big baseball countries, the sport has had its
challenges in a country where futbol is king.
</P>
<P>
   ``People laughed,'' Jose Mata said. ``They thought they looked
like pajamas. We have always liked futbol, basketball, volleyball.
But baseball? Nobody knew it. I had never seen it, even on
television.''
</P>
<P>
   In the country's largest newspaper, La Nacion, there are stories
on men's and women's soccer, basketball, volleyball, cycling, river
rafting, even chess, but no baseball. In the briefs, the sports
section rounds up events as far-reaching as Lenny Wilkens signing
to coach the Toronto Raptors. But the paper has no mention of the
major-league standings.
</P>
<P>
   In a factory that sponsors 10 soccer leagues, the plant
directors, Douglas and Diane Kralik, tried to get baseball off the
ground. This husband-and-wife team, former farmers from Iowa, grew
up with America's pastime and hoped Turrialba would accept the
sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't want to be just the gringos from the States that
were starting this for our kids,'' said Douglas, whose three
children went to private school in San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   Although more than 250 youngsters showed up for the practices
every Saturday, the lack of a baseball field and waning interest
doomed the effort. But if you can't beat 'em, sponsor 'em. Rawlings
became the official sponsor of the town's traveling soccer team,
the equivalent of a Triple-A minor-league team, which is hoping to
graduate to the big time.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball is putting down some roots, though, in that it is a
Generation-Y sport, the way soccer is booming with America's youth.
</P>
<P>
   Cesar Arrieta Solis, 23, whose grandfather worked the cane
fields in Turrialba, remembers helping his mother stitch baseballs
at home for fun. Now a student at the University of Costa Rica and
a certified English professor, he realizes that baseball has become
the sport of the next generation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before, futbol was what everyone talked about. But when Sammy
Sosa and Mark McGwire were chasing the (home-run) record, my
friends were always talking about it,'' he said. ``I would love
there to be (baseball) fields here so the kids could learn.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the controversy over juiced balls provided a little
excitement for the town. However, the University of
Massachussets-Lowell, commissioned by Major League Baseball, found
no significant differences between the balls used this year and
last year.
</P>
<P>
   More than fans, baseball has cultivated an industry in
Turrialba. It has helped create a new future and way of life for
Turrialbenos. Rawlings was the first factory to move into the area,
but it has been followed by the construction of an office park on
the other side of town, where ConAir has set up a hair dryer
factory. Others are set to follow, the mayor said.
</P>
<P>
   Because two major rivers run through the town _ the Reventazon
and Pacuare _ whitewater thrill-seekers have brought tourism back
to town, despite the long drive. Even a bed-and-breakfast-style
hotel, Casa Turire, built on the outskirts of Turrialba, is banking
on the revival of tourism.
</P>
<P>
   The town even could become the poster child for the IBM Internet
``Are you ready?'' commercials. The government post office built an
Internet computer center, where residents can check their e-mail or
browse the Web for free for 15 minutes a day or buy the equivalent
of phone cards.
</P>
<P>
   Although baseball is still a mystery to some, the people in this
once-quiet mountain town are thankful and proud of everything it
has done for them _ and for what they have done for baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Turrialba is definitely growing,'' said Ariel Mata, 18. He is
the taxi driver's oldest son and attends the Technical Institute of
Costa Rica three times a week in the neighboring city of Cartago;
he is 1 1/2 years from graduating with a degree in computer
science.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's changing,'' Ariel Mata said. ``I guess it is pretty
amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
