<SLUG> BC-APPLIED-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Applied Materials to unveil new chip production technology
 &HT;    By Bob Keefe
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ When it comes to semiconductors, smaller is
usually better _ except when it comes to making them, that is.
</P>
<P>
   For years, semiconductor makers have been inching toward a new
production process that would double the number of chips they could
produce on a single wafer _ the thin disks of silicon where
semiconductors get their start. But until now, they haven't had all
the equipment needed for mass production.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Applied Materials Inc. is expected to introduce the first
complete line of equipment to make chips on bigger and higher
capacity 300-millimeter silicon wafers, which could finally get the
chip industry on the fast track to building more efficient
factories.
</P>
<P>
   At the annual SEMICON West trade show that starts here today,
Applied Chairman and Chief Executive Jim Morgan plans to unveil his
company's new 21-piece line of equipment designed for
300-millimeter production.
</P>
<P>
   Equipment makers typically introduce new chip tools piece by
piece. But the move toward 300-millimeter technology is so
significant that Applied wanted to introduce a complete line all at
once, Morgan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one has ever done this before,'' he said. ``But (chip
makers) need the whole capability to build a 300-millimeter line,
so we had to bring all our products out at once.''
</P>
<P>
   Applied's move could be particularly significant in Austin,
Texas. In addition to being home to more domestic chip makers than
any other place outside than Silicon Valley, Austin is where
Applied has about 4,500 workers.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan said the new machines will be built in Austin factories,
though the company has begun hiring an unspecified number of new
workers and expects to continue to expand in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   The move from the industry-standard 200-millimeter wafer - about
the size of a salad plate - to the dinner-plate-size 300 millimeter
wafers has been a long and arduous one for the industry.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, most chip makers were planning
300-millimeter production. But chip prices dropped dramatically in
1996 and the industry went into a slump. That, coupled with a rift
between chip makers and equipment makers over specifications,
prompted most companies to put their 300 millimeter plans on hold.
A recent rebound in chip sales has prompted many chip makers to
start planning or building new factories again, and many want to
build at the 300-millimeter standard, which allows up to 2 1/2
times more chips per wafer than 200-millimeter production.
</P>
<P>
   Applied and other equipment makers including Tokyo Electron
Ltd., which also has a factory in Austin, already produce some
pieces of 300-millimeter equipment. A few companies use the tools
to make a limited number of chips, but none mass produces
semiconductors with 300-millimeter technology yet. With the
introduction of a complete, 21-piece line of 300-millimeter
equipment, chip makers can start building 300-millimeter factories.
At least a dozen chip companies, including giants like Intel Corp.,
Advanced Micro Devices Inc. and Motorola Inc., all have said they
are planning 300 millimeter factories, but in part have been
waiting on the equipment.You may contact Bob Keefe at
bkeefe(at)coxnews.com or at 760-476-9697.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
