<HEADER>
A8417 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-JDS-UNIPHASE-SDL-ART-     07-10 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JDS-UNIPHASE-SDL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEB HARDWARE MAKER BUYS DIGITAL `PLUMBER' FOR $41 BILLION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mention ``new economy'' and just what comes to mind? For many
people, dot-com companies, fancy Web sites, piles of cash.
</P>
<P>
   Those are all fine images, but these days, the big money in the
new economy is being made not by dot-coms but by the digital
plumbers.
</P>
<P>
   Most people probably never heard of the company that makes the
valves inside the pumps at their local water treatment plant. And
they probably never heard of SDL Inc., either. But that can hardly
bother SDL's investors, because the company announced Monday that
it had agreed to be acquired by JDS Uniphase Corp. for $41 billion
in stock.
</P>
<P>
   That is more than the market values of Amazon.com, At Home
Corp., eBay and Priceline.com combined.
</P>
<P>
   Modern cities are not possible without advanced plumbing, and
the wildfire spread of data communications and the Internet is not
possible without the sort of arcane components for fiber-optic
networks (think lasers and amplifiers) made by companies like JDS
Uniphase and SDL.
</P>
<P>
   That is not an original thought; over the last year, investors
have bid up the price of JDS Uniphase fivefold. But beside the
stock levitation, the financial muscle of the new economy's
plumbers has been felt mostly in explosive initial public offerings
and in rich acquisitions of private companies.
</P>
<P>
   But SDL, based in San Jose, Calif., is publicly traded, on
Nasdaq. And now the plumbers have announced what may just be the
biggest technology takeover yet.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal, each share of SDL would be exchanged for 3.8
shares of JDS Uniphase. JDS Uniphase's shares closed on Friday at
$116.1875, making the transaction worth $441.5125 for each share of
SDL. SDL's shares, meanwhile, closed Friday at $295.3125, giving
the company's investors a takeover premium of almost 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, by the time trading was over Monday, the value of the
deal had declined substantially. With such a wide spread between
the implied value of the deal, as announced, and where SDL's shares
had been trading, the arbitrage opportunity was obvious. Shares of
JDS Uniphase fell $15.0625, to $101.125, while SDL jumped $25.375,
to $320.6875.
</P>
<P>
   But even with those moves, shares of SDL still did not end up
close to JDL Uniphase's bid. With the slide Monday in shares of JDS
Uniphase, the deal is now worth $384.275 for each share of SDL,
which means that SDL could still be described as undervalued by
more than 19 percent.
</P>
<P>
   What that probably represents is moderate uncertainty among
arbitrageurs and institutional investors that the deal will
actually be completed. After all, it must be reviewed by the
Justice Department, which imposed some conditions on JDS Uniphase's
last big acquisition, of E-Tek Dynamics Inc., for about $20 billion
earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   But what is almost certain is that optical networking technology
will in some ways remain the technical foundation of the
communications revolution.
</P>
<P>
   That is because optical networks are generally the most
cost-effective way to transmit gargantuan amounts of two-way
information traffic from one point to another, especially in the
industrialized world.
</P>
<P>
   Copper wires like those used to connect most homes to the
telephone network also used to be employed for regional and
transcontinental networks. But optical networks, which transmit
information using pulses of light modulated by lasers, can be much
more efficient than copper networks using pulses of electricity.
</P>
<P>
   Big communications carriers like AT&AMP;T Corp. and WorldCom Inc.
buy optical communications systems from big equipment vendors like
Lucent Technologies Inc. and Nortel Networks Corp. of Canada. This
is like a city turning to a big water treatment company for a giant
water treatment plant. In turn, companies like Lucent and Nortel
assemble their systems from components and modules often bought
from companies like JDS Uniphase. This is like the water treatment
company turning to another concern for advanced pumps.
</P>
<P>
   Companies like JDS Uniphase then buy more specialized parts from
companies like SDL. This is like the pump company contracting out
to another firm for specialized valves.
</P>
<P>
   But imagine that only a few companies could make the valves
needed. And imagine that the overall capacity of the water
treatment plant (which determines the maximum size of the city it
serves) is closely linked to the performance of those valves. Then
it becomes clear that the valve company is quite valuable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me put it to you in a simple way,'' Anthony R. Muller, JDS
Uniphase's chief financial officer, said in a telephone interview
Monday. ``Think of Amazon and eBay and any number of other
companies that are of this genre. They all require bandwidth to
deliver their products and services. And we and our competitors
make the fundamental underlying technology that provides the amount
of bandwidth that is required for the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Don Scifres, SDL's chairman, said, ``This
combination brings together world-class technical and manufacturing
teams that promise to deliver best-in-class products at increased
volumes for today's systems while developing solutions for
tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Jozef Straus, the co-chairman and chief executive of JDS
Uniphase, said in a statement, ``JDS Uniphase and SDL share a
common vision to provide customers with the most innovative and
technologically advanced products that enhance their ability to
deliver next-generation optical systems.''
</P>
<P>
   SDL specializes in a sort of laser known as a pump laser and in
components that are used to make laser systems. JDS Uniphase is
hoping that by acquiring the company, it will be able to direct
SDL's research in ways that are more complementary to its own
technical plans.
</P>
<P>
   As that happens, the dot-com companies will continue to be the
most visible element of this new economy. And that will not trouble
the plumbers one bit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-00 2111EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
