u p BC-BUSH-GUARD-NYT &LR;      07-10 1125
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-GUARD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH TOOK ANOTHER OPTION TO AVOID VIETNAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: See GORE-MILITARY)  
 By NICHOLAS D. KRISTOF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   While Al Gore was signing up to fight in (or at least write
about) a war that he did not believe in, George W. Bush was
somewhat less resolutely partying in Houston. Bush, like many young
conservatives, had doubts about the war but was nonetheless
inclined to support it _ though not necessarily to the point of
fighting in it.
</P>
<P>
   When Bush graduated from Yale in 1968, he was in roughly the
same situation as Gore was upon graduation from Harvard a year
later. Both were southern men in Ivy League colleges, and both had
fathers in Congress who might suffer politically if their sons fled
to Canada or took extraordinary measures to avoid the draft.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the two sons entered the military in markedly different
ways.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Gore, who enlisted in the Army, taking a path that he
knew would lead to South Vietnam, Bush signed up to be a pilot in
the Texas Air National Guard. It was a coveted posting that
dramatically reduced any risk that he would be sent to Vietnam and
probably would not have been obtainable if his father had been less
prominent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did I think about going to the Army post and saying, `Send me
to Vietnam?''' Bush asked in an interview. ``Not really. I wanted
to fly, and that was the adventure I was seeking.''
</P>
<P>
   The decisions they made were deeply in character.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was always a serious, ambitious young man struggling with
deep moral questions and, in the case of Vietnam, with deeply
practical calculations about how his actions would play in his
father's re-election campaign. Some critics have also suggested
that in later years he embellished his Vietnam role for his own
political career. Bush was a carefree, happy-go-lucky fellow.
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, while Gore might have been more conscientious or
responsible, Bush was far more normal.
</P>
<P>
   While the Bush campaign likes to suggest that service in the
Guard was an entirely honorable alternative to Vietnam, back in
1988 one of Bush's father's strongest backers (and future chief of
staff), John Sununu, publicly criticized the Democratic vice
presidential nominee, Lloyd Bentsen, for getting his son into the
Guard. That was maladroit, since another young man in the same unit
as Bentsen's son was George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he discussed the war with his father, the younger Bush
says he must have but cannot recall any details. Likewise,
roommates and a girlfriend from that period say they do not recall
Bush saying much about the war one way or another, and he came
across as a lukewarm supporter at a time when most people were
passionate one way or the other. ``My first impulse and first
inclination was to support the country,'' Bush recalled in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   Vietnam filtered into the popular consciousness in many ways,
but for Bush and many of his classmates a crucial moment came with
the death of George W. Carpenter. Carpenter, an acquaintance of
Bush and the boyfriend of a cousin, grew up on Long Island and had
been valedictorian and class president in high school, as well as
captain of the football team.
</P>
<P>
   At Yale, the dark-haired, 6-foot-4-inch Carpenter was a
striking, fun-loving figure, but he was expelled in his freshman
year for misbehaving. Having lost his deferment, he signed up for
the Marine Corps and was sent to Vietnam, where he was patrolling
on Feb. 17, 1967, when his squad came upon an obstacle on the
trail.
</P>
<P>
   It was a mine that exploded and killed him at the age of 20. The
death sent a shiver through the Yale campus, and, for classmates
like Bush, Vietnam suddenly seemed more real and dangerous than
ever.
</P>
<P>
   Yet almost anybody clever enough to get into Harvard or Yale
could find a way to evade the draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``For guys in the Ivy League at that time, there was nobody that
I recall very well standing up and saying, `Hey, my country calls
and if these guys from the inner city are going to war, then by God
so will I,''' said John T. Sartore, a friend of Bush at Yale.
``Most people were wandering around figuring out how to get out of
it, and there were so many ways: getting married, getting orthotics
for your feet, getting braces, failing the medical, joining the
Peace Corps and so on.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the routes to evade service in Vietnam were out of the
question for a man like Bush, rooted in conservative Texas values,
and he had his father's political career to worry about.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very hairy time, and I think George had a little
different pressure because his father was a public figure,'' said
Roland W. Betts, one of Bush's fraternity brothers at Yale.
</P>
<P>
   As Bush recalls it, ``There was no question in my mind that
there was going to be a military service in 1969.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the most socially acceptable routes to avoid Vietnam, for
young Democrats and Republicans alike, was the National Guard. It
counted as military service; it offered the opportunity to learn a
skill, like flying fighter aircraft. And it provided a nearly
iron-clad guarantee that its members would not wind up in Southeast
Asia.
</P>
<P>
   For Bush, the crucial step was applying for a position in the
Texas Air National Guard while back in Houston for Christmas
vacation in his senior year. Nationally, 100,000 people were on
waiting lists to get into the Guard, and the details of Bush's
admission to the unit are controversial.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say the Bushes pulled rank, but there is no proof of
this. It is clear, however, that whether or not he demanded it,
Bush got special treatment because he was a congressman's son.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was not only admitted to a program with a long waiting list
but also was promoted to second lieutenant without going to officer
candidate school. Likewise, he was given pilot training despite his
lack of aviation experience.
</P>
<P>
   The Air National Guard was virtually made up of sons of the
Who's Who in Texas. It was sometimes called the Champagne Unit, and
among its members were sons of two other prominent Texas
politicians, Bentsen and John B. Connally, and several wealthy
Texas businessmen.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, sensitive to suggestions that he shirked his
responsibility in Vietnam, said that during his National Guard
service he went to his commander, who is now dead, and asked to be
admitted to the Palace Alert program, which could have sent him to
Vietnam for a short stint.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I remember doing that,'' he said, but he added: ``I
don't want to make it look that I would have been, but was thwarted
by the bureaucracy.''
</P>
<P>
   In any case, as all the pilots knew, Bush's plane, the F-102,
was virtually obsolete, and so there was little chance that he
would be accepted for a mission in Vietnam.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-00 2112EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000710.0406 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 21:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8419 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-ANGELES-VIOLENCE-NYT &LR;      07-10 1096
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANGELES-VIOLENCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GANGS BLAMED AS LOS ANGELES DEFIES NATIONAL CRIME TREND
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  By DON TERRY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In the middle of a sound sleep a few weeks ago,
John W. Mack, the president of the Los Angeles Urban League, was
awakened by a sound he had hoped had vanished from the night here:
the unmistakable rattle of gunfire echoing through the streets.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, he awoke to learn that a man had been shot and
killed 50 feet from his home. Several blocks away, a woman who had
witnessed the shooting was ``blown away, too.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For a while, it looked like we had turned a corner on this
kind of thing,'' Mack said Monday before the start of another
neighborhood anti-crime meeting here. ``But this violence issue is
really, really out of control.''
</P>
<P>
   A seeming resurgence in violent crime has struck Los Angeles in
recent months, at a time when, with only a few exceptions, violent
crime is down nationwide. Compared with this time last year, the
city has experienced a 7.5 percent increase in violent crime,
including 58 more homicides, 97 more rapes, 106 more robberies and
1,437 more aggravated assaults, according to Los Angeles Police
Deputy Chief Maurice Moore.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most publicized cases was the killing of the
20-year-old granddaughter of the city's chief of police. She was
shot as she sat in a car with a childhood friend. The friend, the
intended target, was a gang member. He escaped.
</P>
<P>
   But the violence has been more widespread than was generally
known. Out of the city's 18 police areas, 15 report increases in
violent crime, with several stations experiencing what officials
consider an alarming increase in homicides. The hardest hit, the
Newton station, which includes parts of South Central Los Angeles,
has had 24 more homicides than a year ago, followed by the 77th
police area, with 14 more killings. The Wilshire police area, where
Mack lives, was actually one of only three areas that reported a
slight decrease in violent crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``That just goes to show that there is no sanctuary, no safe
haven from violence,'' Mack said. ``Everybody needs to wake up and
help.''
</P>
<P>
   The police blame much of the increased violence on the city's
65,000 ``identified gang members.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're seeing is multiple gang frictions throughout the
city,'' Moore said, adding that there appeared to be no one reason
for the increased violence. ``A lot of it has to do with turf and
of course drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   But neighborhood advocates such as Najee Ali of Project Islamic
HOPE and Earl Ofari Hutchinson of the National Alliance for
Positive Action say it is too easy to blame the gangs. And police
statistics seem to back them up. So far this year, according to
police, 42 percent of the city's homicides were gang-related,
meaning the majority were not.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a deep sense of hopelessness out there,'' Hutchinson
said. ``We spend more money on prisons than on schools. And the
leadership, particularly the African-American leadership, has
abandoned the inner city. All these factors are coming together and
I don't think this increase in the violence is just an uptick. I
think it's a long term trend.''
</P>
<P>
   It has certainly been part of the city's past. In the 1980s and
early 1990s, street gang violence was almost as much a part of Los
Angeles' image as sunshine, palm trees and bottled blondes. There
have been countless meetings of politicians, ministers,
neighborhood advocates, gang members and grieving parents searching
for ways ``to stop the violence and increase the peace.'' Those
efforts led eight years ago to a well publicized truce among gangs.
That and the overall improvement of the economy contributed to a
lowering of the crime rate here and across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Now, though, some experts say, the coming of age of younger gang
members is at least partly responsible for a seeming resurgence of
violence.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the cause, the drive-bys, the meetings and the funerals
are happening more often. Dozens of people turned out Monday for an
anti-violence meeting at the First AME Church, which became a
shelter for hundreds of people during the flames and civil unrest
of 1992. The meeting was one of two held Monday to search for new
and old ways to stop the killing.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting at AME was convened by Los Angeles County Supervisor
Yvonne Brathwaite Burke and the speaker emeritus of the California
State Assembly, Antonio R. Villaraigosa, a candidate for mayor in
next year's election. The Los Angeles city attorney, James K. Hahn,
another mayoral candidate also attended.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were patting ourselves on the back six months about crime
going down,'' Hahn said. ``We have to recognize the work is not
over.''
</P>
<P>
   Chilton Alphonse, who started an anti-violence program in the
'80s, paced in the back of the meeting. He left the country several
years ago, exhausted and heart broken after seeing so many young
people killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was completely stressed out,'' he said. ``I've been through
all of this before. If it goes away for a while and there's a lull
in the killing, everyone forgets about it. The fire will burn, then
it will smolder and then it will erupt again if they don't put
enough resources into the problem. Jobs and education.''
</P>
<P>
   A job is what Michael Jones, 27, needed when he got out of
prison a year and a half ago after serving nine years for what he
called ``gang related crimes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No one would give me a job,'' he said. ``I was trying to do
right, but I was living on the edge. I started cutting people's
grass and then the police would roust me and say, `Where'd you
steal that lawn mower?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, he was hired by a violence prevention group and now
``kids call me at 2 and 3 in the morning all the time, having a
nightmare about their father getting killed.''
</P>
<P>
   Burke, the supervisor, said finding jobs for young men who had
been in prison should be a major part of any effort to ease gang
violence.
</P>
<P>
   The violence is not confined to Los Angeles. Mary Simmons, a
43-year-old home care worker, lives in Long Beach and she said she
was ``scared everyday.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to get into my home before 9 every night,'' she said.
``I've lost two nephews. We can't go to school because we got to
work all the time to survive on almost no money. My son is 23. He's
tired of struggling. He can't put shoes on his feet. I can't help
him. I don't have any money.'' A big tear fell down her cheek. ``We
can't take care of our kids,'' she said. ``That's why we're losing
our children to these gangs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
