<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 21:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8421 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-ISSUES-ART-1     07-10 1092
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-ISSUES-ART-1,070(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALKS WILL EXPLORE DEEPEST MATTERS DIVIDING ISRAEL AND
PALESTINIANS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(With MIDEAST-TALKS and MIDEAST-ISRAEL) 
 By JANE PERLEZ    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When President Clinton announced the Camp David
summit meeting, he said he hoped it would resolve the deepest
matters dividing the Israelis and Palestinians, questions of
``beliefs, political identity, collective fate'' that raise dark
fears and emotions. He also sounded a note of weary familiarity,
saying that the issues were so well-known that the solutions should
be within sight.
</P>
<P>
   As the Israeli prime minister, Ehud Barak, and the Palestinian
leader, Yasser Arafat, begin their first session of final peace
talks with Clinton, they are expected to test how far apart they
are on the future status of Jerusalem, the fate of more than three
million Palestinian refugees and the borders of a Palestinian
state.
</P>
<P>
   What is intertwined with these overarching issues is the
question of how many Israeli settlers on the West Bank would remain
in Israeli territory and how many would come under Palestinian rule
and then, most likely, be resettled in Israel. The future of the
Jordan Valley will also be on the table.
</P>
<P>
   International financial assistance is likely to be discussed,
including an American component, to compensate refugees but also to
help form a new Palestinian state. Separately, the Israelis are
seeking an upgraded security relationship with the United States,
though one that falls short of a mutual defense pact.
</P>
<P>
   The American team, led by Clinton, has not said whether it will
work on all the issues at once or single out those where the most
progress can be made. Nor has it signaled whether it will present
precise American ideas _ known in negotiating parlance as
``bridging proposals'' _ for all the issues or just for some.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Israeli prime minister, Yitzak Rabin, and Arafat
agreed in principle seven years ago on a peace settlement in which
Israel and the Palestine Liberation Organization recognized each
other, these crucial issues have been kicked down the road for a
final round of talks designed to formally end the more than
five-decade conflict.
</P>
<P>
   The 1993 agreement, which was negotiated in Oslo and signed on
the White House lawn, called for the two sides to make a final
settlement by May 4, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   That deadline was extended last September _ in an agreement at
Sharm el Sheik, Egypt _ to Sept. 13, 2000, the date Arafat has set
for unilaterally declaring a Palestinian state if there is no final
peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   In the seven years since Oslo, the Israelis have withdrawn from
the Gaza Strip and about 40 percent of the West Bank. These moves
were carried out after wrenching negotiations for a series of
interim accords, including one in 1998 at Wye, Md., where Clinton
mediated between Arafat and the conservative Israeli prime
minister, Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the two sides have been called to the endgame on the
hitherto too-tough-to-deal-with issues, the differences appear
acute on every front. A senior American official said that in
on-and-off talks over the last seven months, including back-channel
negotiations in Stockholm, the two sides had ``demythologized'' the
issues. But he said that gaps had been narrowed only in some areas.
And that small progress, he said, was beginning to be eroded by
bitterness in the last month.
</P>
<P>
   The question on which the least progress has been made,
according to all participants in the negotiations, is Jerusalem. In
Stockholm, there was a little bit of ``brainstorming'' on
Jerusalem, but ``brainstorming is cheap,'' said an official
familiar with the talks. A senior Israeli official said here last
week that it was possible that agreement would be reached on
several major points but that an agreement on Jerusalem was much
more unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   The heart and soul of the Israeli position is still that
Jerusalem is the undivided and eternal capital of Israel, the
official said.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Arafat said last month that he remained insistent
that East Jerusalem become the capital of a Palestinian state.
Those who disagreed, he scoffed, could ``go and drink from the Dead
Sea.'' Arafat, his aides say, will not be the Arab leader who gives
up on Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli officials have suggested that Barak is considering
granting some increased autonomy to Palestinians in East Jerusalem
_ specifically, more control of public services.
</P>
<P>
   A 1995 document by Yossi Beilin, now the Israeli justice
minister, and Abu Mazen, the secretary of the Palestine Liberation
Organization, had compromises on a range of issues, but _ showing
how tough the issue is _ not on whose capital the city would be.
</P>
<P>
   Published versions of the document, known as the Beilin-Mazen
agreement, outline compromises on all the major issues in the
Palestinian-Israeli conflict and components of it are being revived
as the talks open.
</P>
<P>
   One version of the document says that the boundaries of greater
Jerusalem would be expanded to include Palestinian districts,
including the suburban towns of Abu-dis, al-Ayzariyan and Salwan.
The Palestinian Authority would create a capital in these new
districts and call it Al-Quds and not Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   For the estimated 200,000 Arabs who live in Jerusalem, a
municipal council would be formed to manage local affairs under the
supervision of the Israeli council that is now responsible for the
whole city. And the Palestinian flag would be flown from the
Islamic holy sites.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, because the plan does not recognize Palestinian
sovereignty over East Jerusalem it has been dismissed by Arab
diplomats as the ``Jewish solution.'' It seemed impossible, they
said, that Arafat would be able to live with what would amount to
only linguistic niceties, such as Palestinian ``autonomy'' in East
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials as well as Israelis and Palestinians
have all said that if the Camp David sessions got as far as
tackling Jerusalem, the compromises necessary on both sides would
be so substantial that the talks could break down at that point. In
the days before the meeting, there have been increasing suggestions
that the White House might have to settle for an agreement that
would leave decisions on Jerusalem for another day.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   But some officials have said that in an overall package there
could be the possibility of both sides moving to fallback positions
on Jerusalem in return for a final agreement that ended all claims
by either side.
</P>
<P>
   On the question of territory _ how much and where the Israelis
will give up land on the West Bank _ there appears to have been
some behind-the-scenes movement. Indeed, both Israelis and
Palestinians say this has been where there has been the most
progress.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat and his top aides have repeatedly declared that Israel
must withdraw from the West Bank and Gaza to the borders that
existed before the 1967 Middle East War, in accordance with U.N.
resolution 242. Part of Arafat's insistence is based on what he
calls the precedent laid down by Israel in its peace deals with
Egypt in 1979, when 100 percent of the Sinai was yielded, and in
Jordan in 1994, when Israel swapped some land with Jordan to
compensate for land taken by Israel decades before along their
joint border.
</P>
<P>
   But in private, the Palestinian leader has acknowledged to
American officials that large Israeli settlements on the West Bank
are certain to be annexed by Israel in a final deal. In return for
such a concession, Arafat contends that Israel must ``swap'' some
Israeli land to be included in the new Palestinian state. Barak's
advisers are reported to be divided on this issue.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli officials said that Barak opposes swapping land because
it would encroach on the notion of Israeli sovereignty. One of the
parcels of land that has been discussed is in the Negev Desert.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the Israelis have not been precise on the amount of
territory they are prepared to give up on the West Bank. The
Israeli press has reported that between 90 and 92 percent of the
West Bank would be ceded _ much more than the 60 percent or 75
percent that had been generally thought. The Barak government has
not officially acknowledged that it is considering these higher
figures, though.
</P>
<P>
   A senior Israeli official said that land with about 70 percent
of the 175,000 settlers would be annexed to Israel. The future of
the remaining settlers _ those in outlying areas or scattered
settlements _ would have to be negotiated.
</P>
<P>
   These settlers, according to preliminary discussions, would have
a choice of taking Palestinian citizenship _ a highly unlikely
choice _ or of being moved back to Israel. The Israelis are
insisting on no ``arbitrary'' dismantling of settlements.
</P>
<P>
   In many respects, the negotiators believe that the future of
more than three million Palestinian refugees, most of whom either
left Israel after the 1948 war or are their descendants, may be the
easiest problem to solve. About a million are in camps run by
international agencies in Lebanon, Syria, Jordan, Gaza and the West
Bank.
</P>
<P>
   The mantra of the Palestinian Authority has been that these
refugees must have the right to return to Israel and that Israel
must accept responsibility for the fact they fled or were expelled
during the 1948 Arab-Israeli conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Israel says it refuses to accept responsibility and will not
acknowledge the right of return but will show ``empathy'' for the
refugees, said a special adviser to Barak, Yossi Alpher.
</P>
<P>
   The Barak government is prepared, Alpher says, as a
``humanitarian gesture,'' to allow some family reunification _ as
occurred in the 1950s and 1960s until the 1967 war _ but on a scale
to be negotiated.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian officials faced with their own budgetary and space
limitations on how many refugees they want to take into their new
state could be willing to go along with a concept that grants the
right of return in principle but stops short of actually carrying
it out, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   About 2.7 million Palestinians live on the West Bank and Gaza,
and U.N. officials estimate that the Palestinian Authority would
probably accept the return of a maximum of 500,000 refugees phased
over a number of years.
</P>
<P>
   A sizable international aid package spread over 20 years has
been suggested for compensating the refugees and the governments
that have been hosts to them. Japan, the European Union and the
United States would be the major contributors.
</P>
<P>
   On the future of the Jordan Valley, the Israelis officially
assert that the area will remain Israel's security border but that
the security presence may be phased out over a period of time. An
international force could patrol the valley, and Israeli soldiers
would be part of it.
</P>
<P>
   While the eventual loss of the Jordan Valley is not popular in
Israel, it is not nearly as sensitive an issue as Jerusalem. ``The
Israeli body politic won't go crazy if the Jordan Valley is handed
over,'' an official said.
</P>
<P>
   For Barak, particularly in his precarious political situation,
the size of the American aid package and the upgrading of the
security relationship are of utmost importance. Part of his ability
to sell a peace deal in general elections _ which he would likely
call _ would depend a great deal on how much he was able to bring
home from Washington in terms of new weaponry and radar capable of
detecting missiles.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Arafat is expecting considerable financial aid from
the United States, as well as Japan and the European Union, to help
get his new state off the ground. Just before departing for the
summit, Arafat's chief economic adviser, Mohammed Rachid, said the
Palestinians would ask the Americans for $40 billion, much of it
for refugee assistance.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-00 2116EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000710.0409 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 21:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8428 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-BRAVES-GOLF-COX     07-10 1198
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-GOLF-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A time to pitch and a time to putt
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALTNATA _ John Smoltz was big-time serious. When it concerns his
golf game or his pitching, he always is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be totally honest with you,'' Smoltz said. ``If there was
ever a chance to become a free agent, I wouldn't even consider any
team that wouldn't let me play golf.''
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't been an issue for Smoltz and the Braves. Since Bobby
Cox took over as Braves manager in 1990, a golf-friendly policy has
been in effect for his multitalented starting pitchers and other
players. Cox not only allows them to take their golf clubs on the
road, he encourages it, citing physical and mental advantages.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, they have been collecting Top 100 golf courses at
an even faster pace than Cy Young Awards.
</P>
<P>
   Although Smoltz, Greg Maddux and Tom Glavine represent the core
of the Braves' golf squad, it often includes starter Kevin Milwood
or WSB producer Dave Baker, with occasional appearances by first
baseman Wally Joyner, Braves broadcasters Don Sutton and Joe
Simpson or first-base coach Glenn Hubbard.
</P>
<P>
   During dead times in the Braves' clubhouse, it is common to see
them in the back, out of view of the media, practicing on their
customized, undulating putting green. On most road trips, they
assemble early in the morning in their Softspikes to play some of
the nation's most prestigious courses.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the Cubs,'' Maddux said, ``we were allowed to stay out
all night drinking until 3 or 4 in the morning. But if you got up
at 8 to take your golf clubs out, `Whoa, don't do that.' I never
understood it, but that's kind of just the way it was.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that a multimillion-dollar salary earner is in dire need of
perks, but in this case the rich certainly get richer. Glavine's
baseball high point was Game 6 of the 1995 World Series, but among
life's cherished moments, right up there was an off Monday in San
Francisco a few years ago when the pitchers drove to the Monterey
Peninsula to play Pebble Beach, Cypress Point and Spyglass and
still made it back to the ballpark Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   A sweet one, Smoltz agreed, but his vote would be for the off
day in New York hen he, Glavine and Maddux played Shinnecock Hills,
site of the 1995 U.S. Open, and the highly regarded National Golf
Links, back to back.
</P>
<P>
   At the center of their golf adventures is The Book. That would
be Smoltz's book of course contacts and telephone numbers, which he
started in the early 1990s. Over the years, dating back to when the
group included then-Braves pitchers Pete Smith and Charlie
Leibrandt, they have developed enough nationwide relationships that
usually only a call is needed to get on Pine Valley, Baltusrol,
Winged Foot or Medinah.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux kids that Smoltz's book could be more valuable than each
player's book on opponent hitters. Or is he kidding?
</P>
<P>
   ``Hitters change,'' Maddux said, allowing one of his devilish
grins. ``Golf courses don't change. They usually just get better.''
</P>
<P>
   Golf `helps everything'
</P>
<P>
   Maddux never fails to appreciate the fact that Cox treats them
like adults in the matter, confident that they will use their best
judgment. Cox's only mandate is that the pitchers do not play the
day they are on the mound, which is a no-brainer, anyway. Maddux
takes it a step further, never playing the day before a start.
Glavine does the same when a day-game appearance is approaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played with some managers who didn't care what you did as
long as you weren't late to the ballpark,'' said Sutton, a Hall of
Fame pitcher. ``But Gene Mauch, who was an avid golfer, said,
`Wherever you play, it better be good, because it's a $500 fine.' I
never understood it. Nothing in golf is going to hurt you as a
pitcher. With some teams, it's OK to go to a topless bar, but don't
get caught with your golf clubs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they should play,'' Cox said. ``It helps everything.
It's an outlet for them. I encourage those guys, the starters, to
do it. It's a good way to loosen up after you pitch. Some managers
used to tell guys years ago, go swim after you pitch. Why not play
golf?''
</P>
<P>
   Cox insists his rules would be the same even if we weren't
talking about Cy Young Award winners who have led baseball's best
pitching staff for the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not drinkers and everything,'' Cox said, ``and they
don't hang out (at the bars) after the games like the old days.
Everybody goes to their rooms. So why not enjoy your life? If golf
helps you, great.''
</P>
<P>
   Long John
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz, who is on the disabled list after elbow surgery and does
not make road trips, even got permission to play in a pro-celebrity
tournament at Lake Tahoe last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Smoltz is the primo player of the group. All of them
have played in PGA Tour pro-ams such as Pebble Beach or the Bob
Hope and enjoyed a few rounds with tour players such as Tiger
Woods, David Duval and Mark O'Meara. But Smoltz, who can bomb his
treasured 5-wood 275 yards or his driver more than 300 yards, is
the total package.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's sickeningly long,'' Glavine said. ``To us, he's like
Tiger is to everybody else on tour. When he hits one, he's 30 yards
by us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's legit,'' Maddux said. ``A lot of guys hit a couple of
good shots a round, and they think they're good golfers, but
Smoltzie is legit. For being a baseball player, he can really go
low.''
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz ``tries not to let baseball interfere with his golf,''
Sutton said. ``The first question after surgery from John is, `When
can I start hitting wedges?' He hits the ball so far, but he also
can control it and he knows the game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He gives me something to shoot for,'' Joyner said.
</P>
<P>
   The oddsmaker
</P>
<P>
   Other than baseball and family, golf is all that Smoltz wants to
do. He almost surely will play the Celebrity Golf Tour full-time
when he is through pitching, and he might try the Senior Tour. His
game has developed to where now a fifth of his rounds are in the
60s. He shot a 68 in Dan Marino's charity event.
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz said he improved from a 12-handicap to an 8, then a 4,
from about 1991-95. ``But it wasn't until last year that I really
got over the hump and started shooting under par almost every four
or six times,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With Smoltz sidelined, there has been a greater load on Maddux
and Glavine to make and confirm their arrangements at prospective
courses. The upside is a gain in their wallets. With Smoltz in the
rotation, the betting can be feverish, with $20 Nassaus and
automatic presses building the pot. Glavine said at one stage, it
got way too serious.
</P>
<P>
   ``Next thing you know,'' he said, ``you're complaining about
somebody moving a ball off a tree root. That's the last thing we
need, is somebody saying, `Hey, you've got to hit that,' and we've
got a broken hand and somebody's on the DL.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, it has become almost traditional to try to hold off
Smoltz's betting schemes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can stick it up a tree 40 feet in the air,'' Maddux said,
``and he'll want odds that he's still going to save par.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
