<HEADER>
A8430 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-SOC-PARLOW-COX     07-10 0430
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-PARLOW-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Parlow prepares for move to Atlanta
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Cindy Parlow has been covering a lot of ground in
Atlanta with one goal in mind: finding a place to live before she
joins her team in the start-up women's soccer league, the WUSA, in
April.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking everywhere,'' Parlow said during a brief visit,
which includes a round of golf and a ticket to tonight's All-Star
Game at Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   Because the franchise hasn't yet decided where it will play or
practice, Parlow is holding off on signing a lease.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want a huge commute,'' said Parlow, who is a senior at
the University of North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   It's understandable, because Parlow is spending most of this
year on the road. The 5-foot-11 forward is the leading scorer on
the U.S. women's national team, including three hat tricks in June.
She leaves Wednesday on a 20-day trip to Europe, where the U.S.
will play Norway, Germany and China.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still developing as a team,'' Parlow said, ``trying to
get injured players back in the lineup and get them some playing
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Goalkeeper Briana Scurry, who also will play on the Atlanta
team, Carla Overbeck and Michelle Akers will rejoin the U.S. squad
for this trip.
</P>
<P>
   Since capturing the public's fancy by winning the 1996 Olympics
and the 1999 World Cup, people expect the U.S. team to win every
time they kick the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time we lose, everybody says, `What's wrong with the
women's team?''' Parlow said. ``Nobody realizes that we don't just
show up and win. We have to bring our best game to the field and
play 100 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the Memphis native was the youngest U.S. women's player
at age 18. Her most vivid memory is standing on the gold-medal
podium, hearing the national anthem, ``as we're all yelling the
words to it,'' she said. ``I wouldn't call it singing.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that Parlow's among the veterans, she appreciates the
experience more than she did four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``In '96 I was just the happy fan, just happy to be there, going
to the Olympics with all of these guys,'' Parlow said. ``Most of
these guys I had posters up on my wall at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I'm on the team, I'm more in the phase of, `I want to help
this team win.'''
</P>
<P>
   The same goes for her next team, the as-yet unnamed WUSA
franchise, which is operated by Cox Enterprises Inc., owner of The
Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been our dream for so long,'' Parlow said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
