<HEADER>
A8436 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-HOCKEY-BEATING-NYT &LR;      07-10 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOCKEY-BEATING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ICE-RINK DEATH REFLECTS PARENTS' RAGE DURING EVENTS FOR CHILDREN 
</HEADLINE>
   By FOX BUTTERFIELD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A suburban Boston father charged with manslaughter in
the fatal beating of another father over rough play at a youth
hockey game pleaded not guilty Monday, as sports officials and
psychologists suggested that the incident reflected a rapid growth
in parents' violent acts at children's athletic events.
</P>
<P>
   Behind that rise in such violence during recent years, the
experts say, is more involvement by fathers and mothers in their
children's sports, greater pressure to see their offspring win
athletic scholarships or big-money professional contracts, and a
tendency to over &UR; - &LR; identify with the children, who, the parents
hope, will become the sports stars they themselves never were.
</P>
<P>
   In the case here, Thomas Junta, a 42-year-old truck driver with
no previous criminal record, turned himself in to the police Monday
and was released on $5,000 bail in Woburn District Court.
Manslaughter carries a maximum sentence of 20 years' imprisonment
in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Junta's court appearance followed by five days the assault on
the 40-year-old victim, Michael Costin, at a hockey rink in
Reading, north of Boston. Martha Coakley, the Middlesex County
district attorney, said Costin's death had resulted from a ``wanton
and reckless assault and battery.'' There is no evidence that the
two men knew each other, she said, and no ``indication of an intent
to kill.''
</P>
<P>
   Costin was beaten after a pickup hockey game where he had been
on the ice monitoring play. Junta, watching from the stands,
shouted at him, demanding that he stop some body-checking and
fighting that the police said involved the two men's 10-year-old
sons. Junta, who is 6 &UR;  &LR; feet 2 inches and 275 pounds, initially
assaulted Costin, 5-11 and 170, as he left the ice, the authorities
said, and then, after being ordered out by a rink manager, returned
and slammed Costin to the ground beside a soda machine.
</P>
<P>
   That blow to Costin's head as he hit the concrete floor
apparently caused brain death almost instantly, Coakley said, but
Junta pushed his knee into Costin's chest and continued to pummel
him in the head.
 &UR;  &LR;  Whatever the root causes that led the events of last Wednesday to
spin so badly out of control, the death of Costin and the arrest of
Junta touched off talk by experts about the harm of parental
over-involvement in children's athletics.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just the tip of an iceberg,'' said William Pollack, an
assistant clinical professor of psychiatry at the Harvard Medical
School who is an authority on father-son relationships. Pollack
said reports of assaults by parents at youth sports events ``have
gotten much worse'' in the last five &UR;  &LR; to 10 years, and statistics
show that the number of injuries in youth sports is also sharply up
during the same period, a result at least in part of parents'
encouraging their children to play more aggressively.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Still, a spokesman for the National Association of Sports
Officials, which represents 19,000 umpires and referees in
professional as well as high school and youth sports, said his
organization had seen a sharp increase in reports of violence by
parents at sports events in the last three or four years, usually
by parents attacking an official, though sometimes assaulting
another parent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get two or three reports of this kind of behavior a week,''
Still said in a telephone interview from his group's headquarters
in Racine, Wis. ``There is definitely a trend.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Still said, he received a report that a coach, the
father of a player, had broken the jaw of a 13-year-old umpire at a
Little League game in Davie, Fla., because he did not like a call.
</P>
<P>
   And last year a mother in Virginia slapped a 14-year-old
official and knocked him to the ground because she disagreed with a
call during a soccer game, Still said.
</P>
<P>
   It has reached the point, he said, where the association has
begun to offer its members assault insurance and provide legal
advice to those who have been attacked.
</P>
<P>
   Sports officials and psychologists agree that there are several
likely causes of increasing parental violence.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Engh, founder and president of the National Alliance for
Youth Sports, a nonprofit organization in West Palm Beach, Fla.,
that works to promote fun and safety in athletics, said the first
cause was ego. ``It's not the kid at bat,'' he said, ``it's the
parent,'' who is living vicariously through his child.
</P>
<P>
   A second factor, Engh said, is greed. ``So many parents today
are saying, `My child is going to get some of that money, the
millions of dollars in professional sports or a college
scholarship.''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard Zaichowsky, a professor of sports psychology at Boston
University, who grew up playing hockey in Alberta, Canada, said one
important change was the sheer increase in parental involvement in
sports. ``When I was growing up, parents were minimally involved,''
he said. ``Kids rode their bikes or walked to games, and they
settled things themselves. Now parents drive the kids to practice
and games, and as things have gotten more organized, the stakes are
higher.''
</P>
<P>
   The death of Costin may well be an example of this increased
parental pressure, Zaichowsky said. ``Who the heck used to play
hockey in July?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Murphy, who has been refereeing high school basketball games
for 20 years in Boston and its suburbs, said: ``Quite frankly, it's
gotten worse over the years because of the way society is. Now it's
win, win, win at all cost. It's no longer about the kids having
fun.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Once the parents get involved,'' he said, ``things seem to go
awry.''
</P>
<P>
   Murphy said he kept parents away from a summer basketball camp
he runs for boys in the sixth, seventh and eighth grades. ``Without
the parents,'' he said, ``there is less chance for confrontation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
