<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 21:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8437 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-BBO-ALLSTAR-BISHER-CO     07-10 1354
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ALLSTAR-BISHER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The old-time All-Stars from Fayette County
 &HT;    By Furman Bisher
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Not exactly neighbors, but living within about 10
miles of each other in rural Fayette County, Georgia, are two
former American League All-Stars. Cecil Travis, 86, was born, grew
up and still lives on original Travis acreage. Billy Moran, 66,
native of College Park, was a searing-hot prospect when he came out
of high school. He got $40,000 to sign. Travis got $500. Travis was
chosen to play in three All-Star Games and played in two. Moran was
chosen to play one time and played in two. You'll see what I mean.
</P>
<P>
   This is the kind of man Cecil Travis is.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ted Williams says you belong in the Hall of Fame,'' was the
way it was put to him.
</P>
<P>
   Travis was thoughtful for a moment or two. ``I don't think
that,'' he said, finally. We sat in lawn chairs in the shade,
sheltered from the blistering heat on the bank of one of his lakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of players with records as good or better than
mine who are not in it. I just don't think it would look right.'
</P>
<P>
   Country gentleman. Solid citizen. Humble to a fault. Without
pretension.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, if I had had several seasons like 1941, then it might be
different. But the war came along, and when I got back, it was
gone. Maybe I tried to come back too quick, but Washington was in a
race for the pennant in 1945, and they thought I could help.''
</P>
<P>
   The season of 1941 was the kind any player would like to hang
from the rafters. It was the season Ted Williams hit .406, last of
the .400 hitters. It was the season Joe DiMaggio had his 56-game
hitting streak. But Cecil Travis had more hits than either, 218,
and led the league. He went to bat 608 times. He struck out only 25
times. In his career he went to bat 4,914 times. He struck out only
291 times. Here was a man with an eye keen enough to count the
stitches on a baseball flying at him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit .359 that season, second to Williams, but I was a mile
behind him.''
</P>
<P>
   When he was first tipped as a lad to the gregarious Tubby
Walton, who ran ``Tubby Walton's Baseball University,'' with a
chicken-wire backstop, Prof. Walton was told, ``I know a boy that
can hit a curveball.''
</P>
<P>
   Tubby said, ``Ain't no boy can hit a curveball.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This one can. I've seen him do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Tubby told the informant to bring the boy in, and so, in a pair
of white duck pants and tennis shoes, 17-year-old Cecil Travis
arrived on the ``campus.'' Tubby picked out the toughest, meanest
pitcher he had. (``He'd done time on the road gang.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``That boy hit every mean thing that ex-con could throw at
him,'' Tubby said.
</P>
<P>
   Tubby wasted no time springing into action, which eventually led
Travis to the Chattanooga Lookouts, then to the old Washington
Senators, the only major-league team he ever played for.
</P>
<P>
   At the signing, on the front porch of the Travis farmhouse,
Cecil's father, an educated man, was reading the contract line by
line. ``First time anybody I signed ever read a contract,'' Walton
said. He looked up at Tubby Walton and said, ``This sounds like my
son is joining the chain gang.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Shore does,'' Tubby said, ``but they don't get paid on the
chain gang.''
</P>
<P>
   From 1933 to 1941, Travis hit below .300 only one season, when
he missed part of 1939 with an injury. His line-drive style, ``blue
darters'' to those of that vintage, was perfect for Griffith
Stadium. The outfield was as big as a prairie and the fences as
tall as redwoods, so you won't see many home runs on Travis'
record.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Moran came out of Russell High School with a variety of
options, but when the Cleveland Indians came forth with a bonus of
$40,000, which looked like $400,000 then, that took everything else
out of play. By 1958, he had arrived in Cleveland, and by 1962, he
was the All-Star American League second baseman after he had been
traded to the Los Angeles Angels, then playing in the Dodgers' new
stadium at Chavez Ravine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was special because I was voted in by my peers, with guys
like Bobby Richardson and Nellie Fox going strong,'' he said.
``With New York and Chicago fans voting, I'd never have made it.''
</P>
<P>
   That was a year of the all-star gluttony, two games instead of
one, thankfully the last year of it. The first game was played at
RFK Stadium in Washington, where Moran singled in four at-bats, the
second in Wrigley Field in Chicago, where his one base hit created
a furor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a line drive to center field, and Henry Aaron got ... a
glove on it. You couldn't tell if he caught it or not, but the
umpire ruled it was a trap. Rocky Colavito hit a home run behind me
and that was the game, 9 to 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a thrill, just being in the clubhouse with guys from
other teams, like Roger Maris, Mickey Mantle and Yogi Berra. Yogi
pinch-hit for me in the late innings. Imagine that, Yogi Berra
pinch-hitting for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Of historical significance is this, that over the next 20 years,
the American League would win only one time.
</P>
<P>
   As for twin ``classics,'' Moran says this: ``That took a lot off
it, I thought. One made it a special event. Two games sort of
watered it down, like what inter-league play is doing to the World
Series.'' That was Moran's best season in the majors, .282, 17 home
runs and 74 RBIs. He was almost as good in 1963, when he hit .275.
Then he made a decision that he lives to regret to this day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Rigney said the Angels had a hot prospect coming in from
Hawaii and wondered if I'd mind moving over to third. Well, when
the manager asks you to do something, you did it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Second base was my home. I'd grown up there. I didn't have a
third-base arm, and I never was the same again. I injured my back,
and they traded me back to Cleveland. I should have said no, but
you didn't do that then.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``hot prospect'' may be seen these days, still in the major
leagues. Bobby Knoop is a coach for Jim Fregosi at Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   Cecil Travis' most vivid All-Star memory involves not him, but
Ted Williams, in the game of 1941 at Detroit. ``Arky Vaughn had
already hit two home runs, and the Nationals were leading, 5 to 3.
Two men were out when Williams hit one (out) in right field for
three runs in the last of the ninth, and we won the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Travis played the 1940 and '41 games at third base, although as
a Senator he was a shortstop. Joe Cronin was the shortstop one
year, Luke Appling the other. Travis got his only hit, a double, at
Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   There wasn't much mixing and mingling between players of the two
leagues in those years. Such comradeship was frowned upon, even in
a picnic atmosphere such as the All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   ``One player you couldn't escape talking to was Luke Appling,''
Travis said. ``Luke was always talking to you. He'd talk your ears
off.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike these times, the All-Star Game was the attraction, and
that was it. No sideshows, no supporting events, no entertainment
at all. Just show up and play.
</P>
<P>
   When the game was last played in Atlanta in 1972, baseball
commissioner Bowie Kuhn invited Travis and his wife to be his
guests. ``Joe Cronin had called. He was president of the American
League, but I had to tell him Bowie Kuhn had already invited me. He
had been a batboy and scoreboard worker in Washington when I played
there, so he had known me since he was a kid.''
</P>
<P>
   A stretch of nearly four seasons away at war pretty much spelled
the end of Travis' career. He never hit .300 again. A story
circulated that he had suffered from frozen feet on the European
front, but he shot that one down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just a couple of frozen toes. Had no effect on me. I probably
tried to make it back too soon,'' he said. ``I'd think I had it
going, then it would go away. Pitchers you used to hit got you out
on most anything.''
</P>
<P>
   He knew it was time. In late 1947, his average at a dismal .216,
Travis packed it in and came home to his farm, from which you can
get a view through the woods of Evander Holyfield's modern version
of the extreme castle.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
