<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 21:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8439 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-EDITORIAL-ABM-COX     07-10 0572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-ABM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Missile defense failures show futility of system
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Saturday's misfire over the Pacific should erase any doubt for
President Clinton about whether he should order the deployment of
the Pentagon's limited missile-defense system. This turkey shows no
signs it can fly.
</P>
<P>
   Let no one gloss over this fourfold failure. Most distressingly,
the missile interceptor started tumbling off-course as it streaked
toward its test target. The interceptor's ``kill vehicle'' didn't
separate from its booster, thus preventing its sensors from
detecting the incoming missile. A balloon decoy accompanying the
missile didn't inflate as it should have, so the system's ability
to distinguish between a real threat and a fake remains far from
proven. Finally, the test was delayed for two hours because of a
battery malfunction.
</P>
<P>
   This test was Pentagon-tailored for success _ simply to ``shoot
at a cooperative target in an orchestrated way,'' in the words of a
leading critic, MIT physicist Theodore Postol. Yet it was a flop,
even when the Pentagon gave itself an extra two hours to react _ a
generosity no enemy would show.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's advocacy of a limited missile shield has always seemed
contrived so as to protect himself and his chosen heir Al Gore from
attack by Republicans who favor an even grander, reincarnated
``Star Wars'' defense. Moreover, the goal of putting his proposed
system into operation by 2005, in light of its spotty test record,
seems hasty to the point of recklessness.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is supposed to make up his mind based on the nature of
the threat, the state of our technology, the cost of the project
and the effect of deployment on U.S. security. Any sensible,
objective analysis of these criteria should lead him to a negative
conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   There should be no rush to guard against a negligible threat.
The most frequently mentioned ``rogue'' nation, North Korea,
recently agreed to extend its nearly yearlong moratorium on missile
flight tests. The longer it observes this pause, the more distant
the danger it poses. As for Iran and Iraq, they are considered
years away from developing long-range missiles. In any event, no
sane enemy is likely to announce his return address, as a missile
attack would do, and thus bring on massive U.S. retaliation.
</P>
<P>
   The technology aspect, as demonstrated Saturday, is no selling
point. Neither is the cost, set at $60 billion, which is no doubt
an underestimate.
</P>
<P>
   The most crucial argument against deployment, however, is its
certain destabilizing effect on the current nuclear balance. Russia
and China are bound to see it as a U.S. effort to blunt their own
nuclear deterrent and doubtless will try to enlarge their offensive
capabilities accordingly. Now that would be a genuine threat to
American security.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said it
would be irresponsible for Clinton to hand off the deployment
decision to his successor next year. No, it would be truly
irresponsible to go ahead with deployment in the face of the weak
case for and the strong arguments against it.
</P>
<P>
   Let the Pentagon continue to research better ways to counter an
enemy's missiles, but don't commit America's defense to this
misbegotten bird.
</P>
<P>
   This editorial appeared in the Atlanta Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
