<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 21:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8440 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-TOUR11-COX     07-10 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOUR11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Armstrong battles miserable conditions to take lead in Tour de
France
 &HT;    By Suzanne Halliburton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOURDES-HAUTACAM, France _ The conditions were miserable Monday,
with an unseasonably cold wind whistling through the passes of the
Pyrenees Mountains, making it seem more like winter than the middle
of July. Rain, ranging from drizzle to a heavy downpour, was
compounding matters, giving the steep, narrow roads more of a
treacherous air.
</P>
<P>
   And then there was the nasty mist that shrouded the tops of the
two steepest climbs, the Col d'Aubisque and the Hautacam, which the
Tour de France cyclists would encounter later in the day.
</P>
<P>
   Austin's Lance Armstrong heard the weather report early Monday
as he was eating breakfast at his hotel outside Dax, where he and
his U.S. Postal Service teammates were staying prior to stage 10.
He laughed in anticipation.
</P>
<P>
   No other rider shared his perverse glee.
</P>
<P>
   Monday morning, Armstrong, the defending Tour champion, started
the 127-mile race in 16th place overall. A little more than six
hours after the start of this frightful stage, Armstrong burst
through the dripping mist as the new leader.
</P>
<P>
   As expected, all the sprinters who were ahead of him to start
the morning fell by the wayside. But the fact that Armstrong
dominated his chief competitors in this first mountain stage
shocked many who closely follow the world's greatest cycling event.
</P>
<P>
   ``His total domination is leaving everybody speechless,'' said
Mark Gorski, general manager of the U.S. Postal Service team. ``You
could just hear the gasps in the media room. I don't think anyone
thought he would be this completely devastating.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong finished second to Spain's Javier Otxoa, a mountain
specialist, in Monday's stage 10, which ended with a mile-high
climb to the summit of the Hautacam. Armstrong started the day 5
minutes, 44 seconds out of first place.
</P>
<P>
   He ended the afternoon with a 4:14 cushion over Jan Ullrich, the
champion of the 1997 Tour. Christophe Moreau was in third at 5:18.
</P>
<P>
   Marco Pantani, who won the 1998 Tour and has a reputation for
making up large chunks of time in the mountain stages, was 25th,
10:34 behind Armstrong. Laurent Jalabert, who wore the yellow
jersey for three days last week, was 18th and 8:01 out of first.
Alberto Elli, who donned yellow to start Monday's stage, was 57th
at the end of it, 25:35 behind Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
   The yellow jersey, which Armstrong wore for the final 12 stages
of last year's Tour, fit as comfortably as it did last July. After
his performance, he found himself answering questions about whether
he had clinched the Tour championship 11 stages from its finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because someone has the lead now, he can lose it like
that,'' Armstrong said. ``With two weeks to go, the Tour is still
anybody's race.''
</P>
<P>
   His performance suggested otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Otxoca gained the stage lead near the top of the Aubisque, which
at 1,709 meters was the highest climb for the day. Another group of
eight elite riders, including Richard Virenque and Fernando
Escartin, reached the top 10 minutes after Otxoca.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong got there almost 12 minutes after Otxoca. He was
accompanied by Pantani, who by now had shed his trademark bandana;
Ullrich and Alex Zulle, who finished second to Armstrong in the
1999 Tour. By this time, Armstrong's protectors, teammates Kevin
Livingston of Austin and Tyler Hamilton, had dropped back in the
pack.
</P>
<P>
   ``This group (of top contenders) went ahead pretty early, and by
this time I didn't have any teammates beside me,'' Armstrong said.
``I had no idea what to do. My only choice was to wait.''
</P>
<P>
   With just more than seven miles to go, as the riders approached
the Hautacam climb, Pantani pounced, making his move to distance
himself from Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong immediately stood forward on his bike, deciding then
that it was time to increase the pace. Over the next three miles,
he made up Virenque's 1:10 margin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Armstrong went like an airplane,'' Virenque said.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the fans who had waited more than six hours in the
miserable weather to see the finish stood on the course, inches
from Armstrong, urging him on. A lone American flag waved as he
neared the finish.
</P>
<P>
   Otxoa appeared to have expended most of his energy by the final
mile, as he literally wobbled toward the finish. But Armstrong
couldn't pass the Spaniard, who blew kisses to the crowd and
crossed himself as he passed the finish line.
</P>
<P>
   Over the final 22 miles, Armstrong made up more than 10 minutes
on Otxoa. Jose Maria Jimenez gave the pro-Spanish crowd even more
to cheer, finishing third. Virenque was fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Otxoa deserved to win,'' Armstrong said. ``He was away all
day. He rode a fantastic race. He rode hard, and about 99 percent
of those people out there were Spanish and cheering him on. I'm
proud of him.''
</P>
<P>
   As for his own performance, Armstrong said: ``I don't know if
I'm stronger than I was last year. I tell you that the tests I did
before the Tour indicate that I'm faster. But the form is a funny
thing. It comes on slowly and it goes away quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Carmichael, who has coached Armstrong for a decade,
watched Monday's stage unfold almost as he had predicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was just doing what he's been doing,'' said Carmichael, who
watched the stage with Armstrong's wife, Kristin, and son, Luke.
``It's what has been in him this whole time. I knew no one would be
stronger, and I said that before the Tour started.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
