<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: IRANIANS PROTEST
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of Iranians in exile demonstrated in Berlin against
the start of a three-day state visit by President Mohammad Khatami.
The police arrested scattered protesters after detaining dozens of
opponents of the Tehran government during overnight searches of
local residences. Security is high during Khatami's visit, the
first by an Iranian leader since the 1979 Islamic revolution.
Critics had urged Germany to withdraw the invitation because of
Iran's poor rights record.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE: MORE MAD COW DISEASE
</P>
<P>
   Officials have found another three cases of mad cow disease,
bringing the total this year to 26. The new outbreaks virtually
assure that authorities will discover far more cases this year than
they did last year, when 31 cases were recorded. Officials had
hoped to see the number of cases declining by now. A testing
program that started last month is likely to increase the number of
cases even further, officials have warned.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA: LATVIA ACCUSED
</P>
<P>
   Russia accused Latvia of ``blatantly inhuman'' behavior after a
court ordered an 87-year-old Russian veteran imprisoned for two
years for World War II crimes against humanity. The former Soviet
KGB official was convicted of persecuting dozens of people, nine of
whom were condemned to death. Russia has long accused Latvia, its
former satellite, of discriminating against ethnic Russians.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   INDIA: CHURCH BLAST INQUIRY
</P>
<P>
   Surveillance and patrolling at all places of worship has been
increased and a special team of detectives has been formed to
investigate recent explosions in churches, said S.M. Krishna, chief
minister of the southern state of Karnataka. A Bangalore church was
hit by an explosion on Sunday, and in June, bombs exploded in four
churches in the states of Karnata, Andhra Pradesh and Goa.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL: ROYAL TRADE VISIT
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to build trade and cultural ties with Latin
America's largest country, King Juan Carlos I and Queen Sofia of
Spain have arrived for a weeklong visit that includes meetings with
political and business leaders in four cities. Spain is now the
second-largest foreign investor in such key sectors of the
Brazilian economy as telecommunications and electrical power,
exceeded only by the United States.
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA: NEW FINANCE MINISTER
</P>
<P>
   With the country mired in its worst economic crisis in a
century, Juan Manuel Santos, a former trade minister under the
opposition Liberal Party, has been named finance minister to
replace Juan Camilo Restrepo, who resigned. Other cabinet changes
are expected to follow as the embattled president, Andres Pastrana,
tries to fashion a ``national unity'' government.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: SUSPECT ARRESTED
</P>
<P>
   Police officers detained Agustin Vazquez Mendoza, accused by
American authorities as the mastermind of the murder in Glendale,
Ariz., of an undercover American drug agent, Richard Fass. In June
1994, Fass was killed by gunmen allegedly working for Vazquez
during negotiations for the $160,000 purchase of 22 pounds of
methamphetamine, according to a statement by the U.S. Drug
Enforcement Administration. American authorities requested
Vazquez's extradition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
