<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 21:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8443 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-K2DESIGN-AD-COLUMN-NY     07-10 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-K2DESIGN-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
K2 DESIGN ACQUIRING SILVERCUBE TO BETTER SERVE ADS TO MOBILE WEB
USERS 
</HEADLINE>
   By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A leading agency in the interactive services field is
branching out with its first acquisition, entering the potentially
lucrative but risky realm of wireless services.
</P>
<P>
   K2 Design Inc. in New York, which handles Internet marketing for
advertisers like Hewlett-Packard, IBM, Philips and Standard &AMP;
Poor's, plans to announce Tuesday that it will join with a venture
capital partnership to indirectly acquire for $14.8 million in
stock and cash a majority interest in SilverCube Inc., a wireless
professional services company that works for marketers like General
Motors Corp. and Edmunds, a clearing house for automotive data.
</P>
<P>
   SilverCube, based in Rochester, Mich., specializes in strategy
and content development for the new generation of cellular
telephones, pagers, hand-held computers and other devices that
deliver text in the form of news headlines, e-mail _ and yes,
advertisements. K2 and Unwired Ventures I, a partnership of Emerald
Ventures Capital in King of Prussia, Pa., will join forces for the
deal and will operate four offices under the SilverCube name.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is indicative of the growing interest in the wireless
Internet among agencies that were founded in the 1990s to
capitalize on the boom in its wired counterpart. The ability to
gain access to the World Wide Web through, say, a display panel on
a cellular telephone or a personal digital assistant is appealing
to marketers that want to aim sales pitches at consumers based on
geography or demographics, as evinced by the formation of the
Wireless Advertising Association.
</P>
<P>
   But there are daunting challenges associated with m-business
(dial ``m'' for mobile) that vary from technical shortcomings to
disparate formats to the costs of gaining wireless access to the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is doing what they did with the Internet in '94,
saying `Here are the limitations of the current technology,
therefore it won't be a component of everyday life,''' Matt de
Ganon, executive chairman at K2, said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``A pure-play wireless professional services company will help
companies sort out the morass of competing issues,'' said de Ganon,
who was joined by executives of SilverCube and Emerald Ventures in
a telephone interview as they provided a preview of the coming
deal.
</P>
<P>
   After the deal goes through, K2 will own 38.2 percent of
SilverCube, Unwired Ventures I will own 35.3 percent and current
shareholders of SilverCube will own 26.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we saw in the people at K2 was their embrace of wireless
technologies,'' said Greg Guidice, chief executive at SilverCube.
</P>
<P>
   ``The devices will continue to change,'' he added, ``but as
everyone becomes more and more familiar with the wired Web, we're
finding they want to take information where they want, when they
want, with wireless.''
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Guidice said, ``our Edmunds clients say they get
phone calls on the weekend'' from car shoppers in metropolitan
Detroit, where auto dealerships are closed on Saturdays, ``who want
to compare the Oldsmobile Aurora to the Toyota Camry.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to tell the callers to check out the Web site,'' he
added. ``But with wireless, we give that ability to do comparisons
by phone.''
</P>
<P>
   Guidice will serve as chief operating officer at SilverCube
after the deal goes through; a search for a chief executive is
under way. De Ganon and Lynn Fantom, president and chief executive
at K2, will most likely join the SilverCube board. Gary Brown,
chief operating offer at K2, will serve as interim chief financial
officer at SilverCube.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been scouring the market for potential acquisitions,''
said Brown, who joined K2 in April from units of UBS, the Swiss
banking company. ``SilverCube has done some pretty significant
business in the unwired segment already with GM, among others.''
</P>
<P>
   For GM, SilverCube designed and introduced a way for users of
personal digital assistants to visit a condensed version of the
Oldsmobile Web site to obtain data like model specifications and
dealer addresses. That is being expanded to the rest of the GM
domestic divisions.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps SilverCube could persuade Leo Burnett, Oldsmobile's
advertising agency, to revive a familiar ad slogan and promote the
new wireless access as ``not your father's wired Internet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
