<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GOP: Get ready for a new convention
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GOP National Convention officials on Monday announced details of
``a different kind of convention for a different kind of
Republican.'' But a watchdog group says it will be paid for by the
same old corporate cash.
</P>
<P>
   In a report entitled ``And Now a Message From Our Sponsors,''
the Center for Responsive Politics detailed the high-dollar
donations that will help pay for this summer's national political
conventions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dozens of the nation's biggest companies, many of which have
major issues pending before Congress, are lining up to help foot
the bill for this year's conventions, some writing seven-figure
checks to each of the events' local host committees,'' said the
report from the center that monitors money and politics.
</P>
<P>
   Each party gets $13.3 million in federal funds to pay for their
conventions. The Republicans gather in Philadelphia July 31 - Aug.
3. The Democrats meet in Los Angeles Aug. 14-17.
</P>
<P>
   The government money doesn't come close to paying for the
conventions, however. The GOP event has a price tag of $50 million,
$20 million more than the party spent in San Diego in 1996.
Democrats plan to spend $35 million, a $5 million hike from four
years ago in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Both parties look to corporate America to help pick up the tab.
Sixteen corporations have given at least $500,000 for the GOP
convention. Ten corporations have been at least that generous to
Democratic convention organizers.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the high-dollar donors have high-stakes interests
pending in Washington. The top single donor, American International
Group, which gave $2 million for the Democratic convention, has
successfully lobbied for deregulation of the financial services
industry as well as open trade with China, a change that could
benefit the company.
</P>
<P>
   AIG also gave $500,000 for the Republican convention.
</P>
<P>
   US Airways, awaiting congressional support for its proposed
merger with United Airlines, has given $500,000 to the GOP
convention. United Airlines is a $500,000 donor to the Democratic
event.
</P>
<P>
   The list of top donors to the conventions also includes General
Motors, Microsoft Corp. and a variety of telecommunications firms.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Fitzpatrick, spokesman for the GOP convention organizing
committee, referred all questions about the money to the host
committee, a private entity set up to raise money for the event.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are set up to gather the resources for the convention,''
he said. ``Technically, it's not accurate to say the Republicans
are getting these contributions.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials with the host committee did not return Monday phone
calls.
</P>
<P>
   For the Republicans, the corporate money will help pay for a
convention aimed at putting a new face on the Grand Old Party.
Details about the convention were released Monday by Andy Card,
general co-chairman of the event and former transportation
secretary under President George Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The Philadelphia event will break some of the rules of
convention scheduling and operate under the theme: ``Renewing
America's Purpose. Together.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are abandoning the tradition of dedicating an entire night
to old-style attack politics,'' Card added. ``Our primary focus
will be talking about what we stand for as a party and where
Governor Bush wants to take the country. However, elections are
about choices, and we expect our speakers to compare and contrast
Governor Bush's positions with those of Al Gore and the current
administration _ clearly defining our differences on the issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Each night will have an issue theme, beginning with education on
July 31. The speakers will include Laura Bush and retired Gen.
Colin Powell. The second night will feature national security
issues, with speeches from Elizabeth Dole, Sen. John McCain and
Condoleezza Rice, a Bush adviser who is expected to play a major
role in the White House is Bush is elected.
</P>
<P>
   Though McCain is riding to the convention in the Straight Talk
Express bus he used during the presidential campaign to highlight
campaign finance reform, his comments will be limited to national
security issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he wanted to talk about strength and security,'' Card
said.
</P>
<P>
   Maintaining prosperity is the theme of the third night, which
also will include a speech from the vice presidential nominee,
something that generally happens on the fourth and final night of
national conventions.
</P>
<P>
   Bush will offer his acceptance speech, as dictated by tradition,
on the final night. The governor is expected to arrive in
Philadelphia on the convention's third night, but he will appear in
live remotes from the campaign trail on the first two nights.
</P>
<P>
   Bush will be nominated on the convention's third night. Instead
of the usual one-night roll call of the states, voting will be
spread over the first three nights.
</P>
<P>
   In another effort to show the GOP as more inclusive than it has
been in the past, Bush is making sure that women and minorities
have key roles. The convention's co-chairs are U.S. Reps. Henry
Bonilla of San Antonio, Jennifer Dunn of Washington and J.C. Watts
of Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our party is one that is inclusive and that stands for the
issues important to Americans,'' said Bonilla, the Texas'
congressional delegation's only Hispanic Republican. ``I look
forward to to being a part of this historic event for both Texas
and America.''
</P>
