u f BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT     07-10 0642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FCC MULLS RADIO LICENSES
</P>
<P>
   For months, Republicans in Congress have sought to block a
Federal Communications Commission program to license thousands of
new low-power radio stations. About half of the first batch of
applications are from religious organizations, mostly the sorts of
fundamentalist churches active in conservative, Republican
politics.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of evangelical churches are asking for space on the
airwaves to spread the Gospel. Some simply want to read Scripture
verbatim; others want to preach against abortion. They will not get
the chance, however, if the Republican congressional leadership
gets its way.
</P>
<P>
   CLANCY FOLDS CHARITY
</P>
<P>
   After seven years, the writer Tom Clancy is scuttling a
foundation that he set up to help children who had cancer and other
illnesses use the Internet to talk with one another and learn about
their diseases. Despite spending more than $5 million on travel,
salaries, fund-raising and furniture, the foundation did not even
have a Web site to show for its efforts. The legal fight that has
broken out over the collapse of the foundation offers a rare
glimpse at the inner workings of a celebrity charity.
</P>
<P>
   ALCOA BEATS FORECASTS
</P>
<P>
   Alcoa said that its second-quarter profit rose 57 percent,
beating Wall Street forecasts by 2 cents, as aluminum prices rose
and productivity improved. Revenue rose 38 percent, to $5.62
billion. Shares of Alcoa increased 7 percent, or $2.0625, to
$29.6875. They had dropped 33 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   DOW RISES, OTHERS DECLINE
</P>
<P>
   Stocks ended mixed in subdued trading, with blue chips pulling
ahead and technology issues slipping. The Dow Jones industrial
average rose 10.60 points, or 0.10 percent, to 10,646.58. The
Nasdaq composite index dropped 42.91 points, or 1.1 percent, to
3,980.29, while the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index fell 3.28
points, or 0.2 percent, to 1,475.62.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON PLANS FUEL RESERVE
</P>
<P>
   Reacting to widespread concern over climbing heating oil prices
and low inventories, President Clinton announced a plan to
establish a fuel reserve for the Northeast, where most of the
country's heating oil is consumed.
</P>
<P>
   ICO-TELEDESIC GETS $300 MILLION
</P>
<P>
   ICO-Teledesic Global Limited, the satellite telecommunications
venture controlled by Craig McCaw, said it had received commitments
for nearly $300 million from influential investors, including Bill
Gates, chairman of Microsoft Corp., and the private investment firm
Clayton, Dubilier &AMP; Rice.
</P>
<P>
   HONEYWELL WARNS ON EARNINGS
</P>
<P>
   Honeywell International warned that its second-quarter profit
would be 75 cents a share, about 3 cents less than it had predicted
earlier this year. Honeywell also lowered its earnings estimates
for the full year and for 2001.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. SUES TOYSMART.COM
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Trade Commission sued to prevent Toysmart.com, a
bankrupt Internet toy retailer, from selling its database of
customer information, asserting the company had assured hundreds of
thousands of online visitors their personal data would never be
shared with a third party.
</P>
<P>
   INVESTORS SNUB AIRBUS IPO
</P>
<P>
   The European Aeronautic Defense and Space Co., or EADS as the
new conglomerate that controls Airbus Industrie is known, received
a chilly response from investors in its long-awaited initial stock
offering as shares dropped more than 9 percent. Philippe Camus, a
co-chief executive, responded by saying: ``You must be humble with
the market. The market indicated to us the price it was ready to
pay. End of story.''
</P>
<P>
   IRELAND CAPS DRINK PRICES
</P>
<P>
   The Irish government took a step to slow the country's racing
inflation rates last week by temporarily capping the prices of all
alcoholic beverages and some soft drinks.
</P>
</TEXT>
