u p BC-REPUBS-CONVENTION-NYT     07-10 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-CONVENTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S SHOW   TIME AT THE GOP CORRAL, AS TRADITIONS YIELD TO RATING 
</HEADLINE>
   By PETER MARKS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The delegation from the great state of Florida may want to brag
from the convention floor about its championship college football
team, while the great state of Wisconsin may seek to tout its
mouthwatering cheeses. But those gushy expressions of state pride
may not command the same level of attention this year as they have
at previous party conventions.
</P>
<P>
   Saying that the traditional roll call of states had become too
long and dull to sustain an evening of prime time television,
officials planning the Republican National Convention said Monday
that they intended to dim the spotlight on the state-by-state
presidential nominating process by spreading the tally over three
nights.
</P>
<P>
   ``One giant chunk of time devoted to counting votes may be
gripping if you are a floor clerk in the House or Senate,'' said
Ari Fleischer, a spokesman for the presumptive Republican nominee,
Gov. George W. Bush of Texas. ``But for 249 million other
Americans, it's not as captivating.'' Convention officials have
told the networks the votes will occur earlier in each evening's
program.
</P>
<P>
   The establishment of the ``rolling roll call'' subject to the
approval of the party's rules committee, is one of a number of
innovations the Republicans say they have developed to make their
convention in Philadelphia more palatable and engaging to viewers.
It is a gathering, vowed Andrew Card, the convention's general
co-chairman, ``that is going to look, sound and feel different from
the conventions of the past.''
</P>
<P>
   It is also a gathering, say some professional convention
watchers, that will further advance the evolution of the event into
a marketing vehicle. Steve Scully, political editor of C-Span,
which will provide pool television coverage of the proceedings,
said that traditionally the conventions were platforms for
governors and senators to speak on the issues that concerned them.
The plan for prime time outlined by Card entails speeches by just
two elected officials: Bush and Sen. John McCain of Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``The era of political conventions being just for politicians is
changing, and may be over,'' Scully said. ``Now you have
conventions that are timed to the minute, to the second for the
hometown audience. It's a production, not a convention.''
</P>
<P>
   Others who were given prime time slots include Bush's wife,
Laura; Gen. Colin Powell, former head of the Joint Chiefs of Staff;
Bush's adviser on security and foreign policy issues, Condoleezza
Rice, and former transportation secretary Elizabeth Dole. Card said
while it was not certain anyone would be designated the keynote
speaker, more people might be added to the speakers' list. The vice
presidential nominee will speak on the convention's third night.
</P>
<P>
   Card, speaking with reporters by conference call Monday, said
the departures from tradition will be apparent in everything from
the benevolent tone of the proceedings _ attacks on the opposition
will be kept to a minimum, he asserted _ to the design of the
podium. The podium traditionally ``looked like the turret of a
castle,'' Card said, adding that this year, it ``will look more
like a stage,'' giving the Republicans more flexibility to use it
for performances by entertainers and ``short presentations from
people across America.''
</P>
<P>
   The slogan for the convention, which begins July 31, is
``Renewing America's Purpose. Together.'' Card said there would be
a specific theme on each of the four evenings: education and health
care on Monday; military strength on Tuesday and prosperity and
protecting Social Security on Wednesday. Thursday will be devoted
to Bush's acceptance speech.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, for instance, will speak on the evening devoted to the
military, Card said.
</P>
<P>
   Republican officials said they were mindful of the need to make
the event as attractive as possible to the networks, and one
network news official, who spoke on condition on anonymity, called
the rolling roll call a ``very smart'' idea, in that the broadcast
networks had no interest in airing the vote in prime time.
</P>
<P>
   While cable channels like CNN, Fox News Channel and MSNBC plan
gavel-to-gavel coverage, the much more heavily watched broadcast
networks are scaling back. Elizabeth O'Connell, executive producer
of special events for NBC News and MSNBC, said that how much
exposure NBC News would provide on its flagship broadcast network
would not be decided until convention officials unveiled a more
detailed final schedule.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
