<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 21:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8457 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-TEN-WOODS-SAMPRAS-COX     07-10 0601
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WOODS-SAMPRAS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sampras is the greatest player ever
 &HT;    By Mark Woods
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nobody complained that Joe Montana was too composed.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody griped that Joe DiMaggio was too calm.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody whined that Jack Nicklaus was too polite.
</P>
<P>
   Yet these, I hear, are the problems with Pete Sampras. Even
today. Even after Sampras won Wimbledon for the seventh time,
surpassing Roy Emerson with a 13th Grand Slam title and earning the
right to proclaim himself the greatest men's tennis player ever _ a
right he, of course, will never exercise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll never sit here and tell you that I'm the best ever,''
Sampras once said.
</P>
<P>
   It is a pledge he has upheld.
</P>
<P>
   Even after his victory against Patrick Rafter, Sampras left the
debate to others. The one gaping hole in his resume, the lack of a
French Open title, does give detractors a little ammunition. And it
is true that Rod Laver certainly would have added to his 11 Grand
Slams if he hadn't been forced to skip majors after turning pro for
the final five years of his career.
</P>
<P>
   But to go as far as some have _ ``Is Sampras' legacy tainted?''
said a headline on one Internet site _ is absurd.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras, still only 28, has racked up his titles in an era of
parity; an era when the never-heard-of-him, No. 232-ranked player
is capable of upsetting the top-10 player; an era when it is hard
to maintain the health and intensity necessary to even stay in the
game, let alone atop it.
</P>
<P>
   He is the greatest ever.
</P>
<P>
   And although there is a temptation today to compare him to Tiger
Woods, that would be unfair _ to Sampras.
</P>
<P>
   What Woods is doing in golf _ taking modern technology and
producing a revolutionary blend of power and touch _ Sampras has
been doing for a lot longer in tennis. Since 1993, he has a 53-1
record at his game's grandest of Grand Slams. And that statistic
doesn't do his play at Wimbledon justice.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, he has been too good.
</P>
<P>
   Technology has been kinder to Woods. On the golf course, it
produces ``oohs'' and ``aahs.'' On a tennis court, it produces
yawns.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us back to the criticism.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras is boring.
</P>
<P>
   In other sports, it is enough to be the best. In tennis, we
demand more. We demand behavior, even if it's bad ... just not too
bad, mind you.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras has learned about this fine line during his annual
visits to London, a place where the tabloids aren't shy about
voicing their opinions. Before his first Wimbledon final, a meeting
with fellow American Jim Courier, one headline screamed: ``BORED ON
THE FOURTH OF JULY.''
</P>
<P>
   ``First, I was the boring guy,'' Sampras said last week. ``Then
I was the biggest, most hated man in England. I wasn't sure how you
guys wanted me to act _ boring or like a lunatic.''
</P>
<P>
   Call me a lunatic, but I kind of like boring.
</P>
<P>
   In this age of players celebrating after a tackle at the line of
scrimmage, I welcome someone who only pumps his fists after a truly
big shot.
</P>
<P>
   In this age of Dick Vermeil crying after a mid-season victory, I
appreciate someone who saved his tears for big moments like while
struggling through a five-set match in Australia after your dying
coach collapses. Or when your parents finally agree to come watch
you play in Wimbledon _ and you survive a nerve-racking,
rain-filled day and emerge with Slam No. 13.
</P>
<P>
   The greatest ever?
</P>
<P>
   In this age of everyone proclaiming themselves No. 1, I like the
fact that Sampras has resisted. Even now. Especially now.
</P>
<P>
   markwoods(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
