<HEADER>
A8458 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-PARIS-FASHION-NYT &LR;      07-10 1242
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARIS-FASHION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASHION, THE FLASH AND THE FLASHBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   By CATHY HORYN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ ``Fashion is about never achieving anything,'' Karl
Lagerfeld said a month ago in an interview. ``You make one good
collection, it doesn't mean there will be another.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet this sense of futility, combined with the prospect of
renewal, is also what drives designers like Lagerfeld, maybe all
creative people, and he likened it to the lash that keeps newspaper
writers toiling in pulp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your work,'' he told me, ``is ready for the vegetable
drippings, and ours is for the markdowns. We know this, and that's
why we start again.''
</P>
<P>
   Knowing this makes it easier to view the frank display of
fetishism that John Galliano put on the runway for Christian Dior
on Saturday _ the start of the fall 2000 haute couture collections
_ without taking any of it too seriously. So Galliano likes the
idea of seeing women trussed up in bondage gear against a
background noise of whips and sighs? Last season it was the
down-and-out look of tramps that lit his lamp, and made front-page
news.
</P>
<P>
   But can any of this really matter if the action is constantly,
and blithely, shifting?
</P>
<P>
   Now a bum, now a voyeur peeping through a keyhole at what was,
and may still be, taboo. ``Very edgy,'' said the actress Kate
Capshaw of the show, as she made her way through a throng of
photographers and autograph seekers with her husband, Steven
Spielberg. ``Very Kubrickian,'' Spielberg said.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, it was. The show, bathed in carnal red lights,
conjured up a vision of disorder and sexual obsession that brought
to mind the violence and perversity in Kubrick's ``Eyes Wide
Shut''and ``A Clockwork Orange.''
</P>
<P>
   Here, on the runway, were suave-looking young men in smooth
Mayfair lounge haircuts and the crisply tailored regalia of empire,
circa 1912 _ officers' field coats, tails and top hats, a kilt
exquisitely worked in sequins. They strolled out among women in
reedy, quivering ivory frocks and mushrooming Edwardian hairdos.
Then the tempo changed: Galliano, who had said before the show that
he thought Christian Dior was one of the first fetishists in
fashion, because he had put women in corsets and was himself ``in
complete awe of his mother,'' parted the curtain, opened the
kimono, to reveal the mischief (naughty nurse, fleshy maid with a
hickey on her neck) of a nice, respectable Edwardian family.
</P>
<P>
   Ten or 15 years ago, before the dawn of tabloid television, one
could have been shocked by the sight of a woman with her mouth
taped shut or another with her arms held down by handcuffs chained
to her belt. And, of course, one can think of the designers who
have been this way before _ namely, Gianni Versace, Jean Paul
Gaultier and Vivienne Westwood.
</P>
<P>
   When news of the Dior show trickled back to him, Lagerfeld said
he could never bring himself to seriously design clothes with whips
and zips because he'd be laughing too hard. That's sort of the way
one felt. Many of the clothes were undeniably spectacular _ a coat
made of tiny stripes of feathers, a gown cut from a length of
alligator skin, a dress of cadet-blue silk with gold military
buttons and lacing up the back. It's also true that the Dior
workrooms were flooded with orders from the spring hobo collection,
especially from young clients, though most designs were toned down.
And so will the latest examples be.
</P>
<P>
   As I sat at lunch Monday at L'Avenue, the swanky bistro, a Dior
staff assistant happened by with a portfolio of sketches of this
collection made palatable for clients. So there's no reason to get
in a twist over Saturday's outrage. It's already history.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander McQueen has had enough uneven seasons at Givenchy to
generate rumors that this would be his last. But after his show on
Sunday, as guests poured backstage, Yves Carcelle, the president of
LVMH Moet Hennessy Louis Vuitton, the owner, was dismissive of the
gossip. ``It's just another rumor in the perverted fashion world,''
he said. McQueen's show _ a kind of party within a party _ was
brilliant.
</P>
<P>
   The set, concealed by four walls that dropped down when the show
began, resembled the sort of funky loft one might see in the East
Village. Cool couples danced around. A D.J. flipped electronic
switches next to a refrigerator. Then came the models, wending
among the party people, in couture's version of modern club
clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Here was the model Alek Wek in patchwork leather hip-huggers
with some sort of flippy-hippy jacket over her zebra top and a
cocoon of fur around her head. Nothing really went together, yet
everything did. A strait-laced jumpsuit, a go-go girl get-up in
pastel leather, a Super Fly cap ballooning like a beanbag chair _
but of course. It's hard to make couture seem valid in a world
where sometimes the choicest thing is a cut-off T-shirt and a
pierced navel. But it's also hard to bring a sense of real
individuality to clothes without the imaginative ballast of
couture. McQueen is a genuine guide.
</P>
<P>
   On her way into Versace on Saturday night, Jennifer Lopez,
dressed in a low-cut Versace number and accompanied by her
boyfriend, Sean Combs, and the usual posse of bodyguards, said in a
plaintive voice to Donatella Versace, ``But I want to know what I'm
going to wear to the Oscars!''
</P>
<P>
   Evidently she can't wait to find out. Nor can Spielberg and
Capshaw, who were front and center. Nor can Gwyneth Paltrow, who
seems to have evolved into a karaoke couture client _ wearing this
dress from Calvin, touting that bag for Dior and surfacing, not for
the first time, in Versace.
</P>
<P>
   But this is fashion _ it's anybody's game, and Versace knows how
to play it with confidence. Her clothes this season emphasize
softness, with hints of volume in sleeves, and cool colors like
lavender, melon and chartreuse. Sun-ray pleats burst with tiny
stones. A floor-length sable coat draped over a filmy top and a
tight pair of pants _ Versace called it the new cocktail suit. The
clothes were the kind you could imagine on anyone with a body, a
taste for flashbulb glamour and the means to indulge it.
</P>
<P>
   Gaultier's approach, on the other hand, is decidedly more
French, and more in the deep grain of tradition. His show on Sunday
lacked the mesmerizing vivacity of last season, when his orders
doubled. But it was solid, with hints of the 1920s, in
loose-fitting dresses with beaded fringe and feathered wigs swathed
in netting. Gaultier's homage to the Eiffel Tower _ upturned as
heels, sparkling in beads _ could have been a hard right to the
souvenir stands of the Rue de Rivoli without his clever eye.
</P>
<P>
   So the new guard keeps advancing while the older denizens of
couture do their best to keep up. Valentino's show, on Sunday
night, was exquisitely heavy going, chic to a fault _ the right
shoe, the right display of beads, but all without feeling. Emanuel
Ungaro's show Monday, in a tunnel near the Seine, was all
lightness. Beautiful, weightless jackets floated over slender
trousers and tops as simple as T-shirts. Feathers of distressed
chiffon glazed a coral coat, and siren gowns in ivory and lavender
were a modern update of the ravish-me style.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there was that sense of family as new and old clients
swanned in blowing air kisses. As Nan Kempner, arriving at the
Ungaro show in a Saint Laurent python coat, said, ``I think my
epitaph should read, `I've kissed a heck of a lot of people I don't
know.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
