<DOCNO> NYT20000710.0437 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8461 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-TIMES-EARNINGS-NYT &LR;      07-10 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMES-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRONG NEWSPAPER AD SALES BOOST EARNINGS FOR TIMES CO. AND
GANNETT 
</HEADLINE>
   By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The flood of advertising that has carried newspaper
company profits to record earnings during the last year continued
almost unabated in the second quarter for both The New York Times
Co., whose net income increased 18.6 percent, and the Gannett Co.,
whose profit increased by 13 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Times Co. posted net income of $101.7 million, or 59 cents a
share, compared with $85.8 million, or 48 cents a share, in the
quarter a year earlier. Including special items, net income in the
period a year earlier was $83.5 million, or 47 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue jumped 13.6 percent, to $885.6 million from $779.4
million. Excluding figures from The Worcester Telegram &AMP; Gazette in
Massachusetts, which the company acquired in January, revenue rose
10.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The results beat analysts' estimates by 3 cents a share,
according to First Call/Thomson Financial, which tracks company
earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Gannett reported net income of $265.8 million, or $1 a share,
compared with profit from operations of $234.8 million, or 84 cents
a share, in the period a year earlier. Revenue rose 16 percent, to
$1.49 billion from $1.28 billion. In the quarter a year earlier, a
gain of $33 million, or 11 cents a share, related to an exchange of
television stations in Texas and California, and profit of $9.4
million, or 3 cents a share, from discontinued cable operations
made net income $277 million, or 98 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   Gannett's results matched Wall Street expectations, according to
First Call.
</P>
<P>
   For the Times Co., excluding results at The Telegram &AMP; Gazette,
advertising revenue increased 14.3 percent, to $564 million, fueled
by a 16.5 percent increase in advertising revenue at The New York
Times and 14.8 percent at The Boston Globe. Including The Telegram
&AMP; Gazette, advertising revenue was $580 million, up 17.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   At New York Times Digital, the company's Internet division,
revenue grew to $13.5 million from $5 million, while operating
losses rose to $15.5 million from $4.6 million. The company
attributed the increased losses to higher staff and promotion costs
associated with Abuzz Technologies Inc., which the company acquired
last year.
</P>
<P>
   The Times Co. has registered with the Securities and Exchange
Commission to issue a stock tracking the results of New York Times
Digital and has won shareholder approval, but it has not set a date
for the offering.
</P>
<P>
   William Drewry, an analyst at Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette, said
the Times Co. results exceeded expectations ``by a very, very
comfortable margin.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's been the trend and will probably continue to be the
trend,'' he added, saying that he expected increases in the price
of newsprint _ a newspaper's biggest cost outside of labor _ to be
manageable.
</P>
<P>
   Gannett's results were announced amid a large-scale expansion at
the company, which has during the last year bought two newspaper
companies in Britain, 21 daily newspapers from Thomson Newspapers
Inc. and, most recently, Central Newspapers Inc., the publisher of
The Arizona Republic and The Indianapolis Star.
</P>
<P>
   For the second quarter, Gannett's newspaper advertising revenue
increased 21.4 percent, to $957 million.
</P>
<P>
   But Michael Beebe, an analyst with Goldman, Sachs, said that
some analysts had been concerned by a one-month ``softness'' in
advertising in June at the company's flagship newspaper, USA Today.
``What they attributed it to was softness in travel and retail
categories in particular due to tough comparisons _ due to some
advertisers taking a mid-year pause,'' Beebe said. ``That's what
spooks investors. We don't now how long this pause may last.''
</P>
<P>
   Drewry said: ``Gannett's numbers were good. The market was
disappointed that they didn't show an upside surprise. The stock's
being punished for that. But they have a lot of upside potential
for the next few quarters, given their acquisitions.''
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Gannett fell $1.875 Monday, to $57.0625, while shares
of the Times Co. rose 93.75 cents, to $40.9375.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-00 2153EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
