<DOCNO> NYT20000710.0438 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8462 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-MICKEY-VERSUS-BANKQCO     07-10 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICKEY-VERSUS-BANKQCOX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bank seeks Mickey Mouse drawings for debt
 &HT;    By Gary Schwan
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOCA RATON _ Mickey Mouse could be in police custody Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   SunTrust Bank has filed a petition to seize 36 drawings of the
famed rodent valued at $3.7 million from the International Museum
of Cartoon Art as penalty for missing mortgage payments. A hearing
will be held today in Palm Beach County Circuit Court.
</P>
<P>
   The drawings were created for the 1928 cartoon Plane Crazy, the
first animated film featuring Mickey Mouse. The museum used the
drawings as collateral for a $3 million loan in 1995 to build its
showplace in Mizner Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are our `Mona Lisa,''' said museum founder and chairman
Mort Walker, creator of the Beetle Bailey comic strip. ``They are
very delicate and we have taken very good care of them. Now it
looks like the sheriff will be coming in Wednesday to take them off
the wall and march them away.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These are popular art icons, and to just remove them without
concern about protecting them is worrisome,'' said Walker's wife,
Catherine. She said the drawings are protected by security and
sophisticated temperature controls at the museum. ``We even cover
them with a black cloth at night.''
</P>
<P>
   The Walkers want the bank to leave the drawings at the museum
until refinancing can be arranged. ``We would even be willing to
put up a sign'' declaring the works the bank's property, said
Catherine Walker. ``Our concern is the care of the drawings.''
</P>
<P>
   SunTrust attorney Lisa Hermann declined comment Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The museum owes roughly $1.1 million to SunTrust, but has missed
$20,000 in quarterly interest payments since October, largely
because of a proposed partnership with Florida Atlantic University,
according to Mort Walker. The deal fell through last month after
criticism from city officials. Under the agreement, the FAU
Foundation would have picked up the museum's debt in return for
using part of its building for classrooms and other projects, he
said. Foundation officials couldn't be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had been negotiating with FAU for six months, and there was
an agreement that they would pay all our bills'' if the deal was
approved by the city, said Walker. ``We asked for an extension in
October, and by January we were talking with FAU'' and thought the
bills would soon be paid.
</P>
<P>
   Walker said the museum is refinancing its mortgage with another
institution, and has begun talking again to other schools and arts
groups about sharing the Mizner Park building and bills. The groups
include the Boca Raton Museum of Art, which has formed a committee
to see if ``there might be a fit between the two museums,'' said
Joseph Borrow, president of the art museum's board of trustees. The
museum will open its new building in Mizner Park in January.
</P>
<P>
   The Mickey Mouse drawings were given to the museum in 1993 by
former board member Stephen A. Geppi, owner of a comic book
distributorship in Timonium, Md. They appear on six ``storyboards''
holding six drawings each. Plane Crazy was the first Mickey Mouse
film, and the third actually released to theaters.
</P>
<P>
   Walker said the museum had permission from Geppi to sell the
works if necessary. He said the American Museum Association advised
that the drawings could also be put up for collateral as long as
they weren't part of the museum's collection. The association's
guidelines frown on selling or collateralizing valuable art. ``They
aren't an official part of our collection,'' Walker said.
</P>
<P>
   Walker founded the museum in Connecticut in 1972. It moved to
Boca Raton in 1990 from Rye Brook, N.Y., and opened a $15 million,
52,000-square-foot building in Mizner Park in 1996. The first floor
exhibits portions of a 150,000-piece collection of vintage
cartoons, comic strips, films and animation art.
</P>
<P>
   Fund-raising problems have left the building's second and third
floors empty. The museum has a roughly $700,000 annual budget and
attracted some 70,000 visitors last year.
</P>
<P>
   garyschwan(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
