<HEADER>
A8465 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-IRELAND-PUBS-NYT &LR;      07-10 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-PUBS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHEERS! IRELAND FREEZES THE COST OF DRINKS TO RESTRAIN INFLATION 
</HEADLINE>
   By BRIAN LAVERY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBLIN, Ireland _ Ireland's booming economy has made it harder
for some Dubliners to find time to grab a pint at the pub these
days, what with so many people working late at the office, but they
are still angry over the soaring price of Guinness.
</P>
<P>
   Evidently, so thought the Irish government when it took steps
last week to slow the country's racing inflation rates: It began by
temporarily capping the prices of all alcoholic beverages and some
soft drinks.
</P>
<P>
   An order from the minister for consumer affairs, Tom Kitt,
limits prices to May 15 levels for six months, and covers all
drinks sold in pubs and restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first time the government has interceded to
control the cost of a drink in a country where hoisting a few is,
for many, a celebrated part of life. The government capped alcohol
prices temporarily in 1997 and 1983. Neither of those efforts did
much to suppress prices, and the latest effort may not work either.
But as Ireland wrestles with the highest inflation in the 15-nation
European Union, the government wants to show that it is at least
trying to do something.
</P>
<P>
   Economists called the price cap politically motivated,
insufficient and a poor substitute for what many have described as
a basic lack of competition in the Irish pub business. The
government regulates the number of pub licenses in Ireland, and
critics have said that one way to keep drink prices down would be
to allow more places to sell them. Legislation to do that is likely
to be debated later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Pub owners themselves reacted as though the price controls were
a bit of a joke, designed to strengthen the government's low
public-approval rating. They also noted that the greatest increase
in pub prices this year came before May, so the government decree
missed the opportunity to make a difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the government copped out,'' said Brian Smyth, 30, who
works in central Dublin at J.J. Smyth's pub, owned by his father.
``If the price was over the top, it's still over the top.''
</P>
<P>
   The price of a pint, at 2.50 Irish pounds, or about $3, has
risen about 5 percent this year, roughly comparable to the
inflation rate. Smyth estimated that the price of a pint, left
unrestricted, could have increased by another 2 percent by the end
of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Other pub owners reacted more indignantly. Dick Dunne, a
third-generation pub owner and chief executive of the Vintner's
Federation of Ireland, a trade group that represents more than
6,000 pub owners, called the price cap ``a crude and discriminatory
measure.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It removes a publican's control over his or her own
business,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With almost 10,000 pubs around the country, the Department of
Consumer Affairs will have a tough time enforcing the regulation,
even though Kitt doubled the number of inspectors _ to 24.
</P>
<P>
   More broadly, however, there is widespread agreement that drink
inflation is a relatively minor cause of Ireland's spiral of rising
prices, which at 5.2 percent is triple the average of other
European Union members. Michael Crowley, an economist at Davy
Stockbrokers, estimated that the price cap would hold down the
overall inflation rate by two-tenths of a percent at the most this
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line here is that you can't do a lot to hold down
inflation rates,'' he said. ``It wouldn't surprise me at all if we
had an inflation rate near 6 percent in late July or early
August.''
</P>
<P>
   For customers, though, a price freeze on a drink is reason
enough to buy one. Patrick Murray, 40, a customer at J.J.'s in
Dublin, said the measure would help maintain pub life as a social
fixture in Ireland. ``For where the working people go, it keeps
prices down to what they can afford,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-00 2155EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000710.0441 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8466 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-GORE-MILITARY-ABRIDGE     07-10 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-MILITARY-ABRIDGED-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR GORE, VIETNAM TOUR OF DUTY WAS BOTH EXCITING AND UNSETTLING
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photos _ NYT6,7 _ are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By MELINDA HENNEBERGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In some ways, Army Private Al Gore was never and could never
have been just one of the guys, another grunt.
</P>
<P>
   Recruiters were afraid to even sign him up without calling in a
supervisor, once they heard his name and caught on that he was the
son of that antiwar Sen. Albert Gore, and just out of Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those with lesser rank bumped him up to me because they were
scared of making a mistake,'' said Dess Stokes, the staff sergeant
on duty at the Newark Armed Forces Entrance and Examination Station
in New Jersey, where Gore went to enlist, hoping to avoid notice,
in August 1969. ``We all knew who he was because of his daddy
opposing the war.''
</P>
<P>
   No less than the Army's highest-ranking officer, Gen. William
Westmoreland, singled him out during a visit to Fort Rucker, Ala.,
where Gore was stationed for more than a year. The Army chief of
staff stopped in the middle of a farewell ceremony to pull the
young man aside for a private chat _ and kept Gore's superior
officers waiting, and watching, while he asked one of the
lowest-ranking men on the base for his thoughts on why so many
young people opposed the war.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there is no evidence that Gore sought special treatment, or
that the extra notice he got anyway provided any real protection.
On the contrary, within the parameters of his job as an Army
journalist, Gore probably assumed more risk than he had to,
helicoptering around South Vietnam interviewing soldiers who had
just seen action.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who knew Al Gore in Vietnam knows he could have sat on
his butt and he didn't,'' said Michael Roche, Gore's editor on The
Castle Courier, the newspaper of the Army's Engineering Command in
Long Binh, near Saigon. ``I had 30 or 40 stringers and 3 or 4 on
staff, and I didn't have one who traveled as much as he did.''
</P>
<P>
   And if Gore has a dirty secret from Vietnam, it is not that he
spent his tour hiding in headquarters, but that he found much of
the experience exhilarating, and loved feeling ``more alive,'' to
use his words, in the middle of the war that he and millions of
other Americans hated.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a vividness in a war zone, even if you're not in
combat,'' the vice president said recently, during one of several
interviews about his military experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're driving down a one-lane road with vegetation on both
sides, and it's an area where people say, `Keep on your toes.'
That's quite vivid. A lot of people when they came home felt
disoriented just because that vividness wasn't in their lives any
more. I know a lot of guys who felt a great urge to go back, and
the camaraderie was very intense and powerful.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore has occasionally added a splash of color to the tableau
when describing his military service. Years ago, he suggested to
reporters that he was shot at in Vietnam when he was not _ an
exaggeration that may have been less an attempt to mislead than an
attempt to make his experience more vivid.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about those statements, Gore said only this: ``I
wasn't shot at, but I was in areas where there was firing.'' He
mentioned a trip with Mike O'Hara, now a sportswriter for The
Detroit News, to Khe Sanh, near the DMZ, where Army engineers were
re-opening an abandoned airstrip.
</P>
<P>
   ``They sent in the infantry to secure it and there were
helicopter gunships firing,'' he added. ``My buddy kidded me for
digging a foxhole, but there was firing in the hills surrounding
there. It wasn't aimed at me, but I wasn't sure of that.'' O'Hara,
who was Gore's closest friend in Vietnam, has said that he
remembers the gunfire, too _ all outgoing.
</P>
<P>
   When he first ran for president, in 1988, Gore's campaign was
criticized for using photos of young Private Gore in his uniform,
carrying a standard-issue M-16. Was he trying to create the
impression that he saw combat?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an accurate picture,'' he said, irritated. ``That's what
I looked like when I was doing my job. The fact is, I carried a
pencil and a loaded M-16 A1 outside the base camp and I worked in
areas where I had to be armed.''
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore's military record is in no particular need of
improvement. He was one of only about a dozen of the 1,115 Harvard
graduates in the Class of `69 who went to Vietnam. And even before
enlisting, he passed up a chance to serve in the National Guard _
the military option chosen by his presidential opponent, George W.
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   A cousin of Gore said she and her then-husband had secured the
promise of a place for him in the Alabama Guard. ``I had friends
who had gone to Vietnam, and one who had come back a paraplegic,
and I was beside myself wanting to keep Al out of there,'' said the
cousin, Gayle Byrne, of Birmingham, who grew up near Carthage,
Tenn, where the Gores spent summers on their farm. So Byrne's
former husband, a member of the Guard, asked a well-placed contact
to hold a spot for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``When the word came back that yes, they would hold a slot, we
were so excited we called Al right away,'' Byrne remembered. ``But
he said, ``I appreciate what you've done, but I just don't believe
I can do this.' He talked about how small the draft roll was in
Carthage'' _ and how, if he did not serve, someone he knew would
have to take his place.
</P>
<P>
   The decision was complicated by his father's upcoming 1970
Senate race, which everyone anticipated as his toughest, in large
part because of Senator Gore's stand against the war. Though Albert
Gore did vote to authorize American involvement in early 1964, by
the end of that year he was pushing for a negotiated settlement
with the Communists.
</P>
<P>
   The war was not the only issue in the election contest, of
course, but so many of the others _ race, busing, even school
prayer _ to some extent became mixed with the war in the minds of
voters, who found the senator too tolerant of social protest of all
kinds and of change in general.
</P>
<P>
   Young Al worried that if he found a way around military service,
he would be handing an issue to his father's opponents. But once he
finally decided to enlist, he never looked back. ``I wanted to
serve honorably and well and get it over with,'' he said recently.
</P>
<P>
   But as others of his generation headed for Woodstock that month,
he was calling his old Harvard roommate, John Tyson, to ask him to
come along for moral support as he signed up for the Army.
</P>
<P>
   Though Gore says his assignment as an Army journalist came as a
complete surprise, Tyson recalls that ``the reason people enlisted
was to have a greater ability to pick'' their job _ an assessment
Army historians say is accurate. A family friend recalled that Gore
surveyed the options and hoped to serve as an Army journalist.
</P>
<P>
   Highly educated enlisted men generally did get their choice of
assignments, and with his Harvard degree, Army officials said, Gore
never ran any real risk of being assigned to the infantry.
</P>
<P>
   So after basic training at Fort Dix, N.J., he was sent to Fort
Rucker, the Army's aviation school in Alabama, where he wrote for
the base newspaper, The Army Flier, under Margaret Cobb, the
civilian who handed out assignments.
</P>
<P>
   ``She and Al were like Lou Grant and Mary Tyler Moore,'' cracked
Maurice Hendrick, who worked there with Gore and later became mayor
of Rutherford, N.C. ``She'd been there 1,000 years and was very
firm and no nonsense,'' while Gore worked hard and aimed to please.
</P>
<P>
   That May, Albert Arnold Gore Jr. and Mary Elizabeth Aitcheson
were married in Washington's National Cathedral, Al in his dress
blues, Tipper in a formal, high-necked gown. Then he brought his
new bride back to Alabama, where home was a 10-foot wide ``Expando
model'' trailer.
</P>
<P>
   There was a sweetness to this anxious time, though. The night
before a friend, Bob Delabar, shipped out for Vietnam, Gore spent
hours crawling around on a highway median looking for a four-leaf
clover _ a talisman Delabar says he carried to Vietnam and back,
until it finally disintegrated in his wallet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd had a few too many beers,'' the vice president says now.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was waiting to go to Vietnam, too. All his friends remember
that he wanted to go, and the usual course of a two-year hitch in
the Army included a year there.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore family could never prove their suspicions, denied by
various Nixon administration officials, that Gore's orders were
held up on purpose. At the time, his Army buddies said, they were
convinced that President Richard Nixon would not allow him sent to
Vietnam while there was even the slightest chance that it might do
Senator Gore some political good should something bad happen to his
son.
</P>
<P>
   But the fact that Gore was eventually sent to Vietnam with only
seven months left to serve in his hitch was highly unusual. In the
end, Gore shipped out the month after the election.
</P>
<P>
   The nastiest fighting Gore saw in 1970 was back in Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Gore's antiwar position was a loser there, and his son
took a couple of weekend passes and a week's leave to try to help
save his father's career.
</P>
<P>
   The son stood behind the father at rallies, sometimes in
uniform, to remind folks that the Gores opposed the war but were
still good Americans doing their duty. They also appeared together
in two commercials _ one in which he and his father were shown on
horseback and another in which the senator told him, ``Son, always
love your country.''
</P>
<P>
   But the senator, always an indifferent fund-raiser, was badly
outmatched this time. And the campaign run by his Republican
opponent, Bill Brock, who later expressed regrets, is still
considered a model of dirty politics: The Watergate investigation
would later discover that Nixon operatives poured illegal money
into the race. One donor was Richard Mellon Scaife, the same
conservative who later spent millions of dollars on anti-Clinton
investigations.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Brock's slogan, ``Bill Brock believes in the things we believe
in,'' was a bald appeal to disaffected supporters of George
Wallace, and his campaign made Senator Gore out to be a turncoat
son of the South.
</P>
<P>
   On election night, Albert Gore gave a concession speech
conceding nothing. ``The truth shall rise again!'' he told
supporters, in what has been interpreted as a reference to the
promise of his son's future. Those who knew the senator, though,
feel he was too lost in his own pain that night to have been
thinking any such thing.
</P>
<P>
   Right after Christmas, Al Gore finally did ship out for Vietnam,
and arrived at the 20th Engineer Brigade at Bien Hoa, outside
Saigon, on Jan. 2, 1971. The Army was in bad shape at that point,
demoralized by the scornful lack of support for a war the country
was no longer even trying to win.
</P>
<P>
   Troops had already been withdrawing for two years, and those
left on the ground were waiting to turn the war over to the South
Vietnamese. Morale was so low that a few American soldiers had shot
their own commanding officers rather than follow their orders to
fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knew what a moronic war it was by that time, and it
was, `Do what you have to do to get home,''' said Roche, Gore's
editor in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   ``So getting in a chopper to go to fire support bases at that
point in time was pretty risky'' for Gore, Roche said, and made his
relatively gung-ho attitude all the more striking.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the one thing you could do'' that didn't seem like an
utter waste in those days, Roche added, was try to build up fellow
soldiers by reporting the individual acts of bravery that did
happen amid so much despair _ and, less dramatically, the good
works of the engineers, who were building roads, hospitals and
water purification systems all over the country. That is what Gore
did in the war.
</P>
<P>
   Bien Hoa was relatively safe, though sirens occasionally warned
of mortar attacks. From the hooch Gore shared with 9 other guys, he
could hear fighter planes taking off throughout the night.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Ancona, of New York City, who had known Gore at Fort
Rucker, said he knew even before Gore arrived that he was on the
``watch list.'' ``All that meant was that he was connected to
someone important. It was more like a protocol thing, but it didn't
mean anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore says he never felt restrained. Did he feel treated
differently by some of the other guys, by virtue of his name?
</P>
<P>
   ``No more so than at any other time in my life,'' he said, after
thinking for a minute. In fact, maybe less, he added; His father,
after all, was not a senator anymore.
</P>
<P>
   After five months in Vietnam, Gore applied for and received an
early out to attend Vanderbilt divinity school in Nashville. The
Army was granting such outs easily at that point.
</P>
<P>
   Though he had gone in hating everything about the Vietnam War,
he was coming out with a more complicated assessment of the
situation _ and an evolving view on the use of American military
force.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still think Vietnam was a big mistake, but it was the
feelings of the ordinary Vietnamese people in the South who were
terrified of losing their freedom that had an effect on me,'' he
said recently. ``Especially Catholics were terrified of a Communist
victory and that sure didn't fit into the cartoon image I had
before I went over.''
</P>
<P>
   Vietnam certainly did not make Gore an anti-interventionist,
even in the 1970s and '80s. Unlike others in his party, he
supported the invasion of Grenada in 1983 and was one of only 10
Senate Democrats who supported the Gulf War in 1991, infuriating
his party's leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Before he left Vietnam, he wrote a letter to Gus Stanisic, who
had worked with him on the ARmy paper at Fort Rucker in Alabama. In
the letter, Gore said that when he got back, he planned to
``atone'' for his sins by attending divinity school.
</P>
<P>
   What was he atoning for?
</P>
<P>
   Stanisic says he has no idea. ``In those days you just said,
``Oh, yeah, man, I dig.''' Gore says he does not remember using the
word atone, but very much recalls his deeply unsettled feelings
about the war. And about coming home.
</P>
<P>
   He had missed Tipper desperately, of course, and was glad to be
back, yet something nagged at him for months, even years, after his
return. On many nights, his wife would wake up and find that he was
out walking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure I fully understand it,'' Gore said quietly. ``But
you know, it didn't end. You were leaving something that was still
going on. If you're a part of something, a war, you want to win it.
Not that I had a bayonet in my teeth, but part of what was screwed
up about it was that we weren't trying to win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-00 2201EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
