<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-GOVS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPEAKING TO GOVERNORS, CLINTON SOUNDS CONCILIATORY NOTE 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARC LACEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ President Clinton toned down his partisan ``Al
Gore for President'' pronouncements Monday at the National
Governors' Association summer conference, knowing that more than
half the governors in the room had a different take on the upcoming
election.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, in what he described as a ``make-a-deal speech,''
Clinton argued before the bipartisan audience that the two parties
could still make progress on a variety of issues _ from Medicare
prescription drug coverage to an increase in the minimum wage _ if
they toned down all the pre-election sparring.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton still made the case, without explicitly naming
names, that large tax cuts like those proposed by Gov. George W.
Bush of Texas, would endanger the longest economic expansion in the
nation's history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've got to keep the economy going by hewing to the
same principles of fiscal discipline that got us where we are,''
Clinton told the governors in State College, Pa. ``And that means I
think whatever combination of spending and tax cuts any candidate
for any office proposes, there ought to be enough left over to get
us out of debt over the next dozen years.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those in the audience were Gov. Tom Ridge of Pennsylvania,
a Republican who has been mentioned as a top vice presidential
prospect for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Ridge said he appreciated the president's
``very conciliatory tone,'' but disagreed vigorously with Clinton
on which economic plan of those proposed by Bush and Gore was more
sound.
</P>
<P>
   ``As he was speaking I was thinking of George Bush's `Prosperity
With a Purpose' plan,'' Ridge said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton turned up his partisan tone later at a fund-raising
speech in Philadelphia for Rep. Ron Klink, who is running for
Senate against Sen. Rick Santorum.
</P>
<P>
   The president condemned Republican lawmakers for failing to
endorse some blacks and Hispanics that he has nominated for federal
judgeships and he accused Republicans of ignoring the poor and
elderly.
</P>
<P>
   But as he spoke to the governors association, the group that
helped catapult him into White House, Clinton was clearly pulling
his punches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know all the press coverage is always on the fights that we
have, but let me tell you, we actually agree on things every now
and then in Washington,'' Clinton said. ``And there are a lot of
things we could do in the next six months.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton added: ``I ask you to help ensure an election season
that is positive, open and vigorous about the real and honest
differences, but devoid of the poison that has too often clouded
the judgment of everybody involved in the public process.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as he offered his views, Clinton acknowledged that his
thoughts matter far less in these waning days of his presidency. He
said his opinions plus a quarter ``will get you half a soda pop.''
</P>
<P>
   After the speech, Clinton met briefly with Sherry Pope, whose
husband, Edmond, a retired Navy officer, was arrested in Moscow on
April 3 on espionage charges. The president told Mrs. Pope that he
was following the case.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the president stopped at the creamery on the campus of
Pennsylvania State University, from where he emerged with a
double-scoop cone of ice cream. He said the flavor was ``Peachy
Paterno,'' named for Joe Paterno, the school's longtime football
coach.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
