u w BC-STARR-LEAKS-NYT     07-10 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARR-LEAKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICE DEPT. DETAILS ITS CASE AGAINST FORMER STARR SPOKESMAN 
</HEADLINE>
  By ADAM CLYMER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Justice Department detailed its case Monday
against Charles Bakaly, the former spokesman for Independent
Counsel Ken Starr, accusing Bakaly of lying when he denied leaking
information last year to The New York Times about a possible
indictment of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Bakaly will go on trial here on Thursday on charges of criminal
contempt of court.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department's brief said Bakaly's false answers to
government lawyers obstructed justice by delaying a federal judge's
investigation into the news leaks and causing ``unnecessary work
and costs'' for the court and others.
</P>
<P>
   In the investigation, Judge Norma Holloway Johnson of federal
District Court had been trying to determine the source of reports
by the Times and other news organizations, specifically a January
1999 article in the Times, that said Starr had concluded that a
sitting president could be indicted.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief filed in response to the charges, Bakaly's lawyers
insisted that his statements were not false and that in any case,
they were not relevant to an investigation of possible leaks of
grand jury evidence.
</P>
<P>
   In their brief, defense lawyers conceded that Bakaly had
discussed the subject with a reporter for the Times, but had not
discussed anything that was not already public knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the lawyers argued, guilt can only be established in a
criminal contempt case by actions that amounted to ``a public wrong
against the court,'' not against others.
</P>
<P>
   Bakaly's lawyers said in the brief that Congress wrote the
contempt law ``specifically to preclude a judicial power to hold a
witness in criminal contempt any time the court believes that the
witness has testified falsely and thereby prolonged or complicated
proceedings.''
</P>
<P>
   While accusations of improper leaks had plagued Starr's
investigation of President Clinton's relationship with Monica
Lewinsky from its start in early 1998, the Jan. 31, 1999, article
in The Times caused a particularly intense response.
</P>
<P>
   The article by Don Van Natta Jr. was published during the
president's impeachment trial by the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   It said Starr had decided that he had the authority to seek an
indictment of Clinton before he left office. It said he had not
decided whether to do so.
</P>
<P>
   The article also said: ``Inside the independent counsel's
office, a group of prosecutors believes that not long after the
Senate trial concludes, Mr. Starr should ask the grand jury of 23
men and women hearing the case against Mr. Clinton to indict him on
charges of perjury and obstruction of justice.''
</P>
<P>
   The report was attributed to ``several associates of Mr.
Starr.'' It said Bakaly had ``declined to discuss the matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson sought to prosecute Bakaly for leaking grand jury
material in violation of federal rules. But last September, a
federal appeals court here said that the rule barred prosecutors
from publicly discussing ``matters occurring before the grand
jury,'' and that the views of Starr and his associates about a
possible indictment of a president did not fit that definition.
</P>
<P>
   Bakaly was accused of lying three times in a sworn statement to
Johnson, specifically when he said that he had refused ``to discuss
nonpublic matters'' with both Van Natta and Jill Abramson, a
reporter who is now the Washington editor of the Times; that he had
``refused to confirm or comment'' on what Starr ``was thinking of
doing''; and that Van Natta had ``assured me that his sources were
outside'' the independent counsel's office and that the reporter
``intended to make it clear'' in his article.
</P>
<P>
   Bakaly was also accused of withholding information from outside
lawyers hired by Starr's office to investigate the leak to the
Times.
</P>
<P>
   Because he withheld the information, the Justice Department
brief said, ``Mr. Bakaly knowingly caused a materially false and
misleading statement to be made in a brief filed by the OIC with
this court, as follows: `Mr. Van Natta further told Mr. Bakaly that
all his information came from sources `outside' the OIC.''' OIC is
the Office of Independent Counsel.
</P>
<P>
   In their defense, Bakaly's lawyers accused the lawyers who
prepared the statement of ignoring much of what Bakaly told them
about his dealings with Van Natta.
</P>
<P>
   Bakaly acknowledged, they said, that he had dealt with Van Natta
on the story and had even sent him portions of an internal
memorandum on the constitutional issues.
</P>
<P>
   They insisted that when Bakaly confirmed to Van Natta that Starr
had the four options _ indicting the president, not indicting him,
indicting him under seal or indicting him after he left office _
the spokesman was in fact revealing nothing but merely acting to
``confirm a truism.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Oreskes, Washington bureau chief of the Times, said
Monday night, ``The Times does not discuss its sources.''
</P>
<P>
   Bakaly won some public support from a consistent, intense critic
of Starr and his investigations, Julian Epstein, the chief
Democratic lawyer on the House Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Epstein called the case ``a terrible prosecution.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the appeals court had found that no offense against grand
jury secrecy had been committed, making this case against Bakaly
amounted to no more than ``a semantical game of gotcha,'' Epstein
said Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-00 2205EDT &QL; 
