</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIGDIG-ESTIMATE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOURCE SAYS `BIG DIG' COULD COST $14 BILLION-PLUS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Budgeted as Bigdig-Slater)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS C. PALMER JR. AND ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ An independent consultant's detailed assessment of cost
overruns at the Big Dig will push the estimated total cost of the
project up to or beyond the $14 billion mark, a source familiar
with the not-yet-released report said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The estimated cost increase would indicate that the Central
Artery/Ted Williams Tunnel project's finance were even more out of
control than state and federal officials have known or acknowledged
to date.
</P>
<P>
   Deloitte &AMP; Touche, the accounting firm hired by then-Secretary
of Administration and Finance Andrew Natsios before he was tapped
to take over the Big Dig, will estimate the cost overruns at $2.2
billion or more, according to the source, who asked not to be
identified.
</P>
<P>
   The the bad news came at an awkward time for Gov. Paul Cellucci,
who was in Washington meeting wiht US Transportation Secretary
Rodney E. Slater for the first time since a humiliating federal
audit of the Big Dig in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   Slater Monday reassured the Massachusetts governor about his
handling of the highway budget crisis, indicating his agency would
approve the state's new financing plan by the end of this month,
though even that plan may now have to be adjusted.
</P>
<P>
   Slater also gave unwavering approval of newly installed Turnpike
chairman Natsios, attendees of the meeting said.
</P>
<P>
   Ten weeks before he was forced to resign in mid-April, Turnpike
Chairman James J. Kerasiotes made a sudden, shocking announcement
of a $1.4 billion cost overrun. During the previous five years or
so, project officials had insisted that its bottom line would not
exceed $10.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Federal Highway Administration officials swooped into Boston and
made their own analysis, raising the estimate of overruns to about
$1.8 billion. Along with a huge insurance credit that the project
was forced to give up, that meant the project would cost about
$13.6 billion when it is completed in 2005.
</P>
<P>
   But Natsios, who as Secretary of Administration and Finance had
questioned Big Dig officials's accounting methods, hired Deloitte &AMP;
Touche to make an independent evaluation.
</P>
<P>
   ``A &AMP; F was concerned that the full extent of the cost overrun
and total project cost were not yet fully known or understood,''
says a June 15 letter from Deloitte &AMP; Touche to Natsios.
</P>
<P>
   Before federal highway officials sign off on the state's latest,
corrected official finance plan, that independent evaluation must
be complete.
</P>
<P>
   According to the letter, which was attached to the June 16
finance plan that the state submitted to Federal Highway, ``the
final report will not be completed until the end of July.''
</P>
<P>
   But the source, who was given a preview of what is in the
Deloitte &AMP; Touche report, said it will apparently force the
Legislature to go back to work to figure out how to pay an even
bigger Big Dig bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``It kind of presents problems for everybody,'' the source said,
referring to state transportation officials and Federal Highway, as
well as state legislators.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature put together a $2 billion bailout package in the
spring, after news of the overruns burst out and federal officials
warned that they did not want any more US highway money used on the
megaproject.
</P>
<P>
   If the cost overruns indeed exceed $2 billion, the Legislature's
work _ even though it was believed to contain a ``cushion'' against
further increased costs _ might not do the trick.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's at least $2.2 billion,'' said the source. ``It could be
higher than that.''
</P>
<P>
   A $2.2 billion increase is $400 million over what federal and
state officials have said they believed it to be. With the accepted
cost of the project at about $13.6 currently, a $400 million
increase would shove the total figure up to the $14 billion range.
</P>
<P>
   The Deloitte &AMP; Touche contract called for its accountants to
examine the project's management costs, redesign costs, and
assumptions on estimating contractors' requests for additional
money.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
