<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8478 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBO-ALLSTAR-EXPLOSION     07-10 1740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ALLSTAR-EXPLOSION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Everyone digs the long ball
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dixie digs the long ball. Hell, even Dixie Chicks dig the long
ball. Doesn't everyone? Indeed, when a capacity crowd and national
TV audience look on tonight in Turner Field, what has become for
many the highlight of baseball's All-Star weekend _ the Home Run
Derby _ will glorify what's long been the most majestic moment in
sports.
</P>
<P>
   And as much as we revel when someone _ Big Mac, Sammy, Rafael
Belliard _ goes yard, imagine how the yardman himself feels about
his handiwork.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing better,'' said Chipper Jones. ``To be able to
make 50,000 people get up out of their seats just by the crack of
your bat, I don't know if there's anything better than that.''
</P>
<P>
   There hasn't been since the '20s, when Babe Ruth transformed
baseball with the home run and transfixed the nation with 60 homers
in 1927. Yes, Roger Maris smacked 61 in '61, but it wasn't until
the summer of 1998 that Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa took our
national love affair with the long ball to the next level. To the
upper level, with 70 and 66 dingers, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Yet not even last season, when a big-league record 5,528 home
runs were smacked (an average of 2.3 per game), could prepare us
for this year's Home Run Orgy. It's not only McGwire, Sosa and
their ilk, but slap hitters who now go deep at such an alarming
rate, they're all on pace (2.56 a game) to shatter last season's
mark.
</P>
<P>
   Is it possible to have too many homers? ``What's wrong with
getting 10 presents for Christmas instead of five?'' asks Greg
Maddux, who has as many Cy Youngs (four) as career homers and feels
hitting a home run is better than throwing a shutout. ``It's still
special.''
</P>
<P>
   For many baseball purists, however, reaching the cheap seats has
never seemed cheaper. For some, the allure of the homer is going,
going, almost gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think home runs are losing their luster,'' said Tom Glavine.
``You see guys hit 30 homers and no one blinks an eye. Or they're
wondering, how many times is Mac gonna break 70? Maris' record
lasted what, 37 years?
</P>
<P>
   ``You used to look at guys at the All-Star break, and 20 homers
and 50 RBIs was a really good year. Now, guys have 30 bombs and 70
RBIs. A guy hits 25 homers and you don't even bat an eye.''
</P>
<P>
   Not with baseball gone batty, and goin' deep, as never before.
</P>
<P>
   While the home run's appeal is undeniable, it carries no
ultimate guarantees. The last major-league homer champ whose team
won the World Series? Mike Schmidt of the 1980 Philadelphia
Phillies. Only thrice in the '90s did a league home run leader's
team even make the playoffs. Albert Belle hit 50 for Cleveland in
'95, the same year Colorado's Dante Bichette led the NL with 40;
Ken Griffey Jr. led the AL with 56 in '97.
</P>
<P>
   Even the team historically linked to the home run has learned to
win without relying on it. The Yankees haven't led the American
League in homers since 1961 (when Mickey Mantle smacked 54 to
Maris' 61) and they've since won six world championships, including
three of the last four. Last season, the Yanks were eighth in the
AL with 193 homers, 51 behind league-leading Seattle (244).
</P>
<P>
   The Braves? They were fourth in the NL last year with 197 homers
(No. 1: Colorado, 223) and led the league twice during their decade
of dominance in the '90s (1993, with 169; and 137 in 114 games in
the strike-aborted '94 season). And then there are the Cardinals.
Somewhere, the Babe is smiling.
</P>
<P>
   In the sweet used-to-be, Babe Ruth was literally the king. After
leading the majors with 29 homers for the 1919 Red Sox, the Sultan
of Swat was sold to the Yankees for $100,000 and abused the short
right field pennant porch in Yankee Stadium for 54 homers in '20,
59 the next, 60 in '27. Seventy-three years hence, Ruth is reborn,
wearing red shoes and a red goattee in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Mark McGwire personifies one of several big bang theories about
the glut of homers in today's game: The ball's juiced. Diluted
pitching, an argument made long before big-league expansion
(Headline in The Sporting News in 1950: ``It's Putrid Hurling, Not
Rabbit In Ball.''). New bandbox ballparks. The ball's juiced(cq).
Better-made and lighter bats that increase bat speed. The
incredible shrinking strike zone. The ball's juiced(cq). And, in
McGwire's case and many of his contemporaries, today's bionic
sluggers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got football players playing baseball now,'' said
Maddux. ``That never used to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The players are in better shape now,'' said Andres Galarraga,
a 20-homer All-Star again after a miraculous recovery from cancer.
``A couple of years ago, players came to spring training out of
shape. They didn't even lift weights. Now they're living in the gym
all year. The players are hungry. They want to make money, be
strong, be a superstar.''
</P>
<P>
   They want to be like Mac. From 1968-92, the Cardinals reached
100 homers in just three of those 25 seasons, hitting 50 in '81. In
1998, with McGwire obliterating Maris' mark with 70 home runs in
his first full season in St. Louis, the Cardinals socked a
club-record 233 homers. They led the NL for the first time since
1944, when the Cards hit exactly 100.
</P>
<P>
   All that was mere prelude to this year's launch(cq) buffet. With
newly-acquired Jim Edmonds aboard, St. Louis hit 55 home runs in
April (three less than its 1986 total) to tie the 1947 Giants' NL
record for homers in a month. The Cards belted 100 homers in their
first 52 games, 125 in their first 74 for the fastest start in NL
history.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire's 20th homer in his(cq) 35th game gave him the fastest
20-homer start ever. Earlier this season, he was averaging an
otherworldly one home run every 5.5 at-bats,
</P>
<P>
   a 90-homer pace. When this past weekend's games began, St. Louis
had 145 homers in 84 games, a 280-homer pace that would break the
major-league record of 264 set by Seattle in 1997. Toronto, which
led the AL with 142 home runs in 86 games, is on a 267-homer pace.
</P>
<P>
   In a word, ``Ka-BOOM!'' Yet it's not just the Cards and Blue
Jays, not just McGwire (30 homers entering Friday's games), Edmonds
(24) and Toronto's Carlos Delgado (28) and Tony Batista (24), who
are clearing fences with impunity.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody's doing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first came in the league, maybe five guys hit the ball
out of the park to the opposite field,'' said Glavine. ``Murph
(Dale Murphy). Jack Clark. Later, (Barry) Bonds. (Mike) Piazza. Cat
(Galarraga). Now, you've got second basemen doing it. I'm not
knocking second basemen. But now, almost everybody in the lineup
can hit the ball out of the ballpark to the opposite field. That's
not bad pitching. That's the ball, and the smaller ballparks.''
</P>
<P>
   Juiced-ball conspiracy theories were in vogue in 1987, the first
year of the home run glut. McGwire hit 49 homers as an Oakland
rookie. Wally Joyner, in his second year with the Angels, improved
his rookie homer total of 22 to 34. Joyner's best year since: 21,
in '91.
</P>
<P>
   Suspicions about the ball were rampant in 1996, after baseball's
precipitous attendance decline in '95 following the
strike-shortened 1994 season. ``If you're trying to get people back
into the ballparks and give them what they want to see,'' said
Braves pitcher Terry Mulholland, ``that's one way of doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   That season, each of the 30 major-league teams averaged a
then-record 1.09 homers per game. So far this season, that average
has leapfrogged to 1.28. With help from seemingly every spot in the
lineup, including the most unlikely of sources.
</P>
<P>
   The latest poster boys for this summer's power surge? Indians
rookie Russell Branyan, with 11 homers in his first 79 at-bats; and
Keith McDonald, whom St. Louis just called up from Class AAA
Louisville and promptly became the second player in major-league
history to homer in his first two big-league at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   They are not alone.
</P>
<P>
   _ Last month, Colorado's Jeff Cirillo, a deserving, first-time
NL All-Star who'd never hit more than 15 homers in a season, hit
three in one game. He was the third player to do so in six days,
joining San Diego's Bret Boone and Detroit's Bobby Higginson.
</P>
<P>
   _ Higginson's Tigers, in business since 1901, slugged a
club-record eight homers June 21 against Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   _ In 220 games in the Astrodome, the Cubs hit 111 homers. In
their first three games at Houston's new Enron Field, the most
obscenely homer-friendly of the new parks, the Cubbies slugged nine
homers.
</P>
<P>
   _ When Barry Bonds blasted his 25th homer to briefly take the NL
lead, it was the first time in his 15-year career he'd homered in
four straight games. Until now, Bonds had never hit more than 24
homers before the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   _ Mike Bordick managed a total of 21 homers in six seasons in
Oakland before signing with Baltimore in 1997. The shortstop
surpassed his '98 season high of 13 homers by hitting his 14th June
21.
</P>
<P>
   _ Boston's Carl Everett, a first-time All-Star, already has 24
home runs, one shy of his career-best 25 in '99. Although his 23
homers already top his season high of 15, Houston's Richard Hidalgo
wasn't named to the NL All-Star team. Jose Cruz Jr. of Toronto has
19 homers, five more than his previous high.
</P>
<P>
   When Montreal's Jose Vidro homered from both sides of the plate
here last Monday, that gave the second baseman 15, topping the
first-time All-Star's previous best of 12 in '99. The NL's starting
second baseman, San Francisco's Jeff Kent, merely leads the league
with 82 RBIs. He's also hit 23 homers while playing a position
that's no longer just for singles hitters with slick gloves.
</P>
<P>
   But then, is any position immune to the lure of the long ball?
And is baseball better off with homers, homers everywhere? Is it
coincidental that ESPN's ``Classic Sports'' network has already
shown _ several times _ the May 28 Sunday night pitchers duel
between Pedro Martinez and Roger Clemens, anointing it an instant
sports classic?
</P>
<P>
   ``If you say to a fan walking into Enron Field, what would you
rather see, a 12-10 slugfest or a 1-0 pitchers duel?'' said Chipper
Jones. ``I know what I want to see: a 12-10 slugfest.''
</P>
<P>
   Not Terry Mulholland. ``If I wanted to watch eight, nine homers
in a game,'' he said, ``I'd go watch a beer league softball game
somewhere. There's a lot more to this game.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
