<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000710.0449 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8479 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBO-ALLSTAR-HRVIEWS-C     07-10 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ALLSTAR-HRVIEWS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Players agree ball is harder, tighter wound
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was time for more exploratory surgery. Already, Billy Koch
had sat in the bullpen one night in Oakland and spent three innings
unraveling a 1999 model baseball. Koch was hoping to unravel the
mystery of this year's ballistic ball.
</P>
<P>
   Now, back home in SkyDome in May, the Toronto closer sat in
front of his locker, trying to get to the core of the conundrum.
</P>
<P>
   Koch had a pair of scissors in one hand, a 2000 ball bearing
commissioner Bud Selig's signature in the other. ``Gonna be some
headlines made here,'' he said. Koch snipped the red seams off the
ball, ripped off the leather cover and unwound the yarn to expose _
what? A Spaldeen, the high-bouncing, pink rubber ball? A half-pint
of spiked Juicy Juice? A marble made of plutonium?
</P>
<P>
   Nope. A rubber core, the one at the heart of every major-league
baseball. It looked identical to the one from the '99 ball Koch had
dissected. After writing the year on each ball, he conducted a
highly scientific test. Koch dropped one ball from chest level,
then the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``In each bounce test I did,'' Koch said, ``the core from the
2000 model jumped two to four inches higher.''
</P>
<P>
   In a word, ``Boing!'' But then, they don't call this game
hardball for nothing. And to many players, Bud Ball 2000 is the
hardest ball they've ever beheld. The slickest and liveliest, too,
and the prime culprit behind the home-run derby that baseball is
becoming.
</P>
<P>
   Wound tighter than Tyson
</P>
<P>
   Major-league teams hit 931 home runs in April _ 195 more homers
than in April '99. While the new ball is hardly the lone
explanation for the long ball, there's little doubt the Bud Ball is
different. And hardly the pitcher's best friend.
</P>
<P>
   The consensus? It's more tightly stitched, wound tighter than
Mike Tyson. The tight stitching results in lower seams and slicker
surfaces. They make it more difficult for pitchers to get a grip
and make the ball move on command. The ball's just plain harder,
too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to be able to squeeze a baseball and feel it give a
little bit, more than it did now,'' Braves pitcher Greg Maddux
said. ``My hand could've gotten weaker.'' Pause. Smile. ``Not
likely.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question in my mind the ball has changed,'' Tom
Glavine said. ``It's just harder. It flies. The combination of a
harder baseball and smaller ballparks are turning people who
shouldn't be into home-run hitters.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this season, one American League hitting coach decided,
``Instead of aluminum bats, we have aluminum balls.''
</P>
<P>
   Cubs first baseman Mark Grace knows the new ball has helped make
Wrigley Field's confines friendlier than ever. ``When I first got
to the big leagues, maybe five, six guys could hit balls out of the
ballpark to center and the opposite way,'' Grace said. ``Now,
you've got little 150-pound backup second basemen hitting
opposite-field homers out of the park. So, something's changed,
however you want to do the math.''
</P>
<P>
   Harder material
</P>
<P>
   Gord Ash, the Blue Jays president and general manager, advocates
a less-destructive test than Koch's. ``If you ask a player to close
his eyes and put two balls on a table _ an old one and a new one _
he can tell you the new one by feel,'' Ash said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before, when you gave up a smash or a line drive, the ball
would come back and have a flat spot on it,'' Cubs right-hander
Kevin Tapani said. ``Now, they stay perfectly round. Now, when
someone hits a home run and some fan picks it up, the ball's still
a pearl. The bat's not affecting it like it used to.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Koch, Tapani won't be conducting any at-home comparative
tests on the 1991 keepsake ball he has at home. .``You don't really
saw that one open,'' he said, referring to a ball from the 1991
World Series, when Tapani, then with the Twins, beat the Braves in
Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves' Terry Mulholland, 37, who broke in with the Giants
in 1986, said, ``It's definitely a harder baseball, which
translates into longer home runs and harder-hit balls through the
infield. Everybody wants to talk about homers, but you get a lot of
hard shots back through the mound. Being a ground-ball pitcher, I
get my share.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Koch, Mulholland won't be opening up any baseballs. ``You
don't have to,'' he said. ``You see enough balls hit nowadays where
the ball jumps off the bat like a golf ball. It's not necessarily
Mark McGwire swinging the bat.''
</P>
<P>
   And like Tapani, Mulholland sees few flat balls these days.
``The only thing getting flat now is the wood on the bat,'' he
said. ``When you throw a ball that's harder than the wood ...''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
