<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 22:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8485 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-NYT &LR;      07-10 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE TURNS TO TARRING BUSH AND CONGRESS WITH THE SAME BRUSH 
</HEADLINE>
   By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW BRITAIN, Conn. _ Vice President Al Gore took a new tack in
his presidential campaign Monday, beginning a series of broadsides
against the Republican-controlled Congress and seeking to align
Gov. George W. Bush, his Republican rival, with antipopulist stands
that he says are a result of the control of Congress by special
interests.
</P>
<P>
   Gore branded Congress repeatedly with a mouthful phrase _ the
``do-nothing-for-the-people Republican Congress'' _ in an effort to
sharpen the differences between him and Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's face it. Never has so little been done, in so much time,
to benefit so few,'' the vice president said, pointing to Congress'
failure to pass legislation he favors, like raising the minimum
wage, protecting the environment, making drugs cheaper for the
elderly and strengthening gun control laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is time for the Congress to listen to the people and not
the powerful,'' Gore said, speaking in an incongruously soft voice
to about 300 people in the ornate auditorium of Central Connecticut
State University. ``It's time for them to do something instead of
doing nothing. I've heard from people all over this country who
can't wait for them to work up the gumption to come out from under
the thumb of the special interests.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said that Congress, in which he served for 16 years, was
controlled by big oil companies, big drug companies, big insurance
companies and health maintenance organizations and that Bush, who
has so far largely sidestepped association with congressional
Republicans, was doing the bidding of these industries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gov. Bush, who is now head of the Republican Party, says
nothing about this,'' Gore said, ``and his silence aids and abets
the do-nothing Republican-led Congress and the same special
interests who are contributing so much to his own campaign: the
HMOs, the insurance companies, the pharmaceutical companies, the
oil companies and the big polluters.''
</P>
<P>
   In essence, Gore was trying to lump Congress with institutions
that, polling shows, people love to hate.
</P>
<P>
   The venue he chose to launch this scorching of the Republican
leadership was a blue-collar region of southwest Connecticut that
is represented in Congress by a Republican, Nancy Johnson.
Connecticut, which voted for President Clinton and is home to two
Democratic senators, is considered a toss-up state this year, a bad
sign for Gore, whose strongest region should be the Northeast, the
most liberal and reliably Democratic part of the country.
</P>
<P>
   A recent poll by the Hartford Courant and the University of
Connecticut showed the two candidates in a statistical dead heat,
with Gore winning 45 percent of the vote and Bush, who has family
roots here, with 43 percent.
</P>
<P>
   G. Donald Ferree Jr., director of the poll, said in an interview
that Gore appeared to be falling back on the strategy of attacking
big institutions because he was having a hard time overcoming the
perception that Bush was more likable and was stronger on personal
matters like leadership and credibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going after Bush personally is not working and may not seem
fair,'' Ferree said. ``The less Gore focuses on personality, the
better for him. It's better for Gore not to treat him as a person
but to treat him as a front for the Republicans. The Congress is
impersonal.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore has been trying to frame the race as a dramatic ideological
choice, between his own moderate, centrist views and those of a
candidate who would be following the dictates of the right wing,
especially with nominations of Supreme Court justices who would
oppose abortion.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore camp has long believed that the vice president would
win the election because the positions he held were more carefully
crafted to public opinion than those of Bush. Gore has spent much
of the spring fine-tuning his positions and is now on a mission to
make the public aware of his differences with Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Working to Gore's advantage, his supporters contend, is that his
positions meld with those of most Democratic officeholders. While
Republicans are splintered along numerous lines, the Democrats are
speaking with more or less one voice, the exception being trade.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, that message was delivered by Sen. Joseph Lieberman, the
Connecticut Democrat who has been mentioned as a possible vice
presidential running mate and who introduced Gore here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am here to fight to protect Connecticut's voters from
deceptive politics,'' Lieberman told the audience. ``Don't let
yourself be cheated by Republican offers that sound good but don't
deliver. Don't let yourself be cheated by statements that seem
centrist, but in the end, end up on the fringes, that talk the
compassionate talk but, believe me, I've looked at the details,
simply do not walk the compassionate walk. Al Gore is the real
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``In Stevie Wonder's words, Al Gore is singing in the
key of life.''
</P>
<P>
   Before his speech Monday, Gore took part in an online discussion
with readers of The Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
   He was asked what effect the results of the recent failed test
of the proposed national missile defense system had on his opinion
of the necessity of its deployment.
</P>
<P>
   He said he still favored the missile system, adding: ``The
failure of the test last Friday night doesn't mean that such a
system is impossible to build, although the specific lessons from
the failure will have to await a more thorough analysis.''
</P>
<P>
   He was also asked why he supported the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I support it for particularly heinous crimes because I believe
there are some offenses for which it is just,'' Gore responded. ``I
know that many feel it does not really have a deterrent effect, but
I think it probably does.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
