<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 22:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8486 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-NFCQ&AMP;A-COX     07-10 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NFC </SLUG>
 Q&AMP;A - COX
<TEXT>
<P>
   NFC Q&AMP;A
</P>
<P>
   Changes in personnel, coaching will have effect on NFC
</P>
<P>
   Cox News Service writer Ken Sugiura answers some key questions
on the state of the NFC and AFC:
</P>
<P>
   Q:Who is the favorite to get to the Super Bowl?
</P>
<P>
   A: Washington is a lot better, but there is no telling what
effect bringing in so many new players will have.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay traded for wide receiver Keyshawn Johnson, but no one
knows whether he will be enough to push the Buccaneers over the
top.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis is the defending champion, but, as folks in Atlanta
know all too well, it isn't always easy getting back.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What possible roadblocks do the Rams face?
</P>
<P>
   A: One place to look is the sidelines. After shedding blood,
sweat and a lot of tears, coach Dick Vermeil retired. Offensive
coordinator Mike Martz took over and made lots of changes to his
staff.
</P>
<P>
   Four assistants close to Vermeil were sent on their way. It
might make the staff stronger, but it seems a risky move to shake
up a winning formula so much.
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, the Rams have changed their team colors, switching
from royal to navy blue.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis also lost two starters from the offensive line, but
did pick up center Steve Everitt from Philadelphia. The schedule is
more difficult, and the Rams can't expect to have the same good
fortune with injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What will Johnson do for the Buccaneers?
</P>
<P>
   A: Most likely a lot. Johnson can do it all as a wide receiver.
He has great hands, catches passes over the middle and will be a
big target for quarterback Shaun King. Johnson won't turn King into
Johnny Unitas, but he doesn't have to.
</P>
<P>
   He will be a constant threat and will open things up for the
running game.
</P>
<P>
   King held his own last season and in the playoffs. If he takes
care of the ball and finds Johnson every so often, Tampa Bay will
be in great shape.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who's the next Kurt Warner?
</P>
<P>
   A: A very tough question, because pretty much no one had Warner
pegged as Super Bowl MVP material this time last year.
</P>
<P>
   For what it's worth, the Buffalo Bills signed all-NFL Europe
League wide receiver Kevin Drake, formerly of the Arizona
Cardinals. Drake set an NFL Europe League record with 12 touchdowns
on just 37 receptions. His quarterback, ex-Florida Gator Danny
Wuerffel, tore up Europe by completing 161 of 260 passes in 10
games for 2,042 yards and 25 touchdowns against only seven
interceptions. He signed with the Packers.
</P>
<P>
   Both played for the World Bowl champion Rhein Fire.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is James Stewart, the Lions' new running back, worth $25
million for five years?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Lions think so. Having let go Ron Rivers, who signed with
the Falcons, and Greg Hill, their running backs from last year, the
Lions are committed to the ex-Tennessee Volunteer.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart ran for 931 yards and a league-high 13 touchdowns last
year. He started seven games for the Jacksonville Jaguars in place
of the injured Fred Taylor and averaged 3.7 yards per carry.
</P>
<P>
   However, in Stewart's five years in the NFL, he only once has
played a full 16-game season. Also, he has a per-carry average of
4.03 yards on natural grass and 3.41 on artificial turf. The Lions
will play 11 games on the fake stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Q: After Washington, Tampa Bay and St. Louis, who comes next?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Cowboys have brought back assistant coach Jack Reilly to
put in the old offense that quarterback Troy Aikman wanted, and
they traded for wide receiver Joey Galloway to try to replace
Michael Irvin.
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings tied Dallas for the third-best record in the
conference at 10-6, but that was before they let Jeff George go and
named second-year quarterback Daunte Culpepper their starter.
Culpepper appeared in one game and didn't throw a pass.
</P>
<P>
   The Packers missed the playoffs for the first time since 1993
and could be shaky on defense. But with Brett Favre, it's difficult
to rule them out.
</P>
<P>
   The Bears are a trendy pick, but they will have to improve a
defense that gave up an average of 356.5 yards per game last year.
</P>
<P>
   The answer should be clearer after the first four games of the
season. Carolina has Washington, San Francisco, Atlanta and Dallas,
and the Falcons play San Francisco, Denver, Carolina and St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, it's probably Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
