<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT OLYMPIANS WILL WEAR AND THE ART OF WINDOW DRESSING 
</HEADLINE>
   By   GUY TREBAY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ What will the U.S. Olympics athletes wear during
medal ceremonies for the summer Olympics, which begin Sept. 15 in
Australia? The quick answer is warm-up suits by Adidas. But anyone
tuned in to the drama of branding knows there are bigger issues
here than a sporty silhouette.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the corporately innocent days of the 1992 Barcelona
Olympics, Michael Jordan made headlines by draping himself in an
American flag during the medal ceremonies. Jordan wasn't being
patriotic. He was safeguarding his brand. The uniforms worn by
athletes to that year's ceremonies happened to be provided by
Reebok. Jordan was a Nike shill.
</P>
<P>
   In the fallout over this logo skirmish, the U.S. Olympic
Committee concluded that the time had come to abandon what one
official at the time called ``ambush marketing,'' with sponsors
throwing money at athletes willy-nilly during games' years and then
blowing out of town.
</P>
<P>
   The committee got serious about marketing the games themselves
as a brand, forming Olympic Properties of the United States, which
last year signed a sports marketing firm, the International
Management Group, to translate stirring gold medal moments into
profits. Enter, among many others, Adidas.
</P>
<P>
   In New York this week to unveil the company's new medal outfits,
Susan Halliday, an Adidas product manager, remarked that, in the
past, ``You'd have a Coca-Cola do a year of the games and then
they're gone.'' By contrast, Adidas, which has signed on for two
years, ``is about long-term contracts and commitment,'' Halliday
said. It's also, presumably, about a revived presence in a
Nike-dominated market.
</P>
<P>
   Designed by Mireille Poujol, the asymmetric outfits have fitted
jackets and stitched-on chevrons that converge to emphasize not
only the medals but the athletes' physiques _ a novel idea.
Formerly, Olympics' sportswear came in unisex styles, Halliday
said, ``which tended to be gaudy and flamboyant, with bells and
whistles.''
</P>
<P>
   In Sydney, you won't be seeing any unseemly logo brouhaha. When
American athletes show up for team processing, not only do they
submit to random drug testing, they also sign waivers guaranteeing
that, should they happen to win a medal, they'll do so wearing the
official sponsor's clothes.
</P>
<P>
   THE ART OF SHOPPING
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved the idea of looking through the words to see the
merch,'' said Barbara Kruger, the artist, taking a break Monday
during the installation of a career retrospective, which opens at
the Whitney Museum of American Art on Thursday. Kruger wasn't
referring to anything in a gallery, however. She was talking about
a display at Saks Fifth Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   The 55-year-old artist was invited to install a series of her
epigrammatic text-based images in the store's Fifth Avenue windows.
Previous contributors have included Kenny Scharf, who installed
green-skinned, one-eyed mannequins wearing John Bartlett camouflage
leather; and William Wegman, who presented his long-suffering
Weimaraners, Chip and Battina, decked out in Dolce &AMP; Gabbana and
wearing Donatella Versace-look-alike wigs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an ongoing commitment to contemporary art,'' said
Michael Macko, a Saks spokesman. Using fine artists in place of
window dressers, he added, ``shows how fashion, art and design
influence each other.'' It also incidentally honors a fine
tradition. Andy Warhol, Robert Rauschenberg and Jasper Johns all
did windows, albeit at a hungrier stage in their careers.
</P>
<P>
   One can only conjecture how pedestrians will react to Kruger's
work, which is probably as recognizable for its social critique as
for its graphic oomph. In block letters dropped out of a signature
red background, one text reads, for example: ``You've got the look
and you intend to keep it. You know how superficial an ornamental
life can be, but at times you live one anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a long way from fashion's traditionally loopy
pronouncements: ``Banish the black, think pink!'' Or is it? The
Saks project, Kruger explained, ``actually came out of a piece I
did for Harper's Bazaar.''
</P>
<P>
   It all ``originates in the fact that I worked at Conde Nast for
11 years,'' said Kruger, who was employed as a picture editor at
House &AMP; Garden and Mademoiselle. ``On a formal level, that's what
my work came from: taking images and putting words across them.
It's sort of fun to be on Fifth Avenue, with all this density of
bodies and eyes, still taking images and putting words across them,
but instead of `Wear This Sweater' I'm using my own words.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
