u p BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-NYT     07-10 0532
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MRS. CLINTON SEEKS NEW FORMULA FOR STATE MEDICAID FINANCING 
</HEADLINE>
  By JONATHAN P. HICKS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLONIE, N.Y. _ Hillary Rodham Clinton continued her focus on
economic issues Monday as she called for a new formula to calculate
the amount of money New York receives from the federal government
for Medicaid expenditures. Her formula, she said, could cut
residents' taxes by an average of $400 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who made the recommendations in a speech to about 100
people at an American Legion hall in this Albany suburb, said that
the current formula reimbursed New York at the lowest rate of
federal subsidy for Medicaid. Since New York's counties share the
cost of Medicaid with the state, the change she proposes would
provide the state with about $3 billion a year, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Her proposal is similar to recommendations made by Sen. Daniel
Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., the man she hopes to succeed. The
difference, Clinton said, is that an expected increase in the
federal budget surplus would make her plan more palatable
politically, with the increased subsidy coming from those funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, because of the surplus, we can present this choice,''
Clinton said. ``And I think we have a better chance than we've ever
had to create a coalition that would enable us to pass this.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposal came at the end of a five-day campaign tour that
has taken Clinton to a dozen communities from western New York to
the Albany area. As she has done frequently during the tour,
Clinton told the audience that her most pressing priority, if she
is elected senator, will be to work to stimulate the economy of
upstate New York.
</P>
<P>
   The plan being pushed by Clinton would use a formula that
largely takes into account the percentage of the population
classified as living in poverty. Under the current system, Medicaid
reimbursement is determined by the state's per capita income.
</P>
<P>
   The current method, Clinton said, means that the federal
government covers about 50 percent of New York's Medicaid expenses,
while other states receive more than 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that her proposal was likely to be viewed
skeptically by Republicans in Congress. ``Obviously I'm in an
election, so people on the other side of the aisle will probably
come out against it within 10 or 15 minutes, if not sooner, because
they don't want me to present an idea that sounds like a good
idea,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think it could provide a way out of the dilemma we've
been in,'' she added. ``We couldn't have presented it too much
earlier because we didn't have the proected surpluses that would
have provided the funding for it.''
</P>
<P>
   In addressing other economic issues, Clinton again discussed her
interest in bringing better airline service and lower fares, as
well as lower utility rates, to upstate cities. She has also talked
often about promoting tourism in upstate New York.
</P>
<P>
   While she has offered few specifics on many of the items in her
plan, she has nonetheless made economic issues the centerpiece of
this campaign trip. At every stop, her staff has distributed
brochures with the headline, ``Hillary's Upstate Economic Agenda.''
</P>
</TEXT>
