u f BC-ICO-TELEDESIC-NYT &LR;      07-10 0518
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ICO-TELEDESIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SATELLITE VENTURE SET TO REPORT BIG COMMITMENTS BY INVESTORS 
</HEADLINE>
   By BARNABY J. FEDER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ICO-Teledesic Global Limited, the satellite telecommunications
venture controlled by Craig O. McCaw, said it had received
commitments for nearly $300 million from a number of influential
investors, including William H. Gates, chairman of Microsoft, and
the private investment firm Clayton, Dubilier &AMP; Rice Inc.
</P>
<P>
   While Gates is the most famous name, Clayton, Dubilier is the
more important catch for McCaw. The New York investment company is
putting up more money _ $150 million to Gates' $100 million. And it
will provide experienced management help in the form of George W.
Tamke, a partner who is the former co-chief executive of Emerson
Electric.
</P>
<P>
   Tamke, who will join the ICO-Teledesic board, has been
consulting with the company's management on a variety of operating
and strategic issues for several months, according to Donald J.
Gogel, Clayton, Dubilier's chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``George will be doing a lot more than sitting and listening at
board meetings,'' Gogel said.
</P>
<P>
   The investments, which are to be announced Tuesday, also give
Clayton, Dubilier an option to invest $200 million more over the
next two years.
</P>
<P>
   ICO-Teledesic is the holding company for ICO Global
Communications and Teledesic LLC, a McCaw-led partnership.
Teledesic, which was founded in 1994 by McCaw and Gates, has a
long-range goal of creating a system of satellites to provide data
and Internet services to computer users anywhere in the world. ICO
Global, which planned a voice service for mobile users, went
bankrupt last year.
</P>
<P>
   McCaw organized a group of investors that brought ICO Global out
of bankruptcy in May. His announced strategy is to merge the two
satellite ventures, reshape ICO's capabilities to provide wireless
data services in addition to voice and then use it as a
steppingstone to the far more ambitious vision of Teledesic.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the investments by Gates and Clayton, Dubilier,
ICO-Teledesic plans to announce Subhash Chandra, an entrepreneur
from India, and Burtington Resources Inc., a private Swiss
investment firm, are investing $65 million.
</P>
<P>
   Some $22.5 million represents Chandra's investment in the group
that brought ICO Global out of bankruptcy. ICO-Teledesic will also
confirm that McCaw's investment firm, Eagle River Investments LLC,
provided $500 million of the $1.2 billion bankruptcy package.
</P>
<P>
   The investments will not be enough to carry ICO-Teledesic all
the way through to early 2003, its projected start-up date. But the
financial vote of confidence stood in stark contrast to financial
and operating disappointments announced recently by satellite
companies like Orbcomm Global and Globalstar Telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
   Orbcomm, which delivers messages to truckers and other mobile
consumers, said late last month that it would lay off 112 employees
and slow the construction of satellites. Globalstar, which offers
voice and limited data services, defaulted last week on a $250
million line of bank credit.
</P>
</TEXT>
