<DOCNO> NYT20000710.0469 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 22:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8499 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-HATE-CRIMES-NYT &LR;      07-10 0379
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HATE-CRIMES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK GOVERNOR SIGNS HATE-CRIME BILL INTO LAW 
</HEADLINE>
   By RAYMOND HERNANDEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Gov. George Pataki on Monday signed into law a
bill that for the first time imposes harsher sentences on criminals
in New York who single out their victims on the basis of sexual
orientation, race, religion or age.
</P>
<P>
   In signing the legislation, Pataki, a Republican, reiterated his
view that crimes spurred by bias can pose a greater threat than
other crimes to the victims and to society as a whole. ``People who
act on hate need to know that their punishment will be swift,
severe and just,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hate crimes do more than threaten the safety and welfare of
our citizens,'' he added. ``They disrupt entire communities and
cannot be tolerated. By signing this legislation today, we are
insuring that these heinous acts, so inherently destructive to our
society, will no longer be tolerated.''
</P>
<P>
   The version approved Monday marks the first time the words
``gay'' and ``lesbian'' or the phrase ``sexual orientation'' appear
anywhere in the dozens of volumes of New York state laws. The
Republican Senate had balked for years at including any language
pertaining to gays or sexual orientation.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new law, a judge or jury weighing a defendant's guilt
or innocence will also be asked to say whether the defendant,
beyond a reasonable doubt, chose the victim because of prejudice.
If a guilty verdict is returned, the defendant will face a longer
prison term if there is a finding of bias than if there is not.
</P>
<P>
   For low-level felonies, the maximum penalty will increase by
three years. For more serious crimes, the additional term for a
bias crime will be greater _ adding a decade or more to the
possible sentence in some cases.
</P>
<P>
   The new law also requires all of the state's law enforcement
agencies to keep statistics on bias crimes and the groups singled
out, something that only a few police agencies now do.
</P>
<P>
   Under the law, a jury or judge can find that a crime was
motivated by prejudice even when the defendant was mistaken about
the victim's identity. For instance, a defendant who believed his
victim was Hispanic can be convicted of a hate crime even if the
victim was not.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
