<HEADER>
A8503 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-CHASS-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      07-10 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-CHASS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE CLASSIC THAT LOST ITS MEANING 
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS   
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ They will play the 71st All-Star Game here Tuesday
night, and it will be the first played without league presidents.
Sort of makes one wonder why they're even bothering.
</P>
<P>
   As in the first 70 games, from 1933 through last season, the
game at Turner Field will match the American League against the
National League, but it won't be the same. The leagues exist in
name only. The baseball offices in New York still have signs
designating the league offices, but if summer tourists want to see
them just to confirm their understanding of what the baseball
structure used to be, they better visit soon. Neither the signs nor
the offices will be there much longer.
</P>
<P>
   The league presidents have already disappeared. Their absence
creates a void at the All-Star Game. Chub Feeney's old heart would
ache if he were still with us, knowing there was no one left to
carry on his practice of delivering a pregame pep talk, his version
of win-one-for-the-Gipper, except in this case, the Gipper was an
entire league.
</P>
<P>
   Katy Feeney, Chub's daughter and a high-ranking baseball
official herself, explained that the old president's All-Star
intensity had its roots in his longtime executive role with the
Giants. ``He came from a team, and he lived and died by the team,''
she said. ``When he became National League president and had to be
neutral, the All-Star team and the World Series team were his
teams. He felt very strongly that the National League was the
best.''
</P>
<P>
   Feeney urged the NL All-Stars to ``show our pride.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a long history,'' he told the players. ``Let's show
what we can do. Don't think this is an exhibition game. You guys
are the best.''
</P>
<P>
   Feeney presided at 17 All-Star Games during his tenure, 1970
through 1986. The National League won 14 of the games, including 11
in a row from 1972 through '82, giving the senior league a run of
19 victories in 20 games.
</P>
<P>
   For 10 of the Feeney years, Lee MacPhail was the American League
president. A forthright and gentlemanly executive, MacPhail didn't
have Feeney's fire when it came to the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never gave them any speeches,'' MacPhail said the other day
from his retirement home on Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   MacPhail rooted hard for his AL All-Star teams, but rooting
obviously wasn't enough because the American lost the first nine
games under his stewardship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did lose a few,'' said MacPhail, no revisionist of history.
He made a comeback briefly two years ago at the game in Denver.
``When they picked me to be honorary captain,'' he related, ``I
said someone had failed to look up my record or else they figure
the law of averages would catch up with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Leonard Coleman, the last NL president, and Gene Budig, the last
AL chief, limited their pregame clubhouse visits to handshakes and
hellos. But they at least were in position where if they ever felt
the urge to erupt with verbal fire and brimstone, they would have
had the players' attention.
</P>
<P>
   No one in either league is in that kind of position today
because the leagues no longer have officials. Katy Feeney, in the
NL, and Phyllis Merhige, in the AL, could be viewed as the
highest-ranking league officials, which they became after the
departure of Coleman and Budig. But they don't work for the leagues
any more; they work for Major League Baseball. So even though each
has taken care of her ``league's'' team here, neither was inclined
to offer a pep talk Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have my father's erudition and charm,'' Feeney said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't and I won't,'' Merhige said.
</P>
<P>
   Bud Selig could speak to the teams. But he's the commissioner of
all of baseball. What's he supposed to do, go into the NL clubhouse
and tell the players there to beat the bejabbers out of the other
guys, then go to the AL clubhouse and urge the players there to do
the same thing to the players he spoke to five minutes earlier?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the managers could assume the role. On second thought,
their credibility might be strained. Bobby Cox, the NL, manager,
played in the American League, and Joe Torre, the AL manager,
played in the National League.
</P>
<P>
   What the game needs is a league lifer like Feeney. But the
leagues are on the wane, too. In the first 67 All-Star Games, when
a pitcher faced a batter, fans knew they were seeing the matchup
for the first time that season. When David Wells pitches against
Chipper Jones and Andres Galarraga in the first inning or two
Tuesday night, the encounters will look familiar. Jones and
Galarraga batted against Wells only five weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Interleague games come, league presidents go.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
