Serbs is considered vital to the success of the Western effort to
restructure Kosovo as a democratic, self-governing entity where all
ethnic groups can live peacefully. The Rev. Sava Janjic with guards
after visiting some of the few remaining Serbs in Pristina, Kosovo's
capital.  Story moved on 070900. (Andrew Testa/The New York Times)
*LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador --July 10, 2000 --
SALVADOR-GARDEN -- The killings of six Jesuit priests and two women
at the Jose Simeon Canas Central American University in 1989 in San
Salvador, El Salvador in 1989, drew international scorn for the
government and helped to propel the peace effort that ended the war.
More than a decade since the killings, tens of thousands of people
from around the world have sought out the Jesuit residence's tiny
garden to bear their own witness to the faith of eight people they
consider martyrs who defended the poor during this country's civil
war. "This is a sacred place where people gave their lives for Christ
and the Gospel," says Lally. The Rev. Brendan Lally of the University
of Scranton kneeling where soldiers killed six Jesuit priests. (David
Gonzalez/The New York Times) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) CAMDEN, N.J. -- July 10, 2000 -- -NJ-WHITMAN-PHOTO --
After enduring two years of criticism for the racial profiling
practices of her state troopers, Gov. Christie Whitman is suddenly
struggling with a self-inflicted public-relations problem: a photo of
the governor herself, grinning as she frisks a black man. The photo,
which has been subpoenaed by two New Jersey troopers who have filed a
discrimination suit against the state, was taken by a trooper during
a trip Whitman made with officers as they patrolled in Camden one
night in 1996. (Photo courtesy of The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) FORT RUCKER, Ala. -- July 10, 2000 -- GORE-MILITARY-2
-- Al Gore's military record is in no particular need of improvement.
He was one of only about a dozen of the 1,115 Harvard graduates in
the Class of `69 who went to Vietnam. And even before enlisting, he
passed up a chance to serve in the  National Guard, the military
option chosen by his presidential opponent, George W. Bush. Army
Private Gore talking with the Army's highest-ranking officer, Gen.
William Westmoreland, during a visit by Westmoreland to Fort Rucker,
Ala., where Gore was stationed for more than a year. (Bob Delabar/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) UNDATED -- July 10, 2000 -- GORE-MILITARY-1 -- There
is no evidence that Army Private Al Gore sought special treatment, or
that the extra notice he got anyway provided any real protection
during his days in Vietnam. On the contrary, within the parameters of
his job as an Army journalist, Gore, probably assumed more risk than
he had to, helicoptering around South Vietnam interviewing soldiers
who had just seen action. Al Gore in Vietnam in 1971, second from
right in the top row, in a picture with Army journalists, from his
personal photo album. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) ORLANDO, Fla. -- July 10, 2000 -- CLANCY-CHARITY -- In
1992, author Tom Clancy embarked on a philanthropic mission worthy of
Jack Ryan, the idealistic hero of his popular techno-thrillers.
Clancy wanted to help children who had cancer and other illnesses use
the nascent technology of the Internet to talk with one another and
learn about their diseases. Clancy's inspiration was 6-year-old Kyle
Haydock, left, who sent him a fan letter while the boy lay in his bed
at Memorial Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center in New York City, ravaged
by sarcoma. After Kyle died in 1991, Clancy set up a foundation and
named it for the boy. Seven years later, Clancy is scuttling the Kyle
Foundation, which despite having spent more than $5 million on
travel, salaries, fund raising and furniture did not even have a Web
site to show for its efforts. Clancy and Kyle in Orlando, Fla. (The
New York Times) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) BALTIMORE -- July 10, 2000 -- BUSH -- Gov. George W.
Bush addressing the NAACP Monday in Baltimore. Bush told members of
the nation's largest civil rights organization that "the party of
Lincoln has not always carried the mantle of Lincoln" and he pledged
that strong civil rights enforcement will be a cornerstone of his
administration. Bush spoke of expanding opportunity in American and
said, "this begins by enforcing the civil rights laws." (Paul
Hosefros/The New York Times)
