A8505 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKEES-STEINBREN     07-10 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-STEINBRENNER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEINBRENNER SAYS METS' PROTEST TAKES FOCUS OFF THEIR LOSING 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ George Steinbrenner says the Mets are a good team.
But he also wonders if they are good at spinning a story.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' principal owner suggested Monday that the Mets had
harped on the beaning of Mike Piazza and a contested umpire's call
over the weekend to draw attention from having lost four of six
games in the Subway Series this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't blame Bobby Valentine and the Mets for doing what
they did,'' Steinbrenner said. ``They had to take the focus off the
fact that they got their fannies handed to them this time _ this
time _ and they are a great team. I'm not sure it wasn't a very
wise public relations move for them to take the focus off the way
they were beaten.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Bobby Valentine and his people would love to take the
focus off of that, and have the people forget about the results. It
would probably be the same for us, if we lost. I'd probably be
trying to think about what I would do. I don't blame him for what
he's doing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' director of media relations, Jay Horwitz, declined to
comment on Steinbrenner's remarks, or to reach Valentine, the Mets'
manager, for comment.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees and Mets split two games played at Yankee Stadium
last month, and the Yankees won the first three games of the four
games over the weekend. But Roger Clemens' beaning of Piazza in the
second inning on Saturday night, which left Piazza with a
concussion and unavailable to play Sunday or in Tuesday night's
All-Star Game, dominated the talk.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza addressed the news media before Sunday's game and said he
believed Clemens threw at him intentionally _ as Valentine and
other members of the Mets organization maintained angrily on
Saturday, when Piazza was being examined at a hospital. Valentine
was also incensed by a rare interference call made against the Mets
in the first inning of the first game of Saturday's two-borough
doubleheader, arguing until he was ejected and then protesting the
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bobby Valentine is a good manager,'' Steinbrenner said. ``He's
also a smart PR guy. He knows there were rumors about his position,
and he came in looking for a big series. I'm sure they were just a
little frustrated, and the frustration all caught up with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a very, very fine team, but so do we. They came in
really looking to try to prove something to us, and the facts of
the matter are it didn't happen. We won the city championship, if
that means anything. We won four out of six games, and that's
pretty convincing, especially against a team as good as they are.''
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner said he was sure Clemens did not try to injure
Piazza. ``The fastball pitchers, they have to live inside,''
Steinbrenner said. ``Look at Pedro Martinez _ he's hit 11 men this
year, almost twice as many as Roger. Roger lives inside. But to say
he intentionally threw at him _ no way. I know Roger, I know he's a
family guy who loves his kids, and there's no way a future Hall of
Famer like him is going to try to hurt somebody.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike Piazza is one of the best players in the history of the
game. We're sorry for Mike, we're sorry it happened. Now let's get
the focus back on the games. I'm sorry this happened. It took away
from the real results of what happened. If they don't get over
this, I feel sorry for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Phillips, the Mets' general manager, would not allow the
Yankees to use the Mets' workout room at Shea Stadium Sunday
because it is part of the Mets' clubhouse and Phillips said he
wanted to eliminate the chance of confrontation. Folks in baseball
have long memories, Phillips said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have long memories, too,'' said Steinbrenner, who did not
disagree with Phillips' decision about the workout room. ``I think
some of it might have been frustration on Phillips' part. I think
that they pointed to this series more than possibly we did. We had
not been playing good baseball coming into this series, and they
had two or three great pitchers ready to go against us. We had been
in some disarray, and we pulled together for this. They had to be
somewhat frustrated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody would take that easy. Nobody. I'm a poor loser, and I
don't know how I would react.''
</P>
</TEXT>
