<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 22:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8507 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-PRACTICAL-MAN     07-10 1208
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRACTICAL-MAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. - The practical man got soaked last week.
</P>
<P>
   At the movies.
</P>
<P>
   He thought he was going to see ``The Perfect Storm `` _ a
tough-minded sea-going tragedy based on a gripping book of the same
name. But it turned out to be ``The Perfect Corn'' _ a sappy
sea-going snoozer based on a dozen other cheesy melodramas he's
moped through in his moviegoing life.
</P>
<P>
   The practical man hasn't time to enumerate the innumerable
stupidities in this fetid flick, which somehow manages to turn the
tragic tale of six swordfishermen wiped out by a 100-foot wave into
a perfect bore. But two things really bugged him.
</P>
<P>
   First, there were no fishing tips. For the love of God, in a
film about pro anglers, you'd think the moviemaker could cough up
at least one clue on how to catch big fish. But no. ``The Perfect
Storm'' is perfectly silent on the bread-and-butter business of its
protagonists. What bait do you use? What rig? What is
``longlining'' anyway? Instead of answers, we see guys tossing
6-foot bobbers in the drink and then magically yanking in fish big
enough to feed a family for a month. Sketchy info like that doesn't
do you much good on the Lake Worth Pier.
</P>
<P>
   Second, it made him giggle. That was because the doomed
swordboat crew, captained by some handsome but untalented TV actor,
laughs in the face of death _ over and over again. Faced with dire
warnings that a killer storm approaches, they guffaw, slap each
other on the back and sail on. Impossibly surrounded by snarling
seas, they cackle fiendishly at every murderous, mountainous wave.
With their boat capsized and death imminent, they make dark jokes.
</P>
<P>
   Like pro wrestling, such romantic rot often entertains the
practical man, for few things are funnier than pathetic macho
fantasies. Thus, he generally gives four stars to sidesplitting
comedies such as ``Terminator,'' ``Rambo `` and anything with Jean
Claude Van Damme, for they generally generate a howl a minute.
</P>
<P>
   But while it's OK to laugh at moronic machismo in the abstract,
``The Perfect Storm'' is about real people. To his chagrin, the
practical man found himself chortling like a chucklehead every time
the valiant crew stared down death with a sneer and a swagger. He
couldn't help it. When the haggard hero, hopelessly doomed, puts on
the handsome face and hisses his hackneyed war cry _ ``This is
where we separate the men from the boys!'' _ that's comedy.
</P>
<P>
   And that was the problem, for the practical man didn't want
funny. He wanted truth. He wanted to know what kind of pride or
greed or stupidity or bad luck put those poor schmoes in the middle
of the worst storm of the century. And he wanted some insight into
what they were really doing and feeling when they knew they were
about to die. The practical man once had a gun held to his head
during a carjacking, so you can trust him: They weren't laughing.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Practical Man: My wife, in my opinion, spends far too much
money and time acquiring all sorts of unctions and potions and goo
for her hair, skin, feet, cuticles, eyelashes, nail beds, the list
goes on. She says it's fun; I say it's frivolous. She says
frivolous is fun. I say fun is overrated. I have a feeling you'll
side with me, but you may have better luck setting her straight.
</P>
<P>
   Slow down, Slim! You're asking at least three questions in one.
But the practical man is in a generous mood. He'll answer them all.
</P>
<P>
   First, you're right. Cosmetics are a waste of time and money,
for they serve no practical purpose. In theory, your wife is
dropping dough to make herself more attractive (presumably to you),
but as you know, the opposite results. Instead of a soft angel
offering you the sweet succulence of flesh on flesh, your gooped-up
bride becomes a greased pig extending an odious invitation to slip
on slime. Nauseated, you pass. Hurt, she counters with more gunk _
and back and forth you go ... it's a sad old story the practical
man is powerless to rectify.
</P>
<P>
   Second, she's right. Frivolous is fun _ if you're 6 years old.
It's not fun if your brain is firing on all cylinders, for any sane
person hates to squander time on stupid stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the practical man never believes people who justify idiocy
by appealing to frivolous fun. They claim lighthearted, childlike
innocence trumps practicality, but of course childlike innocence in
an adult is a sign of mental deficiency, not moral superiority.
Assuming your wife if not deficient, the practical man must
conclude she's invoking frivolous fun to mask the painful truth:
She's addicted to cosmetics because she's either grotesquely vain
or grossly insecure.
</P>
<P>
   Third, you're wrong. Fun isn't overrated. Doing what makes you
happy is the greatest thing in life, the goal of human existence.
But fun takes lots of forms, from downright destructive to yes,
practical.
</P>
<P>
   Smoking cigarettes, as the practical man knows all too well, is
fun. And fun to a serial killer is something few like to think
about.
</P>
<P>
   More benign activities _ like swinging on a swingset, playing
touch football, watching TV, and OK, even gallivanting with goo _
are fun for some people as well, and the practical man will indulge
in similar pastimes in a pinch. But he generally avoids fleeting
fun because it lacks substance and staying power. Once you get off
the swing, the fun is done. Instead, he goes for fun that has some
purpose beyond immediate pleasure and continues to satisfy _
pumping iron or building things, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   So argue your case against makeup this way. Yes dear, you could
do worse than play with makeup. You could, for instance, get your
jollies from banging me over the head with kitchen utensils. But
you could also do better. If, for example, you spent your extra
money and time gardening, or learning to play an instrument, or
fooling with the kids, you'd not only have fun while it lasted.
You'd also have satisfaction that lasts.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Practical Man: What do you think of parents who bring
little kids to R-rated movies? Every time I go to one, I see at
least a few kids under 10 in the audience, and my brother routinely
takes his 7-year-old to anything _ ``Gladiator,'' ``Shaft'' -
whatever my brother wants to see. Is that wise?
</P>
<P>
   No, it's not wise. It's lazy and selfish. What young child wants
to see a movie full of sex, sawed-off shotguns and swear words when
Disney is still choking theaters with kid-pleasers? Your brother
and his ilk sound like the same folks who force 5-year-olds to play
chess, switch off ``Rugrats'' to watch Dan Rather, take tykes out
on the golf course and vacation with them in New York and Las
Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   They need to suck it up and face facts: Parents don't get to do
what they want. If you're going to play, it's going to be on the
floor. If you're going out of town, you're going to Orlando. And if
you're going to a movie, it's going to have an action figure or
singing mermaid or talking lion in it.
</P>
<P>
   If you break these rules, you're a lousy parent and you're going
to hear about it big time _ when Franky says the f-word in front of
Grandma.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail PracticalMan(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
