<HEADER>
A8508 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-WINE-DISEASE-SFCHRON &LR;      07-10 0414
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-DISEASE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 BUG HAS WINERY ON THE MOVE  &HT;     By PETER SINTON 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A little brown bug known as the glassy-winged
sharpshooter is not only devastating vineyards, it is uprooting
entire wineries.
</P>
<P>
   Callaway Winery, Southern California's largest wine producer,
said Monday that it is shifting its main source of grapes from
Temecula Valley, Calif., near San Diego, northward to California's
Central Coast. A major reason is that sharpshooters are spreading a
devastating bacteria known as Pierce's disease as they suck sap
from succulent grape vines. Callaway, which produces 250,000 cases
of wine a year, has lost 120 of its 720 acres to the incurable
disease.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a recent emergency pledge of $22 million by the federal
government to fight the pest, Callaway spokesman George Rose said,
``The problem is not going to get better anytime soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Callaway cites pressures of commercial and residential growth in
Riverside County, Calif., as well as Pierce's disease for becoming
a major buyer of grapes from Santa Barbara to Monterey. Last year,
Callaway bought about 40 percent of its grapes from the Central
Coast. Rose expects the figure to rise to 60 percent this year and
75 percent in 2001. The winery, a unit of Allied Dome Wines USA, is
interested in buying vineyards as well as signing long-term
contracts with independent grape growers.
</P>
<P>
   A problem for vintners around the state is that Pierce's disease
is not limited to Temecula Valley. The glassy-winged sharpshooter
has jumped and hitchhiked to at least 10 California counties,
including Alameda, Contra Costa, Napa, Sacramento, San Joaquin and
Sonoma.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst-case scenario is that Pierce's disease could wipe
out the whole coastal crop within five years,'' said Jon
Fredrikson, a wine industry economist in San Francisco. However,
pesticides are often effective against the carrier of the disease
and the state is expected to implement tough inspection and
eradication measures.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the sharpshooter and a 115-degree heat wave that fried
some North Coast grapes one day last month, grape broker Barry
Bedwell expects that generally healthy growing conditions and
40,000 acres of new plantings could generate a record California
wine grape harvest. He estimates a 3.2 million-ton crop this year,
about 10 percent more than the 1997 2.9 million-ton bumper crop.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Peter Sinton at  &LR; psinton(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
