<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHIRON-AIDS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 CHIRON DRUG MAY FIGHT AIDS  &HT;     By TOM ABATE 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Shares of Chiron Corp. continued a five-day
surge Monday after the Emeryville, Calif., company said that an
influential medical journal will publish a study showing that one
of its cancer-fighting drugs also seems to greatly strengthen the
immune systems of people with AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Chiron's findings about the effectiveness of Proleukin as an
AIDS treatment were first reported at a scientific conference last
year, but the significance of the study was underscored this
weekend at the international AIDS conference in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Jim McCamant, editor of the Medical Technology Stock Letter in
Berkeley, Calif., said publication of the study in the Journal of
the American Medical Association could encourage more physicians to
prescribe Proleukin as a supplement to current anti-AIDS drugs, and
yield more sales for Chiron.
</P>
<P>
   Chiron stock gained 4 percent yesterday to close at $59.13,
extending a run that has added 24 percent to the value of Chiron
shares since June 30.
</P>
<P>
   McCamant said Chiron has surged on rumors that it is close to
settling a patent dispute with Roche Molecular Systems Inc. over
certain diagnostic tests technology. McCamant said Wall Street
believes Chiron will get a large payment and ``significant
royalties.''
</P>
<P>
   A Chiron spokeswoman declined comment and Roche officials did
not return calls.
</P>
<P>
   Chiron has already begun the final stages of clinical tests on
Proleukin for U.S. Food and Drug Administration approval of the
drug as an AIDS remedy.
</P>
<P>
   If that were to occur, FDA approval would enlarge the market for
Proleukin, clearing the way for patients to get insurance to pay
for the drug.
</P>
<P>
   Chiron clinical director Bruce Scharschmidt said Proleukin,
which was approved in 1992 to fight kidney cancer and OKd in 1998
as a therapy for melanoma, seems to fight cancers by increasing the
potency of the patient's immune system.
</P>
<P>
   The study that will appear in JAMA asked if Proleukin could also
help people with AIDS. Chiron tracked 78 AIDS patients, half of
whom got Proleukin in addition to other AIDS drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The Proleukin group experienced a 112 percent increase in the
number of disease-fighting T-cells, a key measure of immune system
strength. This compared with an 18 percent increase in T-cell count
among those who used standard AIDS therapies.
</P>
<P>
   But, Scharschmidt said, the 78-person study tracked patients who
already had moderately strong immune systems, as indicated by
T-cell counts above 200.
</P>
<P>
   The latest study will seek to enroll up to 1,400 patients with
T-cell counts as low as 50, to determine whether Proleukin can
strengthen these very weak immune systems and buy AIDS patients
more time.
</P>
<P>
   Chiron's Proleukin news, along with other reports coming out of
the AIDS conference, boosted biotech stocks, which have been
staging a summer rally despite weakness in the technology sector.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, the American Stock Exchange biotech stock index, a
basket of 17 large companies that includes Chiron, eked out a gain
of just under 1 percent while the tech-weighted Nasdaq sank 1
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Although that difference is small, analysts took yesterday's
results as another sign that biotech is beginning to win back the
independent momentum it enjoyed before March, when a crash in
Nasdaq caused biotech stocks to plunge.
</P>
<P>
   According to BioCentury, the San Carlos, Calif., industry
newsletter, biotech stocks have gained 59 percent during the last
six weeks. Year to date, the 200 stocks in one closely watched
biotech stock index have gained 51 percent. By comparison, the
Nasdaq is still down 2 percent from from its December 31 close.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Tom Abate at  &LR; abate(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
