<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOYSMART-DECEPTION-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 FTC ALLEGES DECEPTION BY TOYSMART.COM   &HT;     By CAROLYN SAID  
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Federal Trade Commission on Monday sued
Toysmart.com to stop the bankrupt toy e-tailer from selling names
and other personal information about its customers.
</P>
<P>
   The Toysmart case comes as a wave of consolidations and company
failures is roiling the e-commerce market. Privacy advocates fear
that other dot-com companies under financial pressure also might
choose to sell customer information.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most valuable asset these companies have isn't their
warehouses and PCs; it's the data they have collected,'' said David
Steer, spokesman for TRUSTe, which issues seals to online companies
that have privacy policies. ``There will be temptation for them to
sell that data.''
</P>
<P>
   Toysmart of Waltham, Mass., which is 60 percent owned by the
Walt Disney Co., ceased operations in mid-May. After seeking
federal bankruptcy protection, it advertised assets for sale,
including the customer lists.
</P>
<P>
   Its customer roster contains home addresses, e-mail addresses,
phone numbers, transaction history and family profiles, such as
children's birth dates. Customers who provided the data were told,
``You can rest assured that your information will never be shared
with a third party.''
</P>
<P>
   David Medine, FTC associate director for financial practices,
said the agency stepped in to send a message to consumers ``that we
are policing Web sites' adherence to their privacy policies. This
is all about developing consumer confidence in e-commerce.''
</P>
<P>
   The FTC's complaint, filed in U.S. District Court in Boston,
charges Toysmart with unfair or deceptive acts for failing to live
up to its stated privacy policy.
</P>
<P>
   Online privacy is now largely a voluntary effort. TRUSTe has
issued seals to some 2,000 Web sites, ranging from e-tailers to
media sites to children's sites. To earn the seal, sites must have
a written policy that discloses what information they collect and
who they share it with; offer a way for consumers to ``opt out'' of
sharing their data and correct inaccurate data; and provide
security tools to protect the data.
</P>
<P>
   Companies that share data with third parties can earn the TRUSTe
seal as long as they disclose that practice.
</P>
<P>
   Toysmart had pledged never to share data and earned the TRUSTe
seal on that basis. So TRUSTe filed a complaint with the FTC,
spurring yesterday's actions. TRUSTe also plans to file a brief in
bankruptcy court arguing against sale of the customer lists.
``Toysmart is hiding behind the veil of bankruptcy to try to
hoodwink their customers,'' Steer said.
</P>
<P>
   Medine of the FTC said the agency is in negotiations with
Toysmart and may reach a resolution before the July 26 bankruptcy
sale. The FTC would accept another firm taking over Toysmart and
reinstating its business, as long as that firm agreed to abide by
the privacy policy, Medine said. ``We're not shutting the door and
saying they can't sell to anyone; just not (the customer lists) as
a discrete asset,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Medine declined comment on whether the FTC is investigating
other recent failed e-tailers that have already sold their customer
lists. Emeryville's Petstore.com last month sold selected assets,
including its customer list, to San Francisco's Pets.com. Britain's
Boo.com sold its customer database and other assets to
Fashionmall.com.
</P>
<P>
   TRUSTe's Steer said his group is reviewing matters at Boo.com,
which was a TRUSTe member. Petstore was not.
</P>
<P>
   Some privacy advocates said the Toysmart situation proves that
self-regulation doesn't work. ``Legislation is definitely needed,''
said Marc Rotenberg, executive director of the Electronic Privacy
Information Center, a Washington, D.C., public interest research
group. ``The FTC is taking a baling-wire-and-scotch-tape approach
to privacy protection. This is too hit-or-miss.''
</P>
<P>
   Rotenberg said he is optimistic that the next session of
Congress will address the issue.
</P>
<P>
   In May and June, Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., held committee
meetings on Internet privacy. Rep. Spencer Bachus, R-Ala., plans to
introduce a bill this week that would forbid bankrupt companies
from sharing information they had pledged to keep private.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Carolyn Said at  &LR; csaid(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
