r f BC-SEMICON-TRADESHOW-SFC     07-10 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEMICON-TRADESHOW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 HOT SEMICONDUCTOR SALES BRING SMILES TO TRADE SHOW  &HT;     By HENRY NORR 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Heartened by a year of strong growth but
frustrated by the battering they have taken from Wall Street in
recent months, makers of semiconductor equipment and material _ the
companies that supply production machinery and materials to others
that actually produce chips _ gathered in San Francisco on Monday
for the opening of the annual Semicon West trade show.
</P>
<P>
   Worldwide, semiconductor capital equipment sales rose 18.4
percent last year to a total of $25.5 billion, according to
Semiconductor Equipment and Materials International, the trade
association that sponsors the event. That was a welcome change from
1998, when the comparable figure plunged 22 percent; or the
previous two years, when the annual growth figures were less than
10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The strongest growth for the equipment-makers last year,
according to the association's figures, came from a recovering
South Korea, where sales were up more than 60 percent, and Taiwan,
which recorded 40 percent growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The numbers aren't good _ they're fantastic,'' said Mark
Fitzgerald, who tracks the industry for Bank of America Securities
in San Francisco. ``There are a lot of happy faces around here this
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the companies that make up the industry watched their
stock prices soar from last summer until about April of this year.
Many of them, including such industry leaders as Applied Materials,
KLA-Tencor and Novellus, were up roughly threefold.
</P>
<P>
   After that, however, the tech panic that began in the dot-com
sector spread to the semiconductor equipment sector, even though
its major players are well-established companies with seasoned
management, real products, actual profits and strong prospects.
Many of these companies have seen their share prices plummet by a
third over the past three or four months.
</P>
<P>
   Industry leaders and analysts say they are confident, though,
that the fundamentals of their business are still solid. ``Believe
you me, there's no evidence of a slowdown, none,'' said Fitzerald.
The association itself forecasts that equipment sales will nearly
double, to $48.4 billion, by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Fitzgerald warned, though, that the industry hasn't completely
overcome its boom-and-bust history. ``I see a lot of upside for the
rest of this year, but the risk starts to build in the second half
of 2001.''
</P>
<P>
   On the show floor, the watchword this year was ``300
millimeter,'' the emerging standard _ roughly 12 inches _ for the
diameter of the silicon wafers from which chips are built. Since
the mid-1980s, most chips have been made from 200mm _ 8-inch _
wafers. Industry leaders began planning a shift to 300mm more than
five years ago. They originally predicted that the transition would
be well under way by now, but it was delayed because chipmakers
hesitated at the high cost of replacing nearly all the equipment in
their plants, or ``fabs'' as they are called in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   A 300mm wafer has 225 percent the area of 200mm chip, making it
possible for chipmakers to increase the number of chips per wafer
by at least by a factor of about 2.5. On the other hand, a new fab
that would cost $500 million with 200mm equipment will cost roughly
five times as much with machines to handle the larger wafers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem,'' said James Morgan, chief executive officer of
Applied Materials, the equipment industry giant, ``was that all of
our customers wanted to be second with a 300mm fab _ no one wanted
to be first.'' Last year, however, Intel signalled its commitment
to proceed with the changeover, and since then, the rest of the
industry has fallen into line.
</P>
<P>
   Applied on Monday announced 21 new machines for 300mm
manufacturing. The company said its 300mm products encompass almost
75 percent of the processes needed to produce state-of-the-art
processors.
</P>
<P>
   The company, however, continues to face stiff competition from a
variety of smaller, more specialized players.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Novellus Systems, a San Jose company that focuses
on machines that deposit the thin films of chemicals that make up a
chip, announced a new 300mm unit that elicited enthusiasm from
analysts and potential customers. Unlike most 300mm machines, the
new one, called Vector, is smaller and already cheaper than current
200mm equivalents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vector will be huge,'' said Fitzgerald. ``It's a
category-killing product _ in terms of bang for the buck, there's
nothing else like it.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the 30th year for Semicon West. Until 1992, it was held
in modest quarters at the San Mateo (Calif.) Fairgrounds. This
year, it fills all available space at both San Francisco's Moscone
Center, where it will continue through Tuesday, and at the San Jose
Convention Center, where it will run Tuesday through Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Attendance is expected to top last year's record of 67,729,
making the show the San Francisco Bay Area's largest. Association
officials last year toyed with moving it to Las Vegas, out of fear
that the Bay Area wouldn't be able to handle its growth but have
decided to keep it here.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
