<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JDS-FIBER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 FIBER FIRMS IN $41 BILLION STOCK DEAL  &HT;     By TODD WALLACK 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ JDS Uniphase, already the 800-pound gorilla of
fiber-optics-components-makers, is putting on more weight.
</P>
<P>
   Just two weeks after buying E-Tek Dynamics for $15 billion, JDS
unveiled plans Monday to buy crosstown rival SDL Inc. for a
stunning $41 billion in stock. All three companies are based in San
Jose, though JDS has a second headquarters in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, one of the largest technology mergers ever,
underscores the race to build increasingly faster networks, using
beams of light instead of streams of electrons, to power the
Internet and zap everything from phone calls to movies around the
world. A strand of glassy fiber, the width of a human hair, can
carry data at speeds 10 to 100 times faster over long distances
than a conventional communications cable, said SDL chief executive
Donald Scifres. Instead of pouring money into dot-coms, investors
have increasingly shifted their focus to fiber optics.
</P>
<P>
   Component-makers like JDS and SDL produce parts like tiny lasers
smaller than the point of a pen and amplifiers to strengthen the
signal along the way.
</P>
<P>
   But fiber-optics-components firms have struggled to keep up with
demand from telecommunications-equipment-makers, like Cisco
Systems, Lucent Technologies and Nortel Networks. Those companies
in turn build the equipment used mainly by telephone companies and
Internet service providers.
</P>
<P>
   By combining, JDS and SDL executives say they can shift around
scarce supplies and people and boost capacity to keep up with
skyrocketing demand.
</P>
<P>
   But Wall Street signaled it was too early to uncork the
champagne. JDS shares fell 13 percent yesterday to $101.13, down
$15.06, on concern that JDS paid too much or that antitrust
regulators will torpedo the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Justice Department held up JDS' purchase of E-Tek
for five months before approving it _ with conditions _ on June 22.
</P>
<P>
   This time, analysts say, JDS will likely face even more
scrutiny. ``There is certainly a bit of uncertainty surrounding the
deal,'' said Bill Gorman, an analyst with PNC Advisors.
</P>
<P>
   Both Gorman and J.P. Morgan analyst Charlie Willhoit said they
figured the deal had better than a 50 percent chance of getting
approved, but approval is by no means assured. Gorman said a key
factor is whether customers like Nortel object. ``If none of the
big equipment providers have a problem with it, I don't know why
the Justice Department would,'' Gorman said. JDS predicted it will
complete the deal by December.
</P>
<P>
   Another issue is price. JDS offered SDL 3.8 million shares, or
$441.51 per share, a 49 percent premium over Friday's closing
price. Analysts said the deal may have been unusually sweet because
SDL was already in negotiations with other players, including
Corning. ``There were a number of suitors,'' said SDL's Scifres, in
a telephone interview from a plane bound for New York. JDS appears
to have come late to the table because it was tied up with the
E-Tek acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   But the moment the E-Tek deal closed, Scifres said he called JDS
chief executive Jozef Straus to see if he was interested in making
a bid. In addition to being a competitor, JDS is also a major
customer, buying pump lasers, a key part in the amplifiers JDS
builds to boost the intensity of light beams.
</P>
<P>
   Less than 10 days after the phone call, JDS and DSL executives
hammered out a deal at a luxury hotel near San Francisco
International Airport. Two San Francisco investment banks advised
the companies.
</P>
<P>
   Bank of America Securities, formerly Montgomery Securities,
acted as co-adviser to JDS, a coup for an investment banking
operation that had been hurt by defections of key employees. And
Thomas Weisel Partners, founded by the former chief executive of
Montgomery Securities a year-and-a-half ago, took a big step into
the big leagues by representing SDL.
</P>
<P>
   Corning spokesman Paul Rogoski said his company walked away from
a deal because it thought the bidding had become too steep.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the high price, JDS and SDL executives insist the
deal will help fuel growth and immediately add to profits.
``There's a lot of upside,'' J.P. Morgan's Willhoit said.
</P>
<P>
   JDS is already the largest stand-alone fiber-optics firm with
17,000 employees, while SDL is second with 1,700, including 800 in
the Bay Area. No job cuts are expected.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from Corning and startups, JDS will mostly face
competition with larger companies with fiber-optics parts
divisions, such as Nortel and Lucent.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, the SDL deal is massive. The record for a pure tech
acquisition was set last year when Lucent paid $25 billion for
Ascend Communications, though there are some larger deals involving
tech firms. America Online's engagement with Time Warner was pegged
at $145 billion when it was announced.
</P>
<P>
   Chronicle staff writer Sam Zuckerman contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Todd Wallack at  &LR; todd(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
