<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 22:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8513 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-LILYLINENS-COX     07-10 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LILYLINENS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For the love of Lilly
 &HT;    By Heather Graulich
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ It's a hot one in Palm Beach, but Lilly
Pulitzer Rousseau is keeping cool at home, her island retreat with
the thick tropical jungle, the one she playfully calls ``the Palm
Beach Taj.''
</P>
<P>
   There's going to be a party on this night to celebrate some
family birthdays, and she plans to be ready for a summery fiesta,
right down to the margarita machine.
</P>
<P>
   These are the days Lilly loves in Palm Beach; sleepy, sultry and
full of sunshine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I live behind my jungle,'' says Lilly, a fixture on the island
and in the world of fashion for more than 40 years. ``It's like
(Palm Beach) has been discovered. It's a little overcrowded for me.
That's why I love summer _ you can't pry me out of here with a
stick.''
</P>
<P>
   So it's appropriate that starting next month, in the depths of
summer's steaminess, fans of Lilly Pulitzer's bright and bold
designs will be able to buy her first collection for the home: a
line of luxury linens for bed and bath featuring her signature hot
pinks and cool greens.
</P>
<P>
   The line is being manufactured by Dan River and will be
available at selected stores, including Pioneer Linens in West Palm
Beach and C. Orrico in Palm Beach. There are six mix-and-match
patterns, including one called ``Palm Beach,'' with prices ranging
from $38 for a washcloth to $600 for a king-size duvet cover.
</P>
<P>
   It's a dream come true for Lilly, 68, who says she's wanted to
launch a home collection for years but never did, largely because
it was such a completely different process than clothing
production, requiring different fabrics and factories.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always, always craved pretty sheets,'' she says. ``But I
didn't know how to go about (manufacturing) them. I have never been
so happy to see anything follow through in my life. I think we've
been overdue for sheets. Lilly has been everywhere but in the
bedroom.''
</P>
<P>
   In truth, Lilly has been everywhere and back, and then some.
</P>
<P>
   While she was married to Peter Pulitzer _ who would later make
headlines during his scandalous divorce from second wife Roxanne _
Lilly Pulitzer ran a small citrus shop in Via Mizner. It was the
early '60s, and Pulitzer wanted some simple shifts for work that
would fit comfortably and hide juice stains. She bought bright,
loud-print fabric at Woolworth's and hired a seamstress to create
dresses to her specifications: straight cut, side slits with bows
atop them, lace tape on the hems.
</P>
<P>
   Customers loved the dresses as much as the fruit, so Lilly began
selling them in the shop. They became wildly popular, and the
citrus business eventually morphed into a clothing company with
more than 30 stores nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   That lasted until the mid-'80s, when a combination of factors
sent the company into bankruptcy. Basically, she had opened shops
when friends needed jobs, not necessarily because her friends lived
in good markets for Lilly stores. And her summery prints fell out
of favor during the '80s heyday of serious, big-shouldered
corporate attire.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1994, with '60s and '70s nostalgia booming, Sugartown
Worldwide bought the licensing rights to the Lilly Pulitzer label
and relaunched the clothing line, with Pulitzer lending her
expertise as a ``consultant-plus-plus.''
</P>
<P>
   After some initial hesitation (Lilly devotees rejected the
company's early attempts to revive the line with more sedate
colors), the line took off _ again. In no time, Lillys had found
their way back to Palm Beach and the Hamptons as the warm-weather
frock of choice.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it appears, the time is ripe for even more Lilly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Home fashion follows the fashion world, that's just the way it
is,'' says Penny Murphy, vice president of Pioneer Linens. ``And
people are ready for color. Things have been tone-on-tone for so
long.''
</P>
<P>
   Personally, Murphy can't wait for the Lilly home line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up with Lilly and all the Lilly skirts,'' she says. ``I
have a pair of the old bell-bottoms that I just could never part
with, in the green and the pink. Lilly is just Palm Beach. A few
years ago, everything was Rodeo Drive. Then it was South Beach. And
now it's Palm Beach.''
</P>
<P>
   And when it comes to Palm Beach style icons, it's hard to top
Lilly, who _ no surprise here _ likes things bright and cheerful in
her own bedroom. ``I love lots of windows, very airy, cool,
overhead fans, no curtains and tile on the floors. I like to see,
to wake up with the light and look out at the trees. I don't like
being hermetically sealed.''
</P>
<P>
   There's certainly nothing stuffy about the new home prints,
which should sell well to Lilly lovers everywhere, says Casey
Orrico of C. Orrico. The Palm Beach boutique has always carried
Lilly clothing, but the Orricos were inspired by her new home
collection to add 1,000 square feet for linens and accessories.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (Lilly) is going to sell in Florida as a master
bedroom, but in the rest of the country as a guest bedroom or
summer home,'' says Orrico, who is decorating two of her own guest
rooms and her main bathroom in Lilly. ``But I don't know _ people
are such Lilly freaks right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Which all comes as a wonderful surprise to Lilly herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am totally speechless,'' she says of her refound success.
``How can anything go on that long? All it does is get bigger and
better and more fun, and brighter and cuter. It's amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
