<SLUG> BC-MONEYBAG-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 MONEYBAG: STOCK SPLIT, DIVIDEND 2 NAMES FOR SAME GAME  &HT;     By ARTHUR M. LOUIS 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Q: In January I received what was described as a 10 percent ``stock
dividend'' from Consolidated Products. I wound up with 11 shares
for every 10 I held before. Is this the same as a stock split, or
is there some distinction that requires me to adjust the cost basis
of my shares differently than I would with a stock split?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: A stock split and a stock dividend are essentially the same. You
wind up with more shares, and you adjust the cost basis per share
by dividing the increased share total into the amount you paid for
the stock.
</P>
<P>
   The term ``stock split'' usually is reserved for occasions when
the shareholder receives at least five shares for every four held.
A 5-for-4 stock split could also be called a 25 percent stock
dividend, but under common usage it normally is not. Exchanges of 4
for 3, 3 for 2, 2 for 1 and upward also are called stock splits.
</P>
<P>
   The 10 percent stock dividend you received also could be called
an 11-for-10 split. A 2 percent stock dividend could be called a
51-for-50 split _ but that seems silly.
</P>
<P>
   Any stock split of less than 2 for 1 could pose tax
complications, because it could involve fractional shares. For
example, when you got your 10 percent stock dividend from
Consolidated Products, if you originally held 125 shares, you
theoretically were entitled to receive 12.5 shares more, for a
total of 137.5.
</P>
<P>
   Most companies will not issue fractional shares. Instead, in the
example above, you would wind up with 137 shares, and the company
would give you the cash value of the remaining half share. In such
cases, the cash usually is taxable as ordinary income _ not as a
capital gain. But you should always check with the company about
the appropriate tax treatment of the fractional share and how the
cash payout will affect the cost basis of the remaining shares.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Weighing Options
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Q: I have a job as a customer-service assistant but am considering
going back to school to finish my degree in computers. It would
take two or three years to finish the degree if I attend school
full time, and it will cost about $20,000 in tuition, fees and
other expenses. Do you think I should quit my job?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: If I were a computer myself, I would reply, in a robotic voice:
``Insufficient data.''
</P>
<P>
   To answer your question with confidence, I would need to know
your age, your present compensation and the compensation you could
expect if you finish school and change your line of work.
</P>
<P>
   If you are near retirement age _ which I doubt _ then it
probably wouldn't be worth the bother. If you are just starting out
and have the opportunity to significantly improve your pay, then
you probably ought to go for it.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps you can work out the mathematics yourself. How much more
per year can you earn for the rest of your working life by
switching fields? Multiply that figure by the number of years that
will be left to retirement once you get your degree. Then, subtract
two or three years of your present salary and the $20,000 education
cost.
</P>
<P>
   However, one essential fact shines through: You aren't satisfied
with your current line of work. If you would be much happier in
computers, that counts for a lot in peace of mind alone.
</P>
<P>
   (I hope I can say that without getting into a territorial
dispute with Dear Abby.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Bargaining With Your Broker
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Q: Until recently I owned 250 shares of a high-technology stock,
purchased at $16.50 per share. When its price reached the high $20s
after three months, I placed an order with my full-service broker _
good until canceled _ to sell at $32 per share or better. The price
shot up that week, finishing on Friday at $31.94.
</P>
<P>
   I then had second thoughts, figuring that the stock could rise
much more, so I called my broker to cancel the order. He had gone
for the weekend, so I left the message on his voice mail. On
Monday, he called to tell me that he had arrived late at the
office, and that my stock had been sold at $32. It has since gone
up several more points. Is there some way I can get the broker to
cancel the sale and restore the stock to my account?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: I think you can make a case that what happened was the broker's
fault. It's worth a try.
</P>
<P>
   Your first step should be to write a formal letter to the
manager of the branch where you have your account, explaining what
happened. Ask to have your stock restored.
</P>
<P>
   You should send copies of the letter to the National Association
of Securities Dealers _ a self-regulatory industry group _ and to
the state Department of Corporations, which regulates corporations
doing business in California.
</P>
<P>
   It also might help to send a copy to the Securities and Exchange
Commission. While the SEC normally doesn't get involved unless a
broker violates securities laws or regulations, the legend ``cc:
Securities and Exchange Commission'' at the bottom of your letter
could intimidate the branch manager, particularly if he believes
that his employee goofed.
</P>
<P>
   However, the manager may hang tough and insist that the matter
be taken to arbitration. The standard contract between brokers and
their customers mandates that unresolved disputes must be settled
by arbitration, rather than lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, your plight provides yet another argument against
using live, full-service brokers and in favor of trading online.
The main advantage of online trading is that the commissions are
generally lower. Now we also are reminded that computers don't get
to the office late.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Arthur M. Louis at  &LR; moneybag(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
