<SLUG> BC-FREQUENT-AIRMILES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 CONSUMERS RACKING UP AIR MILEAGE  &HT;     By BENNY EVANGELISTA 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ David Phillips has taken extraordinary steps to
earn more than 2 million frequent-flier miles. He once peeled the
labels off 12,150 cans of chocolate pudding to cash in on a special
promotion.
</P>
<P>
   He's also had to resort to some fancy footwork to use those free
trips, like when he treated his family to a vacation in Italy this
spring.
</P>
<P>
   To get around the limited seating and other restrictions the
airlines have erected around frequent-flier programs, they had to
endure a grueling 20-hour journey that took them first from
Sacramento to Dallas, before a connecting flight to Newark, N.J.
They then continued on across the Atlantic to London before
completing the last leg to Milan.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the dirty little secret, the problem with these
frequent-flier programs,'' said Phillips, a civil engineer for the
University of California at Davis. ``It's not impossible, but they
sure make it difficult for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips may be an extreme example of frequent-flier mania.
Today, travel experts say the average person no longer has to rely
solely on frequent-flier points for free airline trips.
</P>
<P>
   That's because a growing number of incentive programs now award
mileage points based on credit card purchases of consumer goods.
Experts say that in the next few years, more free flights will be
booked by frequent buyers than frequent fliers.
</P>
<P>
   But the hard part for consumers is finding ways to get the most
value from those points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no trouble at all getting frequent-flier seats from San
Francisco to Dallas, but that's not a very good use of your
mileage,'' said Ed Perkins, a longtime consumer travel advocate who
now works for the American Society of Travel Agents.
</P>
<P>
   Perkins said consumers should treat their frequent-flier points
like money. In this regard, it pays to study how the airlines and
frequent-flier programs work.
</P>
<P>
   Two decades ago, American Airlines pioneered the frequent-flier
concept to build loyalty by simply rewarding customers who flew
tens or hundreds of thousands of miles per year with free trips.
</P>
<P>
   In the past five years, banks and Web-based programs that award
mileage points for credit card purchases have transformed frequent
flying programs into frequent buying clubs.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Purchasing Power
</P>
<P>
   Last year, more than half the frequent-flier trips awarded by
American, which has about 40 million AAdvantage members, came from
points earned from nonflying sources such as programs tied to
credit card use, said Randy Petersen, the renowned ``guru'' of
frequent-flier programs.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the airline industry will be hitting that level in
the next two or three years, said Petersen, publisher of Inside
Flyer magazine, which also operates the consumer-oriented Web site
 &LR; www.flyertalk.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   There are about 90 different frequent-flier awards programs
around the world, he said. Mileage points have become like currency
for an estimated 61 million frequent-flier members in the United
States alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a number of people I know that literally will not
take a vacation unless it comes from redeeming their points,''
Petersen said.
</P>
<P>
   The skies are full of stories about consumers doing wild stunts
to take advantage of loopholes in frequent-flier promotions and
rack up points.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips, for example, became nationally known earlier this year
as the Pudding Man because he took advantage of an offer from
Healthy Choice brand foods that offered 500 frequent-flier miles
for every 10 Healthy Choice brand food products purchased.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips bought 12,150 cups of Healthy Choice pudding for 25
cents per cup, clipped the proof-of-purchase coupons from the label
and donated the pudding to food banks in his area.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mileage programs are the crack cocaine of the travel
industry,'' said consumer travel advocate Christopher Elliott.
``People do the most bizarre things for frequent-flier miles. They
collect them faster than they can spend them.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A Growing Demand
</P>
<P>
   And that's one of the problems. The growing demand for
frequent-flier seats is outpacing the number of seats designated
for those trips, especially for more popular destintions.
</P>
<P>
   Major airlines traditionally set aside only a small percentage
of seats, as low as 7 or 8 percent according to industry
calculations, on any flight for frequent fliers. The percentage is
higher for less popular destinations and lower for popular routes.
And there may be no seats available on popular travel holidays like
Thanksgiving and Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott estimates that only 10 percent of travel-related rewards
points are redeemed each year. And Petersen, after studying
airline, hotel and credit card industry documents, along with stock
market filings, estimates that consumers have now banked about 14
trillion unused miles.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you want to to go Disney World in June with the kids,
it's you and 14 million other people who want to do the same
thing,'' Petersen said.
</P>
<P>
   Understanding the roadblocks helps frequent fliers get the most
out of their points. The first rule is to always be prepared to
look for alternative flights and airlines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just keep trying and be flexible,'' Perkins said. ``If you
can't get to New York, go to Philadelphia. If you can't get to
London, go to Manchester.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Feldman, a professor of biology at University of
California at Santa Cruz who accumulates most of his frequent-flier
points on the ground through credit card purchases, said he had to
readjust his schedule to book a trip next month to Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was unable to get seats on any of the United Airlines
nonstop flights from San Francisco to Philadelphia,'' he said.
Instead, he found a connecting flight through Delta Air Lines,
which has an agreement with United to honor frequent-flier points.
</P>
<P>
   The flight times still were not ideal, but acceptable, Feldman
said. ``We were able to redeem miles. It just took a lot of
adjusting of our schedules.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Perkins and Petersen said it helps to look at mileage
points for what they are worth if redeemed for cash. Generally,
airline mileage points are worth 1 to 2 cents per mile, but that
depends on what rules and restrictions apply to the individual
frequent-flier programs.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a trip from a West Coast city to Hawaii that costs
30,000 points would be worth about $600. That would be a bad deal
because ``most of the time you can find a regular ticket to Hawaii
for less than that,'' Perkins said.
</P>
<P>
   And a ticket to Orlando booked 10 months in advance for a
25,000-mile award, or about $500 at 2 cents per mile, might not be
a good deal because ``that far in advance, you might be able to buy
a ticket for $250,'' Petersen said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would never use an award on something I could buy for below
$250,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Help on the Net
</P>
<P>
   The Web is helping consumers navigate the frequent-flier skies.
Web sites like FlyerTalk.com and MileageWorkshop.com have bulletin
boards that help even seasoned frequent fliers like Phillips. They
offer tips on a wide variety of questions such as how to make sense
out of confusing frequent-flier program rules, how to sort out
which airline has the best rewards program and where to look for
available seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really puts the power of information on the side of
consumers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Looking at tips posted by other travelers on FlyerTalk.com
helped Phillips plan the cheapest airline routes to rack up another
1 million miles in another promotion offered by a consortium of
Latin American airlines. Phillips said he figures he has only
redeemed about 200,000 of the 2.25 million frequent-flier points he
has racked up.
</P>
<P>
   ``They post a lot of detailed information on how programs work,
information on ticket prices and what to do under certain
situations,'' said Feldman.
</P>
<P>
   New Web-based programs like ClickMiles.com and WebMiles.com,
which turn online purchases into frequent-flier points, are also
designed to help take the confusion out of traditional airline
frequent-flier programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody loves free travel,'' said West Shell, chief
executive officer of Netcentives Inc., the San Francisco company
that offers ClickMiles.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips was enthusiastic about WebMiles, a program started
earlier this year by Utah entrepreneurs Jeff Crapo and Tim Olson.
</P>
<P>
   Launched in January, WebMiles promises to simplify the art of
accumulating frequent-flier miles so that consumers can pick any
flight on any airline. WebMiles members earn from 1 to 5 miles for
every dollar they spend on merchandise at such online sites as
Borders.com, DisneyStore.com and JC Penney.
</P>
<P>
   The first 8,000 points gets a $100 discount off flights, while
180,000 gets a trip around the world. WebMiles Inc. books the seats
for the member, and because the company creates its own rewards
points, Crapo said it isn't subject to the same airline seat
restrictions placed on regular frequent fliers.
</P>
<P>
   Crapo said the miles can be redeemed for round-trip tickets if
booked 14 days or more in advance or for discounts of $100 or more
for tickets purchased with no advance notice.
</P>
<P>
   WebMiles advertises that it can get tickets for ``any airline,
any flight, any time.'' Crapo admits that while no company can
guarantee a seat during a heavy travel day like the day before
Thanksgiving, when airlines sell out flights, WebMiles has a better
chance than standard frequent-flier programs that usually offer no
seats for those dates.
</P>
<P>
   Petersen, though, said WebMiles ``is really nothing new, just
another player out there among many who use travel as an award.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said WebMiles points may not work as well for real
frequent fliers because points can't be combined with regular
airline mileage.
</P>
<P>
   Netcentives' more established ClickMiles, started in April 1998,
also allows consumers to accumulate mileage points by buying at one
of 90 online sites like Barnesandnoble.com, or starting a brokerage
account at E-Trade.
</P>
<P>
   Netcentives has also worked out agreements with 10 airlines to
allow ClickMiles points to be combined with regular frequent-flier
mileage, which makes the company ``the leader in that area,''
Petersen said.
</P>
<P>
   Being able to combine buying points with flying points gives the
consumer a better chance of finding that free flight he or she
wants, even though the consumer might have to spend more points to
book the seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no free ticket you can't get, but you just have to be
prepared to pay the miles for it,'' Petersen said. ``The reality
is, for 40,000 miles, you can have any seat. If you have the miles,
you will never be turned away.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he said the airlines must do a better job of managing
seats designated for frequent fliers, domestic airlines served up
about 12 million free tickets last year, Petersen said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There'll always be a John or Jill who can't get what they
want, but the fact is, someone is getting something for free out
there,'' he said. ``I know people who redeem six awards a year and
never have problems.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Benny Evangelista at  &LR; bennye(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
