<SLUG> BC-NETWORTH-PENDER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETWORTH: JDS UNIPHASE MAKING INVESTORS THINK WITH RECENT
SDL  TAKEOVER
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By KATHLEEN PENDER 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It's hard to keep a good stock down, but some
investors think JDS Uniphase could be headed for another lull while
regulators decide whether to approve the company's brash takeover
of chief rival SDL Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of work that will have to be done to convince
both the government and customers that this deal should be allowed,
and shares of JDSU will likely go back to the arbitrage penalty
box,'' J.P. Morgan analyst Charlie Willhoit says in a research
note.
</P>
<P>
   JDSU served a couple months in the penalty box while investors
awaited a decision on its acquisition of E-Tek Dyanmics _ its other
big competitor in the fiber-optics components business.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department approved the E-Tek deal, with conditions,
in late June, and JDSU was barely back on the ice before announcing
the SDL takeover.
</P>
<P>
   JDSU shares plunged $15.06 _ about 13 percent _ to $101.13
Monday. They hit a high of $146.53 in March and had been climbing
back from a six-month low of $79 in May.
</P>
<P>
   SDL on Monday rose $25.38 to $320.69 per share, which is 16
percent below the price JDSU offered. That discount is high for a
normal merger but typical for one that raises immediate antitrust
concerns.
</P>
<P>
   The gap on the E-Tek deal was 20 percent when it was announced
and got as high as 25 percent, says Ken Smith, co-manager of the
Munder NetNet and Future Technology funds.
</P>
<P>
   Most analysts think the deal, if it gets done, will make JDSU an
even more formidable competitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``If your outlook is six months or longer, it's positive,'' says
Jeffrey Wrona, manager of the momentum-oriented PBHG Technology and
Communications fund, which has large positions in both companies.
</P>
<P>
   But, Wrona added, ``from a very short-term perspective, I'm
disappointed. We thought the stock would start rocking and rolling
when the E-Tek deal closed. I thought it would be added to the S&AMP;P
500.''
</P>
<P>
   Stocks get a boost when they join the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index because index-fund managers have to buy them. But JDSU ``was
passed over 10 times while the E-Tek deal was pending,'' says
Wrona. Now he thinks it will be passed over again.
</P>
<P>
   Another question weighing on the stock is whether the merger
will dilute earnings. JDSU has said it won't, but some investors
aren't so sure.
</P>
<P>
   And then there are ``integration issues,'' whether JDSU can
smoothly combine its operations with SDL's and E-Tek's.
</P>
<P>
   Should JDSU have digested E-Tek before it attempted another big
gulp like SDL?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, but that's from a short-term, selfish standpoint,'' Wrona
says. ``Long term, if they can get the (Justice Department) to
approve this, the gap between the No. 1 and No. 2 supplier (of
fiber-optics components) will be bigger than the gap between Intel
and AMD.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not music to Justice Department ears.
</P>
<P>
   But ``if the (Justice Department) looks at (the two companies)
on a product-by-product basis,'' the merger could win approval,
says Giri Devulapally, a telecom analyst with T. Rowe Price.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies make lots of components, but very few of the same
ones. In fact, JDSU probably competes with SDL on fewer products
than it did with E-Tek.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest overlap with SDL is in 980-nanometer pump lasers,
which amplify the power of the light source so it can be
transmitted over longer distances.
</P>
<P>
   This is SDL's biggest product line, and Smith has heard
estimates that together, SDL and JDSU would control 90 percent of
that market.
</P>
<P>
   The DOJ could approve the merger on the condition that JDSU and
SDLI take steps to ensure competition in overlapping products, as
it did with the E-Tek deal.
</P>
<P>
   But the government may not approve the deal at all if it looks
at the two companies as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the DOJ takes the attitude, `You know what, these guys are
just too big,' it's going to be tough for them to get approval,''
says Devulapally.
</P>
<P>
   William Kovacic, who teaches antitrust law at George Washington
University, thinks JDSU may face some tough questions from the
government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Often, if you have two companies that have non-overlapping
product lines, but similar capabilities, the question always comes
up: Are these the companies most likely to invade the other's
product areas?'' If the answer is yes, the government may conclude
that the merger is anticompetitive.
</P>
<P>
   In such cases, the government ``talks to the purchasers of the
components,'' he says. If the customers don't mind the merger, that
``tends to weigh heavily on the agency's assessment.''
</P>
<P>
   JDSU's customers include companies like Nortel, Lucent, Ciena
and Alcatel. But these companies also compete with JDSU in some
products.
</P>
<P>
   Another question the government has in what Kovacic calls
``complementary product'' cases is: ``How easily could someone else
adjust to make the same product?''
</P>
<P>
   In fiber optics, the answer is often not easily. The industry is
plagued by chronic shortages of components and people who know how
to make them.
</P>
<P>
   Working in JDSU's favor is the ``avalanche of work'' facing
antitrust officials, the complexity of fiber optics and the fact
that neither company makes a consumer product, Kovacic says.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it is risky to do a deal thinking it will slip past (the
government's) field of vision, especially because it has identified
high technology as a priority and has a little bit of learning''
from JDSU's previous deals.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Froewiss, manager of the Internet Infrastructure fund,
gives the deal a 50-50 percent chance of passing.
</P>
<P>
   Smith put the odds at 60-40, ``but that's just a guess.''
</P>
<P>
   POTENTIAL TAKEOVER TARGETS: Monday's takeover announcement drove
up the price of other fiber-components companies. None are as big
as SDL, and some have only been public a few months.
</P>
<P>
   Most analysts think any of the public companies listed here are
potential takeover targets, but Smith said he thinks the most
likely are Bookham, a British company, and Avanex of Fremont,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   MRV Communications ``is more of a portfolio (or incubator)
company,'' so it would be less likely to be taken over, Smith says.
However, ``they're expected to spin out an optical company sometime
this year,'' and that could become a target.
</P>
<P>
   Stratos Lightwave was spun off Methode Electronics in June.
Methode still owns 86 percent of Stratos and plans to distribute
that stake to its shareholders. So Stratos would be a less likely
target than the others, says Froewiss.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he thinks the company most likely to benefit from the
merger is Corning. Its main product is glass fiber, but it's also
building a components business.
</P>
<P>
   Corning stock fell Monday, as investors worried about
competition from a larger JDSU. ``But this just positions Corning
as the alternative to JDSU. It also takes JDSU out of the
acquisition game for a while. It gives Corning (which made an offer
for SDL) a window of opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Kathleen Pender at  &LR; kpender(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
