<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 22:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8517 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBA-STONEMAN-ANGELS-L     07-10 1705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-STONEMAN-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S BEEN A LONG RIDE FOR ANGELS' GM STONEMAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Bill Stoneman probably thought he'd never come back.
Not after Angels general manager Harry Dalton's request that
Stoneman, a sore-shouldered pitcher, accept a demotion to the minor
leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Stoneman, who had thrown two no-hitters during an otherwise
undistinguished major-league career, was 30 years old at the time
and felt he was ready to move into a different line of work. But
Dalton persisted.
</P>
<P>
   When it was clear Stoneman wouldn't go to the minors, Dalton
then worked out a deal with the Cardinals. The Angels would get
$20,000, and Stoneman would pitch for the Cardinals' Triple-A team.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he'd split it with me,'' Stoneman said. ``But I still
wasn't throwing any better. I could use $10,000, but it would be
like stealing. So I went home.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As a general manager in those days, you tried to get close
enough to the players to know how they felt about the business and
their jobs,'' said Dalton, who is retired and living in Arizona.
``Bill was a very knowledgeable pitcher. A good competitor. It's a
shame he hurt his arm.''
</P>
<P>
   So in 1974, Stoneman's baseball career was over. Or so he
thought.
</P>
<P>
   Stoneman returned to Anaheim as the club's general manager last
Nov. 1, but his baseball life and professional career have been by
no means typical. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
HUMBLE BEGINNINGS
</P>
<P>
   By his own admission, Stoneman was a mediocre pitcher at West
Covina (Calif.) High School. He played football one year on the 'B'
team but quit when after snapping the ball on a punt, he got his
nose smashed in (they didn't wear facemasks in those days). He also
played basketball.
</P>
<P>
   In the spring of 1962, Stoneman pitched for West Covina, but
graduation was approaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a pretty good student and I wanted to focus on my
studies,'' he said. ``I wasn't a standout on the team, just another
guy who pitched. I was neck-and-neck with one of my buddies for top
male student GPA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't pitching that much, so I figured the time I spent
practicing, I could spend that time studying and beat Mike out. So
that's what I did.''
</P>
<P>
   Stoneman quit the baseball team, and lost the GPA race with
Mike.
</P>
<P>
   Stoneman continued his education at Mt. San Antonio College, but
nearly quit the baseball team there, too.
</P>
<P>
   After working out with the team in the fall, Stoneman went to
register for classes for the second semester but couldn't get the
classes he wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was ready to drop out,'' he said. ``I wasn't going to waste
a semester there. I went to (Mt. SAC coach John) Arrambide to wish
him well. I was just going to take off and pick pineapples in
Hawaii or something. I hadn't found myself yet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Back in those days they gave you classes alphabetically,''
said Arrambide, who is retired and living in Huntington Beach. ``By
the time they got to 'S' the class he needed was filled up. I
talked to one of the counselors and we were able to get him in. It
was a class he needed to get into a university. He was a real good
student at that was important to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time we get together now, he goes through that whole
rigmarole. 'You saved me from dropping out of school.' It's
embarrassing.''
</P>
<P>
   Stoneman became an all-conference pitcher that year, but
scholarship offers to a four-year university were nowhere to be
found.
</P>
<P>
   However, an article in the San Gabriel Valley Tribune noting
Stoneman's all-conference selection made it into the hands of the
University of Idaho baseball coach, thanks to one of Stoneman's old
high school buddies attending Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   Stoneman was offered a partial scholarship, and he was
Idaho-bound. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
POTATO PICKERS
</P>
<P>
   In Stoneman's senior year at Idaho, the team was ``almost
unbeatable'' according to Stoneman. They had four pitchers that
eventually would play professionally Stoneman, Frank Reberger, Al
Simmons and Ken Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   They won an NCAA Regional Tournament in Greeley, Colo., and then
made a trip to Tucson, Ariz. to play the University of Arizona for
the right to go to Omaha, Neb., for the NCAA College World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``He were were, these potato-picking guys from Idaho, wearing
these baggy uniforms,'' Stoneman said. ``We had to play under the
lights, and none of us had ever played under the lights.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona won and advanced, and Idaho's players flew home thinking
they were the better team. But all was not lost. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
FROM FIRESTONE TO FIREBALLER
</P>
<P>
   After Idaho was eliminated, Stoneman, now a college graduate,
returned home to West Covina. His plan was to resume his summer job
driving a truck for Firestone Tires, then go to graduate school.
His ambition was to coach baseball at the college level, and he
needed a master's degree. He had been accepted to the University of
Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   One night after work, Stoneman got a call from a scout from the
Chicago Cubs. It was a week after the baseball draft and Stoneman
had been drafted by the Cubs in the 34th round. But it took the
Cubs a week to find Stoneman.
</P>
<P>
   The scout came to Stoneman's home to sign him, but when Stoneman
asked about a signing bonus, the scout told him there wasn't any
bonus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him to get out of the house,'' Stoneman said.
</P>
<P>
   In the following days, Stoneman's parents stepped in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both my parents were from Chicago,'' he said. ``My dad was
always pushing education. My mom was a baseball fanatic. And now,
both my parents, including my dad, were saying, 'You've got a
degree, baseball is offering you an opportunity. All you're doing
is driving a truck.' Both wanted me to go and forget the bonus.
It's the opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   The scout called back a couple days later and offered Stoneman a
$500 bonus, and he accepted. Stoneman would play in the Cubs'
minor-league system and spend the offseason going to school. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
FAST TRACK TO THE BIGS
</P>
<P>
   Stoneman played in Caldwell, Idaho (rookie league), then in
Lodi, Calif. (Single-A), then in Fort Worth, Texas (Double-A) in
1966. In 1967, he began the season in Triple-A at Tacoma, Wash.,
and soon was called up to the big club, joining Billy Williams, Ron
Santos, Ernie Banks, Joe Niekro, Randy Hundley, Ferguson Jenkins
and Ken Holtzman.
</P>
<P>
   After the 1968 season, he was selected by the Montreal Expos in
the expansion draft and pitched there for five seasons. He threw
his no-hitters vs. the Phillies (1969) and Mets (1972) while with
Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a power pitcher,'' Stoneman said. ``I had a good
fastball and a pretty good curveball. I had a lot of strikeouts,
but I walked a lot of guys too. I was the kind of guy where I could
have full command of the game, but when I lost I beat myself.''
</P>
<P>
   In the spring of 1973, Stoneman was slated to start opening day
for the Expos. But while throwing during spring training, his
shoulder popped.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like getting shot,'' Stoneman said.
</P>
<P>
   The following year his contract was sold to the Angels, with
whom he went 1-8. His shoulder would never be the same, and he knew
it. That's when he had his meeting with Dalton, ending his playing
career. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
TRADING BASEBALL JERSEY FOR BUSINESS SUIT
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't long before Stoneman was back in Montreal, working for
Royal Trust, a financial institution. He quickly ascended in the
company and eventually became a regional manager in charge of 28
branches.
</P>
<P>
   He had been with the firm about nine years when on a vacation
with his wife, Diane and their two children, Jill and Jeff,
Stoneman stopped by the ballpark to see some old friends. While
talking with a writer in the press box, the Expos' president and
general manager, John McHale, asked Stoneman to meet with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He asked me if I wanted to come back to baseball,'' Stoneman
said. ``I said no, I'm doing fine with Royal Trust. But what John
said was that baseball was evolving and becoming more of a
business. He said I've got the business exposure, and now I could
take those skills with my baseball background and bring it all
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Stoneman accepted the job in 1983 as assistant to the president,
and worked there until last year, when he got a call from Angels
president Tony Tavares. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
TIME IS RIGHT
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, Stoneman had rejected opportunities to become
a general manager during his days in Montreal. But last year,
because his children were grown and living on their own, he figured
the time was right.
</P>
<P>
   He has been labeled as a bottom-line guy because of his years
with the Expos, but says it is different now.
</P>
<P>
   ``The budget here is very generous compared to Montreal,'' he
said. ``For whatever reason, the perception is Disney pulls a lot
of strings in my office, but they don't. That's not an accurate
perception at all. I have guidelines and I have a budget. ... I've
had the flexibility to move things around a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Stoneman was criticized early in his Angels tenure for how he
handled the situation with free-agent pitcher Chuck Finley.
Stoneman explained he didn't want to make an offer until having a
face-to-face meeting with Finley, but couldn't get ahold of him.
When the two finally talked on the phone, Finley said he didn't
have time that week, and that he'd get back to Stoneman the
following week.
</P>
<P>
   ``That call never came,'' Stoneman said. ``It became pretty
evident that he just didn't seem to have an interest here.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
BACK HOME
</P>
<P>
   Stoneman and his wife have purchased a home in Orange, Calif.,
but Southern California looks nothing like it did when he left to
go to Idaho nearly 40 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were still orange groves back then,'' he said. ``They
just plowed through them to build housing tracts. And there are a
lot more freeways now.''
</P>
<P>
   He has come full circle, and says he has enjoyed the ride.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly owe a lot to a number of people,'' he said.
``Whether it's John Arrambide or Freddie Martin, my first pitching
coach with the Cubs, or the guy who brought me into the trust
company after my playing career. Talking with John McHale was a
chance meeting. Would he ever have called me if I didn't go to the
game? Who knows. But I'm certainly happy with how it's all worked
out.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
