<HEADLINE>
BROWN, SHEFFIELD WOULD BE HAPPIER IF DODGERS WEREN'T STRUGGLING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The honor is humbling, both left fielder Gary
Sheffield and right-hander Kevin Brown agree. Both are All-Star
veterans accustomed to rubbing elbows with the greatest in the
game, and it never gets tiresome.
</P>
<P>
   But both men said it would be a heck of a lot more fun to
represent the Dodgers in today's All-Star Game in Atlanta if the
Dodgers were playing better.
</P>
<P>
   Things aren't as miserable as they were a year ago when the
Dodgers were hopelessly lost at this point, but the situation is
hardly ideal. The Dodgers, riddled by injuries and attempting to
get away from the cloud caused by the fight at Wrigley Field two
months ago, staggered to the All-Star break losing 10 of their last
17 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we were in first place, it would (feel better),'' said
Sheffield, a six-time All-Star. ``Being six games out, I feel
disappointed. I felt like we achieved a lot as a team, and it just
seems for some reason we can be at a place where things are looking
bright and we don't grow from it. That's the thing that's
frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not a dire position, but after winning a National
League-leading 25 games on the road, the Dodgers thought they'd be
closer than six games and three teams from first place in the
National League West. Instead, at 44-42, including a horrid 19-19
at home, they trail Arizona, Colorado and San Francisco in the
division.
</P>
<P>
   ``The All-Star stuff is great, but it would be a lot sweeter if
we started playing better as a team and we had the chance to play
in the postseason,'' said Brown, heading to his fifth All-Star
game. ``Those individual honors mean so much more when they're set
in the backdrop of a team playing competitive ball.''
</P>
<P>
   And just think where the Dodgers would be without Sheffield and
Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Brown missed 16 days and three starts with a broken right
pinkie, which he suffered in his second start of the season. But
he's 8-2 with a 2.38 ERA, and if not for him, a Dodgers starter
wouldn't have a win in close to a month. The last time another
Dodgers starter won a game was June 18, when Chan Ho Park beat St.
Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brownie should have 11 or 12 wins,'' Dodgers manager Davey
Johnson said. ``If we could score some runs for him, even though
he's been out, he'd have a lot more wins.''
</P>
<P>
   But the most telling statistic showing Brown's first-half value
is his 17 starts. The Dodgers are 12-5 in Brown's starts and 32-37
when he doesn't start.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not (rattled off a long winning streak) this year,
yet,'' Brown said. ``We have the ability to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield isn't just leading the Dodgers in batting (.334),
homers (27), RBI (71) and walks (58), and he's tied for the team
lead with 64 runs scored, but he's taken on the leadership role the
organization hoped he would.
</P>
<P>
   That was apparent from the first week of the season when on
Black Saturday a day Brown, Sheffield, Gregg Olson and Mike Fetters
all suffered injuries Sheffield badly twisted his ankle, needed a
wheelchair to get through the airport in New York, then played two
days later in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield experienced similar mishaps through the first month of
the season, but he didn't miss playing time.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield is the first one to admit one of the reasons he's had
the best first half of his career is the arrival of right fielder
Shawn Green. Though Green is slumping (his average is down to
.294), his left-handed bat provides the kind of protection for
Sheffield in the No.3 spot that right-handed Eric Karros couldn't
last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a team, we have to go higher,'' Sheffield said. ``The
locker room is great, a great bunch of guys, but we have to go
higher. We have to shoot for the sky. We can't just sit here and be
comfortable with where we're at.''
</P>
<P>
   NOTES: The Dodgers are expected to recall catcher Paul LoDuca
for Thursday's game against Anaheim to provide depth at catcher
until Chad Kreuter returns from his eight-game suspension on
Sunday. LoDuca hit .346 with two homers and five RBI earlier this
season.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers thought they could get by with Todd Hundley doing
all of the catching, but he injured his right hand Friday in
Seattle and didn't start at catcher either Saturday or Sunday. ...
Right-hander Jeff Shaw also is slated to be activated and
right-hander Gregg Olson likely will be asked to make at least one
more rehab appearance so he can be evaluated by front-office
personnel. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
