<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Airlines tell subscribers about weekend bargains with Wednesday
e-mails.
 &HT;    By Mary Ellen Flannery
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. - So I'm sitting at lunch on a recent
Wednesday, and I say to my co-workers, ``Guess what I'm doing this
weekend?'' And they can't possibly guess because it's just so
spontaneous. And it seems like something I couldn't possibly
afford.
</P>
<P>
   I'm flying to Boston on just 60 hours notice!
</P>
<P>
   Every Wednesday, I get e-mails from a handful of airlines:
Delta, USAirways, Continental and American. And they all tell me
about last-minute ``e-saver'' sales on their Saturday flights _ one
week, I can fly from West Palm Beach to Boston and back for $159.
(If I were to buy a regular round-trip ticket just three days in
advance, it would likely cost more than $400.)
</P>
<P>
   I have to be back at work Monday, and the airlines specify the
return trip must be taken either Monday or Tuesday. It's a really
short vacation, but 2-year-old Mollie and 5-year-old William
haven't seen their favorite aunt in a whole month. And their
favorite aunt (that's me, by the way) is craving a Wellfleet
lobster.
</P>
<P>
   Two days on Cape Cod gives me enough time to eat too many fried
clams at Sir Cricket's in Orleans, and share a Ben and Jerry's
coffee ice-cream soda with Buzz! Buzz! ice cream. And it gives
Mollie a chance to stuff my bellybutton with rocks and shells she
finds on Nauset Beach. With those opportunities in mind, a short
vacation actually might be better _ one more day in Cape Cod, and
I'd be fat and impaired.
</P>
<P>
   I buy the tickets Wednesday afternoon on Delta's Web site,
www.delta-air.com. On Saturday morning _ 6:30 a.m.! _ I check in at
the gate, where Delta's agent looks over my credit card. By midday,
I'm eating an eggplant sandwich in the historic village of
Sandwich, Mass. Hours later, I've been tricked into buying a $5
Massachusetts instant lottery ticket by the 5-year-old. Five
dollars?!
</P>
<P>
   Of the four airlines I get notices from _ Delta, USAirways,
Continental and American _ the first two occasionally offer deals
from West Palm Beach to places like Washington, D.C., Philadelphia,
Cleveland and Boston. Delta also offers something called ``fan
fares,'' which are trips tied to special events.
</P>
<P>
   Continental flies more often from Fort Lauderdale, and American
offers discount fares from Miami.
</P>
<P>
   I get a weekly message about American's international flights,
too _ Dominican Republic, Costa Rica, the Netherlands ... I can
dream, can't I?
</P>
<P>
   Anyone with Internet access can sign up to get Wednesday
e-mails. Just sign up at each airline's Web site. I use
www.delta-air.com; www.usairways.com; www.continental.com;
www.AA.com. Other airlines also offer special Internet fares. These
include ``dot deals'' at www.twa.com; ``click and save'' at
www.southwest.com; and e-fares on www.united.com.
</P>
<P>
   maryellenflannery(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
