</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ClERMONT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clermont promises change from Disney attractions
 &HT;    By Michael Browning
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLERMONT, Fla. _ If you are looking for a pleasant, inexpensive,
un-Disneyfied weekend getaway, within three hours' drive of Palm
Beach County, then take the high ground.
</P>
<P>
   Here, within a few minutes' drive of each other, are three
inexpensive tourist attractions, an atmospheric old downtown, and a
profusion of more than 1,400 blue lakes where you can bicycle and
picnic atop the rolling hills of the Florida Ridge.
</P>
<P>
   But you better come quick: Lake County is growing by leaps and
bounds, becoming a bedroom community for burgeoning Orlando. New
housing divisions are being sculpted in fanciful swirls over hills
that once were clad with orange groves as far as the eye can see.
</P>
<P>
   And the eye can see pretty far from the top of the Citrus Tower,
where owner Greg Homan has an office just below the observation
deck. He thinks he may be the highest office-holder in the state,
when you add the 226 feet of the tower to the 225-foot natural
elevation of the hill on which it stands. The combined height would
put Homan's desk at well over 40 stories high, from sea level.
</P>
<P>
   ``It rocks a little in a big thunderstorm,'' Homan said. ``The
first time it happened to me, I thought it was my blood pressure
surging. But it was just the tower in a storm.''
</P>
<P>
   It costs just $3.50 to ride the elevator of the 1956 tower to
the top (there are stairs, but they are only used in emergencies)
and one is rewarded with one of the most tremendous panoramas in
Florida. On clear days you can practically see across the state, 60
miles east, 60 miles west. The faraway profile of Orlando's skyline
glows against the morning wash of sunlight, and a small blocky
structure on the very horizon is the gigantic building at Cape
Canaveral where Saturn moon rockets were assembled and housed
upright.
</P>
<P>
   You can see up to eight counties from here: Lake, Orange, Polk,
Sumter, Pasco, Osceola, Seminole and Marion, in wide-cast horizons
of watery blue.
</P>
<P>
   The tower contains 5 million pounds of concrete and 149,000
pounds of reinforcing steel. Homan boasts it can withstand winds of
up to 190 mph. The observation deck at the top is enclosed by glass
and has a curious steel tube, which drops down the full height of
the structure, and is equipped with two ear-tubes, one on either
side.
</P>
<P>
   You're supposed to drop a quarter in a slot, put your ear to the
ear-tube, and listen to it fall, ka-ching, ka-ching, ka-ching, all
226 feet. The coin finishes up with a little bell-like chime at the
bottom.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get about $800 worth of quarters out of the drop each year,
and give them to the Green Isles Children's Ranch,'' Homan said. He
just repainted the tower a creamy white and pastel green, and
regards himself as the trustee of a lofty piece of Florida's past.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Citrus Tower,'' Homan declared, ``is Clermont's claim to
fame.''
</P>
<P>
   The Citrus Tower is open from 8 a.m. to 5 p.m. every day except
Thanksgiving and Christmas; Sundays from 11 a.m. to 6 p.m. Adults
$3.50; children 3 to 15, $1; children under 2 free. Group rates
available. Call (352) 394-4061 for more information.
</P>
<P>
   The House of Presidents
</P>
<P>
   filled with memorabili
</P>
<P>
   A stone's throw away from the base of the Citrus Tower is one of
the most remarkable museums in Florida: The House of Presidents.
Small and unprepossessing from the outside, the white-columned
cinder-block building contains an extraordinary miscellany of U.S.
presidential memorabilia and some fascinating, detailed models of
the White House and its Oval Office under various administrations
going back to 1909.
</P>
<P>
   The lordly height of the nearby Citrus Tower makes this little
place seem a mere footnote at the edge of the parking lot. But the
House of Presidents is a highly original, quirky, almost fanatical
tribute to the American presidency assembled over the space of
nearly 40 years by Orlando entrepreneur and modeler John Zweifel.
It is well worth a visit.
</P>
<P>
   A gigantic original lithograph of President William McKinley
hangs by the door, and behind the cash register is a 1900 election
poster for William Jennings Bryan, decrying imperialism, showing
the great trusts as an evil octopus whose limbs are about to be
chopped off by Liberty. This is hot stuff, and it is only the
beginning.
</P>
<P>
   A half-hour film introduces you to Zweifel and his lifelong love
affair with U.S. presidential history. The masterpiece of the
collection, a 60-foot-long, 20-foot-highcutaway model of the White
House, isn't here now. It is on tour and will return in November.
But what is here, is amazing.
</P>
<P>
   Zweifel acquired huge wooden replicas of the American battleship
fleet that fought during the Spanish-American War: the Maine, the
Olympia and others that were commissioned by then-secretary of the
Navy Theodore Roosevelt, and later acquired by circus master James
Bailey. The models are not named because they pre-existed the
actual ships. Thus the wooden Maine here is older than the real
Maine, which was blown up in Havana Harbor and later refloated,
towed out to sea and sunk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not political. I'm an admirer of every president, really I
am,'' Zweifel said in a phone interview. ``It's such a tremendous,
demanding position that you have to respect anyone who takes it on.
And really, there have only been a handful of presidents who didn't
measure up.''
</P>
<P>
   On permanent display here is a very large model of the White
House under construction, being visited by then-president
Washington. The affair is so large it practically occupies an
entire room and is full of amusing details, like one man running
from an outhouse, doing his trousers up, to be on time to see the
president. Parts of the model move, and sounds of sawing and
hammering, backed up by fife and drum music, add to the
authenticity.
</P>
<P>
   Zweifel managed to acquire an original chair (Number H17) from
Ford's Theater in Washington where Abraham Lincoln was
assassinated. The place was remodeled in the 1950s. He bought
``extras'' of presidential china going back to Garfield's
administration. Original issues of newspapers announcing Lincoln's
murder, FDR's death, Truman's ``defeat'' by Dewey in 1948,
Kennedy's assassination, are all on display here, along with
thousands of other presidential memorabilia and waxworks of the men
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   First ladies' gowns, presidential gift cufflinks, autographs, a
campaign torch from a rally for Lincoln in 1864, a glass bowl
commemorating James Garfield's assassination with the words, ``We
Mourn Our Nation's Loss'' on it. The place is filled to the roof
with an attic-like profusion of artifacts one could spend hours
looking at. The gift shop is as quirky as the museum: I was
attracted by a large gold head of Richard Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you see is only about 15 percent of what I've got,''
Zweifel said proudly.
</P>
<P>
   The House of Presidents is open from 9 a.m to 5 p.m. daily.
Admission is $7.95 for adults, $3.95 for children, with children
under 4 free. One ticket is good for a whole year's return visits.
Call (352) 394-2836 for more information.
</P>
<P>
   Lake Ridge Winery
</P>
<P>
   is Florida's largest
</P>
<P>
   ``Wine is part of civilized life, when consumed intelligently,''
says the video at Lake Ridge Winery, Florida's largest, 7 miles
north of the Citrus Tower on U.S. 27. Set on a hill overlooking two
lakes and several rolling hills, the winery is open free to
visitors and makes its money off sales of wine after a short,
pleasant tour has worked up a gentle thirst, and a free
wine-tasting has titillated the taste buds.
</P>
<P>
   The 127 acres of muscadine, Suwannee and Blanc du Bois grapes
produce 106,000 gallons of various wines, 97 percent of which are
sold right on the premises. The tour takes you through the large
room in which the stainless steel fermentation tanks, each holding
5,000 gallons, stand in rows and along the way you learn a lot
about grapes and wine-making.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the reason champagne costs so much is not that
there is a worldwide conspiracy to make this treat punishingly
expensive, but that champagne is difficult, occasionally even
dangerous to produce (bottles can explode under pressure). It
requires immense coddling, injections of yeast, regular rotation in
racks of steeper and steeper-angled slots to separate out the
sediment, uncorking, recorking, wiring, etc.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors are at last invited to a free tasting of some of Lake
Ridge's vintages _ not the really expensive ones, like the Marquis
Reserve, which goes for $19.95 a bottle, but a fair selection of
about six different whites and reds, with a splash of pink
champagne as well. (Guide Thomas Joaquin slyly turns on a bubble
machine beneath the counter to introduce the champagne).
</P>
<P>
   How good are they? I am no oenologist, but it seemed to me that
the lower-priced wines at Lake Ridge actually had more character
and originality than the upper-tier vintages. The Cuvee Noir
Reserve, a dry red wine similar to a Merlot, was very well-balanced
and dignified, while the Blanc du Bois got off to a great start,
then rather vapored away at the back of the palate.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the chablis, the Southern white and the Southern
red, while too sweet to be ranked with the great wines of
California, Italy and France, had a refreshing short-sleeved
Floridian authenticity to them. Florida's muscadine grape is its
own danged fruit, irrepressible, wildly sweet, sunshiny and
appealing. There was a quality of freshness and spontaneity to its
wine, very sincere and pleasant, very easygoing and amiable, the
way a Beaujolais Nouveau can be on a bright day. The chablis was on
sale for about $4 a bottle if you bought a case, and the more you
buy of anything, the more discounts you get.
</P>
<P>
   The winery supplies little red wagons for you to fill with boxes
and bottles. Wineglasses, corkscrews, olive oils, vinegars, jellies
and other dainties are also on sale in the tasting room.
</P>
<P>
   There is a pretty picnic area adjacent to the winery where you
can lunch and look down, in the distance, on the silver barbed wire
of the Lake County Corrections Institution, whose inmates are, in a
way, trampling out the vintage of their own grapes of wrath.
</P>
<P>
   Lake Ridge Winery is open to the public free, Monday through
Saturday from 10 a.m. to 5 p.m. and Sundays from 11 a.m. to 5 p.m.
Closed Christmas, New Year's Day and Easter. Call (352) 394-1839
for more information
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
