<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Thrill of the chase for a home run ball
 &HT;    By Jenn Hildreth
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Even though it caused two skinned knees, two skinned
elbows, and a bleeding right wrist, it was worth it.
</P>
<P>
   At least that's what the guy who caught one of Sammy Sosa's home
run balls told me as he applied a napkin to his wrist.
</P>
<P>
   That's right, when he went diving in between the rows to grab
one of the eventual Home Run Derby champion's bombs to left field,
I was about six rows up elbowing some kids for position.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that this guy, named Ben Johnson, was sitting in
section 136, row 23, seat 102, while my seat was in section 136,
row 24, seat 103.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that another guy two seats over in section 136 also
has a ball to take home (off the bat of Ivan Rodriguez in batting
practice), and I merely have the memories of the slightly scuffed
ball that he let me hold - briefly.
</P>
<P>
   I think at least two balls even flew into the auxiliary press
box where my laptop was set up in left field.
</P>
<P>
   Talk about being in the wrong place at the wrong time.
</P>
<P>
   But I've got to tell you, honestly, even though I didn't catch a
ball, I could not think of a place that I would have rather been
than where I was tonight.
</P>
<P>
   I thought that hitting a golf ball cleanly was possibly the best
feeling in the world (not that I've felt it that often).
</P>
<P>
   Connecting with the sweet spot on a baseball bat and swishing a
basketball cleanly through the net are tied at a close second, but
seeing that home run ball come hurtling through the air blows them
all away.
</P>
<P>
   It's amazing how everything - the people around you raising
their gloves, the sound of the crowd in anticipation of the home
run, your heart beating in your chest - just swells into a giant
crescendo.
</P>
<P>
   There's that split second when you feel like it really might be
coming your way, when you start to wonder how much you're going to
have to stretch and run and push to get to where it might land, and
that is, to me, one of the best feelings in sports.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so I'm trying really hard to mask the fact that I failed at
my assignment.
</P>
<P>
   And I'd tell you about how I came really close to one of Ken
Griffey Jr.'s shots that richocheted off a few gloves in right
field (I sprinted over there from my spot in left field for the
second round), and how I could probably have gotten another one of
Sosa's hits to left if I had just stretched a little further over
the rail, but I know, close only counts in romance and horseshoes.
</P>
<P>
   Or something like that.
</P>
<P>
   I really did try everything I could think of ... I tried telling
people that I could get their picture in the paper.
</P>
<P>
   I planned to stay away from small children and the elderly -
people that I knew I couldn't push out of the way without feeling
really guilty.
</P>
<P>
   I even secretly urged on all of the people in the section
directly in front of me who were shaking those long, skinny
balloons, hoping their arms would tire out.
</P>
<P>
   But when it all wound down, after Sosa's explosion for nine home
runs in the final round that had me rooting along to ``Rock and
Roll Part Two'' and chanting ``Sa-mmy'' like an audience member on
the ``Jerry Springer Show'', my glove was as empty as the Budweiser
Blimp that sailed over Turner Field all night.
</P>
<P>
   I kind of feel guilty that I don't have any war wounds.
</P>
<P>
   A vendor selling cracker jacks and peanuts who had worked at the
All-Star game at Fenway in 1999 told me before the game that it
could get brutal. He wished me luck and told me not to get hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe if I had actually dove head-first over the seats like one
guy did in batting practice, I would have fared better.
</P>
<P>
   Next year, I'll wear a helmet and pads
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
