<HEADER>
A8662 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBA-RODRIGUEZ-TEX     07-10 1070
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RODRIGUEZ-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUDGE MIGHT BE BEST CATCHER EVER SAW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Ivan Rodriguez picked up another bauble to add to the
trophy case yesterday. The Rangers' catcher received an award for
garnering the most votes in fan balloting for the All-Star Game
today at Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an honor for me,'' Rodriguez said. ``I'm very happy for
that. I never expected in my career that would happen. That means a
lot for me.''
</P>
<P>
   The trophy can take its place next to Rodriguez' 1999 American
League MVP award, his eight Gold Gloves and his six Silver Slugger
Awards.
</P>
<P>
   While perhaps not as prestigious as the others, this latest
award is nevertheless significant. It indicates that baseball fans
throughout the country recognize what the other achievements prove:
That Rodriguez is the best catcher in the game today, and perhaps
the best ever to squat behind the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the best,'' said Joe Torre, the manager of the New York
Yankees and the AL All-Stars. ``Johnny Bench was that one catcher
who used to get all that recognition. But Ivan, he's done it
batting average-wise, power-wise, and you change your whole
offensive scheme when he's the catcher whether you're going to
steal a lot because he's dominant in that area. It's very unusual
to be a catcher and be that effective both offensively and
defensively.''
</P>
<P>
   Modesty forbids Rodriguez from talking about his place in
history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't consider myself the best catcher,'' he said. ``I just
consider myself another player in the game. I don't want to talk
about myself. I'm just trying to do my best.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez might be reluctant to pat himself on the back, but his
awards and statistics state the case very eloquently.
</P>
<P>
   The MVP award, all the Gold Gloves and Silver Sluggers, and the
nine All-Star appearances bear testimony that Rodriguez possesses a
rare combination of lethal bat and game-changing defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen anyone like him,'' said Yankees catcher Jorge
Posada, Rodriguez's All-Star backup. ``Every day he does something
different to help the team win. He could go 0-for-4, but he can
throw two guys out and help the team. He's that good.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past season and a half, Rodriguez has transformed himself
from dangerous hitter to deadly-as-they-come hitter.
</P>
<P>
   He batted .332 with 35 homers, 113 runs batted in and 116 runs
scored last season. The 35 homers were a record by an AL catcher,
and he became the first catcher in league history with 30 homers,
100 RBI and 100 runs scored.
</P>
<P>
   This year, he's doing even better. He's batting .366 with 26
homers and 80 RBI, and is on pace for 50 homers and 152 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   His willingness to swing at any pitch, in any count, in any
location, and more often than not to make contact and hit it hard,
makes him one of the toughest players to pitch to in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to approach him like you have two strikes on him,''
said Oakland Athletics All-Star Tim Hudson. ``You can't throw any
kind of get-me-over off-speed pitches because you'll be backing up
third or he'll be rounding the bases after a homer. He's very
impressive. He's probably one of the best hitters out there. He
hits everything. He really doesn't have a weakness. He's one of
those guys that when he gets out, he gets himself out. As a
pitcher, you really don't get him out much.''
</P>
<P>
   The only catcher in the game today who compares offensively to
Rodriguez is the New York Mets' Mike Piazza, who led the National
League in fan balloting but will miss the game with a mild
concussion.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza has more power, or at least did before this year. He's
the only catcher in history with two 40-homer seasons, but his 24
at the break are two fewer than Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone considers Mike the best offensive catcher in the
game,'' said Rangers pitcher Kenny Rogers, who played with Piazza
for the Mets last season. ``But this year and last year have shown
that Pudge is right up there with anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if Piazza still is considered a better overall hitter
because of his power, Rodriguez has the edge defensively. National
Leaguers say that Piazza is underrated defensively, but even so he
can't compare to the Rangers' Gold-Glover.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take my hat off to Mike Piazza,'' Torre said. ``Mike Piazza,
along with \RMark\S McGwire and \RSammy\S Sosa, is one of the most
feared sluggers. I think Mike is a better hitter than those other
two guys, and he hits almost as many home runs. But Ivan I think is
the total package.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez always has had the quick release and the cannon arm, a
combination that allowed him to throw out 54.2 percent of runners
attempting to steal last year, the best percentage since the
statistic first was kept in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``You steal them off the pitcher,'' Chicago White Sox speedster
Ray Durham said. ``You try to get the best jump you can, and if you
don't you'd better turn around and get back to first. And even
taking your lead off first, you can't get too far out or he'll snap
a throw down there and you'll be walking back to the dugout.''
</P>
<P>
   If there was a criticism of Rodriguez, it was his ability to
call games. But like his hitting, even that has improved.
</P>
<P>
   ``What impressed me the most about him in the past two years was
his ability to call the game, to get on the same page as me and
remember things in the heat of battle we had talked about before
the game,'' said Seattle Mariners All-Star Aaron Sele, a former
Ranger. ``He would call timeout and run out and say remember what
we talked about, this is what we want to do here, stay with this
plan. He really kept his pitcher on the same page and on focus.
That is something that doesn't get talked about a lot with Pudge,
but in the two years I worked with him he got better and better and
better every day.''
</P>
<P>
   The All-Star voters recognized that this year. Along with the
other awards and honors, it's another indicator that the AL's
starting catcher today just might be the best ever at his position.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never played with \RJohnny\S Bench or saw him catch,''
Rogers said. ``I know he was great. But did he throw as well as
Pudge? I don't think so, and I don't think he could hit as well as
Pudge. He's head and shoulders above anybody that's ever played at
doing everything.''  &LR; tagtop:Simon Gonzalez, (817) 390-7760
 &LR; tagbottom:gonzalez &LR; star-telegram.com
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
