<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 23:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8667 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BKC-RECRUITING-TEX     07-10 1058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-RECRUITING-TEX </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   College basketball's summer game is in full swing. Division I's
three-week evaluation/recruiting period started Saturday. For the
rest of this month, at dozens of tournaments nationwide, players
will play and coaches will watch.
</P>
<P>
   And, if the NCAA has its way, summer recruiting will never be
the same. Next year, the summer recruiting period will be trimmed
from 24 to 14 days. By 2002, the NCAA hopes to have a new
recruiting model in place with the goal of ``eliminating summer
basketball environments as we now know it,'' said Penn State
president Graham Spanier, chairman of the Division I board of
directors. The NCAA wants a system ``fair to all schools \Rthat\S
doesn't exploit the student-athlete,'' spokesman Wally Renfro said.
</P>
<P>
   While the NCAA plans to address the problem, many college
coaches believe it wants to do more than that, and eliminate summer
recruiting. The National Association of Basketball Coaches has
called an emergency meeting this weekend in Las Vegas to discuss
the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea isn't to eliminate summer recruiting, it's more to
examine and restructure it,'' said Kim Anderson, Big 12 director of
basketball operations. ``The problem with fixing it is that not
everybody is going to agree with the solution.''
</P>
<P>
   Southwest Missouri State coach Barry Hinson is skeptical,
though. Asked if he thought the NCAA wants to eliminate summer
recruiting, he said, ``You bet I do.''
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't think it'll happen, however. ``I think there will be
some changes but I don't think they'll eliminate it completely. I
think the \RNCAA\S will realize the summer evaluation period is
cost effective. But if they eliminate it completely, the medium
fish will quickly become little fish. The rich will get richer. It
will be Robin Hood in reverse.''
</P>
<P>
   NCAA staff members are attending this month's summer recruiting
events to gather information to make recommendations to the
recently formed basketball issues committee, which will meet for
the first time in August. Its first task will be recommending
changes for the summer recruiting process.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that we believe we need a new summer recruiting model
has been interpreted universally that the NCAA wants to eliminate
summer recruiting,'' Renfro said. ``That's not the intent ... The
concern is there are too many individuals whose interest in the
recruiting process doesn't necessarily reflect the best interests
of the student-athlete. \RThose individuals\S are influence or
profit motivated.''
</P>
<P>
   This past season, a high-profile scandal pointed the spotlight
on the summer basketball scene. Myron Piggie, a Kansas City summer
coach, was indicted for mail fraud and tax evasion. Testimony
during the trial indicated that Piggie had given money to players
on his summer league team. Those players later enrolled at Oklahoma
State, Duke, Missouri and UCLA. That is the type of recruiting
problem the NCAA wants to eliminate.
</P>
<P>
   Since the mid-1980s, the evaluation period each July has allowed
coaches to watch _ but not actively recruit _ players at
tournaments and camps. Combined with scholarship limitations, the
summer recruiting period has helped the lower two-thirds of the
300-plus Division I schools recruit better players. Those schools
hope that through their summer recruiting diligence they can find
the late-bloomer, the diamond-in-the-rough, the player that the top
Division I schools don't need.
</P>
<P>
   UT-Arlington's $20,000 recruiting budget, for instance, is about
one-fifth that of the University of Texas. But UTA coach Eddie
McCarter and his staff can maximize that budget through planning
and hard work in the summer. Typically, UTA identifies about 50
players it can recruit. That list is pared to 10 to 15 players.
They hope to sign three to five of those.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they do away with summer recruiting, we'd be in a financial
bind,'' McCarter said. ``We'd have to find some money somewhere to
add to recruiting.''
</P>
<P>
   Coaches see other problems, should the summer recruiting period
be further cut or eliminated, including more travel and expense
during the school year and fewer coaches with the team during the
season.
</P>
<P>
   Next year, the 10 days trimmed from the summer recruiting period
will be added to the days that coaches can recruit during the
school year. And if summer recruiting is eliminated completely, all
24 days would be moved to the school year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that happens, assistant coaches will be on the road all the
time during the season recruiting,'' SMU coach Mike Dement said.
</P>
<P>
   And even if coaches are prohibited from summer evaluations, the
events likely would continue. Mike Kunstadt, director of the Great
American Shootout that concluded in Denton yesterday, said that he
would continue to hold his event, which drew 184 teams and just
over 2,000 players. ``The kids want to play, they want to face
different competition and travel a little,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Coaches would still need to get updated evaluations on players.
Video services, live Internet feeds and scouting services would
likely fill the void.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coaches will still have to talk to these summer coaches to
find out how the players they're interested in are playing,''
Dement said. ``It's not the \Revents\S that are the problem. It's
some of the people, a small number of people, involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Kunstadt agrees. He estimates that of the 800 to 900
summer-league teams in Texas, only about 10 are coached by people
he suspects of being ``street agents,'' similar to Piggie. Through
the National Association of Basketball Coaches, Kunstadt has
recommended that the NCAA sanction coaches of summer teams. Any
coach that violates the rules could be suspended from coaching
teams in NCAA-sanctioned events.
</P>
<P>
   ``What needs to be done is control the street agents,'' Kunstadt
said. ``If we sanctioned or registered the summer league coaches,
we could eliminate some of the problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone seems to agree the current system is beset with
problems. Solutions are tougher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you make summer recruiting fit into some sort of halcyon
notion of how college basketball should operate? I don't think
anybody knows that,'' the NCAA's Renfro said. ``That's part of the
process that we're going through.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-00 2318EDT &QL; 
