<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 23:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8668 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBA-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-T     07-10 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It would be wrong to say Pudge Rodriguez is concerned. Concern
doesn't register in any conversation. Not yet, anyway. But does
Pudge currently ponder over his future in Arlington with a bit of
uncertainty?
</P>
<P>
   I'd say yes. And to that, you might answer, ``But how could that
be?'' Well ... because. Just because.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, it's the All-Star Game in Atlanta, where this
one-of-a-kind Ranger shows the baseball world what the baseball
world has already recognized.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez is the very best in the business. On that, there is no
debate. The Rangers, in their 29 years of existence, have never had
a player recognized as the very best at his position.
</P>
<P>
   Is Pudge the best all-around catcher who ever lived? And if not
now, will he someday be hailed as even better than the immortal
Johnny Bench? That, of course, is today's on-going argument, one
that continues to pick up steam as Pudge's offensive numbers
mushroom.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, the Rangers were hoping for 26 homers and 80
runs batted in from Rodriguez. In a season.
</P>
<P>
   But those are his current stats at the All-Star break. Along
with a .363 batting average. Don't look back, Mr. Bench. Somebody
is gaining on you.
</P>
<P>
   Mix in on-the-field performance with Pudge's immense popularity
with local fans (second in franchise history to only Nolan Ryan.
Don't look back, Mr. Ryan. Somebody is also gaining on you), and
his self-taught sense of maintaining proper public relations and a
family-values image, and his anti-baseball-greed stance of 1997,
and you combine all of it, and what we have here is Ivan Rodriguez,
a native son of Puerto Rico who has become a local institution.
</P>
<P>
   The Fort Worth Stockyards District would be traded to Dallas
before Tom Hicks would ever allow Rodriguez to wear anything other
than a Rangers' uniform. Or so would be the logical assumption.
</P>
<P>
   But this is also baseball. Uniforms do change. And the money is
so staggering that baseball's international goodwill ambassador of
two years ago, Sammy Sosa, can now be portrayed, fair or unfair, as
Greed Inc. in Chicago. At times, it's the player who demands more,
more, more. At other times, it's the club saying enough is enough.
See Juan Gonzalez last winter.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez has two more years after this season on his Rangers'
contract. but it is later than you think. Pudge is baseball's
biggest bargain at $8 million a season, the contract he negotiated
for himself in '97, personally ending a tense standoff with
management. By this time next year, the sports page will be full of
speculation on whether the Rangers are going to keep Pudge. The
team could not allow him to go to a free-agent season in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa's PR mistake with the Cubs was he demanded a new contract,
and much more money, with still two years remaining on his current
deal. Even with most players, that goes against protocol. Pudge
will not do that next season. He's too smart and too PR savvy. But
it goes without him saying it outright that Pudge is hoping to get
a long-term deal done by the end of next season. Actually, right
now would suit him, and also be the proper move for the Rangers.
Which is why Pudge is already dropping subtle hints.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no better place for me ... absolutely,'' he was
saying one day last week in the clubhouse. ``These fans, this
ballpark, the community ... This is where I want to finish my
career. I'd like a lifetime contract. It's important to me to be
able to say I played my entire career right here.''
</P>
<P>
   As Pudge was talking, a team media-relations guy informed the
press that the pregame clubhouse access was over (the clubhouse
must be cleared of media 45 minutes before the first pitch). Pudge
politely waved him off. ``Stay here,'' he told a guy with a
notepad. Rodriguez continued to stress his strong desire to remain
in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   Later, a friend of Pudge's said it worried the catcher every
time he read a Doug Melvin quote about Melvin being unwilling to go
to the $10 million level with a player's salary. Pudge took
under-market value in 1997 in agreeing to the current deal, but at
age 28, what is his present worth? And in two years, what could it
be? Barring injury, that worth will certainly be far beyond $10
million a year. At what point in today's baseball market would it
become stupid to undervalue yourself no matter how much you want to
remain in Arlington?
</P>
<P>
   From the Rangers' standpoint, they will wonder how many years
Pudge can catch beyond age 30, when this current contract is up,
``Five more years,'' answered Pudge last week, meaning three more
after 30, ``and then I will play another position.''
</P>
<P>
   Again, we are one year away from Pudge's future with the Rangers
becoming an issue, and becoming for the team, a potential PR
disaster of nuclear strength. For Pudge, it's not an immediate
concern, but obviously a nagging worry. For Hicks, Melvin and Co.,
however, the clock is already ticking. / nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
