u a BC-NY-BRICK-ATTACK-625&AMP;A     07-10 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BRICK-ATTACK-625&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE SKULL FRACTURE FROM BRICK, WOMAN SYMPATHETIC TO ATTACKER 
</HEADLINE>
   By C.J. CHIVERS and JOHN W. FOUNTAIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A young woman who was attacked Sunday afternoon with
a concrete block on a Manhattan street left the hospital Monday,
sounding upbeat and expressing a measure of understanding for her
attacker.
</P>
<P>
   Simultaneously, dozens of detectives participated in an intense
manhunt but failed to turn up the assailant.
</P>
<P>
   The woman, Tiffany Goldberg, 25, was discharged from Bellevue
Hospital Center at 4:45 p.m. just one day after a man rushed up to
her from behind on East 29th Street and, in what the police
described as a botched robbery attempt, slammed her head with a
five-pound shard of concrete, fracturing her skull. The attack
occurred minutes after she had left services at Marble Collegiate
Church, where she is a member of the gospel choir.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg, a 1996 graduate of Sarah Lawrence College, has been
accepted to a master's program in clinical social work at Columbia
University. She said Monday that she herself had struggled
academically as a child, but succeeded with the help of adults, and
that the man who attacked her might have needed similar attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy who attacked me, 20 years ago, was probably a
struggling kid,'' she said. ``If anyone had reached him when he was
younger, maybe he wouldn't have done what he did.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting up in her bed before leaving the hospital, Goldberg said
she had been lucky to survive the assault but remembered little of
it, other than the image of the man who came to her aid, Lt. James
Hurley, an off-duty city firefighter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was walking down 29th Street, and the next thing I remember
I was waking up,'' she said. ``Some gentleman was kneeling over me,
trying to wake me up.''
</P>
<P>
   Lorinda Klein, a hospital spokeswoman, said that in addition to
suffering a skull fracture, Goldberg had a large cut on the back of
her head, a black eye and two shattered front teeth, injuries that
apparently occurred when she pitched face-first into the sidewalk
after she had been struck.
</P>
<P>
   But two CAT scans revealed no neurological damage, Klein said,
and Goldberg was expected to recover without complications.
Goldberg walked from the emergency ward accompanied by Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani's community assistance aides, bound for an
undisclosed location. Her spirits were high.
</P>
<P>
   The attack on Goldberg, with its similarities to the brick
attack on another young woman, Nicole Barrett, in Midtown last
fall, spurred an intense and wide-ranging police investigation.
Late Sunday night, the police began circulating a sketch of the
attacker, whom they described as a chubby and unkempt black man
with a crooked nose. They said he was about 5 feet 7 inches tall,
weighed 180-200 pounds and was believed to be homeless.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives were canvassing locations where homeless people
gather. One investigator said a witness, a homeless man, told
detectives that he had seen the assailant running down the street
after the attack and recognized him as a familiar street person.
But the investigator said the police had not corroborated this
account, and had not narrowed their search to a specific
individual.
</P>
<P>
   By nightfall Monday, the police said they had no clear suspects.
They detained a few men based on their resemblance to the sketch,
they said, but released them all after interviews.
</P>
<P>
   Police officials said they also discounted speculation that the
man who had attacked Goldberg was the same man who had attacked
Barrett. A street hustler with an extensive criminal record, Paris
Drake, has been charged with attempted murder in connection with
the attack on Barrett and is being held at the Queens House of
Detention.
</P>
<P>
   Police officials said the latest attack had not given them any
doubts about their case against Drake, who has pleaded innocent.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As the investigation into the attack on Goldberg continued,
Goldberg's friends clustered around her in the hospital or waited
for news of her condition. From her hometown in Madison, Wis., to
her apartment building in Spanish Harlem, to the Bryant Park Grill,
where she worked, her friends all described a responsible young
woman with a charitable streak.
</P>
<P>
   Alfred Colucci, a retired principal of Madison West High School,
from which she graduated in 1992, remembered her as someone who
``never, ever caused anyone any problems.''
</P>
<P>
   One friend, Rachael Blair, supervised Goldberg in February when
she was part of a 13-woman team of volunteers that traveled to
Coban, Guatemala, and built three homes for Habitat for Humanity
International. She impressed Blair as a collegial and hard worker.
</P>
<P>
   ``She never complained; she was an absolute delight,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
