<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 23:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8671 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-TEX     07-10 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-TEX </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ARTHUR GARCIA 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ As soon as Don Nelson plucked Sidney Moncrief out of
the college coaching ranks two months ago, the speculation started.
Was Moncrief, the former Arkansas Razorbacks star and Milwaukee
Bucks standout under Nelson, being groomed to succeed his onetime
mentor as Mavs head coach?
</P>
<P>
   Fair enough question and nothing new for the myriad of Mavs
assistants. Whether it's Donnie Nelson or Del Harris or the
recently departed Gar Heard, most Mavs aids have been the subject
of similar conjecture.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike those other guys, Moncrief welcomes the talk.
Moncrief wants to be the Mavs coach when Don Nelson moves into the
general- manager role full time in three years and he's not afraid
to say it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a head-coach position becomes open, I'm certainly qualified
to be a head coach in the NBA,'' Moncrief said after a minicamp
practice recently. ``I have a lot to learn, obviously, but working
under Nellie is going to help the learning process happen a lot
quicker.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not any doubt in my mind that I can be a head coach in
the NBA and I want to do it here with the Mavericks.''
</P>
<P>
   If that's the plan, no one is saying, but Don Nelson and Mavs
owner Mark Cuban are in agreement when it comes to Moncrief's
value.
</P>
<P>
   ``He brings the level of intensity that Sidney Moncrief was
known for on the court,'' Cuban said. ``He's been-there, done-that
and he's respected by the guys. He's young enough that he can
relate and talk to all the guys. It's a world that's not foreign to
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Nelson: ``He's another quality guy on the bench. Sidney is
quality all the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Moncrief proved his playing worth during an 11-year career, 10
of which were spent with the Bucks and eight under Nelson. Moncrief
averaged 15.6 points and 4.7 rebounds over that span, made the
All-Star team five times and earned Defensive Player of the Year
honors twice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think a lot of these guys are old enough to remember
my career; some remember my name in passing,'' said Moncrief, 4-23
in one season as Arkansas-Little Rock coach. ``But that doesn't
mean they don't relate to me. If you respect them as people and
have a genuine concern for their game on the basketball court, I
think players do respond to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the past two years, Nelson has offered Moncrief several
front-office positions with the club, but those jobs didn't fit
with Moncrief's career goals. Moncrief acknowledged the timing of
Nelson's latest offer was awkward _ he felt leaving Arkansas-Little
Rock after one season wasn't fair to the school _ but he jumped at
the chance to get back into the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``To get in with an organization that's going places, with a
knowledgeable aggressive owner, to coach under Don Nelson and have
the opportunity to learn under him was something I couldn't pass
on,'' he said. ``It had to be a good opportunity for me
professionally to even go anywhere and it also had to be a place I
wanted to live, and the Metroplex is someplace we feel
comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   Moncrief is also excited about the Mavs' prospects in the coming
years. The team got rolling after Cuban came on board last season
and rallied to finish 40-42 _ its best record in a decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the nucleus,'' Moncrief said. ``They have players that
can play more than one position, which has always been important to
me as a player and as a coach that you have players that are very
versatile. I think they're very hungry to win and they're good
people.''
</P>
<P>
   And he's ready to lead the charge ... someday.
</P>
<P>
   ``That certainly doesn't intimidate me, but I'm realistic enough
to know that Mark Cuban has very high expectations for this
ballclub and he's going to do what he feels is in the best interest
to move the team forward,'' Moncrief said. \Nsubheds:Buckner,
Grizzlies agree Restricted free-agent guard Greg Buckner has agreed
to a three-year, $2.5 million deal with Vancouver and plans to sign
with the Pacific Division team on Aug. 1. The Mavs have offered
Buckner a contract starting at about $500,000 per year.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban said he would probably match any offer Buckner receives to
keep him. Buckner, who participated in minicamp, won't play in the
summer league games starting today.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavs' other free-agent guard, Hubert Davis, is being courted
by seven teams, including the Mavs, who have offered a one-year
deal worth between $3.5 million and $4 million. Davis, who has not
ruled out the Mavs, is seeking a contract for approximately four
years and $10 million. \Nsubheds:Briefly The Mavs' summer league
team left for Long Beach, Calif., last night and they'll play the
Los Angeles Clippers at 5:30 p.m. today. Willie Sublett won't be
making the trip as the only minicamp cut.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's second-round pick, 7-foot center Wang Zhi Zhi,
recently completed a solid regular season for the China CBA
All-Stars in the Asian Basketball Association League. He scored 17
points while playing in an all-star game against players from the
United States. Former TCU star Mike Jones scored 22 points for the
Americans, who beat the Chinese team, 95-78.
</P>
<P>
   Zhi Zhi averaged 14.7 points and 5.4 rebounds, and shot 61.8
percent from the field and 83.6 percent from the free-throw line.
The All-Stars are facing the NBA Ambassadors in the ABAL
best-of-there finals, which began last night in Beijing.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
