<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 23:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8679 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-GASOLINE-KAN &LR;      07-10 0499
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GASOLINE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 GASOLINE PRICES DROP BELOW $1.50 A GALLON AT MANY kc AREA STATIONS (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 BY GENE MEYER, THE KANSAS CITY STAR   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gasoline prices dropped below $1.50 a gallon Monday in much of
the Kansas City area for the first time since the start of the peak
summer driving season.
</P>
<P>
   The drop wasn't universal however.
</P>
<P>
   While many QuikTrips and nearby competitors were posting $1.499
a gallon for lead-free regular as the morning commute began, a
midday check of other stations across the metropolitan area found
the $1.52 to $1.65 prices that AAA of Missouri reported in its
latest survey, taken Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Saudi Arabia's announcement last week of planned production
increases and the correction of some Midwestern market troubles
probably contributed most to the latest drop, federal government
analysts and other industry observers said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   What happens next is open to question.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prices will probably go a little lower, but I don't think
we're going to see last year's prices any time soon,'' said Mike
Right, spokesman for AAA of Missouri in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City motorists were filling up for an average of about
$1.06 a gallon this time last year. But crude oil prices at $30 a
barrel and wholesale gasoline prices at 87 cents a gallon are about
50 percent higher than then, Right said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our expectations are for a flattening out or a modest
decline'' in gasoline prices in July, said David Costello, a
spokesman for the Energy Information Administration in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Prices so far have fallen further and faster from mid-June peaks
in the Midwest than in most other parts of the United States, and
the pressure in places such as West Coast markets is pushing up
rather than down, Costello said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe prices will be volatile,'' said Debbi Graham, a
spokeswoman for QuikTrip Corp. ``There is no way we are going to
predict in any form what they will do.''
</P>
<P>
   Cities with some of the nation's dirtiest air were required to
start using cleaner-burning gasoline June 1. That caused storage
and distribution problems in many places.
</P>
<P>
   Prices at the pump have been gradually falling since about
mid-June as those storage and distribution problems were overcome.
Saudi Arabia's announcement last week that it intends to increase
crude oil production by 500,000 barrels a day will help bring
production nearer in line with expected demand, the Energy
Department said in a short-term energy outlook report for July.
</P>
<P>
   Presuming events unfold as expected, the department calculates
that prices through the rest of the summer will balance out
nationally somewhere near $1.63 a gallon.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Monday, President Clinton announced a plan to borrow 2
million barrels of oil from the nation's strategic petroleum
reserve to provide price relief for heating oil users in the
Northeast this winter if it is needed.
</P>
<P>
   The plan is expected to have no effect on fuel prices, Costello
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
