<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
LAND CHARGES FILED IN INVESTIGATION OF LAND TRUST OF JACKSON COUNTY
 
</HEADLINE>
 BC- LAND-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 BY CHRISTINE VENDEL and LYNN HORSLEY, THE KANAS CITY STAR   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Prosecutors on Monday accused the former
office manager of Land Trust of Jackson County, her husband and the
agency's former attorney of engaging in questionable land deals.
</P>
<P>
   Ardie Khan, 53, and Hameed M. Khan, 55, were charged with three
felony counts of violating the state's Land Trust law. Henry Duke
Bledsoe, the attorney for Land Trust, was charged with one count.
Each felony count carries a penalty of two to five years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Police said the three were not in custody but had agreed to
surrender later this week. They could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Land Trust is a state agency that disposes of tax-foreclosed
properties in Jackson County that do not sell at courthouse
auctions. It has an inventory of about 3,000 lots, mostly vacant
and in the inner city.
</P>
<P>
   The trust, acting in a caretaker role, is set up to sell
properties under its control. Proceeds from those sales are to be
distributed by a set formula to Kansas City, Jackson County the
Kansas City school district.
</P>
<P>
   In February, a state audit found that the agency was mismanaged
and had scores of missing or incomplete files. Kansas City fraud
detectives then seized the agency's records, and the office ceased
operations. A special prosecutor, Mark Jones, was assigned to the
case.
</P>
<P>
   According to court records, a four-month investigation by police
and the FBI found that two properties were allegedly stolen from
the Land Trust inventory. The properties were deeded to Hameed Khan
and the deals were made with the help of Ardie Khan, who was
employed by Land Trust under the name of Ardie Shannon.
</P>
<P>
   Court records showed that Hameed Khan submitted a bid of $2,000
to buy a house at 2202 E. 14th St. in 1997. Hameed Khan paid $1,300
for the house and received the title without paying the remaining
$700.
</P>
<P>
   The property was subsequently condemned. The Khans filed a
lawsuit to recover their ``losses,'' and Bledsoe assisted with the
lawsuit. The city paid $10,602 to Hameed Khan as part of a
court-ordered settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Hameed Khan also bid $6,200 in 1998 to buy a house at 2019
Benton Blvd. The property was deeded to him, but no payments were
received, according to court records.
</P>
<P>
   Another alleged violation came in the form of a lawn mowing
contract. Hameed Khan was the highest paid mower for Land Trust,
even though the law forbids spouses of employees from being
employed as vendors. Hameed Khan received more than $60,000 as a
mowing contractor.
</P>
<P>
   The court records stated that Bledsoe knew of the Khans'
marriage and the mowing contract, but he did nothing to correct the
violation.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Monday's charges were part of an ongoing
investigation, with the possibility of more people being charged.
</P>
<P>
   After the audit was released, Mayor Kay Barnes named former City
Councilwoman Aggie Stackhaus to replace Robert Newsome as chairman
of the Land Trust Board. The board consists of representatives from
the city, the county and the Kansas City School District.
</P>
<P>
   Stackhaus said Monday she was determined to reform the way the
agency does business.
</P>
<P>
   ``The No. 1 priority of the new Land Trust of Jackson County is
to serve the taxpayers of Jackson County,'' Stackhaus said.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the police raid, the board fired Ardie Khan. It
later shut down the Land Trust offices and dismissed the remaining
employees, including Bledsoe and Land Commissioner Willie McCann.
</P>
<P>
   The offices remain closed, but the board has been trying to get
the files back from police and get the agency's financial affairs
in order so it can hire new staff and resume normal operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remain optimistic and hopeful we will be selling properties
again by the fall,'' Stackhaus said. ``It's all dependent upon when
we get all the records back, the condition of the files, and the
forthcoming funding from the city and county to operate this.''
</P>
<P>
   Employees from the city and the county have been sorting through
available files to try to resolve land sales that were pending when
the police investigation began.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
