<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 23:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8681 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-ASH-KAN &LR;      07-10 1198
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASH-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS ACCUSE ASHCROFT OF IMPROPER ACTIVITIES IN 1984 CAMPAIGN
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 BY KEVIN MURPHY, THE KANSAS CITY STAR   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ While he was Missouri attorney general, John
Ashcroft improperly used state resources and employees during his
successful 1984 run for governor, the State Democratic Committee
alleged Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The party released a copy of an old 34-page memo that called for
using the attorney general's staff ``both in their existing on-duty
functions and in off-duty time'' for the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   David Ayres, who is managing Sen. Ashcroft's current re-election
effort, said Monday that the document was ``not our 1984 campaign
plan.''
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear who prepared the document. Ashcroft's former
staffers denied the campaign was run out of the state office.
</P>
<P>
   Ayres countered by alleging that Ashcroft's opponent, Missouri
Gov. Mel Carnahan, was the one who used state resources for
political purposes.
</P>
<P>
   He cited as one example Carnahan's listing the number of a phone
in his lieutenant governor's office in 1991 and 1992 as his
gubernatorial campaign headquarters phone in the Jefferson City
directory.
</P>
<P>
   ``This can only mean that his political campaign was run
directly out of his public office with his full knowledge and
consent,'' Ayres said.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Wyche, spokesman for the Carnahan campaign, said the phone
in question was a private line paid from political funds.
</P>
<P>
   Roy Temple, Democratic executive director, sent a letter to
Ashcroft on Monday asking him to explain how ``misuse of taxpayer
dollars'' squared with the senator's ``Missouri values'' campaign
theme.
</P>
<P>
   Several former aides to Ashcroft when he was attorney general
said they did not know the source of the memo.
</P>
<P>
   A section of the memo, dated 1983, shows the name ``DeGregorio''
at the top, an apparent reference to Paul DeGregorio, a campaign
coordinator in St. Louis. DeGregorio, who was not a state employee
at the time, said he did not recall such a memo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't remember what went on 16 years ago,'' he said earlier
this year. ``I'm sure there are many plans that may have been
written in this country for all kinds of politicians.''
</P>
<P>
   Chip Robertson, a one-time deputy attorney general, told
Ashcroft in a letter written last month that the memo, ``if it even
exists, never served as the basis for any decision or establishment
of responsibilities for your campaign for governor.'' Robertson
wrote the letter after being contacted by a reporter.
</P>
<P>
   He said Ashcroft insisted that any political work be done on
personal time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can recall waiting until 5 p.m. before doing something
(political),'' said Robertson, who later was appointed to the state
Supreme Court by Ashcroft and who now is in private law practice.
``It was a strict policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Temple charged that the policy was breached. The Democrats also
released depositions, taken during unrelated litigation, by two
former employees acknowledging some political work done during
weekday hours at the time.
</P>
<P>
   In mid-1983, Ashcroft office scheduler Tom Deuschle testified
that he attended campaign meetings during work hours, that
political calls were referred to him at the office and that he used
the office to contact potential Ashcroft supporters or
contributors.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about it six years ago, Deuschle said he worked 60
hours a week during the Ashcroft campaign, 20 percent of it on
politics. As scheduler, Deuschle would have to sometimes handle
both political and state appointments, Ashcroft said at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Sissel, press secretary then, said in a deposition in the
same case that he traveled from Jefferson City to St. Louis in
October 1982 for a weekday afternoon meeting with Deuschle,
Robertson and Duncan Kincheloe, an assistant attorney general. The
meeting was about the Ashcroft campaign, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sissel and Robertson said recently they might have taken a
vacation day that day, although vacation records are no longer
available in state archives. Kincheloe said he also took days off
from time to time for the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign memo called for expanding the capacity of the
attorney general's staff and said Ashcroft's ``programs and
positions should be aggressively communicated on a regular basis
with members of the press _ particularly in metropolitan areas.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ashcroft campaign had its own press secretary, and state
records show virtually no increase in the size of the total office
staff between early 1983 and the November 1984 election.
</P>
<P>
   But in-state travel spending by Ashcroft's office increased from
$95,253 for the fiscal year ended June 30, 1982, to $128,814 the
following year, to $191,221 the year after that and to $238,078 in
fiscal year 1985, of which only six months were during Ashcroft's
term.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1984 Republican primary, Ashcroft took heat from opponent
Gene McNary of St. Louis for taking 122 flights on the state
airplane during the first three years and five months of his second
term. By contrast, his predecessor had taken 18 flights in his last
four years.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Sissel called the trips ``completely legitimate''
efforts to apprise state residents of the attorney general's
activities in the state's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Bills for long-distance and other phone services also increased
during Ashcroft's term as attorney general. They were $122,983 in
fiscal year 1982, $119,235 the following year, $196,158 the next
year and $145,696 in fiscal year 1985, only half of which was
during his tenure.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson said an explanation for the higher phone bills may
have been litigation being carried out in Kansas City in 1983 on
the school desegregation case. Office policy, Robertson recalled,
was that using state phones for political purposes was improper.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic Party's criticism of Ashcroft's 1984 campaign is
similar to objections voiced over his using U.S. Senate employees
in his current re-election bid.
</P>
<P>
   The Ashcroft 2000 Committee showed more than 100 campaign-fund
reimbursements to Senate employees in 1998 and 1999 for travel and
other expenses. Records from the early 1980s also show about 50
reimbursements to employees of the attorney general from Ashcroft's
gubernatorial campaign committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pattern we've seen repeated,'' Temple said.
</P>
<P>
   But then, like now, the work was done on the employees' own
time, Ashcroft allies insisted. Political work by U.S. Senate
staffers is allowed under Senate rules, if voluntary and at the
expense of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Using another example against the Democrat, Ayres alluded to a
1981 incident in which an employee of Carnahan, who was then
serving as state treasurer, carried some ``Carnahan for Missouri''
files from the office and took them away in a state vehicle.
Carnahan admitted some work like that had been done.
</P>
<P>
   Wyche said Carnahan took prompt action as treasurer to make sure
the employee engaged in no more political work.
</P>
<P>
   State and federal laws prohibit using public resources, such as
employees, for personal gain, but prosecutions are relatively rare
because lines between government and political work are often
blurred.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
