r a BC-DIALYSIS-MACHINE-KAN &LR;      07-10 1391
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIALYSIS-MACHINE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME DIALYSIS MACHINE IMPROVES LIFE FOR KIDNEY PATIENTS 
</HEADLINE>
 -KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 BY ALAN BAVLEY, THE KANSAS CITY STAR   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lucille Shirley has gained a new sense of independence. Sandra
Hampton feels better than she has in years.
</P>
<P>
   Both of these kidney dialysis patients credit Zbylut Twardowski,
a University of Missouri-Columbia professor emeritus, for
dramatically improving their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Twardowski, 66, has been instrumental in developing a home
dialysis machine that Shirley, Hampton and 21 other patients are
testing.
</P>
<P>
   The high-tech device is the realization of Twardowski's
decades-old dream to improve the health and simplify the lives of
many of the more than 200,000 dialysis patients in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   If the Food and Drug Administration approves, the machine could
start appearing in homes across the country next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I strongly believe this is the best kind of dialysis,'' said
Twardowski, an internationally known kidney specialist and native
of Poland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I work on other kinds of dialysis, but I always have in mind
that this is the ultimate goal. I feel if I can accomplish this, it
will be a fulfillment of some long-term desire, some long-term
goal.''
</P>
<P>
   About 300,000 people in the United States suffer kidney failure
caused by diabetes, high blood pressure or other maladies. About
86,000 of these patients have received kidney transplants, but
because donor organs are in short supply, the rest depend on
dialysis to stay alive.
</P>
<P>
   Most dialysis patients now get their treatments three times each
week at clinics. They sit in reclining chairs for three to four
hours as their blood circulates through machines that filter out
the impurities their kidneys no longer can remove.
</P>
<P>
   Twardowski and many other researchers have concluded that
dialysis six or seven days a week is vastly superior to the three
dialysis sessions per week that have been the standard treatment
for the past quarter century.
</P>
<P>
   Patients on daily dialysis feel better, have more energy and
develop fewer infections and other medical problems, researchers
have found. They also take fewer medications and spend less time in
the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   But the expense of providing patients with additional dialysis
and the difficulty of traveling to centers several more times each
week have kept daily dialysis from catching on.
</P>
<P>
   Another form of home dialysis uses the body's peritoneum, the
membrane that surrounds the abdominal organs, to filter impurities.
But peritoneal dialysis can only be used by patients who retain
some kidney function and who weigh less than 200 pounds. And the
large amount of work it requires has limited its popularity among
patients.
</P>
<P>
   Twardowski hopes his machine will make dialysis six days per
week as affordable as conventional thrice-weekly dialysis and easy
enough for patients to perform at home. As many as half the
patients now receiving conventional dialysis may be candidates for
the home machine, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Patients connect themselves to the machine by an intravenous
catheter or needle, then turn the machine on using push-button
controls on a small computer screen. Dialysis sessions usually last
two to three hours.
</P>
<P>
   The machine is programmed to disinfect itself after each use and
then prepare for the next dialysis session. Patients replace the
machine's tubing and blood filter once a month.
</P>
<P>
   Patients in Missouri, Seattle and Jackson, Miss., are
participating in the machine's clinical trial.
</P>
<P>
   Final results will be in this fall. At that time, Aksys Ltd., a
suburban Chicago company that was started to develop the machine,
will apply to the FDA for permission to market it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have to deal with dialysis in your life, definitely,
this is the way to go,'' said Hampton, 58, of Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton suffers from an inherited condition called polycystic
kidney disease. Her kidneys began to fail when she was in her 20s
and she has been completely dependent on dialysis for close to 10
years.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton used to take seven pills a day to control her high blood
pressure, a problem common among kidney patients. Now she is down
to one pill a day, and her blood pressure is better controlled.
</P>
<P>
   Dialysis three times per week at a clinic left her feeling
exhausted, Hampton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You crash,'' she said. ``You have what we call the dialysis
hangover.''
</P>
<P>
   Now she feels energetic enough to cook more meals and work
longer hours at her job selling Avon products.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get up in the morning, clean my blood and get on with my
day,'' Hampton said.
</P>
<P>
   When patients receive dialysis three times per week, their body
is on a constant, stressful roller-coaster ride, doctors say.
Toxins build up in their blood, are removed and then build up
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, daily dialysis is better than three times a week.
Three times a week doesn't make sense,'' said Robert Lockridge, a
Lynchburg, Va., kidney specialist.
</P>
<P>
   Lockridge has 16 patients on daily home dialysis, using
conventional dialysis machines.
</P>
<P>
   After going on daily dialysis, his patients have scored higher
on tests of psychological well-being, their time spent in the
hospital has been cut by 50 percent, and several have returned to
work.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a better quality of care,'' Lockridge said.
</P>
<P>
   Shirley, 60, of Fayette, Mo., had been on daily home dialysis
with a conventional machine before receiving one of Twardowski's
experimental models.
</P>
<P>
   The old machine was too complicated for Shirley to operate, so
she relied on her husband, Robert, to do the work.
</P>
<P>
   ``To look at it was intimidating. I did not know how to do any
of it alone,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   That meant Robert spent an hour each day rigging the machine
with new tubing and filter, stayed with her during three hours of
dialysis and then spent another hour pulling off the old tubing.
</P>
<P>
   Lucille Shirley felt she had imposed an enormous burden on her
husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was my disease, but it took my husband the time every day
to do it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   With the new machine, Shirley said she feels confident doing
home dialysis on her own.
</P>
<P>
   Two big obstacles stood in the way of developing a daily home
dialysis machine, said Leslie Spry, a kidney specialist in Lincoln,
Neb., and a spokesman for the American Kidney Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Because dialysis machines circulate a patient's blood outside
the body, they must be highly reliable, Spry said. And connecting
tubes to patients' veins every day to carry blood to and from the
machine increases the risk of infection.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are the two critical issues that no one has solved
yet,'' Spry said. ``If (Twardowski) has, the dialysis world will
beat a path to his door.''
</P>
<P>
   Twardowski believes he has surmounted those obstacles. His
machine contains a variety of sensors that detect leaks and monitor
the temperature and composition of the chemical solution used by
the machine.
</P>
<P>
   Infections have not been a problem, Twardowski said. Lockridge
also said infections have been rare among his daily dialysis
patients.
</P>
<P>
   Twardowski has been an advocate of daily dialysis since he did
his first studies on patients in Poland about 25 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought about this machine even in Poland, but I really
didn't have support from industry. Industry wasn't interested,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin Cowley, a kidney specialist at the University of Kansas
Medical Center, called Twardowski ``one of the old gurus of
dialysis.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been one of the leaders in dialysis therapy for years, an
elder statesman, if you will, for optimizing care for people on
dialysis.''
</P>
<P>
   With the help of Aksys founder Rodney Kenley, Twardowski
co-designed and patented his home dialysis machine. In 1996, Aksys
was able to interest a group of venture capitalists in backing the
project.
</P>
<P>
   Once it receives FDA approval, Aksys plans to lease its machines
to dialysis centers, which will provide the machines to patients.
Home dialysis patients still will need to visit clinics once a
month for check-ups and stay in phone contact in-between times.
</P>
<P>
   Dialysis centers receive about $20,000 per year from Medicare to
provide treatment to a patient. The machines will lease for less
than that, Twardowski hopes.
</P>
<P>
   If the machines are successful, Twardowski stands to make a
substantial amount of money.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
