<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS JANUS BATTLED TO GO IT SOWN WAY IN KC SOUTHERN'S SPINOFF 
</HEADLINE>
 2NDTAKE-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 BY MARK DAVIS, THE KANSAS CITY STAR   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, _ Mo. To the eyes in Denver, the setup looks like a
shopping spree waiting to happen, with Rowland and the other
Stilwell executives, all of whom come from Kansas City Southern,
picking the merchandise and with Janus' cash flow footing the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no basis to justify the holding company other than
Rowland's desire to have a platform to do other acquisitions,''
said Stolper, who still owns shares in Janus and makes no secret of
his allegiance to Bailey.
</P>
<P>
   Constant, the Lehman Brothers analyst, said the fear was
unfounded. He said Kansas City Southern had made assurances in
meetings with analysts that it didn't plan to use Stilwell's
capital for a string of acquisitions. Most likely it will use the
cash to buy back Stilwell shares in the open market, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Stock buybacks are widely seen as supporting shareholders'
value, and the lO(Wv16OQ &QL; $3M
</P>
