<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRISON-LAWSUIT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAY AREA ACTIVISTS FILE LAWSUIT TO STOP CONSTRUCTION OF
DELANO  PRISON
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By HENRY K. LEE 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A coalition of activists filed a lawsuit Monday in hopes of
blocking a planned maximum-security prison in the Central Valley,
saying a decline in the state inmate population makes it
unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   In a lawsuit filed in Kern County Superior Court in Bakersfield,
two Bay Area anti-prison groups accused the state Department of
Corrections of not considering alternatives to the planned $335
million prison in Delano, such as using the money for schools and
rehabilitation programs.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, citing the California Environmental Quality Act,
said corrections officials did not adequately provide ways to
lessen the effect the 4,700-bed prison would have on local schools
and transportation, water and sewage systems.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs, Critical Resistance of Oakland and the National
Lawyers Guild Prison Law Project in San Francisco, also cited
figures, released by the corrections department last week, showing
that the state prison population over the last year dropped for the
first time in more than two decades, a period that coincided with a
prison-building boom.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all for investment in Delano but we're not for more
prisons,'' said Rose Braz, program director of Critical Resistance
and an Oakland criminal defense lawyer. ``The way to reduce
juvenile crime is not through further incarceration.''
</P>
<P>
   State corrections department spokeswoman Jeanie Esajian said
Monday that she could not comment on the lawsuit because the
department had not been served with it.
</P>
<P>
   But Esajian did say there is a need for the prison.
Inmate-population projections to be released in the fall are
expected to to be higher, she said, because the figures will be the
first to factor in the effect of Proposition 21, the voter-approved
initiative that toughens the penalties for juvenile offenders.
</P>
<P>
   As for the lawsuit's assertion that the state did not meet
provisions of the environmental quality act, Esajian said it was
the Corrections Department's policy to ``fully comply'' with the
statute.
</P>
<P>
   As of June, California's 33 state prisons housed 161,000
inmates. Esajian said the figure will grow to nearly 179,000 by
2005.
</P>
<P>
   Delano, a city of 30,000, has been home since 1993 to the North
Kern State Prison, a medium-security facility. The bulk of the
money for the new prison, known as Delano II, is to come from
revenue bonds, and the Legislature last year allocated $24 million
to purchase land for the facility.
</P>
<P>
   Delano II would house 4,100 maximum-security inmates considered
to be violent offenders, 408 minimum-security inmates and 192
juvenile offenders.
</P>
<P>
   Even after the prison is built, Esajian said, the state will
still have 6,000 maximum-security inmates who are housed in
converted, lesser-security facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Dean Florez, D-Shafter (Kern County), the author of
the bill calling for the prison, said the lawsuit is ill-advised
and the result of groups unfamiliar with Delano.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once again we have urban-oriented groups trying to tell rural
communities what's good and not good for our communities, Florez
said. He said the citizens and leaders of Delano, a city of 30,000,
have embraced the new prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody wants to talk tough on crime, but yet when it comes
to building institutions, no one wants it in the backyard,'' Florez
said. ``The city of Delano has said we do want it in our
backyard.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
